<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Jan. 31. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   EXPLOSIVE (Phoenix) _ More explosives are stolen in Arizona than
almost anywhere else in the country, but so far, the state has done
next to nothing to regulate the industry. Throughout the state,
explosives are stacked in storage magazines outside mines, rock
quarries and construction sites with little security. All it takes
are some good tools and a getaway vehicle to haul off a few hundred
pounds of blasting materials. That's exactly what happened Dec. 12,
when 1,000 pounds of explosives disappeared from a rock quarry near
the rural community of Drake in north-central Arizona. The theft,
coming amid fears of terrorism on the eve of the millennium,
alarmed law-enforcement agencies, who now acknowledge that they are
out of leads despite posting a $10,000 reward. By MARK SHAFFER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NAVAJOS (KYKOTSMOVI, Ariz.) _ Beyond the battles over which
tribe has the stronger spiritual connection to the land or the more
powerful claim for historic justice, the Navaj-Hopi dispute has
also been a battle of public relations. For years, that worked to
the advantage of the Hopis, long celebrated among non-Indians for
their highly spiritual, peace-loving ways. Most outsiders heard
``Hopi'' and thought: kachina dolls. In the 1970s, Hopi tribal
leaders bolstered their position with a PR campaign portraying the
Navajos as marauding bullies. Today, however, it's the Hopis' turn
to be cast as the villains. Clayton Honyumptewa, director of the
tribe's lands office, hears it in telephone calls about the forced
relocation of thousands of Navajos from land granted by federal law
to the Hopis. By JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   HULL (Phoenix) _ In 1962, Jane Hull, Arizona's present governor,
was a 26-year-old schoolteacher who left a comfortable Kansas City
suburb and moved to Chinle, a remote town on the Navajo Reservation
in northern Arizona. There was no theater, no library; only a few
trading posts. There was no supermarket, so Hull did her shopping
in Albuquerque, planning family meals six weeks at a time. Hull's
time in Chinle offers a striking image of the governor as a gritty
frontier woman. But now, as she begins her third year in
office,lawmakers are grumbling that the real power is held by
Hull's chief of staff, Around the capitol, the whispers have
started. Has the Iron Lady started to rust? Hull and her staff
laugh off such claims. She says Collins takes most of the flak,
because that's his role as chief of staff. By BILL MULLER. Story
will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new
books. By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   DISCIPLINE (undated) _ Religious leaders from different creeds
discuss how children should be disciplined. By MAUREEN JENKINS.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``L'' categories.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
