<SLUG> BC-EXPLOSIVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE CURBS URGED ON EXPLOSIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARK SHAFFER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More explosives are stolen in Arizona than almost anywhere else
in the country, but so far, the state has done next to nothing to
regulate the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the state, explosives are stacked in storage
magazines outside mines, rock quarries and construction sites with
little security. All it takes are some good tools and a getaway
vehicle to haul off a few hundred pounds of blasting materials.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened Dec. 12, when 1,000 pounds of
explosives disappeared from a rock quarry near the rural community
of Drake in north-central Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The theft, coming amid fears of terrorism on the eve of the
millennium, alarmed law-enforcement agencies, who now acknowledge
that they are out of leads despite posting a $10,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   It prompted state police agencies to quadruple the number of
officers guarding the Legislature for Gov. Jane Hull's recent State
of the State address.
</P>
<P>
   And it has lit a fuse among some officials, who are calling for
the Legislature to require that the estimated 200 blasters in the
state be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem:
</P>
<P>
   _Arizona is one of only 13 states that do not regulate those who
use explosives, despite its numerous mines and high use of blasting
for new construction.
</P>
<P>
   _The state is third in the nation in the amount of explosive
material stolen and first in the amount of stolen material
recovered, according to the most recent federal statistics
available.
</P>
<P>
   _The state doesn't have a handle on how much explosive material
there is or where it is stored. The feds do, but they don't readily
share that information because they are putting together a database
that state officials cannot yet access.
</P>
<P>
   _And although the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms keeps track of the total amount of explosives stolen and
recovered, a spokesman said he has never seen a breakdown of those
incidents. &QL; 
LEADING THE CHARGE &QL; 
Mining Inspector Doug Martin is leading the charge on the
Legislature to require that blasters be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, the State Fire Safety Committee is charged with
issuing permits to manufacture, transport or use explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still waiting to see my first fire-safety explosives
permit,'' said Phil Howard, assistant state mine inspector.
</P>
<P>
   He added that municipalities such as Phoenix tightly control
blasting, but there are no such regulations in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature tried to regulate blasters, albeit
half-heartedly, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A study committee on explosives regulation was formed but one of
the committee members, Rep. Joe Hart, R-Kingman, said he doesn't
remember it meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling then was that if no one has been killed by
blasting agents, then we shouldn't worry about a law,'' Martin
said. ``I've been saying all along that this is about prevention.
Now, we've got the threat of terrorism, and more explosives were
stolen in Drake than were ever threatened to be brought across the
Canadian border.''
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Lindsey of Phoenix, who has been in the business of
selling explosives for more than 40 years, said the state effort
overreached and would have duplicated the oversight that the
federal government already provides.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ATF's role of documenting transactions and
storage facilities, the U.S. Department of Transportation governs
the transportation of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lindsey said that no amount of regulation would stop
determined criminals. Lindsey said that his company, Lindco
Equipment and Supply, had 600 pounds of blasting powder and more
than 1,200 sticks of dynamite stolen in 1991. Lindsey said most of
the stolen material was recovered over time, dumped in the desert
of the West ern part of the state &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``More regulations are not going to affect theft,'' Lindsey
said, noting that he had upgraded security on 15 explosives storage
magazines around the state after anxious blasting operations called
his office for help in the wake of the Drake theft. &QL; 
TRAINING, TESTING &QL; 
Lindsey says he favors a state license that would require training
and testing for all blasters.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lindsey says even more pressing is a need for a federal
license for buyers, which would require background checks at the
time of the purchase, much as the Brady Law does for guns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Institute of Makers of Explosives, &UR; a Washington, D.C.-based
safety association of the commercial explosives industry in the
United States and Canada, also has been pushing mightily for a
national license to buy explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any person can walk into an explosives distributor and, with a
signature on a form, buy explosives,'' said Chris Ronay, a retired
FBI bomb expert who is director of the institute. ``We've been
trying to close that loophole for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronay said the institute lobbied Congress to address that
loophole and got a rider on a juvenile-justice bill currently
before the assembly, ``but that bill appears dead now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A good example of the problems in monitoring are last year's
statistics,'' Ronay said. ``There were 28,000 pounds of explosives
stolen and half again as much which wasn't reported. There were
100,000 pounds of stolen explosives recovered, some of it going
back years, and a lot of it there were no records on.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute also has lobbied for uniformity in state laws
across the country. There are more than 3,000 regulating bodies for
explosives, Ronay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states can exceed federal regulations, and that would be a
good situation to have,'' Ronay said. ``For example, the feds could
require a minimum number of locks on magazines but Arizona could
decide that it wants explosives in bombproof bunkers instead.'' &QL; 
TOUGH CALIFORNIA LAWS &QL; 
Howard, the second in charge at the state Mine Inspector's Office,
would welcome any state law to control the handling of explosives.
He said he managed a mine in California that has the toughest
regulations for blasters on the books, requiring three years'
experience, training courses and exams for a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the area of our mine, the sheriff's office also required a
background check,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of that, we found the true identity of a felon who had
assumed a man's identity who had been killed in Las Vegas five
years earlier. Being careful pays nice rewards.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at &QL; 
Mark.Shaffer(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8057. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
