<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DORSETT CAN'T DRAW THE LAST LINE
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every Super Bowl has an X factor: a play, a player, a
happening that emerges from the shadows to alter the course of the
glitter-drenched championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Miami, the X factor turned out to be a late-hour,
off-field incident involving Eugene Robinson, the Atlanta Falcons'
veteran safety and team leader, who was arrested on charges of
soliciting a prostitute for $40 the night before the game. It was a
disruption the Falcons could not afford against a Broncos team that
ultimately outclassed them.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, the X factor was Terrell Davis, who had a
breakout game in a breakout season. There was Desmond Howard's
kickoff return for Green Bay in Super Bowl XXXI in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday night's Super Bowl between Tennessee and St.
Louis, Anthony Dorsett was the X factor. The Titans' free safety
was thrust from his special-teams role onto center stage when he
was forced to fill in for Marcus Robertson, the Titans' veteran who
suffered a broken ankle. His father is Tony Dorsett, the Hall of
Fame running back for the Dallas Cowboys. The father-son angle
became one of the compelling story lines this week with the young
Hawk, as Dorsett is called, being asked to look at his celebrity
father through a child's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night into early Sunday morning, Tony Dorsett put
aside the paternal feeling and looked at his son the way the Rams
were looking at his son: like the hunter looks at the deer, like
the lion looks at the zebra.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at him as prey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was game-planning the Titans,'' Dorsett said, ``and I got
a young guy stepping in there, starting for the first time in the
biggest game of the year, I'd test him. I'd test him early and I
might test him often until he gave me reason to say: `O.K., he's
going to hold his own. We might be shooting some blanks thinking
that we're going to win this game going in that direction.' If he
steps up to the plate, that's fine; if he doesn't then they're
going to come at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see if he's going to be the weak link. I just
don't want him to be the reason that things go bad.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly all of the first three quarters and most of the
fourth, young Dorsett played an error-free game. He made jarring
hits on Marshall Faulk, did not give up the obvious game-breaking
play, patrolled the secondary like a center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   But with just under two minutes remaining, both Dorsetts' worst
nightmare unfolded. The Titans had just tied the game at 16-16 on a
field goal by Al Del Greco. Then Kurt Warner and the Rams did what
they had done all season: they made the quick strike. Warner hit
Isaac Bruce with a 73-yard touchdown pass. Bruce beat cornerback
Denard Walker on the catch, but Dorsett, the Titans' last line of
defense, overran the play and missed an arm tackle when Bruce cut
back. Racing away from Dorsett, he sped into the end zone with the
winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, Tennessee's last gasp fell short. Titans
quarterback Steve McNair hit Kevin Dyson with a slant pass just
inside the 5-yard yard line, but Mike Jones, an eighth-year
linebacker, made a sensational open-field tackle and brought Dyson
down at the 1-yard-line, holding him there as Dyson desperately
tried to stretch the ball over goal line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bitter ending for the Titans, their secondary, and
Dorsett. Considering Tennessee's predicament, the secondary,
playing man to man across the field, played heroically against the
National Football League's most prolific offense. Warner completed
19 of 35 passes for 277 yards in the first half alone, 24 of 45 for
414 yards for the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams scored just 9 points in the first half. The
evidence of Dorsett's inexperience was apparent just once in the
first quarter, when Faulk was wide open down the right sideline and
ran for a 52-yard gain. Dorsett was checking coverage with another
defensive back when St. Louis went on a quick snap, and he was late
getting over. But the secondary, as it had done all game, closed
ranks with airtight coverage, tips and pressures from the line. St.
Louis reached the 9-yard-line but missed a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Until Warner's game-breaking play, that was the pattern of the
game. The Rams sliced up the secondary from the 20 to the 20, then
the Titans defenders made plays: they would force Warner to hurry a
throw or make a bad throw under pressure. With 8 minutes 24 seconds
left in the third quarter, Blaine Bishop, the heart and soul of the
Titans' defense, was injured and forced to leave the game after a
head-first tackle on Ernie Conwell. He was replaced by Perry
Phenix, a second-year safety. Three plays after the long, somber
delay, Warner hit Torry Holt for the game's first touchdown.
Tennessee cut the lead to 16-13 with 7:21 to play. Then the defense
held: Faulk was held to a 2-yard gain; Jason Fisk knocked away a
slant to Holt, and Warner was hurried into an incompletion.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dorsett played in Super Bowl XII in 1978 when Dallas
defeated Denver, 27-10; he also played in Super Bowl XIII when
Dallas lost to Pittsburgh, 35-31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Anthony, think about this: I don't know who's
going to be introduced, offense or defense, but if they introduce
that defense, they're introducing you to the world,''' Dorsett
said. ``You got a big stage, a big platform to perform in. The
feeling that you're going to have is unexplainable, it is the best
feeling you're going to ever have, being introduced for a football
game, in your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may come back, but you won't experience it like you're
going to experience it the first time. You ain't going to be able
to wait for that ball to be kicked off.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss in a tough game, a great game, there is the
magic for Tony Dorsett of being able to play in two Super Bowls and
have a son become a central figure in the third.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Dorsett said that win or lose, he would say he
watched his son play in the game of both of their lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
