<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCIPLINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ARE PARENTS EXPECTED TO DISCIPLINED THEIR KIDS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN JENKINS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: ALSO MOVING IN ``L'' CATEGORY
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ ``Webster's Third New International Dictionary''
defines discipline as ``training or experience that corrects,
molds, strengthens or perfects, especially the mental faculties or
moral character.'' And it's through such training that kids become
responsible members of their families and communities, says Paul
Miller, an associate professor of psychology who teaches about
child development and socialization at Arizona State University
West.
</P>
<P>
   In this process, parents ``are not incidental players _ they are
IT, period,'' Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   The parent-child relationship ``acts in a way to temper behavior
that's out of bounds and to reward behavior that's in bounds,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That relationship is both a comfort and a safety zone,''
Miller adds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the world's major religions address the role parents and
other adults are to play in raising future generations. The
biblical book of Proverbs, for example, urges youth to adopt moral
values that will inform their daily lives, as well as their
spiritual formation. In fact, the two are seen as inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   We asked representatives of five religious traditions to answer
these questions from their faith's perspective: &QL; 
What does your faith tradition say about parental responsibility
when it comes to disciplining children? Does it distinguish between
physical and verbal chastisement? &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMAM ABDUR-RAHIM SHAMSID-DEEN &QL; 
Muslim; The Jewel of Al-Islam; Father of eight daughters, including
two sets of twins, ages 8 to 29.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``The Holy Koran directs parents to acknowledge that children have
rights and should be respected by the parents. Parental
responsibility for Muslims when it comes to disciplining the
children begins with teaching and demonstrating proper respect for
Almighty God (Allah in Arabic, the language of the Koran). The
Muslim parents begin immediately to train the children that there
is only one God, and that God created everything in the universe,
including all human beings.
</P>
<P>
   We try our best to demonstrate God-consciousness to the
children, which further helps to develop their character and
self-control. The religion of Al-Islam puts strong emphasis on the
young, who know right conduct from wrong conduct _ and those who
don't know it are not held responsible, even if they cause damage
because of their unintentional actions. The Holy Koran teaches the
parents that our children are being entrusted to us, and as parents
we have an obligation to care for them, be kind to them, and
educate them.
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Koran further states, ``In punishment there is life to
you, if you can reflect and think.'' Muslim parents that understand
their religion usually will punish their children for the wrong, by
first explaining the wrong that has been committed and reprimanding
the children with firmness laced with gentleness. If correctiveness
is rejected and the child shows open disrespect, arrogance and
rebellion, then the Muslim parents will discipline the child with
the best methods available at our time.
</P>
<P>
   The religion of Al-Islam clearly makes a distinction between
verbal and physical chastisement, because the Holy Koran does not
direct the parents to physically punish the children, but to
admonish the children with knowledge, wisdom and understanding. The
first obligation and duty in Al-Islam is to worship and obey
Almighty God; the next in line is for children to be respectful and
obedient to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Koran recognizes very clearly that parents are not always
immune from overprotectiveness or negligence, and has established
certain guidelines with respect to children. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DEBRA AND REED TOLMAN &QL; 
Debra Tolman is a church religion instructor, Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints, and Reed Tolman is youth adviser for
Lehi Third Ward; parents of 14- and 23-year-old daughters and 17-
and 21-year-old sons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are accountable to God for their parental
stewardships. All humans are created in God's image and are his
spirit children. When God sent us here to gain experience and
progress toward perfection, he intended for us to be born into
loving, nurturing families. With each birth, God entrusts to
parents the responsibility to love and teach his children. For
parents who accept the divine principles of parenthood,
disciplining children in righteousness is paramount.
</P>
<P>
   While volumes have been written about disciplining children,
adherence to a few basic principles results in a successful
parenting experience and the fulfillment of our divine parental
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   First, every parent must have selfless love for each child.
Without it, disciplining is a chore and can result in anger and
violence; with it, disciplining, although not easy, brings great
joy as the fruits of a disciplined child are realized.
</P>
<P>
   Second, children must be treated with kindness and respect.
Although younger, smaller and less experienced than we, our
children are our equals in God's plan and must be treated with the
respect they deserve as his children.
</P>
<P>
   Third, children learn with consistent expectations and
discipline; they must know their limits and suffer consequences
when those limits are exceeded. This prepares them to live by the
rules of society and the commandments of God.
</P>
<P>
   Corporal punishment and demeaning chastisement are
counterproductive and inconsistent with Christian principles. The
child may obey, but obedience generated by fear is temporary and
produces negative results. Exhibiting an increase in love after
discipline helps the child to understand its purpose and engenders
a respectful parent-child relationship. Finally, love, respect and
discipline must be accompanied by examples. Years of teaching can
be wasted if parents expect children to ``do as I say, not as I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Applying principles of righteous parenting brings tremendous joy
and the fulfillment of a divine charge to love and nurture God's
children.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE REV. MARY BAARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pastor, Shepherd of the Hills Congregational United Church of
Christ; mother of 10- and 14-year-old daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parenting is one of the most challenging and most enriching
parts of my own spiritual journey. Just yesterday, one of my
daughters asked, ``Is there a day you wish you could live over,
because you did something to hurt someone else, and you want to fix
it?'' When I pay attention, my children have so much to teach me
about discipleship.
</P>
<P>
   At its root, the word discipline is not primarily about
chastisement. Rather, just like the word ``disciple,'' the root
meaning of discipline is ``to learn.'' In the Christian tradition,
parents are called to guide their children in learning to be
disciples of Jesus the Christ who calls us to love God and love
neighbor. Thus, discipline takes place in all our interactions with
our children, not just when they have done something ``wrong.''
It's that simple, and it's that difficult.
</P>
<P>
   This is a particularly hard goal to keep in mind when we are
feeling pushed to the limits and are tempted to resort to physical
chastisement. However, I believe this a temptation we should
resist. I often said to my children when they were little, ``You
may not hit me. I don't hit you. We don't hit in this family.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's parents grew up in a time when their central
question was, ``Will my life have meaning?'' For many of today's
children, the central question is, ``Will you be there for me?'' We
must be there for our children. It is our calling as parents to be
present. It is our responsibility to set firm and clear boundaries,
so that our children can eventually learn to discipline
themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE NAKAMURA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona area leader, Buddhist Soka Gakkai International; father
of 12-year-old son
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddhism teaches the concept of oneness of life and its
environment. Human life and its environment are inseparable.
Therefore, the key to children's discipline is the children's
environment. Adults, including parents, teachers and community
leaders, play an essential role because they are the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism also teaches the concept of the Ten Worlds. Each World
describes a state of human life. Most of the time, we experience
the lower worlds (Six Paths) in our daily life: Hell, Hunger,
Animality, Anger, Humanity, Heaven. As long as we dwell among the
Six Paths we are largely controlled by the changing circumstances
of our environment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Worlds of Learning and Realization, we awaken through
study and observation to the impermanence of all things. The World
of Bodhisattva is a condition of compassion, devoting ourselves to
helping others, performing altruistic actions on their behalf. The
10th World, Buddhahood, is the supreme jewel in the depths of our
being, a condition of absolute and indestructible happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism explains that we elevate our life state to higher
levels so that we can create indestructible happiness. In other
words, through changing our inner world at a fundamental level, we
change the outer world by becoming a better human being who serves
others and our society. We call this transformation of character
Human Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Adults whocontinuously strive to do their own Human Revolution,
regardless of socioeconomic status, naturally create an optimal
environment for children. To create the best environment for our
children, adults must work hard to grow.
</P>
<P>
   As Daisaku Ikeda, president of our Buddhist group, Soka Gakkai
International, writes: ``The first ones who should reflect on their
lives are adults. Otherwise, they are not qualified to scold
anybody.'' Through elevating our life state, we become people of
courage, compassion and wisdom, and from this elevated state of
life, we can conduct dialogue with children that both teaches and
disciplines them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RABBI LISA TZUR &QL; 
Jewish; Temple Chai; mother of 1-year-old daughter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Discipline occupies a central role in Jewish child rearing. &UR; It
is considered a ``mitzvah'' (a commandment from God, not a parent's
prerogative) to discipline our children.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly from a biblical point of view, there are texts about
discipline which might make us uneasy. The most classic of these
texts discusses what parents must do in the case of the
``rebellious son.'' According to the text, the child who is
stubborn and insubordinate to his parents should be stoned to death
by the community at large!
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, there are many biblical verses which seemingly
encourage using the rod with children: ``Withhold not from a lad
correction, for if thou beat him with the rod he will not die. You
will indeed beat him with the rod, but (in doing so) you will
deliver his soul from perdition.`` (Proverbs 23:13).
</P>
<P>
   Does Judaism advocate physical discipline? It would appear
likely from these texts that we do _ yet this is not the case.
Although there were some cases in which ``using the rod'' might
have been taken literally, it seems that the use of the rod is
truly meant to be figurative. The rabbinic sages clearly limited
the use of physical discipline by restricting parents in the
following manner: ``. . . if you hit a child, strike him only with
a shoestring.'' (Talmud, Bava Batra 21a). Moreover, Jewish law
insists that discipline must be accompanied by expressions of
warmth and love, as is shown by the following passage: ``A child,
discipline him with the left hand and draw him closer with the
right hand.``
</P>
<P>
   Another fundamental principle is that the punishment must fit
the crime, and it must be ``immediate,'' preventing a child from
fearing the punishment over a long period of time, and thereby
maintaining a child's sense of dignity and self-respect. Therefore,
Judaism advocates parental discipline in order to guide our
children to adulthood, while severely limiting the role of physical
discipline.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
