<SLUG> BC-VONNEGUT-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURT VONNEGUT HOSPITALIZED AFTER HOUSE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fire at Kurt Vonnegut's Manhattan home sent the
77-year-old author to the hospital suffering from smoke inhalation
on Sunday night, and slightly damaged his four-story townhouse on
East 48th Street, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the blaze was under investigation, but fire
marshals believe that careless smoking by Vonnegut may have played
a role, said a fire official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have been smoking in the room, left it, and then the
blaze started,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Weill Cornell Center of New York-Presbyterian
Hospital, where Mr. Vonnegut was admitted, would not comment on his
condition, but his 17-year-old daughter, Lily, said he was
``okay,'' though he will probably remain hospitalized for a few
days. No one else was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, in a study on the top floor, was spotted around 7 p.m.
by a man who lives across the street from Vonnegut's white-brick
house, Lily Vonnegut said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A neighbor saw smoke and ran over,'' she said. ``The two of us
basically saved my dad. He couldn't see. There was black smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire department was able to put the one-alarm blaze out
within 20 minutes, and Ms. Vonnegut said damage to the study was
minimal. Vonnegut, the nation's unofficial curmudgeon laureate and
the author of ``Slaughterhouse-Five'' and other modern classics,
has lived in the house for more than 20 years, the fire official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
