<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS, LOWLIGHTS OF SUPER BOWL TELECAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Super Bowl XXXIV was a fine way to spend a Sunday
afternoon, especially the second half, when the Titans fought their
way back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   But here's hoping you ended your viewing day by 7 p.m., and
missed the visual everyone in Southern California dreaded Rams
owner Georgia Frontiere holding the Lombardi Trophy and saying
``This proves we made the right decision going to St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Georgia, that, the free stadium and all that PSL money.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of heartburn will last awhile, but at least ABC spared
us a longer Georgia monologue. The camera kept its sideline shots
of her to a few, and L.A. resident Al Michaels needled Madame Ram
several times about her changing the pronunciation of her last
name.
</P>
<P>
   As Super Bowl telecasts go, ABC's effort scored high in several
areas and low in a few others.
</P>
<P>
   The production was crisp and intimate in the style of ABC Monday
Night telecasts, and nary a pivotal replay was missed. Credit
director Craig Janoff for his decision to stick to the basics and
not over reach for a new tech toy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some past Super Bowl telecasts that were choppy due to
too many commercial breaks, ABC's show had a decent pace. Most
breaks lasted less than two minutes, and there were only two times
all game in which the game dragged because of TV timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   There was an 18-minute span in the first half in which less than
eight minutes was football action, and an 11-minute break in the
second half around the injury to Tennessee's Blaine Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   But on the down side, a lot of those breaks feature ABC promos
for their prime time shows. In the first half, there were five
promos for ABC series and three more for ABC made-for-TV movie
about the Beach Boys. The second half presented more of the same.
Millionaire quizmaster Regis Philbin was in so many of the promos
that I expected him to show up in the Rams huddle.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasting booth delivered a split decision. Al Michaels
performed flawlessly as usual. The first half of the game was
choppy, but he didn't try to paint a pretty picture. He let the
Rams errors in the red zone tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   When action picked up in the second half, Michaels kept pace and
advanced the story. When Boomer Esiason criticized a late decision
by Tennessee's Steve McNair to not call time out, Michaels said the
Titans would likely need that time out later, and they did after
the next play, a completion inside the Rams 10.
</P>
<P>
   And when the game ended with the Titans Kevin Dyson a yard away
from the end zone, Michaels summed things up powerfully: ``There's
a (football) movie called The Longest Yard, and there's your
sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason, in his second year at ABC, had a formful day. He got
off to a slow start and made many of the mistakes he's made all
year, like talking over a play and embracing the quick cliche.
</P>
<P>
   He also spends most of his energy telling us what happened
moments after we've seen it. The best analysts in the business give
the audience an idea what might happen and what the coaches are
thinking. Boomer doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   One first quarter sequence underscored Michaels' experience and
Esiason's lack of same. Boomer spent a lot of words trying to
explain the Titans' personnel problems. The camera then panned to
Rams coach Dick Vermeil and all of the ex-coaches on his staff, and
Michaels tells viewers that Vermeil said ``I love to collect
professors.'' Succinct and informative.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the Rams' fairy tale season, Michaels said ``This
story is too good for a movie.'' At show's end, Michaels told the
story of how noted astrologer Georgia told John Shaw that Kurt
Warner might be the next Johnny Unitas. Said Michaels: ``How else
can you explain that the Super Bowl champs are the St. Louis
Rams?''
</P>
<P>
   The revelation in the pregame show was how sharp Steve Young was
with a microphone. He co-hosted with Chris Berman and the four-hour
show actually had a nice paced and balance. Kudos to Berman, too,
for noting in the postgame that the 1951 Rams won a NFL title with
a 73-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial-wise, this was known as the e-Bowl, what with almost
a third of all companies buying spots selling their Internet site
or technology. They generally fell into two categories confusing or
boring and they all could use a little dot.comedy. The best example
was the website whose pitch was text saying ``We don't know diddly
about making commercials.'' No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The best and worst of the lot:
</P>
<P>
   Five worst:
</P>
<P>
   5. The cat herders for a website.
</P>
<P>
   4. The black-and-white commercial for a website showing a
confused woman surrounded by people delivering cryptic comments.
</P>
<P>
   3. The website ad with doctors saying a guy is bleeding money
out his wazoo.
</P>
<P>
   2. The site that was essentially selling spam, saying it would
give you money if you attach an ad to your email and the recipient
buys something.
</P>
<P>
   1. The 7-Up ``show us your cans'' commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Five best:
</P>
<P>
   5. Tie, the Schwab ad showing Charles Barkley, Barry Sanders and
Tara Lipinski in a retirement home, and the Busch designated driver
ad, with Wayne Gretzky driving a guy home in a Zamboni.
</P>
<P>
   4. The Muhammad Ali ad, where he shadow boxes to a camera for
WebMD.com.
</P>
<P>
   3. The acting dog who finds his howling motivation by recalling
the day he chased a Budweiser truck and smashed into a van.
</P>
<P>
   2. The E-Trade ad with a monkey dancing to a boom box, followed
by this line of test: ``Well, we just wasted $2 million.''
</P>
<P>
   1. The Mountain Dew ad, where the biker catches a racing
Cheetah, pulls a can of Dew out of his mouth, and says ``bad
kitty.'' The other Dew commercial set to Queen's Bohemian Rhapsody
was pretty cool, too.
</P>
<P>
   The ad by Britannica.com also got our attention with this
mocking question: ``How do Houston and Los Angeles feel now?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
