<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-TITANS-HOUSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OILER FANS FIND IT HARD NOT TO PULL FOR FAMILIAR NAMES &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 FANS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By T. J. MILLING 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With a little remorse, a little envy, but a good deal
of sportsmanship, former Houston Oilers fans packed area sports
bars Sunday to cheer on the Tennessee Titans in their first Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   From Tina Turner's opening number to the Titans' heart-breaking
23-16 loss, they watched the familiar names and the unfamiliar
uniforms charge down the gridiron in football's final contest. It
took a change of climate and finally a change of name to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can hide the fact that their roots are
here,'' said Gorge Luna, a pharmaceutical sales representative
watching the game at Griff's bar in the Montrose area. ``It's an
incredible franchise, so I root for them. I'll root for them until
our new franchise gets here.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Oilers banners hung from the wall amid posters wishing the
Titans good luck and predicting they would ``ram'' St. Louis. Oiler
blue was the color of the day and a few even displayed the old
familiar oil derrick one last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really do need to get their own identity now that we're
getting our own team,'' said Tanya Eagle, a sales administrator who
was wearing her old Oilers jersey. ``I would really like to see
them (Houston's new team slated for the 2004 season.) named the
Oilers, but I know it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The much maligned Titans owner, Bud Adams, was a favorite target
for criticism when thoughts turned to what might have been. A sign
on the wall said, ``Good luck Tennessee. Good riddance Bud.'' But
even he found some sympathy in the day's high spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Oilers should have stayed here,'' Griff's co-owner
Robert Martinez said. ``I think (former) Mayor (Bob) Lanier was a
little hasty at shutting Bud out. Granted, Bud nickeled and dimed
us to death. I don't like it, but I don't blame him, and I wish the
Titans the best of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams took the Oilers to Tennessee after disagreeing with local
officials over the need for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Ernie's on Banks sports bar, benefits manager Scott
Strother, celebrating his 33rd birthday, said he still felt a
connection with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game I wasn't certain if I was a Titans fan,'' he
said. ``but when it kicked off I was rooting hard for them. I guess
there's still a place in my heart for Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie's owner, Kim Elston, said the game wasn't about the
politics or Bud Adams or the demise of the Oilers name. He said
Super Bowl XXXIV was about the franchise veterans such as safety
Blaine Bishop and offensive guard Bruce Matthews, who wore the
Oilers uniform through many disappointing years and only
reluctantly changed it for a darker shade of blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, to me it's all about Bishop and Matthews,'' Elston
said. ``I would say (kicker Al) Del Greco, too, but he gagged that
field goal. They were the three captains out for the coin toss.
That's probably part of the symbolism. They didn't want to leave
Houston and that's the only reason I'm rooting for the Titans.
Those guys deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY XXXXXX $$$
</P>
