<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-HOLOCAUST (Yantarniy, Russia) _ The slaughter of 7,000
Jews, mostly young women, in Kaliningrad four days after the
liberation of Auschwitz in 1945 may have been the last, and one of
the most forgotten, episodes of the Nazi campaign of genocide. That
is, until Sunday. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-MAVERICK (Mount Gerlitzen, Austria) _ To many Austrians,
Joerg Haider is that southern governor with the odd blend of
liberal spending plans and anti-immigrant sentiments they might
quietly agree with but that they know look bad to the European
Union. To his local fans, he is their maverick man shaking up the
fat cats in Vienna who for decades handed out jobs based on
political connections rather than brains or talent. To foreigners,
he is that xenophobic Austrian who once said several pro-Nazi
things. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DAVOS-CLINTON (Davos, Switzerland) _ After seven years of
pushing harder than any post-War president to expand trade between
the United States and the rest of the world, President Clinton told
global leaders here this weekend that the American people have had
enough. Congress and society at large have less enthusiasm for
exchanging goods and services with the world than they did when he
first took office, Clinton said. If new trade deals are going to
get done, he said, the world needs to reinvent the way it thinks
about trade and globalization to accommodate this American
political reality. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-HACKERS (Tokyo) _ In what has become almost a daily
ritual, Internet hackers posted messages on the web site of Japan's
postal service criticizing this country's wartime role in China in
the 1930s. At least 11 government agencies here have been attacked
by the Internet hackers. In each incident, the hackers have
denounced Japan's involvement in the murderous 1937 sacking of
Nanjing by Imperial Japanese troops. The security breeches have
deeply embarrassed the Japanese government, which has rushed to
create a special task force to catch the intruders. By Howard W.
French.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CONGO (Undated) _ When an unusual meeting of African
leaders and the Security Council ended last week, there was general
agreement that the United Nations will have to be given a major
role in bringing peace to Congo. But when, and in what form, are
still open questions that are expected to dominate council
discussions in coming days. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHER-DEBATE (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ The school voucher
debate is playing out all across the country with increasing
intensity these days as more than 25 legislatures are considering
bills that would create some type of system in which public dollars
would be used for private and parochial schools By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE (Baltimore) _ A $2.5 million federally
financed study at the University of Maryland represents a new wave
in academic medicine: the application of rigorous, Western
scientific methods to test alternative therapies, from ginkgo
biloba to shark cartilage to a mystical Chinese healing art known
as qi gong. Just five years ago, many academics would not have gone
near such studies, for fear they would become a laughingstock. And
while alternative therapies remain hugely controversial,
multimillion dollar clinical trials are getting under way this year
at some of the nation's most prestigious university hospitals. By
Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NH-INDEPENDENTS (Manchester, N.H.) _ Only two days before the
primary in New Hampshire on Tuesday, Bill Bradley and John McCain
are locked in an improbable struggle over a tiny pool of truly
independent voters who are allowed to cast ballots in the
Democratic or Republican contest and _ it turns out _ are torn
between the two men. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DYNASTY (Washington) _ They were on the same platform on
Saturday, George Bush and George W. Bush, father and son, former
president and would-be president, plus the family matriarch,
Barbara Bush, and three of George W.'s four siblings, seeking votes
in the New Hampshire primary. But you will incur the Bushes' wrath
if you compare their family to that other well-known American
political clan, the Kennedys. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
