<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS HANG ON TO BEAT TITANS IN SUPER FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-LEDE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After 27 weeks, through 259 games, the NFL season
ended Sunday at the 1-yard line at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams, not the Tennessee Titans, are Super Bowl
XXXIV champions this morning because, with no timeouts remaining
and time for only one snap for the Titans, the Rams made the last
stop to win, 23-16.
</P>
<P>
   Rams quarterback Kurt Warner was named this game's MVP, getting
13 of a possible 15 first-place votes. But it was Rams outside
linebacker Mike Jones who executed the perfect open-field tackle on
Tennessee receiver Kevin Dyson at the end of a 9-yard pass play
down to the St. Louis 1 as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Both on the surprising underdog Titans ... and on a NFL season
filled with surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, whose miracle return for a touchdown on a trick play in
the final seconds beat Buffalo in the first round of these
playoffs, wound up on his belly on the Georgia Dome turf.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson squirmed, fought and wrenched his 6-foot-1, 195-pound body
in a desperate attempt to break the plane of the goal line with the
tip of the ball held in his outstretched hands.
</P>
<P>
   But Dyson was down.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were out.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rams had their first Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rams, it was a feat this franchise was unable to
complete in Los Angeles, before Georgia Frontiere moved the team to
St. Louis in 1995. For the Titans, formerly the Houston-Tennessee
Oilers, this was their first Super Bowl appearance, and came down
to 1 longest yard, separating defeat from forcing overtime for
Titans' 77-year-old owner, Bud Adams.
</P>
<P>
   This was definitely a game with a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   After spotting the Rams a 16-0 lead, the Titans held on defense
_ except for one 73-yard pass play from Warner to Isaac Bruce _ and
reeled off 16 unanswered points to make a game of it.
</P>
<P>
   The only defensive lapse by the Titans came on the first play of
the Rams' final possession. Warner threw downfield for Bruce.
Titans cornerback Denard Walker slipped and fell. And the home-run
play resulted in a 73-yard touchdown that gave the Rams a 23-16
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to make a play on the ball,'' said Bruce, who
caught six passes for 162 yards, the third-most-prolific receiving
game in Super Bowl history. ``I was dog-tired. Kurt threw it up. I
knew I had to make an adjustment on the ball ... and God did the
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee played about 90 percent man-to-man coverages, and
played the final quarter without either of its starting safeties.
Free safety Marcus Robertson missed the game with a broken ankle
and strong safety Blaine Bishop with a knee sprain, in which he was
taken off the field strapped to stretcher for precautionary
measures.
</P>
<P>
   The play in the Rams' playbook is called ``Nine Ninety-nine,''
and Bruce knew he was going to draw one-on-one coverage. And he
sensed the Titans had to be as tired as he was, or moreso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been moving the ball up and down the field all day, and
there was no reason that we couldn't do it for (the final) two
minutes and put us at least in field-goal range and win this
thing,'' said Warner, who completed 24 of 45 passes for a Super
Bowl-record 414 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, a former Arena League and NFL Europe quarterback who was
working as a stock boy five years ago, threw 41 touchdown passes
this season. He threw two touchdown passes Sunday, including the
73-yard game winner to Bruce on the first play of the Rams' final
drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had one last shot. Quarterback Steve McNair, who
scrambled for a Super Bowl-record 64 yards, ad-libbed for 12 yards
and drew a 15-year face-mask penalty (Dre' Bly) to get Tennessee
into Rams territory. Later on that drive, on third-and-five, McNair
escaped a two-man tackle by defensive ends Kevin Carter and Jay
Williams to hit Dyson for 16 yards to the St. Louis 10.
</P>
<P>
   McNair ``has the heart the size of a basketball,'' Carter said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee burned its final time out.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, the game ended with McNair hitting Dyson
inside the St. Louis 5. Dyson made it to inside the St. Louis 1.
And what would have been the first overtime Super Bowl was averted.
</P>
<P>
   Nerves were on edge when this Super Bowl of ``teams that didn't
belong when this season began'' unfolded. Both teams blew
field-goal opportunities early _ St. Louis twice, Tennessee once.
</P>
<P>
   Rams kicker Jeff Wilkins never had a chance to kick a 34-yard
field goal when holder Mike Horan fumbled the snap on the opening
drive of the game. Then Titans kicker Al Del Greco was wide left
from 47 yards, then, later in the second quarter, Wilkins was wide
right from 34 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams did manage three field-goal drives of 54, 73 and 67
yards in the first half. But in a 9-0 game, the underdog Titans
were allowed to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis ranked second among NFL teams in red-zone offense this
season, scoring 84.7 percent of the time (50 of 59) inside the
opponent's 20, and scoring a touchdown 64.4 percent of the time (38
of 59).
</P>
<P>
   In the first half alone, Warner threw a Super Bowl record 35
times (surpassing Drew Bledsoe's 29 attempts for New England in the
first half of Not even one by accident.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rams had three field-goal drives on five first-half
trips into the red zone. Warner was 0-for-11 in red-zone passing,
19-for-24 everywhere else on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans came out for the second half thinking they could win.
But the momentum slipped away when a 47-yard field-goal attempt by
Al Del Greco was blocked. Rams cornerback Todd Lyght brought
through from the defensive left side to smother the ball on Del
Greco's foot.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Warner hit Torry Holt, whose 109 yards (on
seven catches) were a Super Bowl record for a rookie, for a 9-yard
touchdown play on a quick post, and the Rams took a 16-0 lead on
the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   This was Tennessee's wakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   And it led to the most dramatic ending to a game in Super Bowl
history, all XXXIV of them. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
