<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1456 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-31 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOST, THE BEST, THE GREATEST... THIS WAS REALLY SUPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a Super Bowl that had all the makings of a big
nothing. A couple of longtime nothing teams in a nothing game
providing nothing in the way of a national showcase for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The honest football fan, and certainly skeptical media types,
will admit to having been totally underwhelmed by what Rams-Titans
figured to offer.
</P>
<P>
   But this morning, of course, apologies are in order. And so are
the thank yous. Going back three decades-plus, entertainment,
adventure and thrills have been hard to come by in Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Rams and Titans gave us all that, in addition to the
greatest comeback in Super Bowl history and the greatest finish in
Super Bowl history. Except in No. XXXIV, this finish lasted for the
final quarter and a half, with nonstop, bang-bang action that was
breathtaking, and good to the very last drop.
</P>
<P>
   Or the very last second. Or the very last yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed America what the Super Bowl is all about,'' said St.
Louis Rams coach Dick Vermeil. America certainly agrees.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' 23-16 victory was secured only after unheralded,
veteran linebacker Mike Jones made the most-clutch tackle in Super
Bowl history. (Have you noticed all this
``most...greatest...most...greatest'' stuff?) But that was the name
of this Super Bowl. After a drowsy start, it was the ``most'' and
the ``greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' tackle came at the 1-yard line. As time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Titans receiver Kevin Dyson squirmed in Jones' grasp, fighting
to break loose. But Jones got the takedown, leaving the
second-guessers for quarterback Stece McNair. With no time outs and
six seconds remaining at the snap, why did Steve McNair dare throw
anywhere except the end zone?
</P>
<P>
   But that second-guess is also cheap. First of all, the
McNair-led rally by the Titans from a 16-0 deficit midway through
the third quarter will forever be part of Super Bowl lore. As will
the performance of his Rams counterpart, Kurt Warner, who broke the
Super Bowl passing-yardage record and collected game MVP honors to
go along with season MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   But linebacker Jones answered best why McNair threw underneath
to Dyson, meaning short of the end zone. ``It was man-to-man
coverage,'' said Jones. A linebacker singled up on a wide receiver
_ and Dyson had some separation on Jones _ is a high-percentage
gamble for a quarterback, even with not a second to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job was to wrap him up and get him down,'' said Jones. He
did. Game over. ``Great'' game over. Behind McNair, the Titans had
moved 87 yards in the final 108 seconds, having only one time out.
But 87 yards wasn't the 88 they needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' story, like the Warner story, went the full 180
degrees with this Super Bowl survival Sunday night. From worst team
of the '90s, to world champs. From grocery store stocker/Arena
League nobody, to the best quarterback in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But the Titans had fairy tales of their own to tell about the
season, and about the playoffs, and about making the Super Bowl
after almost 40 years of franchise frustration.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, only one story of record in the first 2 1/2
quarters. It was all about how the Rams had built a 16-0 lead, and
how it could have been double that, and they were apparently on the
way to a blowout kind of win.
</P>
<P>
   But as St. Louis repeatedly malfunctioned in the red zone (five
consecutive trips inside the 20-yard line in the first half
produced nine points), it was obvious the Rams flirted with
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The red-zone problem was no running game from Marshall Faulk.
Warner had thrown 35 times in the first half, hanging up huge
yardage, yet was TD-less. The Rams needed the Faulk alternative,
but it never came, almost proving fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, however, the Rams were breathing easy as receiver
Torry Holt juggled, then grabbed a short Warner TD pass on the
Rams' first possession of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Warner had been 0-for-12 in the red zone until then. But with
the score 16-0, the hully-gully Titans offense appeared to have
zero chance of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, however, started to scramble, and a seasonlong trend
continued. When McNair goes to his feet, the Titans are energized.
Plus, Tennessee had ignored running back Eddie George in the first
half. Wisely, there was no panic, even down by 16 points. George
suddenly got the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was on. The momentum changed quickly. No Super Bowl
team had ever rallied from more than 10 points down, much less done
it in the second half. McNair, however, was a buzz saw. With ease,
he and the Titans erased the 16-0 lead and tied the game with 2:16
to play.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there was a wasted timeout during Tennessee's second
TD drive that would prove costly. So did a failed two-point
conversion after the first TD when McNair flat missed a wide-open
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   But the knife to the Titans came from Rams' big-play man Isaac
Bruce on the first play after it was 16-16. Offensive coordinator
Mike Martz went to the bomb quickly. Warner actually threw short to
a well-covered Bruce, but the receiver slowed, stopped, and caught
the pass. At that point, cornerback Denard Walker fell down. Isaac
Bruce was gone for the game winner. Seventy-three yards of Super
Bowl glory and history.
</P>
<P>
   Except the one minute and 54 seconds remaining was almost too
much to allow McNair and the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   The big nothing had turned out to be the big show. And the best
of all Super Bowls. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
