<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-BOS &LR;      01-31 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS _ BY A YARD 
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pretty boys can be gritty boys, too. And that
makes them champions. Deservedly.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the flashdancing Rams had been bullied by the
brutish Titans as they surrendered a 16-point lead, St. Louis
killed Tennessee with its velvet touch. And then, to keep the
Titans interred, the Rams used the steel grip.
</P>
<P>
   Most Valuable Player Kurt Warner hit Isaac Bruce for a 73-yard
touchdown pass with 1:54 left, giving the Rams a 23-16 victory at
the Georgia Dome Sunday &UR;  &LR; night and deciding perhaps the most
exciting and raucous Super Bowl in the game's 34-year history. But
even that wasn't the climax.
</P>
<P>
   The AFC champion Titans, the Rasputins of the NFL, wouldn't
expire meekly. Passes from heroic quarterback Steve McNair to wide
receiver Kevin Dyson on the last two plays consumed 25 yards.
Unfortunately for the Titans, they needed 26, and thanks to
linebacker Mike Jones, they didn't get them. On first and goal from
the 10 with six seconds left, McNair hit Dyson crossing from the
right, but Jones wrapped him up like a sack of rubies, and the
lunging Dyson came up a yard shy as the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   The death knell seemingly had sounded after Warner, the Arena
Football League and NFL Europe refugee who was an Iowa grocery
clerk five years ago, went for the prime rib. The Rams had the ball
at their 27 for their first play from scrimmage after Eddie George
had left them reeling with his second touchdown run, this one a
2-yarder, and Al Del Greco had converted a 43-yard field goal to
tie it, 16-16, with 2:02 left. But an offense that suddenly had
vanished _ going three downs and out twice in a row after driving
inside the Tennessee 20 on its first six possessions _ wasn't going
to stay back on its heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Martz (the offensive coordinator) had actually wanted to
call that play the previous series when we went one, two, three,
and out,'' said Rams coach Dick Vermeil. ``Earlier in the game, we
had a man open deep but didn't see him. So Mike said this time,
`Let's go for it. If we don't make it, we'll get the first down on
the next two plays. But let's get the ball in the hands of Isaac
Bruce.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Warner found Bruce, one of an array of playmakers on the NFL's
most prolific offense _ or, more accurately, Bruce (6 catches, 162
yards) found the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Warner eluded pressure and unloaded a bomb down the right
sideline as he was decked. The pass was slightly underthrown, and
Bruce stepped back behind Titans defensive back Denard Walker to
snare it. He then skipped around Walker. Titans free safety Anthony
Dorsett _ playing because regular Marcus Robertson had broken his
leg last week _ overpursued, and Bruce romped into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been playing man-to-man coverage all day,'' said
Bruce. ``I came back to get the ball. I saw the safety overrun the
play; that's why I cut back. Then I just ran my ass off.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could cut the heart out of the Titans, not even the
final bit of handiwork by Warner, the league's regular-season MVP,
who completed 24 of 45 passes for a Super Bowl-record 414 yards and
two touchdowns but never saw the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hit in the head,'' said Warner. ``I didn't see (Bruce),
but I knew he caught the ball. I didn't see what he did with it
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did see _ helplessly and in horror _ what the Titans, in
particular McNair, did with their final counterpunch.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over at his 12 with 1:46 to go, McNair parlayed shotgun
scrambles, passes, and Rams penalties to set up a third and 5 from
the St. Louis 26 with 22 seconds left. On the next play, NFL sack
champion Kevin Carter and fellow defensive end Jay Williams
apparently had McNair buried at the right sideline. But he somehow
stepped up and, on the run, gunned a pass to Dyson at the 10.
</P>
<P>
   Time for one more play _ or overtime.
</P>
<P>
   McNair dropped back, and when Vermeil saw the ball in the air,
he immediately phoned Martz to tell him to get a package ready for
OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play we called was for Dyson,'' said McNair.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams had it scoped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was combination coverage,'' said Jones. ``Billy Jenkins
(the strong safety) makes the calls in those situations, and he
made a great one. Both their guys released inside.''
</P>
<P>
   And McNair did what he wanted, hitting Dyson, who could taste a
tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I caught it, I was thinking yellow pay dirt,'' said
Dyson. ``When we called the play, I didn't think anybody would be
in the middle of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was. And he had Dyson dead in his sights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he thought he was going to get in unless I closed
him,'' said Jones. ``But I was planted, and once I was, I said, `No
way this guy gets into the end zone. I've got him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Until the last 22 minutes, it seemed the Rams _ who had parlayed
a tapioca schedule and a supercharged offense into NFC eminence _
had put away the Titans, who had overacheived their way through the
AFC gantlet.
</P>
<P>
   Warner threw the ball 35 times in the first half, shattering the
record of 29 set by the Patriots' Drew Bledsoe three years ago, as
St. Louis pummeled the Titans between the 20s in the first half.
But Tennessee's resilient defense turned the red zone into a black
hole for the Rams, who had to settle for Jeff Wilkins field goals
of 27, 29, and 28 yards. Their two other trips inside the 20
resulted in a botched hold by Mike Horan on Wilkins's initial field
goal bid and a miss from 34 yards by Wilkins, who will undergo
surgery next week for tendinitis in his planting leg. So the
halftime lead was 9-0, and as usual, the Titans were hanging
around, even if they looked dazed doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were frustrated,'' said Vermeil. ``We were the best
red-zone team in the NFL and we weren't getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   They did on their first possession of the third quarter after
Del Greco, who had missed a 47-yard kick in the first half, had
another 47-yarder blocked by Todd Lyght.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams made their sixth straight trip to the red zone, and
this time Warner cashed in, finding Torry Holt (a rookie-record 7
catches for 109 yards) with a 9-yard scoring strike on which Holt
shed Walker.
</P>
<P>
   That made it 16-0, and given the Titans' offensive prowess to
that point, it might as well have been 160-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the protean McNair, who completed 22 of 36 passes for 214
yards and ran 8 times for 64 yards _ a Super Bowl record for a QB _
and the indomitable George (28 carries, 95 yards) started pounding
and gouging away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to move the ball and got into our game plan,''
said George. ``We were able to run the ball and throw the ball
downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's 23-yard scramble _ yet another Super Bowl rushing
record for a quarterback _ to the 2 set up George's 1-yard scoring
blast off left tackle near the end of the third quarter. And even
though McNair misfired on a 2-point conversion toss to Frank
Wycheck, the Titans still had a pulse, trailing, 16-6. Then Del
Greco and George capped the comeback. For a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our defense caught its breath at halftime,'' said
Titans coach Jeff Fisher. ``We were on the field the whole first
half. We made some adjustments. We made up our minds at halftime we
were going to win this game. I credit Kurt Warner on the big play
or it's a different ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Rams' reinvented, pathologically emotional coach,
Vermeil _ who left the game for 14 years not long after losing the
1981 Super Bowl with the Philadelphia Eagles _ finally has
something to really get weepy over. And cosmetically challenged
owner Georgia Frontiere can apply her makeup in front of the
glittering Vince Lombardi Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And the city of St. Louis, which lured the Rams from Los Angeles
five years ago to replace the Cardinals, has its first world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tough town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
