<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER'S STORY BOOK SEASON ENDS WITH ANOTHER MVP PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-MVP-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At this point, the obligatory trip to Disney World as
the Super Bowl MVP will be anti-climactic for Rams quarterback Kurt
Warner, whose wishes upon a star have come true all season.
</P>
<P>
   Warner's storybook season, which began when this former Arena
League and NFL Europe refugee was thrown in the starting lineup
because of an injury to Trent Green in the preseason, ended in
storybook fashion in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who was named the NFL MVP after throwing 41 touchdown
passes in the regular season, passed for a Super Bowl record 414
yards and threw two touchdown passes. His 73-yard game-winning toss
to Isaac Bruce with 1 minute, 54 seconds remaining gave the St.
Louis Rams a 23-16 victory against the Tennessee Titans at the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Rams coach Dick Vermeil said fairy tales don't apply when you're
talking about his second-year quarterback, whose incredible story
should serve as an example to everyone that anything is possible if
you believe in yourself and work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt Warner is Kurt Warner,'' Vermeil said. ``He is not a
fairy tale. This is real life. He is an example of what we all like
to believe in on and off the field. He is an example of persistence
and believing in himself and a deep faith. He was willing to work
and play a subordinate role until he got his opportunity. What else
can you write? He is a book, he is a movie, the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner's on-field story is accompanied by wonderful off-field
story, which includes being deeply religious and a strong family
man. He met his wife, Brenda, while working as a grocery stocker.
She stuck by him when he couldn't get a job playing in NFL after he
finished college at Northern Iowa. Warner, 28, stuck with her,
marrying her and adopting her handicapped son from a previous
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   His heartwarming story spawned Warner-mania in St. Louis, and
movie executives are already talking about putting his life on
film.
</P>
<P>
   Just like he has all season, Warner remained grounded after the
game, downplaying his personal triumph, while relishing in the
Rams' first Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   ``First things first, I got to give the praise and glory to my
Lord and Saviour,'' Warner said. ``Thank you, Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of my story as a Hollywood story,'' Warner
continued. ``It's my life. Everything that's happened is
tremendous. I always believed in myself, and I've got a whole bunch
of people in here that believed in me. I'm blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner was close to brilliant against Titans, completing 24 of
45 passes to nine different receivers. His 277 passing yards in the
first half were second in Super Bowl history to the 307 by Doug
Williams of the Redskins in Super Bowl XXII.
</P>
<P>
   Also, his 35 first-half passing attempts are a record for the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   However, while Warner dazzled the Titans statistically in the
first half, he couldn't get them in the end zone. Five consecutive
drives inside the Titans' 20-yard line resulted in only three field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Warner changed that in the third quarter when hit Torry Holt on
slant from 9 yards out to give St. Louis a 16-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Warner and the Rams' offense bogged down until the two minutes
when he found Bruce for the game winner.
</P>
<P>
   Titans defensive back Samari Rolle echoed Vermeil after the game
when he said Warner was just being Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the MVP of the league, and that's how he played,'' Rolle
said. ``He's been doing that all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Making magic Disney would be proud of. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
