<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     01-31 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WARNER, REAL-LIFE TALL TALE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Five years ago he was asking, ``Paper or plastic?''
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night Kurt Warner bagged the Super Bowl MVP Award.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV _ perhaps the best yet, and certainly the first
to live up to its hype _ brought one of the great sports stories of
our time to Main Street, USA, as Warner completed his journey from
grocery clerk in Cedar Falls, Iowa, to American folk hero in a
23-16 St. Louis Rams victory over the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Rams coach Dick Vermeil said, ``It's not a fairy tale. It's real
life. He's a great example of persistence and believing in yourself
and having willingness to work. What else can you write? He is a
book, he is a movie, this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank all the players and coaches and everybody for
believing in me,'' Warner said at midfield, holding the Super Bowl
trophy aloft while gold confetti fell around his head.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting memory of this game will be that of Tennessee
wideout Kevin Dyson reaching for a final yard he could not get as
time and space ran out on the noble Titans. But two minutes earlier
it was Warner who made the biggest play of his life for the winning
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had battled back from 16-0 to tie the game, 16-16,
with 2:16 left when Warner struck with a 73-yard touchdown pass
play to Isaac Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been moving the ball all day and there was no reason we
couldn't move the ball again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the first snap from scrimmage, with all the momentum gone to
Nashville, Warner dropped back and floated a long pass down the
right sideline to Bruce. Warner was flattened by Jevon Kearse as he
released the ball (``I couldn't see it,'' said the quarterback. ``I
got my head up enough to see him come back, but I couldn't tell'').
The long pass was slightly underthrown, but Bruce came back to it,
made the catch, and ran into history. ABC cut to Brenda Warner,
Kurt's wife, celebrating in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Warner threw for more yards than anyone in Super Bowl history,
completing 24 of 45 passes for a record 414 yards. In the first
half, which ended with St. Louis leading, 9-0, he completed a
whopping 19 of 35 passes for 277 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Rams caught passes. He threw short and long. He connected
on crossing patterns and sideline routes. Early in the third, he
broke an 0-for-12 red zone slump, hitting rookie Torry Holt for a
9-yard touchdown pass. It was 16-0 and Warner was halfway to Disney
World.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their success, the Rams didn't get much national TV face
time in 1999. Warner's story was well worn on sports pages and
weekly magazines, but Sunday &UR;  &LR; night he crossed into mainstream
America. The made-for-TV movie can't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of my story as a Hollywood story. It's just my
life,'' said Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many great American tales, the story begins in Iowa.
Warner was a skinny ninth-grader when he showed up at Regis High in
Cedar Rapids and said he'd like to be a wide receiver. The astute
coach asked the tall boy to throw a couple of passes, and decided
that young Kurt would be better off at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He made it all the way to the University of Northern Iowa, but
didn't start until he was a fifth-year senior. The Panthers were
bounced out of the Division 1-AA playoffs that year when they lost
to Boston University at Nickerson Field in double overtime. The BU
quarterback was Robert Dougherty. Try to find anyone in Greater
Boston who attended the game and noticed Kurt Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was a rookie hopeful with the Packers in 1994, but they
were pretty deep at quarterback. They had Brett Favre, Mark
Brunell, and Ty Detmer. When your third-string guy is a Heisman
winner, it doesn't bode well for a kid from Northern Iowa. Green
Bay coaches Mike Holmgren and Steve Mariucci sent Warner home to
Cedar Falls, where he went to work bagging groceries at Hy-Vee.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't bagging, Warner sent out football resumes and
tapes. The NFL and Canadian Football League teams passed on him, so
he went to the Arena Football League and played for the mighty Iowa
Barnstormers of Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was off to the Netherlands, where he played for
the Amsterdam Admirals of NFL Europe. He led the European League in
yardage, attempts, completions, and touchdowns. There were several
reporters from Amsterdam at  &UR; last night &LR; 's Super Bowl. Bet they
weren't in Miami for last year's game.
</P>
<P>
   After his year in Europe, Warner resumed calling NFL teams with
little success. The Rams were the 13th team he contacted. Former
Patriots scouting director Charlie Armey (now the Rams' general
manager) gave the journeyman kid a shot. Warner wears No. 13 to
remind himself of the 12 rejections.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was the No. 3 quarterback for the Rams in 1998, but
didn't play until the final game of the season. The Rams brought
Trent Green in from Washington this past offseason, but Green blew
out his knee in the next-to-last exhibition game and Vermeil told
the troops that Warner was going to be The Man.
</P>
<P>
   He was The Man, winning the regular-season MVP award. At the age
of 28, after six years of rollerball, Euroball, and No Ball. He was
an overnight success in the biggest, baddest league of them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anybody tell you you can't accomplish something,''
he said. ``I believe in myself and there's nothing on the field we
can't accomplish. We worked hard for this and they stuck with me
through this whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   If you watched the game Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, you saw many TV shots of
Brenda Warner. She is a huge part of this incredible story. Brenda
was a divorced mother of two when she met Kurt. Her older child,
since adopted by Kurt, is disabled because of a head injury
suffered when he was an infant. Her parents were killed by a
tornado in Arkansas in 1996. She married Kurt a year later and they
have a son of their own. Small wonder Kurt and Brenda Warner are
extremely devout young adults.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big deal two years ago when John Elway finally got his
Super Bowl ring. This is even bigger. Kurt Warner. MVP of the best
Super Bowl of them all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
