<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS FINALLY PROVE THEMSELVES TO EVERYONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Take a deep breath, and then give the St. Louis Rams
their props. They are the champions.
</P>
<P>
   They are the best team in the NFL. They were the best team in
the regular season, and they were the best team Sunday in their
23-16 Super Bowl victory against the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever can take that from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you saw,'' Rams coach Dick Vermeil said, ``was no
fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   They no longer have to apologize for their schedule. So what
that the only three victories they had against teams with winning
records came in the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   They no longer have to hear that their statistics were
artificially produced. So what that they played only two defenses
ranked in the top 10?
</P>
<P>
   It should no longer be asked if they could beat the 1998 Denver
Broncos, the 1997 Denver Broncos, the 1996 Green Bay Packers or the
1995 Cowboys. So what that the NFL was watered down this season?
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing matters anymore: The Rams have a Lombardi Trophy
in their display case and rings on their fingers. They are No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, the Rams scored the third-most points
in NFL history. They outscored their opponents by 284 points, the
second-highest differential in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   During the postseason, they beat the Minnesota Vikings with
offense; they beat the Tampa Bay Buccaneers with defense; and they
beat the Tennessee Titans with heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're world champions,'' Rams quarterback Kurt Warner
screamed. ``How about them Rams?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams proved their point.
</P>
<P>
   They were great in the regular season. They were the greatest in
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest of strange seasons saw the Rams and Titans produce
the most dramatic finish in Super Bowl history.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the Titans' eight-play, 28-yard drive that led
to an Al Del Greco field goal and a 16-16 tie with 2:12 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 18 seconds later, there was Warner's 73-yard touchdown
pass to Isaac Bruce that gave the Rams a 23-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 1:54 later, it was St. Louis linebacker Mike Jones making
a textbook tackle on Titans receiver Kevin Dyson at the Rams' 1 as
the gun sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams made the plays when they needed to. They made them when
they had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the plays when we had to make them, and we're world
champions,'' Vermeil said. ``We showed America what Super Bowls are
supposed to be about.''
</P>
<P>
   Say anything you want about the Rams. Just make sure you call
them champions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0021 </DOCNO>
