u s BC-TEN-AUSTRALIANOPEN-BO     01-31 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI READY TO TAKE ON THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ So now Andre Agassi is a bodyguard for a couple of
geezers called McEnroe and Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Just a part-time job, you understand, but Agassi is one of those
hypercharged guys for whom no reach is too far. Some people want to
boss towns. Agassi deals in continents. Having just collected
Australia, he will now take on Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi was saying to a Russian named Yevgeny Kafelnikov Saturday
in Rod Laver Arena that this continent isn't big enough for both of
them. Kafelnikov disputed that contention and knocked Agassi around
for a half-hour. But he didn't guard his own body closely enough.
Agassi got off the hard rock floor and proved his point by winning
the Australian Open for a second time, his sixth major, 3-6, 6-3,
6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's triumph climaxed the most resplendent fortnight ever in
the Aussie for Americans, who were winners in all five events. He
and Lindsay Davenport pulled off the first singles double by
home-grown Yanks since Californians Don Budge and Dodo Bundy won in
1938. Sharing the doubles prizes were Californian Rick Leach with
South African Ellis Ferreira, Pennsylvanian Lisa Raymond with
Aussie Rennae Stubbs, and Floridian Jared Palmer with Stubbs.
</P>
<P>
   First prize for Agassi is $485,000. His second prize is a free
ride halfway around the world to Harare, Zimbabwe, where he will
hunt a couple of local lions named Byron and Wayne Black on behalf
of the newly anointed US Davis Cup captain, 40-year-old John
Patrick McEnroe Jr.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe will need all the protection from the Zimbabweans that
he can get from Agassi because his dreams of an invincible 1-2
punch of Agassi and Pete Sampras were punctured when Sampras called
in sick the other day. Then so did Todd Martin, a mainstay last
year when Agassi and Sampras passed.
</P>
<P>
   There's a limit to how well Agassi can shield his captain. He
can probably win both his singles matches, but it's a five-match
series beginning Friday, and the pesky little Black brothers, who
grew up playing barefoot on their old man's avocado patch, are
capable of taking the other three points. They beat Australia in
the first round (in Australia) in 1998, and they gave the Cup
champs a close scrape last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although McEnroe shamed Sampras into enlisting by calling on him
publicly to do his tennis duty, the captain said he never believed
Sampras would show. Nobody really wants to make this safari, the
first US visit to Africa, anyway, but it was the luck of the draw.
Is it all in Sampras's hip, or his head, that he doesn't want to
track fierce Zimbabweans while wearing a pith helmet? He said he
strained his right hip in the first set while losing to Agassi in
the semis, although he competed splendidly the rest of the five-set
way. McEnroe must accept it.
</P>
<P>
   Mention of Sampras brings up security man Agassi's other client,
63-year-old Roy Emerson, deadlocked with Sampras at the male record
of 12 major singles championships. Emmo, a good old boy Aussie
residing in California, appears defenseless against the Sampras
surge that began with the US Open title of 1990. He hung on to the
record all alone from 1967 until Sampras took his 12th last year at
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been thrilling watching Pete go after the record, and if
he gets it, that's great,'' Agassi said. ``But I won't be happy if
he gets it at my expense. I'll do everything in my power to prevent
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He did just that last week, whacking Sampras even though he was
two points from defeat in their fourth-set tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   That was superb bodyguarding and good news in Blackbutt, a
cattle and timber town of 800 souls in the remote never-never land
of Queensland, the one-saloon settlement where Emerson was reared.
An old pal of Emmo's, Kevin Allery, said over the phone, ``We
really enjoyed Agassi beating Sampras. The Curse of Blackbutt is
still alive. We've got an Aboriginal witch doctor working on it.
Pete may have a piece of the record, but he'll never top Roy.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not, now that Agassi has emerged from the phone
booth in which he appeared trapped three years ago, looking like
supermasher of rubber lemons, and is in the chase with six majors
himself _ three in the last eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accomplished more in those eight months than I ever
dreamed of,'' said Agassi of a wondrous swirl that has embraced
conquests of France, the United States, and Australia; a divorce
from one celebrated woman, Brooke Shields; and the squiring of
another, Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   That's only the beginning, in his view. ``I want to do
everything,'' which means another Olympic gold in September,
retrieving the Davis Cup (last won by the United States five years
ago), and blocking Sampras's route with his own body. Collaterally,
he also would be keeping McEnroe and Emerson undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   Strong is good, but stronger is better in the Agassi canon. ``I
intend to get stronger. The stronger you are, the heavier the
rallying stroke, the more snap to your shots. I'm a better player
than I was winning here five years ago,'' said Agassi, who turns 30
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Agassi was a very fine player, bursting with gifts
but not necessarily the desire to unwrap them with hard
conditioning labor. He regrets probably throwing away the French
Opens of 1990 and 1991, when he got to the finals casually trained
and couldn't beat the faded Andres Gomez and rising Jim Courier.
</P>
<P>
   Those guys are passe, and so is the Agassi of 1995, who looked
like a refugee from ``The Pirates of Penzance'' in head scarf, bold
earrings, and shorts that could have doubled as a buccaneer's
spinnaker. He has been fun, going through all the changes _ nail
polish, magenta ensembles, ponytail, and horselaugh. But now, in
pristine white, head shaved, he's become a head-breaking warrior
who must be considered among the all-time greats _ and rising.
</P>
<P>
   His firepower is astounding, particularly when you consider how
few are his blunders. His serve intimidates with accuracy rather
than power, and he can run for weeks. He's adept at mixing up
shotmaking, as Kafelnikov dourly discovered when Agassi's five
perfect drop shots at important junctures made him feel
quicksanded.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be his teammates in Africa? ``I don't know, and I don't
think John (McEnroe) knew when he got on the plane in New York,''
he said. ``Losing Sampras and probably Martin is unfortunate. Maybe
Chris Woodruff, who played so well against Pete, will be picked.
Doubles? Martin was going to play. Maybe Rick Leach and Alex
O'Brien.''
</P>
<P>
   If the rules were altered, McEnroe's choices would be easy. Just
select his bodyguard for all four singles. And maybe the doubles,
too, alongside the aged captain himself?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
