<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COUNTED, RAMS' BIG-PLAY OFFENSE PAID OFF
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-RAMS-OFFENSE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The big-play Rams used, you guessed it, a big play to
win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise. Surprise.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't think the video-game Rams _ who scored the
third-highest point total in NFL history and had 62 pass plays of
20 or more yards in the regular season _ would be looking to settle
for a game-winning field goal attempt when they got the ball one
last time Sunday, did you?
</P>
<P>
   Rams receiver Isaac Bruce certainly didn't. He hauled in the
73-yard prayer that came via quarterback Kurt Warner's arm and gave
the St. Louis Rams a 23-16 victory over the Tennessee Titans in
Super Bowl XXXIV at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't me that was God,'' said Bruce, who caught six
passes for 162 yards, the third-highest total in Super Bowl
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all God. I just knew I had to make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce got the chance after the Titans scored tied the score at
16 with 2 minutes, 12 seconds to go. With go-for-broke offensive
coordinator Mike Martz at the controls, he said he knew the Rams
were going to go deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk about it,'' Bruce said. ``I just know his
personality. He likes to throw it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rams did, on the first play from their own 27-yard line.
The play, called ``ninety-nine nine,'' had Bruce working against
one-on-one coverage from Titans cornerback Denard Walker. Bruce
sprinted down the right sideline and Warner threw the ball a little
short. But the Rams' preacher-man receiver adjusted to the pass,
while Walker fell to the turf.
</P>
<P>
   A juke and a sprint later, Bruce was in the end zone and the
Rams were in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was not surprised that Bruce, who led the Rams with 12
touchdown receptions in the regular season, was the one who ended
things. He preferred it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the play called earlier and they came back and told me
Isaac could eat him,'' Warner said. ``I knew we needed a big play
and Isaac is our go-to-guy. He came up with the big play for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The play was particularly deflating for the Titans defense,
which despite giving up a bushel of yards to Warner, had done its
job by keeping the Rams from making big plays, and out of the end
zone for a good portion of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And after giving up a 9-yard touchdown pass to Torry Holt to
make the score 16-0 in the third quarter, the Titans defense found
a way to stop the Rams. St. Louis' only two punts of the game came
between the touchdowns by Holt and Bruce. At the same time, the
Tennessee offense rallied for 16 points and the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep them in front of us,'' Titans cornerback
Samari Rolle said. ``We did that up until the last play. Bruce made
the catch and we didn't make the tackle. We came up short.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
