<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLIVER' WILL STICK WITH STECKEL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The greatest Super Bowl ever was in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Les Steckel sat in the Tennessee coaching room high above the
field and loved what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed 10 yards. When I saw that, I got excited,'' Steckel
said. ``We had the perfect play for that situation. I knew we could
get a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Steckel, the offensive coordinator of the Tennessee Titans,
leaned forward and sent orders down to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sliver Right. Sliver Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall in the St. Louis coaches box, Rams defensive
coordinator Peter Giunta wondered what Steckel would do. Like
Steckel, he faced the biggest call of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Fischer vs. Boris Spassky. Steckel vs. Giunta, in the most
critical situation in Super Bowl history.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the time left (just six seconds) I thought they were
going to throw,'' Giunta said. ``I know they loved to run, and they
killed us with the run in the fourth period, but I thought they
would throw. We called a combination coverage where we would have
three of our guys covering two of theirs. We thought the ball would
go to a wide receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was holding on for dear life. The Titans already had
roared back from a 16-point third-quarter deficit, only to fall
behind, 23-16, on a 73-yard Rams touchdown with 1:54 to play.
Tennessee again came back, moving to the St. Louis 10-yard line,
but now had time for just one more play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had practiced this play three times (Sliver Right),'' said
Steckel. ``And every time it worked. We got the coverage against us
that we thought we would, but it just didn't happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Steve McNair went back to pass and looked to his
right. He watched for his tight end to clear underneath the
three-man zone Giunta had put together, and saw wide receiver Kevin
Dyson slanting toward the middle of the field. McNair, who had not
thrown well most of the night, threw a perfect strike to Dyson, who
caught the ball at the 4-yard line and had to get into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   But linebacker Mike Jones saved the game and the world
championship for the Rams. ``On our coverage I just drop back and
look for someone coming inside,'' Jones said. ``I saw the wide
receiver coming, so I broke on the ball and went for him. I knew we
were near the goal line. But I didn't think about anything else but
getting him on the ground. Nothing else mattered. I just wanted to
get him on the ground. When I did, I knew he didn't make it. He was
still on the 1-yard line.''
</P>
<P>
   Steckel was shattered. All his brilliant work calling plays over
the last 20 minutes and moving Tennessee into position for a
remarkable victory evaporated in front of his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens under pressure is that a player tends to do
things a little too quickly,'' Steckel said. ``They cut things
short. Our guy (Dyson) did that. He should have run a little deeper
before he made his move into the end zone. But that's what happens.
I feel so sorry for our guys. Putting up such a great battle and
coming so close was hard to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Giunta knew his defensive unit, which had completely shut down
Tennessee in the first 40 minutes, was lucky to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were beating us physically at the end of the game,'' he
said. ``Their offense wore our guys out. We were tired. I give them
all the credit in the world for being behind like that and still
running the ball. Les made some great calls for them.''
</P>
<P>
   What Steckel, a former Patriots coach under Raymond Berry, did
in the fourth quarter was completely unorthodox. Teams just don't
continue to run the ball down 16 points with time running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, we had 23 plays. They had 50. We weren't
playing our game,'' Steckel said. ``We were calling in running
plays, but Steve was reading the defense and checking to passes. He
went for what he thought would be the better play. But it wasn't
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the half, I told our team we had to go out there and beat
them up. We knew we could beat them up physically. That's our game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded them of a game we had with Tampa Bay a year ago.
Tampa Bay has a great defense, and they had us down, 17-3, at the
half. We still ran the ball in the second half, and took it to them
to win the game. They couldn't believe it after the game, and they
admitted it. I told them we were going to run and keep on
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee did just that. After rushing for just 30 yards in the
first half, the Titans finished with 159 on the ground against the
No. 1 defense in the league against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it going our way in the first half,'' said Giunta. ``We
put them in third-down-and-long situations, and we got them off the
field. They couldn't convert on third down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (late) in the third period, they started going to the
running game and making big gains on first down. First down started
to kill us and they kept pounding the ball. In two games we played
against these guys this year, they did not turn the ball over once,
and we are a defense that has taken the ball away from teams all
year. Twice in the fourth period we had a chance to make an
interception and stop them, but we didn't make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, the Titans beat St. Louis in Tennessee,
24-21. The Titans led, 21-0, in the second period, and St. Louis
came roaring back at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Both games were settled on the final play of the game. In
Tennessee, the Titans won when St. Louis missed a field goal to tie
it. Sunday night, St. Louis won when the Titans missed the tying
touchdown by a yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game time ran out on them,'' said Tennessee wide
receivers coach Steve Walter. ``The clock saved us. Today, the
clock saved them. That's how close these two teams are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
