<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELANGER TRIES TO ROLL WITH THE PUNCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After missing 34 games because of post-concussion
syndrome, left wing Ken Belanger returned to the Bruins' lineup
Saturday night against the Buffalo Sabres at the FleetCenter. He
only logged three shifts and just more than two minutes of ice time
in Boston's 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said he eased Belanger back, but conceded
Belanger has a specialized role and hopes his enforcer understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he'd stop worrying about everything. He worries about
everything,'' said Burns, whose team takes on the Anaheim Mighty
Ducks Monday night at the FleetCenter. ``He worries a lot about
(Gino) Odjick playing a regular shift, but the Islanders are out of
it and we're in it. He worries about a lot of things like that. He
worries about (Washington forward) Chris Simon, but Chris Simon has
been in the league for a while. How many full seasons has
(Belanger) had? We have to work with him on that and spend some
time with him. He has to stop worrying about all that crap.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said all players who primarily are enforcers go through
some sort of an identity crisis at some point in their careers.
Belanger said he wants to make his game more complete, but Burns
said the 25-year-old shouldn't be distracted by what goes on with
other players on other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a common thing with those types of players,'' said Burns.
``I had it with (Ken) Baumgartner in Toronto. We had the same
situation with him. The way they have to think is, `This is what I
do, this is what I've got to do best.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Stu Grimson has the same thing in Anaheim. You have to come to
terms with that, that this is your job. Like Grimson says, (he
creates) a safe environment for his teammates. If you don't accept
that job, you've got to do something a hell of a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the enforcers he's had in the past eventually have
come to terms with their role.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not until they understand they can make a pretty good
living at it if they do it well,'' he said, ``like Baumgartner came
to terms with it and so did (John) Kordic and Grimson. They sold it
to us. We didn't sell it to them. They sold that package to us,
that that was the player they were. But then when they get into it,
they start thinking they should do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said some have suggested Belanger be used on the power
play because of his booming shot, which has been a hit at skills
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the skills competition, you have time to set it there and
take a running start. Sure, your shot is going to be hard, but when
you have pressure on you, everything is bang, bang, it's a
different story,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Burns appreciates that the enforcer's role isn't easy. ``You
have to really respect them because it is a tough job to have to go
out and do that and maybe not getting the ice time,'' he said.
``Marty (McSorley) made himself a better player, but he knows his
role and still does it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger said he understands Burns's point of view but still
wants to challenge himself to be a more complete player. He knows
the layoff has affected his conditioning, but said he would like to
work his way into more ice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your first two years, you don't expect too much, but the more
years you play in the league, the more respect you get and the more
room you get on the ice and the more you can expand your game,'' he
said. ``You get to build the coach's confidence and he can put you
in different situations like I did in the playoffs last year, where
I got to play regular. It takes time to prove yourself. When you
get a regular shift, you're not worried about making a bad pass and
not getting another shift. It's all part of the game that takes
time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Joe Murphy, who felt ill after the game Saturday,
didn't practice Sunday because he was still under the weather.
Burns said he expects Murphy to be fine Monday night . . . Burns
said it's likely center Shawn Bates (wrist injury) and left wing
Joe Hulbig (groin injury) will be sidelined until after this
weekend's All-Star break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
