<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING CHEATED, CAYARD FIGHTS FOR SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ AmericaOne was licking its wounds Sunday
as Prada resisted the irresistible: envisioning itself as the
winner of the Louis Vuitton Cup next week, and sailing for the
America's Cup Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   During the lay day, both camps went on, business as usual,
getting ready for Monday's Race 5 of the nine-race series.
</P>
<P>
   Up, 3-1, Prada must win only two of the next five, while
AmericaOne has to win four. It's a tall order, but AmericaOne
skipper Paul Cayard ignores the loss column.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to do what we had to do yesterday,'' he said,
``win four races.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the last two AmericaOne losses, one in which
AmericaOne got beaten up in a gale that Prada survived and the
other in which a controversial penalty call in the last 300 yards
took it out of the lead, the future looks bleak.
</P>
<P>
   How does Cayard now rally his troops to the daunting task of
winning four against battle-toughened Prada?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving (my crew) much rah-rah talk,'' said Cayard,
looking forward to a few hours of recuperation and preparation time
before Race 5. ``They don't need that. They're as tough as I am. We
all feel pretty cheated by the (race-ending penalty) call. We just
can't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard was reflecting on AmericaOne's misfortunes on the last
leg of Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is that the wind died. If the wind had stayed
up, they would not have caught up. So first the wind dies, then
they catch up, and the penalty just finished us off.''
</P>
<P>
   Very much like a charge/block call in basketball _ and subject
to interpretation _ the umpire boats called the penalty on the
final run to the finish. After conferring by radio, two umpire
boats _ one astern of each racer _ decided AmericaOne was guilty of
violating Rule 11 of the canons of maritime law known as
International Regulations for Preventing Collisions at Sea, from
which modern race rules are derived.
</P>
<P>
   The situation: On the final run, the Italian Luna Rossa, sailing
in more breeze and 3 knots faster, closed from behind AmericaOne.
Skipper Francesco de Angelis was on the advantaged starboard tack,
and Cayard gybed to windward, putting AmericaOne on starboard with
Luna Rossa to leeward.
</P>
<P>
   Luna Rossa gradually gained an overlap to leeward and, as the
boats came close together, both protest ``Y'' flags went up.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires penalized AmericaOne under Rule 11, which states:
``When boats are on the same tack, and overlapped, a windward boat
(AmericaOne) shall keep clear of a leeward boat (Luna Rossa).''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they found Luna Rossa not to have violated
Rule 17, which AmericaOne accused it of doing: ``A boat that
establishes a leeward overlap (Luna Rossa) . . . shall not sail
above her proper course during that overlap.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cayard and tactician John Kostecki maintain that Luna
Rossa did sail above proper course (the straightest line to the
finish), the umpires saw it differently and flagged only AmericaOne
for Rule 11.
</P>
<P>
   With AmericaOne leading just slightly at that point, the
penalty, requiring a 270-degree turn, was fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goes up must come down again,'' Torben Grael, Italy's
tactician, said afterward, referring to the race at the end of the
semifinals in which the umpires ruled in AmericaOne's favor in a
similar confrontation. ``The difference (between that race and
this) is that we were not sailing above proper course today.
(Cayard) tried to sail below and squeeze us up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grael was still steamed about an earlier confrontation on
the Leg 2 run. During a luffing match, AmericaOne ripped its
spinnaker, and with just a mainsail up was able to luff Luna Rossa
so high the Italian boat spun out of control in the 25-knot wind,
coming almost head to wind, with the spinnaker in mayhem. By the
time the crew got the boat under control, Prada had lost more than
half a minute.
</P>
<P>
   During the flurry, both boats raised protest flags and shouted
exchanges, but the umpires green-flagged (no-foul) both boats.
Grael still maintains Cayard violated the ``seamanship'' clause in
the rules by luffing Luna Rossa as hard as he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was unseamanlike,'' Grael said. ``If one boat
doesn't have a spinnaker and the other boat has one up in 25 knots
. . . if that's not unseamanlike, I don't know what is.''
</P>
<P>
   So no love is lost as the two boats square off Monday in what
has become AmericaOne's fight for survival. Two more losses and the
United States faces the prospect of the first America's Cup in the
event's 149-year history without an American boat.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard has won such fights before _ most notably in 1992, when
he came from behind, 1-3, to beat New Zealand, 4-3, in the Louis
Vuitton finals.
</P>
<P>
   But that was seven years ago in vapid San Diego, against an
opponent that was unraveling fast. Facing a tough, solid opponent
out on the washing machine of Hauraki Gulf, it's hard to see how
history will help AmericaOne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
