<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-NORTHEASTERN-DREX     01-31 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHEASTERN-DREXEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREXEL BEATS NORTHEASTERN AT BUZZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston's America East basketball fans are glad to see
Drexel senior guard Bryant Coursey leave town.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Coursey delivered his second winning shot of the weekend,
sinking a one-handed runner off the glass with less than a second
to play and giving the Dragons a 57-56 victory over Northeastern at
Cabot Gym. His off-balance 12-footer with four seconds left gave
Drexel a 62-61 overtime win at Boston University Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special weekend for him,'' said Drexel coach Steve
Seymour. ``I don't know how many players in Division 1 have made
game-winning shots in back-to-back games like he has. It was just a
special weekend for a special kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Coursey, who ended up with 12 points: ``I was just trying
to get to the basket. I was hoping to get fouled and win it that
way with a couple of free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   While Coursey stood in the middle of a happy mob of teammates
and celebrated Drexel's stunning rally from an 11-point deficit
with 2:52 to go, Northeastern coach Rudy Keeling darted across the
court, went into the stands behind press row, and heatedly
complained to Charles Diehl, America East coordinator of officials,
about the officiating of William Laubenstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played well enough to win and I felt Drexel
played very well in coming back and getting back into the game,''
Keeling told reporters after the game. ``When it comes down to one
shot, you'd like to think your guys can defend for one shot. We're
up 11 with less than three minutes to go and we got a lot of foul
calls, a lot of little calls which stopped the momentum. They just
marched to the line and stopped the flow and it really hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the one official (Laubenstein) was the official we had in
Vermont (an 85-82 loss Jan. 21) and he called a very poor game in
Vermont and I let him know about it,'' Keeling said. ``I'll let you
see the tape, but the first call he called for us (Sunday) was when
he called the foul against them right at the end (with 10.2 seconds
left) and George (Aygar) shot the foul shot. It was the first time
he called a foul for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if you get mad at me, but you don't, as an adult,
take the game away from the kids, and that's what happened. I
thought he took it away from us. No way was there enough time for
them to win the game unless he consciously did that. I know it
sounds like sour grapes because we lost, but if we had won by 1, it
would've been the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeling's plea to Diehl fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of his buddies, so he's not gonna (do anything),''
Keeling said. ``He saw the game like we saw the game. If he was
honest about it, he would've said, `I thought there was something
strange,' if nothing else. There's nothing he can do about it now,
but at least he could've been fair about it and he wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 31-21 halftime lead, the Huskies (4-15 overall,
2-8 conference) appeared well on their way to victory when Aygar
(who had a team-high 12 points) hit a baseline jumper that gave NU
a 54-43 lead with 2:53 to go. The Dragons (9-11, 6-4) then went on
a 12-2 run and pulled within 1 (56-55) when Ashley Howard knocked
down a line-drive trey with 1:08 left.
</P>
<P>
   NU's Cortez Bond committed a costly turnover with 32.6 seconds
left but atoned for the miscue when he blocked a shot by Stephen
Starks to give NU possession with 11.7 seconds left. Aygar took the
inbounds pass, was immediately fouled by Robert Battle, and went to
the line for a crucial one-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   Aygar, however, opened the door for Coursey's heroic shot when
he missed the front end. Starks controlled the rebound for Drexel
and worked the ball to Coursey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some stupid things,'' Keeling said. ``I mean, we threw
the ball away, and we didn't execute and we didn't make our shots
when we had a chance. All those things would've won the game, but
to put us in that situation is a different story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
