<HEADLINE>
CELTICS PACE THEMSELVES FOR INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ The Celtics had three days to prepare for
Tuesday's game against Indiana. That appears to be an optimal
amount of time for the team members to gain perspective and for
coach Rick Pitino to instruct them in the ways and means of the
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a two-fold advantage,'' Pitino said Sunday. ``There
is the advantage of getting ready for the team that has the
strongest home-court advantage in the league, and this will allow
us to get healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana is 18-2 and has a 15-game winning streak at home. The
Pacers have not lost in Indianapolis since a 107-99 defeat against
Detroit Nov. 25. That was three days after a 95-85 loss to the
Celtics in Boston and marked a low point in the Indiana season. The
Pacers have won 22 of 31 games since.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Celtics have won only four games on the road.
Pitino said the Celtics' road failures have often resulted from
lack of preparation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting into a groove offensively and defensively,''
Pitino said. ``We will be prepared. We are going to know their
plays. But what it comes down to is us making our shots and forcing
them to miss theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike most teams, which run fast breaks for layups, they run
fast breaks for 3s. And they are very good at it. We have outplayed
them for 60-70 percent of games, and then they hit a barrage of 3s
and we're out of it. It's very difficult to defend them the way
they run the break.''
</P>
<P>
   This is sort of like redirecting Pitino's favorite weapon
against him. Pitino's teams usually utilize 3-pointers as their
point of reference. But they are having to become more concerned
with stifling the long ball than launching it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the 3, but the most important thing is to stop it if
it's there,'' Pitino said. ``The important thing is the
differential. I don't want them making 12 and us making 3. At
Kentucky, we would have a 21-point differential on 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is not stop the 3 but stop the attempt.
Because if you give them the attempt, in this league, with guys
like Reggie Miller, they are going to make 40 percent of those
shots. And that is better than making 50 percent on 2-point shots.
Most of our losses, there has been disparity the other way on 3s.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pierce and Antoine Walker are expected to be the Celtics'
answer to Miller, though mostly inside the 3-point circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and Antoine put a lot of pressure on the defense,''
Pitino said. ``And that opens it up for others. They take the heat
off the defense, and that allows others to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they work out during the offseason, and if they continue to
grow together, they are going to become a lethal weapon. That means
they also have to continue to work on defense and be the best
defensive players on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Williams returned to practice for the first time after
being placed on the injured list with a right knee injury Jan. 25.
Williams, who has not played since a 94-90 win over Toronto Jan.
19, is eligible to return against New Jersey Friday . . . Pervis
Ellison (strained left calf) participated in a practice that was
open to a youth group but closed to the media. Ellison was listed
as ``not with team'' during a 91-88 win over Phoenix Friday . . .
The Celtics meet Miami Wednesday at the FleetCenter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
