<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFSTRA DEALS BU 7TH STRAIGHT LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
 UNIVERSITY-HOFSTRA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You lose five of your previous six games in the final
seconds and you figure your fortunes are due for a turn. Boston
University has been ever so close to turning around a season
riddled with injuries and setbacks; a win Sunday against America
East leader Hofstra would have been a major step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, BU did the moonwalk. Trailing by 2 with 17:00 left, the
Terriers succumbed to a 16-0 Hofstra run.
</P>
<P>
   Such a surge would be tough for any team to overcome. When you
dress just seven scholarship players and have two walk-ons (one a
former team manager), as the Terriers do, it all but guarantees
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   BU never threatened after the onslaught and Hofstra overcame
some sloppiness down the stretch to record a 64-49 triumph before a
Case Center crowd of 505.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Richardson had 17 points and Craig Claxton added 16 for
Hofstra (14-5, 9-1), which overcame poor shooting in the first half
(39 percent) by hitting 52 percent in the second and forcing 20 BU
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taking the same shots in the second half as we were in
the first,'' said Claxton, ``but in the second half they just fell
for us, and that was the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That made Sunday's contest a contrast from BU's previous six
outings, which the Terriers lost by a total of 8 points (including
two in overtime). BU (3-17, 2-9) has dropped seven in a row, its
most consecutive defeats since 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers played aggressive defense in the first half, were
within 5 (27-22) at halftime, and pulled to 31-29 with 17:00 left.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson drained a trey with 16:07 remaining, teammate
Lars Grubler sank two free throws, and Richardson followed with a
layup. The rout was on. Hofstra capped the run with a 3-pointer by
Claxton for a 47-29 advantage with 11:07 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score for a long time,'' said BU coach Dennis Wolff,
who has lost two players to season-ending injuries and one to
academic problems. ``We made some fatigue mistakes in the second
half.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Hofstra's 16-0 run, Wolff said, ``At that point, because of
the makeup of our team, with its numbers, and it being the second
game of the weekend _ and I'm not making up excuses here _ we hit
the wall at a certain point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids still showed a little bit of life when we tried
trapping, but we don't have a whole lot of energy and a lot of
options.''
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers got no closer than 13 after Hofstra's run, and a
4-point play by Hofstra guard Jason Hernandez with 5:43 left put
the Flying Dutchmen up, 55-36.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got beaten by a better team,'' said Wolff, ``and in my
opinion, they didn't play their best.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Jean Avebe led BU with 12 points, 7 rebounds, and 3
steals. Teammate Paul Seymour, last week's America East rookie of
the week, had 11 points, but failed to score in the first half on
0-for-5 shooting from the floor, 0 for 4 from 3-point range. BU
shot 38 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers have a much needed week off before playing at
cross-town rival Northeastern Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to come back working every day. That's the only
way I know to go about it,'' said Wolff. ``We have to accept it and
keep trying to improve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
