<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-VERMEIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMEIL MAY LEAVE _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It might be justice if Dick Vermeil decided to walk
away after winning the Super Bowl with the Rams here Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Just about a year ago this time, the Rams asked him to walk
away, and he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   They can deny it if they want, but a year ago this time, after
finishing a dismal 4-12 season, the Rams did not want Vermeil back.
</P>
<P>
   He offered to take a settlement on the remaining three years of
his contract and walk away from coaching forever.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, if a coach gets fired, the team has to pay his
contract in full. Vermeil had only finished two years of a
lucrative five-year contract. The Rams owed him three years. If
they fired him, they'd have to pay him for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   They offered Vermeil a settlement. He didn't think it was enough
and rejected it. So they brought him back to lead the Rams on one
of the most incredible runs in pro football history.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Rams also tried to get rid of Kurt Warner, the
season and Super Bowl Most Valuable Player, just about the time
they were trying to say goodbye to Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   All 30 teams in the NFL had to leave some players exposed to the
expansion draft to stock the Cleveland Browns last February. Warner
was put on the list. Cleveland could have had him for nothing, but
they didn't pick him, so Warner returned to the Rams _ and a date
with destiny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling how good the Titans' Steve McNair would be if
he could throw the ball with accuracy. McNair once again showed the
football world he is probably the greatest running quarterback ever
to play the game. The Rams made it their first item of business not
to let him run successfully, but they couldn't stop him as he ran
eight times for 64 yards, an 8-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   McNair is a wonderful playmaker and clutch player. He seems to
get better when the game is on the line in the fourth period,
improvising and creating havoc with the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half we did a lot of good things, and then
stopped ourselves with mistakes,'' said McNair. ``We were stopping
ourselves. They couldn't stop us. In the second half, we stopped
making mistakes, and we started moving the ball. Their linebacker
(Mike Jones) made a great play on the last play. I thought
(Kevin)Dyson might break the tackle and get into the end zone, but
it didn't happen for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
