<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-LAST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORY OUT OF REACH FOR DYSON 
</HEADLINE>
 PLAY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The play is called ``Sliver Right'' and if ``Sliver
Right'' unfolded in the ``slowest of slow-motion,'' as Tennessee
fullback Lorenzo Neal saw it and felt it and will relive it for the
next year and beyond, then that sliver stuck sharply underneath the
fingernails of the Titans. For ``Sliver Right'' came up a yard
short.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is such a roller coaster . . . I know it now,'' said
the Titans' Kevin Dyson, who ran ``Sliver Right,'' delaying his
slant while his tight end, Frank Wycheck, occupied Rams linebacker
Mike Jones. ``And when I caught the ball, I was open and I thought
I was in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sliver Right.'' Under the fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson is the Titan who ran the ``Music City Miracle,'' that
lateral and 75-yard run that won Tennessee's first playoff game
against Buffalo with 16 seconds left. ``We were down against
Buffalo . . . then the lateral. We were down today . . . and we
came back,'' said Dyson. ``And I was open . . . it's such a
roller-coaster ride . . . I don't know . . . to come up a yard
short.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for lack of effort, no, definitely not.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson was running into the end zone _ in the clear it seemed _
with his next step, ``but their guy got me by my feet,'' the
Tennessee wide receiver said.
</P>
<P>
   No Super Bowl had ever come down to this. Six seconds left, one
play left in the game, one play to tie up Super Bowl XXXIV, one
play from the 10-yard line of the St. Louis Rams. One play called
``Sliver Right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good play,'' Wycheck thought as quarterback Steve
McNair called it in the huddle. It called for the Titans to run two
routes on the right side, Wycheck heading down the seam and Dyson
slanting inside. Jones was going to have to make the decision of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had run the play against Pittsburgh this year ``and
we were confident in the play,'' said Wycheck, ``and it had gotten
us a touchdown then. It was a good call.''
</P>
<P>
   On the play before, one of the greatest of Super Bowl history,
McNair somehow eluded two Rams who were seemingly jumping on his
back. He ducked underneath the behemoths, somehow scooting free,
scrambled right, and hit a wide-open Dyson for a 16-yard gain to
the 10-yard line. ``That was Steve at his most courageous,'' said
Wycheck, ``and after Steve somehow made that play, we all thought
we were going to tie it up.''
</P>
<P>
   A timeout. Wycheck knew the Titans were in this precarious
predicament, striving to drive 88 yards in 1:46, with only one
timeout left, ``because we had used two timeouts earlier when maybe
we didn't have to,'' said the tight end. But ``Sliver Right'' was
the right call, Wycheck knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play was designed for Jones to run with me and sort of
double me up,'' said Wycheck, ``and have Kevin come straight
underneath on the slant. And if Jones dropped off on Kevin, then
Steve'd have me in the back of the end zone. If Jones stayed with
me, there'd be Kevin.''
</P>
<P>
   As McNair dropped back, he patiently waited, ``knowing if a guy
was open in the end zone, you get it to him. But you don't have to
go to the end zone to score.'' He saw Wycheck head to the back of
the end zone and Dyson slip underneath ``and he was open,'' said
McNair.
</P>
<P>
   So he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was open and I saw the end zone,'' said Dyson. He thought a
cornerback was chasing him because ``I came off the linebacker and
he fell off of me and their cornerback must have made a good
play.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Jones piercing under every Tennessee fingernail with
that sliver. ``I thought when he got his hands on me, I was going
to break free and break the tackle. But he got my foot, tripped me
up, and wrapped up nice.''
</P>
<P>
   As he went down, Dyson elongated his body like some Rubber Man,
trying to will it one last yard, and when his body wouldn't
stretch, his arm did, reaching out as far as it could with the ball
in his fingers, but reaching up more than out.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson lay on the turf for the longest time. ``It was a sick
feeling,'' he said, ``to have come this far and come up just so
short.''
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't until later, much later, that Dyson realized
perhaps he hadn't done all he could to cross that final yard. This
man, who will be on every NFL highlight film from now until the end
of football with his ``Music City Miracle,'' realized in a hallway
outside the Tennessee locker room he might have done more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' Dyson said, ``I could have pitched it back to
somebody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 0225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
