<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP INJURY PROVIDES A JOLT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By now, virtually every Tennessee Titan was dressed
and leaving the locker room. A Tennessee equipment man was reaching
into the locker of Blaine Bishop and carefully placing Bishop's
highly polished black shoes, shaving kit, and clothes into a duffel
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Robertson, Tennessee's other starting safety, stood by
Bishop's locker and said the game had turned when his closest of
friends was laid out on the field with a jammed neck early in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   All the Titans feared the worst for those 15 minutes when Bishop
lay immobile on the Georgia Dome field, ``but then coach (Jeff)
Fisher came over to us and told us Blaine was going to be all
right,'' said Robertson, who missed the game with a leg injury.
``And that's when we all got together and said we were going to win
this for Blaine. That's when we came alive.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bishop's X-rays proved negative, and he will return with his
teammates to Nashville Monday.)
</P>
<P>
   It was 16-0, St. Louis, at that moment. According to Robertson,
the turning point came when Bishop was carted off the field.
Tennessee did stage the biggest comeback in Super Bowl history _
tying the game at 16 _ but it was all to end a yard short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather we lost by 70 points,'' said Robertson, ``than by a
yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Steve McNair had been noble, stepping up to the podium
and very calmly describing what had just happened. This had been
one of the most exciting Super Bowls ever, if not the most
exciting, but McNair was able to dissect it calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Wycheck, McNair's tight end, had said what all of football
had just seen, ``that Steve McNair tonight put his stamp on the
NFL, for he played with so much courage.'' Yet, McNair seemed
dispassionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance in the end,'' McNair said in the
understatement of understatements, ``but we just came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair would go through the Titans' last drive, recalling what
he felt as he ran onto the field, with the ball on his 12-yard line
and 1:46 to go, only one timeout left in the kitty. ``I said (the
Rams) made one mistake by scoring; they gave us too much time to
score. That was my attitude going out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   On the last pass to Kevin Dyson, McNair calmly said it was not a
mistake to not throw the ball into the end zone on the last play of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't force the issue,'' McNair said. ``The linebacker (the
Rams' Mike Jones) came off Frank (Wycheck) which, you know he made
a good decision, just peeled off and made the tackle. That
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotion will come later.
</P>
<P>
   For Eddie George was just then giving a clue of what McNair and
all these Titans will feel, because the Titan running back had
mounted a podium, told his thoughts, answered the questions, and
spoke some more, before heading back to the dressing room _ where
he sat by his locker, hands over his face, as every one of his
teammates dressed.
</P>
<P>
   And Eddie George did not move.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras from Nashville and the networks approached
George. His hands kept covering his eyes. He could not move, could
not talk more than a word or two at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good game,'' a friend said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you.'' Hands still covered face.
</P>
<P>
   ``So close,'' George was heard saying.
</P>
<P>
   And there he sat, until virtually everyone and virtually
everything, including Blaine Bishop's shoes and shaving kit, had
left the Tennessee Titans' locker room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
