A1496 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NEWHAMP-DEMOCRATS-SFC     01-31 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWHAMP-DEMOCRATS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   GORE, BRADLEY TRADE SHOTS AS CAMPAIGN GROWS INCREASINGLY BITTERBy 
 MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  MANCHESTER, N.H. _ A tightening Democratic contest for
president turned increasingly bitter Sunday, as Vice President Al
Gore called his rival ``manipulative'' and former Sen. Bill Bradley
accused Gore of jumping ``in bed with special interests'' in the
latest election.
<P>
   The barbs, made during the final rallies before Tuesday's
first-in-the-nation primary, are rooted in disagreements over
campaign finances and Gore's record on abortion and have escalated
into the most personal and mean-spirited of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   After months of low-key disputes over health care, gun control
and leadership style, the exchanges have left some Democratic party
leaders concerned that they might hurt the winner's chances of
defeating the Republican candidate in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bradley campaign has suddenly changed. Instead of the
promised character, courage and commitment, we have manipulative
attack after manipulative attack,'' Gore said in a spirited rally
before 1,000 supporters in Somersworth, N.H., where he aimed a
considerable portion of his remarks at his rival. ``Senator Bradley
is now stepping down to the level of personal vilification.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has faced renewed questions about his health,
appeared on ABC's ``This Week'' and called Gore and his fellow
Democrats' methods of raising money in the latest campaign
``disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we clean up our own house, Republicans are going to
clean our house in the fall,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp rhetoric came as polls show both the Democratic and
Republican races tightening. A CNN/Gallup poll released yesterday
found Gore and Bradley in a statistical dead heat. A Reuter's poll
found Gore up by seven points _ a drop from 11 points one week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The race is just as close on the Republican side. The CNN poll
found Arizona Sen. John McCain with a five-point edge over Texas
Gov. George W. Bush; however, other polls showed the contest
essentially even.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in tomorrow's primary are particularly high for
Bradley and McCain, both of whom have placed great emphasis here
and are given a better chance of defeating front-runners Gore and
Bush in New Hampshire than most anyplace else.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley to win the nomination, most strategists believe that
he also must do well on March 7 in California, where according to
the latest Field Poll he trails Gore by nearly 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because no one in California has even focused on this
race,'' Bradley said on ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the country, outside of Iowa, New Hampshire, the
media and the political pundits, have actually focused on this
campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about Bradley's irregular heartbeat resurfaced after
he disclosed to the New York Times that in three times since 1996
he has undergone a procedure known as cardioversion, in which the
heart is jolted with electricity. The procedure requires a few
minutes of general anesthesia, prompting Bradley to acknowledge
that were such a procedure needed if he were president, he might
have to invoke the 25th Amendment to empower the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley received an unusual nod from the conservative Manchester
Union Leader, the state's most influential newspaper, which has
already endorsed Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial titled ``Almost an Endorsement,'' the paper
urged Democrats to vote for Bradley, stating: ``The cancer of the
Clinton Presidency has mortally infected (Gore), and he is
ethically damaged beyond repair. ... Bradley is much more liberal
than Gore, but at least he is honest. An honest liberal beats a
dishonest one any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley began running TV commercials over the weekend suggesting
that he is the only candidate _ Democrat or Republican _ who has
always stood for a woman's right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Gore conceded that he had voted against federal financing of
abortions as a member of the House during the '70s and '80s but
said he has always supported the right to a legal abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley accused Gore of dishonesty, noting that among Gore's
votes was a 1984 vote in support of a civil rights amendment that
would have defined a fetus as a ``person.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the attacks prompted Democratic leaders in the
House and Senate _ both Gore supporters _ to issue an statement
urging an end to the personal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Democrats, we urge that Sen. Bradley's campaign remain
focused on the issues and that he abandon negative, personal
attacks that do not bring credit to this nomination contest or to
the Democratic Party,'' Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle and
House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt said in a statement
distributed by the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who are all opposed to legal abortions, also have
been fighting over their commitment to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life PAC sent a mailing to New Hampshire
residents urging them not to vote for McCain, quoting an interview
McCain did with The Chronicle's Editorial Board last year in which
he said that Roe vs. Wade _ the landmark Supreme Court decision
that upheld a woman's constitutional right to abortion _ should not
be immediately repealed because it might force thousands of women
to undergo illegal and dangerous operations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain contradicted that position Sunday, saying the decision
should be reversed, and pointed to his 17-year voting record
against legal abortions. The attack, he said, is motivated by the
anti-abortion group's fear that his plan to reform campaign finance
laws would limit their influence.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thinks a win in California, where he trails
Bush by a 4-to-1 ratio, is the key to nomination, McCain noted that
there are 13 GOP contests on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the nomination will be decided on that day, and I
believe California is very key,'' McCain said on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was joined on Saturday by his father, the former
president, and brother, the governor of Florida, said he was
growing more confident about his prospects in New Hampshire, where
he has trailed McCain in the polls for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my chances,'' he said between stops.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates all ended their schedules early yesterday so as
not to bother voters during the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had an event on his schedule marked as a Super Bowl Party
with John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   No, his staff explained, it was not the popular sports
broadcaster and former Oakland Raiders coach. It was instead a
campaign contributor from Amherst, N.H.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
