<SLUG> BC-KC-LITE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONOMICAL SOCIETY FIGHTS LIGHT POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISBURG, Kan. _ Most evenings at Powell Observatory in
Louisburg, Kan., a faintly orange, hazy glow appears above the
southern horizon about a mile from the observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Like dust in the eye, that glow is an irritant to the members of
the Astronomical Society of Kansas City, (Mo.) which operates the
observatory.
</P>
<P>
   The glow muddies the heavens. It makes deep space _ that part of
the night sky that harbors faint or nearly invisible stars and
galaxies millions of light-years away _ nearly impenetrable. And it
makes the observatory's 30-inch Newtonian telescope, one of the
most powerful in a five-state region, seem not so powerful after
all.
</P>
<P>
   That glow, that irritant, has a name: light pollution. And as
more houses are built, more roads and parking lots paved, the
Astronomical Society's members find themselves spending more time
educating the public about how light interferes with their view of
the skies. ``We're not anti-light,'' said Nick Ruess, the
observatory's director. ``We're just anti-irresponsible light.''
</P>
<P>
   All of us live with light pollution. To motorists it's the glare
from improperly shielded streetlights. To homeowners living near
parking lots or convenience stores it's the light that splashes
through their bedroom windows. To some pedestrians it's buildings
and parking lots that are lighted up like they are in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   But one person's light pollution could be another's security
blanket. When Kansas City voters approved a $110 million bond issue
in 1997 for new lights, they did so, in part, because they thought
it would make the streets safer.
</P>
<P>
   To Kansas City resident Steve Stroade, who lives just south of
the Country Club Plaza, the new 110-watt lamp across from his house
and the eight others on his block are a blessing. He not only feels
safer, but he also has a brighter path for taking evening walks to
the Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can appreciate concerns about light pollution,'' he said.
``But if I want to see the stars, I'll go to Colorado.''  &LR; brk:Dark
skies
</P>
<P>
   Ruess, the observatory director, is a 46-year-old amateur
astronomer who moved from Kansas City to south of Paola, Kan., in
his personal quest for darker skies. He says reducing light
pollution and fighting crime are not necessarily incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many crimes are committed in the sky,'' Ruess said.
``Having something that's going to detect a hang glider doesn't
make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Light pollution is essentially misdirected light. The
Astronomical Society, following guidelines set forth by
organizations such as the International Dark-Sky Association in
Tucson, Ariz., suggests several ways for redirecting that light.
The basic guidelines, though, are fairly simple:
</P>
<P>
   - Use only the amount of light you need and direct it on the
object that needs illumination, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   - To light a street, mount the lamp in a fixture that does not
allow light to shine skyward. Cities can do that, Ruess said, by
housing their lamps so the lenses or bulbs do not hang beneath the
fixture like a teardrop but are shielded with flat glass.
</P>
<P>
   - To make a parking lot or some other property secure, be
judicious in the number of watts you use.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the sky glow south of the observatory. Part of it comes
from the dozen or so 1,000-watt metal halide lamps that light the
parking lot of a Price Chopper grocery in Louisburg. Ruess said the
lamps were properly shielded. But they are so powerful that a pair
of good eyes can read fine print standing 100 feet away from the
nearest pole. The same light that allows you to read is bouncing
off the parking lot and into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   When the supermarket opened two years ago, the society took its
concerns to the store's managers. Upon hearing they had unwittingly
brightened the skies, the managers agreed to turn off the lights
after the store's 10 p.m. closing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, late most nights, the sky glow suddenly shrinks a bit.
 &LR; brk:Positive feedback
</P>
<P>
   Often, Ruess said, all it takes to mitigate the effects of light
pollution is a brief discussion about how changes can reduce energy
costs. A little positive feedback doesn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the society has begun awarding businesses and
governments for responsible lighting. One award went to Kansas City
Power &AMP; Light Co. for the lights it used at a site in southern
Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   Ruess also gives jurisdictions such as Miami County, Louisburg,
Overland Park, Johnson County and Kansas City credit for their
efforts to put up good streetlights or monitor the way various
businesses and developments light their properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who put up irresponsible lighting, they just don't
know,'' Ruess said. ``Given a choice between a good plan and a bad
plan, most people will choose the good. Even though the responsible
fixtures might cost more, it saves them money in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes compromises a little easier. For example:
</P>
<P>
   - When Louisburg built a ballpark adjacent to the observatory,
the city agreed to turn off the lights by 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   - Several years ago the McDonald's restaurant across from Price
Chopper voluntarily readjusted its parking lot lights, which were
mounted at an angle and allowed light to escape. A nearby Burger
King later followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   - After hearing concerns from the Astronomical Society, the
Miami County Planning Commission began referring developers and
engineers to the society for recommendations on how to prevent
light pollution.  &LR; brk:Solutions
</P>
<P>
   Changes like these have noticeably improved the skies south of
the observatory, Ruess said. But it would take more than a modest
education campaign to reduce the massive glow that comes from the
hundreds of thousands of lights the Kansas City area turns on every
night.
</P>
<P>
   Members say that when the society headed for darker skies,
moving its observatory from Swope Park to Louisburg in 1985, that
glow stretched about 20 degrees above the horizon. Today they
estimate that figure at 45 degrees. The society has no illusions:
Kansas City's sky glow probably will not get smaller, especially
when brighter lights are increasingly seen as a critical tool in
the fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lee, manager of Kansas City's streetlight services, oversees
the city's $110 million light project. He is aware of the society's
concerns and believes the city is at least addressing some of them
by trying to provide uniform lighting with as little glare, or
``trespass,'' as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that reaching that goal is not easy. ``It's a
complicated design problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the first lights went up, the city has either
upgraded or installed 25,000 streetlights. When the job is done,
the city will have upgraded or installed about 73,000 lights.
</P>
<P>
   As the new lights go up, many of the older ones that used
energy-wasting mercury vapor lamps have come down, replaced by more
efficient and longer-lasting high-pressure sodium lamps.
</P>
<P>
   Wide, main thoroughfares are getting 250- and 400-watt lamps
with full, cutoff lenses that reduce glare and prevent most of the
light from escaping into the sky. Residential streets are getting
100-watt lamps with semicutoff lenses. Lee said the city could have
gone with completely shielded lamps in residential areas, but that
would have required the city to put up more fixtures and spend more
money in its quest for uniform lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The partly shielded lamps are not the perfect solution, Ruess
said, adding that the city's streetlights were a ``drop in the
bucket'' when compared to all the lights that contribute to the
area's sky glow.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Ruess and his colleagues will continue
monitoring the skies and pressing for more responsible lighting.
``I've got hope,'' he said. ``Some good can come from our
efforts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
