<HEADER>
A1505 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-KC-PRES-KAN &LR;      01-31 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-PRES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WICHITA MAN HAS $1,000 AND A YEN TO RUN FOR PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ Vice President Al Gore may have the prestige of
Air Force Two.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush may have scads of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Oyler, though, has a Web site and a dream.
</P>
<P>
   And because Oyler, a Wichita engineer, also had $1,000 to spare,
his name will appear on the Republican ballot in the New Hampshire
presidential primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: Tom Oyler is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Men like Gore and Bush _ with money and experience _ may get
most of the publicity. But there are 30 persons on the ballot in
New Hampshire this year. That's fewer than in recent elections _
more than 60 presidential candidates signed up in 1992, and 45 ran
in 1996 _ but still a lot more than the six Republicans and two
Democrats you see in debates and on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   The 22 others are the so-called ``fringe candidates.'' They may
not have much hope of winning. But like the more mainstream
candidates, they paid the $1,000 filing fee to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, they are a welcome part of the political
landscape, said former Gov. Hugh Gregg, the primary's unofficial
historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them have a serious interest in some message they want
to deliver,'' Gregg said. ``They know they're probably not going to
get elected. They should be treated well because their hearts are
in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Oyler is 54, a bookish, graying little man with big,
friendly eyes and an easy smile. Like a smallish Fred MacMurray.
</P>
<P>
   He lives alone in Wichita in a trim little yellow-brick ranch
house that he inherited from his parents. He has a 70-acre farm
outside of town where he raises hay he sells to local farmers. He
smokes cigars and drinks, by his estimate, about one beer a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly he keeps to himself. Seemingly, an everyman.
</P>
<P>
   Except that beneath his placid demeanor boils a cauldron of
contempt for the federal government and the cookie-cutter
candidates he sees vying for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is, the common good is individual liberties,''
Oyler said. ``None of the other candidates, except maybe Alan
Keyes, has brought up the question of reducing the size of the
federal government. Even George Bush's education proposals would
expand the bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oyler touts that smaller-government message on his Web site,
which he has dubbed ``The Dissenter.'' The site features editorials
dripping with sarcasm about the government, plus biographical
information on the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Congressmen, senators and President Clinton have been subjected
to the wrath of his tartly worded letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent a letter to Clinton about nine months ago,'' Oyler
said. ``He was giving away money right and left. I asked him for
$243,000 as long as he was giving money away. That was the first
estimate on the house I wanted to build. He never answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, lots of people have Web sites. Lots of people write angry
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Most don't spend $1,000 on a bid for president.
</P>
<P>
   Oyler whetted his political appetite with two U.S. Senate runs.
In 1996, he finished third of four candidates in the GOP primary,
with 23,266 votes. In 1998, Oyler got 11,545 votes as the
Libertarian Party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Oyler, who works at the Boeing company's sprawling plant in
Wichita, decided to take the big plunge this year after a
conversation at work in which colleagues derided the well-known
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest question people ask me is, `Why?' &UR; '' Oyler said.
``I don't know. Some days I think it's some kind of noble cause.
Other days, it's just that the guys who are running make me mad. I
can't give you a straight answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, running for president is kind of neat.
</P>
<P>
   Oyler's boss whistles ``Hail to the Chief'' when he passes
Oyler's desk. And, Oyler reports, his family is ``proud as punch.
Nobody's ridiculed me.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not likely anybody in New Hampshire would either, Gregg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's taught they can grow up to be president,'' Gregg
said. ``We really honor that tradition here. We listen to people
you've never heard of, like Jimmy Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that it's so easy to get on the state's primary ballot.
Most states require signed petitions from a certain number of
voters. In New Hampshire, all it takes is $1,000. Candidates can
mail their checks, so there's no need to even go to the state.
</P>
<P>
   So the fringe flocks to New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Call them the political progeny of Harold Stassen, the one-time
Minnesota governor who went from legitimate contender to national
joke during his record seven New Hampshire primary campaigns.
Stassen last ran in 1992, garnering 206 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Harold,'' Gregg said. ``He ran in New Hampshire
because it was a place he could express his views and people would
hear him. Some of his views might be a little far out, but people
listened.''
</P>
<P>
   Oyler hasn't been to New Hampshire for any one-on-one
campaigning (``I'm not really Mr. Social.'').
</P>
<P>
   He runs the campaign from the spare bedroom where he keeps his
computer. He answers e-mail and sends his editorials to newspapers
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   And he figures his campaign slogan _ ``Better Than None of the
Above'' _ might attract some folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you figure, 40 percent of the people are actually
going to vote?'' Oyler asked. ``So 60 percent of the people don't
vote or are fed up or don't think their vote matters. They're
essentially voting for none of the above. I wanted to find a way to
get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oyler is realistic. He hasn't really bothered to plot a
post-New Hampshire strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have a chance, it's slim,'' he conceded wistfully as he
eased back in his favorite chair, the one with the faded flower
pattern. ``Maybe I can influence the election just by bringing up
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a pebble in the water...you know, a ripple can make
a wave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
