<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX     01-31 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Nonsensical reaction to common-sense gun proposal
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the lesser items in President Clinton's
valedictory agenda, and one many Americans would judge among the
least arguable, but expect an outsized political detonation from
his proposal that handgun owners be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott instantly dismissed
the idea as violative of the Constitution's Second Amendment,
though it would deny no firearm to anyone who may legally buy one
now.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, licensing would bring a new sobriety to personal
decisions about whether to take in firearms. Some of the most
deadly guns have been ones bought impulsively, often during a local
panic over crime stories, by persons ill-prepared for the
responsibility and thoughtless in how and where they maintain the
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   That casualness and negligence are at the root of the
president's appalling observation that the accidental gun death
rate among American kids under 15 is nine times higher than in the
other 25 industrial nations _ combined.
</P>
<P>
   The bother of licensing would cut the number of firearms coming
into play. The process would impress upon buyers the life-or-death
enormity of their decision.
</P>
<P>
   We must be licensed to operate an automobile, which, although
potentially deadly in its misuses, has as its purpose only the
benign objective of getting from point A to point B. To drive
legally, we have to show that we know the traffic laws and can
wheel the machine around with at least rudimentary safety.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we may buy purposely deadly weapons without in any way
reassuring the community we have the slightest idea of how to
handle them properly.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that we have a constitutional right to bear arms and no
constitutional right to be borne by a car is often cited as somehow
clinching, but it is meaningless when licensing would deny no one
access to a lawful firearm.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of firearms proposal the president rightly
likes to characterize as common sense, but brace for a blast of
nonsense against it even so.
</P>
<P>
   Expect, for example, a golden oldie of the guns-first set _ the
claim that it was because German gun owners were licensed and their
firearms registered that Hitler took over Germany. It would happen
here, the hysteria goes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes _ if, first, we lost a world war, were reamed out by
hyperinflation, had wobbly political institutions and a recent
tradition of autocratic rule, elected a fascist party and then, on
second thought, didn't mind going up against the subverted armed
forces with handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's commentariat generally has it that this proposal
and all the rest in the State of the Union are just so much
election-year issue-mongering, a platform for Al Gore to run on and
the Republican Congress to run from. That's so, but so what?
</P>
<P>
   How odd that in a system set up to manage our common affairs
politically, it is now fashionable to dismiss any proposal, without
reference to its merits, on the grounds that it is political.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
