<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lincoln/Washington/King: Just a day off
 &HT;    (For release Feb. 2, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have been quite cognizant of George Washington's birthday,
especially since my wife and I were married on that date. And we
were mindful of Abraham Lincoln's birthday as well, as that is the
date my wife's sister was married.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, we were aware of them because each was a
separate observance of great Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There was Abraham Lincoln's birthday on Feb. 12 and George
Washington's birthday on Feb. 22. I don't recall schools and
businesses being closed down in observance, but at least there was
symbolic liturgy around the dates.
</P>
<P>
   I also can't recall when the change was made, but what we knew
as Lincoln's birthday and Washington's birthday were merged into
something called Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
   It conveniently is placed on a Monday so that mainly workers in
the public sector, schoolchildren, judges and lawyers get the day
off: a bonus add-on to weekends.
</P>
<P>
   All but lost in the observance is what it all is about. And, at
times, it confuses me. Is Presidents Day an observance of all
presidents? Is it an observance of just Lincoln and Washington? Or
is it just an excuse to take another day off work or school?
</P>
<P>
   I cannot help but note that when Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s
birthday is observed, it too is designated to be a Monday. This
year, it was Jan. 17. Next year, it will fall on his actual
birthday, Jan. 15, not so much because accuracy is being cultivated
but because it's a Monday. And that goes with Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the King observance different from Presidents Day is
that on King's birthday, people really understand what the day is
about. Speeches are made, parades held. It is a true American
observance for a man who deserves the plaudits.
</P>
<P>
   But what of Washington and Lincoln, all but disappeared in the
justification of a Monday without work? Is there a chance that the
Father of our Country and the Great Emancipator might be remembered
in states, cities and neighborhoods as is Dr. King? And on their
actual birthdays?
</P>
<P>
   About all I can recognize about celebrating our great
forefathers is when department and tire stores create huge Lincoln
or Washington sales on that Monday. Like the Fourth of July, a
solemn holiday is treated as a premier day to shop. (And how soon
before the Fourth moves to the Third or the Fifth, as long as it is
a Monday?)
</P>
<P>
   It would not be past the thinking of the obscure Monday Day Off
Gang to slide the ascribed birthday of Jesus Christ to a Monday as
well. Hey, anything to package a three-day weekend!
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Columbus is credited with arriving at San Salvador
on Oct. 12, 1492. Now, the exact date really doesn't matter, what
does is that it is a Monday. This year, Columbus Day will be
observed on Monday, Oct. 9, or at a time when the admiral still was
floating lost east of the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day, which began as a May 30 observance, is on May 29
this year. Reason? Correct! It's a Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Day falls this year on Feb. 21, which, of course, is
a Monday. It is now a day without purpose other than a portion of
the population feigning observance but really sitting at home and
watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   The only holiday with a floating date that does not conform to
the Monday mandate is Thanksgiving, which is set by Congress to be
the fourth Thursday in November. This, too, has become a bonus for
people who don't want to work or go to school. The Friday
surrounded by Thanksgiving and Saturday is fast becoming another
day to take off; that one makes for a four-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Subliminally, the aim of moving holidays to Mondays is to create
a four-day work week.
</P>
<P>
   We're up to five proscribed Monday holidays a year; just another
47 to go.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
