<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMNS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher shortage won't be solved by turning away older
applicants
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDs: The following is designed to run as the first of two
consecutive columns on the same subject or be merged into one op-ed
or perspective section piece by merely deleting the dateline and
lede of the second section. Either piece also could stand alone.
Both are available on the Cox and New York Times wires. Since this
is the hiring season for next fall's crop of teachers, a local
situationer is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``This country is facing an extensive teacher
shortage
</P>
<P>
   and will need to hire more than 2 million instructors over the
next 10 years. But the recruitment effort will be wasted unless the
states raise standards for what teachers need to know, commit
themselves to hiring only qualified teachers and revamp schools of
education that are often no more than diploma mills, offering
watered-down courses and marginal preparation.'' _ Editorial, The
New York Times, Sunday, Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I wrote of the plight of my friend Gail, a dedicated
lady who found the schoolhouse locked when she tried to realize her
dream of teaching high school history. After completing her
education (cum laude and post-kids), she has been unable to land a
job in anybody's school system because she has two strikes against
her: a master's degree, and her age.
</P>
<P>
   Gail's advanced degree would cost the school a few more bucks,
and education is not known for putting its money where its mouth
is. And as for age, a 53-year-old is not going to die (or retire on
a pittance) any quicker than a 25-year-old is going to apply for
maternity leave or quit to follow her boyfriend to Myrtle Beach,
S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the volume of mail from all over the country, Gail
is far from alone in her under-employed state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read with great interest (and understanding) your article in
The Dayton Daily News this morning. I am 49, have a master's and
experience to compound the predicament. I am constantly receiving
substitute positions and accolades, but not a permanent position.
Comments I have received include, 'I don't want any more your age
in my building.' and 'I'm proud
</P>
<P>
   not to honor loyalty and dedication. That's not important in
education.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed,'' she adds, ``when I decided to return to
teaching, went back to school to become current and meet the state
standards, that I would
</P>
<P>
   have difficulty. I won't get pregnant, I have the maturity from
raising my own children, I'm stable in the community, and most
importantly, I know what I want to do with my life. I have even
offered to start at base pay. I truly love teaching, so money is
not my sole objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Ohio reader thanked me for trying to show the public
what she believes really fuels teacher shortages (money and age
bias). ``Our short-sighted superintendent hired a 26-year-old with
no experience as principal at our elementary.''
</P>
<P>
   A 34-year-old subbed for two years but gave up teaching after
watching 23-year-olds finding positions in the same systems where
she had applied.
</P>
<P>
   Another feels lucky to have a job, but watches as colleagues
continue to sub while children of neighboring school
administrators, school board members, or ministers are hired. And
as for minorities in her community, forget it. ``They recruit,
interview, but never hire.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hingham, Mass., a concerned parent admits she has no respect
for public education because budget is their biggest concern. She
suggests Gail go into private tutoring where she could be making up
to $40 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   On an up-note, the principal of a Dayton Catholic high school
admits it's quite a commute from Boston, but he values life
experience as a qualification for teaching, and would welcome
Gail's resume. He even includes his address.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT: Readers are still talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
