r k BC-LANE-COLUMN01-COX     01-31 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A dumb way to pick a president
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ Imagine that someone proposed the following
system for choosing a Florida governor: For the first round, we
should pick some forsaken county out in the Panhandle. A county
with an agricultural economy. A county that's nearly all white. A
county unaffected by most of the economic and growth trends that
worry the rest of the state. A county with big spaces between towns
and really, really bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Then, we should choose a day guaranteed to have the kind of
weather that would make you think twice about walking your dog. On
that day, registered Democrats and Republicans would meet in school
cafeterias and gyms, in churches and libraries, and vote.
</P>
<P>
   We should pick a week night for this exercise in democracy, a
week night when school is in session, just to make sure too many
people with children and jobs won't show up. We should make them
sit in metal folding chairs and listen to speeches from their local
party officers, for whom this is the one big deal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   No quick in and out of the voting booth here. Instead, we'd have
the political equivalent of a couple thousand PTA meetings.
</P>
<P>
   For the second round, we should pick another small, rural, cold,
all-white county for a more standard primary. Again, we would ask
voters to come out during a week when the weather can be relied
upon to be so miserable you'd think twice about walking your dog.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we would hold this in another Panhandle county away from
the social changes and economic pressures that define politics in
the rest of the state. Only after the people of, say, Suwannee and
Okaloosa counties have spoken would anyone get any say about who
becomes governor. Except, of course, the people who pour their
campaign donations into candidates'
</P>
<P>
   Suwannee and Okaloosa county operations.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more.
</P>
<P>
   To make things interesting, we'll add a few more counties of
middling size for the last primaries, but only in one part of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   We would design this process so at no time would the state's
major urban centers vote. South Florida, Orlando and even Volusia
County would have no say. Those voters would be allowed only to
vote for the two candidates left standing when it's all over.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone proposed such a system for selecting a Florida
governor, he or she would be laughed out of the building. Rightly
so. Such a plan would be undemocratic and a bit racist. It would
disenfranchise people who live in cities. It would be convoluted
and just plain dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that's how the major parties pick candidates for president.
We give over the selection of The Leader of the Free World to
rustics in mukluks and coats that look like space suits. In the New
Hampshire primary and Iowa caucuses, people who wear hats with ear
flaps are a major voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, we also put candidates on a diet of fried
chicken and church-basement coffee and send them out into sub-zero
temperatures dressed inappropriately because it wouldn't do to
appear on television dressed to look like the Michelin Man.
</P>
<P>
   I'm surprised people don't die doing that.
</P>
<P>
   The whole experience makes candidates unhealthy, pale and mean.
It gives a nasty edge to the reporting as well. The press guys
don't like being out at the Nowhere Diner in a snow drift taking
pictures of Candidate A promising to keep subsidies moving to corn
farmers and it's reflected in their reports.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say there's anything wrong with New Hampshire and
Iowa. This time of year, I'm sure they are great places to be from.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't deserve their prominence. No state does.
</P>
<P>
   There is no state where people are so wise and representative of
the rest of us that they should have the power to choose the
president for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that no state would ever knowingly reproduce the
presidential primary system for choosing state officials should be
a clue this is a system that makes no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
</P>
<P>
   Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
