<SLUG> BC-MCCARTNEY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Two of Us' a poignant tale of two Beatles
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's 1976 _ six years after The Beatles'
painful breakup. Paul McCartney is riding around New York City in a
stretch limo. Suddenly he gets a loopy urge to pay John Lennon an
unexpected visit at his spacious Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Would the bitter and reclusive Lennon let him in? If so, what
would they talk about? Would they even talk at all? Could the
meeting lead to a Beatles reunion?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that visit never took place. But it does happen in
``Two of Us,'' a purely fictional, yet wonderfully insightful and
intimate look at two larger-than-life rock legends, convincingly
played by Aidan Quinn (McCartney) and Jared Harris (Lennon).
</P>
<P>
   Most TV rock movies are simply glorified excuses to play great
music by hit-making artists. The stories wrapped around those
songs, however, are usually tissue thin. But, as Lauren Zalaznick,
VH1's senior vice president of original programming and
development, notes, ``This movie is all about two souls, arguably
the most famous musicians of our time. It's not an excuse for a
Beatles hit parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, VH1 tried to get the rights to some Beatles songs, but
wasn't successful.
</P>
<P>
   The songs weren't necessary, however. On the surface, ``Two of
Us'' is about a long overdue meeting between two music industry
icons. Look deeper and the film is really about friendship and
loss. You don't have to be a Beatles junkie to identify with that.
</P>
<P>
   First-time writer Mark Stanfield wrote a surprisingly
thoughtful, though at times hokey, script. That the script is
insightful is a surprise since Stanfield is only 35, which means he
was in diapers when The Beatles stormed America in 1964. But
Stanfield managed to capture the essence of the gruff Lennon and
laid-back McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney's in New York to play a string of sold-out concerts at
Madison Square Garden, when he decides to visit his old mate on a
whim. But Lennon, essentially a prisoner in his own home, is
reluctant to see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you don't mind me surprising you,'' McCartney says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too soon to say,'' replies Lennon.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, both are meditating, smoking pot, drinking tea
and talking about old times. They even venture out to Central Park
_ in disguise _ and sing reggae tunes. But the palpable rift
between the two is about as wide as the Big Apple. Lennon gets in a
lot of snipes about McCartney's ``silly love songs.'' And
McCartney's still angry at Lennon for choosing his wife, Yoko Ono,
over the group. There's also a lot of psycho-babble about Lennon's
rough childhood.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney: ``I see a frightened man who doesn't see how
beautiful he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennon: ``You're the only thing that keeps me from
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Quinn and Harris (Richard's son) are fine in two
challenging roles. Harris is particularly effective in turning
Lennon into a delightful study in contrasts. One moment he's crying
about the pain in his life, the next he's berating two fans who
want him to sing ``Yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, ``Two of Us'' almost didn't get made. When VH1's
Zalaznick got the script, she saw its potential. Leon Falk, the
film's executive producer, was equally impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by how much rung true,'' says Falk. ``It was an
unconventional view of them as real people. They weren't
celebrities to each other, they were just two guys who knew each
other since they were 15.''
</P>
<P>
   But the VH1 suits weren't as impressed. ``It was a risk, in that
it wasn't a traditional movie,'' Zalaznick admits. ``They said, 'We
like it, but it's not right for us.'''
</P>
<P>
   It took Zalaznick over a year to get the green light. It helped
when Quinn, Harris and director Michael Lindsay-Hogg, who directed
``Let It Be,'' The Beatles' last film, liked the project. ``Michael
had turned down many other Beatles offers,'' says Falk. ``But he
said, `You guys got this one right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they did.
</P>
<P>
   The show airs Tuesday at 9 p.m. on VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
