<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chip got under professor's skin
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Meet the first real cyborg in the February issue of
Wired magazine. It's a British computer scientist named Kevin
Warwick who has a silicon chip implanted in his arm. The chip
communicates via radio waves with computers in Warwick's lab at the
University of Reading, just west of London. When he enters the lab,
the computers inside know who he is and greet him with a ``hello.''
Warwick and his chip are part of a new but growing field of
computer engineering in which engineers are trying to embed
computing power into people.
</P>
<P>
   Learn what it's like behind the scenes in the fast-paced world
of start-up tech and Internet companies in Silicon Valley. In ``The
Monk and the Riddle,'' entrepreneur Randy Komisar confides what
it's like. Published by Harvard Business School Press, the book
retails for $22.50.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Who needs snow and ice to do luge racing if you have a computer?
At least that's the idea behind ``Street Luge Racing,'' a new title
from Head Games. In this game, you ride luge sleds with in-line
skating wheels through the streets of big cities, contending with
oncoming traffic, rain-slicked roads and police cars. ``Street Luge
Racing'' is available only for PCs with Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sci-Fi Pinball'' is a cross between a television promotion
video and pinball. It's a pinball game that incorporates screen
shots and video clips of some popular movies and TV shows for
teen-agers. You'll find material from ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
``Aliens'' and ``The Fly,'' to name a few. Published by Fox
Interactive, ``Sci-Fi Pinball'' is for both PCs and Macs.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Do you want inexpensive long-distance telephone service but are
overwhelmed by all the company claims? Then check out a site called
10-10phonerates.com. The site offers a price comparison of all the
different 10-10 numbers advertised on television. You'll also find
articles about the services concerning how to compare them and get
a good deal. The site is www.10-10phonerates.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
