r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY01-COX     01-31 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Radio reception rotten? Just add an old-fashioned antenna
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I grew up in a world of antennas.
</P>
<P>
   In those ``Leave It to Beaver'' days, each house, no matter how
ramshackle, had shiny tentacles of aluminum on top. We thought them
beautiful. Those antennas were proud proof that Arkadelphia, Ark.,
was connected with the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   As a ham radio operator, I had antennas of my own. There were
tubular aluminum beams that dwarfed the TV antennas and long wire
shortwave antennas that stretched from pecan tree to pecan tree.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what I knew as a kid is outdated now. But what I learned
about antennas still comes in handy.
</P>
<P>
   One co-worker has a mountain home, and reception for AM and FM
broadcasts is dicey. An antenna can solve that problem. While you
may not have an isolated mountain home, there are probably times
when a good antenna can help. In my own house, some of the FM
stations have signals too weak for good reception. And there are
times when I want to listen to a football game being played in
Arkansas and broadcast on an AM station there. Without an antenna,
I would be out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   A technology older than Marconi _ the antenna _ can help you
pull in signals your radio couldn't ordinarily receive. You'll need
a radio that has connectors for an external antenna (almost every
stereo receiver has both AM and FM antenna terminals). But, before
we are done, I'll also tell you a tiny trick that also may help the
reception for a radio without antenna terminals.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with the easiest way to improve your reception for
FM. Simply buy an old-fashioned television rabbit ear antenna and
connect it to the FM antenna terminals. You may need an adapter if
the rabbit ears have a coaxial connector such as the one used for
most modern TVs. But the adapters are easy to find at electronics
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit ears should do the trick unless you live in a really
remote area. If the reception is still marginal, you will need an
outside antenna. Luckily, that's something you can do for yourself,
and it doesn't have to be as elaborate as one of the old-fashioned
television antennas. You can find simple outdoor FM antennas,
including some designed to be hidden under the eaves, at
electronics stores. Also buy coaxial cable _ the people at the
store can recommend the type you need _ to connect the antenna.
</P>
<P>
   For AM signals, an outdoor antenna can make a huge difference.
Your FM antenna won't help. You'll need a separate one. But a less
elaborate antenna _ literally copper wire strung between two trees
_ will do fine. Radio Shack sells a shortwave antenna kit for about
$14 that includes everything you need, including insulators and
lead-in wire. Even though the kit is made for shortwave reception,
it will work fine on the AM broadcast band.
</P>
<P>
   I know that many of you won't go to all that trouble. So here's
a trick from the days when every radio was tuned to ``The Green
Hornet'' or ``The Lone Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have an external antenna and you can't quite pull
in a wavering AM signal, wrap several turns of the AC power cord
around the radio. That forms an antenna of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   And antennas, as any kid in Arkadelphia, Ark., could have told
you, can be very beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
