<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snow fails to show in Georgia
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Weather forecasters had predicted a major snowstorm in
the northern half of Georgia over the weekend, when Atlanta played
host to the biggest of all football games: the Super Bowl. Instead,
residents and visitors in town for the game were treated to a slow,
freezing drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there was no repeat of the huge power failures from
last weekend's ice storm, which left about 500,000 Georgians
without electricity, some of them for days. This time there were
scattered outages, but most were repaired quickly. Some of the
outages, though, affected MARTA train service, which many people
were using to get to Super Bowl events downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem this time was icy roads, which caused a
large number of wrecks across North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE SCHOOLERS LIGHTING UP
</P>
<P>
   About one in every eight middle school students uses some form
of tobacco, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 National Youth Tobacco Survey was conducted from
September to October of this year. It is the first survey to look
at tobacco use by middle schoolers. It asked students whether they
had used tobacco within the past 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that about 9 percent of middle school students
smoked cigarettes. About 6 percent smoked cigars. About 3 percent
used dip or chewing tobacco. About 2 percent used flavored
cigarettes called ``bidis,'' and 2 percent smoked clove cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control
Foundation and the American Legacy Foundation, a group dedicated to
reducing tobacco use among young people.
</P>
<P>
   BURGER KING WILL TRADE `POKE BALLS' FOR FRIES
</P>
<P>
   If you have any ``Poke Balls,'' the plastic containers that hold
Pokemon toys from Burger King, give them to your parents
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-month-old baby suffocated last week when half of a Poke Ball
covered his mouth and nose. Another baby died in December in the
same type of accident.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 million of the toys were handed out with Burger
King's children's meals last year. Burger King will give you a free
order of french fries if you return a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King said it will start running TV commercials on Tuesday
warning parents about the toys.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
