<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-CHIPMEMORY01-COX     01-31 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CHIPMEMORY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memory chips race to catch up to processors
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The advent of lightning-fast microprocessors
running at 700 megahertz and more has put pressure on the rest of
the electronics innards in personal computers to pick up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   And most of the pressure is coming down on the companies that
make lots of computer memories, including Korea's Samsung and
Hyundai and Micron Technology of Boise, Idaho. Among them, those
three companies controlled about 60 percent of the $20 billion
memory market last year.
</P>
<P>
   If computer users are going to harness the latest whiz-bang
processing performance, their computers had better have memory
chips that are running lickety split. If memory chips cannot keep
pace, then those fast and expensive new processor chips will be
sitting idle most of the time and not earning their keep.
</P>
<P>
   Memory chip makers have created a series of faster memory
technologies throughout the 1990s. Usually, after a short period of
time, the new standard dominates and all the world's memory makers
shift their production to the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   But this year and next year, things could go differently. Two
competing standards could emerge, and, if they do, then life gets a
little more complicated for the companies that make computers and
for PC buyers as well.
</P>
<P>
   The big driver behind this industry shift is Intel Corp., which
makes most of the computer world's microprocessors, and, because of
that, has become the biggest, richest and most powerful chip
company.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, more than most companies, depends on memory chip
performance getting faster. Without that steady progression, the
improvements Intel makes in processor speeds won't translate to
significant increases in computer performance. And if that happens,
then Intel's incredible profit margins from processor sales are in
jeopardy. Intel would have a hard time commanding big price
premiums for its processor chips if it couldn't show that they make
computers work faster.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is pushing hard for the industry to adopt a new kind of
fast memory, promoted by a small Silicon Valley company called
Rambus Inc. Rambus had designed special circuitry for memory chips
that lets memory chips spit out streams of information more rapidly
than before.
</P>
<P>
   Rambus technology, for example, has been used in memory chips
that go into Nintendo 64 game consoles in order to deliver more
graphics information faster to meet the demands of graphics-hungry
game players.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Memory chip makers must pay Rambus Inc. a royalty _ typically
between 1/2 and 1 percent _ for every Rambus chip they make. And
Rambus chips, because they contain extra circuitry, are larger that
standard chips. That means they are more expensive to make.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those added costs and because of some recent delays
at Intel, memory chip makers haven't been chomping at the bit to
make Rambus memories. Samsung has been the most active Rambus
manufacturer. Because supplies have been limited, analysts say
Rambus chips cost about three times more than conventional memories
right now.
</P>
<P>
   That has slowed their adoption in computers. Dell Computer Corp.
is one of the few big computer makers that makes and promotes
high-end computers with Rambus chips. Dell chief executive Michael
Dell was an early investor in Rambus.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the industry is sticking with conventional memory chips
that run at 100 megahertz. That's what Samsung's Austin factory
presently makes. Soon, however, those conventional chips are
expected to speed up to 133 megahertz, resulting in performance
boost of about 10 percent that will show up in some computers.
</P>
<P>
   Even faster versions of conventional chips, employing something
called Double Data Rate technology, are on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   So who wins this battle of technologies? Different analysts have
different ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest Inc.'s Jim Handy says the smart money has to stick
with Intel and the technology that Intel supports. Because Intel is
backing Rambus, Handy believes that Rambus will capture about 15
percent of the memory market this year and more than half the
market next year.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, Handy believes, is simply too powerful a force in the
computer business for memory chip makers to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Mike Feibus of Mercury Research in Scottsdale,
Ariz., isn't so sure. Maybe there will be two high-speed memory
standards, he says, because Intel's main rival in the processor
business, Advanced Micro Devices Inc., doesn't seem interested in
backing the Rambus standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still on the fence about which memory technology is
going to dominate,'' Feibus said last week. ``So far, we haven't
seen much movement toward Rambus.''
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of next year, the question of which technology
will win will probably be settled. In the meantime, there is plenty
of uncertainty in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be one of the most fascinating years ever in
the computer industry,'' Feibus said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
