<SLUG> BC-TECH-GADGET01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Polaroid's new digital line offers variety
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Storing family photos as data and sending them by
e-mail across the country is one of the more enjoyable uses for a
personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   And digital cameras, one of the most direct ways to capture an
image for storage in the computer, are available at prices
appropriate for the family photographer if you aren't too fussy
about exceptional photo quality.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid, the company that pioneered instant photography, has
jumped into the digital camera market with a line of cameras that
starts with inexpensive models for children and goes up to a
megapixel model for the discriminating photo hobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of digital picture images is measured in pixels,
the colored dots that combine to make up the picture. A megapixel
image is made up of about a million dots.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the range of Polaroid's digital cameras is the
PhotoMAX PDC 640 digital camera that has started showing up in some
local stores. It has a resolution of 640 by 480 pixels, about a
third of a megapixel.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras in that range produce photos that look fine on a
computer screen, but large prints on paper aren't very sharp.
</P>
<P>
   The PhotoMAX PDC 640, though, has a lot of features to recommend
it, including a price of only about $200. Megapixel cameras usually
start at about twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   The 640 functions like a typical point-and-shoot film camera
only it doesn't use film. It has an automatic flash and an
automatic focus feature. It stores up to 96 images on its memory
card. And when its first 2 megabyte SmartMedia card is full, you
can pop in another.
</P>
<P>
   The camera comes packaged with a kit that includes a PhotoMAX
2.0 Image Maker software CD, personal computer and television
cables, an AC adapter and instructions both in written and online
form.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
