r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-ELIAN01-C     01-31 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-ELIAN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids mixed on Elian's fate
 &HT;    By Anne Y. Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We asked sixth- and seventh-graders around Atlanta
what they think should happen to the 6-year-old Cuban boy caught in
an international custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez was found on Thanksgiving 1999 clinging to an
inner tube in water off the Florida coast. His mother and
stepfather drowned while fleeing Cuba by boat.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father still lives in Cuba. His great-aunt and uncle
want him to stay in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans risk their lives to make the 90-mile crossing to the
United States because they believe they would be better off in this
country. Cuba has a Communist government. Here are some excerpts of
the kids' opinions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Roe Hunter, 13, Lost Mountain Middle School, Cobb County
</P>
<P>
   ``He was illegally brought in, but I think he should stay. I
don't think he really wants to go back, because Cuba is Communist
and I don't think it's a very good place for a child to grow up in
a Communist situation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Elizabeth Cogburn, 13, the Schenck School, Fulton County
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he is an illegal immigrant, he should have to go back to
Cuba. I think it would be good for him to have a happier life in
the United States or Cuba and not a long court thing where he's in
between places.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LaKeisha Holmes, 11, Shamrock Middle School, DeKalb County
</P>
<P>
   ``He should go back with his dad. He probably is not old enough
to make any of his own decisions because he's only 6. His dad can
make the decisions for him.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrick McGlynn, 12, S.M. Inman Middle School, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think he should go back to Cuba because that's where
his grandparents and his dad are. It makes me feel sorry for him,
because I don't think he knows what's really going on, and I don't
think he knows who he wants to be with.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tori Godfrey, 12, Sweetwater Middle School, Gwinnett County
</P>
<P>
   ``If his mother wanted him to come to America, then he should be
able to. His mother probably wanted him to go to America for a
particular reason, like maybe to have a better education and for
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
