<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DVDs, videotapes always good fit for online shopping
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Online merchants aren't just selling a product, they
are selling convenience. So, many people searching for a DVD or
videotaped movie, even those who live close to well-stocked retail
stores, are buying online.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a person making one more stop on the commute home
from work, the movies arrive at the doorstep. And _ unlike buying a
sweater or a piece of furniture online _ there's no need to worry
if your purchase will look and fit right. A DVD of ``Casablanca''
bought online will be identical to the one you find in the store.
</P>
<P>
   If you are into shopping online, it will come as no surprise
that one of the real leaders in merchandising is Amazon.com. It's
an enormously efficient organization with excellent customer
service. Although some people associate Amazon totally with books,
the strategy of the company has been to be an online merchant of
almost everything that can be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazon.com site at www
</P>
<P>
   .amazon.com has a broad selection of DVDs and videotapes. Prices
are good. In many cases, you'll pay less _ even with shipping _
than typical retail prices. The ability to search for the movie you
want by title, director or actor is pretty standard at most of the
sites reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com does have other features _ not all are exclusive to
Amazon _ that make shopping fun. For one thing, you can view a
list, updated hourly, of the top-selling videos. Even if you're the
sort of person who doesn't like swimming with the stream, it's fun
to see what's hot right now. You can also browse movies by
categories such as comedies, dramas and action.
</P>
<P>
   If you're into DVD, you may prefer a site that specializes in
just that format. That's literally the name of the game at DVD.com
located at www2
</P>
<P>
   .dvdexpress.com/consumer
</P>
<P>
   /movies/. The assortment is excellent and the delivery times _
based on several orders _ are astonishingly short.
</P>
<P>
   One nice feature that DVD.com pushes is the ability to preorder
a DVD. Usually a discounted price is offered for that kind of
order, and if you've been waiting for a specific movie, you can be
sure that you'll be among the first to get it. DVD.com has a handy
list of upcoming releases, and that makes for interesting browsing.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may be reluctant to buy a videotape or DVD, figuring
they'll watch the film once and that will be enough. So a site such
as MovieRent.Com offers that as a possibility. The site at
www.movierent.com
</P>
<P>
   /resources1.htm will be happy to rent the videotape or DVD or
sell it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a nifty site for a lot of reasons. Besides its own
sections within the site, you'll find links to other places on the
Web devoted to movies and DVD.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to discuss DVDs and videotaped movies
without mentioning Blockbuster. Undoubtedly there's a retail outlet
near you. But there's also an outlet on the Web at www
</P>
<P>
   .blockbuster.com.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find a good selection of movies here in both formats. The
prices are on par with those you'd find elsewhere. But one feature
that takes advantage of the Blockbuster retail business is the
ability to buy used videotapes online. The prices are great ...
averaging about $5 each.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you really need to know about a site that doesn't sell
DVDs or videotapes. Instead, it searches the sites that do sell
them and tells you where the bargains are. This truly valuable
service is located at www.moviepriceguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   Since the service is unique and difficult to explain in a few
sentences, go to the page at www.moviepriceguide.com
</P>
<P>
   /aboutus.shtml to read the explanation. It's a free service and
well worth checking out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
