<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A01-COX     01-31 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: My fiance and I are planning on getting
married in Cancun, Mexico. Do we need to apply for a marriage
license in Texas in order for the marriage to be valid here? Do we
need to take any special documents to Cancun for the marriage
ceremony to be performed? _Klira R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure you want to do this? Many hotels in Mexico have wedding
coordinators because regulations vary from state to state, city to
city. Coordination does not come cheaply, advises the Mexico
Tourism Office _ $250 minimum. Basic requirements? Certified birth
certificates, blood tests within 15 days of the wedding, a copy of
your tourist cards and, if either party has been married
previously, a certified copy of the divorce decree or the former
spouse's death certificate. Call (800) 44MEXICO (800-446-3942) for
details. It is easier to comply with U.S. laws to legally establish
your married status. How about a civil ceremony here and a
religious one in Mexico?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard from several people that boiling water in the
microwave can cause it to blow up. Also that dumping powdered
coffee, sugar, etc., in microwaved water can cause the water to
explode. _John Nemetz
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Superheated water'' can occur when water or any other
liquid is heated in a microwave for more than two minutes. The
liquid does not always come to a visible boil in the microwave, but
it could bubble out of the container when taken out. Best advice?
Do not heat liquids in a narrow-neck container and allow them to
stand in the microwave for 30 to 40 seconds before removing or
adding an ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just bought some English bone china tableware with gold
rims _ not marked ``dishwasher safe.'' The manufacturer says they
can go in the dishwasher provided I use liquid dishwashing
detergent. But a salesperson told me detergent would discolor the
gold, and another said the water jets might chip the rims. Can I
safely wash my dishes in the dishwasher? _S.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Occasionally, you can, considering the manufacturer's advice
(no hard water, I hope). Hand washing is preferred for fine china.
Remove large food particles off all the dishes to prevent
scratching during the wash cycle. In addition to using liquid
detergent, load the dishes carefully and turn off the heated drying
cycle. Cool china before unloading. Q: I wonder how many football
players from the University of Texas have been on a winning Super
Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   _D. Lunceford
</P>
<P>
   A: Quite a few. Thirty different Longhorns have played on 20
teams in the Super Bowl. Eleven have been on a winning side. Two
have done it twice: Dan Neil of the Denver Broncos in 1998 and 1999
and Terry Orr of the Washington Redskins in 1988 and 1992. The
others? John Elliot, Jim Hudson, Pete Lammons and George Sauer of
the 1969 Jets; Ricky Churchman with the 1982 49ers; Bill Heathcock
and Steve McMichael of the 1986 Bears; Raul Allegre of the 1987
Giants; and Terry Tausch of the 1990 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whenever I buy a suit, I am confused about the wool label:
100 percent wool, 100 percent new wool and wool gabardine. What's
the difference with respect to warmth? _Donna Ehrke
</P>
<P>
   A: Wool gabardine is my pick for year-round wearability in a
suit or trousers. Wool absorbs moisture and keeps a layer of dry
air near the skin. One hundred percent wool garments are made from
all wool, which could include wool derived from another wool
fabric, whereas 100 percent new wool garments contain virgin wool
(never part of any other fabric). Wool gabardine is a weave, a
tightly woven wool twill with a high sheen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our company CEO has decided, in order to save money, to turn
off the hot water in the building. I'm convinced that this is
against some health code, city or OSHA or other. Where can I get an
official publication (that I can mail anonymously) that will
convince him to turn the hot water back on? Also, I can no longer
find Sara Lee Chicken and Broccoli Croissants. Has the company
stopped making them? Do I need to make regular ``stock-up'' trips
to the outlet store? _B.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Occupational Safety and Health Administration spokesman
Lyndol Miller says, ``OSHA requires employees must be provided with
tepid water'' to wash their hands. Want to report this situation
(anonymously or otherwise)? Contact OSHA at (512) 916-5783. If you
spy any chicken and broccoli croissants, buy 'em. Sara Lee recently
ceased production.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Maytag Neptune washer and cannot use powder
additives. Do you know of any liquid water softener? I would also
like to know what kind of liquid I can add to my wash to take out
men's underarm odor from shirts and T-shirts. _ J and M
</P>
<P>
   A: Maytag Neptune customer service at (888) 462-9824 says you
can use powdered water softeners _ just cut the recommended amount
in half. As for that underarm odor and stain, try an enzyme
detergent like Biz or scrub the area with a toothbrush dipped in
sudsy ammonia or shampoo to loosen body oils before laundering. Q:
I own a 1995 SUV with 200,000 miles. It runs very well, but the
high mileage makes it impractical as a trade-in. My child will be
ready to drive in three years, and this vehicle would be a
practical, relatively safe vehicle for a teen-ager. Is it practical
to store a vehicle this long? What preparations would be necessary?
_ J. M.
</P>
<P>
   A: The best solution is to drive the car every month or so for
about 10 minutes to get the engine warmed up, advises car repair
czar Ben Schotz at Ben's Workshop. This circulates the fluids. If
you are determined to store it rather than drive it, there are a
few general guidelines, notes Schotz. Remove the battery and change
the engine oil and coolant as well as the brake fluid. Remove the
spark plugs, place an ounce of oil in each cylinder and crank the
motor briefly, then replace the spark plugs. Fill the fuel tank to
prevent condensation and get the weight of the vehicle partly off
the tires to prevent flat-spotting. When you are ready to put the
vehicle back on the road, drain and dispose of the fuel properly
(it's no good after three years). Be prepared to replace the
fluids, the battery and perhaps the tires. Driving it occasionally
is a whole lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is that familiar sounding voice in the McDonald's McRib
commercials local Asleep at the Wheel leader Ray Benson? Also, were
the ladies who sang the Southwest Airlines western swing-type ad
from the Austin area? _ R. Ellis
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it is Ray Benson. Those swing singers? Austin's Ethyl &AMP;
Methyl. Talented Austin musicians have appeared in advertisements:
You must have heard Christine Albert as the voice of Blue Bell and
Jerry Jeff Walker and Delbert McClinton in Thundercloud Subs spots.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
