<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available Tuesday after 2 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0201 -- In the strange world of online gaming, many
players say the attraction is a friendly thing, not a killing
thing. (Stafford, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes a
magnificent 4-column color illustration of computer gamers
surrounding a crystal ball.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY -- There is no need to jump into an upgrade to
Windows 2000. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes
1 column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS -- The Stowaway keyboard wins awards, support for
innovation. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) Art includes a 1-column
color photo of The Stowaway.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEF: A new Web hopes to connect well-heeled invetors with
high-tech entrepreneurs. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art
includes a 1-column color illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   TECH TOOLS: Adobe's new Photoshop LE is a good ``light'' version
of image-editing software. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
Art includes a 1-column color photo of the cover of the software
box.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GADGET _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Polaroid, the company that
pioneered instant photography, has jumped into the digital camera
market with a line of cameras that starts with inexpensive models
for children and goes up to a megapixel model for the
discriminating photo hobbyist. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CHIPMEMORY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ If computer users are going to
harness the latest whiz-bang processing performance, their
computers had better have memory chips that are running lickety
split. If memory chips cannot keep pace, then those fast and
expensive new processor chips will be sitting idle most of the time
and not earning their keep. Memory chip makers have created a
series of faster memory technologies throughout the 1990s. Usually,
after a short period of time, the new standard dominates and all
the world's memory makers shift their production to the new
technology. But this year and next year, things could go
differently. Two competing standards could emerge, and, if they do,
then life gets a little more complicated for the companies that
make computers and for PC buyers as well. (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ANNOY _ This week's most annoying gadget. (Kallenberg,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PLAYGEAR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Sony's Music Clip. (Kallenberg,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GAMER _ This week's rundown of games for the console and
desktop. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SHOP _ This week's rundown of shopping sites on the Web.
(Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-BLIND _ Atlanta's Center for the Visually
Impaired is focusing on using the computer to give employment and
independence to blind citizens who want to work. (Holsendolph,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: getting better radio reception using
an old-fashioned antenna. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Oz Clarke's Ultimate
Wine Guide. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ This column will not move today. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: buying DVDs and
videotapes on the Web. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ News on Apple and its products. This week: updated
Internet Explorer for the Mac. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-PREVENTION _ People who work in public health know all
too well the pattern of how the public responded when Y2K bugs
didn't materialize. People complained that too much money and time
were spent of Y2K readiness, and it really wasn't a big deal.
That's because it worked. And it's the same with public health
prevention programs. If they work -- no outbreaks of smallpox and
polio, nobody dying because they didn't get a flu shot -- the
public doesn't notice, and it makes it all the harder to get
funding for vital services the next year. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION-BOX _ Ten things you can do to prevent illness and
promote better health. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   FLU-VACCINE _ The formula for next year's flu vaccine has been
OK'd, and we'll say what strains are supposed to be circulating,
plus update the year's flu season so far, nationwide and in
Georgia. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   NURSE-TRAINING _ DAYTON, Ohio _ She's been having trouble
breathing, the patient tells nurse Mindy Stumm in the emergency
room. It's been going on for a day or so. Her feet are swollen,
too. ``Have you been coughing often?'' asks Joanne Crawford, the
respiratory therapist. All night, the patient says.It's all very
real, but the patient is just a lifeless dummy, the Human Patient
Simulator at Sinclair Community College. (Dayton Daily News). 40.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   OXYGEN _ Every major media company, from Time Warner to Disney,
has tried to corral woman viewers as their own. None have yet
succeeded. Can Oxygen, a new woman's channel pioneered by Nike
legend Gerry Laybourne, succeed where the giants have stumbled? We
explain her strategy and examine, through the lens of industry
observers, its chances of success. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OXGERRY: A profile of Gerry Laybourne, Oxygen's CEO. It's a look
at what she did at Nickelodeon and how that history might shape
Oxygen. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTNEY _ It's 1976 _ six years after The Beatles' painful
breakup. Paul McCartney is riding around New York City in a stretch
limo. Suddenly he gets a loopy urge to pay John Lennon an
unexpected visit at his spacious Manhattan apartment. (Thompson,
Palm Beach Post). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Three or four briefs of world and national news,
written for kids to understand. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
