<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-SPREAD (San Francisco) _ Studies in AIDS-ravaged Africa have
found that people with very low levels of HIV in their blood are
unlikely to infect others - suggesting that drug therapies or
vaccines that suppress the virus could significantly reduce its
spread. The research also gives compelling evidence that
circumcision may be protecting many men from contracting the
disease. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   MALES-COLLEGE (Undated) _ High school males are increasingly
less likely than females to take college entrance exams, creating
an unusual gender gap that puts fewer men in the pipeline to
college, according to recent testing data. While the trend is true
for all income groups, statistics show fewer low-income males take
the tests than any other group and have fallen behind their female
counterparts by a nearly 2-to-1 margin. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER-ELIANS (Brownsville, Texas) _ Elian Gonzalez, the
6-year-old Cuban whose name has become a household word, is one of
thousands of children taken each year by one parent and spirited
across international boundaries. Some parents who are hoping for
the return of a child complain about the attention that the
Gonzalez case is getting while they wait to learn the plight of
their children. By ALISON GREGOR.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PRIVACY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Should privacy come at a pricefor
consumers who don't want to be bothered by telemarketers? That's a
question state officials are expected to debate as New York looks
to join a growing number of states with ``do not call'' registries
_ special lists to protect people from unwanted phone sales pitches
throughout their days and nights. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-CUSTODIANS (San Francisco) _ Some San Francisco school
custodians have doubled their salaries through overtime pay,
earning more than top administrators and more than most teachers,
according to an analysis of school payroll records. One former
janitor earned $55,000 in overtime, becoming the 14th-highest paid
employee in the school district, with income of over $100,000. By
JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-INDEPENDENTS (Riverside, Calif.) _ For politicians aiming
at a statewide election victory, the easy lure are the 20 wealthier
western counties of California. But the second California _ the 38
eastern counties that can make or break the 2000 presidential race
_ is harder to encapsulate. Riverside and San Bernardino counties
have become the new voter-mining operation for politicians who
really know California. Mostly conservative voters here are crucial
to candidates because they are so independent. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SUPERBOWL (Undated) _ With a promise to limit any kind of
www.badjokes.com moments, here's a list of the good, the bad and
the bland of Super Bowl commercials. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TATTOO-ARTIST (Albany, N.Y.) _ William DeMichele's elegant
studio in a desolate section of Albany is, like his work, on the
fringe _ where there is often more than meets the eye. For more
than a decade, DeMichele has photographed people, mostly women,
with tattoos: Women with purple grapevines across their chests,
women with elaborate underwater scenes of tropical fish across
their backs, women with leopards on their thighs. He now has more
than 80,000 images of beauty that's skin deep. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   ICE-BREAKER (Troy, N.Y.) _ After a day on the Coast Guard cutter
Hawser, every member of the eight-person crew is sore. Twelve hours
of breaking up ice will do that. Twelve hours of driving the
64-ton, 400-horsepower ship up onto Hudson River ice until it
cracks, or smashing ``pancake'' ice into smaller pieces. ``This is
nonstop,'' Jim Todd, the officer in charge, said as the boat took
another lurch. ``When we tie up, everybody's dead tired.'' By ALAN
WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-FUR (Troy, N.Y.) _ Fur, in the form of coats, jackets,
wraps, accessories, trim and more, has made a comeback, hitting the
runways and closets of many women this winter. Despite controversy,
the popularity of fur is on the rise, with more than 200 designers
employing it in their collections for 1999-2000, as opposed to 45
designers in 1985, according to the Fur Information Council of
America. By KRISTI L. GUSTAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE (San Francisco) _ Whenever Europe calls me, I call
Rick Steves. He spends more time in Europe than any other traveler
I know, updating his guidebooks, and filming his popular PBS
series, ``Travels in Europe with Rick Steves.'' His advice this
year: Don't worry about the hordes predicted for this millennium
year. Except for Rome, Europe should be no more crowded than usual.
By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-WARNER (Atlanta) _ Dick Vermeil, in a routine burst of
hyperbole, said before the NFC Championship Game that he thought
Kurt Warner could be the next Joe Montana. He was, of course,
crazy. But not nearly as crazy now as he seemed then. Warner is
still three rings light, and he has not yet done nearly enough to
stroll into the Hall of Fame without so much as a nominating
speech. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
