<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1729 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      01-31 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET DOT-COMS _ BEST AD MOMENTS ARE DITKA'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's heartwarming that in what was supposed to be the
dot-com Super Bowl, some of the best commercial moments belonged to
a low-tech lunkhead.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Mike Ditka, former coach _ until his recent firing
_ of the New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ABC charged a record $2.2 million for 30 second ads during the
game between the Tennessee Titans and the St. Louis Rams, and it
seemed as if most of them involved some sort of e-business,
e-commerce or e-money-making outfit.
</P>
<P>
   E-eeew. Most were as confusing as Boomer Esiason's ``analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Ditka will do anything for money, including make a fool
of himself. His best moment came in an ad for Blockbuster Video, in
which he explained, in desperate fashion, the charms of the Julia
Roberts movie `Runaway Bride.` Chick flick? Nonsense, he pleaded _
to a kid selling popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help me out here,'' Ditka whined. ``I can't afford to lose
this job, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka also served as comic relief in a commercial for Charles
Schwab, set at the ``Shady Rest Retirement Home,'' where geezers
such as Charles Barkley, Barry Sanders and Wade Boggs now reside,
knitting and playing shuffleboard.
</P>
<P>
   The ad ended with Barkley sitting on the bottom rung of a bunk
bed. In came new roomie Ditka.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley: ``You got the upper.''
</P>
<P>
   Dot-coms fared less well. Yes, EDS Corp.'s ad about cat herding,
including testimony from cowboys _ or is that catboys (``Herdin'
cats, don't let anybody tell you it's easy'') _ and laugh-out-loud
shots of cats being herded across the plains, was hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   So was Etrade's ad about a man hospitalized because he has
``money coming out the wazoo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Get this man a private room,'' a doctor orders. Just like real
life.
</P>
<P>
   But they were the e-xceptions. Dot-coms may be revolutionizing
the stock market, but they're not setting any commercial standards.
</P>
<P>
   You may remember last year's big dot-com hit _ Monster.com's
black-and-white commercial showing kids talking about their
ambitions: ``I want to claw my way to middle management,'' that
kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   You'll forget its ad this year _ also black and white, with
people reciting from Robert Frost's `The Road Not Taken` as they
walk past a woman on a street corner. Pardon me while I empty my
brain trying to figure out what that has to do with a company that
helps people find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Another Etrade spot flaunted its ineptitude. After a monkey
danced for a few seconds between a couple of yokels, the following
flashed on screen: ``Well, we just wasted 2 million bucks. What are
you doing with your money?''
</P>
<P>
   Not giving it to you, pal, if that's the best you can come up
with.
</P>
<P>
   A Mountain Dew commercial showing a kid on a bike chasing _ and
catching _ a cheetah, then sticking his arm down its throat to
retrieve his soda can, gets points for either good computer effects
or great cheetah wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of effects, a Nuveen Investments ad set in the future
showed a computer-animated Christopher Reeve, who is paralyzed,
walking. Technically impressive, it was meant to be inspiring;
instead, it came off as manipulative, if not a little creepy.
</P>
<P>
   But does anyone get less bang for its buck than Budweiser?
Whether a dog actor recalling running into a van, designated driver
Wayne Gretsky driving a tipsy friend home in a Zamboni or a guy
leaving a black-tie party to deliver a baby Clydesdale _ cheers! _
none of the beermaker's ads scored.
</P>
<P>
   Worst still was the ``whassssssup?'' ad, in which Bud-swilling
imbeciles call each other and say that very word. Swell. Drink Bud
and become a monosyllabic wasteoid.
</P>
<P>
   So. Then. Why. Me. Want. Beer? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8974. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
