<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-TV-BEATLES-VH1-HNS &LR;      01-31 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BEATLES-VH1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATLES BIOPIC ASKS, `WHAT IF?' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine Paul McCartney and John Lennon. Imagine them six years
post-Beatles, separate and estranged. Now imagine Paul, on an
impulse, showing up at New York's Dakota apartment building.
Imagine him knocking on John's door.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the conversation that would take place.
</P>
<P>
   That's the exercise awaiting those who watch ``Two of Us,'' a
wonderful experiment in what-iffery that's sure to do one of two
things if you are a Beatle fanatic _ it'll either trigger rage (the
sacrilege!) or admiration (one more piece of Beatlemania!).
</P>
<P>
   I grew up on the Beatles without becoming a Beatlemaniac, and
exercises like this challenge me, so count me among the admirers. I
like the audacity of it and admire the work and the talent that
went into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always laughing about it at the beginning,'' said
Aidan Quinn, who plays Paul in the movie (Tuesday night, VH1). ``We
were calling it career hari-kari.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you not be daunted by this?'' added Jared Harris,
who plays John. ``We were very nervous and not sure whether we were
making the right choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lindsay-Hogg, whose directorial career includes such
films as Horton Foote's ``Alone, Celebration: The Music of Pete
Townshend and the Who, As Is, Brideshead Revisited`` and a little
ditty called ``Let It Be,'' chose well when he picked these two. He
based his choices on talent and not how closely the two resembled
the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, because neither actor looks like the person he is
portraying. That liberates the viewer from the distraction of an
impersonation, allowing the focus to be more on what's being said
and done.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, for example, fretted over his looks initially, then went
with a wig and brown contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had dreams of doing a whole bunch, and it became a problem
of logistics and time, and finally I just gave up trying to look
and sound like Paul,'' he said. ``I said just forget it, I'd have
to lose 50 pounds, get liposuction and plastic surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris apparently found the transition easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the look, it was the nose,'' he said. And the tinted
granny glasses helped, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``John had such a strong sartorial sense and image, you just get
in the right clothes and put the glasses on and you're
three-quarters of the way there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There'' is New York City, 1976, six years after the Beatles
have broken up. Paul has found new success with Wings. John is on a
creative timeout. His wife, Yoko Ono, is in California (``buying a
cow'') but ever-present.
</P>
<P>
   Paul is in town to play the Garden and, on a whim, decides to
stop by and give old friend John a buzz. There is initial
nervousness, followed by a slow descent of the walls that separate
them, followed by a daring outing in disguise _ to a park, then a
pub.
</P>
<P>
   There's a moment when they actually sit down at John's grand
piano and sing something. An old bond re-establishes. There is
warmth between the two.
</P>
<P>
   And wariness. The breakup thing. The wives thing. The
who-gets-credit-as-most-important-Beatle thing. The reunion thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us were there and could imagine accurately what went
on, but it is very well researched,'' Quinn said. ``A lot of the
things we said to each other are actual things Paul and John said
in interviews about each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the writer got the spirit of the two men. If their
names were Bob and Phil, I'd still want to do this project because
it was just that compelling a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer Mark Stanfield based his work on documented conversations
and a McCartney biography, by Chet Flippo, that recounts several
post-Beatles conversations between Paul and John. These are
squeezed into a second day for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always a good script but a little overwritten,'' said
Harris, who is the son of the actor Richard Harris. ``Mark was in
the Lennon camp, so we spent a week of rehearsal basically
adjusting that balance, in the sense that there isn't any way that
those two people could be anything other than a matched pair of
equals in temperament, talent, ego, strength of personality and
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn _ whose credits include ``In Dreams,`` ``Commandments``
and ``Legends of the Fall`` _ has never been a fan of biopics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've turned down many of them before because they're like
picking the bones,'' he said. ... ``I had to have a moral talk with
myself _ is this OK to do?'' Because the kind of tabloid
sensationalism that feeds into that fame thing ...is something I
would be so upset if I contributed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither actor has met a Beatle, but Quinn sent McCartney a
letter ``meant as an homage of respect and love, and I hope he's
not offended by it and hope it doesn't add to any of the
discomforting, dark side of all that fame stuff. I apologized to
him because I wouldn't know how I would feel if I became megafamous
and 20 years later someone's playing me as a young man. I'd
probably be amused. It's got to be weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Weird? Maybe so. Perhaps even someone as famous as McCartney can
be made uncomfortable by such stuff.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I fell head first into the exercise. The writing
worked for me, and Quinn and Harris had me in a spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of Us`` is a little gem and a nice big notch on the belt
of VH1, a fledgling in the made-for-TV movie biz.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
