<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TATTO-ARTIST-HNS &LR;      01-31 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TATTO-ARTIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PHOTOGRAPHER HELPS REDEFINE BODY ART 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ William DeMichele's studio is in a third-story
walkup in a converted Albany warehouse on a desolate stretch of the
Hudson River, across the street from an abandoned building with
shattered windows and thick weeds that almost obscure the sad old
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But venture inside and you will see beautifully restored
hardwood floors, classy furniture and startlingly rich photographs.
</P>
<P>
   DeMichele's studio, like his work, is on the fringe, where there
is often more than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, DeMichele has photographed people,
mostly women, with tattoos: Women with purple grapevines across
their chests, women with elaborate underwater scenes of tropical
fish across their backs, women with leopards on their thighs. He
now has more than 80,000 images of beauty that's skin deep.
</P>
<P>
   DeMichele's 1992 book, ``The Illustrated Woman'' is in its third
printing and has been translated into Japanese, and 16 of his
photos make up the largest part of ``Body Art: Marks of Identity,''
an exhibit at the American Museum of Natural History in New York,
which closes in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of there being a body-art exhibit at the American
Museum of Natural History is groundbreaking,'' says DeMichele,
sitting in his spacious studio. ``The fact that the most
prestigious museum in the United States recognizes body art as a
true art form and as a true medium that has been in our culture and
other cultures since the beginning of man really legitimizes
tattooing.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming negative stereotypes about tattoos and the people who
collect them has long been one of the photographer's missions.
``I've become one of the ambassadors of tattooing,'' says
DeMichele, who travels around the country and the world covering
tattoo conventions and seeking models for his portraits. ``Tattoo
conventions are not biker-oriented, per se. They really don't
follow the cliche that most people have about tattooing. These are
professional people who can afford professional tattoos.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMichele's pictures focus more on the individual than the
tattoo. ``They are portraits of women with tattoos. They aren't
tattoos on women,'' says DeMichele, adding that he has always been
attracted to both the tattoo artwork itself and the people
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his subjects are photographed nude and unposed. ``I
don't want them to be showing fashion. I want them to be showing
themselves. You can see that mostly in the eyes or how they pose or
how they stand. I let them react to the environment. It's my job to
just capture that moment in time.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMichele, 46, sports several tattoos, three small earrings in
his left ear and a salt-and-pepper beard that makes him look a
little like Martin Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer's wife says DeMichele's rapport with his
subjects contributes greatly to the final image. ``He really has a
gift for bringing out beauty in even the most ordinary women,''
says Cynthia DeMichele, who runs her own graphic design business
near their home in Bethlehem. ``I've seen girls go into his studio
with stooped shoulders and obvious low self-esteem and they emerge
just radiant.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair met a decade ago when Cynthia was designing a CD cover
with one of DeMichele's photographs. They arranged to discuss the
deal over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up eating lunch and never even talked about the
photo,'' she says. For their first date, DeMichele went to her
apartment and cooked a delicious meal of lobster ravioli. ``He's a
man of many talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia DeMichele says she knew ``little or nothing'' about the
world of tattoos when she met her husband, but after attending her
first convention, she was hooked. ``Here's just a plain white girl
such as myself with an opportunity to meet so many interesting
people,'' says Cynthia, who recently got her first tattoo. ``I
consider it an adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMichele says tattoos have become more acceptable and more
artistic in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the quality of the tattooing has changed. I think the
type of tattoo people get has changed, and the clientele has
changed. It's gotten much younger. Years ago it was primarily just
sailors and laborers. Then in the hippie era and the first women's
movement, women started getting tattoos, but they were much
smaller. It was more of a statement of independence. It didn't take
much, just a little butterfly or flag or peace sign. Then it went
into hiatus a little bit in the '70s, but then in the late '80s and
'90s it became very popular and trendy again because of the rock
stars and athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the same time, a lot of young people started becoming
tattoo artists, the difference being these artists have art
backgrounds. We're talking about college graduates with (master of
fine arts degrees), many in printmaking. Of course they brought
their artwork with them, so they were doing fantastic art pieces.
And the (subjects) were willing to oblige and willing to donate
more of their skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been more people with larger, more visible
tattoos, including ``sleeves,'' which cover the arms to the wrist,
and full, detailed back pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women definitely changed tattooing,'' says DeMichele.
``They changed it from being just a ritual meant to denote
friendship or time or camaraderie to making a visual statement to
beautify the body. Women were showing that they could make a
choice, that they could dedicate themselves to something and show
strength in ways that hadn't been seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what happened was the quality of the tattooing got better,
the quality of the imagery got better. No longer were you seeing
the traditional type of tattoo imagery. You started to see much
more decorative, much more ornate tattoos.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeMichele's adventure with all things tattoo began in 1976, when
he saw a poster advertising classes with landscape photographer
Ansel Adams in California. DeMichele headed West, stopping for a
detour in San Francisco on his way.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that he spotted the studio of Lyle Tuttle, who was
famous for tattooing the likes of Janis Joplin and Peter Fonda. ``I
saw the tattoo studio right across the street from the bus station
and I walked in, looked around and picked out a little tiny tattoo.
I was very intimidated that it was the Lyle Tuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Tuttle of DeMichele, ``He's a complete package: good
businessman, good photographer, good promoter.'' The two are now
partners in an on-line tattoo business that offers articles on
tattooing techniques and history, lists tattoo conventions around
the world and yellow pages of tattoo artists, and displays tattoo
designs for sale. Tuttle says his friend is successful at his craft
because of his ``attention to detail. It's more than inborn
patience. It's just professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an ingratiating guy and he's as gregarious as hell,''
says Tuttle, now retired from tattooing and still living in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When Ann Fitzgerald, senior researcher for the department of
anthropology at the American Museum of Natural History, began
researching contemporary tattooing for the exhibit, DeMichele's
name came up repeatedly. ``His pictures are very appealing,'' says
Fitzgerald, who worked with DeMichele for a year to create the
exhibit. ``They're very direct. You feel like you've met these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald says she knew almost nothing about tattooing when she
first approached DeMichele for help. He opened up that world for
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very generous and extremely curious and exploratory,''
she says. ``He's got a real sense of enthusiasm for the way in
which we all experiment with ourselves and our lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
