<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1755 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-HNS &LR;      01-31 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VETERAN OF EUROPE OFFERS TRAVEL TIPS FOR THE CONTINENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is the time of year when my thoughts turn
to cafe au laits in sidewalk cafes and scones with clotted cream in
thatched-roof cottages, to spooky gothic cathedrals and
sun-splashed vineyard picnics, to gargoyles and lederhosen and
cobblestones and gelato.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Europe calls me, I call Rick Steves. He spends more
time there than any other traveler I know _ an average of 100 days
a year for the last two decades spent updating his ``Europe Through
the Back Door'' and other guidebooks, and filming his popular PBS
series, ``Travels in Europe with Rick Steves.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently I asked Steves what is in store for travelers headed to
Europe this summer, perhaps for the first time in years. He opened
up his notebook, and here's some of what spilled out:
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about the hordes predicted for this millennium year.
Except for Rome, which expects to be packed with Eastern European
Catholics permitted to travel there for the first Holy Year of
their lifetimes, Europe should be no more crowded than usual. If
anything, hoteliers are nervous that the Continent could resemble
Yogi Berra's classic koan: It's so crowded no one goes there
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Leave your travelers' checks and currency converters at home.
ATMs are now so ubiquitous you can find them in even the smallest
villages. And with the euro trading at almost exactly a dollar, the
days of converting deutsche marks into dollars while the waiter
drums his fingers impatiently on the table are over. (The euro
won't replace local currencies in euro countries for two more
years, but for the purposes of credit card transactions, menus and
price tags in euro countries almost always carry both figures.)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Italy, classic monuments and artworks are finally
available for viewing. In Venice, the scaffolding is off of St.
Mark's, and for the first time in memory the entire front of the
basilica is viewable and looking sumptuous. In Milan, Leonardo's
Last Supper has finally reopened to the public, but with a rigid
reservation system allowing only 25 people to enter every 15
minutes. You must have a reservation to get in (call
011-39-028-942-1146 from the United States). In Assisi, the
Basilica of St. Francis, with its frescoes freshly restored after
suffering earthquake damage, is now ready for visitors. The
Franciscans have opened a huge new subterranean entrance area below
the square in front of the church.
</P>
<P>
   In London, the famous Half-Price Ticket Booth at Leicester
Square is now surrounded by fake ``half-price'' booths that confuse
and cheat tourists. Be warned: The real booth is a free-standing
kiosk actually in the square, not a ticket agency near the tube
station.
</P>
<P>
   In England's Cotswold region, the new Cotswold Link bus service
runs twice daily in both directions between Bath and Stratford,
making up to 13 stops en route, hitting the highlights of the
Cotswolds including Chipping Camden, Stow-on-the-Wold and
Moreton-in-Marsh. You can use this service to day-trip from Bath to
visit one Cotswold town; as transportation through the Cotswolds
(stopping where you like for an overnight); or to day-trip from a
Cotswold town to see Stratford. A Bath-Stratford ticket costs 7
pounds ($12.)
</P>
<P>
   All over Ireland, big modern and inexpensive hotels are driving
bed and breakfasts out of business. Every big Irish city now has a
Jurys Inn offering hundreds of cookie-cutter rooms with unbeatable
prices and no character.
</P>
<P>
   Dublin's Smithfield Village, until recently a rundown industrial
area, is about to become the next Temple Bar. Its Ceol Music Museum
is an interactive Irish music encounter, a high-tech opportunity to
bone up on ``trad'' before heading for the small-town pubs. The
neighboring Old Jameson Distillery is OK, but nowhere near as good
as the Old Bushmills tour in Northern Ireland. The distillery's
chimney now comes with an elevator taking tourists 175 feet high
for the best view in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   The new Oresund bridge connecting Denmark and Sweden is set to
open in July 2000, making the ferry obsolete. This new 10-mile span
will speed train travel and save motorists time (but not money: the
toll is 210 kroner _ $29!)
</P>
<P>
   In Amsterdam, the Rijksmuseum is celebrating 2000 with a year of
special exhibits. Through the tourist season it will host the Glory
of the Golden Age exhibit, amassing an extravaganza of 17th-century
Dutch art. The unfortunate result: too much art, long lines, higher
prices and very likely a complex reservations-only system. Check
before heading to the museum. The Van Gogh museum is newly
renovated, and the new Dutch Resistance Museum gives the best
anywhere look at resistance to the Nazis..
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, you can now climb the stunning new glass dome on the
Reichstag, Germany's new/old Parliament building. Lighted from
within at night, the dome gives Berlin a memorable new night light.
It's free and open daily from 8 a.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Prague Excursion Pass, a rail pass for Eurailers who want to
go to Prague (a non-Eurail country) without hassling with tickets,
is sold by Euraide offices in Munich (011-49-89-593-889;
www.euraide.de) and Berlin ($46 first-class, $31 second-class, $23
for those under 26). You can also get them through Euraide's U.S.
office (phone: 941-480-1555; fax: 941-480-1522) or Steves' Europe
Through the Back Door (425-771-8303).
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has just adopted a direct-dial phone system, joining a
growing list of European countries _ Spain, France, Italy, Norway,
Denmark _ that have dropped area codes. If you have old numbers for
Portugal, replace the initial 0 with a 2 and you'll likely get
through.
</P>
<P>
   In Granada, Spain, lines for the Alhambra are long and only a
certain number of people are admitted per day. You can now reserve
by phone. Call at least two days or as much as a year in advance
(011-34-90-222-4460), pay by credit card (Visa, Mastercharge
accepted; there's a surcharge of around 75 cents) and get a
reference number that allows you to pick up your ticket at any BBV
Bank (a minimum of a day before your visit) or at the main Alhambra
entrance (at least two hours before your visit).
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, visitors continue to marvel at the time-saving
efficiency of the Paris Museum Pass (which allows you to skip all
the lines) and the sneaky secret entrance to the Louvre Museum (off
Rue du Rivoli). With new security tighter, lockers in the train
stations are now available again. The grand Pompidou Gallery of
Modern Art reopened on Jan. 1. Don't miss the impressive new museum
of Jewish History in the Marais. Monet's water lilies are out of
view, as the Orangerie will be closed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More Europe updates are available at www.ricksteves.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
