<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1759 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIE-HANGAR-KANSAS-K     01-31 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HANGAR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECT LANDING FOR MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYVILLE, Mo. _ The first thing you notice about the new Hangar
Cinema is that it doesn't look like a five-screen movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   What it looks like, in fact, is a small-town airport somehow
transported to 1602 S. Main Street _ a collection of arched Quonset
hut-type metal buildings with big sliding doors (nonfunctional, it
turns out) and topped by a huge windsock.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of these structures _ the three-story one smack dab
in the middle _ is further distinguished by the small passenger
plane that appears to have plowed into its facade about 20 feet
above the sidewalk. The aircraft's tail section sticks out from the
wall, a red running light still blinking in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cavernous lobby the aeronautical decor continues. The
bare concrete floor has been painted like an airport runway. Trash
cans appear to have been fashioned from old jet fuel barrels.
Dangling from the high ceiling are three colorful hang gliders and
an unfurled yellow parachute. The walls are decorated with junked
airplane parts: smashed doors, twisted propellers, a pilot's seat
stripped down to its metal frame, beat-up instrument panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a theater design that was both functional
and cost-effective,'' explained Hangar owner Tad Gordon, WHO.
``Your basic airplane hangar was perfect. This theater is built
from the same materials the Air Force uses for hangars. It's even
used for housing on the South Pole.''
</P>
<P>
   The early career of the New Jersey-reared Gordon, 46, centered
on his own Wall Street brokerage firm and running a commercial hog
operation. He'd never been in the movie exhibition business before
founding Countryside Cinema a few years ago in Princeton, Mo.,
where he lives with his wife and three children.
</P>
<P>
   The five-screen Hangar, his first theater, opened in November in
Maryville, a town about 40 miles north of St. Joseph with a
full-time population of nearly 12,000 and 6,000 students attending
Northwest Missouri State University.
</P>
<P>
   The Hangar has been such a success, Gordon claims, that it will
be operating in the black in only six months. If that's true, it
represents a rate of return virtually unheard of in the movie
theater business.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things hugely lacking in small towns is
entertainment,'' said Gordon, who moved to Princeton, about 70
miles east of Maryville, more than a decade ago as the co-founder
of Premium Standard Farms, a hog processing operation. ``It drove
me nuts that I had to go all the way to Kansas City to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   His answer is the Hangar, the first of what he foresees as a
chain of state-of-the-art movie houses designed specifically for
small-town America.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane-themed decor is only the frosting on the cake.
Consider these innovations:
</P>
<P>
   - A full-service Italian restaurant in the lobby seats 55; it's
open for lunch and remains in operation as late as necessary to
keep the patrons happy.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking pre-processed microwaved portions served on
Styrofoam with plastic utensils. Made-from-scratch dishes are
served on real plates with real silverware. The menu ranges from
appetizers to such entrees as pizza, lasagna and fettuccine ($6.95
to $9.95), sandwiches and desserts like cannoli and tiramisu. The
restaurant also serves wine and beer.
</P>
<P>
   (This reporter and a photographer dined at the Hangar's
restaurant and found the food and service to be the equal of most
stand-alone Italian eateries.)
</P>
<P>
   And there's more.
</P>
<P>
   - The Hangar's most unusual feature may be its ``dinner
theater,'' a 100-seat movie theater where patrons sit at tables and
order Italian meals _ or your regular concession-stand fare _ via
white telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Typically patrons arrive an hour or so before the movie starts
in order to dine, but they also can order a meal any time during
the show.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday night Pat and John Schieber of Maryville
settled into their seats, dug into their ravioli and ziti, and
while awaiting for the start of Oliver Stone's ``Any Given Sunday''
explained that the Hangar had completely changed their
entertainment habits.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Scheiber described Maryville's longtime movie house _ a
decades-old facility divided into two auditoriums _ as ``smelly and
musty with uncomfortable seats. No class, no appeal. We used to
drive to St. Joe to see movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hangar, though, got a rave review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maryville has needed a place like this for ages,'' she said.
``My two oldest boys are grown now, but they say they would have
killed to have had this when they were young. One reason kids in
small towns get into trouble is that they're bored. There's nothing
to do. This place is great.''
</P>
<P>
   - In fact, Gordon sees the Hangar as not just a movie theater
but also a community center. A game room in the lobby features two
pool tables, an air hockey game, several video games and a
large-screen TV that plays music videos. There are even two free
phones so that youngsters can make local calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a high school hangout. You don't have to see a
movie to come here to eat or play pool,'' Gordon said. And, he
emphasized, the Hangar is yet to witness any teen-age incidents or
alcohol-related disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any more problem with that than your average
Pizza Hut does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the dinner theater is equipped with large-screen video
projection. Chiefs games and Northwest Missouri State away games
play to big crowds; the facility also can be adapted for business
and community meetings.
</P>
<P>
   - Even in the more prosaic area of simple moviegoing, the Hangar
reaches for a state-of-the-art experience.
</P>
<P>
   Because each of the complex's five auditoriums occupies its own
hangar, ``in effect, each auditorium is in a separate building,''
Gordon said. ``So there's no sound bleed. You don't hear `Top Gun'
coming through the wall when you're trying to watch a quiet love
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Each auditorium has stadium seating _ virtually unknown in
smaller markets. Plus, there's 30 feet of floor space between the
screen and the front row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every seat,'' manager Richard Groves says, ``has a perfect
view.''
</P>
<P>
   Seating capacity in the individual houses ranges from 150 to
249.
</P>
<P>
   - The gently arched ceilings of the hangar structures provided
an unexpected bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for the floor, there's hardly a flat surface in this
place,'' Gordon said. ``Turns out that's what gives us such great
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, once treated with sound-absorbing material, the curved
surfaces became an acoustical dream.
</P>
<P>
   The Hangar offers nearly perfect digital sound, according to
Larry Jacobs, whose Lenexa-based LJ Technologies Inc., installs
theater sound and projection systems throughout the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound absorption up those side walls, along the ceiling
and down again along the back is almost complete,'' said Jacobs,
who last year won a technical Oscar for his part in developing a
system to analyze movie theater projection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most theaters just have laid-in ceiling tiles. But the Hangar
has minimum reflection, virtually no sound anomalies, no sound
clutter. It's as good as anything I've encountered.''
</P>
<P>
   - There's more. Each of the Hangar's five auditoriums is
equipped with four TV monitors mounted on the side walls. Before
the movie this closed-circuit system shows advertising, the
theater's screening schedule, previews of upcoming movies and
public service announcements. It can display sporting events pulled
off satellites or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local ads pay for the whole thing,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is working on a campaign to spread the word about his new
movie palace. Although the Hangar is drawing audiences from a
100-mile radius _ including Iowans who travel across the state line
20 miles north of Maryville (this reporter spotted several Iowa
plates in the parking lot) _ locals have been without a first-class
movie theater for so long that many have fallen out of the
film-going habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out here it's strictly `show me,' '' Gordon said. ``Word of
mouth. Advertising doesn't work. You don't try something new until
someone comes up to you and says: `I was there. It was neat.' Then
you go see for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his effort centers on developing the Hangar's mascot,
the fictional Bob the bush pilot. Bob's a hard-luck sort of guy
whose planes always crash. The aircraft parts scattered around the
theater supposedly are the result of Bob's past mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is developing a lobby display that traces Bob's history.
The idea is to suck customers into the fun of this local mythology.
</P>
<P>
   As the majority owner of the Hangar, Gordon is looking to expand
the concept, although he plans to steer clear of big cities and
competition from major chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conveniently, there are lots of small college towns in the
Midwest,'' he said. ``Maryville was just one of 10 regional sites
we considered. We'll perfect the concept here, then go looking for
new locations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
