<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1761 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-HEALTH-VISION-KANSAS-     01-31 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-VISION-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP REKINDLES INTEREST IN KC OPTOMETRIST'S UNORTHODOX METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Were you a patient?
</P>
<P>
   If you were a patient of Joseph J. Kennebeck, an optometrist
practicing in Kansas City from the 1930s to the 1970s, and if you
can provide details about his treatment technique, call Joseph
Miele in New Jersey at (732) 671-5550. He is gathering information
from former patients in an attempt to piece together Kennebeck's
methodology.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Kennebeck may have been onto something.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1930s to the 1970s, Kennebeck practiced optometry in
Kansas City, but his methods were different from those used by most
optometrists then or now. He believed he could improve vision or at
least prevent further losses by putting patients through a regimen
of eye exercises and teaching them a different way of reading.
</P>
<P>
   Kennebeck died in 1977, but not before putting his thoughts into
a book titled Why Eyeglasses Are Harmful for Children and Young
People.
</P>
<P>
   Theories similar to Kennebeck's have come in and out of vogue
over the years. And now a group of optometrists from across the
country is seeking former patients and colleagues who could shed
light on the sort of unorthodox work done by Kennebeck.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Miele is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole group of people who are interested in the kind
of things Kennebeck was trying to do,'' said Miele, who practices
optometry in Middletown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas being explored, he said, are similar to the ones
Kennebeck used decades ago in his practice downtown and, later, on
the Country Club Plaza and in Brookside.
</P>
<P>
   Kennebeck's daughter, Sister Rose Joseph Kennebeck, is with the
Benedictine order in Nauvoo, Ill. She worked in her father's office
a couple of summers in the 1940s and remembers patients ``from all
over the United States'' who would come for treatment of
nearsightedness, farsightedness and crossed eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is fuzzy on the particulars of his approach, she
thinks he usually began by lobbying his patients to give up their
glasses. She says her father had boxes and boxes filled with
discarded spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   His theory, as she recalls, was that he could strengthen eyes by
forcing them to focus without glasses. She remembers seeing 30
persons at a time seated in the office with various lenses over
their eyes. They would then look either out the window at a distant
landmark or at a book nearby, depending on their vision problem.
Some patients looked through glass lenses of varying strengths, and
others peered through tiny pinholes poked in metal lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Carney, a retired Kansas City priest, sought out
Kennebeck's therapy in the early 1950s. Carney's glasses were a
nuisance during the baseball and basketball games he played while a
student at Conception Seminary in northern Missouri. He had heard
that Kennebeck favored jettisoning spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   Although two other optometrists had told Carney he needed
glasses, he got rid of them at Kennebeck's urging _ flung them out
the car window as he was driving over the Missouri River, in fact,
on his way back from Kennebeck's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't wear glasses for 20 years,'' he said. ``I was 41 when
I got glasses again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennebeck convinced Carney that his sore, watery eyes were the
result of poor reading habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would stare at the lines and never blink my eyes,'' Carney
said. ``My eyes never relaxed, and got sore. Watering was a
reaction to soreness. He said, `You have to blink more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brookside resident Don McDonald Sr., a nephew of Kennebeck, has
seen letters from former patients testifying to how much their
sight improved with Kennebeck's unorthodox treatments.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald remembers that the optometrist refused to ever wear
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Kennebeck definitely was an outsider in his profession. He spoke
to a group of optometrists at Columbia University about his
technique early on, but he never gained a following, according to
his daughter. He then kept his theories to himself, recalls Louis
Bono, a retired optometrist who grew up as a neighbor of
Kennebeck's in Brookside.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bono didn't embrace Kennebeck's approach, he recalls
that patients reported success. Men rejected by the Air Force
because of vision problems often sought out Kennebeck's services.
And Bono says many of them improved their vision enough to be
accepted as pilots in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could bring them perhaps from 20-30 to 20-20'' by teaching
them tactics to make sense of blurry images, according to Bono.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Kennebeck's approach was the premise that some vision
problems are caused at least in part by the way people use their
eyes. Refractive disorders _ nearsightedness and farsightedness _
occur when light rays, which are bent or refracted by the lens and
the cornea, meet either in front of or behind the retina, causing
blurry vision. The distance is too long, from front to back, in the
case of nearsightedness (also known as myopia), and too short in
the case of farsightedness (hyperopia).
</P>
<P>
   The role of reading and other ``near work'' in the development
of myopia ``is a topic of great debate in the research community,''
said Karla Zadnik, an associate professor at the Ohio State
University College of Optometry. ``It's an ongoing debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennebeck believed that children should not wear glasses at
least until the age of 10 or so, when eye growth mostly ceases.
</P>
<P>
   Studies involving different animal species have established that
eye growth during childhood is affected by environmental factors _
specifically, the clarity of the images eyes are exposed to. An eye
exposed to a fuzzy image will grow in such a way as to compensate,
to some degree, for the vision impairment, according to Michael
Oberdorfer, a grants administrator for the National Eye Institute
in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is financing a study of 450 nearsighted
children to determine whether early eye strain exacerbates myopia,
Zadnik said. The study also might show whether the strain that
results from ``near work'' contributes to myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the children are being fitted with standard single-lens
glasses and half with progressive bifocals to minimize the strain
of reading and other close work. In the next three years the
researchers will compare the two groups' myopia. The results might
suggest that early eye strain promotes nearsightedness, which would
reinforce Kennebeck's belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking about retarding the future development of
myopia,'' not regaining vision that's already been lost, Zadnik
said. She characterized Kennebeck's claims as ``pretty dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   David Guyton, too, is circumspect about Kennebeck's apparent
belief that he could prevent or in some cases correct certain
visual problems. Guyton is a professor of ophthalmology and
director of the Krieger Children's Eye Center at Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors who treat vision problems acknowledge that glasses,
``especially for close work, can make your nearsightedness worse,''
Guyton said. ``That we know pretty well. The way to keep it from
getting worse is not to push glasses on people.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the problem of how people with refractive errors
will compensate for whatever visual problems they have, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kennebeck's theory that children and young adults, at
least, could exercise their way to improved vision, Guyton said:
``There are certain exercises for eyes that are misaligned that can
make them better. There's not much that can be done in the way of
exercises to change refractive errors that we know of. There's been
a fringe element of people out there all this time who have claimed
there are ways to do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of treatment is looked at by most ophthalmologists
and optometrists as a type of quackery. And yet, there are certain
things that these `quacks' have done that do work. You can't say
everything is wrong. Some of the things they are doing have merit,
and some don't. Separating them out is a bag of worms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
