<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1764 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-WOMEN-AGGRESSION-KANS     01-31 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-AGGRESSION-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRLS, INTERROGATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When women go bad, they rarely follow the path of Pheng
Siriboury.
</P>
<P>
   Siriboury is charged with using a gun and taking several people
hostage while attempting to rob an Olathe bank on New Year's Eve.
Her next court appearance is set for Feb. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about that incident _ not the confrontation, not the
setting, not the gun, was typical of how women run afoul of the
law. Females tend to commit crimes in ways and for reasons distinct
from males.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, an increasing number of girls are being detained and
being sent to juvenile treatment centers, and more women are being
arrested and charged with domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Women account for a growing proportion of Missouri's prison
inmates. In 1980 women were 3 percent of the prison population of
5,014. Now they make up almost 8 percent of the population of about
26,300.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this alarming rise, women continue to cause a relatively
small percentage of the crimes in the United States. Women on
average accounted for 14 percent of the violent offenders between
1993 and 1997, according to figures released in December by the
U.S. Bureau of Justice Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1989 and 1998, arrests of women and girls increased by
27.5 percent. Although the numbers in most major violent crime
categories dropped or remained pretty stable, aggravated and simple
assaults by women increased dramatically _ by 67 percent and 98
percent, respectively. Offenses by women against family members
increased by 130 percent. And drug-related arrests of women also
have increased substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests of female minors increased by 50 percent between 1989
and 1998, also fueled in large part by disproportionate spikes in
aggravated and simple assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Total arrests of male minors, though about three times as high
as arrests of girls, increased by only 16.5 percent during that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Meda Chesney-Lind isn't ready to conclude that women and girls
are getting rougher and tougher. She suspects that greater numbers
of women arrested in domestic disputes or girls detained for simple
assaults may reflect a changed attitude on the part of police,
schools and society in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us suspect that the push that the women's movement
initiated to encourage mandatory arrest in domestic violence has
been a source of this,'' said Chesney-Lind, a professor of women's
studies at the University of Hawaii in Honolulu, and author of
several books about females who break the law.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Hanna, a Vermont law professor who for three years
prosecuted people for domestic violence in Baltimore, said she also
thinks women are being prosecuted more frequently in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   She cites two reasons. One is decreased social tolerance for
aggressive women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police are more willing to arrest women'' and in a domestic
dispute will sometimes arrest both parties if they aren't sure whom
to blame, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, according to Hanna, ``Women are more likely to strike
back and to use violence in a relationship. The stereotypical big
bad husband with a wife cowering in the corner is less and less
likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence charges aren't reserved for spouses or
partners. Chesney-Lind, who has studied police reports about
domestic disputes, said they are sometimes leveled against
daughters who can't be arrested for, say, leaving home or hanging
out with the ``wrong'' boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds for assault charges are sometimes quite thin.
Chesney-Lind cited one case in which a girl was charged with
assault for throwing cookies at her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the walls of home, many girls who commit crimes do so
within the context of a street gang, according to Hanna, who has
researched girl gangs and violent girls.
</P>
<P>
   The growing numbers have provoked opposing interpretations. Some
thinkers ascribe it to what Hanna calls a ``decline in chivalry.''
Translated, that means a decreased willingness to overlook violent
behavior among girls.
</P>
<P>
   Chesney-Lind points to ``zero tolerance'' policies at schools,
which can result in adolescents being referred to law authorities
for offenses that would have gone unreported in an earlier time.
</P>
<P>
   Another camp think girls have, in fact, become more aggressive
and willing to break laws _ ``one of the unintended consequences of
liberation,'' Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   Females tend to target other females when they commit crimes,
and simple assaults are one of the most prevalent crimes committed
by women and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Much female violence is ``gossip gone lethal. It's interpersonal
issues that spill over into a violent area,'' Chesney-Lind said.
</P>
<P>
   She characterizes their crimes as ``expressionist,'' or ``an
extension of women's more normal kinds of relationships with each
other. There can be a lot of high drama around women's
relationships with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's crimes tend to be what she calls ``instrumental. It's
using violence to get at some other goal,'' often money or power or
status.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna suspects that much adolescent female violence stems from
competition for men, a contest that is waged in more ``socially
acceptable'' ways among most women.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that's so fascinating to discover is that
many of these girls are competing for high-status males. It's like
the head of the cheering squad wants to go out with captain of the
football team. It's girls competing for the most high-status
males.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna quoted a theory formulated by Anne Campbell, an
evolutionary psychologist from England: ``Female violence is more
likely to arise when there are fewer good men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's absolutely right,'' Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding sexual competition, Hanna contends, is what she
believes to be a current ``cultural norm that says `aggressiveness
is sexy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna sees signs of a social embrace of female aggressiveness in
certain pop cultural and entertainment figures such as the Disney
movie character Mulan, some members of the Spice Girls music group
and Xena, Warrior Princess.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Levin, a professor of sociology and criminology and
director of the Brudnick Center on Violence at Northeastern
University in Boston, disagrees: He thinks aggressiveness has lost
some appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he concurs with Hanna that girls have grown more
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``And sadly enough, I think women have used men as a role model.
Teen-aged girls are more likely to get involved in violence than
they used to, but they haven't caught up with their male
counterparts. Women's violent behavior is where men's was in the
'60s and '70s. Women are still using their fists, pulling hair and
occasionally pulling a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of women recently charged with battery sought legal
counsel from Scott Gyllenborg, a criminal defender in Olathe. His
take on it: that police ``are becoming more sensitive to the fact
that all along, women have had their share of domestic violence. If
the idea is to arrest and prosecute to instill respect for the law,
it has to work both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   He definitely thinks more women are being arrested. What's less
clear to him is whether they've grown more criminally aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Also among Gyllenborg's recent caseload are two women charged
with criminal damage to property _ two professional, middle-class
mothers who were accused of expanding their usual suburban
chauffeuring duties to include aiding and abetting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each case, completely independently, somebody (ticked) off
the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl involved took umbrage at another girl who ``dissed''
her boyfriend. The boy involved in the other case was angry about
being confronted by a friend's parents about drinking in their
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd go home and tell the folks about it,'' Gyllenborg said.
``The moms, in each case, offered to take them back to the house
and damage some property.''
</P>
<P>
   There were fathers in both households.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what was kind of weird about the whole thing,''
Gyllenborg said. ``I'm not sure the fathers even knew anything had
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
