<HEADER>
A1768 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-ROMAN-POLANSKI-INTERV     01-31 2450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMAN-POLANSKI-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMAN CANDLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Roman Polanski is available FREE OF
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent
ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when
you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By DANIEL PERES  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   He's trying not to talk with food in his mouth, but Roman
Polanski is brimming with ideas and can't quite contain himself.
After all, a little grilled Porcini salad should never get in the
way of a discussion about sex _ particularly for Polanski.
</P>
<P>
   But before he can get his words out, he's interrupted. He
doesn't seem to mind. She's blond, built and gorgeous. And, yes,
she's young.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing here?'' she says as her mother stands
beside her, clearly in awe of her daughter's famous acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is Rome. He manages to stand up, sandwiched between his
chair and the table. There's a moment of awkward silence before the
young lady's mother points out that Francesca has to get some sleep
because she's been up since dawn posing for a calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, it was nice seeing you again,'' Polanski says politely,
still clutching his napkin.
</P>
<P>
   After a sip of wine, he admits that he can't quite remember how
he knows Francesca.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know so many of these young girls,'' he says, seemingly
oblivious to the irony hanging in the air.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, at 66, Polanski has mastered the art of ignoring
the obvious. He's certainly no fool: He knows exactly what comes to
people's minds the instant his name is mentioned. That's why he
loathes interviews and occasionally interrogates journalists before
agreeing to a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My story has been told many times,'' he'll say. ``I'm tired of
talking about it. I think I'll pass.''
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that after nearly 30 years as Hollywood's
best-known pariah, he is anything but blase about his image. In
fact, he's still angry about it.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm autumn evening in Rome, Polanski settles down for
dinner, a bottle of Chianti and a surprisingly candid conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly he's here to promote an upcoming project, ``The Ninth
Gate,'' which stars Johnny Depp as a book broker in search of
manuscripts that unlock the mysteries of Satan. This is Polanski's
25th movie, but he believes he has yet to make his masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a film that makes me truly proud from the
beginning to the end,'' he says. Perhaps that's why the filmmaker
doesn't try too hard to sell his new project. Instead, the
discussion quickly turns to sex, a subject Polanski feels he knows
very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great sex enthusiast,'' he says. ``But not kinky sex.
Doing it with two girls, yes, that's fine. But not with a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously though, people don't realize how important a part
sex plays in human life,'' he goes on. ``Everybody thinks about it.
In fact, I think between the ages of 17 and 40 men just think about
sex more and more. Now, I actually think about it much less,
because I have a family. And plus, at my age, your glands function
differently. Shame.''
</P>
<P>
   He feels sorry for people unfortunate enough to have entered
their sexual prime within the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex used to be fun,'' he says. ``You could vent your
frustrations without taking risks. The period in which I went
through my manhood was the freest period sexually in the history of
human beings. It was between the pill and AIDS. Sure, there was
syphilis, but there was also Penicillin. Now, you have to screw
around parading in a condom.''
</P>
<P>
   Polanski is proud of his sexual education, which he received in
Hollywood during the 1970s _ alongside such pals as Jack Nicholson
and Warren Beatty. When the director first visited L.A. in 1963, he
was already a star. His low-budget Polish film, ``Knife in the
Water,'' the story of a married couple playing perverse games with
a hitchhiker, had already received an Oscar nomination; three years
later, he managed to persuade Catherine Deneuve to appear in
``Repulsion'' wearing only an ultra-sheer nightgown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roman was fast-moving and fast-talking,'' remembers his
longtime friend Anjelica Huston. ``He was arrogant in the way
Nureyev was. There was this Eastern Bloc flair. He wore silk shirts
from Turnbull and Asser unbuttoned to his stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposite sex was always attracted to him,'' says
``Chinatown'' producer Robert Evans. ``He was a magnet wherever he
went.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Polanski made ``The Fearless Vampire Killers'' _ his
first English-language film _ with Sharon Tate, whom he married the
same year in Los Angeles. The couple rented a house on Cielo Drive,
where, in 1969, not long after the release of ``Rosemary's Baby,''
four disciples of Charles Manson broke in and murdered Tate and her
unborn child, along with three houseguests.
</P>
<P>
   Polanski, who was away on business in London, returned to Los
Angeles the following day, to face allegations in the press that
his onscreen flirtations with the occult were to blame for his
wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is responsible for most of my trouble,'' he says.
``The occult bores me. I just think it's a good subject for a
movie. But the media perpetuates this. I've been sick of it for
years, but I guess you get used to living with your sickness.''
</P>
<P>
   He points to ``Tess,'' ``Chinatown'' and ``Death and the
Maiden'' as evidence that not all of his films are obsessed with
sex or the occult.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm a real weirdo,'' he says. ``They see me
through the prism of a few of my films and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. There was also that little incident in 1977,
involving a 13-year-old girl, Quaaludes and Nicholson's Jacuzzi on
Mulholland Drive. What began as a Vogue photo shoot ended with a
sexual encounter between Polanski and his young model.
</P>
<P>
   This is the one topic Polanski is definitely tired of discussing
_ and reading about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pisses me off, actually,'' he says. ``Enough. But what can
I do about it? It's hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Polanski tried to set the record straight in his 1984
autobiography, denying that he forced himself on the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no doubt about (her) experience and lack of
inhibition,'' he writes. ``She wasn't unresponsive.''
</P>
<P>
   After he was arrested and charged with six crimes, ranging from
rape to ``perversion,'' his lawyers arranged a plea bargain,
leaving him guilty of only the least serious charge, unlawful
sexual intercourse. He underwent a psychiatric evaluation while
serving 42 days in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his release, he expected to be sentenced with a fine or
probation, but when he heard that the judge had something else in
mind, he decided to skip town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unfortunate situation, and the judge was part of
it,'' he says now. ``He was holding press conferences and just
catering to the media. That's why I left. I went to prison and that
was supposed to be it. All parties had agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 he made a settlement with the girl and the civil suit
was dropped. While he feels he has paid his debt, Polanski is still
considered a fugitive by authorities in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Today, despite everything, Polanski has no problem admitting he
still likes younger women. He has been married to actress
Emmanuelle Seigner, who is 32 years his junior, for 10 years. They
live on Paris' avenue Montaigne with their two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked younger women,'' he says. ``I think it has
something to do with an image I had of a woman when I was young.
Maybe my mother? Maybe the first love of my life? But why should I
try to figure that out? That's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Polanski's honesty about his sexuality would undoubtedly seem
out of place in America today. He doesn't understand all of the
fuss over Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most men in important positions in America have these types of
affairs,'' he says. ``It's so chaste. What, they never had a
blowjob? Come on. Who cares?''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Polanski gets distracted. He is fixated on the
guitarist working his way around the restaurant's outdoor patio.
When the man _ collecting lire in an old hat _ finally arrives in
front of the director, he is quickly shooed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always give money to beggars and singers, but he gets on my
nerves, this guy,'' Polanski says. ``He produces sounds that are
unpleasant and insists on being rewarded for it. How arrogant!''
</P>
<P>
   He turns in his chair to see how much money the man is taking
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was a child, I could never ignore people like that,''
he says. ``I think I identify with them _ any beggar, really. I
remember walking with my mother when I was a little boy and there
was a beggar with a beard always sitting in the same place. Once,
he vomited all over and I remember how moved I was. It didn't occur
to me that he was drunk; I just felt so sorry for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory is one of only a handful of images Polanski has of
his mother, Bula. He grew up in a barbed-wired ghetto in wartime
Cracow.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, when he was 8, she was taken to Auschwitz, never to
return. He spent the next several years slipping through chain-link
fences in search of food for his family before he escaped on his
own, finally settling in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Holocaust has more influence on my life now than I
thought it would,'' he says. ``I think the character of a man is
made when he is a very young child. The whole mind is formed
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his traumatic childhood, Polanski never wanted to
have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea terrified me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust is still so real to him, in fact, that when Steven
Speilberg approached him to direct ``Schindler's List,'' he
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I could do a good movie there,'' Polanski says.
``I was too close. It was very difficult to watch. The places and
even the people looked the way I remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Polanski, who has been observing Hollywood as an outsider for
the last 30 years, has grown deeply critical of the American
moviemaking machine. He's particularly offended by the huge
salaries actors are commanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly can't imagine how a person with this type of salary
can keep his sanity and sense of proportion,'' he says. ``Some have
the brains to realize it is just money, but others _ most _ start
to think they're special in all other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Polanski offers a case in point: John Travolta. The two were
supposed to work together three years ago on a film called ``The
Double.'' Travolta was reportedly unhappy with the script and
demanded changes, ultimately requesting that Polanski be taken off
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started reading, and right away he got offended by my
directing him,'' he says. ``There is an enormous ego there. He's
probably never been directed before. Most actors enjoy it. I've
worked with bigger stars than him: Harrison Ford, Jack Nicholson,
John Huston.'' (Travolta declined to comment for this story.)
</P>
<P>
   Polanski doesn't consider himself difficult to work with, as
long as those around him are professional. That hasn't always been
the case. On ``Rosemary's Baby,'' he recalls another big battle _
not with his star, Mia Farrow, but with her husband, Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was too macho,'' Polanski says. ``I think he harmed her
career a lot in that period.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrow was supposed to act alongside Sinatra in ``The
Detective,'' which was going into production while she was still at
work on ``Rosemary's Baby.'' According to Polanski, Sinatra ordered
her to begin working on his own film, but she refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he sent a lawyer over with divorce papers,'' Polanski says.
``That's an assh---'s behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   He's surprised that Farrow hasn't worked more in the time since
their collaboration. He's not shocked, however, at the level of
fame achieved by his old friend Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Polanski suddenly bursts out laughing. ``I taught Jack how to
ski,'' he says. ``This was many years ago in Gstaad. The first time
I took him up the mountain, he thought I was trying to kill him. He
just kept falling, but he was indestructible. And then one day I
lost him on the mountain and he came back to the chalet at 10
o'clock in the evening, completely ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could see more of him,'' Polanski adds with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Huston, because of her long relationship with Nicholson, has
observed the two men together many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roman is one of the few people who really makes Jack think,''
she says. ``Spiritually, they are in sync with each other. They
share a common genius and also a deep sorrow _ several deep
sorrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Polanski misses just a few things about L.A. ``Like Nat &AMP; Al's
Deli,'' he says. ``They have great pastrami. Los Angeles is ugly as
hell, but there is one beautiful view, at night, from the hills. I
miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Polanski ever tempted to fly back to LAX and see what happens
when he walks through Immigration?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were not condemned to the media exposure, I would
probably go back to get it over with, at least for peace of mind,''
he says. ``But I don't think I could really cope with what it
entails. It would be a circus all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   With the plates cleared away and most of the other diners long
gone, Polanski decides that perhaps he's said enough. He is anxious
to get some sleep, and he wants to call his wife in Paris before it
gets too late. But when he's asked about his regrets in life, he
can't refuse a few parting words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've always regretted that I was not in the house on
Cielo Drive the night Sharon Tate was murdered,'' he says. ``I've
always thought a teeny bit that maybe I could have prevented it.''
</P>
<P>
   After it's pointed out that he would most likely have been
killed as well, Polanski empties his glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he says. ``But at least I wouldn't have the feeling
that I still have. I wouldn't still be wondering.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Daniel Peres is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
