<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-MEDIATOR-BOS     01-31 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-MEDIATOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW'S HANDPICKED CHECHEN LEADER TREADS A FINE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Malik Saidullayev's plush office in central Moscow is a
world away from the bombed-out wasteland that his native Chechnya
has become.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of his family and paintings of horses adorn the
walls, along with Russian and Chechen flags. Dressed in a dark blue
suit, Saidullayev, 35, settled onto a soft leather sofa last week
as he sipped a cup of tea and explained why he was about to leave
his luxurious surroundings for his war-torn homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow-based millionaire businessman turned self-styled
peacemaker is the latest in a long line of Chechens the Kremlin has
turned to in its attempts to rein in the separatist region. It does
not deter him that he has no clout with the rebels, and that even
his sponsors in Moscow have their doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Saidullayev, who had never expressed public interest in his
homeland until the Russians called on him, flew to the capital,
Grozny, to try to jump-start peace talks _ talks that the rebels
scorn and that the Kremlin has not officially sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Known in Moscow as a ``pro-Russia Chechen,'' Saidullayev has
amassed a small empire that includes a popular lottery business,
restaurants, and car dealerships. In October, the Kremlin plucked
him out of obscurity to head its handpicked government-in-exile for
the breakaway republic. Since then, he has been trying to start
peace talks between Moscow and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Chechnya's independence or non-independence is not the
main issue. I have one goal, and that is to end the war,''
Saidullayev said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are tired of war and brutality, and most of the
rebel commanders are tired of fighting,'' he added. ``Chechnya is a
small nation. We can't continue fighting forever. The republic
needs to develop so people can live normally.''
</P>
<P>
   Saidullayev has toured Chechnya and has promised to provide
money to repair destroyed schools and hospitals. He has also
delivered food and supplies to the swelling ranks of refugees
fleeing the four-month-old war.
</P>
<P>
   As a pro-Russia Chechen, Saidullayev has had to walk a fine line
to wield any influence in the separatist republic, as
independence-minded Chechens viewed him with suspicion. And in his
efforts to win the Chechens over, he managed to alienate the
Russians when he publicly accused Russian troops of atrocities
against civilians and of corruption in their administration of
refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Saidullayev announced that he was holding peace
talks in Moscow with a group of rebel commanders who had traveled
there. The Kremlin acknowledged that they had arrived, but little
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nobody among the rebel commanders who can negotiate
with the federal government,'' the Kremlin's official spokesman on
Chechya, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, told reporters last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen leaders have been equally dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not support it at all,'' said Ilyas Akhmadov, who acts
as Chechnya's foreign minister, during a visit to Boston. ``One
needs to know, in a Chechen environment, just who Malik Saidullayev
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Akhmadov said he suspected that the Kremlin had blackmailed
Saidullayev, telling him to ``either close your business or head
the Chechen government-in-exile.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharip Yusupov, a Moscow-based spokesman for the Chechen rebels,
called Saidullayev ``the hand of Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Saidullayev brushed off such accusations, saying his only agenda
is to help Chechnya's civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pro-Russian,'' he said. ``I don't reject this label. But
I am only pro-Russian to the extent that I think it can help my
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts in Moscow say the Kremlin had hoped to use
Saidullayev for their own purposes, but he has proved to be too
uncontrollable. In December, he angered officials in Moscow when he
helped expose a massacre of at least 41 civilians in his hometown,
Alkhan-Yurt, a village about 10 miles from Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Since, the Kremlin has seemed to distance itself from
Saidullayev, and has turned its attention to another pro-Moscow
Chechen, Bislan Gantamirov, a former mayor of Grozny who was loyal
to Russia in the 1994-96 war.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov, who had been serving a prison sentence for
embezzlement, was pardoned last month by then-president Boris
Yeltsin and has begun forming pro-Russian militias in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saidullayev is clearly trying to play both sides,'' said Tom
de Waal, a London-based specialist on the region who co-authored a
book on the 1994-96 war. ``In exposing the Alkhan-Yurt massacre he
was trying to set himself up as a credible force inside Chechnya.
Whether or not this is realistic is another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest the Kremlin may be using Saidullayev to feel out
the rebels' desire to negotiate an end to the war, while publicly
distancing themselves from his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Iskandarian, a Moscow-based specialist on the Caucasus
region, said the military situation in Chechnya is ``very bad for
Russia,'' and acting President Vladimir V. Putin ``needs to find a
way out'' of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can lie on television as much as they please, saying they
took this or that territory and show Russian flags being raised on
buildings, but sooner or later there needs to be some results,''
Iskandarian said. ``At the same time, Putin cannot appear to be
backing down or negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saidullayev, he noted, has virtually no power base in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has long struggled to find a Chechen leader who would be
accepted by the republic's population but still be loyal to the
Kremlin. During the 1994-96 war, authorities in Moscow supported a
series of anti-independence Chechens before they finally settled on
Doku Zavgayev, the republic's Soviet-era ruler. Zavgayev, however,
wielded no real power and was ridiculed for rarely leaving Grozny's
heavily fortified airport. He fled Chechnya after Russian troops
withdrew in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The government that Saidullayev nominally heads is centered in
the so-called Chechen State Council, a pro-Moscow parliament
elected in June 1996. At the time, Russian forces controlled about
half the republic, including Grozny, and the vote was held in the
occupied territory only.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zavgayev's administration and the legislature were
disbanded when Russian troops withdrew in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The breakaway region held its own presidential elections in
January 1997, which were monitored by international observers.
Aslan Maskhadov won the vote in a landslide. In May of that year,
Yeltsin signed a peace treaty with Maskhadov, saying the deal
``puts a stop to 400 years'' of conflict between Moscow and
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But since Russian troops entered the republic in September, the
Kremlin has refused to negotiate with Maskhadov, saying he is
illegitimate and does not control the situation in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin revived the State Council in October, calling it the
``only legitimate authority'' in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Saidullayev is about to find out whether he meant it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CALIF-INDEPENDENTS-HN     01-31 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-INDEPENDENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO LONGER A BOONDOCKS, CALIFORNIA'S `INLAND EMPIRE' IS A HAVEN
FOR MODERATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERSIDE, Calif. _ The political and economic fissure that runs
through California begins just south of here, where the Toyota
Camrys and Hyundais slip through the Marsscape rocks on Highway 91,
and into the shiny office parks in Orange County for a day's work
and back again.
</P>
<P>
   The 300,000 workers who make this daily commute return with a
paycheck and a traffic migraine. Riverside and San Bernardino
counties are the ubiquitous rent-to-own bedroom communities to the
richer stucco-and-tile cities on the coast, where the jobs pay
better and the politics are less textured.
</P>
<P>
   For politicians aiming at a statewide election victory, the easy
lure are the 20 western counties of California _ wealthier, easier
to define. But the second California _ the 38 eastern counties that
can make or break the 2000 presidential race _ is harder to
encapsulate.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside is at the heart of this new landscape for inland
California.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a low-wage, blue-collar microstate, a backstage engine
supplying products and manufacturing support for the high-profile
dot-coms and techies in coastal cities. In Riverside and San
Bernardino counties, sprawling warehouse businesses are filling
with workers who have grown increasingly tired of the two- to
three-hour commutes to Los Angeles and Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside and San Bernardino counties _ dubbed the Inland Empire
_ recently have become the new voter-mining operation for
politicians who really know California. Mostly conservative voters
here are crucial to candidates because they are so independent.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, showed he understood the state's
changing political landscape in his successful 1998 gubernatorial
bid, a lesson he hopes to hand to Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic presidential favorite. But analysts say few presidential
candidates have begun to recognize the importance of Californian's
growing inland area.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco and Los Angeles _ liberal and overwhelmingly
Democratic _ are predictable. Riverside, one of the fastest growing
counties in the country, is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always voted Democratic, every single time,'' said John
Hall Jr., 49, who moved to Moreno Valley in 1993 from Santa Monica,
about the time housing prices started pushing more people inland.
``But I think it's time for a change. I've even discussed it with
my parents, and my father thinks I should vote Democratic because
the unions brought us through the Depression. But then again, he
was born in 1920.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall sat outside the Mission Inn, Riverside's famed
Spanish-baroque hotel and central meeting place, where Ronald and
Nancy Reagan spent their honeymoon. A financial adviser, Hall said
he wanted to support a party that would further change the
country's welfare system, which he finds too liberal, too
permissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really kind of tired of the two parties,'' he said. ``I'm
really looking for someone to shake it up. I respect Al Gore a lot
for distancing himself from (President) Clinton. That impressed me.
But I have been thinking about registering Republican. I have
seriously been considering (George W.) Bush. I've been looking at
him.'
</P>
<P>
   Riverside County elected state Sen. Ray Haynes, a conservative
who once declared, ``I don't want a homosexual representing me in
Congress.'' The former Republican Assembly leader, Rod Pacheco,
also is from Riverside. The county went for Democrat Bill Clinton
for president in 1992 and Bob Dole, the Republican, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Brown, a Democrat, won a record 18th term in 1996 _
and the seat stayed Democratic in November when state Sen. Joe Baca
was elected to fill the rest of the term for Brown, who died last.
And the county voted for Davis over conservative Republican Dan
Lungren in the 1998 gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party loyalty just isn't what it used to be,'' said David
Lara-Telles, chairman of the Riverside County Democratic Party and
a resident of Moreno Valley, one of the fastest-growing areas in
the Inland Empire. ``People here are much more willing to jump
between Democrat and Republican, even on the same ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riverside's development the past two decades is a familiar
story. Families looking for cheaper housing fled Los Angeles and
Orange County in the 1980s. When the recession hit in the early
1990s, the cash-poor families found their homes worth less than
they paid, and their commute sometimes stretching two or three
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these former commuters are beginning to stay home, making
tires and tortilla chips, furniture and fixtures. The Inland Empire
is the only place in the state that added jobs every year in the
1990s, even during the tough recession early in the decade. Since
1990, Riverside has gained 200,000 jobs, compared with 165,000 in
Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians still think this is an area with 300,000 to
400,000 people in the boondocks with cows,'' said John Husing, a
principal with Economics &AMP; Politics Inc., a consulting firm.
``There are in fact 3.1 million people and $60 billion in personal
income in the area. Eighteen states are smaller than we are. ...
Politically, what you see is a fundamental misunderstanding in
leadership circles about the growth paradigm in this state. Simply,
they haven't gotten a clue about what's going on in places like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   A decidedly middle-class Riverside County has a household income
of about $40,200 a year compared with $53,600 in Orange County,
based on joint tax returns compiled by the state Department of
Finance. Riverside ranks 28th of 58 counties in income. Orange
County ranks seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Once dominated by Roosevelt Democrats, Riverside County has
become one of the top five Republican strongholds in the state
based on party registration _ with 47 percent registered in the GOP
and 37 percent Democratic. The 1999 Empire Annual Survey found that
31 percent of voters considered themselves ``middle of the road,''
with 17 percent ``somewhat liberal'' and 22 percent ``somewhat
conservative.'' The survey is produced by Max Neiman, a professor
at the University of California at Riverside who specializes in
Inland Empire demographics, and his associates.
</P>
<P>
   The Inland Empire residents tend in general to vote for
``Republicrats,' moderate politicians who can merge the two
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a Republican than I am a Democrat,'' said
Riverside County Supervisor Tom Mullen, a registered Democrat,
echoing a fairly consistent theme. ``I've wanted to switch several
times, and then someone on the right will open their mouth, and I
don't. But at the same time, I'm not a socialist. I'm as conflicted
as the voters are.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman's survey found these same contradictions. Although party
registration in Riverside County is mostly Republican, voters were
less likely to identify with the Republican Party when surveyed.
When asked to ``best describe`` their party affiliation, 40 percent
said Democratic, and only 37 percent said Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Voters here are also far more interested in quality-of-life
issues _ like traffic and schools _ than they are about the
emotional, divisive issues such as abortion and the death penalty,
for example. Few presidential candidates have caught on to this
theme _ most can't break free of the old talking points.
</P>
<P>
   No political team knows the Inland Empire's shifting nature
better than Davis and his senior adviser, Garry South. More than
two years ago, when Davis was being written out of the political
calculus in California, South was pulling reporters aside over
coffee, trying to convince them Davis could win. He divided the
state straight down the middle, and the numbers didn't lie _
moderate voters in Riverside and the inland areas loved
straight-down-the-middle Davis in election after election.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after Davis' landslide victory in the 1998 election, South
is sharing his knowledge with Gore as he tries to capture the
state. Davis tailored his message for different parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the inland areas are so conservative, my view is you
have to approach them much differently,'' South said. ``You have to
establish your bona fides in inland California as someone who is
fiscally responsible, who is good on public safety issues, who is
not some left-wing coastal nut, before they will listen to anything
else you have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have the benefit of the doubt in the inland areas,
South said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drag on Gore is going to be his record on the
environment,'' South said, ``particularly his book. We worked with
them pretty intensively on what our playbook was, and how to
replicate it. ... I think you'll see their inland campaign is the
same as ours was, because frankly the factors are the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
