<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK LOOKS TO JOIN OTHER STATES IN LIMITING TELEMARKETERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y., _ Should privacy come at a price for consumers who
don't want to be bothered by telemarketers? That's a question
officials are expected to debate as New York looks to join a
growing number of states with ``do not call'' registries _ special
lists to protect people from unwanted phone sales pitches
throughout their days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, seven states have such lists. Most companies
that do telemarketing in those states _ regardless of where their
headquarters are _ must obtain the no-call lists and avoid
contacting people on them. Groups like charities or political
opinion pollsters are usually exempted.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties can be stiff, ranging from $2,000 in Georgia to
$25,000 in Oregon for each call.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot Spitzer wants such a system in New York,
too. So does Assemblyman Jeffrey Klein, D-Bronx. Their ideas have
one fundamental difference: Spitzer suggests the service should be
free for consumers; Klein's bill proposes a $5 annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's plan follows the lead of most states. Shelly Andrews,
Klein's counsel, said the fee is matter of political practicality:
``It's easier to pass through the state legislature if it's not
going to cost the state anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Georgia, on whose system the bill was based,
reported few complaints about the charge, she noted. Georgia
residents pay $10 to register and $5 a year to renew.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bennett, vice president of Computer Business Services, a
Georgia company that compiles no-call lists for several states,
said people seem to consider the fees a bargain to avoid ``the
dinnertime nuisance.'' Some were so eager they paid 10 years in
advance. And most of the roughly 20 other states studying the idea
are considering consumer fees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hottest piece of legislation in the country today,''
said Bennett. ``More citizens are demanding some kind of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The fees haven't stopped 3,000 people from signing up for
Alabama's program even before it begins July 1, said Thomas
Whatley, chief of staff and general counsel of the state's Public
Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees. Tennessee and Kentucky don't have a
consumer fee; instead, they charge telemarketers much higher fees
than other states _ $400 to $500 a year compared with $10 to $120
in other areas. Spitzer's proposal would allow the Public Service
Commission to charge companies, but not consumers on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Givens, director of the nonprofit Privacy Rights
Clearinghouse, said it is not fair for government to make people
pay extra to protect their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't have to pay for that,'' she said. ``You're the
one who's being annoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Without such a list in place, the only significant legal
protection consumers have now is a federal law requiring
telemarketers to maintain their own do-not-call lists. But
individuals must ask every firm that calls and keep track. And,
Bennett noted, there are more than 30,000 telemarketing firms
making 18 million calls a day.
</P>
<P>
   A less official option is to register with the Direct Marketing
Association, a trade group. Under the association's rules, members
must respect its do-not-call list, which totals about 3 million
names and is free to join, according to spokesman Stephen
Altobelli.
</P>
<P>
   DMA's membership, however, is small compared with the industry _
about 4,600 members, which include not only telemarketers but
catalog, Internet and direct mail companies, Altobelli said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
