<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHOSTAKOVICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOSTAKOVICH'S WORK TRANSCENDED THE BOUNDARIES OF IDEOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SHOSTAKOVICH 
A Life 
By Laurel E. Fay. Oxford University Press. 458 pp. Illustrated.
$35. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dmitriy Shostakovich was a quiet and private man, but his
musical genius made him an international celebrity in a troubled
time. Bruno Walter introduced the First Symphony of the 22-year-old
composer to Berlin in 1928, and the piece went around the world _
Shostakovich was the last composer whose symphonies, some of them
anyway, immediately entered the standard repertory. He became the
most famous artist of the Soviet era because his work could travel
without translation.
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich became an emblem both inside the Soviet Union and
outside, but he never could exercise much control over what the
emblem meant to others, or how changing power structures would
manipulate it. At points in his career he was laden with official
duties and honors _ he won the Stalin Prize five times. At other
times he was dismissed from his teaching posts, denounced in public
debate as a ``formalist'' who had lost touch with the aspirations
of the people. After the sexual frankness of his opera ``Lady
Macbeth of the Mtsensk District'' offended Stalin himself in 1936,
Shostakovich had good reason to fear for his life. Yet within a few
years, in America, Shostakovich would appear in his fireman's
helmet on the cover of Time magazine after he had finished his
once-famous symphony about the siege of Leningrad.
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich's work was excessively praised for reasons having
nothing to do with music, excessively reviled for the very same
reasons. Shostakovich lived in a difficult place during complicated
times; he had to chart a careful course. He was capable of
subversive daring throughout his long career; he set songs from
Jewish folk poetry at a time when it was dangerous for him to do
so, and built a symphony around Yevgeny Yevtushenko's poem
``Babi-Yar,'' which contains a powerful denunciation of
anti-Semitism. But he also turned out works that toed the party
line, and because he was an artist, some of his ``politically
correct'' pieces couldn't help being musically distinguished. And
then the wheels of history turned, and those works have been
treated just as dismissively as the subversive ones were before.
</P>
<P>
   The controversies swirling around Shostakovich during his
lifetime did not abate after his death. No one seems to know how
committed a communist he was; he was certainly not reluctant to
receive honors and perks. He officially joined the Communist Party
only in 1960, by which time he presumably didn't have to; one story
goes that he did so under the influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testimony,'' his posthumously published memoir (as told to
Solomon Volkov, and published first in English in 1979), presented
an alternate portrait of the composer; it was cut to the fashion of
a different political climate. The book has never been
satisfactorily authenticated, though a stout volume has now been
devoted to defending it. ``Testimony'' presented Shostakovich as an
inner emigre, the composer of music that did not mean what people
thought and said it did at the time, or even what Shostakovich
himself may have said it meant. The finale of the Fifth Symphony
changed from a picture of jubilation and triumph into an ironic
depiction of jubilation forced under the lash. It is a paradox that
the music of Shostakovich speaks quite directly to us, but it isn't
always easy to make out what it is saying.
</P>
<P>
   Until the appearance of Laurel E. Fay's careful new biography,
it has been almost impossible to get at a reliable set of facts
about Shostakovich _ even an accurate chronology of his works with
correct dates for important premieres and performances has proved
elusive. With laudable persistence Fay has spent years checking and
cross-checking every known ``fact'' about Shostakovich, and
correcting countless errors that have persisted even in the most
careful reference books and scholarly studies. Her text runs to 287
pages; her notes, work-list, glossary of names, and select
bibliography take up another 133.
</P>
<P>
   She tells Shostakovich's life straightforwardly, making very few
attempts to heighten the drama of any incident. Many commentators,
for example, assert that the Pravda editorial denouncing ``Lady
Macbeth of the Mtsensk District'' was written by Stalin himself, as
if this were an established fact; Fay doesn't even mention this
possibility as a rumor. Her purposefully plain, dry style admits no
coloring, which in the case of this particular subject is an
important advantage. She pursues no agenda, political or otherwise,
except to make Shostakovich's artistic accomplishments her first
priority. She is interested only in what he did and in where and
when he did it, and in anything else that can be definitely
established about his life.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of significant details here that are
otherwise hard to come by. Shostakovich was a skillful pianist, for
example, and wrote some great music for his own instrument. Fay
sheds light on Shostakovich's career as a performer (he was a
Soviet candidate in the 1927 Chopin Competition in Warsaw, along
with Grigoriy Ginzburg, Lev Oborin, and others). It doesn't come as
a surprise to learn that Shostakovich once had to play the
Tchaikovsky Concerto on ``a vile tinkling upright'' with a
provincial orchestra in an outdoor arena, but it is interesting to
learn what parts of the standard repertory he was drawn to in his
own concerts _ at 15, he played Beethoven's ``Hammerklavier''
Sonata at the Leningrad Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   If Fay couldn't find out all she wanted to about a matter, she
simply admits her failure. Only two paragraphs, for example, treat
Shostakovich's second marriage, which lasted from 1956-1959.
``Little is known about (Margarita) Kainova. Although Shostakovich
tried to introduce her into his circle of friends and family, no
one seems to have understood or approved of the match. . . .
Margarita was never able to win the support of the children or the
domestic staff. After three years of marriage, in the summer of
1959, Shostakovich terminated the relationship _ designating his
son as intermediary to effect the break _ and divorced her,
settling her into an apartment with a monthly stipend.'' After that
Kainova disappears from the chronicle, though Fay includes an
interesting photograph of her with Shostakovich in Paris in 1958 _
it is one of the two images in the entire collection in which
Shostakovich appears relaxed and at ease (in the other, he is
attending a soccer game, a favorite pastime).
</P>
<P>
   Fay's sources were period newspapers, concert programs and
reviews, personnel files, transcripts, letters and diaries, and she
approached memoirs by others with scrupulous caution. The
autobiography of the great soprano Galina Vishnevskaya does not
record that she ``flubbed up badly'' twice during the Moscow
premiere of the Fourteenth Symphony, and that Shostakovich much
preferred her alternate; Fay has established this.
</P>
<P>
   Some pertinent and touching details do come from memoirs. The
composer Galina Ustvolskaya, for example, attended the premiere of
one of Shostakovich's party-line pieces in 1949, ``The Song of the
Forests.'' She recalls that after the performance ``Shostakovich
returned to his room in the Hotel Europe and began to sob, burying
his head in a pillow. He sought consolation in vodka.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the most enthralling passages come from the vast
correspondence of Shostakovich, which has become available only in
piecemeal fashion. Here, for example, is a letter to the young
composer Edison Denisov, who had written to complain about the
injustices he had faced and how slowly his career was advancing.
``A few words about your grievances. I advise you to envy Mozart,
Beethoven, Tchaikovsky. To envy Koval, Muravlyov, and so on, really
and truly isn't worth it, no matter how successful these failures
sometimes may be. . . . P.S. I repeat: envy of Mozart will lead you
forward. Envy of talentless losers will take you backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay is becomingly modest about her accomplishment in this
volume. ``Shostakovich scholarship is in its infancy. Most of the
composer's personal legacy remains in private hands. His own
archival repository contains but a small fraction of the evidence
that will eventually contribute to a fully nuanced assessment of
the man and his career.'' The rest of us can nevertheless be
grateful for her humble and Herculean efforts, thanks to which
Shostakovich can no longer be discussed in terms of black or white;
her work has begun to make it possible to focus on the lasting
inner life of the music and to think of the music's creator in
fuller human terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
