<HEADLINE>
BERLIN OFFICIALS, US AMBASSADOR SQUABBLE OVER EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The US embassy on Pariser Platz was deserted in 1941,
bombed by the Allies during World War II, and torn down by the
Communists in 1957 to make way for what would become the Berlin
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   The wall has since been torn down, too. But getting the embassy
back up in what many regard as its rightful place has proved more
difficult because of a dispute between the State Department and
Berlin officials that sheds light on strains between the US and
Germany a decade after the Cold War ended.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say the new embassy needs a minimum of a 100-foot
security perimeter to guard against terrorist attack. Berlin
officials say that would force the closing of two streets and cause
traffic chaos around the nearby Brandenburg Gate, the actual and
symbolic heart of the city that has just resumed its role as the
capital of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the $150 million embassy was supposed to start
last year, but unless the dispute is resolved soon, a new site will
have to be found and relations between Washington and Berlin could
sour considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are clinging stubbornly to symbolism. The Americans
want to return to the spot they had to clear out of in 1941, after
Adolf Hitler had declared war on the United States. The Germans
have invested mightily in rebuilding the area around Brandenburg
Gate, which they hold as a symbol of a reunified Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Some attribute the inability to resolve the dispute to
personality conflicts, particularly between US Ambassador John
Kornblum and Berlin Mayor Eberhard Diepgen. Others, however, see
the dispute as evidence of a Germany more confident of its place in
the world and less willing to accept the demands of the United
States. After 55 years of American influence, a more assertive
Germany wants to wean itself from its old benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   If not a cold war, the dispute is certainly a big chill. The
spat has been, at times, public and tawdry, with each side accusing
the other of name-calling and arm-twisting.
</P>
<P>
   In October, at the opening of the 1,000th McDonald's franchise
in Germany, Diepgen sarcastically suggested that Kornblum build a
McDonald's on the Pariser Platz instead of an embassy. Kornblum was
furious.
</P>
<P>
   But Germans have accused Kornblum, who has worked as a diplomat
in Germany for much of the last 30 years, of acting less than
diplomatic by belittling Germany and dressing down journalists who
have suggested the Americans are acting like the occupying force
they were a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The German press has fanned the flames. Der Spiegel, an
influential German magazine, accused Kornblum of ``putting a strain
on German-American relations because of his stubborn and rude
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Bolling, a commentator and former spokesman for the former
chancellor Helmut Schmidt, wrote a column titled ``The times have
changed, Mr. Ambassador,'' about how Germans would not be dictated
to and accused Kornblum of arrogance. Bolling said Kornblum
reprimanded him when they bumped into each other at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the opening in November of a new center here to
foster American-German cultural and academic exchanges, Kornblum
said Germany had progressed but that ``it will be a probably fairly
long process before Germany finds the right tone and the right
feeling for exerting what is after all a very strong role in
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   His critics called the remarks patronizing. Even some who are
critical of Diepgen suggest that Kornblum, who was appointed
ambassador in 1998, is a product of the old school, in which
German-American relations were framed in the narrow margins of the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has proved embarrassing to both governments and to
those who regard the American-German relationship as one of the
most important and mutually beneficial in the world.
</P>
<P>
   As Catherine Kelleher, director of the Aspen Institute, a
Berlin-based think tank, put it, ``It's gotten out of hand. We need
some statesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   The German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, has offered to mediate
the dispute, but as of Friday negotiations were continuing between
city officials and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   US diplomats, meanwhile, continue to work out of the nearby
former US Embassy to East Germany and other offices in western
Berlin. The old embassy is an eyesore, surrounded by barbed wire
and German antiterrorist police, the street blocked off.
</P>
<P>
   Security was always going to be a problem at the new site. But
it became a bigger problem after August 1998, when terrorist
attacks on US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania left some 200 people
dead and led to a review of security at US embassies worldwide. A
panel headed by former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman Admiral
William Crowe concluded that $14 billion should be spent on
improving security at embassies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe, the former US ambassador in London, was so disturbed by
what he saw as the vulnerability of the US Embassy planned for
Pariser Platz that he asked Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to consider a new site. Sources familiar with those discussions
said that Kornblum made an impassioned plea about the symbolic
importance of the site. Albright relented but insisted that the
traffic had to be pushed back 100 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin officials, however, said that would ruin the traffic flow
around Brandenburg Gate. The Reichstag, which reopened last year as
home to the Bundestag, Germany's parliament, is nearby, as are the
offices of many German government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The British and French embassies are already under construction
at their former sites near Brandenburg Gate, and the Russian
Embassy is still down the street, reinforcing the American
government's determination.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Dennis Wolf, a US Embassy spokesman, said the
100-foot buffer zone was a worldwide directive but suggested that
compromises are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Ambassador Kornblum said, we are on the right path. There
seems to be forward movement, although there are a number of
outstanding issues. We still need to have negotiations on the
details of an agreement before a decision can be reached,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Berliners seem torn. Edith Kasch, 67, a retired
secretary, remembers eating food dropped by American planes during
the Berlin Airlift, when the Soviets tried unsuccessfully to
blockade West Berlin. She is not troubled by more than 50,000
American soldiers remaining on Germany soil. She believes Germany
still owes a debt to the United States. ``A disgrace,'' she calls
the ongoing dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Hermann Vogel, a 30-year-old librarian from eastern Berlin,
holds a different view. He said the American rebuilding of Germany
and use of it as a front line in the Cold War was more about
America's interest than Germany's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans need to treat Germany with more respect, as an
equal, not as a colony,'' he said. ``Times have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   James Cooney, executive director the Weatherhead Center for
International Affairs at Harvard University, pointed to Germany's
role as a leader in the European Union and its armed forces
returning to combat in Kosovo for the first time since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the generation over 40 is tired of the occupying powers.
They appreciate what was done, but they want to move on,'' said
Cooney.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Krause, deputy director of the German Society for
Foreign Affairs, a Berlin-based think tank, said the room for
compromise is limited, because Pariser Platz is relatively small
and is next to the city's Holocaust memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they'll have to have two embassies,'' he said. ``There
has to be a pragmatic solution. Too much is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the dispute is resolved soon, it will take at least
three years to build the new embassy, and probably longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real tragedy,'' says Kelleher. ``In the new Berlin,
there will be no new US Embassy for years. . . . This has got to
get worked out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
