<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ELIAN-SMUGGLE-BOS &LR;      01-31 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-SMUGGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN SMUGGLERS PROFIT FROM 1994 CHANGES IN US POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When he set out from Cuba, little Elian Gonzalez was one
of 14 people crammed into a 17-foot aluminum skiff. The ``life
preserver'' that saved him was one of three overinflated truck
inner tubes that had been crudely lashed to the boat in an
unsuccessful plan to keep it afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Elian drifted some 30 miles before he was discovered off Fort
Lauderdale, wearing only a gray sweatshirt and his underwear. He
was suffering from shock and hypothermia, and a rash covered his
body. Two other survivors came ashore in Miami. They told
investigators that they had paid $2,000 each to make the perilous
journey to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the political furor and the family histrionics now
enveloping Elian, the 6-year-old boy's odyssey is primarily a
smuggler's tale, one of thousands that have played out across the
Florida Straits since a 1994 agreement fundamentally changed how
many Cubans come to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that some of these people were paying money to be
taken to the United States,'' said Steve Quinones, special agent in
charge of the US Border Patrol's antismuggling unit, which
investigated the case. ``There are clear indicators that there was
some level of organization here.''
</P>
<P>
   The accounts of how the journey was organized cut through some
of the mythology that has surrounded the case, particularly with
regard to Lazaro Munero, the 24-year-old boyfriend of Elian's
mother, Elizabet Brotons. Cuban-American exiles fighting to keep
the boy in Miami have portrayed Munero as a loving, heartsick
stepfather who returned to Cuba to retrieve Elizabet and Elian and
ferry them to a better life.
</P>
<P>
   Although that may be true, investigators have concluded that
Munero organized the trip as a profit-making venture, turning his
modest boat with a 50-horsepower motor into paid transport for
people desperate to reach the United States. The boat was so
unsteady that when it ran into mechanical trouble shortly after
leaving Cuba and was forced to return to shore, Arianne Horta, one
of the three passengers to survive the crossing, nervously dropped
off her 5-year-old daughter and resumed the trip on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That boat was probably doomed before it ever left Cuba,'' said
Lieutenant Ronald A. LaBrec, a spokesman for the Coast Guard in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the human toll _ seven bodies have been found and four
others, including those of Munero and Brotons, are still missing _
authorities were hardly surprised by what they called the
carelessness and callousness with which the trip was organized.
Since a 1994 shift in US policy in favor of Cuban migrants, South
Florida has seen an explosion of unscrupulous entrepreneurs who are
willing to smuggle Cubans to the United States for as much as
$10,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in smuggling has to do with the nature of the
agreement, which stipulates that Cubans intercepted at sea, with
few exceptions, must be returned to Cuba. Before, nearly all Cuban
migrants were eligible for asylum under the Cuban Adjustment Act of
1966, a law that seemed to encourage periodic spasms of mass
migration.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent ``rafter crisis,'' the Coast Guard picked up
37,139 Cuban migrants in 1994. Knowing that they merely needed to
reach US authorities, the migrants ``would use anything they could
find,'' said Jose Basulto, who heads a group of volunteer pilots
known as ``Brothers to the Rescue.'' Basulto recalled seeing people
floating on styrofoam containers, inner tubes, even a ``raft''
whose hull was carved from the top of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coast Guard now is acting as Cuba's border patrol'' to
prevent people from leaving, said Basulto.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the year after the agreement, the Coast Guard
intercepted just 625 Cuban migrants, most of whom were returned to
Cuba. The figures have remained relatively low, but immigration
authorities recently have become alarmed by some of the unforeseen
effects of a ``wet foot, dry foot'' policy that seems to reward
Cubans with residency if they can somehow manage to reach US soil.
</P>
<P>
   The policy creates a market for the smugglers, who often use
high-powered cigarette boats, infrared night goggles, and
sophisticated global positioning systems that allow them to assess
their longitude and latitude at any time. It also seems to ratchet
up the desperation of migrants once land is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency they have is that they get more aggressive
because they know they're so close,'' said Petty Officer William
Weaver. ``That's a fact, that's not personal opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver should know. Last September, his 41-foot utility boat
stopped a sailboat filled with Cuban migrants about 500 yards from
shore. When Weaver tried to cut the boat's sail to prevent it from
advancing, one of the migrants tried to hack Weaver's arm with a
rusted machete. The boat eventually capsized and the migrants were
taken into custody about 100 yards from shore.
</P>
<P>
   The list of violent incidents involving Cubans at sea is
growing. Last August, a man chewed the inside of his mouth until it
bled, then pretended to cough up blood so the Coast Guard would
take him to the United States for medical attention. He was
returned to Cuba. In July, a man doused himself and his boat with
gasoline, then threatened to light himself on fire. The Coast Guard
crew sprayed him with fire-resistant foam and took him into
custody.
</P>
<P>
   That same week, a Cuban man slit his wrists with a torn soda can
and smeared blood all over himself and a female companion before he
was subdued. The Coast Guard crew was forced to install plastic
fencing on deck to prevent the migrants from jumping overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know if they touch land they're pretty much here,'' said
LaBrec, the Coast Guard spokesman. ``They'll do anything to touch
land. They've held babies out over the side of the boat and tell
us, `Don't come any closer or we'll drop the baby.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the Elian Gonzalez case appears to involve a
similar combination of desperation and greed. The idea for the trip
apparently originated with Munero, who first came to Miami in June
1998. He returned to Cuba sometime last year, although it is
unclear why. Cuban American exiles have said that Munero went back
to get Brotons and Elian. But Verne Eastwood, the lead investigator
for the Border Patrol, said he was told by family members that
Munero's original intention was to return to see another woman to
whom he was still married.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Brotons met Munero and moved in with him. At
the same time, Munero began working on the boat with his father,
and he quietly sent word of his plans throughout Cardenas, a port
city on Cuba's northern coast. ``It appeared that both the father
and the son were working jointly as far as the preparations for the
trip were concerned,'' said Eastwood. ``The survivors said they
paid them $2,000 each to board the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   By today's smuggling standards, the operation was small-time,
and therefore infinitely more risky, authorities said. Munero tried
to cram the boat with as many people as possible. The boat
apparently was not equipped with life vests. The three inner tubes
were brought along not as safety precautions, but to balance the
overcrowded craft. Two of the inner tubes were positioned on either
side of the boat, and one was positioned in front.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they believe the boat was two-thirds of the
way to its destination when, during a storm, the motor gave out and
the boat began to take on water and capsized. The passengers then
climbed onto the 14- to 16-inch diameter inner tubes and cast off.
</P>
<P>
   A fisherman pulled Elian from the water about three miles
offshore. A woman whose body was found a mile away might have been
tethered to the same inner tube, authorities said. Petty officer
Travis Kane, one of the first Coast Guard officers to treat Elian,
said, ``He knew for a fact that his mom had died. When I talked to
him, all he said was his mom was gone. He said he asked her for a
bottle and she never answered him. That was the first thing he told
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Baena, a Spanish-speaking seaman for the Coast Guard, tried
to keep Elian conscious by asking him questions like what his
favorite color was. ``He didn't recall how many days he had been in
the water,'' said Baena. ``He just knew that his mom was dead. He
didn't even remember how long the trip was.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian drifted in and out of consciousness. After initial
treatment for shock and hypothermia, he was rushed to shore for
additional medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began his life at the epicenter of an international
political crisis. Had he been picked up earlier, or had he not been
ill when authorities reached him, his life would have been
dramatically different. Coast Guard procedure is to hold all Cuban
migrants until an Immigration and Naturalization Service officer
can interview them. In nearly all cases, the migrants are then sent
back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was no reason to bring him to shore for medical
reasons, he would have been kept on a cutter,'' said LaBrec. ``Then
the INS would have done their thing and they would have decided
what to do with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-WIT-BOS &LR;      01-31 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-WIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDITH LIGHT BATTLED HER FEARS IN `WIT' ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a stormy day two weeks ago in Los Angeles, six women who had
worked together on the original production of ``Wit'' got together
to hold a vigil. Three thousand miles away in a New York hospital,
their friend, the play's director, Derek Anson Jones, was dying of
AIDS. It was raining when the call came; the ocean and the sky were
painted the same dull gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was near the end, we walked out to the end of the
pier,'' recalls actress Kathleen Chalfant. ``The air was soft and
gray, and it was like walking into some dark gray cocoon and saying
`goodbye.' It was important that we were together.''
</P>
<P>
   The LA production of ``Wit'' opened the next night, with a
tribute to Jones. In New York, the actors asked the audience for a
moment of silence. The touring production, which stars Judith Light
and opens a three-week run at the Wilbur Theatre on Tuesday, will
also be dedicated to the late director.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while a play comes along that bonds people
together in extraordinary ways. ``Wit'' is one of those plays.
Written by Jones's childhood friend Margaret Edson, this play about
a terminally ill poetry professor has had a profound effect on the
company members, both on and off the stage. The play, they say,
isn't a tearful lecture about how to die; it's a dry-eyed lesson
about how to live _ with simplicity and kindness. Chalfant, a
theater veteran who is repeating her original performance in Los
Angeles, absorbed that lesson firsthand; she learned that her
brother was dying when she was doing the role at New Haven's Long
Wharf Theatre. ``The play taught me how to look after him,'' she
recalls. ``There was an odd kind of synergy between my life and the
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Another actress, Frances West, opted to postpone a round of
chemotherapy to play the role two years ago at Shakespeare and
Company. ``I am an actress, and I have cancer, and I am playing a
woman who has cancer,'' she said at the time. ``But just because
you have this disease, it doesn't mean your life ends.'' Like all
the other women who have portrayed Dr. Vivian Bearing, West shaved
her head for the part, and she also overcame her anxiety about a
brief nude scene that revealed the scars of two mastectomies. It
was her last role onstage; she died in November. ``Frances was
unafraid, and she wanted to fly in the face of her death,'' recalls
Shakespeare and Company artistic director Tina Packer. ``It was a
real act of bravery, and I have to tell you, I don't know that I
could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The play required a different sort of risk for Light, a Soap
Opera Hall of Fame honoree who is best known as the blonde in the
sitcom ``Who's the Boss.'' Classically trained, she hadn't been
onstage in 22 years and had been afraid to try other theater
auditions before she replaced Chalfant off-Broadway. ``I wasn't
challenging myself. I wasn't putting my feet up against the fire,''
she says. ``To me, this play isn't about ovarian cancer; it's about
realizing you can change the way you live _ that is an option. And
to me, that is a profound piece of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one involved in the production had a deeper
understanding of the play's lessons than Jones, who didn't tell
anyone that he was ill until about six months ago. ``It was his way
of being selfless,'' says Light. ``The play was really his mission
and his voice and his way to tell people what was important to him.
And the beauty of it is that he succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   A personal mission
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both the play and the production have garnered a slew of
awards, including the Pulitzer Prize. But there was a time it
seemed as if the script wouldn't make it any further than the
bottom of Jones's backpack. Edson, an Atlanta kindergarten teacher,
wrote the play in 1991; she says the story of Vivian Bearing, a
John Donne scholar, just appeared fully formed in her head. She
staged the first reading at her mother's dining-room table in
Washington, D.C., casting her high school buddy (and prom date)
Jones in the role of Bearing. ``Derek was a secretary at Blue Cross
at the time, so he wasn't the obvious choice for director,'' says
Edson.
</P>
<P>
   Several years passed. The play was produced quietly at the South
Coast Repertory Theatre in Costa Mesa, Calif., but then nothing
happened. Meanwhile, Jones graduated from the Yale University
School of Drama, and the play became his personal mission. He sent
it out to scores of regional theaters, receiving enough rejection
slips to carpet a decent-sized room. But in 1996, he assisted
director Doug Hughes on a production of ``Henry V,'' which featured
Chalfant as the queen of France. (In theater circles, the actress
is known for her stirring performance in ``Angels in America.'')
Jones gave the script to both of them, and Hughes promised to
produce it if he ever ran a theater, which seemed unlikely at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, Hughes opened his inaugural season at the
Long Wharf with ``Wit,'' starring Chalfant and directed by Jones.
The production was a huge hit, but when the team tried to move it
to New York, the only place that would take it was MCC Theater, a
tiny off-off-Broadway venue. Again, the production was a runaway
success, but Hughes still couldn't find a producer willing to move
the play to Broadway. ``They said, `Nobody wants to see a play
about cancer,' '' Hughes recalls. The production ended up
off-Broadway at the small Union Square Theater, where it has played
more than 450 performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every point in the life of the project, the conventional
wisdom said, `Stop. Enough,' '' says Hughes. ``The whole experience
has been an exercise in trusting one's instincts and mustering the
courage to overcome obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone involved agrees that the play would not have gotten
produced at all had it not been for the tenacity of Jones. ``He
attacked this play in a fierce, rigorous, unsentimental way,''
recalls Chalfant, ``and looking back on it now, that's
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the character of Vivian Bearing would bristle at the
slightest soupcon of sentiment. The expert in metaphysical poetry
could analyze a verse down to the final breath without deigning to
embrace the emotion at its core; she's all head and no heart. In
Chalfant's estimation, ``She's mean as a snake.'' In Frances West's
view, ``She's a tough, courageous bird, this woman.'' The professor
harangues her students and won't suffer fools. And she certainly
doesn't gloss over the gory details of her own predicament: ``It is
not my intention to give away the plot,'' she announces at the
outset, ``but I think I die at the end.'' Even as she undergoes
eight months of an experimental treatment and deteriorates
physically, she still wrestles with the proper punctuation of
Donne's ``Death, Be Not Proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Donne's meditations on mortality are of little use when one
comes face to face with the real thing. Yet this is a woman who
doesn't have the telephone number to her own emotions. ``She's
dying of ovarian cancer, which is the cancer of the life-giving
organs, the nurturing organs,'' notes Light. ``This is a woman who
has given birth to nothing. She has not nurtured. She has not taken
anyone into the enfoldment of her body or her arms or her breast.
Symbolically, that's very powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is an unspoken solidarity among the women of ``Wit,''
who share the experience of walking around bald in an
image-obsessed society. ``Being bald has been extremely freeing,''
says Light, who doesn't wear a wig in public. ``I don't have
cancer, but it's my attempt to let people know that at some level I
know what they might be going through. I can't understand it
completely _ that would be arrogant _ but I know what it's like
when people stare at me and think, `Oh that poor woman, she must be
so ill.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, the play will be performed at dozens of
regional theaters nationwide, as well as at venues in other
countries. ``I'm just charmed by the idea of this legion of
50-something-year-old bald women walking around the world,'' says
Chalfant. ``We have this bond which in one way is superficial and
in another way is not. Women's hair has such a symbolic power, it
is as though we have made a sacrifice to some odd religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you want to call it, that spiritual experience has been
life-changing for everyone involved, thanks in no small part to the
influence of Jones. In the end, there's a certain poetic beauty to
his passing. In a 1998 interview, he said that the play wasn't
about cancer, but about taking stock of life. ``Being smart is not
the most important thing, being successful is not the most
important thing,'' he said. The most important thing, he said, is
quite simple, really. The professor puts it this way: ``Now is not
the time for for verbal swordplay, for unlikely flights of
imagination and wildly shifting perspectives, for metaphysical
conceit, for wit. . . . Now is a time for simplicity. Now is a time
for, dare I say it, kindness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
