<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PARKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIFFERENT KIND OF COMPULSIVE COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Cornelia Parker lives in Shoreditch, a part of East
London with a market where ``every Sunday thieves bring all their
wares to sell,'' she says cheerfully. She's a regular there. A
compulsive scavenger and shopper, she used to have her own stall in
the somewhat tonier Portobello Road Market _ until she decided to
use all the junk she amasses in her art.
</P>
<P>
   Which strategy has brought her considerable success _ more in
Britain than in the United States. That's a situation Boston's
Institute of Contemporary Art remedies with ``Cornelia Parker,''
the 43-year-old artist's biggest presentation in this country to
date, on view from Wednesday through April 9. The show is organized
by ICA curator Jessica Morgan, also an Englishwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Scooping up stuff in a flea market is one of Parker's least
adventurous means of acquiring materials for her art. For a series
that might well have been dubbed ``Great Tarnishes of History,''
she polished metal icons including Henry VIII's armor and Davy
Crockett's fork, exhibiting the results as art.
</P>
<P>
   For her ``Room for Margins'' she borrowed the canvas linings and
excess margins removed from the Tate Gallery's J. M. W. Turner
paintings during conservation in the 1950s and '60s, and exhibited
them on their own. The dark, ragged scraps, originally consigned to
the unseen backs of the paintings and then hidden away in
conservation lab drawers, took on independent life. Like her fellow
British sculptor, Rachel Whiteread, who makes casts of the
undersides of chairs or the insides of vacant rooms, Parker likes
to give presence to the overlooked. And like yet another
distinguished British sculptor, Tony Cragg, she revels in
collecting and arranging what others consider junk.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Thirty Pieces of Silver,'' for instance, she collected
battered old plates, beakers, butter dishes and other metal
tableware, had it all steamrollered to flatness, and arranged it on
wires suspended from the ceiling, so it hovered and shimmered with
air currents and changing light. Visually magical, ``Thirty Pieces
of Silver'' carries at least two opposite meanings. It alludes to
the pathetic, even ridiculous, uselessness of all this squashed
metal _ and to the 30 pieces of silver Judas was paid to betray
Christ. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Growing up in Cheshire &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 8 or 9,'' Parker recalls, ``I put coins on the
railway track to see them get smashed.'' It wasn't that she was
flush with funds. But she grew up in a remote part of Cheshire, in
England's unfashionable North, and ``there wasn't anything to do
with money up there in the middle of nowhere,'' she says. ``Also, I
was terrified of trains. I put the coins on the tracks to confront
my fears and get over them.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker was raised on what she calls ``a small holding, too small
to call a `farm,' part of a huge estate owned by the queen. My
father came from generations of farmers. We did everything by hand:
scything hay, tying up tomato plants. I was always working with my
hands and doing repetitious things. Growing food is so ephemeral;
it's there and then it's gone, and then you start again.'' She
compares tying up tomato plants with tying up her sculpture,
elements of which tend to hang from wires, suspended in midair.
``It's got to be redone for every show, like growing crops every
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspending her work, rather than placing it on pedestal or
plinth, takes the pompousness out of sculpture and gives it
ambiguity. Those hanging curtains of white chalk or charred wood
seem to be holding their breath, deciding where to go next. The
same goes for Parker's photograms of illustrious feathers: one from
Freud's couch; one from one of the ravens resident at the Tower of
London; a pigeon feather from Benjamin Franklin's London house; a
feather that climbed Everest in a down jacket. ``Feathers have this
mythic, Icarus quality, which I like,'' she says. ``You can't tell
if they're going up or down.''
</P>
<P>
   Feathers are a gentle material. Violence is also an important
component in Parker's art. She's had an abandoned building blown up
so she could recompose the remains, reused wood from a building
burned by arsonists, used various materials to test the sharpness
of the guillotine that beheaded Marie Antoinette, and thrown things
off the White Cliffs of Dover _ including the words of the
dictionary definition of ``gravity,'' cast in lead.
</P>
<P>
   She's also fascinated by fame. ``I'm attracted to structures
like the Empire State Building and people like Freud and Einstein,
whom everybody knows. We use them to measure the world, to describe
it.'' &QL; 
Regional schooling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parker didn't attend one of the chic London art schools. ``I'm a
country girl, and I went to regional schools,'' she says, to
Wolverhampton Polytechnic and Reading University, where she made
abstract sculpture from scraps of wire or plastic. Nominated in
1997 for the Turner Prize, Britain's most prestigious contemporary
art award, Parker was looking forward to being the first
Wolverhampton grad ever to win. (She didn't.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a slightly maverick position in the art world,'' she
says, ``being a bit older than the Young British Artist
generation.'' Her work has, however, been bought by the collector
who coined the term ``Young British Artist'' _ the controversial
Charles Saatchi. She has mixed feelings about him. ``He's done some
good things for British art, but also some damaging ones,'' she
says, ``by buying up whole shows, keeping all the work without
showing it, and then selling it off.'' Parker's work, meanwhile, is
sold through London's Frith Street Gallery. ``ARTnews'' recently
reported that prices for her photograms and large-scale sculptures
range from $16,000 to $56,000. She has a large public in Britain:
Her 1998 show in London's Serpentine Gallery, a lovely space in the
middle of Kensington Gardens, drew 46,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   She's become sufficiently successful that, after years of
renting in the East End, she's recently been able to buy a rather
derelict building there, in a section she describes as ``not quite
Tribeca yet, although Rachel Whiteread has just bought a synagogue
down the road to use as a studio. This used to be a Jewish area;
now it's Bangladeshi. In Victorian times, the neighborhood was
deliberately razed, because it was so crime-ridden.''
</P>
<P>
   On the top of her low-rise she's refurbished a handsome flat
with a skylight. Her studio is downstairs. ``But I don't use it
much,'' she says. ``I'm more an out-and-about kind of person. I
tend to make big works on site. And fear of the studio comes from a
childhood spent outside. I get claustrophobic.''
</P>
<P>
   `I used to focus on large, site-specific pieces that didn't
exist afterward,'' she says. ``Now I also make quieter, more
reflective works.'' The tarnish pieces fall into the latter
category, as do those stained by a piece of meteor she cherishes.
Tarnish is how a piece of metal meets the world; Parker removes
that intersection, creating, in the process, something like a
trace-bearing Shroud of Turin.
</P>
<P>
   She had a residency at London's Science Museum last year, which
gave her access to the Royal Mint and to the air base where crashes
are researched: She saw the Lockerbie plane still being picked
over. ``Artists,'' she says, ``are barred from certain places.
Scientists aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   While she'd previously been using recognizable objects, at the
Science Museum she produced a series of photomicrographs _ extreme
close-ups whose subjects you can't guess. ``They remind me of those
photo puzzles in the newspapers when I was a child, which asked:
`What is this object?' '' Her objects range from a blackboard
covered with Einstein's equations to the handle of the Chancellor's
Budget Bag; blown up, they all look like crusty moonscapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often get ideas for my activities from the non-art people I
meet,'' she says, ``like the Customs officials who told me about
people who starch their clothes with cocaine to smuggle it into the
country. That gave me the idea for starching sheets with chalk from
the White Cliffs of Dover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking authority figures to help me is slightly subversive,
and it takes some nerve,'' she says. Her growing gutsiness all goes
back to that childhood episode of putting those coins on the
railroad track.
</P>
<P>
   She gets bolder every year. On the subject of the leftover
Turner scraps now housed in the conservation department of the
Tate, for instance, ``I've gotten really cheeky. I've asked about
having them relocated to the modern collections.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking the Daughters of the Republic of Texas if I could
polish Davy Crockett's fork was really scary,'' she says. ``I was
testing my own mettle,'' she notes, ``more than the metal of the
fork.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
