<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1813 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      01-31 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING HOME TO LANDSCAPES ACROSS AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Places are primary documents of the American character. The best
detective fiction testifies to this thought, rooting crimes and
criminals in recognizable environments. Such books are as far from
fantasy and science fiction as one can get. Living abroad this
year, I find no need for Big Macs, a Dunkin' Donut, or intelligible
wiring, but every now and then I need to come home to the American
landscape _ its long reaches, its flats and curves, its hills and
dusty towns. I need to revisit places I believe I know.
</P>
<P>
   No one is better at the literary equivalent of a road movie than
Thomas Perry, and ``Blood Money'' (Random House, $24.95) shows
perfectly all his many strengths and his few weaknesses. Perry once
taught literature at the University of California; then he wrote
one, and another, novel about a professional hit man who knew how
to disappear. For his sixth book, he brought all his talents
together _ an ability to make the reader feel ``right there,'' on
the streetcorner watching, in the back seat of the car listening; a
powerful sense of plot; an ear for how many different people speak;
an eye for the turn in the road, not this one but the next one _
and created Jane Whitefield. She is a Native American who has been
a professional ``vanisher,'' a person who helps people disappear
when they must, from wife-beating husbands, from Mafia goons, from
the kind of hit man Perry once wrote of. ``Blood Money'' is the
fifth Jane Whitefield book, and for two-thirds of its length it is
better than any of the other four, and then for the last third
perhaps a little less good than any of them. It is still a
terrific, pell-mell book, as Jane tries to help a young and at
times foolish girl and a wise old man escape from entire teams of
Mafia pursuers. The detail on how to create a new identity and how
to bury an old one is consistently intriguing and fresh; upper New
York State, Florida, Oregon, California, Ohio, and much in between
are wonderfully described; and if the breathless finish is just a
tad unconvincing, the book is a terrifying ride almost to the end.
</P>
<P>
   David Housewright, whose work I have not read before, is also
very good with place and voice, and in ``Dearly Departed'' (Norton,
$23.95) he sends his Minneapolis-based private eye, Holland Taylor,
into small-town Wisconsin to search for a woman who has
disappeared, leaving behind a tape for her lawyer that begins, ``If
you are listening to this now, it is because I am dead.''
Housewright follows the usual formula _ we watch the investigator
search _ where Perry reverses it, making us watch the pursued
looking over their shoulders. Read together, the two books tell us
much about identity and how easily its surface attributes can be
constructed in America. Native Americans figure in Housewright's
plot too, though in quite a different way.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Slickrock'' (St. Martin's, $22.95), Laura Crum writes a
low-key story of Gail McCarthy, veterinarian, who sets out into the
Sierra Nevada Mountains of California on a solitary pack trip.
There is much about horses, and horse sense, and what can go wrong
while on the trail, with some observations about human
relationships woven in.
</P>
<P>
   Les Standiford also takes us into the high valleys, this time in
the Grand Tetons of Wyoming, in ``Black Mountain'' (Putnam,
$23.95). A presidential candidate who wants to look like an
environmentalist, along with his wife and entourage of mostly city
types, is taken by air to the back of beyond for a river float. The
plane that is to come back for them explodes on takeoff, and the
group must face trekking out. The reader knows from the first page
that there are forces out there in the wilderness determined that
they will not survive. Standiford does a fine job with these
ingredients, effectively reworking the tradition of the ``and then
there were none'' plot (indeed, referring to ``Ten Little Indians''
midway through).
</P>
<P>
   Still, all those rural scenes, those mountain passes, those
one-light towns, do make one long for the bright lights of the
city, and for such a longing, the best cure is an Ed McBain 87th
Precinct book. ``The Last Dance'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is the
50th installment in this series, and though the title, and a hint
here and there, might suggest that McBain is about done _ having
written 90 books, 20 of them as Evan Hunter, since 1952 _ I hope
the hints are misleading, for he is as good as ever. Here the 87th
Precinct team investigates a suicide that (surprise!) soon proves
to have been murder and, in the patented McBain way, produces a
near-surprise in the last pages. This is Isola, for which read New
York City, perfectly spoken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      01-31 0159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Vast Conspiracy: The Real Story of the Sex Scandal That
Nearly Brought Down a President'' by Jeffrey Toobin (Random House,
$25.95). A serious yet entertaining chronicle of the late
unpleasantness. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So I Am Glad'' by A. L. Kennedy (Knopf, $23). The shade of
Cyrano de Bergerac enters the life of a cool Scottish maid. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Gloaming'' by Alice Elliot Dark (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$23). Stories that suggest a whole universe in a single incident. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fasting, Feasting'' by Anita Desai (Mariner/Houghton Mifflin,
$13). A novel of youth, at home in India and in the United States. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of No Country I Know: Selected Poems and Translations'' by
David Ferry (University of Chicago Press, $14). In his own work and
interpretations of classics, the poet's powers have deepened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
