<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MISSING-BOS &LR;      01-31 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MISSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVESEY'S EVIL WEARS FAMILIAR FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MISSING WORLD 
By Margot Livesey. Knopf. 
327 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the finest fear-practitioners from Poe to Hitchcock, the
Scottish-born writer Margot Livesey knows that the creepiest
moments of life generally insert themselves into an ordinary day:
The sun is shining in what appears to be a relatively benign
universe, then something wicked walks in wearing penny loafers and
a crooked grin. This conceit governed Livesey's acclaimed 1996
novel, ``Criminals,'' and it hovers throughout ``The Missing
World,'' which manages to be delicate and terrifying at once.
</P>
<P>
   For what if the world as we thought we knew it turns out to be a
fraud? The internal laws of our own life stories _ our narratives
built from memory and experience _ are the banisters to which we
all cling. Certainly Hazel Ransome's wintry afternoon seemed
unspectacular enough, until a car speeding through snowy North
London knocked her over in a pedestrian crossing. Hours later,
she's carried to hospital suffering from seizures and on her way to
a coma, with her estranged boyfriend, Jonathan Littleton, hovering
by her side. Hazel's parents rush to her bed, as does her best
friend, Maud, with Jonathan doing his part to orchestrate her
rehabilitation. But as Hazel makes her way out of a neurological
fog, the medical mystery surrounding her condition is matched by
the hauntingly missing synapses of her past. Who are these people
standing around her, this gentle, aging couple who seem so
concerned? ``Jonathan,'' she whispers upon waking, reaching out for
the man who loves her _ or is she uttering something far darker, a
warning from a yesterday she can't retrieve?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missing World'' is a modern-day ``Rebecca,'' a
psychological suspense story handled with acumen and a riveting
sense of timing, but the real dazzle of the novel lies in its
structure. We learn the necessary facts about Hazel and Jonathan
from neutral sources: Jonathan's initial transfer of information to
medical personnel, say, or his advice to her parents about her
fragility, or conversations with his boss at the insurance company
where he works as a claims adjuster. We know that Hazel is a 30ish
freelance journalist; that she and Jonathan _ who've been living
together for four years _ had been quarreling before the accident,
and that Hazel had recently taken a sublet across town. We know
Maud adores her and that her parents think Jonathan, with his
buttoned-down ways, has been a good influence. What we don't know
are the same things Hazel doesn't know, which include most of the
emotional nuances and truths of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Enter, stage right and loudly, Charlotte Granger, an unemployed
actress and irredeemable screw-up who happens to be the sister of
one of Hazel's nurses. Slightly further afield, at least
geographically, is Freddie Adams, a black American who has found
peaceful anonymity from a troubled past by living a downscale life
abroad. Having fled a brilliant career in Silicon Valley along with
some bad memories, Freddie found his talents best served by
carrying stretchers at Lourdes _ this is a man whose heart is great
but amorphous, and who thus needs desperately to exist in relation
to others' needs. Six degrees of separation are the outer edges of
coincidence in this novel; everybody's paths cross mischievously
and often, so it's only a matter of synchronicity before Freddie
winds up repairing Jonathan's roof and Charlotte winds up reading
to Hazel, who is recuperating at home. Or home is what Jonathan has
called it, at any rate: Spotting Hazel's amnesia as his golden
second chance, Jonathan has gone about reconstructing her immediate
past with the skills of an architect _ one who specializes, it
should be added, in castles in the air.
</P>
<P>
   For Jonathan is demonic, or at least capable of being so, and we
discover this with the same growing dread as does his invalid
prisoner. Livesey titrates revelations about her characters with
ominous control; she also uses a prismatic point of view to
wonderful effect. We meet, for instance, the woman who lives next
door to Jonathan, a Mrs. Craig _ who seems dowdy and agreeable and
a bit of a pest. Then Freddie befriends her, and we realize that
Mrs. Craig is a very cool lady who's been in her ashram-like house
meditating; she's also no slouch when it comes to looking out for
Hazel. It was through Jonathan's eyes that we were imagining the
woman; Livesey, with formidable subtlety, is able to pull off this
kind of chameleon shift without an artifice in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, these are not merely one-act characters: Charlotte,
who spends most of her waking days trying to avoid the messes she
wrought the day before, even emerges as something of a reluctant
heroine when the stars are in the right position. (Driving this
point home is the tantalizingly enigmatic Mr. Early, a set designer
and Charlotte's old teacher, who acts as traffic cop for the
novel's entire cast.) So while Jonathan has given Hazel what he
perceives as ``the illusion of choice,'' Livesey's people seem to
trip and stumble their way toward the light _ wanting to be good a
lot of the time, realizing too late that fine intentions are often
only an arrow shot in the air. ``You can't change back,'' Hazel
remembers shouting at Jonathan during a row; the news in this
novel, both good and bad, is that you can.
</P>
<P>
   There are disappointments in ``The Missing World,'' most of them
because Livesey has set her hurdles enviably high. One female
betrayal in particular, which I won't give away, seems
ill-conceived. Jonathan's original sin couldn't possibly live up to
our projections about his horrid possibilities. And a few too many
metaphors _ which, like the characters, roam about charged with
happenstance _ converge somewhat blatantly at the end to make their
point. But like the Greeks who discovered the mnemonic link between
spatial reality and information retrieval, Livesey has built here
an imaginary palace that serves well as an ode to memory. And she
has made me as fond of Charlotte and Freddie _ endlessly tripping
over curbs or their own feet _ as I am frightened of Jonathan
Littleton. Perhaps most remarkable, she has opened the door to a
stranger's knock and looked into the face of meanness _ a hapless
guy who's a bit short of breath, who looks just like someone
everybody knows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
