<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
!!!! ``Mr. Death'' Errol Morris takes on execution technology and
Holocaust denial in the person of Fred Leuchter Jr., a self-taught
``execution technologist'' from Malden whose profitable career as a
death-house fixer-upper crashed when he went to bat in court for a
Canadian Holocaust denier. As with all of Morris's films, the word
documentary doesn't adequately describe this one. It's as much a
fascinatingly reverberant meditation on self-delusion. (PG-13) 
 
!! ``Eye of the Beholder'' Potentially interesting but ultimately
failed psychological thriller that can't pull its ambitious _ and
ambitiously photographed _ plot strands together. Ewan McGregor and
Ashley Judd star, he as an unhinged British high-tech security
voyeur, she as a murderess he feels obliged to protect, whether
she's his long-lost daughter (as he imagines) or not. (R) 
 
!!! ``Isn't She Great'' The life and times of ``Valley of the
Dolls'' novelist Jacqueline Susann and her huckster husband, Irving
Mansfield _ belted out warmly, knowingly, gleamingly, and
entertainingly (as biopic fairy tales go) by Bette Midler and
Nathan Lane. Savvy troupers both, they affectionately genuflect to
the rambunctious bygone world of Broadway as they zoom from wannabe
status to shagadelic high life. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ANTHONY-BOS &LR;      01-31 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ANTHONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARC ANTHONY FINDS A BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The firestorm of Latin pop is cooling off, as red-hot trends
invariably do. Enrique Iglesias is slipping down the charts. So is
Jennifer Lopez. Ricky Martin is nowhere to be found _ neither on
the radio nor gracing the magazine covers that were so recently
plastered with his 1,000-watt smile. The media, and the fans, are
looking elsewhere for the next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   And Marc Anthony is quietly, possibly even unwittingly, making
his move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird moment,'' says Anthony, on the phone from his
apartment in New York City. ``I Need to Know,'' the first single
from Anthony's self-titled English-language debut, is No. 9 on the
Billboard Hot 100 after 21 weeks on the charts, nestled comfortably
between Top 10 regulars Celine Dion and Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A worldwide salsa star for the past eight years but a newcomer
to the pop mainstream, Anthony is ambivalent about the so-called
Latin craze in music. ``No one should be seen by their ethnic
background first,'' says Anthony, who is gracious to a fault, but
willing to speak his mind. ``I feel too caught in that. People
think it's calculated. So many people are getting it so wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the great irony of the last, incredible year in Latin pop
that Anthony, 30, got lost in the shuffle. Maybe it's dumb luck and
bad timing; Anthony's album was delayed by his participation in a
film project (Martin Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the Dead'') and
legal haggling with his former record company. Maybe it's fate:
Anthony's been trailing in Ricky Martin's wake since they were
teenagers. Martin became a phenom in the Puerto Rican bubblegum
group Menudo; Anthony wrote songs and sang backup for them. Last
February, both were Spanish-language successes with forthcoming
English releases. Martin was invited to sing on the Grammys and
gave a vivacious performance that anointed him crown prince of the
Latin explosion; Anthony won a Grammy during the prebroadcast
segment.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly a beefcake in black leather with twitchy hips is an
easier pitch than a skinny guy in glasses who falls to his knees in
a fever of song. But even on an album saturated with overblown
power ballads, Anthony's got the ardent soul of a salsa singer and
the voice of an angel. Note for note, phrase for itchy, liquid
phrase, Marc Anthony's sheer musicality reduces Ricky Martin, by
comparison, to a well-buffed marionette. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No rivalry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony swears he bears no animosity. ``There is no competition
at all,'' he says. ``Ricky or Jennifer (whom Anthony used to date)
could be No. 1 for the rest of their lives. It won't make me any
less proud of who I've become.''
</P>
<P>
   As well it shouldn't. Anthony is the youngest of eight children
born to Puerto Rican immigrants; his father, a composer and
musician, hosted regular jam sessions that eventually grew to
revolve around his young son's formidable singing. In 1992 Anthony
``jumped into salsa'' and has since released three stellar albums
in that genre. Lots of people saw him as the one shining light in
the short-lived production of Paul Simon's 1998 musical ``The
Capeman.'' Simon, who handpicked Anthony to play the title role,
has compared him to Sinatra. The admiration is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was in Harvard for three years, working under
him,'' says Anthony, who grew up in Spanish Harlem. ``To be
welcomed wholeheartedly into his world, . . . how lucky I have
been. All I can say is I set out to learn.'' Of the show's quick
demise, Anthony only remarks, ``I can't say disappointment in the
same sentence with `Capeman.' '' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony has been doubly blessed with mentors, and he seems
genuinely humbled by the talented people he has had the good
fortune to cross paths with. At 15, he went on tour as water boy
with the legendary Panamanian musician and actor Ruben Blades, and
the relationship blossomed into a lifelong friendship. ``Ruben has
taught me so much _ as a musician, yes, but also as a man, as a
human being. He showed me by example.'' Serendipitously, Blades was
cast in the adult role of Anthony's ``Capeman'' character, Salvador
Agron. ``It was poetic,'' Anthony says.
</P>
<P>
   Blades was the one who encouraged Anthony to make the leap into
the Anglo market _ a move supported by Sony Music chairman Tommy
Mottola, who signed the singer to a bilingual multirecord deal
worth more than $30 million. ``You know, this is music that I would
buy,'' Anthony says of the mainstream, heavily MOR style on his
English-language album. ``I grew up listening to Air Supply and
Gloria Gaynor. It's my music. Had I had more African influences,
I'm sure it would have shown up,'' Anthony says, a discreet barb
aimed at those who've criticized him for not including more Latin
flavors on the album. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ethnic advantage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's no denying that Anthony's ethnic heritage has been
an advantage in the current Latin-pop boom. ``It disturbs me to
even think about it, that I might have been accepted because I'm
Latin and not by the merit of my music,'' Anthony insists. ``I'm
glad that Latinos in general feel like this might be their chance
to express themselves, but I beg them not to do it because it's a
chic thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, as passionate in his opinions as in his singing, is
extraordinarily proud of his pop album. He bristles at how many
have misunderstood him, and his music. ``I'm Puerto Rican, but
(itals)I'm from New York(unitals),'' Anthony pronounces in clear,
measured tones. ``I've done so many interviews where people say,
`Wow, you speak English so well!' They ask `What do you think of
American women?' That is disturbing, to feel like an outsider in
your backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost in the same breath, Anthony describes himself as
``extremely fulfilled.'' He spends as much time as he can with his
5-year-old daughter from a relationship that's ended, and recently
announced his engagement to former Miss Universe Dayanara Torres,
whom he met in San Juan last winter. Last month Anthony released
``Desde un Principio / From the Beginning,'' a compilation of salsa
tracks from his first three albums, to excellent reviews. He has
finally achieved, he says, a great sense of musical and personal
balance. ``I'm doing pop and I'm doing salsa. I can do both. I am
both. And it's like a great weight has been lifted off my
shoulders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1400EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-31 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING THE URGE TO CALL HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emma Bovary sighs. She weeps. Rodolphe, the love of her life,
has deserted her. She must have him or die.
</P>
<P>
   What's this?
</P>
<P>
   A book has arrived in the post. ``Don't Call That Man! A
Survival Guide to Letting Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Emma doesn't recall requesting this book. Yet the author's oddly
euphonious name, Rhonda Findling, resonates. Did she perhaps write
any of those forbidden romantic novels Emma devoured so many years
ago at her convent school?
</P>
<P>
   Emma has time to kill. She opens the book and reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheila, an attractive 27-year-old computer programmer, sat in
her apartment staring at the telephone. She yearned to call Tony, a
handsome life insurance agent she had been dating for the past six
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh Sheila, I know your pain, thinks Emma, I, too, yearn to call
the man I love, even though the telephone won't be invented for
another 40 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   Emma reads on and learns that Sheila's heart sank when Tony said
he didn't ``see himself'' marrying her.
</P>
<P>
   Cruel Tony! Cruel Rodolphe!
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Sheila felt alone and desperate. She wanted to be with
Tony on any terms. . . she couldn't bear the thought of life
without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Emma feels faint and throws herself onto a nearby divan.
However, just prior to falling into a serious swoon, she picks up
the book again and turns to another chapter. After answering a
series of probing questions posed by the author, Emma comes to
realize that she has turned to Rodolphe, a classic ``ambivalent
man'' type, because she is the victim of inadequate fathering.
</P>
<P>
   I am a victim, says Emma to herself. I have always suspected as
much. She reads on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is a loss, you have to feel the pain of the
loss,'' Rhonda Findling advises.
</P>
<P>
   Emma learns that she must get in touch with her grief and give
herself permission to experience her pain. She howls and weeps and
rolls on the Turkish carpet and beats her tiny fists against the
cold, hard plaster walls.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour or so of refusing to deny her pain, Emma feels
much better. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Emma turns once again to the book and reads about the crucial
importance of having a network of understanding friends. She
decides to start a ``Don't Call That Man!'' support group for
literary figures in similar straits. Anna Karenina is the first to
join. Tess Durbeyfield comes around, and brings Scarlett O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hester Prynne wanted to be here but she couldn't get a
sitter,'' Tess tells Emma.
</P>
<P>
   Together they work through the ``Don't Call That Man!'' 10-step
program. Step nine, they all agree, is the most difficult. It
requires each of them to keep an hour-by-hour diary describing any
urges they may have to call their former lovers and how they manage
to resist calling. They all agree that the total lack of telephones
makes not calling a lot easier than it might be otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Emma and Anna, Tess and Scarlett consider Findling's suggestions
for self-nurturing. This is a very important part of the healing
process, Findling writes. Go to Paris. Get your hair done. Go
shopping. Go to concerts. Go off your diet and eat desserts all day
long. Go to the movies. They decide to do it all, even go to the
movies, as soon as someone invents them.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Emma has an idea. ``Let's get a literary agent and
write no-holds-barred, tell-all memoirs for big money,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And so they do, and they live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
