contemporary U.S. society. The organization, comprised of
historians, legal scholars, genealogists, economists and lawmakers,
would start the conversation over reparations by asking a few key
questions: (1) Should the U.S. government issue a formal apology
for sanctioning slavery? and (2) Is a debt owed to the descendants
of slaves who helped build this country without compensation? In
this commentary, Monifa explains why such a commission should be
instituted.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S AT STAKE IN CALIFORNIA'S ANTI-GAY PROP. 22. Fourteen
words in Proposition 22 could change state law, triggering a
national backlash against gay civil rights: ``Only marriage between
a man and a woman is valid or recognized in California.'' With
public opinion holding steady; campaign war chests overflowing; and
politicians, celebrities and interest groups lining up to oppose
it, Prop. 22 has become the major gay civil-rights battleground of
the primary season, writes columnist Chuck Colbert. If it passes,
what's at stake? Recent gains in gay civil rights, including
lesbian and gay parenting and adoption rights, domestic-partnership
registrations, health-insurance benefits and anti-discrimination
laws.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ... OSCAR DE LA RENTA. What is Oscar de la Renta's
favorite book? What does he like most about his job? What is his
most recent accomplishment? What does he feel is the most pressing
issue that Hispanic-Americans face? These are just a few of the
questions we asked this international clothing designer in this
original entertainment feature from New America News Service.
``Spotlight On ...'' is available as a formatted page -- in an
eye-catching layout with text and art.
</P>
