<P>
   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   `ONE HUNDRED, TWO HUNDRED MILLION ...' On the topic of the
upcoming census, two projections are meaningful, writes columnist
Raoul Lowery Contreras. One is that the number of seniors will
increase significantly _ from the present 34.6 million to 82
million in 2050. The Census Bureau also projects that the number of
immigrants will increase to 53.8 million in 2050, from 26 million
today. The combination of immigrants and young Hispanics will be of
huge value to an America with a median age of 40. In other words,
the work force will be made up mostly of Hispanics and immigrants.
Blacks, Asians and non-Hispanic whites will be minority segments of
the work force, Contreras writes.
</P>
<P>
   FORGOTTEN FAMILY VALUES. ``In a better world, this titanic
battle over the fate of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez would have ended
long ago,'' writes columnist Juan Gonzalez. ``There is no contest
in this custody battle. Grandmothers ... are the central figures of
every Latino family. They ... care for the youngest children when
their parents go off to work, pamper them with affection while the
parents stumble through life and provide them solace and comfort
when the parents separate, divorce or die,'' he adds. In this
commentary, Gonzalez denounces the actions of Elian's U.S.
relatives and discusses why he feels Elian should be sent back to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   40 ACRES AND A MULE PLUS INTEREST. ``It's the year 2000 and we
are still discussing the same thing we did in 1865 _ reparations
for African-Americans,'' writes columnist Akilah Monifa. It's not
that the discussion has been constant for the past 135 years. On
the contrary, we spend most of our time refusing to discuss the
issue. Since 1989, Rep. John Conyers Jr. (D-Mich) has introduced a
bill every legislative session to establish a commission to examine
slavery and its lingering effects on African-Americans and
contemporary U.S. society. The organization, comprised of
historians, legal scholars, genealogists, economists and lawmakers,
would start the conversation over reparations by asking a few key
questions: (1) Should the U.S. government issue a formal apology
for sanctioning slavery? and (2) Is a debt owed to the descendants
of slaves who helped build this country without compensation? In
this commentary, Monifa explains why such a commission should be
instituted.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S AT STAKE IN CALIFORNIA'S ANTI-GAY PROP. 22. Fourteen
words in Proposition 22 could change state law, triggering a
national backlash against gay civil rights: ``Only marriage between
a man and a woman is valid or recognized in California.'' With
public opinion holding steady; campaign war chests overflowing; and
politicians, celebrities and interest groups lining up to oppose
it, Prop. 22 has become the major gay civil-rights battleground of
the primary season, writes columnist Chuck Colbert. If it passes,
what's at stake? Recent gains in gay civil rights, including
lesbian and gay parenting and adoption rights, domestic-partnership
registrations, health-insurance benefits and anti-discrimination
laws.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ... OSCAR DE LA RENTA. What is Oscar de la Renta's
favorite book? What does he like most about his job? What is his
most recent accomplishment? What does he feel is the most pressing
issue that Hispanic-Americans face? These are just a few of the
questions we asked this international clothing designer in this
original entertainment feature from New America News Service.
``Spotlight On ...'' is available as a formatted page -- in an
eye-catching layout with text and art.
