 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-MEDIATOR (Moscow) _ Chechnya's self-styled ``mediator''
is a Moscow lottery millionaire of Chechen descent. Russia is not
much amused at his effort; Chechens say he's just a tool of Putin.
By Brian Whitmore. 1270 words.
</P>
<P>
   US-GERMANY (Berlin) _ A dispute between German and American
officials over plans to build a new US embassy in Berlin highlights
strains in relations between former enemies who became close
allies. By Kevin Cullen. 1390 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-SPIRIT (Undated) _ Beaten in Iowa and battered by Al
Gore's continous attacks, Bill Bradley is suddenly reeling. How
could he get back on track, assuring Democrats the spirited primary
they've come to expect? A few tips. By Scot Lehigh. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   NH-DOLLAR (Manchester, N.H.) _ Without the primary, New
Hampshire would be an afterthought in the political world, a
Delaware with mountains, a South Dakota with a seashore. How a
state cashes in on politics. By David M. Shribman. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-HEARTLAND (Omaha) _ Away from the frenzy of New
Hampshire are millions of Americans only vaguely aware that there's
a presidential race going on. By Lynda Gorov. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MANDATE (Undated) _ Both Steve Forbes and Bill Bradley
present detailed proposals that leave no uncertainty among voters
about what they intend to do. If elected, each would assume a
mandate that opponents would defy at their political peril. By
Michael Crowley. 880 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-SMUGGLE (Miami) _ In the shadows of the Elian debate are
the smugglers who tried to bring him here _ and have enriched
themselves by ferrying thousands of refugees at up to $10,000 a
head. By Steven Fainaru. 1600 words.
</P>
