<P>
   &UR; KURT WARNER AS THE NEXT JOE MONTANA?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RAY RATTO &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C.2000 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dick Vermeil, in a routine burst of hyperbole, said
before the NFC Championship Game that he thought Kurt Warner could
be the next Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   He was, of course, crazy. But not nearly as crazy now as he
seemed then.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is still three rings light, and he has not yet done
nearly enough to stroll into the Hall of Fame without so much as a
nominating speech. If you want to play the odds, figure that
Warner, the stock boy, the Iowa Barnstormer, the Amsterdam Admiral,
will never be the next Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Deny at your peril, though, the fact that he took a pretty
healthy stride toward the unreachable goal Sunday in Super Bowl
XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   His sensational performance against the Tennessee Titans Sunday,
and especially his winning touchdown pass to Isaac Bruce in St.
Louis' 23-16 victory, advances Vermeil's suggestion from idiotic to
merely highly implausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,`` Warner said, his MVP Trophy already
stowed away for the flight back to St. Louis. ``But I know I always
had faith in Dick, because from Day One, when he gave me the
chance, I mean, I believed in him. Their belief in me was
tremendous. Having never played in a regular-season NFL game, and
handing the job over to me, that takes a lot of courage. They saw
something in me, I guess, that I could bring them to this level.``
</P>
<P>
   That's not entirely true, of course. They saw him as the backup
to Trent Green, and if truth be told, they didn't even see Green
leading them to the Super Bowl this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner provided all the setup with a brilliant regular
season that culminated in being named league MVP, and he trumped
all of it with Sunday's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Warner completed 24 of 45 throws for a Super Bowl-record 414
yards against the Titans, but the numbers aren't as eye-popping as
the fact that he did it without any discernible Rams running game,
or for that matter, any interest in developing one. He used his
passing game to set up more of his passing game, and when it looked
as though he had finally run out of a passing game, he gave America
one more glimpse of what could be in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   He had led the Rams up and down the Georgia Dome asphalt much of
the day, building a seemingly safe 16-0 lead, but the offense was
stopped cold midway through the third quarter, and Tennessee
rallied to tie the game on Al Del Greco's 43-yard field goal with
2:12 to play. The MVP Trophy was slipping away to Titans QB Steve
McNair, and as an added sidelight, so was the football game.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, though, is all about risk, and he was determined to stop
the Titans from holding the momentum they had just acquired. He
determined that, even from his own 27-yard line and with barely two
minutes left, the instrument of all the Rams' deliverance would be
Isaac Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd called a play earlier and they had told me Isaac could
beat (cornerback Denard Walker),`` Warner said. ``We knew we needed
a big play.``
</P>
<P>
   Bruce never said anything to Warner. ``When I talk in the
huddle, bad things seem to happen, so I keep quiet and let the
other guys do the talking.``
</P>
<P>
   He just ran his route, running an up and then cutting inside
Walker to make the catch on a slightly underthrown ball. He burst
past him and the other Tennessee defenders and sprinted freely the
final few yards to finish the 73-yard catch-and-run that won the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just saying we had two minutes left,`` Warner said of
the discussion in the huddle. ``We'd been moving the ball up and
down the field all day long, and there was no reason we couldn't do
it for two more minutes and put us in field-goal range.``
</P>
<P>
   To the Rams' great fortune, the field goal became moot in about
12 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In finishing one of the exemplary single seasons in NFL history
in such grand fashion, Warner now dares comparisons without meaning
to. He is not Montana yet, and is careful to make sure that you
know he doesn't think that way even now. Mathematically, he is only
25 percent of the way there, and Super Bowls get tougher after
you've had one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vermeil, the man everyone thought was crazy just for
returning to the NFL, is having an extra last laugh today. Kurt
Warner isn't there yet, but he also isn't done. The possibilities
are fascinating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
