<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHIPS (Hsinchu, Taiwan) _ The assembly lines at Taiwan
Semiconductor Manufacturing were running full tilt after midnight
last Sept. 21, when the floor suddenly began to rumble. A massive
earthquake had struck central Taiwan 60 miles south of here. But
the quake did little structural damage to the factories. The main
problem was the lack of electricity, which left Taiwan's largest
chip-maker becalmed at a time when worldwide demand for its
semiconductors was running at a fever pitch. For Morris Chang, the
founder and chairman of Taiwan Semiconductor, the solution was
obvious: he placed a call to Taiwan's prime minister, Vincent Siew,
to request that power be restored to Hsinchu as soon as possible.
Within three days the lights starting coming back on, and less than
10 days later, Taiwan Semiconductor's factories were humming at 95
percent of capacity. It is Chang's happy quandary to be caught in
one of the chip industry's periodic booms. After slumping for three
years in the late-1990s, demand for semiconductors rebounded in the
second half of 1999. That is due both to the end of the Asian
economic crisis and to the proliferation of new digital devices,
ranging from set-top boxes and video games to electronic organizers
and cellular phones. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (Dateline to kum) _ Developments on
Vodafone's hostile bid for Germany's Mannesmann. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A recap of the Super Bowl
commercials, reviewing the winners and losers and going over the
results of polls from ad agencies, USA Today, as to which spots
broke through and which will leave the advertisers broke. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
