<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      01-31 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 (Fixing slug to ILL-DEATH-PENALTY)  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Feb. 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-BRITAIN (London) _ A British judge rejects the
human-rights groups' appeal, seeming to clear way for Augusto
Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator, to return home _ probably in
a few days. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-REPORT (London) _ The Northern Ireland peace effort
could plunge into crisis if the head of the disarmament commission
reports, as expected, that the IRA is not disarming at all. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Moscow) _ Secretary of State Albright meets with
Foreign Minister Ivanov, but no progress is reported on the missile
defense issue. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   IVORYCOAST-CRASH (Nairobi) _ Folo on crash of Kenya Airways
plane (about 150 dead) into sea off Ivory Coast. Interviews with
relatives, friends; airline press conference. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-RIGHTS (Jakarta) _ Indonesian human rights
investigators on Monday accused former military commander Gen.
Wiranto and other top generals of being responsible for ``crimes
against humanity'' in East Timor. President Wahid says he'll ask
Wiranto to resign. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TERROR (Tokyo) _ A Japanese security commission ruled
Monday that the sect that killed 12 people in a nerve gas attack on
the Tokyo subway in 1995 continues to pose a threat to society and
instructed security authorities to put the sect under surveillance
for up to three years. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-WATTS (Washington) _ Will J.C. Watts retire at the end
of this session? An announcement is to be made Monday in Oklahoma
from the most prominent black Republican in Congress and the
representative in charge of the party's congressional message. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-DEATH-PENALTY (Chicago) _ Gov. George Ryan of Illinois is
suspending all executions and creating a special panel to study the
state's capital punishment system, focusing on on what happened in
13 death penalty cases in which the convicted person later was
found innocent. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NH-VOICES (Manchester, N.H.) _ Voices of the voters on the eve
of the primary. By Richard L. Berke and Adam Nagourney. (1800
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NH-MCCAIN (Nashua, N.H.) _ Leading in the polls on primary eve,
this is Sen. John McCains' big moment. By Alison Mitchell. (1100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NH-MCCAIN-FANS (Raymond, N.H.) _ John McCain doesn't just have
supporters, he has fans. At each stop there is a cadre of people
who have already been to four or five of his events, who chase his
campaign bus from town to town, to cheer for him, shake his hand
and help pass out brochures. By Richard Perez-Pena. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   NH-BRADLEY (Dateline to kum, N.H.) _ On the last day before the
primary, Bill Bradley returns to the professorial approach that has
a certain appeal for many voters. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LANDER (Undated) _ Developments in the search for radio
signals from the long-lost Mars Polar Lander. By William . Broad.
(800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-ESTROGEN (San Francisco) _ Estrogen has strongly
protected against infection with the simian form of the AIDS virus
in experiments in monkeys, offering hope that hormone might be used
to do the same in women, researchers reported in an AIDS meeting in
San Francisco. By Lawrence K. Altman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREENBERG-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ Many linguists are reluctant
to tie the root of languages back to a single mother tongue,
largely because languages change so rapidly and any traces of a
single tongues were lost eons ago. But one linguist, Joseph H.
Greenberg of Stanford University, he has classified most of the
world's languages into just a handful of major groups. Though it
remains unclear how these super-families may be related to each
other, he has identified words and concepts that seem common to
them all and could be echoes of a mother tongue. By Nicholas Wade.
(2200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-HORMONES (Undated) _ Millions of middle age women now
are weighing hormone replacement therapy in light of possible
increased risks of breast cancer, women's most feared disease. But
the therapy also brings protection against many other diseases. The
bottom line: each woman's individual risks must be assessed, but
most women are likely to find benefits in the therapy: Over all,
studies have shown, women who have used hormone replacement therapy
tend to live longer than women who do not. By Jane E. Brody (1725
words)
</P>
<P>
   For other science stories, see the separate ScienceTimes budget.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHIPS (Hsinchu, Taiwan) _ The assembly lines at Taiwan
Semiconductor Manufacturing were running full tilt after midnight
last Sept. 21, when the floor suddenly began to rumble. A massive
earthquake had struck central Taiwan 60 miles south of here. But
the quake did little structural damage to the factories. The main
problem was the lack of electricity, which left Taiwan's largest
chip-maker becalmed at a time when worldwide demand for its
semiconductors was running at a fever pitch. For Morris Chang, the
founder and chairman of Taiwan Semiconductor, the solution was
obvious: he placed a call to Taiwan's prime minister, Vincent Siew,
to request that power be restored to Hsinchu as soon as possible.
Within three days the lights starting coming back on, and less than
10 days later, Taiwan Semiconductor's factories were humming at 95
percent of capacity. It is Chang's happy quandary to be caught in
one of the chip industry's periodic booms. After slumping for three
years in the late-1990s, demand for semiconductors rebounded in the
second half of 1999. That is due both to the end of the Asian
economic crisis and to the proliferation of new digital devices,
ranging from set-top boxes and video games to electronic organizers
and cellular phones. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (Dateline to kum) _ Developments on
Vodafone's hostile bid for Germany's Mannesmann. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERBOWL-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A recap of the Super Bowl
commercials, reviewing the winners and losers and going over the
results of polls from ad agencies, USA Today, as to which spots
broke through and which will leave the advertisers broke. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (For other Super Bowl folos, see the Sports Budget.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments One of the
friend-of-the-court briefs in the Microsoft case is being filed
Monday. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-NATWEST (London) _ Royal Bank of Scotland sweetens its
bid for National Westminster Bank by 6 percent, to $38.6 billion.
Bank of Scotland may also raise its still-higher bid for NatWest by
the midnight deadline Monday. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   LAFARGE-BLUECIRCLE (Paris) _ Lafarge of France, the world's top
building-materials maker, says it may bid for Blue Circle
Industries after the British rival rebuffed an informal approach.
Shares of Blue Circle rose as much as 24 percent in London. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
