<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-RICH-CUSTODIANS-HNS &LR;      01-31 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-CUSTODIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCHOOL CUSTODIANS DOUBLE WAGES WITH OVERTIME PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some San Francisco school custodians have
doubled their salaries through overtime pay, earning more than top
administrators and 100 percent more than most teachers, an analysis
of school payroll records shows.
</P>
<P>
   The custodians frequently bill for more than 40 hours a week and
have signed off on each other's overtime pay, the records show.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond McQuoid, a former custodian who monitors school alarm
systems, earned $55,000 in overtime in the 1998-99 fiscal year,
making him the 14th-highest paid employee in the district with
income of more than $100,000. Former custodian Willie Green, who
also monitors school alarm systems, earned $43,000 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Custodians David Kwok and Ronny Lee increased their paychecks by
$45,000 and $30,000, respectively. The custodians and security
workers earn between $36,000 and $46,000 a year in regular pay.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis of the overtime records for the San Francisco
Unified School District shows that each of the four employees
logged more than 1,100 hours of overtime last year, with Kwok
earning an average of 72 hours of overtime each week for a month.
Of the school district's top 25 overtime earners, 14 work in
custodial services, either cleaning schools or handling security.
</P>
<P>
   Operating at a site across town from the school district
headquarters, custodial services charged nearly $300,000 in
overtime, $100,000 more than any other department.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, the overtime was charged when custodians and security
workers responded to school alarms at night and on weekends. Union
rules guarantee them a minimum of four hours of overtime pay when
they respond to an alarm after normal work hours. If they responded
to four alarms staggered throughout a Saturday, they could earn up
to 16 hours of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The overtime was paid at the same time the cash-strapped school
district was forced to cut $20 million from its budget, eliminating
elementary arts and an academic period for middle school and
halving its classes for gifted students. It also was handed out at
a time when teachers received a 5 percent raise, boosting a
starting teacher's salary to $31,172. After 24 years in the
district, teachers can earn $56,000, roughly the same amount that
one custodian earned in overtime alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd expect the superintendent to look into this, hold her
staff accountable and come up with a recommendation as to how to
better handle overtime,'' said Board of Education member Juanita
Owens. ``How do you put in that many hours when there are only so
many hours in the day? It's a serious question.''
</P>
<P>
   Board Vice President Frank Chong said he was ``deeply troubled''
by the overtime numbers but needs to carefully study the data
before passing judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure the priority of services goes into the
classroom,'' Chong said. ``This doesn't appear to be the case here.
If we go through this with a fine-tooth comb and determine that
there is runaway overtime, we need to put a stop to it
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The records, analyzed by the San Francisco Examiner, include the
overtime of every employee in San Francisco Unified, the
fifth-largest district in California. Although several departments,
notably facilities planning, accounting, school assignment and
budget management, logged significant overtime, custodial services
consistently racked up extensive overtime hours, the records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of that overtime is for security,'' said Martin
Escalante, whose 270 full-time custodial employees are responsible
for everything from school landscaping and window-washing to
security.
</P>
<P>
   The four men who reported more than 1,100 hours each of overtime
_ McQuoid, Green, Kwok and Lee _ rotate weekend security shifts,
with two on call two weekends per month, Escalante said. When an
alarm goes off at a school, the employee on call generally goes to
the school site to assess the situation, he said. Or the employee
may be called over the weekend by someone at a school who needs,
for example, bathrooms unlocked because of an athletic event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised by these numbers. I know they're up there.
There are documents to verify everything they're signing up for,''
said Escalante, who earns $80,000 per year as head of the
custodians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
