<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SACAGAWEA-COIN-HOT-TI     01-31 0195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACAGAWEA-COIN-HOT-TIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STITCH IN TIME SAVES ... A DOLLAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the new Sacagawea dollar is issued by the U.S. Mint later
this year, you can spend it or you can save it. Or, if you're a
needleworker, you can reproduce it in floss.
</P>
<P>
   Posy Lough's The Posy Collection, which provides counted
cross-stitch graphs of historical sites and scenes, has released a
new cross-stitch kit depicting the female Shoshone scout who in
1804-05 helped explorers Lewis and Clark find the source of the
Mississippi River and open the Oregon Territory to exploration.
</P>
<P>
   The design, 4 1/4 inches by 5 inches on 14-count fabric, depicts
the young woman with her baby on her back. It also includes the
inscriptions ``Liberty,'' ``In God We Trust,'' and the year of
issue, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacagawea golden dollar coin counted cross-stitch kits are
available for $16 (including shipping and handling) from the Lewis
and Clark Center, 701 Riverside Drive, St. Charles, Mo. 63301;
(636) 947-3199; fax (636) 916-0240, or on the Web at
www.lewisclarkcenter.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1453EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1934 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FLOWERS-HOT-TIP-LADN &LR;      01-31 0167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOWERS-HOT-TIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLOWERS THAT BLOOM IN THE SPRING, TRA LA!
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever look a tagetes patula in the eye? Sure you have ... That's
a Tiger Eye French marigold, the little orange beauty that chases
aphids away from your roses.
</P>
<P>
   That's only one of the annuals _ flowering plants that last just
for a season _ you'll meet in ``Taylor's Guides Annuals'' (Hougton
Mifflin Co.; $23), edited by Barbara Ellis. The 442-page,
soft-cover compendium has probably every flower you've ever heard
of pictured or described between its covers, along with how-to
advice on growing and an interesting section on how to thwart
leafhoppers, beetles and other critters that like to eat annuals.
</P>
<P>
   There's a photo of every flower, so you know what to ask for at
the local nursery or what to look for on the seed rack. It's
available at bookstores or can be ordered by calling (800)
225-3362.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
