<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1939 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SPONG-AGENDA-NYTSF &LR;      01-31 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPONG-AGENDA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP SPONG GETS A CHANCE TO LISTEN, FOR A CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Every time Bishop Spong opens his mouth,'' remarked an
Episcopal priest friend shortly after the bishop's last book
appeared, ``a dozen people call and threaten to quit the church.''
 &HT;    This week, my friend can breathe a little easier. On Saturday,
after 25 years as the Episcopal bishop of Newark, N.J., the
always-controversial John Shelby Spong retired.
 &HT;    Unlike most Episcopalians, who are generally a genial lot, Spong
is the churchman every one loves to hate.
 &HT;    Over the years, he has attacked traditional Christian doctrine
and morality. His publications include: ``Living in Sin? A Bishop
Rethinks Human Sexuality,'' ``Rescuing the Bible from
Fundamentalism,'' ``Resurrection: Myth or Reality?,'' ``Born of a
Woman: A Bishop Rethinks the Virgin Birth,'' and ``Why Christianity
Must Change or Die.''
 &HT;    He has championed women's ordination, same-sex unions and the
ordination of gay and lesbian persons. Throughout, he has become
the nation's most well known -- and notorious -- religious
provocateur.
 &HT;    The bishop's enemies equate him with theological liberalism and
cite him as prime example of its bankruptcy. It is no surprise that
conservative Christians hate him. He has attacked every belief they
cherish and, in their mind, pushed one denomination over the brink
of heresy.
 &HT;    How could any person, in the paid employ of a Christian church,
so gleefully assail its creeds, scriptures and ethics?
 &HT;    But for all his blustering, Spong is neither a true liberal nor
a true theologian. Instead, his new autobiography, ``Here I
Stand,'' proves him a rather illiberal theological popularizer.
 &HT;    Whether the bishop recognizes it or not, his stances have often
harmed those who agree with him on the issues. Although he depicts
himself as a theological gadfly, he is really a sort of
institutional horsefly.
 &HT;    In the months leading up to his retirement, Spong called for a
``New Reformation'' in Christian theology and practice. He argues
that outmoded forms of doctrine and ethics can no longer adequately
express the power and meaning of Christian faith.
 &HT;    In ``Why Christianity Must Change,'' he offered his ``Twelve
Theses'' as a reform agenda arguing, among other things, ``Theism,
as a way of defining God, is dead.''
 &HT;    His autobiography ends with this appeal: ``I urge my successors
in faith to embrace, not to fear, the changes necessary to enable
the Church of the future to be born -- I think a radical
reformation is on our doorstep.''
 &HT;    These insights are neither original nor unique. That theism is
in trouble and that Christianity needs reform are truisms so
obvious that it almost seems ridiculous to state them. And reform
is, in many ways, already occurring. Since the end of World War II,
western Christianity has been undergoing a vast theological and
ethical reorientation that defies simple ``liberal,''
``conservative,'' ``heretical,'' or ``orthodox'' labels.
 &HT;    Many clerics, theologians, and faithful lay persons have
dedicated their lives to thoughtfully guiding Christian
institutions during this challenging time. Old patterns of doing
spiritual business no longer work. Even rather traditional churches
-- such as the bishop's own Episcopal Church -- are experiencing
new waves of creativity in ministry, worship and community.
American church life is being reformed.
 &HT;    But that reformation does not follow a particular agenda.
Sometimes, it takes the form of a local ``community'' church whose
members find spiritual fulfillment in small groups. At other times,
reform expresses itself through walking the labyrinth, silent
retreats and centering prayer.
 &HT;    New interpretations of Jesus -- from ``What Would Jesus Do?'' to
the Jesus Seminar -- are having a powerful impact on theologically
diverse congregations.
 &HT;    Even church conflicts, such as struggle over the role of
homosexual persons in religious life, are reshaping the nature of
faith communities.
 &HT;    In short, Bishop Spong, get with the program. Even those of us
who agree with you on some issues (like gay and lesbian ordination)
do not need your agenda.
 &HT;    Indeed, one of the major problems with contemporary religion is
that it persists in being hierarchical. Having a bishop tell us
that what we should no longer believe is as retrograde as the
biblical fundamentalism you castigate.
 &HT;    Maybe now that you have retired, you can sit in the pews and
listen to us for awhile. We are further along than you suspect. And
we all think you need to shut your mouth.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
