 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Feb.
1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE-TIMES &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LANDER (Undated) _ Developments in the search for radio
signals from the long-lost Mars Polar Lander. By William J. Broad.
(800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-ESTROGEN (San Francisco) _ Estrogen has strongly
protected against infection with the simian form of the AIDS virus
in experiments in monkeys, offering hope that hormone might be used
to do the same in women, researchers reported in an AIDS meeting in
San Francisco. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREENBERG-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ Many linguists are reluctant
to tie the root of languages back to a single mother tongue,
largely because languages change so rapidly and any traces of a
single tongues were lost eons ago. But one linguist, Joseph H.
Greenberg of Stanford University, he has classified most of the
world's languages into just a handful of major groups. Though it
remains unclear how these super-families may be related to each
other, he has identified words and concepts that seem common to
them all and could be echoes of a mother tongue. By Nicholas Wade.
(2200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GALILEO-EUROPA (Undated) _ When the durability and longevity
of spacecraft have counted most, on long voyages to the outer
planets of the Sun, fortune has smiled on American space
scientists. In the tradition of hardihood, the Galileo spacecraft
has defied engineering's actuarial tables, completing more than
four years of orbiting Jupiter and taking in the sights of its four
major moons. In an especially close encounter with the moon Europa
last month, the spacecraft picked up the most compelling evidence
so far of an electrically conducting material in Europa's
subsurface, like an ocean of salty water. By John Noble Wilford.
(1875 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-HORMONES (Undated) _ Millions of middle age women now
are weighing hormone replacement therapy in light of possible
increased risks of breast cancer, women's most feared disease. But
the therapy also brings protection against many other diseases. The
bottom line: each woman's individual risks must be assessed, but
most women are likely to find benefits in the therapy: Over all,
studies have shown, women who have used hormone replacement therapy
tend to live longer than women who do not. By Jane E. Brody. (1725
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OPTICAL-BLACK-HOLE (Undated) _ Astronomers believe that
nothing, not even light, can escape after it has been captured by a
black hole in space and goes, so to speak, down the cosmic drain.
Two physicists in Sweden have now theorized that the same effects
may be produced in laboratories: light could be gobbled up by
swirling gases and fluids that look suspiciously like water going
down an ordinary drain. Called an optical black hole, this
laboratory creation would rely on the recent discovery that in
certain substances, light can be slowed from its usual 186,000
miles a second to a pace well below a highway speed limit. By James
Glanz. (725 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIRE-CHEATGRASS (Reno, Nev.) _ The federal government is
spending millions of dollars in a desperate effort to reverse an
accelerating cycle of fire and weed invasion in Nevada. Fire and
cheatgrass _ a fire-loving invasive annual grass from central
Eurasia _ are locked in a deadly dance that is steadily turning the
sagebrush steppes of the Great Basin desert into a weedy wasteland.
By Jon Christensen. (1580 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICS-REALITY (Undated) _ It comes as unwelcome news to
some physicists that just as their field is enjoying unparalleled
success, its relationship to reality is being questioned with a
pointedness not seen for decades. Logically, reality would begin
with elementary particles and the interactions that bind them to
build the universe that our instruments measure, our eyes see and
our hands touch. Physics, with its ambition of understanding these
building blocks at the most basic level, therefore becomes a prime
target for doubt. By James Glanz. (1235 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on how
horses cool their brains, plant oxidation and a meteor over the
Yukon. By Henry Fountain. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEPRESSION (Undated) _ While some forms of depressions are
clearly a result of genetic vulnerability and brain abnormality,
others may have their roots in evolutionary history, a prominent
psychiatrist argues. In some cases, depression may help a person
disengage from what has proved a hopeless effort; in other cases,
it may protect the person from jumping ship too rashly, perhaps
landing in even less hospitable seas. By Erica Goode. (1425 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEMORY-LOSS (Undated) _ As the huge baby boomer generation
ages _ and the blank stare of a blank memory becomes a not-so-funny
fact of more daily lives _ researchers are increasingly attempting
to discover if memory loss is inevitable with age. At the moment,
it is still thought to be generally true that older people remember
less well than younger people. By Linda Carroll. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: Well, folks, the
year 2000 is here and the bad news is that Americans failed to
achieve many of the health goals established by the surgeon general
in 1979 in an ambitious report called Healthy People 2000. The good
news is that we are being given a second chance, as outlined in
Healthy People 2010 issued last week by Dr. David Satcher, the
surgeon general. By Jane E. Brody. (1150 words).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILD-HEALTH (Undated) _ A major survey of children's health
care finds they aren't going to the dentist and use of Medicaid is
high. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health:
</P>
<P>
   _ Children who show a propensity for extreme aggression at young
ages often have low levels of a hormone produced by the body at
times of fear or stress, researchers have found. Although the
findings may appear counterintuitive, scientists at the University
of Chicago Medical Center believe they may mean that some violent
people may simply experience less fear than normal people, leading
to unchecked aggressiveness. (380 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Problems in childhood that lead to other diseases and
conditions may also be a factor in developing Alzheimer's, some
research suggests. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Scientists may be no closer to explaining why incidents of
asthma have been escalating in the united States over the past
decades, but a new study confirms that a number of common indoor
materials are making the situation worse. (280 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mentally ill patients who suffer heart attacks tend to receive
fewer invasive treatments than others. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A British medical journal reports that Monday is the most
popular day for Scots to die from heart attacks, And researchers
believe increased drinking over the weekend may play a role. (175
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science question answered: Will it ever be
possible to synthesize blood the way way insulin is made? By C.
Claiborne Ray. (300 words)
</P>
