<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1958 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-TWO-OF-US-REVIEW-L     01-31 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TWO-OF-US-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A TV MOVIE LIKE THIS, YOU KNOW YOU SHOULD BE MAD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Tonight is Tuesday, Feb. 1. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Throughout ``Two of Us,'' a shockingly tedious speculative
fiction on a day in 1976 when Paul McCartney visited John Lennon in
New York City, Lennon (Jared Harris) wears a T-shirt (not the one
shown in ads for the TV movie) that reads on the back: ``This is
not here.'' Were we that lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what John and Paul (Aidan Quinn) do in their time
together at Lennon's apartment _ art-directed to look mainly like a
dumpy bachelor pad _ as envisioned by screenwriter Mark Stanfield:
Paul offers John tickets to a Wings concert (surprisingly, John
doesn't kick him out immediately). John pokes fun, repeatedly, at
``Silly Love Songs,'' Paul's hit of the moment but the nadir of his
'70s music. Perhaps a script this insipid shouldn't be knocking
lame works of pop-culture so aggressively. They share some pot.
</P>
<P>
   Paul says, ``Sometimes I feel like there's so much stuff that
hasn't been resolved.'' Well, duh!
</P>
<P>
   They fool around on a piano, dueting, poorly, on, of all things,
``Tumblin' Tumbleweeds.'' They bicker about music and their past
and talk dreamily about their families. They dance to a reggae band
in Central Park, and Paul rescues John from his worst impulses when
a couple of cops harass them. They go to a neighborhood joint for
some cappuccinos, and John insults fans who speak to him. They
reconcile, to a degree, and nearly fall asleep watching ``Saturday
Night Live,'' until Lorne Michaels' infamous request for the
Beatles to reunite on the show almost inspires them to head down to
NBC at that moment. Except, drat the luck, Yoko unwittingly
intervenes; yes, again, Yoko breaks up the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how bad this plays out _ had they played video Pong for a
half-hour, the movie would have been vastly improved. If they had
counted how many holes it takes to fill the Albert Hall? About the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's quite likely that had the most celebrated songwriting
team of the 20th century in fact got together for a day years after
their acrimonious separation, they probably would spend it in such
a banal fashion _ !ital!but that's no reason to go and make a movie
about it. Lennon has been the victim of speculative fiction in the
past, in ``The Hours and Times'' and ``Backbeat'' (not to mention
Albert Goldman's ``The Lives of John Lennon''), but at least those
movies (if not the book) had something on their minds beyond simply
cashing in on the ghosts of the past. And at least Goldman's book
was scandalously spurious, not timidly so.
</P>
<P>
   To top it all off, Harris and Quinn don't even really
approximate John and Paul. Quinn looks like McCartney from one
angle, with one expression; otherwise, he's too old and puffy to
credibly depict Paul in his early 30s, and his accent is shaky.
Harris, likewise, is hardly a dead ringer for Lennon, but he
manages to convey a kind of intriguing sense of disconnect from
society that doesn't wholly mask a sharp, embittered intellect
underneath. He might have been interesting had a script with an
ounce of oomph been in his proximity.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Lindsay-Hogg, who directed the Beatles' last
film, ``Let It Be,'' creates a few tableaux recalling famous photos
of the guys but lets the action drag in a fatally listless fashion.
Lindsay-Hogg doesn't quite betray the band or its memory _ ``Two of
Us'' is far too prosaic for that _ but he has certainly knocked his
own place in the Beatles' iconography down a few pegs. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``Two of Us.'' &QL; 
What: Telefilm speculatively reuniting Lennon and McCartney. &QL; 
The stars: Aidan Quinn, Jared Harris. &QL; 
Where: VH1. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 1 star &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1513EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
