<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1959 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-SUPERBOWL-HNS &LR;      01-31 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUPERBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUPER BOWL ADS: BIG E-DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There is a commercial that says ``E-nough'' to
dot-com mania. It didn't air during the Super Bowl. It should have.
Then again, we might have forgotten it in the clutter.
</P>
<P>
   When will e-tailers or e-commerce or e-business realize that it
takes more than a funny commercial to make anyone realize who you
are or what you do? Yeah, that cat-wrangling commercial was pretty
funny, but half the country probably thinks EDS has something to do
with erectile dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   With a promise to limit any kind of www.badjokes.com moments,
here's a list of the good, the bad and the bland of Super Bowl
commercials:
</P>
<P>
   All hail E-Trade for its hilarious string of commercials. This
company produced two of the funniest, first with the monkey making
bad music with two dim-witted pals and the kicker, ``Well, we just
wasted two million dollars'' and asking you what you're doing with
your money. Excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the base but hilarious ad where a guy is wheeled into a
hospital face down on a stretcher. His problem: ``He's got money
coming out the wazoo.'' That was a show-stopper. Grade: A-plus for
both.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, the EDS commercial about feline herding was ingenious,
as rough hewn catboys rounded up cute cats, complete with visual
references to balls of yarn, lint brushes and allergies. But what
do they do again? Grade: B-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game started, Motorola had a nice pager commercial
featuring ``Baywatch'' star Yasmine Bleeth trying to pick up her
car at an auto shop where two young men had a shrine built for her.
Hey, that was some of her best acting yet. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed results for Computer.com, whose retro ads and faux
low-budget approach just tried too hard. Still, a couple of laughs.
Grade: B-minus.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the cola wars dominating the Super Bowl. 7-Up failed
to ignite much imagination and came off, in all of their attempts,
as predictable and mediocre. Grade: C-minus.
</P>
<P>
   And what was up with the Pepsi One ad where a rocking commuter
ferry slid that drink and a Coke into the hands of thirsty
travelers. Was the point that Pepsi One, or Diet Pepsi One tasted
as good as Coke? Really? Grade: D.
</P>
<P>
   Give the NFL credit for some nice work thanking the fans and for
reminding us, with Samuel Jackson's narration, that the Super Bowl
is indeed our unofficial national holiday. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   Netpliance, with its nerdy tape-on-glasses commercial, gets a B
for good visuals but leaves us mystified at what Eliott Gould's
voice-over is really saying about the company. E-duh?
</P>
<P>
   Bet you can't even remember the Doritos ad. Grade: F.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Tostitos ad with the New York Knicks sliding on
the ice because the floor crew didn't switch Madison Square Garden
from hockey to basketball? Lost in the dot-com craze. Grade:
C-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab usually has good commercials and it came through
again with one on retired athletes (Grade: A-minus), one with staid
golfer David Duval (Grade: B) and one with retired, staid Ringo
Starr (Grade: B).
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com had one of last year's best commercials with its
take on kids saying what they want to be when they grow up (mostly
oppressed at work) and this year went the emotional route, tapping
into the road less traveled, poetry and whimsical images. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   What's Budweiser going to do without the frogs and with all this
dot-com competition? Nothing much stood out, even the do-gooder
designated driver ad with Wayne Gretzky driving the zamboni. Or the
talking dog. Whatever. Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Dew is usually a hit-and-miss with its ads. But its
take on the mountain biker racing down the ``bad cheetah'' and
ending with, ``That's why I'm not a cat person'' was funny. Grade:
B-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali in almost anything is great TV. But what was WebMD
trying to tell us? Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is bad form, but the Nuveen Investments ad where
Christopher Reeve is depicted walking, somehow came off as forced.
Are we really to believe that people will take their dot-com
profits and invest in something good, like research? A stretch.
Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Spoofing Gap ads is sooo 1999. But Oldsmobile did it. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Visa has always turned out good ads and the
ones for the Olympics, like synchronized swimming (Grade: B-plus)
and women pole vaulters (Grade: B-plus) worked well.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't know that Oxygen is a cable channel for women,
its ad about baby girls resisting stereotypes was fun. Hats off.
Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   Wizard of Oz. Fed Ex. No. Grade: D.
</P>
<P>
   ABC hyping Regis. Yes. Grade: B-plus.
</P>
<P>
   We are huge suckers for hand-puppets singing and saying, ``I
think I'm gonna boot.'' So hurray for Pets.com. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, of all the ads for on-line job placement and head
hunting, the only one to stick out was HotJobs.com and its giant,
cocky hand. But that didn't make it good. Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeminders.com said its all-type, no graphics ad would be the
worst one of the Super Bowl. Close. Grade: D.
</P>
<P>
   But that ad was trumped by the you've-gotta-be-kidding,
we-hope-this-is-a-costly-spoof campaign by Epidemic.com, where
someone apparently gets money for going to the bathroom and
sneezing. Grade: F.
</P>
<P>
   What we learned from MicroStrategy, other than they exist at
all: That smart, smug people are using e-something to win at life.
Oh, great. Grade: D (or A for arrogance).
</P>
<P>
   Did we eat too much dip of a strange nature or was there a
low-tech commercial with some old guy talking about heart pills?
Correction: Nobody eats green M&AMP;M's, male or female. Grade: C.
</P>
<P>
   There was more. But did there need to be? Outside of E-Trade and
the Pets.com puppet _ and that weird guy with the bad ticker _ will
we remember anything we saw, much less the game?
</P>
<P>
   E-normous e-overkill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
