<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MARY-AND-RHODA-FEATUR     01-31 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARY-AND-RHODA-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIL `MARY AND RHODA'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: ``Mary and Rhoda'' airs Monday, Feb. 7. Fact box below) 
 
 
 
 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember mild-mannered Mary Richards, Mary Tyler Moore's 1970s
alter ego who just couldn't call her boss anything more familiar
than Mr. Grant, who stood up for everyone but herself, whose every
move and word was laced with genuine and often naive sweetness?
</P>
<P>
   Well, picture Mary Richards 25 years older, wiser, more worldly.
Mary Richards, fresh from her Tae Bo workout and on her way to an
assertiveness training class. A class she teaches.
</P>
<P>
   That's more like the character Moore plays in ``Mary and
Rhoda,'' the long-awaited resurrection of ``The Mary Tyler Moore
Show,'' one of TV's most popular and most honored situation
comedies ever.
</P>
<P>
   She says it was ``tremendous fun'' to play the role again.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been so much a part of me. Couldn't I be Mary
Richards sitting here talking to you right now? But it's me, Mary
Levine,'' she said, referring to her married name. ``We are soul
mates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' isn't coming back as another sitcom because, as Moore,
the executive producer, learned the hard way, there is just too
much information to pack into a half-hour pilot script, what with
renewing old characters and introducing new ones. Instead she has
settled for a two- hour movie, airing Monday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Harper is back as Rhoda Morgenstern, Mary's neighbor and
close friend from that quaint Minneapolis apartment house. But
anyone looking for other familiar faces _ maybe Edward Asner, Betty
White or Gavin MacLeod _ or warm, fuzzy references to old episodes
may be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   In this scenario, Mary, recently widowed, returns home to
Manhattan. Her daughter, Rose (Joie Lenz), is a semi-punk student
at New York University (she says her tongue jewelry is a
``clip-on''). After WJM, Mary finished her college degree and
worked as a network news producer, but she put her career on hold
for wife-and-mother duties.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rhoda has been in Paris for years in what turned out
to be a bad marriage to a philandering Frenchman. In fact, she and
Mary had parted in anger after Mary told Rhoda that her groom had
been pawing a bridesmaid before the wedding. Rhoda has moved back
to New York to be near her daughter, Meredith (Marisa Ryan), who is
studying at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Mary and Rhoda meet up again in Manhattan, ready to forgive and
forget. Rhoda moves in with Mary at her insistence, and they
attempt to jump-start their careers, Mary in television and Rhoda
in photography.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and Harper, talking about the project, stepped on each
other's words and finished each other's sentences while trying to
drive home the point that this is not a reunion show, that it's
about moving on.
</P>
<P>
   And in the spirit of moving on, Moore suggests this may be the
last we'll see of Mary Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed doing the movie but I think I would rather go
on to other things now,'' Moore said. ``I'm going to hang onto this
experience in that I'm writing an outline now for a book about the
emergence of me, Mary, as a grown-up person who, for the first time
in her life, actually took the reins and made something happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time I was the MTM initials of that fabulous
production company, I really was never involved, but I have been
involved in this, and so I'm going to write this whole story from
trying to sell it as a series and then having it happen as a
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore knows the old series is practically sacred to millions of
fans, revered for its writing, its characters, its shelves of
Emmys. But she did not hesitate to bring back the franchise at the
risk of harsh comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't scare me at all,'' Moore said. ``I think it scared
the hell out of Les Moonves (of CBS), who was the first one I
brought the idea to. He said, `Do you realize you're talking about
possibly casting a shadow on what I think was arguably the best
situation comedy ever on television?' And I said, `Yes, but are you
really going to walk away from this opportunity?' And he said, `No,
I'll give you money to write a script.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day I had an appointment with ABC, and Stu Bloomberg
and Jamie Tarses jumped up and down and said, `We'll give you a
commitment.' And that's how it started.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said it's important to view the series and the new TV
movie as two distinct works. ``(Mary) said to me, `Val, we can't
let that there was this fabulous show before stop us from doing
this, and ... I will kick myself if I don't do it for fear of how
it will turn out. Maybe we'll fall on our faces, but let's take a
chance.' And I agree with her.''
</P>
<P>
   At 62, Moore wears her age well, distracting from it more than
concealing it with a pair of spike heels and a slim skirt slit up
to there on the thigh. But she faces aging issues head-on in the
story as a qualified applicant confronted by employers' prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can't help but reflect what goes on in society,
whether it's movies or television, and unfortunately that is a fact
of life and a tradition that is hard for some people to let go of _
that is the minute menopause hits, women are no longer
interesting,'' she said. ``And we took that on as our challenge, to
show that, in fact, it does not make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aging is so inevitable, and we should start embracing it,''
added Harper, 59. ``I was so taken with what a wonderful
expression, without wagging a finger, this movie is about our
American ... obsession with shelf life, particularly for women.''
</P>
<P>
   In typical Mary Richards form, Moore can find the silver lining
in graying: ``I don't think the core values have changed,'' she
said of herself. ``Maybe a little rounding of the edges as one gets
older and develops a patina, maybe a little more awareness of the
reality of life as opposed to the happy endings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Also more self-acceptance,'' added Harper. ``As Mary quoted (a
line from the movie), `Years ago, this would have devastated me.'
We don't devastate so easy.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``Mary and Rhoda.'' &QL; 
What: Reunion of characters from the classic sitcom. &QL; 
The stars: Mary Tyler Moore, Valerie Harper, Joie Lenz and Marisa
Ryan. &QL; 
Where: ABC (Channel 7). &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Monday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
