<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     01-31 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: ON HEALTH REPORT CARD, THE `F' STANDS FOR FAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, folks, the year 2000 is here and the bad news is that
Americans failed to achieve many of the health goals established by
the surgeon general in 1979 in an ambitious report called Healthy
People 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the societal goals, like improvements in maternal and
child health and fewer deaths from breast cancer and heart disease,
were met. But we fell sadly short on most of the objectives that
are under personal control, like diet, exercise and cigarette
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that we are being given a second chance, as
outlined in Healthy People 2010 issued last week by Dr. David
Satcher, the surgeon general. And there is no time like the present
to get started. Americans are living longer than at any time in
history, so it is increasingly important to stay hale and hearty
for as long as our genes and life circumstances permit.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 objective of Healthy People 2010 is to get America
moving. Despite the enormous amount of attention being paid to
physical activity, the sedentary life is as popular as ever. Forty
percent of adults are still sitting on their duffs all day every
day. Only older people have made significant improvements in their
activity levels.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 percent of Americans now engage in moderate physical
activity like brisk walking, swimming, cycling, dancing or doing
yardwork, for at least 30 minutes at a time, five or more times a
week.
</P>
<P>
   And only 23 percent engage in vigorous physical activity, like
jogging, lap swimming and racquet sports, for 20 or more minutes at
a time three or more days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The modest goals for 2010 are to increase to at least 30 percent
the proportion of people who exercise five or more days a week,
increase to at least 30 percent the proportion who do vigorous
exercise, increase to at least 30 percent (from 19) those who do
activities that enhance strength and endurance and increase to at
least 40 percent (from 30 percent) those who do exercises to
enhance flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in regular physical activity is the one behavioral
change that can have the greatest impact on health and longevity.
In addition to rejuvenating nearly every organ system, it reduces
the risk of heart disease, stroke, hypertension, diabetes,
osteoporosis, obesity, stress-induced illness, mental and muscular
deterioration, falls and fractures and even cancer of the colon.
The surgeon general is calling on employers to help by offering
physical activity and fitness programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the nation's young people are now more sedentary than
ever. Only 20 percent of high school students engage in moderate
physical activity five or more times a week. School-based physical
activity has been declining steadily for years. The surgeon general
is asking not just for an increase in physical activity during
school hours, but also wants schools to provide after-school and
year-round access to their gyms and playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, too, are being asked to participate by assessing and
counseling patients about their physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   You've no doubt heard by now of the ``five-a-day'' program,
which suggests the minimum number of servings of fruits and
vegetables that people should consume daily. Only about 3 percent
of Americans 2 years old and older consume at least three daily
servings of vegetables (and a major proportion do it by consuming
fried potatoes, not the nutritious dark green and deep yellow
vegetables), and only 28 percent consume at least two daily
servings of fruit. Healthy People 2010 wants half the population to
be eating three vegetables and 75 percent to be eating two fruits
daily.
</P>
<P>
   There is probably no other change in eating habits that could
have a greater impact on health. Not a week goes by without a new
study proclaiming yet another health benefit from eating lots of
fruits and vegetables. The risks of developing debilitating
conditions like heart disease, stroke, cancers of the breast and
prostate and sight-robbing cataracts and macular degeneration are
reduced by consuming a plant-rich diet.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, grain-based foods and dried beans and peas are also
plant foods that are associated with better health. These, too, are
rich in protective nutrients and, if grains are unrefined, they are
excellent sources of dietary fiber, which can help to normalize
blood levels of cholesterol and sugar and keep weight under
control. When you eat fiber-rich foods, more is less _ you can
achieve greater dietary satisfaction for fewer calories. Fiber
fills you up before it fills you out.
</P>
<P>
   In the matter of filling out, Americans not only failed to reach
the year 2000 goal, we have gotten worse. Some 35 percent are now
significantly overweight (as against 26 percent when the first goal
was established) and by the new standard for 2010, which wants us
leaner still for health reasons, a whopping 59 percent of Americans
are overweight, sporting a body-mass index BMI) of 25 or more. The
proportion who are obese, with a BMI of 30 or greater, has also
risen.
</P>
<P>
   By 2010, the surgeon general wants at least 60 percent of
Americans to be maintaining a healthy weight, with a BMI between
18.5 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   Now, only about two Americans in five fall within that range.
The BMI is calculated by multiplying your weight in pounds by 700,
then dividing the result by your height in inches and dividing that
result by your height in inches once more.
</P>
<P>
   Especially disturbing has been the rise in overweight and
obesity in children. About one child in 10 now weighs too much, a
figure that should be halved by 2010, the new report states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to exercising more and eating more fruits and
vegetables, better weight control can be achieved by eating less
fat, which supplies more than double the calories of other
foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the percentage of calories from fats has declined from
about 40 percent to about 34 percent, Americans are eating as much
actual fat as ever. They are simply consuming more calories,
primarily as refined carbohydrates (sugars and white, low-fiber
starches).
</P>
<P>
   Although smoking by adults has fallen significantly since the
first Surgeon General's Report on Smoking and Health in 1964 so
that now only one in four people over 18 is a smoker, the 2000 goal
of 15 percent adult smokers was not achieved (the goal for 2010 is
12 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Most disturbing of all, however, has been the increase in
smoking by teen-agers, especially teen-age girls, who now are as
likely to smoke as boys. The 2010 target is for at most 21 percent
of high schoolers to have used any tobacco product, down from 43
percent in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
