<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDE TRIPS ON `STRAIGHT TALK EXPRESS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ A presidential candidate can wiggle a bit, even
on the ``Straight Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush ``would make a good president of the United
States,'' John McCain said last week, as he motored around New
Hampshire on the campaign bus with the noble-sounding name.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two is that he, McCain, would make a
better president, the senator from Arizona explained.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was a pretty straightforward, although highly
subjective, assessment of the two leaders for the Republican White
House nomination.
</P>
<P>
   This was the same day, however, that McCain also was launching a
new television commercial in New Hampshire, claiming that ``there's
only one man running for president who knows the military and
understands the world _ John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that McCain really didn't mean it when he said on
the bus that Bush would make a good president?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to draw that conclusion, particularly since the ad, by
implication, says that Bush doesn't know the military and doesn't
understand the world. And if he doesn't, how could he be even a
mediocre president and commander in chief?
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the wiggle _ either on the ``Straight Talk Express'' or
in the TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush supporters _ ever so sensitive to such things _ may
have felt their candidate had again been victimized by a
``negative'' ad. In reality, though, the commercial, while pointed
and a bit creative, was easily within the bounds of fair play.
</P>
<P>
   Although Social Security and taxes, over which McCain and Bush
will continue to duel, may be on the minds of many New Hampshire
voters, McCain obviously believes that foreign affairs and
veterans' benefits are major concerns as well. New Hampshire, one
of the senator's campaign leaders noted, has one of the highest
populations, per capita, of veterans in the United States. And
South Carolina, one of the next key nominating tests, has an even
higher percentage of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   So it should be no surprise that McCain, who must score big in
New Hampshire, would attempt to contrast his military background
and foreign affairs experience with Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was a Navy pilot who spent five and one-half years in a
North Vietnamese prison camp. Bush was a Texas National Guard pilot
during the same era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a hero in the Vietnam War,'' McCain tells voters.
But, pushing the right patriotic buttons, he adds, ``I was
privileged to serve in the company of heroes.``
</P>
<P>
   One man who attended a ``town hall'' meeting with McCain in
Hampton Beach the morning after the last New Hampshire presidential
debate may not end up voting for the Arizona senator. But the man
clearly was impressed with McCain's ``tough-enough'' background.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched those damn fools last night who were trying to get
his goat (in the debate), and they forgot he was a POW,'' he was
overheard to tell a friend.
</P>
<P>
   As a U.S. senator, McCain has debated, negotiated and voted on
defense budgets, international treaties and other foreign affairs,
has visited foreign countries in an official capacity and met
foreign leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's main foreign policy experience as governor of Texas has
been to praise the North American Free Trade Agreement and act as a
good will ambassador to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bush isn't the first governor with little foreign policy
experience to run for president. Most governors who run for
president don't have much foreign policy experience because that's
not part of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the last four presidents, however, were governors
before they were elected to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The only recent exception was Bush's father, former President
George Bush. And although his wealth of foreign affairs experience
and his World War II service record may have helped him win the
1988 election, even his success in Desert Storm couldn't boost him
to a second term against a governor who avoided military service
during Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Winning presidential elections and being a successful president
are obviously more than just having or claiming a longer foreign
affairs resume than your opponents. Some governors-turned-president
_ including Republican Ronald Reagan _ became known for foreign
policy successes. And the younger Bush, who has surrounded himself
with foreign policy experts, could prove the merits of high-level,
on-the-job training if he is elected to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But it is understandable that McCain would try to paint a
contrast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
