<SLUG> BC-LEONARDO-DICAPRIO-IN-THE-BEACH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITANIC' 
</HEADLINE>
 
 BEACH BOY: LEONARDO DiCAPRIO ON FAME, `THE BEACH' AND, OH YEAH, (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Leonardo DiCaprio in a scene from ``The
Beach.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's been two years since ``Titanic,'' and Leonardo DiCaprio is
still fighting to keep his head above water.
 &HT;    ``Every single day I'm drowning in the rumors,'' says the
25-year-old actor, standing on a bluff overlooking a white sandy
beach in Maui.
 &HT;    And what rumors they are: The tabloids say that, during the
making of ``The Beach'' _ his latest film, opening Feb. 11 _
DiCaprio was attacked by sharks. He became paranoid about his food
being poisoned and hired food-tasters. He got co-star Virginie
Ledoyen pregnant _ an impressive feat, since apparently he was also
dating Carmen Electra.
 &HT;    ``I've been shocked in the last couple of years to find out how
easily people will lie about me,'' he says.
 &HT;    These days, he adds, he doesn't let it get to him.
 &HT;    ``There was a point, when `Titanic' first came out, that I took
everything personally,'' he says. ``If someone didn't like me,
misquoted me or lied about me, I was distraught. I couldn't live
with myself. I wanted to give a press conference every five
minutes.''
 &HT;    DiCaprio runs a hand through his windswept hair, pensive in a
black T-shirt and jeans.
 &HT;    ``Now I know that I have no control over my life _ the only
thing I can do is not feed the fire,'' he says. ``I just want my
work to speak for itself and who I am. Any other assumptions about
me can be made _ I just don't care anymore.
 &HT;    ``Fame is a monster that you have no control over,'' DiCaprio
says, throwing his hands up in the air. ``I'm at the point where I
just want to live my own life and defy my fame, because I can't
escape it.''
 &HT;    Escape is the name of the game in ``The Beach,'' which casts
DiCaprio as a young man who, with two companions, seeks fulfilment
on a remote tropical island, only to find that their island Eden
has its own stock of serpents.
 &HT;    It's a dark, quirky story which couldn't be less like
``Titanic'' (1997) or the equally romantic ``William Shakespeare's
Romeo and Juliet'' (1996) _ which, DiCaprio says, is no accident.
 &HT;    ``After `Titanic' I said, `Let's be very clear. I will not play
another doomed romantic hero,''' he recalls.
 &HT;    Instead, he chose Richard, the troubled protagonist of ``The
Beach.''
 &HT;    ``He eventually realizes, as we all do, that paradise is a false
concept,'' DiCaprio says. ``Paradise doesn't really exist. And you
have to make sacrifices and be selfish to achieve your version of
total happiness.''
 &HT;    Director Danny Boyle notes gleefully that DiCaprio's fan base of
adoring teen-age girls may find this a bit hard to take.
 &HT;    ``The studio was constantly handing me notes saying, `Why can't
Leo be a little nicer? Why does he have to lie to people in this
movie? Young girls aren't going to like the fact that he's a little
bit mean,''' the director says.
 &HT;    DiCaprio just shakes his head.
 &HT;    ``I'm playing a real human being,'' he says. ``He is neither a
hero nor a villain.''
 &HT;    If ``Titanic'' made DiCaprio a hero to thousands of young girls,
reports of his hard-partying lifestyle made him a villain to some
others. The actor, who makes no claims to be a role model, shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I didn't sit at home at first,'' DiCaprio says
matter-of-factly. ``I don't think I need to apologize about it _ I
won't be a hermit because it looks good.''
 &HT;    In the next breath, however, he protests that his reckless
lifestyle has been much exaggerated.
 &HT;    ``You know what? Most nights these days, I'm not running around
_ I'm sitting at home on a Friday night. I'm in my living room,
surfing the Web,'' he says, laughing. ``I'll log onto my own sites,
and no one believes that it's me.''
 &HT;    When he does go out, DiCaprio and his ``posse'' can count on an
escort of tabloid photographers _ which, the actor says, is all
right with him.
 &HT;    ``I'm not one to sit here, be bitter and complain about the
position I'm in these days,'' he says. ``There are pros and cons to
everything. You just adapt. I think the opportunities I have been
given for the job I love to do make it all worthwhile.
 &HT;    ``I'm smart enough to know that I could never even hope for all
these opportunities without the fame.''
 &HT;    That fame came on the heels of ``Titanic,'' which won Oscars for
Best Picture and Best Director, as well as an Best Actress
nomination for Kate Winslet _ but not one for DiCaprio. His absence
from the Academy Awards ceremony led to reports that he was sulking
over his omission.
 &HT;    Not so, says the actor, who did attend in 1994, when he was
nominated as Best Supporting Actor for ``What's Eating Gilbert
Grape'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``Nothing against those award shows, but I feel really
uncomfortable at those places,'' DiCaprio says. ``No, I wasn't
nominated, but I wasn't upset about it by any means.
 &HT;    ``During the `Titanic' year, I had no reason to go to the Oscars
_ not being nominated gave me a way out.''
 &HT;    There were also reports of friction between DiCaprio and
``Titanic'' director James Cameron, which he doesn't entirely deny.
 &HT;    ``Yes, I can tell you now that James Cameron has a certain type
of personality,'' DiCaprio says. ``The truth is that it takes a
commanding, general-like personality to do a movie like `Titanic.'
He wouldn't have been able to achieve what he did cinematically if
he couldn't control 1,000 people and contain the environment.''
 &HT;    He might work with Cameron again, he adds, if it were the right
script.
 &HT;    The script is also the answer to another hot rumor, that
DiCaprio will play the adult Annakin Skywalker in George Lucas'
second ``Star Wars'' prequel.
 &HT;    ``I have met with George Lucas,'' DiCaprio admits readily. ``I'm
interested. I'm a huge `Star Wars' fan. But I have to see a
script.''
 &HT;    And no, he adds, that's not a veiled criticism of ``The Phantom
Menace.''
 &HT;    ``I have to see a script of everything I will do,'' he says
firmly.
 &HT;    Those scripts are piling up at his new Los Angeles pad, which he
shares with ... no one. All rumors to the contrary, DiCaprio says
that there is no one special woman in his life.
 &HT;    ``I don't say that sadly,'' he insists. ``This is the time in my
life to focus on work. I still have this insane desire to perform
in front of people _ it has been that way since I was 5 years old.
 &HT;    ``Without sounding pretentious again,'' he adds, ``I really do
think of myself as an artist. And I think being an artist is about
the coolest thing in the world.''
 &HT;    His art will take him to Rome this spring, where he will star in
Martin Scorsese's ``Gangs of New York.'' Some have it pegged as
another potential blockbuster, but DiCaprio says he couldn't care
less.
 &HT;    ``I have no control _ over the box office, over the rumors, over
my life in some respects,'' he says, throwing up his hands and
feeling the brisk winds whipping over the ocean.
 &HT;    ``At this point,'' he says, ``I just let go and hope for the
best.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Beach,'' consult the
official Website at www.thebeachmovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
