<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALENTINES-DAY-MOVIE-QUIZ-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS OF THE HEART: A VALENTINE'S-DAY MOVIE QUIZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Cher and Nicolas Cage in a scene from
``Moonstruck.'') 
 By S. BURELISON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Scholars disagree on who St. Valentine was and even how many
Valentines existed. But the most popular account has him as a Roman
bishop who aided young lovers _ and, in A.D. 270, was beheaded for
his efforts.
 &HT;    The idea of losing your head over love has not been lost in the
movies. In fact, romance has been a consistent ingredient
throughout film history.
 &HT;    The earliest snippets of film were usually everyday scenes _ a
sneeze, a boxer _ caught by the camera, but in 1896 the first
glimpse of movie affection was captured. Titled ``The Kiss'' _
a.k.a. ``The Widow Jones'' _ the whole ``picture'' lasted only
three minutes, focusing on the title osculation, and was critiqued
in one journal as ``disgusting.''
 &HT;    A decade later, ``An Exciting Honeymoon'' offered a little more
plot, but its seven-minute length _ and contemporary censorship _
limited how exciting the honeymoon could really get.
 &HT;    As films became longer, boy-meets-girl stories of laughter and
heartache became staples of the medium. And while out-and-out
romances were long relegated to ``women's picture'' status, love
has found its way into every genre from Westerns to war epics to
science fiction.
 &HT;    It may not always take conventional form, of course. King Kong
loved Fay Wray, Norman Bates loved his mother and Citizen Kane
loved his sled. And few would have guessed that the classic film
released on Valentine's Day in 1931 and advertised as ``The Story
of the Strangest Passion the World has Ever Known'' would be ...
``Dracula.''
 &HT;    Test your knowledge of more mainstream film romances with this
heart-tugging quiz. 
 -0- 
 MATTERS OF AFFECTION  
 &HT;    1. Garbo smiles. Count Leon d'Algout (Melvyn Douglas) melts the
icy heart of Nina Ivanova Yakushova (Greta Garbo) in what 1939
classic?
 &HT;    2. In ``You've Got Mail'' (1998), Meg Ryan owns a bookstore
whose name is also the title of the first film version of this
classic story. What's it called?
 &HT;    3. Why doesn't Deborah Kerr keep her date with Cary Grant in
``An Affair to Remember'' (1957)? Extra credit: Where were they to
meet and _ for real buffs _ when?
 &HT;    4. In ``Moonstruck'' (1987), Nicolas Cage tells Cher that there
are only two things he loves. What are they?
 &HT;    5. In which 1945 British film does the audience hear Celia
Johnson's thoughts about her clandestine fling?
 &HT;    6. After a spat with Ann-Margret in ``Viva Las Vegas'' (1964),
what gift does Elvis Presley send her to make amends?
 &HT;    7. In what 1942 soaper does Bette Davis evolve from frump to
femme fatale, in the process falling for a married man (Paul
Henreid)?
 &HT;    8. What famous couple shares a romantic spaghetti dinner behind
Tony's Restaurant?
 &HT;    9. As Richard Gere sweeps Debra Winger off her feet and out of
the paper factory in ``An Officer and a Gentleman'' (1982), what
Oscar-winning song is heard, and who's singing it?
 &HT;    10. ``Casablanca'' (1942) may be the most romantic film ever
made. So, aficionados all, what is Ilsa wearing the last time Rick
sees her in Paris?
 &HT;    11. In ``When Harry Met Sally'' (1989), when and where does
Harry meet Sally?
 &HT;    12. In ``Gone With the Wind'' (1939), where does Rhett take
Scarlett for their honeymoon?
 &HT;    13. In ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' (1961), what gift does Lulamae
Barnes receive from the lover she calls ``Fred?''
 &HT;    14. What 1973 film tells the story of the unlikely pairing of
political activist Katie Morosky and preppie writer Hubbell
Gardner?
 &HT;    15. The winner of the 1977 Oscar for Best Film was described in
its advertisements as ``A Nervous Romance.'' What film is it?
 &HT;    16. What is saloonkeeper Mae West's invitation to mission worker
Cary Grant in ``She Done Him Wrong'' (1933)?
 &HT;    17. In the ``Andy Hardy'' film series, what is the name of
Andy's high-school sweetheart?
 &HT;    18. Why does movie star Julia Roberts first go to average guy
Hugh Grant's apartment in ``Notting Hill'' (1999)?
 &HT;    19. In the classic romantic comedy ``It Happened One Night''
(1934), what does Clark Gable call the blanket separating his bed
from Claudette Colbert's?
 &HT;    20. What 1970 tearjerker opens with the line ``What can you say
about a 25-year-old girl who died?''
 -0- 
 ANSWERS FOR THE HEART  
 &HT;    1. Her friends call Nina Yakushova ``Ninotchka,'' which is also
the name of the 1939 film promoted by MGM as ``Garbo Laughs!''
 &HT;    2. Ryan's bookstore is ``The Shop Around the Corner,'' a salute
to Ernst Lubitsch's classic film of 1940. A musical version, ``In
the Good Old Summertime,'' was released in 1949, and a stage
musical, ``She Loves Me,'' bowed on Broadway in 1963. All, however,
were derived from Miklos Laszlo's Hungarian play, ``Parfumerie''
(1937).
 &HT;    3. Kerr is hit by a car on her way to the Empire State Building,
where Grant is waiting for her ... at 5 p.m. on July 1.
 &HT;    4. Cage loves Cher and the opera _ which is why he wants to take
her to see ``La Boheme'' at the Metropolitan Opera.
 &HT;    5. Johnson's voiceover narration explains her character's
``Brief Encounter'' with a married man (Trevor Howard).
 &HT;    6. Because she dreams of `` ... a white house with a tree in the
front yard,'' Presley sends Ann-Margret a tree _ but no house.
 &HT;    7. ``Now Voyager'' sees Davis go from beast to beauty. It also
offers Henreid's memorable, if no longer politically correct, stunt
of lighting two cigarettes at once and then passing one to Davis.
 &HT;    8. On their first date, the title dogs in ``Lady and the Tramp''
(1955) dine blissfully in the alley behind Tony's.
 &HT;    9. Trick question: The song is ``Up Where We Belong,'' but no
one is singing it _ only an instrumental version plays during the
climactic scene. It isn't until the final credits roll that Joe
Cocker and Jennifer Warnes add the vocals.
 &HT;    10. As Rick recalls `` ... the Germans wore gray, you wore
blue'' _ though the film is in black-and-white. Ilsa adds, ``I put
that dress away,'' so she must have been wearing a blue dress.
 &HT;    11. Harry (Billy Crystal) and Sally (Meg Ryan) meet in 1977 at
the University of Chicago, prior to sharing an overnight drive to
New York.
 &HT;    12. The Butlers (Clark Gable and Vivian Leigh) honeymoon in New
Orleans, where Scarlett loves the cuisine but longs for Tara.
 &HT;    13. Lulamae _ who prefers to be called Holly Golightly _
receives a Cracker Jack ring from her lover Paul (George Peppard),
whom she calls ``Fred.'' But it features an engraving from her
favorite jewelry store, Tiffany.
 &HT;    14. Knowing that Barbra Streisand was Katie and Robert Redford
was Hubbell should surely revive memories of ``The Way We Were.''
 &HT;    15. Practically any of Woody Allen's screen love stories could
be called a ``nervous romance,'' but the phrase was found on
posters for ``Annie Hall'' (1977).
 &HT;    16. Frequently misquoted, West's line to Grant is actually ``Why
don't you come up some time and see me?''
 &HT;    17. In the original ``A Family Affair'' (1937), Margaret Marquis
played Polly Benedict, high-school sweetheart of Andy Hardy (Mickey
Rooney). For the next 12 films, however, Ann Rutherford took over
the role. After Andy leaves home for college in ``Andy Hardy's
Double Life'' (1942), however, Polly vanishes from the series'
final three films.
 &HT;    18. Grant spills orange juice on Roberts during their second
chance meeting, then invites her to his nearby apartment to clean
up.
 &HT;    19. Gable calls the motel blanket ``the wall of Jericho.'' Like
the original, that wall eventually comes down, in the final shot of
the movie.
 &HT;    20. Ryan O'Neal narrates the opening of the two-hanky ``Love
Story,'' with Ali MacGraw as ``a 25-year-old girl who died.''
 c.2000 S. Burelison  
