<SLUG> BC-MARY-TYLER-MOORE-IN-MARY-AND-RHODA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIRLS ARE BACK IN TOWN: MARY TYLER MOORE RETEAMS WITH VALERIE
HARPER FOR `MARY AND RHODA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Mary Tyler Moore with Valerie Harper in
a scene from ``Mary and Rhoda.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Haven't we been here before?
 &HT;    Mary Tyler Moore is playing Mary Richards again, engaged in
heated conversation with a smarmy young television editor _ an
exchange that ends with him deferring to Mary with the following
exit line: ``You're a rebel, baby. Ma'am. Baby, ma'am.''
 &HT;    After a few takes, director Barnet Kellman is satisfied. Scene
124A of ``Mary and Rhoda'' is in the can.
 &HT;    Moments later, star/executive producer Moore steps into a
hallway to talk about the much-anticipated television movie that
reunites her with Valerie Harper as Rhoda Morgenstern.
 &HT;    ``This is kind of blurring the lines, isn't it?'' the
63-year-old Moore says cheerfully, eyeing a television camera which
has arrived to tape her playing a scene in a television station
once again. ``It's nice to know that people are excited about what
we're doing.
 &HT;    ``Valerie has finished her scenes already,'' she adds, ``but
when we were working together, it was like coming home. We were
separated twins who came back together after 20 years apart and
were suddenly finishing each other's sentences again. That was such
a pleasure in front of the camera and a real personal glee for
me.''
 &HT;    The movie, which will air Feb. 7 on ABC, catches up with Mary
and Rhoda two-plus decades after the last episodes of ``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show'' and its long-running spinoff, ``Rhoda.'' Mary is
a recent widow, Rhoda is divorced and both women are single mothers
struggling to get by in the Big Apple.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to make sure the movie was not a typical reunion,''
Moore says, looking professional in a greenish-gray skirt and
jacket offset by a distinctly less businesslike pair of black
slippers. ``Not an `Oh, there they are again. Isn't that swell?'
kind of thing.
 &HT;    ``I wanted a new story with real impact,'' she adds. ``I wanted
the patina of the years and the experience to show on these women.
Yes, two old friends come together _ but it's about how they deal
with their adult daughters, what they do in the '90s, how they face
being 60 and in the workplace.''
 &HT;    Moore must return to the set in a moment. Before doing so,
however, she confirms the general assumption that ``Mary and
Rhoda'' is a back-door pilot _ that the characters could return on
a weekly basis if the movie draws good enough ratings. Such other
``Mary Tyler Moore'' regulars as Ed Asner (Lou Grant), Betty White
(Sue Ann Nivens) or Cloris Leachman (Phyllis Lindstrom) might even
be involved.
 &HT;    ``I'm thrilled with the idea of doing this as a series,'' she
says. ``We could keep the story going between Mary and Rhoda, and
maybe also bring in Ed or Betty or Cloris from time to time.
 &HT;    ``I just don't know how practical it is for the network,'' she
adds. ``Networks today don't pay what I think of as proper respect
to the people who write and direct _ they send their minions to
dictate what is funny and what is not.
 &HT;    ``So there would have to be an understanding, going in, that the
kind of control I've had on this movie would continue.''
 &HT;    With that comment, a warm handshake and a promise to talk again
when ``Mary and Rhoda'' has wrapped production, Moore strides off.
 &HT;    A few weeks later, the actress follows through on her promise,
calling by telephone from her Manhattan apartment to report on the
finished product.
 &HT;    ``I am so thrilled with it,'' she says. ``It does what I hoped
it would do, which is stand alone as a story.''
 &HT;    Happy though she may be, Moore is now whistling a different tune
about a ``Mary and Rhoda'' series, amid rumors that she and Harper
didn't get along this time around.
 &HT;    ``I would not want to do it again,'' she says. ``At some point,
if somebody wanted to do another movie with, say, Lou Grant or
Phyllis, that would be great fun.
 &HT;    ``And I'm not against doing another series _ I just wouldn't
want to do this one.''
 &HT;    Why the change of heart?
 &HT;    ``Just too many impositions,'' Moore says quietly. ``Arbitrary
negative situations came up and took a little of the fun out of it
for me. While I'm thrilled with the way it turned out, I don't have
the energy to go through that kind of thing again.''
 &HT;    Thirty years ago, of course, Moore had no idea that anyone would
want to see more of Mary Richards. She'd enjoyed a successful run
on ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' (1961-1966), and while ``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show'' sounded promising, nobody expected it to make
television history.
 &HT;    ``We had no idea,'' Moore says, laughing. ``We knew the show
would be good, because the spirit and the determination were there.
But there was never any inner epiphany about how it would play.
 &HT;    ``Nor should there ever be,'' she adds. ``When you do something
that turns out well, you're usually focused on the work and you're
not sitting around daydreaming about how it will be received.''
 &HT;    By the time the show faded to black with its famous group hug,
Moore wondered what the future might hold.
 &HT;    ``I was a little concerned that the shadow of Mary Richards
might be a problem,'' she admits, ``but it has never proven to be
that. I have gone from one very different role to another and in
various media.''
 &HT;    Indeed, Moore stunned audiences with her portrayal of an
emotionally frigid wife and mother in Robert Redford's
Oscar-winning ``Ordinary People'' (1980). She received a special
Tony Award for her performance as a quadriplegic in the Broadway
production of ``Whose Life Is It Anyway?'' (1980), and took home an
Emmy for the 1992 cable-television movie ``Stolen Babies.''
 &HT;    It hasn't all been joyous for Moore, however. She's survived
personal traumas and tragedies including the gunshot death of her
only son, which was ruled an accident. She's also struggled with
diabetes, drinking, failed marriages and quickly axed series.
 &HT;    In retrospect, she admits that she regrets having made her
career her life.
 &HT;    ``You can't have it all,'' she says plaintively. ``It is my
life, and I'm not necessarily proud that it is my life _ I wish I'd
had more children. I wish I could have done that better. I wish I
were a grandmother, and I will never be a grandmother.
 &HT;    ``But this has been my life,'' she says, ``and, given that, I'm
very proud of what has happened. I'm very glad that the audience
has seen fit to applaud my work.''
 &HT;    Away from the set these days, Moore spends time with her third
husband, Dr. S. Robert Levine, tends to her garden and horses at
the couple's country home and raises funds for the Juvenile
Diabetes Foundation and several animal-welfare organizations.
 &HT;    Moore also gives speeches to women's groups and students, during
which she discusses her work as an actress and her growth as a
person. It's caused her to re-evaluate her own life, and come to at
least one conclusion.
 &HT;    ``I'm not such a bad kid, after all,'' she says contentedly. ``I
started out as a perfectionist, and was always apologizing to
myself for not being better, for not having done more, for not
having thought of something to do other than what I did.
 &HT;    ``I've eased up on myself,'' she says, ``and in doing that I've
eased up on other people.
 &HT;    ``So Mary Tyler Moore has mellowed, and this is a good thing.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
