<HEADER>
A2007 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-MULLALLY-AND-HAYES-IN     01-31 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULLALLY-AND-HAYES-IN-WILL-&AMP;-GRACE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILL' POWER: MEGAN MULLALLY AND SEAN HAYES JUICE `WILL &AMP; GRACE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Megan Mullally and Sean Hayes with Eric
McCormack, Debra Messing and Veronica Cartwright in a scene from
``Will &AMP; Grace.'') 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before 13 February 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actors who play outlandish television characters are, usually,
quiet and reserved in real life. The zaniest buffoons are generally
virtual churchmice offscreen.
</P>
<P>
   And then again, there's Sean Hayes and there's Megan Mullally.
Better known as the quirky, combative Jack and Karen on the
sophomore series ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' they're actually even more
outrageous than the characters they play.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, but it's true: After spending the
afternoon at a photo shoot with Mullally and Hayes, you realize
just how restrained their television performances really are.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Will &AMP; Grace'' finally finds its footing after a shaky
beginning to its second season, the characters of Jack McFarland
and Karen Walker have come into their own.
</P>
<P>
   Each started off as little more than a wacky caricature,
basically ids to the title characters' egos. But this season,
through some adroit writing, they have been fleshed out into fully
fledged sociopathic nightmares with the ability to sucker-punch
laughs out of an audience with relentless comic accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   They are the funniest duo working on television right now,
well-manicured hands down.
</P>
<P>
   As the photographer struggles to sweeten the photo set and give
it a Valentine's Day air, Mullally wanders over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love Valentine's Day,'' she says in a voice much
huskier and more thoughtful than her character's. ``I used to love
when we were little kids and we'd get valentines from people at
school _ I think that's so fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually collect antique valentines, from like the '20s and
'30s and the '10s and the Victorian era,'' she adds. ``I love old
valentines. Particularly from the '20s and '30s, though, there are
some cute ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes comes over to see what Mullally is saying, but screws up
his face on hearing the word ``Valentine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Valentine's Day is all about Saccharin for me _ it's all about
the chocolate,'' he says with a scowl, and then bursts out
laughing. ``Yes _ the sugar high!''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes and Mullally are fan favorites, more popular in many
circles than stars Eric McCormack and Debra Messing. Among ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' fans, a common refrain is, ``That show should be called
`Jack &AMP; Karen!'''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes should be flattered, but he bristles at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Will and Grace, you can't have a Jack and Karen,'' he
says, all trace of laughter draining out of his voice. ``It's very
simple, because a half-hour of Jack and Karen would last about half
a season _ it's too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice balance, and it has become an ensemble,'' he says.
``It has developed into an ensemble show because you realize that
these four people need each other in some way, and it's not about
two people per se.''
</P>
<P>
   All four of the show's leads are accomplished singers, and the
writers are currently exploring the possibility of a completely
musical episode. Mullally, the cast's most experienced vocalist, is
predictably delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should be an operetta,'' she says cheerily. ``No
talking at all, just singing!''
</P>
<P>
   Between shoots on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' Mullally has found time to
mount a one-woman musical show, entitled ``Sweetheart,'' twice in
the past year. She hopes to stage it again in Los Angeles, then
take it on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a really, really good director that is interested in
coming on,'' she says. ``That would be cool, because I really feel
like there are still some other places to go, creatively. It's
still not where I want it to be, but I really love it.''
</P>
<P>
   A CD of the show can be ordered online at
www.supremeprogram.com.
</P>
<P>
   Mullally and Hayes have nothing but praise for ``Will &AMP; Grace,''
the producers, McCormack and Messing. To all appearances there's
none of the jealousy that second bananas often nurse toward their
names-above-the-title colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But wait _ after a moment's thought, Hayes admits that one of
his co-stars really did get on his nerves. That would be ... the
now-departed Guapo the parrot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated that thing,'' he says, laughing. ``I would go down
with my arm to pick him up and he would peck at it. Parrots are
very temperamental, and they're only responsive to their trainers _
it takes a while for them to let other people in.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I had to work with it all week, and it senses if you're
scared. It kind of sensed that I was scared, so obviously it pecked
the s--t out of my arm! They put a little pad underneath my shirt,
so I just went for it. If you get close enough to their feet they
have no choice but to get on, so I just went for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my story,'' he says with a grimace, ``and I'm sticking
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's story lines include Jack's reunion with his father
and a continued exploration of Karen's sordid past, which began
with the revelation that she made a pornographic bondage flick in
her wild youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, honey, we shot footage for that,'' Mullally says, laughing
throatily. ``It was hilarious, but I guess it was too real or
something _ they never showed it on the show, you just heard it
coming out of the TV!''
</P>
<P>
   As its second season gathers steam, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is looking
to many experts like a ``Seinfeld'' or an ``X-Files,'' shows that
took a while to find their feet but then blossomed into classics.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, Mullally and Hayes will have more than a
little to do with it, a fact which television insiders are already
acknowledging _ none more prominently than ``Frasier's'' David Hyde
Pierce, one of television's most accomplished scene-stealers.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting his Emmy Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy
last year, the actor departed from the usual thank-yous, saying
perfectly earnestly that he didn't really deserve the award, which
should have gone to Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty amazing,'' Hayes says, still seemingly awed.
``This is my reaction for about 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   He lets his mouth hang wide open, his eyes glazing over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' he says after a moment. ``I was at
home in my shorts eating popcorn, like `Wow, he just said that
guy's name from `Will &AMP; Grace!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so weird, but it was really cool, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based correspondent for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
