<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BEHAVIOR: The Chemistry of Unchecked Aggression &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Children who show a propensity for extreme aggression at young
ages often have low levels of a hormone produced by the body during
times of fear or stress, researchers have found.
</P>
<P>
   Although the findings may appear counterintuitive, scientists at
the University of Chicago Medical Center believe they may mean that
some violent people simply experience less fear than normal people,
leading to unchecked aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests to us that there is something fundamentally
abnormal in one of the systems that responds to stress,'' said Dr.
Keith McBurnett, the child clinical psychologist, who was the lead
author of the study published in The Archive of General Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers were prompted to conduct the study of children,
ages 7 to 12, by an earlier study that found that the most
antisocial prison inmates were ones who had low levels of the
hormone cortisol. Scientists wanted to see if the difference could
be found earlier on, and so over a four-year period they studied a
group of 38 boys who had been referred to a psychiatric clinic for
disruptive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Through interviews, the boys, their families and even their
classmates (who were asked, among other things, to list the three
meanest boys in the class), the scientists gauged the children's
penchant for acts like cruelty to animals or starting fights. They
also took a series of measurements of cortisol from saliva samples.
The 12 children who showed consistently low levels of the hormone
also proved to be three times as aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether the cortisol deficiency is genetic,
environmental or even if it can be caused by stress on the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Although McBurnett said the results were unlikely to lead to
improved diagnosis or treatment any time soon, he said they gave
insight into what might be going wrong biologically with aggressive
children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTCOMES: Exploring Alzheimer's Early Roots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's remains a poorly understood disease, but one study
suggests a possible link between it and early life.
</P>
<P>
   One of the University of Washington researchers involved in the
study, Dr. Victoria M. Moceri, an epidemiologist, who presented the
research in the journal Neurology, said she was not claiming she
had found the cause of the debilitating illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many different causes of Alzheimer's disease,'' Dr.
Moceri said. ``One factor will not be unique to every person. There
are genetic risk factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware that early childhood factors play roles in a wide variety
of other illness, like cardiovascular disease, the researchers
reasoned that the same might be true for Alzheimer's. They were
especially interested because the areas of the brain showing the
first signs of the disease take the longest to develop, often
maturing well into adolescence, as crucial synaptic and other
connections are made.
</P>
<P>
   So they studied 700 members of a Washington HMO who were 60 or
over. Of those, 393 had Alzheimer's, and the rest showed no signs
of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers say they found a link between the patients with
Alzheimer's and the conditions of their childhood homes. For
example, those with more than five siblings, which the researchers
associated with lower income generally, at least when the subjects
were children, had 39 percent more cases of Alzheimer's than other
members of the group. Those who grew up in the suburbs, on the
other hand, were less likely to develop the illness than those who
grew up in poorer farm areas or more crowded cities, places where
children would be more likely to be exposed to infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAUSE &AMP; EFFECT: Little Things That Aggravate Asthma &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists may be no closer to explaining why the incidence of
asthma has been escalating in the United States, but a new study
confirms that a number of common indoor materials may be making the
situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine, part of the National Academy of
Sciences, has issued a report agreeing with those who believe that
factors like dust mites, secondhand smoke and allergens shed by
pets can play a role in making asthma worse for those who are
predisposed to the disease. The institute also recommended ways to
limit the irritants.
</P>
<P>
   More than 17 million Americans suffer from some form of
long-term respiratory disease, and since 1980, the prevalence of
asthma has increased by about 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In their report, scientists working for the medical institute
reviewed the literature about asthma to try to determine what
substances, if any, might cause or worsen it.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest consensus involved dust mites, the tiny creatures
existing in virtually every household.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concluded that, for dust mites, the evidence showed that
they were a cause of the disease,'' said Dr. Thomas A.E.
Platts-Mills, the allergy division chief at the University of
Virginia Health Sciences Center and a member of the institute
committee that prepared the report. ``But for the other allergens,
the evidence as not as clear.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATTERNS: For the Mentally Ill, a Gap in Cardiac Care &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mentally ill people who have heart attacks are less likely to be
offered the kind of treatment customarily available to other
patients, a new study reports.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Yale researchers wrote in The Journal of the
American Medical Association, patients with conditions like
schizophrenia are 32 percent less likely to undergo cardiovascular
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers came to their conclusions after reviewing the
cases of 113,653 patients 65 or older who had had heart attacks _
5,653 of whom were listed as mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   They found that those patients with mental disorders were 25
percent less likely to be given angioplasty to remove blockages, 32
percent less likely to have bypass surgery and 28 percent less
likely to have cardiac catheterization.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers were unable to establish a reason for the
disparity, but added that a variety of factors could be involved,
including difficulties dealing with disturbed patients and bias on
the part of the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies found differences in cardiovascular treatments
that appeared to have been related to the race and sex of the
patients, the Yale researchers noted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSEQUENCES: A Darker Down Side for Mondays &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A British medical journal has reported that Monday is the most
common day for the Scots to suffer fatal heart attacks, and
researchers believe that increased drinking during the weekend may
explain the death rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish scientists, who reported their findings in The
British Medical Journal, recounted a study they made of coronary
heart disease from 1986 to 1995, a period during which about
170,000 people died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   They found that Monday was the deadliest day for those under the
age of 50 who died outside of a hospital. The group accounted for
about 20 percent of the deaths in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Although they said other factors might play a role, they
theorized that drinking over the weekend could be one of the
causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possible link between binge drinking and deaths from
coronary heart disease has potentially important public health
implications and merits further investigation,'' the authors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On a brighter note: Monday night tipplers seemed to have less to
worry about, since Tuesday saw the lowest number of heart attack
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
