<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2012 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-TAXES-3TAKES-TEX     01-31 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXES-3TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME SONG, SECOND VERSE: A BUSH AND TAXES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush had ample reason to crow in
fall 1995, as the first laws carrying his signature began to take
effect: Welfare reform. A crackdown on juvenile offenders. Curbing
frivolous lawsuits. An education overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four for Four,'' a ``Texas Monthly'' headline had roared in
June, crediting Bush's determined adherence to his priorities as
the glue that held the various programs together.
</P>
<P>
   The new Republican governor said he'd like to use his political
capital to tackle a tougher issue: tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enough (capital) to do it on my own,'' Bush
cautioned. ``It's not a one-man job.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was prophetic. Two years later, Bush watched
helplessly as a parade of senators walked into his office and
declared their opposition to a compromise plan that would have cut
taxes for some but raised them for others.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the unpopularity of the legislation, one senator
said, ``The rest of you may want to drink poison Kool-Aid, but I'm
not,'' Bush writes in his autobiography, ``A Charge to Keep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One by one, they would not'' support the plan, Bush said. ``It
was most dramatic and most disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Bush's proposal for sweeping tax reform, which had
consumed him and the Texas Legislature for months, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, lawmakers voted to increase the standard homestead
exemption, saving the average homeowner about $140 on his or her
school property tax bill with no corresponding tax hikes. Many
complained later that local school tax increases wiped out those
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the bitter failure of the tax plan and the
overwhelming success of the 1995 initiatives provide a glimpse into
Bush's five years as governor of Texas. When sticking to his
popular core issues, he has built bipartisan coalitions,
compromised when necessary and generally enjoyed victory. But when
encountering more politically charged topics, such as tax reform
and last session's battle over hate crimes legislation, he has
tasted defeat or waited quietly on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree that the soaring Texas economy has kept Bush from
being severely tested in Austin. But his GOP supporters say they
are confident that he possesses the traits to succeed as president
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that he's had a trial by fire,'' said state Sen.
Bill Ratliff, the Republican lawmaker who helped craft the
education reforms that Bush touted on the campaign trail in 1994.
``I don't know that that's his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served in one session where we had to raise gas taxes and we
had to raise some franchise taxes and so forth, and it wasn't
pleasant. My assessment of him is, he can steel himself for
whatever has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   GOOD GOVERNOR, GOOD TIMES
</P>
<P>
   Accessible. Charismatic. Cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Those words come up again and again when legislators describe
Bush's tenure in the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Toby Goodman, R-Arlington, said he marvels at Bush's
approachability, even when the two have disagreed. He said Bush at
times unexpectedly popped into his office or into mundane committee
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd for a governor to go to a committee to sit in on
hearing. (Former Gov.) Ann Richards never did that,'' Goodman said.
``He's been real accessible to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, calls Bush a ``super nice guy'' who
``goes out of his way to make you feel like he knows you well.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maxey, the only openly gay member of the Texas Legislature,
said Bush has avoided firm stands on controversial issues such as
the hate crimes bill in 1999. Opponents have echoed the criticism
on the presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tends to run away from a lot of the nitty-gritty things
that could get somebody in trouble,'' Maxey said. ``He never got
out front or put his fingerprints on'' the hate crimes bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, describes Bush's gubernatorial
agenda as ``fairly modest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a rocket scientist to come in and try to give
a tax cut when you have a record surplus,'' he said. ``I'd say he
did a good job as governor during the best of times. The real
challenge is: What kind of leader will he be, if the people give
him the opportunity, during the worst of times?''
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINING THE RECORD
</P>
<P>
   As Bush crisscrosses the nation in pursuit of the Republican
presidential nomination, his record as governor of the second
most-populous state is under increasing scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   During his two terms, he has worked with three legislatures. In
five years, Bush:
</P>
<P>
   _Advocated between $6 billion and $7 billion in tax cuts and
signed legislation enacting about $2.7 billion. Though the cuts
were popular, some claim that the state property tax reductions
were negated by local tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   _Vowed to return ``local control'' to and increase
accountability in public schools, to end ``social promotions'' and
fight for limited private school vouchers. Vouchers failed, but a
compromise bill curtailing social promotion passed in 1999. The
1995 education bill, which included local control and
accountability revisions, passed largely intact.
</P>
<P>
   _Spearheaded efforts to curtail damages awarded from lawsuits,
advocated a voluntary approach to reducing pollution from factories
exempted from clean air laws, and helped scrap an unpopular auto
tailpipe testing program.
</P>
<P>
   _Pushed for and signed legislation requiring that parents be
notified of a minor's abortion, signed compromise legislation
toughening the state's welfare laws and accepted a bill to limit
cities' ability to sue gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax plan was the focus of Bush's second legislative
session.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was difficult because it required raising some taxes
and dissolving certain business exemptions to get the revenue
necessary to fund meaningful property tax reforms, lawmakers and
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's original proposal, many entities that do not pay
franchise taxes _ such as doctors, lawyers and accountants, who
typically organize as exempt partnerships _ would have been taxed.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for that and a higher general sales tax, property
taxes would have been lowered for both residential and commercial
property owners. The plan also used a $1 billion budget surplus to
achieve tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   Although some property-intensive companies liked the concept,
many politically powerful business interests did not, and they made
that known to lawmakers.
(MORE)
nn
</P>
<P>
   Tony Proffitt, a former aide to the late Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock
and now a private consultant with clients from both parties, said
many senators were taken aback by the new franchise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `We're going to put doctors in, we're going to put
lawyers in, we're going to put sole proprietors in.' They were
like, `Now, why are we doing this again?' '' Proffitt recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut effort was controversial from the beginning. The day
it was introduced, the bill's sponsor, Rep. Tom Craddick,
R-Midland, said he attached his name to the legislation as a
courtesy to Bush and declined to answer any questions about it.
</P>
<P>
   The structure of Bush's proposed ``business activity tax'' also
became contentious. The plan called for a 1.25 percent tax on
revenues over $500,000, minus the cost of goods and capital
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans alike called it an income tax _
something Texas has never had, and which polls show voters don't
want.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had vehemently opposed a state income tax, and he denied
that his plan would create one. But many lawmakers, including
Bush's own fellow Republicans, didn't buy that logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call a horse a donkey and it's still a horse. It was
an income tax,'' Goodman said. ``If it's a tax on gross revenue,
it's an income tax.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, a House committee dumped the plan and began
considering alternatives before settling on a bill that would cut
school property taxes by about half in many districts. But it
included more than $4 billion in increased tax revenue, raised in
part by the removal of many sales tax exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, quickly became problematic. Virtually every industry
whose exemption was to be removed, ranging from aviation fuel to
hair-cutting services, protested loudly. The compromise would also
have raised cigarette taxes by 25 cents a pack.
</P>
<P>
   The plan eventually passed a cautious House in the final weeks
of the session, although half the Republicans voted against it.
Bush watched the debate on closed-circuit TV and made a rare
appearance on the floor to offer his support.
</P>
<P>
   But that House vote was as close as Texas came to dramatically
restructuring taxes on Bush's watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something finally emerged from the House, it was not
agreeable to Bush's own Republican senators,'' Proffitt said. ``So
Bullock told him it was dead unless he could turn his own people
around.''
</P>
<P>
   He could not, and legislators settled for something Bullock had
proposed months earlier: an increased homestead exemption, paid for
with the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he sincerely thought this was a way, as a
conservative, to provide leadership,'' Proffitt said of Bush's
tax-cutting mission. ``Of course, it begs the point of, `well, did
he have enough experience or enough understanding of the
Legislature to cut this deal?'
</P>
<P>
   ``As it turns out, apparently he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   WORKING WITH DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   The problems of 1997 stand in stark contrast to the 1995
session, which Bush supporters cite as a model of bipartisan
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1994, it became clear that Bush was seriously gaining on
Richards among likely voters, despite polls showing the incumbent
Democrat with historically high approval ratings _ about 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that he would win, Bush decided to pay a visit to
Bullock, the crusty Democratic powerhouse of the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   After some small talk, Bullock cut to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very, very disappointed, and still am, in Ann
Richards,'' Bullock told Bush, according to the biography ``First
Son: George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty.'' ``If you're
going to be that kind of pussy-footing, headline-grabbing,
television-grabbing governor, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush replied: ``I'm going to work with you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of a close friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock crossed party lines to endorse Bush's re-election bid in
1998, and praised his prospects as a presidential candidate before
he died of lung cancer last year.
</P>
<P>
   That tendency to reach out to would-be enemies has served Bush
well, said many lawmakers, including those who have had policy
disagreements with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann probably had a staff that had more of a political agenda
of their own than Bush's staff at the beginning,'' said House
Speaker Pete Laney, D-Hale Center. ``Sometimes you've got to give a
little bit on your cause to make the system work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Laney credits Bush for making things ``work smooth from
the executive branch standpoint'' in 1995, the speaker said much of
what the governor advocated on the campaign trail was already in
the works in the Democrat-controlled Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tracked what we were doing pretty close,'' Laney said. ``I
think it was probably, one, good politics on his part, but it also
was probably what his focus groups were telling him what the public
was talking about. And if the Republicans hadn't been talking about
it, we probably wouldn't have been talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ART OF COMPROMISE
</P>
<P>
   Observers say Bush can legitimately claim success in each of the
four areas where he focused his energy in that first session. But
he also had to accept significant compromise and change.
</P>
<P>
   In reforming the way lawsuits are handled, the Legislature
approved caps on punitive damages of $750,000 _ higher than lots of
Republicans wanted but not high enough for many Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also approved changes in the way juvenile offenders
are handled. They lowered, for example, the age at which juveniles
can be tried as adults from 15 to 14 _ something Bush had strongly
advocated.
</P>
<P>
   In the welfare reform effort, Bush suffered a couple of serious
setbacks. He had fought hard for his campaign promise of capping
benefits to women who have more children while on welfare. But
Bullock didn't like the idea, and it didn't make it in the final
version.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill, which Bush called ``watered-down,'' also
did not contain the lifetime cap on cash welfare benefits that Bush
sought.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Bush's agenda was decentralizing public
education by giving local districts more control over their
programs and curriculum. Many now cite the law as at least
partially responsible for improved education statistics. (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, the Mount Pleasant Republican who chairs the Senate
Education Committee, said in July that the school district
accountability system put in place in 1993, before Bush took
office, is ``the major reason that things are improving.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview this year, Ratliff said the 1993 reforms
were a precursor to even more difficult reforms that occurred in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (1993 reform) only got us the foundation so that we could
take the controls off (in 1995,) the decontrol and removal of all
the mandates, and frankly between the two that was the harder
task,'' Ratliff said. ``I'm convinced we never could have put in
place the massive reforms we put in place in 1995 if it hadn't been
for his extraordinary support.''
</P>
<P>
   Both inside and outside the legislative arena, Bush also had a
hand in shaping the state's environmental policies, which have
since come under sharp attack. Houston has the nation's dirtiest
air and the federal government is coming down hard on local and
state government agencies with mandates to clean up the air in
North Texas and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush says the state is making progress toward cleaner air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas leads the nation in the reduction of toxic waste. We've
reduced industrial emissions,'' he said. ``I signed an electric
deregulation bill that was hailed by the Environmental Defense Fund
as one of the best bills in the country in terms of reducing
industrial pollution. ... We're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   That electric restructuring bill was signed into law during the
legislative session that began in January 1999. By that time, the
governor was well on his way to a presidential campaign, and the
eyes of the national media were on Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One aim of deregulation was to reduce emissions from electric
power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had for months been insisting on an industry-backed,
voluntary approach to reducing pollution from so-called
``grandfathered'' plants, which had for three decades been exempt
from modern clean-air laws.
</P>
<P>
   Many environmentalists were surprised, therefore, when he agreed
to a provision that made emission reductions mandatory for
grandfathered utility plants.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks earlier, Bush had also stunned environmentalists and
business leaders alike when he shifted his position on global
warming, saying he had been convinced the planet is indeed getting
hotter. He had said before that the science was inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   HATE CRIMES MELTDOWN
</P>
<P>
   As in 1995, the 1999 session also featured tightly organized
priorities that Bush advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not get everything he wanted _ a plan for
publicly funded private school vouchers failed, for example _ much
of his agenda passed.
</P>
<P>
   Among those items: business and property tax cuts, a law
requiring parental notification when minors receive abortions, and
a huge boost in state funding for education.
</P>
<P>
   One item that was not on Bush's priority list in 1999 _ or his
political radar screen, critics say _ was a bill strengthening laws
against hate crimes. It would prove to be a key moment in the 76th
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, the Houston Democrat who gives Bush high marks for
working with minority lawmakers like him, had named the bill in
honor of James Byrd Jr., the black man whose dragging death
horrified the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Before debate over the legislation ended, a bitter partisan
fight would temporarily shut down the Senate, threaten to kill off
dozens of unrelated measures and prompt President Clinton to urge
Bush's support for the measure during an Austin appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Bush) saw it coming,'' Ellis said. ``I don't
think they realized how that issue became such a hot button and had
the potential of blowing up the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not publicly stake a position and stayed out of the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood back and said I was going to analyze the bill once it
made it off the floor of the Senate. It never did,'' he said at an
appearance in Dallas shortly after the bill failed.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the sticking point was a provision that extended
protections to homosexuals. Ellis said some Republican senators
told him that if he dropped gays from the bill it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in this building understood the real issue
was the fear of a backlash by having the phrase `sexual
orientation' in the bill, that you'd have a backlash from the right
wing of the Republican Party,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied that the gay issue was the only sticking point,
telling reporters ``good people just couldn't agree.'' However,
Bush did say he was opposed to including homosexuals in the hate
crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   BIPARTISAN PARADE
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, state lawmakers disagree about whether Bush has had
a positive impact on Texas during his five years as governor.
</P>
<P>
   One view, held by his most vociferous detractors, is that Bush
takes credit for successes that were not of his making. They say
that the one time he abandoned that strategy _ in the 1997 tax
reform effort _ he faltered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush waits for Democrats to do the real work and make the
tough decisions, then he jumps out in front of the parade to make
it look like he's leading it,'' state Democratic Party Chairwoman
Molly Beth Malcolm said. ``When he tried to break out on his own
and be a real leader, he fell flat on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington, said the various reforms
that have passed on Bush's watch _ from tax cuts to education
rewrites _ would not have happened had it not been for the
governor's ability to build coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his career as governor he has been able to get a
substantial number of things passed and do it in a way where
everybody thought they were a party to it,'' Harris said. ``I think
his bipartisanship is his strength.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
