<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DMA-ART-TEX     01-31 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DMA-ART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEGAS TO PICASSO' EXPLORES THE ROLE OF PHOTOGRAPHY IN THE CREATIVE
PROCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plenty might have gone awry with ``Degas to Picasso: Painters,
Sculptors, and the Camera,'' the Dallas Museum of Art's sprawling
new exhibit opening on Tuesday. Its roster of 14 post-impressionist
and symbolist artists is a recipe for aesthetic overkill. Its
400-plus works risks being more exhausting than stimulating. And
the need for at least an hour to absorb the exhibit flies in the
face of what appears to be the current fad for narrowcast shows
catering to shrinking attention spans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is precisely the scope of ``Degas to Picasso'' that
serves as its greatest asset. From the grand tableaux of Edgar
Degas and Pablo Picasso, the majestic sculptures of Auguste Rodin,
to the smaller, more sensual works by Pierre Bonnard and Edouard
Vuillard, any novice gallery patron will have much to feast on. As
for the seasoned art aficionado, the show's sheer girth allows for
plenty of scholarly exploration of the role of photography in the
mysterious alchemy of creating a grand painting or sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of this exhibit made a fortuitous decision. They
shrewdly larded the show with plenty of choice artworks, as its
cerebral premise might have ponderously clouded over the
collection's beauty. The impetus for ``Degas to Picasso'' is very
much a curatorial one; the show is the ambitious brainchild of the
DMA's curator of European art, Dorothy Kosinski. Kosinski, the
editor of the exhibit's opulent catalog, is a passionately erudite
champion of the underappreciated role photography played at the
dawn of the 20th century in stimulating a slew of artists from
Paris to Prague.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the show is sometimes fuzzy in its focus, shifting
between photography as artistic influence or as individual art form
capable of exposing a Freudian inner landscape. Still, the exhibit
never wavers from its theme: introducing the camera as a new tool
in the hands of artists previously associated only with a brush or
chisel. So on the one hand there is the familiar beauty of Degas'
canvas ``Blue Dancers.'' On the other, it is paired with
photographer Eadweard Muybridge's lineup of dancers, all done in
poses implying that Degas made use of the shots to help him
choreograph his ballerinas.
</P>
<P>
   But _ and this is the exhibit at its most innovative _ there are
several photographs taken ``by'' Degas. The self-portraits, along
with a particularly inspired shot of Pierre-Auguste Renoir,
constitute a voyeur's dream, allowing the viewer access to Degas'
private photo album. It is particularly amusing to consider that
many great painters of Degas' echelon, though avid users of this
emerging tool, all sniffed at photography's claim to be art. That
the artists would continue to use the camera for their own art only
underscores their hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of ``Degas to Picasso'' is at its most literal in
the painting ``Wayfaring Poet,'' by Gustave Moreau. This 1891 work
is preceded by several preparatory studies. But unlike classic
preliminary work done in charcoal or pen and ink, Moreau used Henri
Rupp's photo ``Male Model Posing for `Wayfaring Poet.''' This shot
provided Moreau with almost the exact position of the arms, leg and
any other detail that Moreau used in his final canvas. The only
major difference is gender, as Moreau's ethereal poet is most
assuredly a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The forest of Rodin sculptures in the exhibit's third gallery is
alone worth the price of admission. It is difficult not to spend an
hour just basking in ``Shade, Adam,'' excerpted from Rodin's grand
``The Gates of Hell,'' or any one of the grandiose ``Balzac''
bronzes. The accompanying photos by, among others, Jean-Francois
Limet and Jacques-Ernst Bulloz are certainly serviceable homages to
Rodin's works, but they seem inconsequential compared with Edward
Steichen's sepulchral shots, especially one of the Balzacs titled
``The Silhouette, 4 a.m., Meudon.'' Here, Steichen transforms the
pompous Balzac figure into someone otherworldly.
</P>
<P>
   The Paul Gauguin section reveals that the exhibition has a more
ambitious agenda than first thought. Rather than just plumb the tie
between photography, painting and sculpture, the exhibit hopes to
dissect the flesh and bone of the artistic process. As the Gauguin
room makes clear, artistic inspiration don't always emerge from a
live scene. More likely, art can be midwifed from such varied
elements as photographs, plaster casts, wax imprints and
illustrated journals, all contributing to the final canvas.
</P>
<P>
   A series of Charles Spitz's sepia-hued photos of Tahitian
thatched huts and banana-toting natives clearly gave much artistic
grist for Gauguin's paintings. The photos take on the role of a
kind of intermediate veil or substitute truth. In ``The Large Tree
(Te raau rahi),'' the finely detailed bamboo logs echo the Spitz
photo, ``Tahiti: Indigenous Dance.'' And in a stunning bit of
replication, Gauguin's richly colored ``Melancholic (Faaturuma)''
calls on inspirational sources mimicking the pose used by Henri
Lemasson in his photographic study, ``Half-Tahitian Woman'' and
found in an anonymous reproduction of Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot's
``The Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   While this section of the exhibit clearly illustrates the
protean origins of artistic inspiration, it sometimes neglects to
delineate fully the bridge between one medium and another. Where
Gauguin is concerned, it is a stretch to connect the posed figures
on the photo of the ``Relief on Temple at Borobudur, Java'' and the
positioning of three of the figures in Gauguin's ``Change of
Residence.''
</P>
<P>
   The photographs of Milanese-trained sculptor Medardo Rosso's
wax-over-plaster figures actually transform the original
sculptures. All of the ridges and crevices of Rosso's ``The
Concierge (La Portinaia)'' seem to melt away in the photo of the
same work.
</P>
<P>
   One is pleasantly torn between Edvard Munch's grandiloquent oils
of ``Elisabeth Forster-Nietzsche'' or ``Female Nude (Anna)'' and
his scrapbook of photographic self-portraits. The photos show
Munch's fascination with how a Kodak box camera captures light and
shadow through under- and overexposure and with photographic
accidents producing inadvertent halos.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Munch's beautifully realized oil ``Friedrich
Nietzsche'' relied on such disparate source material as a postcard
of Nietzsche and a Hans Olde photograph of the philosopher. Yet the
exhibition falls short by not elaborating on which aspects of the
photograph's texture or lighting actually shaped Munch's resulting
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   What ``is'' made clear is that the photographs can actually
transform the artist from behind-the-scenes interpreter to upfront
actor. This is never more evident than in the work of Franz von
Stuck, where a photo of him posing with his wife duplicates the
exact position of John and Mary in his ``Crucifixion of Christ.''
Von Stuck's campy Kodak moment is easily as illuminating as his
painting.
</P>
<P>
   As for Constantin Brancusi, while the exhibit contains two
lovely sculptures including the maple, limestone and oak ``The
Sorceress,'' it is the series of self-portraits of the Romanian
artist at work, the proletarian craftsman caught in an inky studio
corner, that commands attention. And a Brancusi photo of ``The
Kiss,'' made roughly 12 years after he cast the original in
plaster, obscures the sculpture's original effect. The statue
delivers the embrace's passion, while the photo makes it clinical
and distant.
</P>
<P>
   The final Picasso section is, in this rich collection, perhaps
the most haphazardly presented. Though the viewer is rightfully
hypnotized by the two wondrous paintings _ ``Two Youths (Les
Adolescents)'' and ``Boy With a Pipe'' _ representing respectively
Picasso's rose and blue periods, there is a surfeit of pen-and-ink
studies, charcoal on paper and watercolors, in addition to
photographs, some of which are too tangential to Picasso's final
work to be germane.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is precisely this attic's box of influences in the
Picasso section that drives home the exhibition's ultimate raison
d'etre. While the camera's influence on the final art is manifestly
clear, the exhibition can't ignore the art's other conspiring
forces. Though uneven at times, this show should be commended for
attempting to disentangle the chaos of creativity, atomizing it
down to something as innocuous as a Kodak snapshot.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
