<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-OTHER-ELIANS-HNS &LR;      01-31 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTHER-ELIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PARENTS OF MISSING CHILDREN GRIEVE AS ELIAN GONZALEZ GETS
ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ A small child is taken by one parent,
survives a perilous journey to a foreign land and becomes the
center of an impassioned international custody dispute.
</P>
<P>
   No, the child is not Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban whose
name has become a household word since he arrived in the United
States on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, thousands of children are taken by one parent from
another and spirited across international boundaries never to be
heard from again. These stories are rarely told.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Luna, who lives near Austin, gazes daily at her missing
daughter's face in a photograph taped to the dashboard of her car.
But Luna doesn't see 7-year-old Laura on the television or read
about her in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been sitting here, waiting and waiting,'' said Luna, who
said she believes Laura was taken to Tamaulipas, Mexico, two years
ago by Luna's former husband, Joel Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comes up, and he (Elian) gets all the attention,'' she
said in frustration. ``With this little boy, they are doing
everything they can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that any child that's missing should get that
attention,'' Luna said.
</P>
<P>
   Other parents are equally befuddled or embittered by the hype
over Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Congress would do half as much as what they're trying
to do for Elian for the thousands of American children, including
Vivian Trout, who are overseas against their will,'' said John
Trout of Miami, whose 5-year-old daughter has been taken twice to
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   When Trout last saw his daughter, she was 2. He said he believes
she may be in Spain, where his estranged wife, Marina Lopez, has
relatives, or Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   But he admits he really doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just tearing me up,'' he said. ``I've gotten almost no
attention for my case, because all the newspapers and TV stations
tell me that there are too many parental kidnapping cases to put
the pictures in the paper or on TV. ... If there's too many of
them, doesn't that right there tell you there's a major problem?''
</P>
<P>
   While Elian Gonzalez's face has been burned into the national
consciousness by extensive news reports, the faces of these other
children linger in the shadowy recesses of the mind, stowed away
after glimpses at milk cartons, junk mail or posters at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are really angry and frustrated that their cases
haven't received this kind of attention,'' said Maureen Dabbagh,
president of PARENT, a Virginia Beach, Va., group that helps
parents of children abducted internationally by noncustodial
parents. ``And they're really confused as to why legislators would
work so hard, but not on their case.''
</P>
<P>
   Dabbagh said Congress has passed only one resolution in U.S.
history asking for the return of a child _ her daughter, Nadia,
from Syria in 1998. But the effort stopped there, and Dabbagh's
daughter remains lost to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet they're in this frenzy looking for loopholes to help
Elian,'' she said. ``Not only are they dissecting the law, but they
are willing to override it.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno last week that any intervention by
Congress in the Gonzalez case could cause problems later for
Americans trying to recover abducted children. Some lawmakers are
considering legislation that would grant the Cuban boy citizenship,
although many concede it is unlikely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we got into a situation where American children ended up
abroad and American parents wanted them returned and a foreign
country made them a citizen so they did not return, I don't think
the people in the United States would be very happy about it,''
Reno told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts warn that circumventing U.S. laws about
custodial jurisdiction and ignoring precedents in international law
to keep Gonzalez in this country could undermine the 20-year-old
Hague Convention, a treaty among 53 nations that establishes
procedures to find children and resolve custody cases.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty is meant to help all parents equally. Though Cuba did
not sign that agreement, the United States did, and some lawyers
feel that may be binding enough.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gonzalez case, it is not his mother, who died when their
boat capsized off the Florida coast, demanding to be awarded
custody and citizenship for Elian. It's relatives in Florida with
tenuous connections, wanting to keep the boy from his father in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress chooses to (grant Elian citizenship), they would
certainly be undermining the spirit of the Hague Convention. They
would be thumbing their noses at all its precepts,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Hilgeman, director of the San Jose, Calif.-based
Vanished Children's Alliance, another advocacy organization for
parents of internationally abducted children, said: ``If our
country doesn't respect the rights of other countries, we can't
expect that in reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is one of the countries with the worst recovery rate,
although it is a treaty signatory.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Fortney of Hollywood, Fla., knows all about that. She hasn't
seen her sons, Daniel, 8, and Christopher, 11, in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Though Fortney has legal custody of the boys, her numerous trips
to Mexico to recover them have been unsuccessful. She tried to get
a local news station interested in a trip she made to Mexico to
find the boys in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fortney and 14 Mexican law enforcement officials tried to
recover her sons from school, but the principal locked them out,
stalling them until Fortney's ex-husband, Juan Munguia, could file
another court challenge, partially typed on a typewriter on a card
table outside the school gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a circus,'' said Fortney, who left hours later without
even seeing her sons. But the news station wasn't interested in the
story without videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, how much has been made of the fact that these
grandmothers went back to Washington, D.C., without seeing their
grandson?'' Fortney asked resentfully, referring to reports about
Elian's two grandmothers' early attempts to see him before a
meeting was ordered last week by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service. ``I mean, here's a mother, and because that camera wasn't
rolling, nobody cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has spurred public protests in the United States and
Cuba, legislative subpoenas, congressional banter and unending news
reports to help catapult the issue of international parental
abduction into the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   But to parents with empty houses, every click of the camera
shutter on Elian marks another heartbeat separating them in time
from their missing children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe his case is going to help anybody else in this
situation,'' said Paul Fedynich, an Orlando, Fla., resident whose
three children were taken in 1998. He said he believes they are in
Mexico with his ex-wife, Linda Marie Fedynich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everybody's going to get tired of hearing about this
issue,'' Paul Fedynich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
