</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-EUROPE (Paris) _ In an unprecedented move to control the
internal politics of a member nation, the European Union warned
Monday that its 14 other members would diplomatically isolate
Austria if the anti-immigrant Freedom Party led by Joerg Haider
enters a coalition government. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Three Israeli soldiers were killed
in southern Lebanon on Monday as Party of God guerrillas continued
to escalate their low-level warfare during a lull in peace
negotiations between Israel and Syria, Lebanon's powerbroker. The
guerrilla forces attacked an Israeli army post just as Akel Hashem,
the deputy commander of the Israeli-backed South Lebanese Army, was
being buried. Hashem was assassinated on Sunday. In response,
Israeli planes conducted attacks on Party of God, or Hezbollah,
targets in Lebanon. But in Israel, the emotionalism of the Lebanon
issue resurfaced as bereaved parents returned to the airwaves and
political leaders debated what to do next. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-BRITAIN (London) _ A judge issued a tough-worded
judgment on Monday supporting the British government's decision to
release Gen. Augusto Pinochet and let him return home to Chile, but
Belgium held up any final action by lodging an appeal against the
ruling. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-DEATH-PENALTY (Springfield, Ill.) _ Citing a ``shameful
record of convicting innocent people and putting them on death
row,'' Gov. George Ryan of Illinois on Monday halted all executions
in the state, the first such moratorium in the nation. Ryan, a
moderate Republican, noted that 13 men had been sentenced to death
in Illinois since 1977 for crimes they did not commit, before
ultimately being exonerated and freed by the courts. The ruling was
hailed by opponents of the death penalty, who said the mistaken
convictions discovered in Illinois were common throughout the
United States. Some 85 people have been found innocent and released
from death row since 1977, when the Supreme Court allowed the
reinstatement of the death penalty. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NH-VOICES (Peppermint Corner, N.H.) _ In random interviews with
dozens of voters across this state on the eve of the nation's first
primary, New Hampshirites said they were pleased with the choice of
candidates and heartened by what they described as an unexpectedly
uplifting discourse. And, more than ever, they said they were
convinced that this state serves a valuable role in inspecting, and
even educating, the Democrats and Republicans who have put
themselves forward to be president of the United States. By Richard
L. Berke and Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NH-MCCAIN (Nashua, N.H.) _ Leading in the polls on primary eve,
this is Sen. John McCain's big moment. By Alison Mitchell. (1100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK REGION
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-BOSTON-RAIL (Undated) _ Amtrak unveiled its new fully
electrified service between Boston and New York on Monday, but the
first day of the service, which aims to reduce the ride between the
cities to three hours, was marred by technical problems that seemed
symbolic of the problems the company has faced in the $2 billion
high-speed rail venture. By Jayson Blair.
</P>
