<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-OPTICAL-BLACK-HOL     01-31 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OPTICAL-BLACK-HOLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMULATING A BLACK HOLE IN A LAB 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers believe that nothing, not even light, can escape
after it has been captured by the powerful gravity of a black hole
in space and goes, so to speak, down the cosmic drain.
</P>
<P>
   Two physicists in Sweden have now theorized that the same
strange effects might be produced in laboratories on Earth, though
not with gravity. Instead, they suggest, light itself could be
gobbled up by swirling gases and fluids that look suspiciously like
water going down an ordinary drain.
</P>
<P>
   Called an optical black hole, this laboratory creation would
rely on the recent discovery that in certain substances, light can
be slowed from its usual 186,000 miles a second to a pace well
below a highway speed limit. In that sort of fluid medium,
according to the physicists, a very fast vortex would also have a
point of no return for light rays that came too close to its
center, or ``eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Light that passed inside the boundary, which in gravitational
black holes is called the event horizon, would be inexorably
dragged into the eye of the vortex, like an unfortunate flea
carried down a bathtub drain no matter how desperately it
struggles. And far from being a mere curiosity, such an experiment
might let laboratory physicists study the properties of real black
holes in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mathematical analogy between the two,'' said Dr. Ulf
Leonhardt, a physicist at the Royal Institute of Technology in
Stockholm and the University of Saint Andrews in Scotland.
``Therefore, the effects you expect to occur for gravity, you would
also expect'' in the vortexes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A paper on the theory by Leonhardt and a colleague, Paul
Piwnicki of the Royal Institute of Technology, was published in the
Jan. 31 issue of the journal Physical Review Letters.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that moving matter can drag light goes all the way back
to Augustin Jean Fresnel, a French physicist who lived around the
turn of the 19th century. Light moves more slowly in any
transparent medium, like water or air, than it does in a vacuum.
But Fresnel realized that any such medium could, in effect, exert a
weak pull on light and change its speed by moving, too.
</P>
<P>
   At about the midpoint of that century, another Frenchman, Armand
Fizeau, actually showed that light moved slightly more slowly
against the flow of water than with it.
</P>
<P>
   But those changes amount to a small fraction of the overall
speed of light, so that the consequences are ``not very exciting,''
Leonhardt said. More interesting possibilities had to await the
testing of materials that could slow light much more, and therefore
were able to exert a stronger pull when they were moving.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking such experiments were performed last year by
Dr. Lene Vestergaard Hau of Harvard University, Dr. Stephen E.
Harris of Stanford University and their colleagues. They used an
ultracold cluster of sodium atoms called a Bose-Einstein condensate
to slow light to a speed of about 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Related experiments have been done in a vapor of rubidium atoms,
Leonhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Leonhardt and Piwnicki suggest that experimenters
create vortexes in those substances while shining laser light
through them. They calculate that the black hole effect could take
over in small vortexes moving at the outer edge of the effective
black hole with speeds of from hundreds of yards per second to just
a few feet per second, depending on how much further progress is
made on the slow-light substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that now there will be a laboratory-scale, even
simple, benchtop way of making predictions about what the
astronomers may then go out and try to verify,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   One conceivable laboratory measurement of black hole properties
will certainly not be made by astronomers anytime soon. That
property is a kind of faint radiation that the British cosmologist
Dr. Stephen W. Hawking predicted should be emitted from just
outside the event horizon of a real black hole.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Hawking emissions would be obscured by more powerful
radiation sources in space, it would be difficult to observe with
astronomical instruments. But Leonhardt hopes that optical black
holes will reveal Hawking radiation, though he cautions that he has
not yet managed to calculate how intense it would be in the
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe by thinking about this analogy, one can get a better
understanding of Hawking radiation,'' Leonhardt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
