<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2035 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-NOVA-SPI &LR;      01-31 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOVA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOVA' SERIES REVEALS SOME SECRETS, OTHERS REMAIN A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like any 9-year-old, I love to throw things. Small rocks across
water. Big rocks into water. Pine cones at tree trunks. Nerf balls
at wastebaskets. Socks into a hamper from 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Could be a genetic thing. Or, as my wife suspects, just a
pathetic thing. I don't care. After viewing ``Medieval Siege'' I
want my own trebuchet. And I want it now, please.
</P>
<P>
   A trebuchet is a slingshot on steroids, a gunpowderless cannon
that can hurl a projectile the length of two football fields and
hit a wide receiver on the numbers. Said wide receiver would then
be listed as questionable for next week's game, but anyone trying
to catch a 250-pound stone ball is probably questionable to begin
with.
</P>
<P>
   I digress.
</P>
<P>
   King Edward I of England _ the bad guy from ``Braveheart,''
remember? _ also liked to throw things. A bellicose sort who went
about the countryside alternately building and destroying castles,
Edward was a cagey military strategist who usually won, Mel Gibson
notwithstanding, because he had better war toys.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 13th century, when castle walls were getting thicker
than a linebacker's neck, Edward ordered up some trebuchets and
made the Scottish skittish. The rest, as they say, is history,
except no one bothered to save a blueprint of a trebuchet for those
of us who might want to fling boulders in our spare time.
</P>
<P>
   That's where ``Nova'' comes in. Armed with a limited budget but
limitless curiosity, the PBS series that makes science more fun
than recess created two medieval catapults on the strength of
sketchy information and healthy conjecture. The result is
installment one of a wonderful new ``Secrets of Lost Empires''
package on ``Nova'' _ an idea that began in 1992 with ``This Old
Pyramid'' and blossomed in 1997 into the first ``Secrets'' series,
which explored how the ancients built Stonehenge in England, the
obelisks in Egypt, intricate temples in the land of the Incas, and
huge awnings over the Colosseum in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the medieval trebuchet, this latest ``Secrets''
tackles obelisks again (they didn't get it right the first time),
along with the enormous statues of Easter Island, incredibly
ingenious Roman baths, and the startlingly beautiful rainbow
bridges of 12th-century China, all without benefit of blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the specials, airing on Tuesdays before the regularly
scheduled ``Nova,'' emphasizes the exclusive use of tools and
techniques available to the ancients. Because of time constraints,
most of the construction teams ended up cheating a bit _ it's
amazing what a little silicone caulk will do in a pinch _ but the
point of ``Secrets of Lost Empires'' is not lost because ``Nova''
cut corners. Rather, it is enhanced. Turns out that the knowledge
of ancient civilizations, sometimes lost for centuries before being
rediscovered by others, is a terrific teacher _ and a great
humbler.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the five-week miniseries:
</P>
<P>
   `Medieval Siege'
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night
</P>
<P>
   This one's the cream of the crop for those who like to throw
stuff. The efforts of two teams trying to replicate a medieval
catapult encapsulates the best of ``Nova'': scientifically
satisfying, historically rewarding, and just plain fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   `Pharaoh's Obelisk'
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 8
</P>
<P>
   After getting maybe a little too technical in trying to emulate
the Egyptians' knack for pointing massive, one-piece granite
needles skyward, the ``Nova'' team realizes that simplicity is
probably a better approach than a complex system of weights,
counterweights and pivots. Either way, the abilities of the ancient
builders is something to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   `Easter Island'
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 15
</P>
<P>
   Native legend has it that the mammoth stone heads of Easter
Island, called moai, walked from the quarry to their sacred
platforms scattered about the island. A team of archaeologists,
engineers and architects tries to suggest otherwise, but despite
some success in moving a modern version of a moai, the legend seems
like a fairly reasonable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   `Roman Bath'
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 22
</P>
<P>
   Probably the least satisfying of the ``Secrets of Lost Empires''
miniseries, ``Roman Bath'' bogs down because the construction of a
mini-bathhouse in Turkey uses construction techniques that are
essentially similar to modern methods. While certainly a tribute to
the Romans' engineering savvy, it's a lot like watching your
neighbor install a spiffy new spa.
</P>
<P>
   `China Bridge'
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 29
</P>
<P>
   Though not available for screening, this episode promises to
blend science and art in a refreshing way. Reproduced throughout
China, a scroll painting of an intricately woven rainbow bridge of
the 12th-century Song Dynasty is as ubiquitous there, ``Nova''
says, as the Mona Lisa is in the West. But how the bridge was built
is a mystery because the elegant wooden arch ultimately succumbed
to the elements, and no plans of the rainbow bridge exist today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
