<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-31 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR-COOLED HORSEPOWER  
 PLANT PROTECTOR  
 FIREBALL OVER YUKON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any animal that loses its cool during physical activity is in
for trouble. Specifically, the brain cannot be allowed to overheat,
or irreversible damage may occur. Most animals have evolved some
sort of system for regulating brain temperature during exercise,
but how horses do it has been a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, veterinary researchers in Canada have discovered that, like
an old VW engine, a horse is air-cooled.
</P>
<P>
   A horse's internal carotid arteries, which supply blood to the
brain, are enveloped by a pair of air-filled pouches associated
with the upper respiratory tract. By using tiny implanted
thermometers, researchers found that these structures, known as
guttural pouches and containing about half a pint of air, cool the
carotid arteries when the horse exercises.
</P>
<P>
   During cantering, for example, the temperature of the blood in
the arteries before it passes through the pouches climbs about one
and a half degrees over five minutes. The arterial temperature
measured on the brain side of the pouches, however, actually drops
slightly, the heat having been transferred to the air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plants do not get much exercise, but they can have overheating
problems as well. That is, too much sunlight can cause oxidation
and death of cells, bleaching a plant like a cheap T-shirt left on
a clothesline for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Most plants have a way of dissipating excess solar energy as
heat, but the mechanism by which this happens has not been well
understood. Now, Swedish and American researchers have discovered
that a specific protein plays a major role.
</P>
<P>
   The protein, called PsbS, is one of many involved in the
photosynthesis process. The researchers, in experiments with
Arabidopsis, a weed with a relatively small and simple genome,
found that mutant plants without the protein could not handle too
much sun, developing bleached, dead spots. When the scientists
reintroduced the gene that produces PsbS, the resulting plants were
able to dissipate the excess energy.
</P>
<P>
   The work, reported in Nature, also suggests that some plants
synthesize more of the protein as they are exposed to excess
sunlight on a daily basis. So PsbS may play a role in helping some
plants become acclimated as their environment changes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Yukon in northwestern Canada might have
wondered if United States-Russian friendship had come to a
screaming end in mid-January, when a huge, and loud, fireball
lighted up the early morning sky. It was not a nuclear warhead (or
even the latest antimissile missile test) but rather a meteor, one
of the most spectacular to be seen in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The meteor, which exploded at an altitude of about 80,000 feet
with a force estimated to be equal to about two or three thousand
tons of TNT, was detected by U.S. military satellites and caused
two sonic booms heard across the Yukon and into Alaska. It left a
contrail that lingered for about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, a foul odor was detected for several hours after
the explosion. A witness said the fireball lighted up mountains
about 10 miles away as bright as daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Jan. 18 event, NASA sent a high-altitude
research plane into the region to collect samples from the
lingering plume of particulates left by the meteor. Any dust or
rock particles recovered may give a hint as to the origin of the
meteor.
</P>
<P>
   The plane also took reconnaissance photos of the area, which is
largely unpopulated, in hope of discovering any impact crater or
other damage on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Any damage found is likely to be slight compared with the
devastation caused by another spectacular aerial blast, in Siberia
in 1908. That explosion, thought to have been caused by a meteor
with a 100-foot diameter, was equivalent to 20 million tons of TNT
and incinerated trees in a 9-mile radius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
