<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l BC-EXERCISE-STRETCH-SPI &LR;      01-31 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXERCISE-STRETCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRETCHING: THE TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY E. NEVALA  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Double-knot your running shoes, drink water and stretch _ that's
the long-recommended routine to start an injury-free workout.
</P>
<P>
   But a study in the journal of the American College of Sports
Medicine this month says stretching before exercise doesn't prevent
muscle pulls and strains.
</P>
<P>
   And if stretching is performed wrong, the study says it may hurt
the body more than help it.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries can happen whether or not you stretch before exercise,
said Rod Pope, the study's lead author. The Australian army
physiotherapist found no difference in injury rates among 2,660
Australian soldiers, some of whom stretched before training, while
others didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stretching was assumed to work in preventing injury, but there
was no evidence to suggest it did,'' said Pope. ``We are telling
the army to no longer stretch, but it's a long tradition and
traditions die hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope's research follows a study published last year by Dr. Ian
Shrier, of Quebec's Centre for Clinical and Community Studies, who
found that ``stretching before exercise is more likely to cause
injury than to prevent it.''
</P>
<P>
   His findings, which appeared in the Clinical Journal of Sport
Medicine, were based on 12 articles, all grounded in clinical and
scientific research. Four suggested stretching before exercise is
beneficial, three called it detrimental and five suggested no
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the only studies to suggest that stretching before
exercise might prevent injuries (also) included a warm-up
program,'' Shrier reports. ``All other studies suggested that
stretching before exercise does not benefit or may be
detrimental.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-area exercise authorities aren't ready to dump
stretching, and some say it is an absolute necessity for some
professions, such as ballet. But in general, warm-up exercises _
combined with, or instead of, stretching _ may be even more
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still recommend warming up,'' said John O'Kane, team
physician for the University of Washington intercollegiate athletic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Muscles are like rubber, he explained. Warming up, or
encouraging blood flow through the tissue, helps muscle loosen and
operate more efficiently and effectively. A light jog before a run
or an easy swim before laps can warm the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ideal situation is to do a gentle warm-up and after five to
10 minutes, when the muscles are warm, do some stretching,'' O'Kane
said. ``If you don't have time for that, I'd say the warm-up is
more important than stretching.''
</P>
<P>
   He added a cautionary note about stretching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a morning runner, you don't want to hit the floor
cold, stretch and then go running,'' he said, because jerking tight
muscles with a stretch can trigger pulls and strains.
</P>
<P>
   O'Kane's preference for a warm-up over just stretching is good
news for Cindy Martin, 48, who hates stretching but does warm-ups.
Her weekly exercise routine includes five hours of swimming, three
hours of weight-lifting, 12 miles of running, plus weekend skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be the poster girl for never stretching,'' said
Martin, of Seattle. ``I'm so inflexible because I don't stretch, so
when I do it, it hurts. So I'm like, `Oh, forget it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, it's boring. I usually start out running slowly and
figure that will take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian physiotherapist Pope stresses that it is important to
stretch tight muscles and he suspects that stretching after
exercise could be beneficial, although this has not been
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Some physical therapists cringe when exercisers shrug off
stretching. Exercise science suggests that when stretching is done
correctly, athletes who make it part of their training prevent or
reverse the loss in joint range-of-motion that occurs with aging.
</P>
<P>
   This encourages a limber body longer and later in life.
</P>
<P>
   Therapists also say stretching improves athletic performance by
building stronger muscles and flexibility. This can, say, shave
strokes off golf handicaps or add height to soccer kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my work with athletes, I've seen that a good, stretched-out
muscle responds much better than a muscle that's all knotted up,''
said sports medicine physical therapist Lori Sabado at the
University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sabado recommends stretching to her patients. ``Years of
anecdotal evidence can't be wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For baseball pitchers, gymnasts and other athletes whose sports
require noodlelike flexibility, stretching before a game or
performance isn't optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as an inflexible, unstretchable
ballerina,'' said Marjorie Thompson, therapy and conditioning
program coordinator with the Pacific Northwest Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   If increased flexibility is your goal, O'Kane said the best time
to stretch may be after your workout, when the muscles are warm
from blood churning through the tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Sabado said people need to be careful if they stretch. ``You're
better off not doing it if you do it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   While bending over, grabbing her ankles and bouncing a hamstring
stretch, Sabado said, ``this form is bad. I've seen kids hurt
themselves by bouncing like this, which can strain muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain while stretching indicates improper technique. Athletic
trainers, physical therapists, and aerobic and yoga instructors can
advise on correct positions.
</P>
<P>
   Whether stretching is good or not, it appears fixed in our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Toddlers nationwide flex tiny calves and biceps through
Stretch-n-Grow classes, while 90-year-olds attempt to beat
arthritis and keep hamstrings limber through toe touches in
retirement-home programs.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching gimmicks _ from Stop 'n Stretch videos to the Helping
Hand Stretch-o-cizer _ stock the shelves. A ministry in Memphis
stretches parishioners arms, legs and necks along with their
spirits. ``Maintaining our health depends on the regular nurturing
of both body and spirit,'' said chaplain Kim Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle area Microsoft employees flock to yoga classes seeking
relief for computer-cramped necks, shoulders and backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are some of our biggest clients,'' said Mona Renner,
assistant director of Yoga Centers in Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   And humans aren't the only ones who stretch. ``Some trainers
have begun to stretch and warm up their dogs prior to
competition,'' said Robert Gillette, a senior research fellow in
veterinary sports medicine at Auburn University in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Still not convinced that stretching works? Anxious to simply get
sweaty? Maybe you should take the gazelle as your role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certain,'' Gillette said, ``that the Thompson's gazelle
does not take the time to warm up before running away from the
cheetah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
