<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PHONE-RATES01-COX     01-31 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-RATES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONSUMER, BUSINESS GROUPS SEEK LOWER MONTHLY PHONE FEES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY JR.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A coalition of business and consumer groups urged
the federal government Monday to reduce monthly telephone fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern stems from the fact that since Congress passed the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, consumers have seen more than $4
billion in fees,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of Consumers
Union. The act was supposed to reduce telephone users' costs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The group called for cutting subscriber line charges on
consumers' and business' phone bills by $1 a month, eliminating a
$1.50 monthly federal access charge and cutting other special
access charges many businesses pay. Telephone users would save
nearly $8 billion over the next four years, Kimmelman said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition includes the Texas Office of Public Utility
Counsel, the National Retail Federation, AARP, Consumer Federation
of America and others.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it would will ask the Federation Communications
Commission to adjust a telephone access fee reform proposal
submitted by an industry group known as CALLS, for Coalition for
Affordable Local and Long Distance Service. Members of CALLS
includes Bell Atlantic, BellSouth, AT&AMP;T, GTE, SBC and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   It said the CALLS plan fails to utilize the limited cost-cutting
mechanism in FCC rules and adds $2 billion a year in new fees to
phone bills, the coalition said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's plan is misleading, responded John Nakahata, a
CALLS spokesman. He said contrary to the consumer groups' claim,
CALLS would not add any new charges, and in fact would save
consumers in every income category $5.8 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Nakahata also noted that the telephone fees are an important
source of funding for telephone service for rural and low-income
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (coalition's) plan does not guarantee universal service,
fails to strengthen protection for low-income consumers, does
nothing to promote competition and choice and strands rural
consumers on the wrong side of the digital divide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if you could construct the phone network for
free, but that's not the case,'' Nakahata said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Moir, who represents the International Consumers
Association, said CALLS' $2.50 per line monthly fee may not seem
like much to large companies, but it adds up when major
universities, for example, have 30,000 phone lines. He said the
universities are forced to increase tuition and other fees to pay
for the extra phone charges.
</P>
<P>
   The phone companies have decreased long-distance charges, but
the low per-minute rates cited in television ads are misleading,
said Mark Cooper of Consumer Federation of America. He said
consumers are not aware that they are paying up to $15 per month in
line charges ``before you place a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
