<HEADER>
A2062 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FIRE-CHEATGRASS-A     01-31 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FIRE-CHEATGRASS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEADLY DANCE ON THE STEPPES OF NEVADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JON CHRISTENSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. _ Fire and cheatgrass, a fire-loving invasive annual
grass from central Eurasia, are locked in a deadly dance that is
steadily turning the sagebrush steppes of the Great Basin desert
into a wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the government is spending a desperate effort to
reverse a cycle of fire and weed invasion in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, dry lightning storms set off wildfires that raced
across cheatgrass-infested range land and blackened a record 1.8
million acres in northern Nevada. By next summer, experts warn,
much of the burned area will be covered with cheatgrass and the
stage will be set for even bigger fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're to the point of almost no return,'' said Robert V.
Abbey, state director of the federal Bureau of Land Management in
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   While federal land managers are deliberately burning forests and
grasslands in many parts of the country as a force for restoration,
fire is naturally coming more frequently to the Great Basin. But
here, fire is in league with weeds. Moreover, while the spread of
invasive species is considered a threat nationwide, it appears that
the best tool for fighting the spread of fire and cheatgrass is to
introduce even more exotic grasses and shrubs from Eurasia, the
original home of cheatgrass.
</P>
<P>
   So this winter the government is spending $43 million to get
grass and shrub seeds on the burned land before cheatgrass takes
over. Officials said it was the biggest single post-fire
rehabilitation plan ever undertaken by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of trucks loaded with 50-pound sacks of seeds have
arrived in Nevada in recent months on a staggered schedule because
there is not enough warehouse space for the 5.4 million pounds of
seeds. Pilots have been flying over the burned land dumping seeds.
Crews have been using farm equipment to sow seeds and turn the
soil. Volunteers have been gathering seeds from native plants like
sagebrush.
</P>
<P>
   But because of a shortage of seeds, money, equipment and
workers, this effort will cover only about a third of the burned
land this year. Native plants made up less than a third of the
seeds planted after the fires and only 1 percent was sagebrush.
</P>
<P>
   So the Bureau of Land Management is proposing to spend up to $25
million a year on a Great Basin Restoration Initiative to try to
stop the cycle and restore the grasslands. ``We're going to spend
the money anyway,'' Abbey said. Although restoration will cost $32
to $80 an acre, Abbey said it would help reduce firefighting costs.
</P>
<P>
   If the restoration effort does not succeed, the Great Basin
could join the ranks of the world's bleakest deserts, warned Dr.
James Young, a scientist with the federal Agriculture Research
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Young said that what was once an unbroken ocean of sagebrush was
now ``an endangered landscape.'' Cheatgrass has already taken over
a third of the 19 million acres of sagebrush grasslands in Nevada,
he said, and more than 100 million acres across the West.
</P>
<P>
   Vast steppes once covered with tall bunch grasses interspersed
with pungent-smelling, gray-green sagebrush shrubs are increasingly
covered with a uniform carpet of short blond cheatgrass. Cheatgrass
has a foothold in nearly all the sagebrush, Young said, and it
dominates much of land that has burned in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that cheatgrass arrived in North America in
the mid-1800s as a contaminant in grain seeds from Europe. Farmers
called it cheatgrass because it lowered their yields. Its spiky
seeds easily stick in hind and hair, so cheatgrass steadily
expanded with herds.
</P>
<P>
   An annual that puts all its energy into seeds, cheatgrass easily
outcompetes native perennial grasses and sagebrush when the land is
disturbed. In winter and early spring, cheatgrass sends roots deep,
monopolizing water and nutrients. And it sets seeds early in the
summer, then dries to an explosive tinder.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, fires were smaller and lower in intensity than
those today. The frequency in any given patch of healthy sagebrush
ranged from once every 11 years, which is just long enough for
sagebrush to get established, to as seldom as every 200 years. By
contrast, cheatgrass-dominated lands burn every two to five years,
giving sagebrush no chance to come back.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Sagebrush is especially vulnerable to the frequent fires that
cheatgrass fuels. Sagebrush usually dies after a fire. Its seeds
may survive, but when they compete with cheatgrass, they lose. And
sagebrush's tiny seeds fall right around the plant, so stands of
sagebrush expand slowly.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is not just sagebrush, and a landscape that might
already seem bleak and forbidding, but a whole ecosystem that is
changing rapidly as cheatgrass spreads. Some species benefit
temporarily, like mice that feast on abundant cheatgrass seeds.
</P>
<P>
   But many animals are left bereft, without a home. The sage
grouse, for example, scientists say, seems to be headed for the
endangered species list. Small birds like the sage thrasher, small
mammals like the pygmy rabbit, and a host of reptiles like the
sagebrush lizard all depend on sagebrush for shelter. &UR;  &LR;  ``When the
sagebrush goes, the structure goes, and when the structure goes,
most of the vertebrates go,'' said Dr. Peter Brussard, co-director
of the Nevada Biodiversity Initiative, a federally financed effort
to document and monitor the state's ecological health. And many of
these animals will never return to the burned land if it turns to
cheatgrass.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Nevada Division of Wildlife said last
summer's fires burned habitat that was used by close to 40 percent
of the state's wildlife, including pronghorn antelope, elk and mule
deer. In some areas of the state that burned in previous years, the
mule deer population has fallen in direct proportion to the loss of
sagebrush.
</P>
<P>
   So far the main strategy for fighting the spread of cheatgrass
has been to use other exotic species from Eurasia, like crested
wheatgrass, a perennial grass, and forage kochia, a shrub. These
plants are more resistant to fire and grazing than their native
counterparts, so they can compete with cheatgrass. They also
provide forage for livestock and big game wildlife like deer.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain, said Young: The West will look more
like the Eurasian deserts, at least in the short term. Using these
exotic species is an ``ecological Band-Aid,'' he said, ``but it's
the best thing we've got now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists doubt that native grasses and sagebrush will
ever come back and compete with the introduced species.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you end up with at best is replacement of one introduced
species with another,'' said Dr. Richard Mack, a professor of
biological sciences at Washington State University, who has studied
the spread of cheatgrass across the West. ``Restoration doesn't
mean sowing non-native species over large areas of the
intermountain West. If you're going to restore, you're going to put
back what was there, and that would mean the native communities
that were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Monsen, a botanist with the U.S. Forest Service's Rocky
Mountain Research Station in Provo, Utah, said there was a middle
ground in the debate. Scientists at the research station have been
searching for ways to combat cheatgrass invasions in the West since
the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a shift now to try to restore the native communities
and to move away from introduced species,'' said Monsen, who has
worked on projects around the West that have succeeded in restoring
the key species in sagebrush grasslands. What is needed, he said,
is both an immediate intervention to halt the spread of cheatgrass
and a long-term restoration effort to bring back native plants.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that huge fires like those that burned 1.8
million acres in the Great Basin last summer quickly swallow up all
the available native seeds and resources for restoration, and still
much of the land remains vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big concern in Nevada,'' said Monsen, ``is that if they're
not successful in seeding, the next burn will be five or 10 times
that size.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
