<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CHILD-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      01-31 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHILD-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDY OF WHAT PUTS CHILDREN IN HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asthma and infections like pneumonia and bronchitis accounted
for more than half the hospitalizations of children from 1 to 4
years old in a major study of children's health in the United
States. The research, the most comprehensive in a decade, also
found that the conditions were responsible for nearly a third of
hospital stays for 5- to 9-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Among 15- to 17-year-olds, 3 out of 10 hospitalizations were for
pregnancy or childbirth. And for younger adolescents, depression
and other mental disorders were the main diagnoses, accounting for
more than 9 percent of hospital stays for 10- to 14-year-olds,
compared with less than 2 percent for adults.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the United States Agency for Healthcare
Research and Quality, a research arm of the Department of Health
and Human Services, is in the current issue of The Journal of the
Ambulatory Pediatrics Association. The wide-ranging study culled
1996 statistics, the latest available, from parents, hospitals and
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marie C. McCormick, a researcher at the Harvard Center for
Children's Health and an author of the report, said that while the
findings would not surprise professionals in pediatric medicine,
they did point out the differences between the medical needs of
adults and children. As the report shows, she said, children are
most often hospitalized for a handful of reasons while the
diagnoses for adults are much more varied.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on children's health have been sorely outdated, Dr.
McCormick said. Medicare provides a wealth of data on care of the
elderly, she noted, but children have been less carefully tracked,
in part because of the expense.
</P>
<P>
   But with a push from Congress in the late 1990s, the agency put
children's health care back in the limelight. This is the first in
a series of annual reports that the agency plans to issue that will
also monitor expenditures and patient satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This research will become particularly important in the next
few years as we see such rapid changes in children's health care,''
Dr. McCormick said. Those changes include a decline in private
coverage and growth of state-sponsored insurance programs for
children.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1996, the number of children covered by private
plans dropped, while public coverage grew. In two-parent families,
the percentage of children with public coverage doubled in that
period, to 12.7 percent from 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings, Dr. McCormick said, will be important in
tracking the effects of the new state-based insurance coverage for
children that was begun through the Balanced Budget Act of 1997.
With $24 billion set aside over five years, the State Children's
Health Insurance Program has resulted in the largest single
expansion of health insurance coverage for children in more than 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   The report also looked at who paid for children's hospital
visits, and more often than for adults, it was Medicaid. Of all
hospitalizations in 1996, Medicaid paid for about 40 percent of
children's stays, and only about 17 percent of adult stays, the
study found. Nearly 90 percent of children under 18 had health
insurance for some part of 1996, and about 21 percent of them were
covered by public insurance like Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although a lot of people look down on Medicaid, it is an
increasingly important part of the safety net to ensure care for
children,'' Dr. McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   One finding that did surprise Dr. McCormick was that fewer than
half of all children under 18 saw a dentist in 1996. ``The low use
of dental care clearly reflects the access to insurance,'' she
said. Although dental care is covered by Medicaid, the families of
many children either do not take advantage of it or cannot find a
dentist who accepts Medicaid, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The data for black and Hispanic children were even more grim,
with fewer than 1 in 3 making a dental care visit in the year.
Hispanic children were the most likely to be uninsured, with 21
percent having no coverage. Nearly four times as many black
children were covered by public health insurance as white children.
</P>
<P>
   Not unexpectedly, the method of payment affects the care a child
receives. Publicly insured children were 50 percent more likely
than uninsured children and 20 percent more likely than privately
insured children to make at least one trip to the emergency room in
a year. Although more than half of all children receive at least
one prescription medicine in a year, only about 36 percent of
uninsured children do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
