<HEADER>
A2070 &Cx1f; ttd-z
e a BC-ART-LEWITT-ART-SFCHRO     01-31 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-LEWITT-ART-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DRAWING ATTENTION: LeWitt's Giant Paintings Add a Splash of
Color  to Museum  
 (ART ADV: Art being sent to NYT photo clients.)  
 By JESSE HAMLIN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Somebody once asked Sol LeWitt, the conceptual
artist who began making wall drawings in the 1960s, who started the
wall-drawing thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be those cave people,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how Joe Watanabe tells the story. He's the guy
directing the draftsmen now painting a pair of giant LeWitt
drawings on the atrium walls at the San Francisco Museum of Modern
Art, where ``Sol LeWitt: A Retrospective,'' opens February 19.
</P>
<P>
   It pleases Watanabe that they're using an acrylic paint called
Lascaux _ named for the French caves where Cro-Magnon painters made
potent images of animals. It's just a coincidence that LeWitt
picked Lascaux, a Swiss paint whose rich color and pigment he
preferred to the other brands he and his crew experimented with.
But it's a coincidence Watanabe finds ``very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   A printmaker by training, Watanabe has overseen the physical
creation of many LeWitt works since the 1970s. At SFMOMA, he's
directing the work of some 20 artists and art students making 46
LeWitt wall drawings in paint, ink or pencil. The artist's first
major retrospective since 1978, the show will also include
structures, photographs, books and works on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The museum commissioned LeWitt to create two 29-by-32-foot works
in the vast, light-filled atrium, one on either side of the central
black-granite stairway. They're huge, but not LeWitt's biggest: At
Atlanta's High Museum of Art, he created a six-panel piece that was
nearly 80 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Here, working on 40-foot scaffolding that was erected at 3 a.m.
a few Sundays ago, four painters are executing LeWitt's giant
rainbow-colored drawings. The pieces, which the artist conceived
after visiting the museum a few months ago, are adaptations of the
gouaches LeWitt painted for the cover of the exhibition catalog.
</P>
<P>
   One side consists of four black-framed panels filled with arcs,
each set running in a different direction; the other has four
black-framed panels of stripes _ one vertical, one horizontal and
two panels of diagonals in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer of conceptual art, LeWitt has always focused on the
idea; the physical object is the manifestation of the idea, and who
actually makes it is unimportant as long as it's done right. That's
the job of Watanabe and the artists LeWitt hires to produce the
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not an artist. I am basically an extension of Sol's
hands,'' says Watanabe, 53, a Tokyo native who owns a print shop in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has only two hands. If he has me to do certain things, then
he can do more things at the same time. Then I always have
extensions,'' he says, motioning to the crew, ``and they have
extensions, too, people from San Francisco to help them. So Sol's
hands are, let's say, 20 feet in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Taped to the wall are photocopies of LeWitt's schematic
drawings, simple pencil sketches showing the design of the pieces
and the color of each band: ``P'' for purple, ``G'' for green,
``O'' for orange and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The painters _ Dutch artist Wim Starkenburg, the New York-based
Norwegian painter Thomas Ramberg and San Francisco artists Andy Cox
and Susan Dopp _ have translated LeWitt's little hand-drawn lines
into 15-foot red, blue and yellow stripes.
</P>
<P>
   But before they could begin, the walls needed a coat of
oil-based primer, then three coats of white latex paint. ``The
walls have to be really smooth,'' says Kent Roberts, the museum's
director of exhibition design. His staff also also prepped walls on
the fourth and fifth floors where LeWitt's work will be installed.
``They had to be painted cross-hatched, because (LeWitt) doesn't
want any lines to show through.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the uniform look LeWitt wants, the painters often
switch position on the scaffolding. The goal is to create bands of
pure color with no gestural marks, ``very bright and very
plastic,'' Watanabe says, ``like a brand-new car body.''
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt usually likes the finished pieces when he sees them,
Watanabe says, but sometimes he doesn't. When that happened at a
museum in the Midwest, LeWitt hired a new crew and redid the whole
piece.
</P>
<P>
   But ``it's working very nicely here,'' says Watanabe. ``It's
satisfying that Sol LeWitt formula.''
</P>
<P>
   That formula for making art, as Watanabe calls it, derives from
LeWitt's way of ``bringing up the essence of the visual world,
seeing the world as lines _ straight lines, broken lines, and the
directions of those lines. (Then) there's the color and the
location in space. The combination of all that, somehow, attracts
the human mind very strong ly.''
</P>
<P>
   The genius of LeWitt, Watanabe adds, is that in ``using one
idea, he comes up with so many different results as individual
works. ... I like this piece very much. It delights me.''
</P>
<P>
   Starkenburg, who lives outside Amsterdam, is an abstract painter
who has worked on several major LeWitt installations, the first in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare it often to music,'' says Starkenburg, 53. ``Sol is
the the composer and we are the musicians. We're playing with
colors.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ramberg, 26, the job depends on his ability to conceive the
piece in his mind and focus on drafting it precisely.
</P>
<P>
   He takes pleasure in ``how simple it is in its essence,
(although) it's a complex piece. There are different coherences,
reminiscences of different kinds of systems, different levels of
logic. It's a play; it's like a puzzle. But it doesn't go one way,
it's sort of circular. There are always surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes the way these LeWitts play off the architecture,
the visual rhythm of the color bands in counterpoint with the
various striped forms throughout the atrium: the granite stairway,
the wooden walls and ceiling, the steel framing in the huge
elliptical skylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in a very interesting dialogue with this room,'' Ramberg
says. ``It's very musical in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will have plenty of time to check out the groove. The
LeWitts will stay on the atrium walls indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
