<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-CITRUS-0201-COX     01-31 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CITRUS-0201-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE THIRSTY FOR AMERICAN CITRUS, OFFICIALS SAY
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON and LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Exports of fresh U.S. citrus to China could begin
soon, a group of Chinese officials told members of Congress Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Xia Hongmin, who headed a delegation of Chinese agriculture
officials who toured citrus groves and packing houses in four
states _ Florida, Texas, Arizona and California _ said the
inspections were running ``quite smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The delegation was well received in all four states,'' Xia
said through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   The only missing pieces, Xia said, are U.S. Department of
Agriculture documents related to shippers, packagers and groves
involved in the prospective trade. The Chinese delegation also
would like to see the reports on fruit fly infestations from 1998
through 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Xia's comments came at a luncheon in a Senate office building
with Reps. Mark Foley, R-Fla., and Matt Salmon, R-Ariz. Also on
hand were representatives of federal and state agriculture
departments, and growers headed by Henry ``Skip'' Clements, chief
executive of Clements Citrus Sales of Stuart, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Clements, who organized the lunch _ which included chicken,
twice-baked potatoes, green beans and of course, orange juice _
said he was confident that last year's citrus trade agreement
between the United States and China will be very successful.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is already exporting frozen orange juice to
China, and Clements said he believes fresh citrus and perhaps even
meat may be not far behind. Clements started trade talks with the
Chinese on his own two years ago, meeting with officials and
retailers from China to educate them about U.S. grown citrus.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, noting that Xia will likely make the key decisions on
imports, called it ``helpful and hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the guy who apparently can make that decision,'' Foley
said, adding that he spoke with the Chinese Prime Minister Zhu
Rongii about citrus exports during a trip to China a few years ago
with former House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Foley told the Chinese delegation that they must be prepared for
a ``two-way street'' involving trade with the United States _ not
only shipping goods to America but also purchasing products such as
citrus from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials promised to expedite whatever documentation is
needed by the Chinese before final approval for exports will be
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's all that remains, Hallelujah, it's time to ship!''
Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   (AngelW(at)coxnews.com and LarryL(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
