<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-31 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MCCAIN MAKES SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again, Sen. John McCain got it right.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only anti-abortion Republican presidential candidate
with the wisdom and courage to acknowledge that a pregnant woman
may have powerful, legitimate reasons not to bear the child.
</P>
<P>
   He has also said that were his teen-age daughter to become
pregnant, what she did about it would be ``a family decision,''
suggesting that he would not automatically rule out an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican party is so solidly against abortion that all its
other candidates are sticking to the rigid doctrine expressed in
the 1996 GOP platform, which demands the procedure be outlawed
entirely, with no exception to protect the health of the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Even Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who used to favor exceptions for
rape, incest or for saving the mother's life, now says he supports
the current platform and supports the overturn of Roe vs. Wade, the
Supreme Court ruling that a woman's right to privacy provides
limited constitutional protection for abortion in the early phases
of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   McCain insists he is just as opposed to abortion as his
presidential rivals but he is the only one to express concern for
the living adult involved as well as the fetus. In this, he is
being politically savvy, appealing to moderate and independent
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careful balances'' among competing interests are required, he
said on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' citing ``legitimate exceptions''`
that might make an abortion necessary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said he believes that life begins at conception,
which is the basis for the political position that a fertilized egg
has rights equal, if not superior, to those of the pregnant woman,
making abortion the equivalent of murder. But religions differ;
some Protestant and Jewish theologians hold that life does not
begin until the fetus ``quickens'' after a few months and is
capable of living independently outside the womb, which is the
viewpoint adopted by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   McCain adds, however, that ``I don't claim to be a theologian.''
No one can know for certain which religious theory is correct.
</P>
<P>
   This does not bother Bush, Steve Forbes and the other GOP
candidates, who would impose their moral certitude upon those who
disagree with them by criminalizing the procedure. The most extreme
of the group, Alan Keyes, lectured a classroom of 10-year-olds
recently in frightening terms, graphically comparing abortion to
the killing of a living child and refusing to concede any moral or
theological disagreement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, competing for the GOP's anti-abortion vote, has accused
Bush of ``straddling'' the issue because Bush veils his references
to Supreme Court appointments in strict constructionist language
rather than pledge to make uncompromising anti-abortion selections
to the bench. The Forbes complaint is silly _ but Forbes is a
desperate candidate, willing to pander to anyone with a particular
gripe.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are similarly united on the abortion issue, lined
up on the opposite side.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore and ex-Sen. Bill Bradley support a
woman's right to choose an abortion, insisting the decision should
be a private one between her and her doctor. Bradley, challenging
Gore's integrity, is trying to make an issue of the fact that in
Congress two decades ago Gore opposed federal funding for the
procedure for poor women and voted for an amendment describing a
fetus as ``a living human being.'' This is as silly as Forbes'
attack on Bush and will have the same impact on the voters _ none.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responds that he long ago resolved his doubts on the issue
and has been firmly pro-choice ever since, which the record
confirms. It is not where he used to be but where he is now that
counts.
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, no matter which Republican or which
Democrat is running, the contrasting opinions on abortion will be
sharply drawn.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's compassion toward the plight of pregnant women unable
emotionally, economically or physically to bear a child may make
his opposition less alarming than that of say, Gary Bauer, who
promises to work night and day in the White House on the cause.
Although I happen to think he is wrong to oppose abortion, McCain
strikes me as a reasonable man, not a scary demagogue.
</P>
<P>
   If this is indeed to become one of the campaign's central
issues, the candidates will have to address the way they intend to
enforce their views. This is a tough one for the Republicans. If
abortion is illegal, does someone go to jail for it? The woman, the
doctor, the father, the parents, the clinic receptionist? Or
everyone? Who gives evidence and becomes the new Linda Tripp?
</P>
<P>
   Voiding the Supreme Court decision would merely leave it up to
the state legislatures to determine legality. This would result in
unequal treatment, of course, with women in some states penalized
and those in other states free to exercise their will on the issue.
This would never do for those who believe that life begins at
conception.
</P>
<P>
   The battle would spread across the country, creating political
chaos, religious tension and social instability. Not a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne means may be reached via e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2088 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-AUTHORS-NICHOLS-SPI &LR;      01-31 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-NICHOLS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MILLION REASONS TO KEEP HAMMERING AWAY AT THAT BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Mother of three sons, wife of an attorney,
part-time college secretary _ these were the devotions of Linda
Nichols' daily life for many years. And there was her devotion to
writing, as she toiled away at community college writing workshops,
listened to critiques of her work by fellow students and hoped that
someday some of her words might be published.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the encouragement of her teaching mentor, Nichols
decided to finally act on her writer's dreams. This is what happens
in just three weeks:
</P>
<P>
   _She sends out 19 query letters to literary agents, asking if
they might be interested in taking a look at her novel, a romantic
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   _New York agent Theresa Park, who discovered best-selling
novelist Nicholas Sparks, quickly plucks Nichols' letter from her
``slush pile'' of unsolicited inquiries, asks to see a copy of the
novel, reads it with great enthusiasm and immediately signs up
Nichols as a client.
</P>
<P>
   _Universal and Dreamworks, through Park's Hollywood connections,
buy the film rights to Nichols' novel at a price of $1 million
($500,000 up front, $500,000 upon film completion), a sum similar
to what was paid to David Guterson for the film rights to ``Snow
Falling on Cedars.''
</P>
<P>
   _Delacorte Press, spurred by the film sale, decides to publish
the novel and pays a hefty advance of $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   This three-week whirlwind hit more than a year ago, yet Nichols
is still recovering from her sudden good fortune as her first
novel, ``Handyman'' (Delacorte, 296 pages, $20), finally appears in
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked myself many times, `Why me?''' Nichols relates in
the dining room of the family's bungalow. ``The only thing I can
come up with is that, for whatever reasons, God decides to bless
you. I'm very grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, 45, also has been the beneficiary of the increasing
synergy between the publishing industry in New York and the film
business in Hollywood. Their never-ending search for new material
sometimes prompts a feeding frenzy that sends prices skyrocketing,
especially when a property from an unexpected source is deemed
eminently marketable as both a book and a film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handyman'' is definitely that. Think Tom Hanks, think Meg
Ryan, think boffo box office and soaring book sales. For
``Handyman'' is a chocolate bonbon of a book, a guilty-pleasure
fairy tale of modern love and romance that is based upon an
absolutely irresistible plot premise.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Ivey is a 26-year-old single mom struggling to get by in
the Bay Area. She has a dead-end bank job, a leering boss intent on
sexual harassment and a ramshackle apartment in a rough
neighborhood. Her problems are intensified by guilt about a
4-year-old son growing up without a father and no male replacements
on the horizon, plus the death of her own dreams of being an
artist. Maggie's life is, in short, a mess, with prospects of it
only getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   So a sympathetic friend signs her up for the ``21-Day Overhaul''
offered by Dr. Jayson Solomon Golding, a popular pop psychologist
and best-selling author. Maggie turns up for her first session in
tears and finds Dr. Golding to be a most sympathetic listener, such
a sympathetic listener that he hardly asks any questions at all.
But the hour together flies by and it turns out to be a comforting
experience for Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that the person listening to all her
problems is not Dr. Golding. He is a contractor, about to embark on
a remodel of the doctor's office, who has been surprised by the
arrival of the crying visitor and is overcome with pangs of
sympathy. ``She was so _ pathetic. It was like I was her last
hope,'' Jake Cooper tells a friend afterward. Jake is a
good-hearted guy who has a tendency to turn shy and tongue-tied
around women, as he demonstrated in that first encounter with
Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   How long it will take Jake's psychologist charade to unravel,
and with what consequences, is the delectable tease of Nichols'
novel. It entices even more as Maggie's life takes a turn for the
better with Jake's unorthodox assistance, and she comes to reflect
that ``he had turned out to be nothing like she had thought he
would be, and his practical caring was nothing like the silly
psychotherapy she had been afraid he would offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols came up with this comic premise after years of
frustrating attempts to concoct short stories of the gloomy sort
published in the literary magazines she kept buying in hopes of
picking up pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The philosophy of those stories always was that life is
absurd, and that never fit my own beliefs,'' Nichols stresses. ``I
am not a pessimist at heart, and thinking that way never occurred
to me. So I decided to have some fun with my writing, just goof
around a little and try to write something romantic for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols often took solace in romantic comedies on video during
difficult periods in her own life. Viewing one during her writing
crisis prompted her to think ``I could write that!'' and she was
soon reflecting on film comedies and what made them work, as she
brainstormed her novel.
</P>
<P>
   A deception was a key element, Nichols concluded; a deception
made especially interesting when one person is smitten with someone
who is not who he seems to be. Where that seemed most likely to
occur was in a work situation and counseling soon popped into
Nichols' head because of its shared trust. So a counselor who was
not a real counselor, and a loser in love besides, became her
premise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handyman'' flowed swiftly into the computer crowded into the
corner of Nichols' small bedroom, the queen bed often strewn with
papers, the writer often wearing what she laughingly calls her ``I
Love Lucy'' pajamas. She completed the first draft in six months,
amid her usual doubts about whether it would be published, even
with her communications degree from the University of Washington
and her six years of writing workshops.
</P>
<P>
   But she paid Kathy Keller, her teacher and friend at Tacoma
Community College, to critique the novel. Her verdict was delivered
over lunch at a time when Nichols was considering whether to quit
writing and enroll in nursing school, where she had finally been
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it to me straight,'' Nichols said to Keller. ``Do you
think I will be able to get an agent and sell a novel? Should I
continue writing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I absolutely do _ but you're going to have to work to
develop your craft,'' Keller replied. ``I think you should continue
writing. Take a year, say until January 2000, and if you still do
not have an agent or have not sold a book, then go to nursing
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols embarked upon her search for an agent, with no
expectation that her fairy tale novel was about to turn into a
real-life fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was optimistic that I would eventually get an agent, but did
not have not any premonition about `Handyman.' It wouldn't have
surprised me that I would have to write two or three books to sell
one,'' Nichols remembers. ``But I did know I had a lot of
determination and I was not going to give up easily.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was shocked when agent Park wanted to see her manuscript
as soon as possible. Nichols ``just about died'' when she had to
spend $50 to ship it to New York, the first time she had used
Federal Express for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Park called back after the weekend, voicing her enthusiasm for
the novel, and telling Nichols that she had shown a copy to two
film agents who might want to make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For how much?'' asked Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to guess,'' Park said. ``How much would you
want?''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols thought for a moment, then suggested, ``Two of my sons
attend private school and if film rights could pay the rest of
their tuition and I wouldn't have to go back to work, that would be
great. That is $8,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Nichols was hooked up in a four-way conference
call with her literary agent in New York and the two film agents in
Los Angeles who informed her that she was being offered $1 million
for the rights to her novel (``which should probably cover your
tuition,'' one added).
</P>
<P>
   Nichols was so stunned that she asked if she could call them
back. It was no negotiating ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a strange reaction,'' Nichols recalls. ``It would have
been a lot easier to say yes if I had been offered $20,000. I sort
of freaked out about being offered so much money. I also had fears
about what Hollywood does to books. I didn't want to be associated
with something I would be ashamed of, especially morally. I had
written a romantic comedy and I didn't want it turned into
something sleazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nichols' Christian faith is much in evidence in their home,
with sheet music for hymns on the piano in the dining room,
religious and inspirational sayings displayed on the walls,
including ``God Bless Our Home'' above the mantle.
</P>
<P>
   It is a home that may have been short on money, but was rich in
other things. As Nichols says proudly, ``I'm very grateful that we
did not have a lot of money during the first half of our years
bringing up our boys. They have not been spoiled that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone call, Ken Nichols advised his rattled wife that
he thought it would be fine for her to accept the $1 million for
the film rights to her novel. She was, he said, only responsible
for what she had written and there was certainly nothing sleazy
about that. That quieted her concerns to a manageable level.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the book is finally out (with 100 added pages from the
original draft), Good Housekeeping is set to publish a condensed
version of ``Handyman'' in its next issue. And the film plans are
progressing, with screenwriter Gary David Goldberg (``Family
Ties,'' ``Spin City'') working on a script and Tom Shadiak (``Patch
Adams'') set to direct.
</P>
<P>
   Life at the Nichols' house has not changed greatly. A restaurant
meal is more likely, every now and then. The young men in the
family (ages 18, 15, 13) have each received a present or two
(snowboard, guitar), although it has been slow to dawn on them, as
one said, ``so, mom, this is like a very big deal.'' And Ken is now
cutting back his law practice.
</P>
<P>
   But great extravagance seems unlikely, despite the ``Handyman''
windfall. This is a family that moved down the street to a larger
house a couple years ago, but moved back to where they had lived
before after five months away. The new place was more spacious, but
did not feel like home.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Linda Nichols plan to mention her publishing success
story in the commercial fiction class she has been taking in
Seattle. That could divert attention toward her and cause
unnecessary distraction. She's in the class, after all, because she
wants to learn more about writing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
