<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2096 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-0201-1     01-31 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-0201-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in lede, corrects spelling to 'reins' sted of 'reigns'
 &HT;    ESCALATED FIGHTING IN LEBANON ENDANGERING SYRIA-ISRAEL TALKS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After the killing of three Israeli soldiers Monday,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak threatened not to resume peace talks with
Syria until it reins in Hezbollah guerrillas in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli government cannot conduct negotiations when the
Syrians are not preventing the Hezbollah from its activities
against the Israel Defense Forces,'' Barak said in a written
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The statement came after a three-hour, emergency meeting of
Barak's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Hezbollah opened fire with rocket-propelled
grenades on an Israeli post in southern Lebanon. A major was among
those killed, and four others were wounded _ one critically.
</P>
<P>
   It came a day after Hezbollah killed a top commander of the
South Lebanon Army, a force trained and paid by Israel. For nearly
18 years, Israel has occupied a swath of land, now about nine miles
wide, of southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. officials feared that the war could escalate out of
control, the Israeli Air Force retaliated with bombing runs on
Hezbollah targets. U.S. officials have been trying to restart peace
talks between Israel and Syria, and the fighting Monday seemed to
complicate that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is the dominant power in neighboring Lebanon and maintains
40,000 troops there. Syrian officials maintain they are limited in
their ability to control Hezbollah, a grass-roots Lebanese force
backed by Iran, that aims to push Israel out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Israelis accuse the Syrians of encouraging Hezbollah
attacks as a way to exert pressure on Israel to make concessions in
currently stalled peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Syrians must understand that the present situation has a
risk of deterioration,'' Barak said on Israel Army Radio. ``That
could hurt Syrian interests.''
</P>
<P>
   He also vowed to not let the attacks go unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will arrange to make our enemies pay the price,'' Barak
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the attacks also prompted renewed calls in Israel for
a withdrawal from southern Lebanon. Barak has promised to remove
the more than 1,000 Israeli troops there sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly four years without formal negotiations, Israel and
Syria opened peace talks in December in Shepherdstown, W.Va., near
Washington. But, they stalled again three weeks ago. The Syrians
complained that Israel had not committed to what they consider a
full withdrawal from the strategic Golan Heights. Israel captured
the Golan Heights from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to, and throughout, the talks, southern Lebanon had
been relatively quiet. But, last week, Hezbollah killed the first
Israeli soldier to die there in months. Sunday, a roadside bomb
killed South Lebanon Army Col. Akl Hashem. He was expected to
someday lead the force, and his assassination was a major Hezbollah
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's attack brought to four the number of Israeli deaths
there this month.
</P>
<P>
   However, in one sign that Israel may be planning a restrained
reaction, Israeli officials were not ordering residents of northern
Israel into bomb shelters. That order is usually given when it
appears the violence could escalate.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official in Israel said Monday that diplomats for
the United States were contacting Israeli, Syrian and Lebanese
officials in order to try to control the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the condition of anonymity, the official said that
Syria had been restraining Hezbollah in the last six to nine months
but that, historically, southern Lebanon has become more violent
when Syrian-Israeli talks were stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
