<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seasonably cold, dry weather will dominate the Northeast Coast
on Tuesday as a brisk wind from the west descends the Appalachians
causing low clouds to yield to intervals of sunshine. An
approaching cold front will contribute to snow showers near the
eastern Great Lakes and along the west slopes of the northern
Appalachians. Very chilly air will return to the upper lakes
region.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over the Southeast will promote sunny and cool
conditions in most of the Carolinas. A stream of clouds associated
with the southern branch of the jet stream will spread across
Florida and the central Gulf States. Low pressure developing in the
western Gulf of Mexico should produce a cold rain in central Texas
and a wintry mixture from the Red River Valley to east central New
Mexico. Light rain and drizzle will dampen much of south Texas and
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonably mild conditions will cover the northern Rockies and
western Plains. A large fair weather system, crested over Wyoming,
will circulate Pacific air into this region with ample sunshine and
an active afternoon breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and strong winds are expected to buffet the Northwest Coast
as a potent disturbance approaches Washington. A surge of
relatively mild, moist air will raise snow levels and limit
freezing rain to a few patches well inland. Showers should reach
northern California late in the day. The Southwest will become
brighter and milder, especially as winds blow offshore in southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Forecasting Snow
</P>
<P>
   A storm that left a trace to more than a foot of snow around the
Northeast on Sunday supports the notion that predicting snow totals
is the most difficult problem in weather forecasting.
Meteorologists begin by estimating the amount of liquid that will
fall. On average, an inch of liquid will produce 10 inches of snow.
However, the ratio of liquid to solid precipitation can vary by
over 200 percent, depending on temperature and moisture conditions
aloft. Also, because the heaviest snow often occurs at temperatures
near freezing, mixtures of sleet and freezing rain complicate
snowfall forecasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
