<SLUG> BC-SCI-PHYSICS-REALITY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEORY, REALITY AND SKEPTICAL TOURISTS IN PHYSICS LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a Fodor's guide to Manhattan, the science of physics is
generally sold as the ultimate, indispensable, up-to-the-minute
guide to reality. The parallel is far from exact: physicists cannot
credibly tout their research as inexpensive and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one thing that the painstaking experiments and
deep thinking of physics are meant to produce, it is theories that
explain both the delights and the details of natural reality at its
most fundamental level.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as unwelcome news to some physicists that just as
their field is enjoying unparalleled success, its relationship to
reality is being questioned with a pointedness not seen for
decades. Since the doubters are mostly nonphysicists _
philosophers, historians, even the public in general _ it is as if
tourists from Keokuk had begun questioning just how unimpeachable
the guidebooks are.
</P>
<P>
   In a quick-and-dirty definition, reality would begin with
elementary particles and the interactions that bind them to build
the universe that our instruments measure, our eyes see and our
hands touch. Physics, with its ambition of understanding these
building blocks at the most basic level, therefore becomes a prime
target for doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Some motives for this skepticism can be found in the 20th
century's scientific triumphs themselves, said Dr. George Levine,
director of the Center for the Critical Analysis of Contemporary
Culture at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's provoked by the overwhelming authority that
science has been able to accumulate,'' Levine said. ``There's a
sense that there are a few adepts, highly trained, who talk to each
other, and there is no point of entry for anyone outside that
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Driven by that sense of disenfranchisement, Levine said, anyone
can scour the annals of philosophy for potential wedges to separate
science from an immutable, objective reality that it seeks to
explain. Philosophical pragmatists and empiricists, for example,
hold that while a successful theory should describe experiments as
accurately as possible, it has no necessary relation to ultimate
reality, partly because one can never say whether new experiments
will give new results and force changes in the theory.
</P>
<P>
   More irksome to physicists is a school that finds its source in
``The Structure of Scientific Revolutions,'' a book first published
in 1962 by the philosopher of science Thomas Kuhn. In this school,
the form that theories take has as much to do with the politics and
sociology of science as with its duty to describe reality.
</P>
<P>
   The book seemed to show that science did not progress inevitably
toward a better and better representation of reality, but instead
that scientists moved from one ``paradigm,'' or theoretical
framework, to another based on social and psychological factors as
well as experimental ones.
</P>
<P>
   That view suggests that research in any paradigm brings science
``closer to answering its own questions,'' said Dr. Steve Fuller, a
sociology professor at the University of Warwick in England, whose
book, ``Thomas Kuhn: A Philosophical History for Our Times,'' is to
be published soon by the University of Chicago Press. ``But those
questions are autonomous from the bigger question of how close they
are getting to reality as such.''
</P>
<P>
   Measured against such doubts, physicists almost seem to be
inhabiting another universe. For one thing, physicists regard their
theories as much more than a Fodor-like compendium of detail.
</P>
<P>
   Theories like the one governing elementary particle physics are
based on simple principles with a distinct aesthetic appeal. And
physicists point out that they have a presumably objective arbiter
for deciding the correctness of a theory: how well its predictions
compare with experiments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Dr. Frank Wilczek, a theoretical physicist at the
Institute for Advanced Study, and two other physicists came up with
the idea of asymptotic freedom, which held that the elementary
particles called quarks have the strange property that they feel
scarcely any mutual attraction when they are very near one another,
despite their powerful attraction when separated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that that has moved us closer
to reality,'' Wilczek said. ``There were experiments whose outcome
was doubtful,'' but they later supported the theory, he said. ``So,
yes, we have understood more; it's not a social construction.''
</P>
<P>
   When pushed, physicists will often concede that there is room,
at least linguistically, to wonder how absolute the correspondence
is between successful theories and what might be regarded as
ultimate reality.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the spirit of philosophical empiricism, theories get
revised in light of fresh evidence that they cannot explain.
Sometimes the need for later revision is clear even as the theories
are being devised: nearly all modern theories of matter and energy
are called ``effective field theories.''
</P>
<P>
   That qualifier, ``effective,'' means physicists already know
that as the level of energy of things like particle collisions is
pushed higher and higher, the theory gives wrong answers and cannot
be trusted _ even though physicists may not be sure how to fix it
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we always required that our field theories would
at least mathematically be consistent up to the highest possible
energies,'' said Dr. Chris Quigg, a physicist at the Fermi National
Accelerator Laboratory. ``Now we admit the feeling of humility.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Newton's laws of motion, which hold that gravity
moves objects by applying a force on them at some distance from a
star or planet, were superseded by Einstein's general theory of
relativity. In that view, the objects move because gravity curves
space around them, leaving force-at-a-distance out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   These revisions, however, do not rattle physicists, since the
earlier theories almost always remain mathematically valid in some
way or other. Effective field theories will still work at low
energies, even after a fancier version is developed for higher
energies; Newton's laws hold when the strength of gravity, and the
curvature, are small.
</P>
<P>
   As Fuller's book recounts, Kuhn rejected many skeptical schools
of thought that were generated by his own ideas. But with varying
degrees, those schools assert that the forms taken by accepted
scientific theories, at any level, have as much to do with
ephemeral factors of politics, personal influence and historical
chance as with reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason one theory becomes dominant is because of locally
specific, social factors which then get a kind of institutional
momentum at one time,'' Fuller said of his own views, which do
allow for a connection between physics and reality. The distance
between the two views is so great that cliche-makers have coined
the term ``science wars'' to describe their interaction.
</P>
<P>
   In a more worrisome if less fraught metaphor, scientists, who
depend heavily on public financing for their work, may wonder if
the doubts will someday keep the tourists, so to speak, from
feeling an occasional need to visit the scientific paradise of
ideas. Without those tourist dollars, the debate could become moot
even as it remains unresolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
