<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULTICULTURAL-MUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOSING KIDS TO GOOD MULTICULTURAL MUSIC MAKES THE WORLD A BETTER
PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give children music and they smile.
</P>
<P>
   Give them rhythms and percussion and happy sounds, and they
dance and laugh and spin around and shake their hips _ joyously,
without a hint of self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Give them music made all around the world, and not only will
they do all of the above, but they will begin what could, with
luck, be a lifetime discovery of other cultures and countries, from
the reggae of Jamaica to the sinuous salsa and merengue rhythms of
Latin America to the ``rancheras'' of Mexico to the jigs and reels
of Ireland to the zydeco of Louisiana, and more.
</P>
<P>
   World music _ and that includes such divergent influences as Bob
Marley, Ladysmith Black Mambazo, the Chieftains, Johnny Clegg and
Ry Cooder's Cuban connection, the Buena Vista Social Club _ has
never been more popular.
</P>
<P>
   From contributions to pop records (see Paul Simon's
``Graceland)'' to collaborations (as in Ry Cooder and his Cuban
pals) to stand-alone releases (Ali Farka Toure or Bob Marley,
anyone?), world beat musicians have never been more high-profile.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you bring world beat music to your kids? And how do
you make the experience meaningful?
</P>
<P>
   It's as easy as playing music and talking, say several world
beat and children's music experts _ and it's an important part of
kids' development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate good is that if children can learn about other
cultures, there's enormous opportunity to expand their horizons and
make them interested in the world, to explore other cultures,''
says Dan Storper, president and CEO of Putumayo World Music, which
has released several excellent world beat children's records, as
well as, for schools, a multicultural curriculum kit that blends
cultural information and music. ``It's the first step toward
eradicating prejudice and racism.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the most enjoyable. Remember, say Storper and
Grammy-nominated musician Linda Tillery, that you probably already
have some world music around the house, be it Marley or Santana or
Chieftains. Just find some world beat you like, start playing it
for your toddler and go from there, building a collection as time
and money permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids' tastes are far more eclectic than we imagine,'' says
Tillery, who has cut several children's records, including one,
``Shakin' a Tailfeather,'' that earned her and collaborator Taj
Mahal a 1998 Grammy nomination. ``And I'd start talking to them
about it as soon as they can understand.''
</P>
<P>
   What to say? Well, you can always listen to a song and then
explain what the music is, and where it comes from, and about the
country and culture of origin. Ask your kids why they like it. What
are some of the instruments they hear? How would they play them?
What do they know about, say, Africa or Cuba or Ireland?
</P>
<P>
   And from there, you can drop in little nuggets of history and
culture and discuss different races.
</P>
<P>
   Tillery says kids ``will follow a parent's lead. And they know
what they like. I'd play them 50 percent what they like and 50
percent what they might like but won't know unless they get a
chance to hear it. You can play Ladysmith for them and explain to
your child what makes their music different from music from another
place. You can never underestimate little people's ability to
absorb and retain information.''
</P>
<P>
   Storper advises parents to read the liner notes and mix
narratives with the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids love the romance of far-off places and imagining
themselves there,'' he says. ``If you can combine stories with
music, it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   This is becoming easier and easier to do. Fifteen years ago, the
Music For Little People label became the first record company to
introduce world music to children.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the label has a series of CDs by everyone from Los Lobos
to Sweet Honey In the Rock that combines children's stories with
bright, fun, colorful music. ``Gift of the Tortoise,'' for example,
fuses a story about Africa as told by an old tortoise with
Ladysmith's music.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's society, people in the U.S. are very isolated about
knowledge of other cultures,'' says Sheron Sherman, the label's
founder and CEO. ``It's important for children to know about this.
You can sing and play and dance and then sit down and talk with the
child about the country.''
</P>
<P>
   And giving kids these sorts of fun cultural lessons is
increasingly important, what whith pop music invading kids' lives
earlier and earlier, via teen-focus acts such as Britney Spears and
the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Those influences will inevitably creep in, but teaching kids
about music from other places at a young age lets them know there's
more out there than one-hit-wonder bands on VH1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, it's often uncomfortable to be on the
outside,'' Tillery says. ``But if you've introduced kids to
multicultural music, by the time they're 14 or so, they can hold
their own. They can value something other than American pop
music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get away from TV and videos,'' says Sherman. ``They
don't give anything to the intellect. There's no doubt this gets
harder as the kid grows up, but there's also no doubt I control my
9-year-old son Dusty's purse strings, too. I'm going to spend time
with him that he's just not going to listen to Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to parents to regulate what their child listens to,
not the child driving the parent. The more positive musical
experiences we can give our children, the better off the whole
country is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
