<HEADLINE>
SINGLES GROUP HELPS FIND CUPID IN THE HAYSTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (IL, IA Attn) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KIMBERLY DURNAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Finding cupid in the haystack can be as hard
as finding the proverbial needle, say some lonely-hearts who are
looking for friendship and romance in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I graduated in a town of 1,000 people,'' said Don Trewin of
Fredericksburg, Iowa. ``Half of the girls went to college and never
came back, and those who stayed around got married within a year or
two. Now there's no one left. Next thing I know, I'm partying with
the kids of the ones who got married.''
</P>
<P>
   Trewin was a prime candidate for membership in a club called
Singles in Agriculture, which aims to help single people who hanker
to socialize with someone other than farm animals or the county
extension agent.
</P>
<P>
   Living on a farm or ranch, miles away from a city, can make that
a bleak prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Singles in Agriculture, based in Pearl City, Ill., has about
1,600 members nationally and schedules several meetings a year,
including an annual national convention and social functions in
several states.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, the club has arranged mixers in
connection with the Southwestern Exposition and Livestock Show in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Trewin and about 40 other single men and women from across Texas
and the United States came to the show to mingle with kindred
spirits. In addition to the show, the group attended the rodeo and
visited the Texas and Southwestern Cattle Raisers Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The group allows anyone who is single, divorced or widowed to
join but asks that they have some background in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't come to meet Prince Charming or Cinderella,'' suggested
John Newcomb, who leads the club in Fort Worth. ``Just come to make
friends with people who have something in common with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The club does not promote high-pressure romance but offers a
venue for singles with like interests to meet for friendship, and
perhaps dates, said Jerome Hoelscher, who owns a farm near Midland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people get married and others just meet new people,''
Hoelscher said. ``It's just a chance to meet people with the same
kind of lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Dating people with urban backgrounds often ends in rejection for
some who live in the country, said Margie Hayden, who lives in San
Antonio but helps on her parents' farm in Floresville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think it's a novelty,'' she said. ``They think, `Oh the
cows are interesting,' but they don't want to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoelscher agreed. He said that some city slickers don't
appreciate the slow pace of rural life, with its lack of noise and
bright lights. In rural West Texas, he said, ``It's so quiet you
can hear the quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are different,'' Hoelscher said of city dwellers. ``Some
people, when they don't see the lights, they can't handle it. A lot
of people who live in the city don't want anything to do with a
farm. They say, `This is way out here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's why a group like Singles in Agriculture is needed to
bring people together, whether they find romance or not, said
Hayden, who had just finished a conversation about how to handle a
bull in a pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about working the animals,'' she said. ``You
can't do that with most people who only quote movies like `City
Slickers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The singles group has sparked several romances, some of which
have led to marriage. Group members range in age from about 45 to
55, but the club rules allow membership for anyone over 21. The
Iowa chapter is the largest, with about 380 members. The Texas
chapter has about 90.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Green, of Cedar Park, Texas, near Austin, said she joined
the group to socialize with those who have like interests. But if
she finds a significant other along the way, well, that's OK, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know if you can associate with people with a farming or
ranching background, then they are just good stock people,'' Green
said. ``But this is not one of those singles groups where everyone
has to get together.''
</P>
<P>
   Some singles in the group, however, wouldn't mind _ after
meeting the right someone _ joining an offshoot branch of the club,
Singles No More.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I joined the group was to look for guys,'' Hayden
said. ``There's lots of flirtation; that's always good. All the
guys dance with all the girls. It doesn't matter what you do or
what you look like. I hope to meet someone and think, `Gee, down
the road, maybe we'll be more than just friends.' ''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
