<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WEBSITES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICK AND WIRED? TAKE 2 DOT.COMS _ BUT CALL YOUR DOCTOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's ironic, isn't it, how medical information gleaned from the
Internet can have detrimental side effects.
</P>
<P>
   I recently took the life-expectancy quiz on the Web site
health.yahoo.com. The test results told me I may live to age 80. If
I drop all my bad habits, it said, I'll live to age 82.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years gained? Really? I decide the quiz is solid proof
I should lie around and eat chocolate, lest I spend the last two
years of my old age bitter about not having taken more time to
enjoy life. This is likely not the result the health.yahoo.com
folks had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are flocking to health-related Web sites. One popular
site, the Mayo Clinic Health Oasis, reported nearly 2 million
visits in November, about double the number of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocacy groups watching the Web say the Internet is a
valuable tool for researching health conditions, if we do so with a
good dose of caution.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of room for error. Using the Alta Vista search
engine, I found 87,658 sites that mention back pain. Obviously, not
all of those sites are worthy of an Internet browser's time.
</P>
<P>
   Here's advice from consumer advocates for judging Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   Information on the Web should support, not replace, a patient's
relationship with his or her doctor. That's the most important rule
for consumers, say consumer groups, which would frown upon me
making a health decision based on an Internet quiz.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to distinguish between reliable and
questionable sources is to consider who sponsors the page.
</P>
<P>
   The Mayo Clinic recommends looking for pages sponsored by
well-known sources, such as medical schools, government agencies or
national organizations like the American Cancer Society or the
American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   Those sites aren't selling or representing a product, and are
therefore more likely to offer objective information.
</P>
<P>
   Web addresses ending with .gov indicate the page is sponsored by
a government agency; a nonprofit organization's address ends with
.org; and sites by colleges and universities end with .edu.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial sites _ those with addresses followed by .com _ can
be good sources for information, but read them with some caution.
The ``dot-coms'' sometimes find themselves in real or perceived
conflicts of interest. ``Men's Fitness'' magazine in its December
issue reported that DrKoop.com, the site started by former Surgeon
General C. Everett Koop, had listed 14 hospitals as the ``most
innovative,'' only to have it revealed that those hospitals had
paid to be in the listing. The site has since abandoned the
practice of mixing advertising and editorial content, ``Men's
Fitness'' reported.
</P>
<P>
   One example of a good commercial site is health.yahoo.com, which
provides a roundup of articles from mainstream news sources, such
as The Associated Press and Reuters news service. This site is
considered commercial not because it sells a product it might be
tempted to tout, but because it sells advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Sites that sell products can contain insightful information,
but, again, read them with caution. Know that clickwell.com, for
instance, is a vitamin purveyor, and its lengthy list of columns on
fitness and nutrition are interesting, but remember it will not
steer you away from vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the site address, it's a good idea to click on
the ``About Us'' or ``Mission Statement'' icon found on most Web
sites. They offer insight into the policies of the page's sponsor,
and oftentimes disclaimers that stress the limits that should be
placed upon the information.
</P>
<P>
   Health on the Net, a consortium of health-care providers, says
readers should look for the following information on any credible
Internet health page: the author's credentials, the date the
information was last modified, whether any personal medical
information they are collecting will remain confidential,
attribution for all sources, and a statement on the advertising or
funding policy for the page.
</P>
<P>
   As for the e-junk that arrives unsolicited in your in-box, be
careful. For one thing, those e-mailings use way too many capital
letters and exclamation points. To me, messages such as ``NO SIDE
EFFECTS!!!!!'' or ``QUICK WEIGHT LOSS,'' suggest a digital snake
oil salesman, so I delete them right away. Any message without a
name, address and telephone number should be considered suspect,
says Quackwatch, a nonprofit Internet site that offers consumer
advice on medical Web sites. And the Mayo Clinic warns against
sites that promise cures, put down other sites or insist that you
buy a special product.  &QL; 
Reliable Web sites
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of Web sites with a reputation for reliability:
</P>
<P>
   www.hon.ch _ This site, sponsored by the Swiss-based Health on
the Net Foundation, screens Web sites for reliability of
information. Surfers can use the foundation's Web site to search
for other reliable sites.
</P>
<P>
   www.mayohealth.org _ This Mayo Clinic site includes screening
tests and consumer news.
</P>
<P>
   www.nlm.nih.gov _ The National Library of Medicine, the National
Institutes of Health and the Department of Health and Human
Services operate this site, which offers searches of 4,300
biomedical journals.
</P>
<P>
   www.healthfinder.gov _ This Department of Health and Human
Services site provides links to a broad selection of health-related
sites on the Web, as well as publications.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
