<P>
   TECH-CHIPMEMORY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ If computer users are going to
harness the latest whiz-bang processing performance, their
computers had better have memory chips that are running lickety
split. If memory chips cannot keep pace, then those fast and
expensive new processor chips will be sitting idle most of the time
and not earning their keep. Memory chip makers have created a
series of faster memory technologies throughout the 1990s. Usually,
after a short period of time, the new standard dominates and all
the world's memory makers shift their production to the new
technology. But this year and next year, things could go
differently. Two competing standards could emerge, and, if they do,
then life gets a little more complicated for the companies that
make computers and for PC buyers as well. (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
