<P>
   ECONOMY _ Congratulations, America, you've spent your way to
another important record: the longest economic expansion in U.S.
history. Tuesday is the first day of the 108th month of an
expansion that started in March 1991, as determined by the National
Bureau of Economic Research _ official keeper of business cycles.
The record is expected to lengthen, although the growth may slow
down a bit. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-AIRLINES _ AOL scores deal with American Airlines frequent
flier program to let American frequent flier users redeem miles to
pay their AOL bills, shop online etc. Interview with Ted Leonisis,
president of AOL or similar executive. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALLIED _ Allied Holdings is North America's leading car-hauler,
delivering more than 12 million new vehicles a year to dealerships
under contract to auto-makers. The problem with rising demand for
SUVs and trucks is that fewer of the bulky vehicles fit on a
trailer, cutting Allied's average load about 20 percent over the
last few years. That helped push the company's earnings into the
ditch for much of 1999 while Allied tried to adjust its pricing
structure, as well as recover from a mid-1998 strike at its biggest
customer, General Motors. fact box. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
