<P>
   BUSH _ (developing; possible) On the campaign trail with George
W. Bush the day before the New Hampshire primary. (Herman/Heath,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENTS _ NEW HAMPSHIRE _ New Hampshire independents,
famous for making up their minds the week before the primary, cast
ballots today. With the polls narrowing for weeks, who knows if
they'll go for Gov. George W. Bush, whose camp admits he could
lose, or U.S. Sen. John McCain, who has been courting the
Independents? We talk with New Hampshire voters and gauge their
mood right down to the wire. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Independents comprise about 37 percent of New
Hampshire's electorate, and an even larger share of its political
lore. But are they really the persnickity old New Englanders of
political stereotype, who vote regularly and steer their own
course? On closer inspection, it turns out the majority of New
Hampshire's independents are younger people who moved here recently
and don't care much about politics. The independents of legend do
exist, but overall New Hampshire's electorate may not be so unique.
(Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAPRIMARY _ It's Friday night at the American Legion hall in
Rochester, N.H., and who do I run into? Five guys from Georgia,
political junkies who want a first-hand look at the action. John
McCain is delivering his usual fare on reform and honesty. One of
the Georgians is Emory Fiveash of Statesboro. Fiveash is vice
chairman of the Bulloch County Republican party and he's wearing a
tan down jacked that is zipped up in the chill of a January night.
Or maybe it's because underneath he's wearing a Bush for president
T-shirt. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
