<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-ALDAPE-COLUMN-TEX     01-31 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALDAPE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER ECUADOR'S DEMOCRATIC PATINA IS THE MILITARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAVIER ALDAPE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The military, again, reigns supreme.
</P>
<P>
   Newly installed Ecuadorean leaders and the U.S. State Department
tried to characterize Ecuador's recent political turmoil as a
constitutional transfer of power. Not quite. The constitution's
remaining shreds are so smudged by the military's fingerprints that
they're practically illegible.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, the military staged a coup, toppling the democratically
elected president, Jamil Mahuad. After all but inviting indigenous
protesters to take over the Congress building in Quito on Jan. 21,
Defense Minister Carlos Mendoza stripped Mahuad of all military
protection and asked for his resignation. Mahuad fled the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   Moving swiftly to fill the power vacuum he instigated, Mendoza
that same day announced the creation of a new ruling triumvirate
made up of him, an indigenous leader and a former supreme court
justice.
</P>
<P>
   A mere eight hours later, Mendoza dissolved that council and
installed the vice president as the nation's ruler. U.S. pressure
and equivocation from several military leaders prompted the return
to civilian authority.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, a country mired in the throes of economic collapse
has now installed its sixth president in four years and earned
itself the dubious distinction of being the home of the ``First
Coup of the 2000s.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmingly, the Ecuadorean military's most recent assault on
democracy was not an aberrant act but rather the culmination of its
increasing involvement in civilian life. As in Venezuela, the
military and its standards of order and discipline have become the
country's de facto political compass, serving as a check on
civilian mismanagement and corruption. Paraguay has seen a similar
trend in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A shift toward greater military interference in this
hemisphere's civilian governments is of grave concern. U.S. policy
has discarded the ideological litmus test of the Cold War. For now,
the United States continues to reject overt military involvement in
governments, but it appears willing to accept the more insidious
behind-the-scenes control.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, that may help guarantee some stability; in
the long term, it fortifies the military's role in Latin American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the return of democratic rule in 1979, a military
triumvirate ruled Ecuador. In the years since, corruption,
mismanagement and political stasis have plagued the country.
</P>
<P>
   Vast regional differences _ particularly between the insulated,
mountain bureaucrats in Quito and the tropical, entrepreneurial
bankers and traders in Guayaquil _ only served to further striate
the country's political legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   This latent regionalism was both assuaged and then ignited by a
singularly decisive event: the war with Peru and subsequent peace
agreement, ending 150 years of territorial disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador occasionally fought skirmishes along its southern border
with Peru over a remote, sparsely populated part of the rain
forest. These periodic moments of nationalist fervor were
buttressed by an absurd claim to Amazonian lands printed on state
letterhead and reflected in national maps. This helped political
leaders gloss over the country's intractable poverty and regional
schism.
</P>
<P>
   In January and February 1995, the two countries again fought a
limited war. The military emerged re-energized and highly
respected.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that a delicate cease-fire was implemented,
then-President Sixto Duran-Ballen's tenure was virtually over. An
aging, statesmanlike figure, he lacked the political capital to
initiate meaningful change, and his coalition government was
grossly fractured. Amid signs of economic deterioration, the
country looked to the 1996 presidential election for answers.
</P>
<P>
   The answer provided was the wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo-populist Abdala Bucaram was best known by his nickname,
``El Loco (The Crazy One),'' which he reveled in.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadorean presidential elections have long been dictated by
regional politics. The July 1996 runoff pitted two Guayaquil
politicians, though: Bucaram, adored by the poor and reviled by the
monied, and Jaime Nebot, Social Christian party leader. Nebot's
party was anathema to much of the population outside the coast.
Privately, some hoped for a Bucaram victory, believing it would
lead to a military coup.
</P>
<P>
   Though often suggested in jest, it was a telling quip in a
country with few national figures of authority. Power and respect
resided with both the military and the Roman Catholic Church _ the
military still glowed in the aura of its war with Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Bucaram did win, but ratcheted corruption and a deadlocked
Congress led to a massive national strike. Congress took advantage
of this and deposed Bucaram in February 1997 for ``mental
incapacity.'' Though the hoped-for coup did not materialize, a
late-night TV interview with a high-ranking general who voiced
support for the congressional action effectively ended Bucaram's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The military did not openly oppose Bucaram, but the removal of
its support was crucial to his fall. That same month, Bucaram went
into exile in Panama, and the military manipulated the subsequent
transfer of power. Vice President Rosal!a Arteaga was president for
a weekend before ceding control to the president of the Congress,
Fabi n Alarc''n.
</P>
<P>
   Though Western governments applauded the peaceful transfer, left
unsaid was the fact that the military was now a political enforcer
of sorts. Though officially apolitical, the military reasserted
itself as a political power of great authority.
</P>
<P>
   Jamil Mahuad, 51, was elected president in July 1998 after an
extremely successful term as mayor of Quito, including the
installation of a new trolley bus line that helped ease congestion
in the highly polluted mountain capital.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the candidates, Mahuad was the most promising. His
Harvard education suggested that the United States would be apt to
smile on his election, and his significant electoral bloc in a
historically fractured Congress gave many at least a glimmer of
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, the lack of congressional consensus, the
continued fall of the monetary unit _ the sucre _ and the growing
instability in the local financial markets engulfed Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
   He did sign a peace agreement with Peru in October 1998, ending
the long-simmering dispute. Unwittingly, that merely accelerated
the country's downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   After a short period of celebration, the country quickly
realized that it faced no external enemy. The deeply held regional
differences were exacerbated, as the yoke of nationalism, which the
conflict with Peru helped to maintain, had been gravely
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The military suddenly found itself with no rival and with no
definable purpose. The military's stated goal was to ensure
stability for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   As 1999 progressed, that became increasingly difficult. The
economy steadily declined and civil unrest continued to grow.
Ecuador defaulted on some public debt and closed many major
national banks, and then Mahuad all but erased the sucre. It will
remain only in coins; U.S. dollars will be the de facto national
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Many looked to the military for a way out.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, military leaders took pains to assert their support
for the government and the democratic process, but their importance
within the political landscape continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the year, the military saw a country with no
national currency, a looming debt burden, widespread civil unrest,
a diminishing economy and political paralysis. They also faced a
contentious regionalist issue: an impending nonbinding vote for
autonomy in the coastal province of Guayas, which includes
Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
   The old specter of regionalism threatened to overtake political
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising, then, that Gen. Mendoza took action to
avert what he feared would be a ``social explosion.'' The
self-styled defender of peace, order and national unity, the
military thought it was compelled to act.
</P>
<P>
   The end result, however, is an inevitably weaker democracy than
before. Subject to the whims of the military and lacking in any
representational authority, the new president, Gustavo Noboa, is
hopelessly disabled. He's not even the member of a political party.
</P>
<P>
   Allies may applaud the continuation of democracy in Ecuador, but
it belies the broader point. Though it may be democracy in name, it
furnishes none of the things such a government should provide:
political freedoms, due process, an orderly transfer of power, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, if such overt manipulation continues, Ecuador
has little chance of ever developing such a government. With scant
political legitimacy, a shaky historical foundation, and the
specter of past military interference, Ecuador is a perfect example
of a puppet democracy _ manipulated and cajoled until things turn
out the right way.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. foreign policy standard of the new decade may be that.
No longer will we demand the ideological purity of anti-communism;
the new criterion is merely a patina of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   (Javier J. Aldape is publisher of La Estrella, the
Star-Telegram's Spanish-language edition, and a member of the
Star-Telegram Editorial Board. He was managing editor of El
Telegrafo in Guayaquil, Ecuador, from 1996 to 1998. He can be
reached at (817) 390-7903 or at javier(at)laestrelladigital.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
