   &UR; Church and State: How the Wall Came Tumbling Down &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Recycled Generation &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The following articles from the Jan. 30 issue of The New York
Times Magazine are now available as special ``one-shot'' buys:
</P>
<P>
   .....................
 &UR; THE WHOLE WORLD ISN'T WATCHING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By A.O. Scott &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: Jan. 30 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   American TV shows no longer rule the airwaves. Much of what's on
television, whatever its scale or country of origin, is pretty bad.
And people may just prefer the whiff of home-grown garbage to that
which originates on the other side of the world. Includes a brief
sidebar: ``Top-Rated TV Exports.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A.O. Scott is a film reviewer for The New York Times. slugged:
BC-TV-AMERICAN-ABROAD-NYTSF, priority code r, category codes a,e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RECYCLED GENERATION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Stephen S. Hall &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: Jan. 30 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to stem-cell medicine _ which Science magazine called
``the breakthrough of the year'' _ there may be 5.3 million people
a century from now living to the age of 100 and perhaps much
longer. In the process of ``human therapeutic cloning,'' a single
human skin cell, with its unique payload of human DNA, can be
plopped into the egg of a cow. Consider the possibilities, and the
ethical morass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Stephen S. Hall is a contributing writer for The New York
Times Magazine. slugged: BC-BIOTECH-IMMORTALITY-CLONE-NYTSF,
priority code r, category codes a,k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHURCH and STATE: HOW the WALL CAME TUMBLING DOWN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Jeffrey Rosen &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: Jan. 30 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In an era when religious identity competes with race, sex and
ethnicity as a way in which Americans define themselves, it seems
discriminatory to forbid the expression of spiritual beliefs in the
public sphere. And far from threatening public life or liberty, the
revived cooperation between church and state may be a healthy
result of treating religion as just another aspect of self-identity
politics in a multicultural age.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeffrey Rosen is legal affairs editor of The New Republic and
teaches law at George Washington University. slugged:
BC-PRAYER-IN-SCHOOL-NYTSF, priority code r, category codes a,k) &LR;
</P>
