<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE ENDS N.H. CAMPAIGN FIGHTING ON THREE FRONTS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore closed out his New
Hampshire primary campaign Monday fighting on three fronts _
promoting the administration's economic record, preparing to take
on the Republican candidates, and defending his own character
against attacks from Democratic rival Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   His message, delivered in 30-second TV spots throughout the day
and in person at a diner, an Italian restaurant and a senior
citizens center, sought to convince the state's Democrats that he,
not Bradley, is the candidate best prepared to ``fight'' the
Republicans this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a contest,'' he said as he shook hands outside a
Nashua electronics firm at dawn Monday. ``The real fight is for our
future,'' he added, alluding to the fall campaign against the
Republican Party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists are hoping that a convincing win in New
Hampshire on Tuesday, coupled with the one-sided victory in Iowa
last week, will persuade Bradley to withdraw from the contest,
allowing the vice president to start concentrating on the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, with campaign coffers exceeding those of Gore, has
indicated he intends to continue his quest for the Democratic
nomination and the ``old politics'' that he says Gore represents.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the final full day of campaigning, Gore sought to
strike a positive note, in contrast to the harsh exchanges between
him and Bradley over the last three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to confine my campaign to the issues, as I have from
the beginning,'' Gore told a diner breakfast crowd, emphasizing the
issue of ``how we keep our prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he mingled with a lunchtime restaurant crowd in
Concord, he asserted that responsibility for the negative tone of
the campaign rests with Bradley. ``Personal attacks, no, I have not
engaged in them and I won't.''
</P>
<P>
   But gone from Gore's standard stump remarks was the often
repeated comment that Bradley is ``a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although CNN's tracking polls showed him with a lead of six
percentage points among likely Democratic voters, Gore campaigned
as if he continued to trail Bradley in the Granite State, as he did
just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be campaigning full blast every minute of every
hour between now and (when the polls close Tuesday), leaving off a
few hours for sleep tonight,'' Gore said in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   With harsh weather conditions forcing his campaign aides to
improvise his schedule, Gore visited his campaign headquarters in
Manchester and joined the phone bank that is trying to reach
150,000 Democratic voters before the polls close at 8 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He ended the day with an open meeting with undecided voters in
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
