<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA HIGHLIGHTS ABORIGINAL TOURISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Feb. 6) 
(jt) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a half-century ago the Australian Unesco Committee for
Museums put together a traveling exhibition of the country's
Aboriginal culture, which toured the United States and Canada. The
accompanying catalog extolled the rich heritage of the Aborigines,
the indigenous people who came to Australia more than 30,000 years
ago, and it concluded with the hope that the exhibit would
``engender a curiosity about Aboriginal life.''
</P>
<P>
   That curiosity took a long time to awaken, but a growing recent
interest in other cultures is beginning to pay off for Australia's
Aborigines. The most recent figures from the Australian Tourist
Commission show that in 1997 the 200 tourism businesses operated by
Aborigines generated $20 million a year, while the sale of
indigenous arts and crafts brought in another $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   While small compared with overall tourist revenues in Australia,
about $10 billion, it is a start for a people who number only about
400,000, or just over 2 percent of Australia's population of almost
19 million. And it is all the more impressive in that most
Aboriginal villages, cultural centers and tour operations are far
from big cities and their amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Aboriginal tourism has stirred some resentment against
tourists _ particularly for what the Aboriginal people regard as
tourists' cultural insensitivity and their failure to respect mores
and traditions. Perhaps the best known example is that of the
visitors who climb Uluru (formerly Ayers Rock), even though they
are asked at the cultural center at the Uluru-Kata Tjuta National
Park not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   For related reasons, in 1998 the Queensland government issued a
code of conduct with suggestions such as these: That visitors learn
a few words of the Aboriginal language, and be aware that avoiding
eye contact is a sign of respect. But with many more visitors
expected this year for the Olympic Summer Games in Sydney, and with
almost 5 million projected in 2001 (compared with 4.2 million
visitors in 1998), the chance to satisfy that ``curiosity about
Aboriginal life'' is greater than ever _ and so is the likelihood
of offending Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore the Australian Tourist Commission is drawing up
another _ and presumably more detailed _ code of conduct for
visitors, to be issued within a few months. It will counsel them to
respect Aboriginal sacred sites, ceremonies and traditions. In the
United States, some Indian tribes have also adopted codes of
conduct for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian government wants Aboriginal tourism to succeed
for several reasons. Some of them were detailed in a speech at the
National Press Club in Canberra three months ago by John Morse,
managing director of the tourist commission. Describing Aboriginal
tourism as a ``win, win, win'' situation, he said it can help
Aborigines achieve economic independence and help the wider
Australian population ``discover more of this rich and diverse
culture.'' And it can appeal to ``people in countries around the
world, over 80 percent of whom want to experience culture in some
form or another.'' And, of course, it adds to the national
treasury.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Morse mentioned two particularly successful
examples of Aboriginal tourism. The Aboriginal Cultural Park in
Cairns, created by the Tjapukai people, last year won the Gold
Award for Culture, given by the Pacific Asia Travel Association.
With five theaters, an art gallery, a museum and a cultural show,
the park _ in the city that is a tropical gateway to the Great
Barrier Reef _ is already a major tourist attraction. And there is
the Sydney Aboriginal Discovery Tour, whose Aboriginal owner,
Margaret Muragun Campbell, has arranged tours for some 10,000
visitors not only to the landmark Sydney Opera House and the city's
harbor, but also to the outback and Aboriginal communities.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other examples of successful Aboriginal tourism,
as well as a popular tourist site partly on Aborigine land _ Kakadu
National Park in the Northern Territory, 100 miles southeast of
Darwin. It is a trove of archaeological treasures that is on
Unesco's World Heritage list; its 8,000 square miles include
hundreds of plant and bird species and more than 5,000 rock-art
sites, most of them consisting of paintings but some with
engravings or designs in wax. Yet while Aborigines have lived in
Kakadu for at least 25,000 years, it is not technically an
Aboriginal park, since the native people leased their half of the
land within the park to the government about 20 years ago. In
return, they own concessions in the park and participate in its
planning, management and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Other Aboriginal tourism operations include Native Guide Safari
Tours in Mossman, Queensland. Founded by Hazel Douglas, it operates
a variety of tours including visits to the Daintree rain forest, a
World Heritage site, and catamaran cruises off the beaches of
Cairns. Harry Nanya Tours in Wentworth, 60 miles from Sydney, also
specializes in tours conducted by Aboriginal guides. And in Alice
Springs, in the Red Center desert of central Australia, a Southern
Arrernte Aboriginal tribal group owns and operates the Aboriginal
Art and Cultural Center, which sells art, crafts, books, CD's,
tapes and didgeridoos, the haunting Aboriginal wooden wind
instruments. Its Web site, aboriginalart.com.au, sells these items,
too _ and if a didgeridoo strikes a browser's fancy, the site also
offers lessons in how to play it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
