<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINING CHILDREN ON CRUISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Feb. 6)  
(jt) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does a child think is the most fun on a cruise? For Bill
Driscoll of Wilmington, N.C., who has sailed more than most third
graders, it is ``going where you can't usually go.'' Specifically,
he said, last month it was getting into the casino aboard
Carnival's Ecstasy, where a scavenger-hunt clue was taped to the
side of a slot machine.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, two of my granddaughters were of a similar mind
aboard the American Adventure: They enjoyed the in-line skating
program, but returned again and again to the whirlpool tubs, mainly
because health clubs on shore barred them.
</P>
<P>
   What was the down side? Bill said he was not big enough for the
Ecstasy's water slide. Always some rule.
</P>
<P>
   So, for kids on a cruise, a lot of fun comes from passing
through the normally adult world, under the aegis of an authorized
and supervised on-board recreation program.
</P>
<P>
   Most cruise lines now have activities tailored to children; some
provide baby-sitting. ``Cruise Vacations With Kids'' a fat book by
Candyce H. Stapen, published by Prima Publishing ($16), lists 18
lines as providing ``top family cruises.'' And the number is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   How extensive a line's program is, and how many counselors are
on board to lead the activities, particularly sports like
basketball, often depends on the season. At vacation times,
counselor corps swell, but travel agents should be pressed on which
ships post ``closed today'' signs on activity rooms in off periods.
Bill Driscoll, who is 10 and goes on a lot of cruises because his
father, Michael, writes a newsletter, Cruise Week, recalled that
once, water activities were limited to a kiddie pool and it was
``really crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents who crave a meal alone may find it possible often or
only on pizza party night, depending on the ship. Children's rates
also vary by line and season; third and fourth passengers in a
cabin can be cheap, but in the off season, an adjoining cabin may
be in the same range.
</P>
<P>
   Two lines go all out for children: Disney, with its new ships,
the Magic and the Wonder, and Premier, with its Big Red Boats. Two
Premier vessels, the Oceanic and the Rembrandt, are being renamed
Big Red Boat I and Big Red Boat IV, and two more are in conversion.
Here is information on these lines' children's programs, and those
at Carnival, the biggest line, and at Princess, whose Love Boat
Kids program is popular.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Big Red Boats
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Bruce Nierenberg, who now heads Premier
Cruise Lines, created American Family Cruises, which operated the
ship my granddaughters enjoyed. American Family lasted less than a
year, but Nierenberg has transferred a number of his concepts to
the Cruisin' Kids program at Premier.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if skating would be offered aboard, Nierenberg said that
the jogging track was available but that the space was a little
tight. ``Kids can bring their in-line skates and be able to use
them on shore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet cafes and television production rooms will be provided,
as well as a separate children's pool, but most sports activities
will be planned for shore excursions.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Red Boats, children 2 to 17 are divided into five age
groups for activities: 2 to 4 (they must be toilet-trained); 5 to
7; 8 to 10, 11 to 13 and 14 and over. On busy cruises, group
baby-sitting in the evening costs $5 an hour, and $3 for each
family's additional child.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises average 500 children, less than half the capacity.
Thirty-two counselors are aboard, Nierenberg said, but the younger
children get a higher ratio of adults.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Disney Cruise Line &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Disney does diapers,'' said Kiersten Murnane, a
spokeswoman for the company's cruise line. Babies 12 weeks to 3
years are watched over in the Flounder's Reef Nursery for $6 an
hour, and $5 for a second child. This service is provided 2 to 4
p.m. and 7 p.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Older children are split into four groups, with the 3- to
5-year-olds getting one counselor to each 15 children and the 6 to
8's and the 9 to 12's getting one to every 25. The teen-agers have
a coffee bar with tabletop games, computers, music and Disney
professionals teaching improv skills. Basketball, shuffleboard and
team contests are organized, but not pool activities. There are
lifeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Younger groups make costumes and milk shakes, search for lost
treasures and participate in quiz shows. Ashore at Disney's island
in the Bahamas, treasures or ``fossils'' are dug up and pizza is
prepared in an oven made by the children.
</P>
<P>
   One sure draw: ``Discover the Magic: Your children are featured
stage performers in this Walt Disney Theater presentation.'' Only a
parent who has experienced 17 dance recitals in five years could
resist that.
</P>
<P>
   Disney takes 50 counselors on each vessel, and also gets an
average of 500 children a sailing, about a quarter of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Carnival Cruises  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Carnival expects 250,000 children on its dozen ships this year.
Carnival's activity groups are for 2- to-5-year-olds,
toilet-training not required, then those 6 to 8, 9 to 12 and 13 to
15. Activities for older teen-agers are also available.
Sing-alongs, puppet shows, pizza parties and face-painting are
offered for the younger children, Ping-Pong, video games,
computers, scavenger hunts and backstage tours for the older ones.
</P>
<P>
   An average of 10 counselors are aboard. Baby-sitting for
children under 2 is provided in the evening and, on days in port,
in the morning. The cost is $5 an hour, $3 each for additional
children. Carnival ships have three pools each and a water slide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Princess Cruises &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Princess has no youth or teen centers aboard the Royal or
Pacific Princesses, but when at least 15 children ages 2 to 17 are
aboard, kids' programs are offered. In port, all the ships offer
group baby-sitting or supervised activities in daytime for $4 an
hour each child. Princess does not do diapers.
</P>
<P>
   On ships with children's centers, those 2 to 12 are in the
Pelicans group, and those 12 to 17 join the Princess Teen Club. The
Pelicans work at arts and crafts, go on scavenger hunts, hold
parties, tour the bridge and galley, and watch videos and
Nickelodeon programs. The teen-agers have a disco, engage in
shipboard Olympics, murder-mystery games, karaoke and lip-synching,
and have a movie fest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Costly Soft Drinks &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The cruise lines have heard an outcry from parents about the
cost of the sodas that fuel the young. Whether the wine flowed free
or not, the final bill on a cruise often sagged with pricey Cokes
and Pepsis. The lines are now responding.
</P>
<P>
   Premier provides free sodas in a glass to anyone under 17 at the
soda fountain; if it must be a can, the charge is $1.75. Disney has
a new package for children 12 and under: unlimited sodas for $12
for three days or $16 for four days. Sodas at meals are free for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival has unlimited soft drinks for anyone under 21, for $8
for three days and $18 for seven days. Princess, for now, is
sticking with $1.50 a can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
