<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SAFRICA-SYMPHONY-1020     01-31 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-SYMPHONY-1020(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORCHESTRA FALLS SILENT AS SOUTH AFRICA STRUGGLES ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa's National Symphony
Orchestra is silent, maybe for a few weeks, maybe for a few years,
maybe forever.
</P>
<P>
   The 76-year-old symphony orchestra was still searching for money
and for its place in the national landscape when funds ran out last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Since losing its annual support from the national broadcasting
company a few years ago, the orchestra had been living pretty much
month to month, check to check, dependent on the continued
beneficence of big corporations to meet its $2.4 million annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   So when the orchestra took the stage recently, only moments
after each of the musicians had been handed a ``retrenchment''
letter, it was to say goodbye. There was no charge for the patrons
and there was no pay for the performers. There was no conductor, no
soloist, not even air conditioning. Some of the audience came in
jeans, and many of the performers played in their shirt-sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   It was to be about making music and nothing else. It was Bach's
Air soothing the sore hearts that filled Linder Auditorium that
night. It was the intermezzo of Mascagni's ``Cavalliera Rusticana''
tugging at those same hearts. Many were close to tears.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people, almost all of them white, watched an
orchestra, itself almost entirely white, in a country whose black
majority was effectively excluded from such cultural indulgences
until a decade ago and whose own artistic avocations were until
even more recently largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   So the final concert was a small window into how change is
reaching into every corner of this society. If classical music is
to make it in the new South Africa, it will have to find a way to
survive alongside a multitude of musical forms, all competing for
scarce resources in a country rich in artistic talent but too poor
to nurture it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the government's priorities,'' said Donald Ezard,
the general manager of the orchestra. ``They are trying to bring
water and electricity into people's home and trying to feed people
and make life more livable. But we've got to feed the soul of the
people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra's members understand that need, which is why they
returned for a last encore. ``For me, as a music lover, this is an
essential part of my life,'' Maeve Jacobs, a season subscriber for
25 years, said. ``Musicians are precious people. It's a gift that
they give us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a gift that people like Mrs. Jacobs and her husband, Gil,
who has been going to the orchestra since 1954, when he was 10, are
not prepared to give up. ``As a South African in a new South
Africa, if you want something you have to fight,'' Jacobs said.
``And if they take away our culture from us, we are destroyed, so
we have to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the evening seemed to redouble the resolve of many
present to save the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let this go,'' Robin Finlay, the principal trumpeter
and an 11-year veteran of the orchestra, said moments after walking
off the stage for what he hopes will not be the last time. ``It's
too good to let go.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's minister of arts, culture, science and technology,
Dr. Ben Ngubane, is the man who has to make sure that none of those
souls starve, that all of them are fed at least a morsel or two.
And contrary to what some critics might argue, Ngubane said that
he, too, wanted to see classical music thrive in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed and so must the orchestras.
``Essentially, they must undergo very far-reaching transformation,
which they haven't done by and large,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   For most of their lives, the country's principal orchestras,
based in Pretoria, Durban, Cape Town and until last week
Johannesburg, depended on the government for most of their money.
</P>
<P>
   The National Symphony received the bulk of its budget from the
state-supported South African Broadcasting Corp. For the other
orchestras, opera houses and ballet theaters, there were the
Performing Arts Councils, which controlled nearly 70 percent of the
country's arts budget and existed essentially to support the
artistic interests of the white minority.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of apartheid and the establishment of majority
rule, such largess soon became untenable. Long neglected, the
artistic interests of the black majority finally would be
supported. With little additional money available, however, this
has meant radically reducing the allocations for historically white
cultural interests, which means that today those Performing Arts
Councils control just under a third of the country's total arts
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The change, Ngubane told Parliament last year in his budget
speech, has allowed projects unthinkable not long ago to at least
have a chance today, projects like the Soweto Community Dance
project, the Hennie Joubert Piano Competition and the Madimba
Institute of African Culture and Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country's many cultures and forms of artistic expression
are, at last, given equal opportunity,'' Ngubane said in his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   For the orchestras this has meant looking down new avenues for
money and turning away from their long-held expectations of
significant government support, expectations that did little to
prepare them for the pressures they have encountered. ``There was a
laissez-faire attitude among administrators,'' Kenneth Marcus,
chairman of the Cape Town Philharmonic Orchestra, said. ``You
didn't have to be innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two long-established orchestras that merged a few
years ago to become the Cape Town Philharmonic drew as much as half
of their funds just from the local city council, Marcus said. Today
the Philharmonic receives modest subsidies from the national and
provincial governments but is otherwise dependent on its own fund
raising, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, expanding the audience is necessary to save the
orchestra, and the only way do that is to bring blacks into the
fold, in particular children, who are just starting to develop
their tastes and interests. That process is under way, with
orchestra programs venturing into the townships for concerts and
workshops.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ezard, a Briton who joined the National Symphony as general
manager just last August, said that he understood Ngubane's
intentions and his limitations. ``He is obviously concerned, but he
doesn't have a shed full of money,'' Ezard said. ``What I think he
wants is for us to come up with some sensible, proactive
suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the nation's orchestras have been meeting to try
to plot their collective future. Their efforts promise hard,
sometimes painful decisions that are likely to worsen some of the
tensions that have already been voiced by those who say the
government now cares only about the art and culture of the black
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always this fear that any nation that is majority
black is going to renege on Western culture, and that's not true,''
Ngubane said. ``In this country we are very keen on it. We are
supporting it.''
</P>
<P>
   But orchestra supporters worry that if the National Symphony is
allowed to die, its efforts to reach the blacks will die with it.
Certainly, to look around Linder Auditorium, the results of the
orchestra's efforts have been modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've come a long way, and I don't want to see it
end,'' said Susan Harrop-Allin, who runs the orchestra's outreach
efforts. ``We're building something, and if we stop, we'll be going
backward, and I don't want to see that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If it does, she said, it will be young people like Alex
Hitzeroth who suffer. An 18-year-old trombonist from Port
Elizabeth, he is one of the orchestra's two black musicians.
Devoted to his trombone since he was 10 years old, Hitzeroth joined
the orchestra last month on the very day word arrived that the
money had run out, that the season would be canceled and that the
orchestra was closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you wonder why you did all that practicing, what was
it all for,'' Hitzeroth said in between warm-ups in the dressing
room backstage. ``It will make young people across the country
wonder: If there's nothing to aspire to, is it worth all the
practicing?
</P>
<P>
   Eager as he is to see more black faces onstage, Hitzeroth is not
one to criticize the orchestra's efforts. It has been trying, he
said, to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process to get people into the orchestra, and I think
the orchestra is doing quite well,'' he said. ``It's not like you
can throw 10 million rand into development and you'll have 10 black
guys in the orchestra. It takes time. I think they are doing well.
It may not look that way, but they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
