<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-TWO-REVIEW-NYT     01-31 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TWO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TWO-BEATLE REUNION, BUT IT'S JUST IMAGINATION
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 1976, six years after the breakup of the Beatles and four
years before the death of John Lennon. Paul McCartney, whose band,
Wings, has the No. 1 record in both the United States and Britain,
has come to New York for some concerts. He decides to drop in on
John unannounced. They get together and talk. And talk. And talk.
They sing briefly. And talk. They take a walk. They stop for
coffee. And ... you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   This imaginary encounter between these two indelibly familiar
figures is portrayed in ``Two of Us,'' a film that VH1 is unveiling
on Tuesday night. Although it drips with sincerity, the exercise
falters as both iconography and drama. If you carry cherished
images of these men, as Beatles and beyond, you may well be
uncomfortable with the imitations before you.
</P>
<P>
   The two featured actors, Aidan Quinn as Paul and Jared Harris as
John, have a virtually impossible assignment here. On screen, just
the two of them, for nearly the whole film, they do manage to
connect emotionally with each other and with the viewer. Onstage,
where conventions of acting and expectations of verisimilitude are
different, this encounter might have worked better. But here, in a
medium that depends on the seamless illusion of reality and that
relies heavily on the close-up, the trick doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is too beefy to play the wiry John, and his snarling
portrayal smears the character's pain all over his surface. This
doesn't jibe with the memory of a man whose essence seemed securely
locked away, even, one suspected, from himself.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn looks more like the Paul of that time, but neither actor
has the body movements or vocal cadences that you recall from
interviews, feature films and recordings. Perhaps a different
script could have helped, but Mark Stanfield has written his
characters too many cryptic exchanges that begin to sound like
deadpan Monty Python routines as rewritten by Harold Pinter. Take
this encounter at John's apartment door:
</P>
<P>
   PAUL: Hi, John.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN: The Ghost of Christmas Past.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL: You gonna let me in?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN: Aren't you one of them?
</P>
<P>
   PAUL: Well, I used to be. Now I'm one of me.
</P>
<P>
   Once the talking gets going in earnest, you learn that John
isn't performing or writing and that he's a bit contemptuous of
Paul's continuing drive to please the public. But John quickly
confesses that he's still carrying around a bellyful of childhood
fears. Paul says, ``That's heavy, John.''
</P>
<P>
   So is this film, leavened only by a brief sequence in which the
men don false mustaches, both looking like a cross between Ringo
and Groucho, for a walk in Central Park. Later, as tears glisten in
their eyes, Paul tells John that he mustn't be a slave to those
fears, that the world isn't really such a dangerous place. Under
Michael Lindsay-Hogg's direction, this uplifting scene works
dramatically until you remember that Lennon was gunned down right
in front of his apartment house. Pretty dangerous, that.
</P>
<P>
   The film keeps playing with the notion of a Beatles reunion
performance, which never took place. The four Beatles did get
together in 1979, not to make music but to discuss legal strategy.
They were determined to block a film version of ``Beatlemania,''
the stage show in which they were all impersonated. When the
current film was proposed, once again someone should have spoken
words of wisdom: Let it be.
</P>
<P>
   Production notes:
</P>
<P>
   TWO OF US
</P>
<P>
   VH1, Tuesday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Aaronson and Leon Falk, executive producers; Michael
Lindsay-Hogg, director; Mark Stanfield, writer. A production of
VH1.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Aidan Quinn (Paul McCartney) and Jared Harris (John
Lennon).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN01-COX     01-31 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indepentents to have last say
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Independents comprise about 37 percent of
this state's voters, but as a component of New Hampshire primary
lore, they play an even larger role.
</P>
<P>
   They evoke the image of crusty old sixth-generation New
Englanders, certain to vote in any weather and unswayed by party
label or the tide of national opinion. The reality, it turns out,
is somewhat different.
</P>
<P>
   Some independents tend to be older, have lived in the state more
than 20 years, are fairly politically sophisticated and make up
their minds late about which primary to vote in, depending on where
the action is, said Andrew Smith, director of the University of New
Hampshire Survey Center.
</P>
<P>
   But a slightly larger number are voters who have lived in the
state less than five years and don't fit the stereotype of the New
Hampshire independent at all.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers have increased as the state's economy has bounced
back. New Hampshire was losing population at the beginning of the
`90s, but is rapidly gaining today, drawing new residents primarily
from neighboring New England states as the high-tech corridor grows
northward from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Often on talk radio, you hear New Hampshire Republicans
disparage them as Massachusetts liberals. And it's true these
voters helped elect the state's Democratic governor, Jeanne
Shaheen. But the newcomers who register as independents don't fit
neatly under either party's banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically they're younger people who don't have much interest
in politics. They just don't vote,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   It's somewhat misleading, he said, to describe these voters as
independents, since more than two-thirds lean pretty consistently
toward one party or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more accurate to describe them as undeclared
voters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat more people register as independents here than in other
states, but that's in part because they have an extra incentive
here. The state allows nonaligned voters to pick up either party's
ballot on primary day, which is not true of those who register as
either Democrats or Republicans. So by registering as independents,
voters get to keep their options open.
</P>
<P>
   All this has important implications for Republican John McCain
and Democrat Bill Bradley, both of whom have fashioned campaigns
based on their appeal to independent-minded voters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaners, McCain has the definite advantage. About 40
percent of New Hampshire's independents generally pick up
Republican ballots, compared to about 30 percent who tend to vote
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   What about those who could go to either McCain or Bradley, or
for that matter, to Vice President Al Gore or Gov. George W. Bush?
When you boil down the numbers, that turns out to be a group which
may not number many more than 10,000 voters, according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   How many of these truly independent voters actually show up at
the polls could depend a lot on the weather, which was precarious
Monday as the latest winter storm moved toward the state.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with both the Democratic and Republican primaries
tightening in the closing days before the vote, this small group
could spell the difference for either McCain or Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   And for a few more hours Tuesday, they will be the most
intensely fought-over voters in America.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER01-COX     01-31 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: McCain still leading in N.H.
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUPER BOWL OVER _ NOW FOR NEW HAMPSHIRE
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates are doing some last-minute
campaigning in New Hampshire, which holds its primary Tuesday,
Cox's Tom Baxter reports. The voting actually begins at midnight,
when little Dixville Notch weighs in. John McCain says he is
``confident of victory,'' over George W. Bush. Bill Bradley asked
voters to support him as ``something that is new and fresh.'' Al
Gore got up before dawn to visit a defense plant in the freezing
rain and said, ``The real fight is for our future.'' Most polls
show McCain with a slight lead or tied with Bush, and Gore with a
slight edge over Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST THE PANCAKE, THEN FLIP YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer was flipping pancakes at a campaign event in
Manchester, N.H., today when he fell off the 3-foot riser. He's OK,
though. It happened as he stepped back to try to catch one of the
flapjacks. Bauer disappeared off the back of the stage, but popped
right back up _ beet red _ with the pancake in the pan. ``I'm a
fighter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH COFFERS BURSTING ...
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush reported today that he raised $11 million during
the last three months of 1999, bringing his total to a record $68.7
million. Bush had $31.4 million in the bank as of Dec. 31,
according to documents filed with the Federal Election Commission.
That's four times the estimated $7.7 million of John McCain, who
had around $1.5 million and expected an additional $6.2 million in
federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   ... AND BRADLEY PICKING UP THE PACE
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, Al Gore reported raising $28.2 million, plus
$2.9 million to pay legal and accounting costs in the general
election. Bill Bradley reported raising more than $27 million, but
twice as much money as Gore during the last quarter 1999: $8
million to $4 million. Bradley had $8.3 million in the bank at the
end of the year, and expected $11.4 million in federal funds.
Gore's bank account balance stood at $5.7 million, plus an expected
$12.4 million in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   MORE EXPENSIVE THAN A DRUG HABIT
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer has complained that he needs $25,000 a day to keep
campaigning, and that unless he does well in New Hampshire he will
be running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   THE EFFECTS OF MOBILITY
</P>
<P>
   Independents comprise about 37 percent of New Hampshire's
electorate, and an even larger share of its political lore. But are
they really the persnickity old New Englanders of political
stereotype, who vote regularly and steer their own course? On
closer inspection, Cox's Tom Baxter reports, it turns out the
majority of New Hampshire's independents are younger people who
moved there recently and don't care much about politics. The
independents of legend do exist, but the overall state electorate
may not be so unique.
</P>
<P>
   THE HEART OF THE MATTER
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley said he might put his vice president in charge of
running the country if treatment for his non-life-threatening heart
condition forced him under anesthesia. ``I think that that's
probably appropriate,'' Bradley told ABC yesterday. ``I'll make the
decision at the time ... if I decided to'' undergo a course of
treatment that incapacitated him. Bradley, 56, acknowledged that
treatment for his irregular heartbeat has required him to be
unconscious three times since 1996. Said Bradley adviser Anita
Dunn, ``We've got a healthy candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   WOOING FEMALES WITH INTENSITY
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley has not been able to overcome a gender gap that has
plagued his campaign from the start. And polls conducted in the
past week show Bradley trailing Al Gore by as much as 21 percent
among women in New Hampshire. So Bradley's accusations that Gore
has flip-flopped on abortion may reflect not only his passion
concerning a volatile issue, but the harsh reality of weak support
among women, the Democratic Party's largest group of voters.
</P>
<P>
   `DROPPING OUT' NOT IN THE VOCABULARY
</P>
<P>
   As if to ward off any more negative chatter about Bill Bradley's
future if he loses New Hampshire, his staff sent out his
post-primary schedule days early and the words ``dropping out'' did
not appear. Instead, his camp announced a wild swing across the
country and back, including stops in Hartford, Conn.; New York
City; San Francisco; College Park, Md.; and Tampa. With plenty of
money in the bank, Bradley's aides say he will stay in the race,
regardless of whether the news from New Hampshire matches that in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUL OF CONSERVATISM
</P>
<P>
   David Schippers, the Republican lawyer and ex-Democrat who
authored that devastating narrative for the House Judiciary
Committee during President Clinton's impeachment hearings, has
endorsed Alan Keyes for president. Some polls show Keyes gaining on
Steve Forbes in a race as to which Republican will be the
conservative alternative to the GOP establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH, ALREADY!
</P>
<P>
   James Siglio of Manchester, N.H., is a prime target for
presidential campaigns looking for young workers. Siglio, 18, a
senior at Manchester Central High School, was a volunteer for the
local political group Democracy in Practice last fall. Since then
he's been a marked man, and now wishes they'd stop calling. ``These
people call every day,'' said Siglio, 18. ``I'm sick of the
election and it's only January.''
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF JOHN Q.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush knows his family name is a political asset and it
gives him a chance to make his case. But he says he stands where he
does, as national Republican front-runner, on the basis of his
record, his programs and his proposals. The only son ever elected
president after his father held the office was John Quincy Adams,
in 1824. John Adams was elected in 1796. Each served one term.
</P>
<P>
   HOPING SOME OF THAT OLD MAGIC RUBS OFF
</P>
<P>
   He's got Alzheimer's now and can't speak for himself, but he's
in John McCain's campaign ad, Gary Bauer's campaign literature and
George W. Bush's campaign rhetoric. And he's in Steve Forbes'
campaign book and Alan Keyes' campaign Web site. ``Ronald Reagan is
the most popular president certainly in our lifetime, and everybody
wants to campaign as the heir to the Reagan legacy. It's smart,''
says Steve Duprey, the New Hampshire GOP chairman.
</P>
<P>
   THEY REALLY WANT TO BE WHERE THE REDSKINS ARE
</P>
<P>
   To Al Gore, they are the Tennessee Titans, but George W. Bush
insisted on thinking of them still as as the Houston Oilers. ``If
he's rooting for the Houston Oilers, that is typical of living in
the past,'' said Gore with a chuckle, sporting a Titan cap at his
Super Bowl party at a Nashua, N.H., eatery. John McCain and Alan
Keyes bowed to tradition and attended a couple of Super Bowl
parties, but admitted they weren't paying much attention to the
game. Gary Bauer, originally from Kentucky, tilted toward
neighboring Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   CHOICE MEANS NOT HAVING TO TALK ABOUT IT
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, whose big campaign issue is opposition to abortion,
encountered a few college students sporting ``Choice'' buttons the
other day. Initially, Bauer finessed the moment, telling them,
``I'd rather have people with `choice' buttons on'' than young
folks uninvolved in politics. ``At least we can have a
discussion.'' One student tried to take him up on it. ``My question
is ...'' he began. ``I'm sorry,'' Bauer said, cutting off the
question and walking away. ``We're late.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOK, KID, THIS IS REAL LIFE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain gave 11-year-old Jonathan Hutchings a lesson in
bluntness during a town hall meeting in Hampton, N.H. Little
Jonathan gathered up his courage, stood directly in front of the
candidate and asked him: ``Will you take some of the large military
money and put it into school education for children like me?''
After a pause, McCain replied, ``No. We should take care of
education separate from our obligations to the military and
national security.''
</P>
<P>
   NEXT TIME, TRY PICKING UP HIS CHECK
</P>
<P>
   Some New Hampshire eateries thrive on the politics. At the busy
Puritan Backroom in Manchester, for instance, the sign outside
boasts, ``The candidates say this is the primary place to eat.''
But when George W. Bush burst into the Golden Egg diner in
Portsmouth with his sunny side up, the fellow at the end of the
counter just wanted to be left alone with his coffee, his food and
his newspaper. ``I came here to eat breakfast,'' the customer
grumbled, ``not to shake hands.''
</P>
<P>
   SICK JOKE ACTED OUT
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer says he's saddened by an article that details the
first-person, undercover exploits of an openly gay columnist who
secretly joined his Iowa campaign to give him a contagious virus.
In the online magazine Salon, sex columnist Dan Savage chronicled
how he tried to give Bauer his flu bug by licking objects Bauer
would come in contact with, such as door knobs. ``I'm not
particularly feeling anger,'' Bauer said. ``I just feel kinda sad
for the guy that he's so consumed with hate that he would not only
do something like this, but actually brag about it.'' Savage said
he was trying to get back at Bauer for opposing gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
