<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABERNATHY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abernathy receives just punishment
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlantans should derive no pleasure from the
sentencing of convicted chiseler Ralph David Abernathy III to four
years in prison. What a comedown for the son and namesake of one of
the civil rights movement's foremost leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the punishment was appropriate considering the younger
Abernathy's offenses. True, the amount of state money the former
state lawmaker was convicted of pocketing, $5,700, may seem paltry
by the standards of big-league rogues. Just the same, he violated a
public trust in helping himself to unauthorized state funds, and he
made matters worse by pressuring an assistant to lie on his behalf
to officials investigating financial irregularities in his office.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Abernathy should be relieved that his witness-tampering
gambit, which was caught on tape and played at his trial, didn't
earn him an even harsher sentence. Give L.A. McConnell Jr., the
visiting judge who presided over Abernathy's case, credit for
adhering to probation office sentencing guidelines. That way,
McConnell hoped, he could avoid the appearance of taking a
supposedly hard-nosed downstate attitude toward a case tried in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McConnell went out of his way to treat the Abernathy
family with dignity and respect. He paid tribute to Abernathy's
father as one of the most admired men of the last century and noted
the defendant has talents that could benefit his community _ once
he pays his debt to society.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Abernathy's supporters continue to maintain this
wasn't a prosecution, but rather a persecution on the basis of
race. For instance, Hosea Williams, a longtime friend of the
Abernathy family, takes the tack that the defendant only did what
other legislators do.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams has evidence of wrongdoing by other lawmakers,
whatever their color, he ought to present it to appropriate
authorities. In any event, his rationale for Abernathy's
transgressions is no defense.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial originally appeared in The Atlanta Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
