<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Feb. 6)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; In the Footsteps of the Impressionists &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Paris, always a city for browsers, is even more so if you have
in hand ``Impressionist Paris: The Essential Guide to the City of
Light.'' Written by Julian More and published by Pavilion/Trafalgar
Square ($19.95 for the paperback), the book provides detailed
itineraries for 30 walks and drives in and around the city, along
routes well worn by Monet, Manet, Cezanne, Pissarro, Sisley and
their artistic brethren. It provides a way to see, or at least
imagine, the charm and elegance of late 19th-century Paris through
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The book begins with a brief introduction to Impressionism, from
its early days in the Fontainebleau forest to its final days in
Paris and southern France. Organized geographically, the chapters _
on Montmartre, the Seine River valley, both banks of the Seine in
Paris and the River Oise, to name a few _ are full of information,
both historical and practical (like public transportation, hotels
and restaurants).
</P>
<P>
   Say you would like to visit Auvers-sur-Oise, Cezanne and van
Gogh country, which More advises is a 90-minute train ride from
Gare St.-Lazare. He recommends two restaurants and a B&AMP;B, then
suggests a half-day walk that takes you past the church made famous
by van Gogh, the cemetery where he is buried and the Rue
Francois-Coppee, where Cezanne loved to paint.
</P>
<P>
   The book, illustrated with reproductions and photographs,
includes a who's who of the artists, brief sketches of the museums
whose holdings are discussed and a bibliography for those who want
to know more about what they have seen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Crude Oil Prices Cause Air Fare Surcharges &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices have soared, and air passengers are paying for
it. All of the major domestic airlines are imposing a fuel
surcharge on domestic tickets. The charge is $10 on one-way tickets
and $20 on round trips, except for Alaska Airlines, a mostly
short-haul carrier on the West Coast that is charging half as much,
and US Airways, which is limiting the surcharge to advance-purchase
fares.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, which has both low fares and short flights, is
imposing a charge of $2 on flights up to 600 miles, $6 for 600 to
900 miles and $8 for longer flights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fuel surcharge is the equivalent of about a 3-4 percent
increase in overall domestic fares, according to Brian D. Harris,
the airline industry analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. Harris said
the flat surcharge was unfair to people who took short flights
because the fee was the same whether one flew the 200 miles between
New York and Washington or across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines, the first to add the surcharge, put it in
effect last month. Other airlines quickly followed after Delta
imposed the fee. Delta's decision was key because it has contracts
that allow it to buy most of its fuel at last year's prices. But as
world crude oil prices have gone up, the cost of jet fuel has
doubled in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In Montreal, a Multimedia Festival &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Montreal loves festivals, and is starting a new one Friday: the
Montreal High Lights Festival. Through March 4, the city will
celebrate the culinary arts, performing arts and museums and
lighting arts, with more than 2,000 artists participating.
</P>
<P>
   The opening performance on Friday will feature Jessye Norman,
who will sing spirituals and a new piece by the French jazz
composer and pianist Michel Legrand at the Wilfrid-Pelletier
Theater in Place des Arts (tickets $25 to $104, at 1.5 Canadian to
the dollar). The festival will close with a multimedia homage to
the music from the film ``The Red Violin'' with the violinist
Joshua Bell at the Molson Center ($18 to $54). A Bach mini-festival
at the Centre Pierre-Peladeau from Feb. 26 to 28 honors the 250th
anniversary of Bach' death; $12 for the 7:30 p.m. concert, $15 for
the 10:30 p.m. performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first Montreal International Symposium on Lighting will
feature displays by lighting specialists at six parks throughout
the city. A multimedia show titled ``This Is a Sphere'' will be
shown free each evening at 5:30 and 7:15 by the Place des Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of the French chef Paul Bocuse, the festival
also showcases the city's cuisine. Montreal chefs have invited
chefs from Europe and the United States to join them in producing
special menus at 50 restaurants; visitors with festival passports
will be given a 15 percent discount. There will also be workshops
and tasting events ($20 to $110), with some lectures and events
free. Information: (514) 288-9955, (888) 477-9955 or
www.montrealhighlights.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A New View of the Firmament &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Manhattan, earthbound since the old-fashioned but
beloved Hayden Planetarium closed in 1997, will once again be able
to scan the galaxies beginning this month. The $210 million
Frederick Phineas and Sandra Priest Rose Center for Earth and Space
at the American Museum of Natural History in New York opens two
major spaces on Feb. 19: The new Hayden Planetarium and the Dorothy
and Lewis B. Cullman Hall of the Universe. The center's third hall,
the David S. and Ruth L. Gottesman Hall of Planet Earth, opened in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic spherical planetarium soars 87 feet into the air
and from the outside appears suspended inside a 95-foot-high glass
cube. It has been divided into hemispheres. The visit begins with
an elevator ride to the darkened anteroom of the planetarium, where
visitors are given a video introduction to the Rose Center. They
proceed to the Space Theater, the top section of the sphere, where
they take seats to watch ``Passport to the Universe,'' a 23-minute
journey though space narrated by Tom Hanks. The presentation, based
on data collected from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratories and the
Hubble Space Telescope, is not limited to Earth-based observations
as the old planetarium show was. Visitors inside the Digital Dome
will feel as though they are soaring through space as they travel
beyond the Milky Way, stopping at the rings of Saturn, supernovas,
the Orion nebula, the Andromeda Galaxy and a black hole. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lower hemisphere houses the Big Bang Theater. Visitors stand
on a glass floor and look down into a simulation of the dawn of the
Universe. The Harriet and Robert Heilbrunn Cosmic Pathway, a curved
ramp that winds around the exterior of the planetarium, leads from
the Big Bang through 13 billion years of cosmic evolution, at the
rate of about 3 million years per inch.
</P>
<P>
   The Cullman Hall of the Universe presents the discoveries of
modern astrophysics _ the evolution of the universe, how atoms were
created, where life originated and how stars, galaxies and planets
were formed. Ecosphere, focusing on the search for extraterrestrial
life, and Astro-Bulletin, a log of space-related current events,
are highlights of the hall.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Center is at the American Museum of Natural History on
Central Park West and 79th Street; (212) 769-5100. Show times are
being determined. Suggested museum admission, including the Rose
Center, is $10; $7.50 students and seniors, $6 for children;
combination ticket including the space show is $19, $14 students
and seniors and $11.50 for children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
