<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Feb. 6) 
(jt) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Vienna Performances &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Several couples will be in Vienna the last weekend in May and
would like to see performances of the Vienna Boys Choir and the
Lipizzaner horses. Is this possible? _ H.C., Upper Saddle River,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are opportunities to see both of these Vienna
traditions on the last weekend in May, but you may have to act
quickly to get tickets
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish Riding School's Lipizzaners will prance in a regular
80-minute performance on Sunday, May 28, at 10:45 a.m. At this
writing, only standing-room tickets are left, the director's office
said. These cost about $14.50, at 13.7 schillings to the dollar,
and can be ordered from Spanish Riding School, Michaelerplatz 1,
A-1010 Vienna, Austria; (43-1) 533-9031, fax (43-1) 535-0186; or at
www.spanische-reitschule.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unlucky in getting these tickets (or prefer to sit),
it may be possible to see the slightly shorter Saturday ``Classical
Art of Riding With Music'' show. Tickets for these 10 a.m. events,
essentially training sessions with music, must be obtained from one
of about two dozen travel agencies in Vienna. The tickets cost
about $25, including a service charge. These seats in the
classically Baroque arena are not assigned.
</P>
<P>
   The school's Web site lists the agents, but among them is
American Express Reiseburo, Kaerntnerstrasse 21-23, A 1015 Vienna;
(43-1) 515-400, fax (43-1) 5154-0777.
</P>
<P>
   For 502 years, the Vienna Boys Choir has performed at Sunday
morning Mass at the Burgkapelle at the Hofburg, and it is to
continue that tradition on May 28 at 9:15. Tickets (about $30) are
obtained through the Imperial Chapel at (43-1) 533-9927, fax (43-1)
533-9927-75 and by e-mail at Hofmusikkapelle(at)asnwien.ac.at. Ask
for seats with a view of the choir.
</P>
<P>
   The choir also sings on Fridays at Musikverien, the concert hall
on Karlsplatz. Tickets, $28 to $40, are available from Mondial
Destination Management in Vienna, (43-1) 588-040, fax (43-1)
587-1268.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Irish Golf Outing &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My siblings and I are planning to visit Ireland and we'd like
to hold our annual family golf tournament there, probably near
Dublin or in Galway. Who could help us organize such an outing for
12 to 15 people who would want to rent clubs? _ Robert Powers, Des
Moines
</P>
<P>
   A. The equivalent of the United States Golf Association in
Ireland _ albeit much smaller _ is the Golfing Union of Ireland.
According to Pat Finn, assistant to the general secretary, the
union does not make arrangements for playing, or handle golf
packages, but it can provide a list of courses and of companies
that put together packages.
</P>
<P>
   You can address such inquiries to Seamus Smith, General
Secretary, Golfing Union of Ireland, Glencar House, 81 Eglinton
Rd., Donnybrook, Dublin 4; or call (353-1) 269-4111 or fax (353-1)
269-5368.
</P>
<P>
   Finn noted that the courses in Galway were likely to be less
busy than those near Dublin, though he said there were more than
enough in any region to handle your family. He cautioned that some
courses might not have as many sets of clubs for rent as your party
would need.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of his personal suggestions were Galway Bay Golf and Hotel
Resort, Renville, Oranmore, Galway, (353-91) 790-500; Galway Golf
Club, Blackrock, Salthill, Galway, (553-91) 522-033, and Connemara
Golf Club, Ballyconneely, Clifden, Galway, (353-95) 23502. (But
Connemara says it does not have enough rental clubs for your
group.) Greens fees and club rental would be about $24 at Galway,
and about $44 at Galway Bay, at $1.25 to the Irish pound. More
information about these and other golf courses is available on the
union's Web site, www.gui.ie.
</P>
<P>
   Among companies that handle golf packages, with or without
travel and lodging, is Golfing Ireland, 18 Parnell Square, Dublin
1, (353-1) 872-6711, fax (353-1) 6632; www.golfing &QC; -ireland.com.
For reservations, call (353-66) 979-2022. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To simply learn about courses, www.uk-golf.com has information
on many by region.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Elephants in Amboseli &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We'd like a guided tour of three to five days in Amboseli
National Park in Kenya, with an emphasis on the elephants studied
by Cynthia Moss. Are such tours available in English? _ M.S., New
York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Safaris are big business in Kenya, where English is widely
spoken. The Kenya Association of Tour Operators alone lists more
than 200 members, and how to contact them, at www.gorp.com/kato; or
you can contact the association at Post Office Box 48461, Nairobi,
Kenya; (254-2) 225570, fax (254-2) 218402. The association said
that the park itself does not have guides but that many of its
members offered drivers and guides.
</P>
<P>
   So finding a guide is not difficult; finding one right for you
may be. Probably the best way is to deal with a travel consultant
in the United States who is familiar with Kenya. Two experienced
ones are Bruce Baum and Mackey Arnstein, and either can arrange as
much or as little of your excursion as you want.
</P>
<P>
   Baum, who runs Kenya Consultants, 4 Miller Road, Mount Tremper,
N.Y. 12457, (914) 688-5951, fax (914) 688-2438, has been going to
Kenya for 19 years. His recommendation, depending on your budget,
is to hire Tony Archer, a former hunter who, he said, is a friend
of Ms. Moss, who is known for her pictures of Amboseli elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Baum said Archer charged $250 a person a day and could arrange
for all your needs, including a car and driver, which would be
extra. (A private tour for two could easily cost $700 a person a
day.) He suggested staying at Tortilis, a tent camp bordering the
park, which both he and Ms. Arnstein called comfortable and well
maintained. Baum, whose e-mail address is
brucebaum(at)earthlink.net, asserted that his 15 percent commission
was less than that of Kenyan operators.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arnstein, who has been handling tours to Kenya since 1972,
said there were probably better areas to study elephants than in
Amboseli, which is relatively easy to reach. Its popularity has
resulted in limits on travel within the park, and a private guide
might not get you close to many more animals than a group tour
would, she said. So unless you are more interested in Ms. Moss than
in elephants, she might suggest other destinations, like Tarangire
National Park in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where you choose to go, her East Africa Safari
Co., 1500 Broadway, New York, N.Y. 10036, (800) 772-3274, (212)
840-7800 in New York City, fax (212) 840-9411, can arrange for a
guide, lodging and travel _ or any of those elements.
</P>
</TEXT>
