<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERRIN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another week, another 100-year storm
 &HT;    By Jeff Herrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Locusts, anyone? Boils? Hives? Horrible
lesions?
</P>
<P>
   Wanna rent some garments?
</P>
<P>
   It's the end of the world as we know it, and I feel cold.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain part of me that's sure I'll turn on the tube
tomorrow morning and find one of the Storm Team Men With Deep
Voices pointing to an Accu-Trac model of a poxes-upon-these-houses
system.
</P>
<P>
   He'll make sweeping arm gestures toward doomsday icons and tell
us in his friendly let's-not-be-alarmed-but-for-God's-sakes-run
kinda voice that quite frankly we're all gonna die. Then we'll flip
off the tube, go outside and play in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's it going?'' my brother in Florida asked last week over
the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you know, I said. Another week, another storm of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said. ``We might get some rain here.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll freely admit it. I could enjoy the snow a lot more if it
weren't for people like ... well, like myself. We in the media seem
determined to chart the landing of every snowflake in the state. I
think we feel better about ourselves for informing the public, even
when our latest cause for alarm can be summed up in two words:
</P>
<P>
   It snowed.
</P>
<P>
   I worked once for a young, professional city editor who spent an
entire February morning checking in an authoritative voice with
everyone who trudged into the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim,'' he asked as one of the veteran reporters began taking
off wraps. ``What's the scene today in Davidson County?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's damn cold,'' Jim said. ``What'd you think?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a pain, all of this. We have to figure out who owns trucks
that can make it through the stuff, then map out ways to get copy
editors here. And I can't even begin to comprehend the nightmares
that Circulation's having.
</P>
<P>
   But every once in a while we catch sight of our real selves. The
phones don't ring as much in weeks like this. I can gaze out my
office window at the brilliant majesty of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The folks in Creative Services built a structure of twigs and
snow on top of a trash can just outside the door. Granted, it
looked like something out of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' but at
least it captured the spirit of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee somehow tastes better. Spirits are higher. Our sense
of purpose is larger.
</P>
<P>
   I drove home at lunch one day to find a broken snowman lying in
three pieces in my yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rise and fall of Snowbodan Milosevic,'' I told the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the jokes aren't any better.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I remember the reckless winter of 1981 when we spent
every weekend sliding off mountainsides to be with each other. I
was in my first newspaper job. She was a senior at Appalachian
State.
</P>
<P>
   Snow didn't seem such an apocalypse then. Just a beautiful
backdrop to something bigger.
</P>
<P>
   It's something to think about as I grumble my way to the car
each morning for another half-hour of championship windshield
scraping.
</P>
<P>
   It's damn cold. But it's improving.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Herrin is the editor of the Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky
Mount, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
