<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2188 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-NH-INSURGENTS-HNS &LR;      01-31 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-INSURGENTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN, BRADLEY LOOK BEYOND NEW HAMPSHIRE  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H.  &Cx1f; _ Republican John McCain and Democrat Bill
Bradley, who will wrap up insurgent campaigns against front-runners
in the New Hampshire presidential primary on Tuesday, face
dramatically different challenges in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is banking that a strong showing in the nation's first
presidential primary will enable his populist crusade to make
inroads against Texas Gov. George W. Bush in South Carolina,
Arizona and Michigan over the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, bracing for a setback at the hands of Vice President Al
Gore in their rivalry for the Democratic nomination, is looking to
the next contests to help rescue a faltering bid to succeed
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The latest public opinion surveys showed McCain leading Bush
while Bradley trailed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's strength nationally, 10 of 11 surveys in the
final days of the New Hampshire contest showed McCain ahead of Bush
by margins that ranged from 1 percentage point to 15 percentage
points. The 11 surveys showed Gore leading Bradley, with margins of
victory ranging from 3 percentage points to 14 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear friends, young and old, rich and poor, from all over
the state of New Hampshire, all I can do is ask you to get out our
vote tomorrow,'' McCain, the senior senator from Arizona, told
several hundred supporters in front of the New Hampshire state
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident we will achieve victory if you do that,''
McCain added. ``I am not afraid of losing, my dear friends, and I'm
very confident of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, addressing dozens of employees of the Oracle Corp.'s
computer software development operation in Nashua, made a pitch for
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask for your vote tomorrow,'' said Bradley, who represented
New Jersey in the Senate for 18 years. ``And I hope you will feel
if you cast that vote, that you're part of something that is new
and fresh and that we're at a time of a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley already were casting their eyes down the
campaign trail, with plans to depart New Hampshire within hours of
the returns coming in on Tuesday night. McCain, joined in Concord
by Republican Reps. Lindsay Graham and Mark Sanford of South
Carolina, said his expected success in New Hampshire would
strengthen his hand in South Carolina's GOP primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to win the state of South Carolina,'' McCain told
the crowd, as he stood in front of a mountain of snow bedecked with
his campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   McCain still faces an uphill struggle in South Carolina, with
the latest CNN-Time survey in that state showing McCain trailing
Bush by 20 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, hoping to underscore what spokesman Eric Hauser
described as a long-term challenge to Gore, mapped plans for
campaign appearances in Connecticut, New York City, San Francisco,
Baltimore and Tampa, Fla., by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley were preparing to leave New Hampshire with
the centerpieces of their challenges well established. Both made
town hall-style question-and-answer sessions the hallmark of their
campaigns. Both vowed to reform the way political campaigns are
financed by restricting donations that are largely unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley hit their populist theme on the final day on
the hustings here in New Hampshire, where an overnight snowstorm
lifted by midday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow night, we will send a message to America and the
world that the American people feel that they want someone who is
fully prepared to be president of United States, (someone) who
needs no on-the-job training,'' McCain declared. ``There will be
the message that the American people want to get the government out
of the hands of the special interests and the big money and be
represented again.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has criticized Bush's fund-raising, adding that ``the
corruption that characterized the campaign of 1996 by Clinton and
Gore will not be tolerated in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley echoed the theme. ``I hope that the independent-minded
people of New Hampshire will send a message to this country that
the old ways are over and the new politics has arrived,'' Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley have courted independents _ the largest bloc
of voters in the Granite State's electorate. Independents are
permitted to cast ballots in either party's presidential primary
and then re-register as independents. Of the state's 738,422
registered voters, 37 percent are independents, 36 percent are
Republicans and 27 percent are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Secretary of State William Gardner forecast that
independents would account for nearly one-quarter of the vote,
casting an expected 80,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   But two independent voters said on Monday that they would cast
ballots in the GOP primary for McCain rather than voting in the
Democratic primary for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Davison, 37, a software developer with Oracle living in
Amherst, said he wanted to hear Bradley speak before making up his
mind. But Davison said afterwards that he would vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my vote to make a difference,'' Davison said, noting
that Bradley is far behind Gore in the latest polls. ``I think we
can send a message with McCain that we can't send by voting for
Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul De Angelis, 64, of Concord, a retired printing press
operator, said that he would vote for McCain because ``he tells it
like it is, he doesn't lie.'' De Angelis, who said that he was so
inspired by President John F. Kennedy that he named his first born
son after the slain president, said that McCain commands the same
kind of devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What scares me about Bush is all that campaign money,'' De
Angelis said. ``It makes me afraid that if he gets in, all he'll do
is help big business.''
</P>
<P>
   De Angelis said that even if McCain wins on Tuesday, he faces
immense challenges in follow-on primaries. ``New Hampshire could be
a good stepping stone for him,'' De Angelis said. ``But he'll have
a tough road ahead against all Bush's money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign announced Monday that the Texas governor has
raised $68.7 million. McCain has raised $15.6 million, including $2
million transferred from his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed with the Federal Election Commission showed that
Bush had $31.4 million in the bank as of Dec. 31 _ four times the
estimated $7.7 million that McCain has available to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley remain more closely matched. Bradley has raised
more than $27 million; Gore has raised $28.2 million. Bradley has
$19.7 million available from donations and federal matching funds
compared to Gore, who has $18.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Bradley are banking on New Hampshire voters to
help upset the well-laid plans of party front-runners, as has
happened in the past.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush's quest for a second term ran into trouble
in the primary here in 1992 when the incumbent eked out victory
over populist GOP challenger Patrick Buchanan. Buchanan's 37
percent against Bush's 52 percent revealed vulnerabilities that
contributed to Bush's subsequent loss to Democrat Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Jimmy Carter's bid for a second term encountered
trouble here in the 1980 primary, where he managed to win 47
percent of the Democratic vote compared to 37 percent rolled up by
his liberal challenger, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts.
Carter lost to Ronald Reagan in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
