<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For new Coke CEO, headaches come with job
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Less than two months ago, few people outside of
Coca-Cola would recognize Doug Daft's name.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company's new president and chairman-designate has had
his picture and comments in newspapers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could do without it,'' Daft said Monday in an interview. ``I
could assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows it's human nature to enjoy the sudden notoriety that
comes with achieving a top position in the corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to see themselves in print,'' Daft said. But,
he added, all the attention has gotten old fairly quickly,
especially with the issues he now has to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Daft announced a major reorganization of the world's
largest soft-drink company, just 53 days after he was named
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   He said the reorganization, which involves cutting 6,000 jobs,
including 2,500 in Atlanta, was the most ``difficult and
devastating'' decision he has made.
</P>
<P>
   While the 56-year-old executive may not like all the publicity,
he knows it goes with the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize it's part of the role, a critical part of the
role,'' Daft said. ``I want to build relationships with the media
and the community.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Atlanta investors should understand that his recent
moves are being made to strengthen the company over the long-term.
If the company becomes stronger, he said, Atlanta will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to be an integral and important part of the
Atlanta community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the overall direction of the company has been decided,
Daft said, he will be spending more time talking with his top
management team about how to implement the strategy, which includes
decentralizing the company.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, he said, ``We'll be putting some real meat
around the strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft said he has been putting in his normal 12-hour workdays,
but there's one key difference from his former job heading Coke's
Middle East, Far East and African operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days are much more pressured, because the decisions affect
many more people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To take some of the enormous pressure off, Daft said he spent
last weekend with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did some cross-country skiing,'' he said. ``It tends to
clear the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
