A2190 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-31 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOM, DADDY, I'M PREGNANT' _ IT'S DECISION TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By O. RICARDO PIMENTEL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - (begin ital) A fictional account of an important chat
with a 15-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Background: I have one. So does Arizona Sen. John McCain. I
suspect most of the press corps on McCain's bus do not. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: Mom, Daddy, I need to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Mom: OK, sweetie, what's on your mind?
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Uh, OK. (Dread, dread, dread. Puts down the remote control.
Knows it's trouble when he gets called ``Daddy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Daughter (tears and sobs): I know . . . I mean . . . What I'm
trying to say . . .
</P>
<P>
   Mom: (hugging daughter): Go ahead, sweetie. You can tell us
anything. (Looks at Dad.)
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Anything, honey.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: I'm pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   (Dumbfounded silence. Mom looks at Dad, tears in her eyes. Dad
tries to unclench his jaw. Unclenches when he suddenly remembers
daughter as 3-year-old in pigtails with bright red fat cheeks, who
giggles and smiles while playing silly games with him. Anger at
first. Then, as daughter continues crying, anger softens to
concern. Mom hugs daughter harder, looks at Dad.)
</P>
<P>
   Dad: Who? I'm sorry. I know who. What do you want to do? Do you
want to have the baby (he asks hopefully)? I mean, you know we'll
help, right? You know, you and the baby can be with us.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: I don't know, Daddy. I think . . . Oh, God, I know how
disappointed you are . . . I mean, what if . . . I don't know if
I'm ready to have a baby. We've been talking about . . . about . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Dad: You mean an abortion?
</P>
<P>
   Daughter (head nods): It's just that . . . God, I'm still in
high school. I want to go to college. I know we're Catholic and
we're not supposed to believe in abortion, but . . . (tears start
again).
</P>
<P>
   (Mom and Dad resist temptation to say, ``You should have thought
of all of that before.'' Both suddenly remember being 15.)
</P>
<P>
   Mom: What's he want to do? You're too young to be married. I
mean, it takes two to tango. What's he want to do?
</P>
<P>
   Dad: I don't care what he wants to do. He's not having the baby
(angry now).
</P>
<P>
   Mom: I just mean he has responsibilities here, too, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Dad (unclenching jaw again): What's he going to do? Quit high
school? Work at McDonald's? Try to support our daughter on minimum
wage and no health insurance?
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: We don't want to get married.
</P>
<P>
   Dad (hands go to head): It feels like the right thing to do is
to have the baby. God, but (exasperated now) you're just 15! You
know how we feel about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: Like you said, I'm the one who's pregnant. This is my
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dad (considers telling her that Arizona is a parental-consent
state. Reconsiders. Deep sigh.): Sweetie, I know. But this is a
decision, no matter which way we go (emphasizing the ``we''), that
will have lasting consequences. If you have the baby, we'll help.
If you don't have the baby, I think you'll always wonder . . . was
it the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter (nodding): I know. I've thought this through. I think I
need to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Dad (considers telling her he won't have anything to do with
this. Looks at Mom. He wonders, how do you force someone who
doesn't want a baby to have one?): How about adoption?
</P>
<P>
   Daughter (shakes head emphatically): I know I've done wrong,
Daddy. I know you maybe think abortion is murder.
</P>
<P>
   Dad (realizes he can't think of his daughter as a murderer under
any circumstances, even with abortion): It looks like you've
thought this through. I guess my choice is to help or not. (Pause)
</P>
<P>
   Put your own ending on this story. I've got mine and I'm keeping
it to myself because, frankly, it's none of your business. And,
it's also none of your business what McCain would do in this
fictional episode.
</P>
<P>
   He's answered the abortion question several times. We know he
doesn't favor abortion except in cases of rape or incest. From a
public policy standpoint, I have no difficulty discerning where he
stands.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was right both times, when he said it would be his
daughter's decision and again when he said it would be the
family's. It is her decision, but it is not a decision she must
make alone.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be less enamored of ``gotcha'' journalism and more
concerned with the real question. I don't care what McCain would do
with his own daughter. I care what he would do with mine and yours.
That's why they call it public policy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Pimentel at Ricardo.Pimentel(at)ArizonaRepublic.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
