<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      01-31 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RAGE AGAINST THE MACHINE? WHY, YES, DON'T MIND IF I
DO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're in the midst of what promises to be the most expensive
presidential primary season in history, and I think we'd all have
to agree it's been money well-spent. Sure, bloated, sybaritic rock
stars tour the world on smaller budgets, but they don't entertain
us nearly as much.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets and schools and greasy spoons of Iowa and New
Hampshire, no hand has gone unshaken, no rock unturned (oh, lookie,
another Pat Buchanan supporter!), no issue unkicked.
</P>
<P>
   It's still early in the campaign, but those of us watching on TV
at home already have learned many valuable things about the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   We know, for instance, that John McCain is simultaneously for
and against abortion, Confederate flags, and a slew of other stuff;
that Al Gore and at least one old friend can't agree on when Gore
quit smoking marijuana; and that George W. Bush has seen a
grocery-store scanner and knows what it's used for. (We have
established that, right?)
</P>
<P>
   The scanner question, of course, is not trivial. Every campaign
has to have at least one defining moment, whether it's a candidate
forgetting where he last found Poland on a map (Ford), or taking an
ill-timed look at his watch (Bush the Elder), or climbing atop a
tank and posing for a goofy photo (Dukakis).
</P>
<P>
   Such things may seem silly in retrospect, but they help us
decide whether the candidates really know what our lives are like,
or whether they're hopelessly out of touch, like some bloated,
sybaritic rock star.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea when or where the defining moments of the 2000
campaign will occur, but I'm pretty sure one just happened in a
mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   You may have missed it, but the subject of moshing _ a youthful
art that, among other things, involves passing youthful bodies
overhead, usually to the accompaniment of youthful music _ arose
unexpectedly during last week's presidential debate in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wobbly on this issue, now may be the time to study up
on it and take a firm stand. (I've never moshed myself, although I
once had a co-worker who insisted the phrase was ``gnosh'' pit,
which prompted me to daydream about franchising a chain of highly
profitable gnosh-and-mosh pits. Alas, an investor has yet to step
forward.)
</P>
<P>
   This is complicated, so please bear with me. The way I
understand it, Republican candidate Alan Keyes emerged from a rally
in Iowa recently and was hoisted in the air by folks outside. He
was then passed from person to person as a song by the rock group
Rage Against the Machine played in the background.
</P>
<P>
   This apparently irked fellow GOP candidate Gary Bauer to no end.
Bauer, who is emerging as one of the premier scolds of our day,
declared during the debate that he was ``a little surprised'' at
Keyes' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As George W. Bush no doubt looked on anxiously (``Josh Pitts? Is
he prime minister of some place?''), Bauer proceeded to chide Keyes
at length for being anywhere within earshot of tunes put out by, as
Bauer called it, ``The Machine Rages On.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said those ``killers in Columbine'' listened to music like
that and engaged in such hooliganism. ``Do you think that's
consistent with the dignity of the president?'' he asked,
witheringly.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, apparently taken off guard, said he was ``not morally
responsible for the music that was playing'' and began blathering
as if he were being questioned as part of an impeachment trial. ``I
had nothing to do with that music, disclaim any knowledge of it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed further, Keyes defiantly said he'd had fun in the mosh
pit and noted with pride that he'd kept his tie straight the whole
time. ``The real test of dignity is how you carry yourself in hard
times,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, you said it, pal. And we voters are finding our ties all
askew.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, neither Bauer nor Keyes has a chance of winning the
GOP nomination. But when they drop out, which could be any day now,
I'll miss them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I think the United States should be more like
countries where the winners _ say, Prime Minister Josh Pitts _ are
forced to serve with some of the also-rans in a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
   With a stage of presidential candidates this thoughtful and this
talented, it seems a pity to throw any of them into the pit just
yet.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is an editorial writer at the Herald-Tribune in
Sarasota, Fla. His e-mail address is
daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2193 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b x BC-EDITORIAL-CUBA-BOS &LR;      01-31 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CUBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRAVE CUBAN'S MANIFESTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS GAGEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cubans can gripe about the oppressive reality of daily life to
themselves and to foreigners, but if they try to put their
complaints into organized political activity, they invariably get
into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fate of Oswaldo Paya, one of the most respected
Cuban dissidents, whom I interviewed in Havana last month. ``Cuba
is in a very dangerous moment,'' he said, `The new wealthy (class)
is gaining control of all the assets. The United States is playing
the stability card. It wants no exodus.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Soviet Union collapsed, Fidel Castro has transformed
Cuba's economy. It now relies on European and Canadian investment,
money from tourists, and remittances from Cuban-Americans, all in
US dollars. Castro divvies up the money, with much going to the
military-security complex.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which ought to be making plans for a
long-term transition to democracy, is preoccupied with the
complexities of an imperfect trade embargo and management of the
refugee problem, as personified by Elian Gonzalez. Paya's analysis
was right on target, and he outlined a plan to transform the
country:
</P>
<P>
   --Cubans alone must define the process of change, but Cuban
exiles, ``an inseparable part of the Cuban people,'' should take an
active part in solving Cuban problems.
</P>
<P>
   --The United States should end the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   --Foreigners should not invest in Cuba until Cubans are allowed
to exercise economic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   --``Project Varela'' should be implemented. This is Paya's plan
to gather 10,000 signatures so that a bill could be presented to
the Cuban assembly to allow freedom of association and the press
and the establishment of small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba and the United States are so closely intertwined that a
cutoff of economic activity is impossible. And Cuban-Americans pour
hundreds of millions of dollars in each year to help friends and
relatives. The embargo has failed to promote Castro's overthrow or
cause him to change his ways. Paya is right that it should be
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Castro has long derided the exile community as ``gusanos'' or
worms. Yet they love their country of birth and are sustaining it
with their donations. Paya was vague as to how he would involve
them in Cuba's future, but their active support would do much to
ease the transition to a new Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Castro makes much of the damages supposedly inflicted by the
embargo, but Soviet subsidies and now foreign investment, mostly
from Europe and Canada, have done much to mitigate its effects.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lives of most people are made difficult by a
two-tier economy. Those with dollars do well, but those who depend
only on earnings in Cuban pesos cannot make ends meet. Physicians
in the state health service make the equivalent of $15 to $16 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Food is available, but it is plain fare for those without
dollars. Public transit in Havana consists of a few buses and
trucks pulling trailers, called ``camels,'' that hold 300 people.
Automobiles are few and creaky (those famous American '50s relics
are still running) but there are enough new sub-subcompact Subarus
and Fiats darting about to suggest that the government is rewarding
favored people with reliable transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The Varela project, named after a famous Cuban priest, is
intended to begin a process of great change. Working within the
constitution, Paya wants to improve the economy quickly by
promoting the growth of small businesses, then begin an
unrestricted dialogue about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is 73, and although he is looking remarkably hale, change
is coming when he dies. The worst scenarios have the country riven
by civil strife and US troops intervening. More likely, the army,
security forces, and the Communist Party will coalesce around an
individual or junta to maintain their grip on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans, repressed and impoverished for 40 years under Castro,
deserve better. They need an opportunity to open the economic and
political life of the country while sustaining the education and
health-care systems that are the strong points of the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want violent change,'' Paya said. ``We don't want the
strongest to be in charge.'' Even in an hour's interview, he seemed
to exhibit the compelling presence, conviction, and intelligence
that would make him a leader in a transformed Cuba. Unfortunately,
the Christian Liberation Movement, his political group, has only
400 members and is unlikely to get many more.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, he and several other dissidents were arrested as
they were about to discuss a human-rights initiative. They were
released after a few hours, but they did not hold their meeting.
The security services are adept at preventing dissidents from
coalescing into a formidable faction.
</P>
<P>
   I left Cuba the next day, impressed by the endurance of the
people in coping with everyday difficulties and Paya's courage in
seeking to get his message to Americans. Cuba is a lush island,
with a distinctive Afro-Latin culture and great potential for
economic and political growth, but when Castro's government thwarts
the aspiration of Paya and people like him, it becomes little more
than East Germany with palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS GAGEN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UPS01-COX     01-31 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS sees unusual situation: earnings report good but stock drops
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service reported better-than-expected
fourth-quarter earnings on Monday, but saw its stock drop more than
8 percent _ by $5.43 3/4 to $59.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the reason'' for the slump on Wall Street, said
spokesman Norman Black.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one analyst blamed it on unrealistic expectations
about how much and how fast Internet-related sales would add
noticeably to UPS's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started to get excited about the big Internet sales and
strong Christmas,'' said analyst Peter V. Coleman of Banc of
America Securities. ``They see online shopping doubled this year...
and they look for 20 percent'' increase in package volume from UPS,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take a while for Internet shopping to have a major
impact on a company that delivered more than 14 million packages a
day in the fourth quarter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the rising cost of fuel, Coleman said, the Sandy Springs
package delivery company ``knocked the cover off the ball'' in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, UPS reported a 37 percent increase in fourth-quarter
net income, while revenue grew just under 12 percent. Growth in
higher-margin services, an increase in international profit, and
results from its excess insurance business were behind the climb in
earnings, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Net income was $661 million, or 56 cents a share, in the latest
quarter, the first since UPS went public in November. The company
earned $482 million, or 43 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose to $7.45 billion from $6.66 billion. Wall Street had forecast
UPS would earn 55 cents in the 1999 fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Airborne Freight on Monday announced a 62 percent
fall in fourth-quarter profit, and blamed a decline in domestic
shipments and higher fuel costs. In December, FedEx reported a 6.6
percent dip in quarterly profit. FedEx cited fuel costs and
slower-than-expected growth in domestic shipments.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, UPS reported revenue of $27.05 billion.
Excluding a $1.44 billion tax assessment, the company would have
earned $2.33 billion, or $2.04 a share, last year.
</P>
<P>
   UPS, which held a conference call with analysts after announcing
its results, did not offer a specific forecast for this year. But
analyst Coleman, who says he is on the high side of the range of
forecasts, looks for UPS to earn $2.40 a share in 2000, and $2.75
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference call, UPS said it will not add a surcharge
to help offset rising fuel prices. The company traditionally
adjusts shipping rates early in the year, and the cost of fuel is
one factor.
</P>
<P>
   Late in December, UPS announced average rate hikes of 2.9
percent for international shipments, 3.1 percent for ground
shipments, and 3.5 percent for those that go by air. The increases
are effective Monday.
</P>
<P>
   David McNaughton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
