<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2195 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-HULL-AZR &LR;      01-31 2562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HULL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S `IRON LADY' ANSWERS HER CRITICS WITH WIT _ AND VETOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MIGH HAVE MISSED IT 
 
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It's a scene straight out of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   A young mother looks out over the barren high desert, her three
small children huddled behind her skirts. Horses graze out front as
a wagon rolls by.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Hull, you're not in Kansas anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Arizona's present governor was a 26-year-old
schoolteacher who left a comfortable Kansas City suburb and moved
to Chinle, a remote town on the Navajo Reservation in northern
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real culture shock,'' Hull recalled. ``We were there
in the days when the wagons pulled up for commodities at the
boarding school.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Terry, a doctor, had been assigned to Chinle by the
U.S. Public Health Service.
</P>
<P>
   There was no theater, no library; only a few trading posts.
There was no supermarket, so Hull did her shopping in Albuquerque,
planning family meals six weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first year, there was no TV . . . we had to make our own
fun,'' Hull said. ``We had more time to really enjoy each other, I
think, than I ever had, before or since.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull's time in Chinle offers a striking image of the governor as
a gritty frontier woman. But it doesn't square with the portrait
being painted by some detractors in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, they say that Hull is out of touch and over her head,
and being led around by her staff. As evidence, they point to an
excessive number of vetoes (21) last session and a breakdown in
communication with the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   As Hull, 64, begins her third year as governor, lawmakers are
grumbling that the real power is held by Hull's chief of staff,
Rick Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got sick last year . . . you saw a change,'' said
state Rep. Sue Gerard, R-north central Phoenix. ``Rick did gain
more power, and she did become more isolated. It became harder for
us to talk to her independent of Rick.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the capitol, the whispers have started. Has the Iron Lady
started to rust?
</P>
<P>
   Hull and her staff laugh off such claims. She says Collins takes
most of the flak, because that's his role as chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually too involved in too many things,'' Hull said. ``I
micromanage around here more than we would like. Everybody blames
it on Rick. It's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the office, Hull doesn't stand on ceremony. She sometimes
answers her own phone and gets her own coffee and is still
embarrassed when staff members rise when she enters a room.
</P>
<P>
   She's not much of a public speaker, actually more of a public
reader, as evidenced by her recent State of the State speech, which
was described by one catty observer as ``almost lifelike.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that Hull was speaking to a somewhat hostile
Legislature, including people who want to teach gun safety in
public schools, but don't care whether kids fall out of the back of
pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hull tried to entertain them a little, with a tame joke
or two. The speech's solitary attempt at statesmanship _ a Latin
phrase _ fell flat when Hull mangled it.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the spotlight, Hull is quick-witted and engaging. She
reminds one of former Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole,
whose singular wit never translated in big rooms.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Hull met with the media after her state
address, she ribbed one reporter for appearing to sleep through the
speech. &QL; 
A parent's patience Hull also exhibits the patience of someone who
has raised four children and taught thousands more. After 21 years
in public office, she boasts, ``I usually can get along with
everybody and anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor gently notes that she has turned the emphasis back
to helping people. She's proud of programs such as KidsCare, which
provides health insurance for the children of the working poor, and
Students FIRST, a plan to fix dilapidated school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   And Hull has another advantage over her predecessor, Fife
Symington. Her staff members aren't preoccupied with keeping their
boss out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   As for her dust-ups with the Legislature and House Speaker Jeff
Groscost, R-Mesa, Hull is puzzled. She spent 14 years in the House,
including two terms as speaker, so she knows how the Legislature
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem understanding why they just don't pick up the
phone and call me, at night or at home or whatever,'' Hull said.
``Because I've known a lot of them for a long time. And some of
them have said, `But you understand, you're now the governor, and
we can't do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Hull remains immersed in affairs of state,
attending meetings, taking work home, even e-mailing staffers in
the wee hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does her homework,'' said Collins, waving a handful of
bureaucratic minutiae that Hull will inevitably want to see. ``I
guess that's the schoolteacher in her.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, both the governor and Collins acknowledge that Hull's
hospital stay in March started tongues wagging. Was Hull gravely
ill? Could she still govern? Would she serve out her term?
</P>
<P>
   The illness gave an opening to Hull's enemies to undermine her
in a way that goes far beyond making fun of the governor's big hair
or knocking her for talking about curlers.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad that at one point, Collins was denying rumors that
Hull had a fatal liver disease.
</P>
<P>
   Hull admits she is sick _ sick of hearing about the issue. To
muzzle the gossip, Hull granted a reporter an interview with her
physician, Dr. Anita Murcko.
</P>
<P>
   Murcko said Hull was hospitalized with a serious kidney
infection. It started in the urinary tract and reached Hull's
bloodstream, but it did not advance to the more serious condition
of toxic shock.
</P>
<P>
   In typical Hull fashion, she tried not to create a fuss, walking
the short distance from her doctor's office to Good Samaritan
Regional Medical Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked over because she didn't want to alarm her security
guards,'' Murcko said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was treated with intravenous antibiotics and suffers no
lasting effects. She takes medication for arthritis and a thyroid
condition, and Murcko describes her as very healthy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rumors, Hull cracked, ``I keep saying they're jealous
because I've lost weight.''
</P>
<P>
   They also might be jealous of Hull's knack for always being in
the right place at the right time. Hull never has to run that hard.
The ball always comes right to her.
</P>
<P>
   She's the Silver Surfer of Arizona politics, riding a wave of
serendipity to the top of state government.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to the House in 1979, Hull made headlines in 1982 by
suggesting that the state could save money by allowing the swamp
coolers at the Perryville prison to fall into disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the swamp coolers will break down,'' she said. ``That
might get rid of some of our prison population.''
</P>
<P>
   As majority whip in 1987-88, Hull became the de facto majority
leader, filling in for an ailing Jim Ratliff. In 1989, she landed
in the speaker's chair after Joe Lane was ousted by voters angry
over Lane's role in the impeachment of former Gov. Evan Mecham.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was known as a no-nonsense speaker who kept her fellow
Republicans in line, never hesitating to bonk a fews heads if need
be. While speaker, she earned two nicknames _ ``Iron Lady'' from
her supporters and ``Dragon Lady'' from her enemies _ and weathered
the AzScam public corruption scandal, which led to criminal charges
against several legislators.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Hull inherited the Governor's Office from Symington,
who was forced out after being convicted of bank fraud. Symington's
conviction has since been overturned. Hull ran for re-election in
1998 and won by a wide margin. &QL; 
Shaky public relations
</P>
<P>
   Despite her long experience in state government, Hull is off to
a shaky start, at least as far as public relations go.
</P>
<P>
   When news leaked last year that the state was ordering a
14-year-old to have an abortion, Hull appeared to waffle.
</P>
<P>
   First, she said there was little the state could do. But as
public pressure mounted, Hull reversed field, calling on state
Attorney General Janet Napolitano to appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Hull took a bum rap in that case, which would be
clear when the records are made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was going this path until a document was set down in front
of her face, from a psychiatrist, that was contradictory to the
route she was going,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull also got some bad press for her push to install cable
barriers on Valley freeways. After several people were killed in
head-on collisions, Hull told the state Department of
Transportation to study the barriers.
</P>
<P>
   After a friend, former state legislator Polly Getzwiller, was
seriously injured in a similar crash, Hull cut the study short and
ordered the department to install the barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said her decision was not linked to the accident involving
Getzwiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a nice lady, and I know her . . . and some day we have
to find out if she's ever gotten out of the hospital,'' Hull said. &QL; 
Power struggleWhether Hull blows with the wind or not, one thing is
certain: She faces a Legislature that borders on insurrection. Some
lawmakers are upset because they didn't see Hull's vetoes coming
last session.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first I heard of it, a reporter called me,'' said Sen. Tom
Freestone, R-Mesa, an amiable ex-wrestler and fixture in Maricopa
County politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Guess what, Freestone. Your bill just got
slaughtered' . . . I was caught flat-footed.''
</P>
<P>
   Freestone, whose open-meetings bill should survive this session,
said he understands why legislators bristled at the vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like working through the whole season raising
crops, then you find out you had a tornado come through and destroy
everything,'' Freestone said.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, lawmakers may take the fight with Hull a step
further. In a move that smacks of bravado, they have hinted about a
``veto session'' _ reconvening to revive any bill struck down by
Hull.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about power, says Groscost, who believes Hull vetoed a
number of bills to re-establish control of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some of it was aimed at making sure she sent a
message to legislators who disagreed with her,'' Groscost said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In her mind, she tried to show that she was in charge and in
fact people better listen to what she had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Marc Spitzer, R-north-central Phoenix, said Hull had
good reasons behind her vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she vetoed bills for fun,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Hull says the vetoes were all about policy, not
payback. Most of them involved bills that called for spending
beyond the current budget, or bills that cut into the power of
state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Hull's disagreements have been with Groscost, who
clearly loves stirring the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Although they hail from the same party, Hull and Groscost
couldn't be more different. Hull is a member of the old guard, a
moderate, a grandmother and a Catholic. Groscost is a young turk, a
staunch conservative and a Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost sometimes sports the demeanor of a used car salesman,
but he's no dummy. He understands how to consolidate power and hold
it, and he lives for political gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Widening the rift, Hull chose to back Texas Gov. George W. Bush
for president, while Groscost and most other state Republicans are
pushing Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Groscost has baited Hull at every turn. He invited
National Rifle Association President Charlton Heston to address the
House, despite the governor's moderate position on guns.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, he held a downtown fund-raiser featuring skits
lampooning Hull.
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute to understatement, Hull said she was
``disappointed'' in the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you respect the governor or not, respect the office,''
Hull said. ``The fund-raiser and the singing, those things are not
a respect for the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull has also taken criticism for letting her various policy
experts lobby the Legislature, meaning her office doesn't speak
with one voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problem is, all of her staff people are real technocrats . . .
they don't know politics,'' Gerard said. ``Because Rick (Collins)
is so authoritarian or totalitarian, they can come down and talk to
us, but they have no authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Last session, Gerard and Collins stopped playing nice and
started kicking sand in each other's faces.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the session, Gerard sent Collins a box of
chocolates as a make-up present. Collins sent it back. So there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had accused me of not being truthful and questioning my
integrity . . . that's the kind of thing that happens in the heat
of battle,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little out of line in sending it back.''
</P>
<P>
   This session, Hull has taken steps to open the lines of
communication between her office and the Legislature, in part by
naming aide Jaime Molera as chief lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the governor smiles when legislators say they want a
return to the Symington administration, when one lobbyist, Barry
Aarons, did most of the governor's talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all want Barry Aarons back . . . every one of those
people had said, `Get Barry Aarons out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull admits she takes a different tack with lawmakers than
Symington did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like that style of having one person go down there and
twist their arms, twist their necks,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull also ran into trouble with the Legislature during
December's special session to replace the dilapidated state mental
hospital. Hull called the session, only to watch her proposal die
in a committee. &QL; 
A new session
</P>
<P>
   But things improved when the regular session started. One of the
first acts was passage of a bill to provide $80 million for a new
state mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Hull's legislative troubles have to do with term limits
and the current leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In another environment, Senate President Brenda Burns,
R-Glendale, might be able to play peacemaker between Groscost and
Hull, but Burns has troubles of her own.
</P>
<P>
   For one, she faces the challenge of running the Senate with a
one-seat (16-14) Republican majority. On top of that, she may not
be able to hold on to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Due to term limits, Groscost must leave the House next year and
probably will run for the Senate, where he and pal Rusty Bowers, a
Republican senator from Mesa, could form a cabal to oust Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the hubbub, Hull probably will find a way to
survive, just as she did in Chinle years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Allen, a Navajo registered nurse who befriended the Hulls,
said there's just something about Jane.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be very resourceful to find things to do, and get
acquainted,'' Allen said. ``That's what Jane did . . . She was a
very easygoing person, very outgoing. She doesn't just sit back and
wait for people to come to her.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Hull will not write off the Legislature. She will not give
up. She'll crack her jokes, make her phone calls, do her homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing to me is that I leave a legacy that
says the state of Arizona is better for my five years of being
governor,'' Hull said. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Bill.Muller(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8178.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
