<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BIOTECH-RICE-NYTR &LR;      01-31 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-RICE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LSU SCIENTISTS COOKING UP A SUPER RICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Attn: La, Ark., Mo., Texas, Calif.)  By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To hear a rice researcher tell it, the latest
breakthroughs in genetically engineered rice could offer a kind of
cure-all for crop disease, pests, weeds and a host of other
problems outside the realm of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be able to tailor rice to do a lot of things,''
said Steve Linscombe, a scientist at Louisiana State University's
Rice Station in Crowley. ``It's going to be a plus for farmers as
well as consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, crop scientists have figured out a way to add vitamin A
and beta carotene to rice, offering more nutrition to nations where
rice is a staple.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, researchers at the LSU Rice Station hope to market a rice
that is resistant to six different herbicides. This development
could reduce herbicide use in U.S. rice farming by 98 percent, LSU
researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dramatic effects of this new strain of rice may
be on planting methods, which are centered around a stubborn weed
known as red rice.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, farmers where red rice is a problem must rotate crops
between rice and soybeans, a less profitable crop. The rotation is
necessary to stop the red rice from taking over the rice paddy. In
the future, growers will be able to stick with a rice crop
year-to-year.
</P>
<P>
   They will finally have a mild herbicide that can kill red rice,
a close cousin of white rice, without killing some of the main
crop. They can cut down on water costs, too, since the new rice
will not require as much flooding. That in turn will reduce
infestations of the rice water weevil.
</P>
<P>
   Linscombe called this advance a ``very important mechanism for
increasing agriculture production.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, though is enthusiastic about genetically enhanced
crops.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Federation of America is especially leery of
enhancements that provide more direct benefits for farmers than the
general public. In addition, it wants tougher standards for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Tucker Foreman, head of the federation's Food Policy
Institute and former assistant secretary of agriculture, said the
federal approval process for these products needs to be revamped in
this emerging field of science.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these products will continue to be suspect until there
is a rigorous approval process to ensure human safety,'' she said.
Part of the federal process is voluntary, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   But, she does not doubt the potential benefits of some of these
products. ``I happen to be one of these people who wants to see
these products move ahead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The LSU researchers said the herbicide-resistant rice could be
ready for market as early as 2001 if it is approved.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hensgens, president of the Southern Seedsmen's
Association and vice president of G &AMP; H Seed Co. in Crowley, La.,
said he is comfortable with the advances in genetically altered
rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is changing our business and it's changing our business
rapidly,'' he said. He looks forward to the day when genetically
enhanced food will be the ``norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensgens said, however, he could understand why the public might
be concerned: ``It's been altered and you're giving it to me?,'' he
said, playing the role of consumer. He advocates more carefully
worded labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Similar genetic enhancements have been present in milk and corn
products for years. With rice grown only on 3.5 million acres
nationally, the investment in genetic research has reached this
crop more slowly. Louisiana, Arkansas, Texas, Missouri and
California are the main producers.
</P>
<P>
   By splicing genes into food to enhance quality and yield
scientists can customize products according to consumer demand or
production needs. This field, known as biotechnology, is taking
agriculture into the 21st century, and rice farmers don't want to
be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Rice farmers in the United States have been suffering from a
slump in prices and are eager for ways to invigorate the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing, on the short term, is to help the U.S. rice
farmers get competitive,'' Linscombe said. ``But when you look at
the broad-based benefits of genetic engineering, it goes way beyond
that. We're doing this for a lot of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Hollingsworth is in the Washington Bureau of the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
