<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      01-31 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
  
 RETRANSMITTING / 
  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``WORD COURT'' &QL; 
By Barbara Wallraff (Harcourt, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wallraff, who was born and raised in Tucson, now lives in
Massachusetts, where she is a senior editor at ``The Atlantic
Monthly.'' In addition to reading nearly every word that goes into
nearly every issue of the magazine, she writes ``The Atlantic's''
``Word Court'' column, a clearinghouse, of sorts, for questions
about grammar, punctuation, word usage and the general health of
the English language. Her new book is based primarily on
reader-submitted questions, which she answers with an appealing mix
of common sense, research, wit and an occasional foray into
improvisation (although she would not emphasize this _ most of her
``rulings'' are based on solid advice from her dictionaries). She
also includes a ``Grammarian's Dozen,'' in which she addresses
recurring troubles such as the split infinitive or a preposition
left at the end of a clause. This is an engaging book for people
who love language and want to see it treated, if not with
reverence, at least with a little common courtesy.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
``MY GOODNESS'' &QL; 
By Joe Queenan (Hyperion, $21.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The word ``curmudgeon'' has been used to describe Joe Queenan
(``Red Lobster, White Trash''), but we think it is too kind. More
appropriate, perhaps, would be ``curmudgeon with fangs,'' or
``curmudgeon with occasional bouts of virulent malice.'' Either
way, he's a funny guy, except, we are sorry to say, in this book,
where he makes a tedious show of stifling his mean streak and
embracing goodness. He tries to make his newfound virtue
entertaining, but we'll bare our own fangs and say we didn't laugh
much. Far funnier is the paperback ``Confessions of a Cineplex
Heckler'' (Hyperion, $12.95), a collection of previously published
essays in which Queenan, among other exploits, shouts comments in a
dark movie theater just to see how other patrons will react, or
jumps fully clothed into the Atlantic to prove that Leonardo
DiCaprio could not have lived as long or talked as much as he did
at the end of ``Titanic.''Queenan might be hostile, but which book
do you want to read? &QL; 
 &QL; 
``ON THE REZ'' &QL; 
By Ian Frazier (FSG, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's something edgy _ dangerous, even _ about the premise of
this book: A middle-age, middle-class White man with a ponytail and
no particular leg to stand on writes about Indians, specifically
the Oglala Sioux of the Pine Ridge Reservation in South Dakota.
Indeed, Frazier begins by announcing his affinity for things
Indian, by confessing his admiration for historic Indian leaders
and wishing something ``Indian'' for himself, something traditional
``but harder to pin down.'' It's enough to make you squirm, were it
not for the immediate, disarming quality of Frazier's voice. By the
third page, you know you are not in for worshipful romance, but for
a story _ many stories _ told in a scattered but engaging way,
devoid of judgment or condescension, attentive to virtues but
unflinching in the face of trouble, all of it lifted by Frazier's
descriptive style (in winter, he says, cottonwood trees look ``as
if they had decided never to grow leaves again and were tormented
by the decision''). &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE TOP 10 OF EVERYTHING 2000'' &QL; 
By Russell Ash (DK, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   Every year, we swear we will not do this, every year we resolve
to banish Russell Ash from our thoughts, and every year we find
ourselves sitting for an irrational amount of time with his new
book of trivia clutched in our hot little hands. This time, we
learned that the pope who served the shortest term was Urban VII
(12 days in 1590). That the first American singer to have a No. 1
hit single in the United Kingdom was Al Martino. That the longest
word in the English language is the name of an enzyme and has no
less than 1,909 letters (this sounded familiar, giving rise to the
suspicion that Ash is cribbing from his earlier books, but we
refuse to go back and check). That the world's greatest population
of pigs can be found, thankfully, in China. That the country with
the highest life expectancy for males and females is Japan (the
United States is not in the Top 10). None of this information has
staying power, of course. By the time you read it, we will have
moved on. See you next year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
