<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2198 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-INDEPENDENTS-COX     01-31 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates targeting independents in New Hampshire
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRIMACK, N.H. _ Tonight Gov. George W. Bush finds out if the
people he calls New Hampshire's ``tire kickers'' have planted both
feet on the ground, sized up the merchandise and decided to buy.
</P>
<P>
   To close the deal, Bush has been rolling from town to town in
his campaign bus, squeezing hands and gripping shoulders at
coat-and-tie Republican dinners, the occasional diner or bowling
alley and on the hushed plant floors of the high-tech companies
that are transforming the southern part of this tiny New England
state. Neck-in-neck with U.S. Sen. John McCain in most polls, he
has kept up a steady drum beat of attacks, casting McCain as a Bill
Clinton-Al Gore softy and even hauling out the big ammo _ his dad,
the former president, and his mom, the pearl-wearing,
straight-talking former First Lady, before cheering fans at a rally
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits, pollsters and political aides are predicting a tight
race, too close to call despite Bush's improved performance in
recent days. And much of the speculation is focusing on New
Hampshire's famous independents, always tough to figure out but
always important because of their numbers. They make up about 37
percent of the registered voters, outnumbering both Republicans and
Democrats, and they are free to vote in either primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Democratic Sen. Bill Bradley, casting themselves as
iconoclasts, have been fighting over the independents, a fight that
could work to Bush's advantage if these voters choose Bradley. But
polls show they're leaning toward McCain, while Bush is also
scrambling to win over voters in his own party _ many of whom, like
the independents, won't make up their minds until they step into
the voting booth tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is picking up undecided Republicans,'' said pollster John
Zogby, whose firm, Zogby International, is nonpartisan. ``McCain is
picking up Bradley independents. ... (Bush) should have an edge
because of organization. But McCain has passion and he's got a lot
of first-time voters and so I think, ultimately, we're looking at a
pretty close race.''
</P>
<P>
   The hand-shaking, the polls, even the family bit won't help
Cyndi Kiernan make up her mind. The 27-year-old student attends New
Hampshire Community Technical College where she is learning to
``take computers apart and put them back together again.'' She also
works at Gold's Gym in tiny Merrimack, N.H. and counts herself
among the state's approximately 275,000 independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican-leaning independent, Kiernan is trying to decide
between McCain and former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley. And Bush? She
grilled him about something that means a lot to her when he came by
the gym to work out last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that ... he would pass a law that the military could
not practice Wicca, and I'm not willing to give up my rights of
religious freedom,'' said Kiernan, who lived in Austin until 1993
while her husband, Michael, was stationed at nearby Fort Hood. `` I
like Bush. He's a very nice man. The time I spoke with him he told
me was not informed for making that statement. He still has until
November to redeem himself.''
</P>
<P>
   With Kiernan, at least, Bush is still paying for a statement he
made last year that Wicca _ whose practitioners call themselves
witches and believe in the dual deity of god and goddess _ is not a
religion and should not be practiced on military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Baker, 52, telecommunications consultant and an independent,
likes Bradley but prefers McCain because of his calls for campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little bit tougher,'' Baker said. `` It seems like he's
really going to push.''
</P>
<P>
   As is so often true in politics, the fight is also as much about
style as it is about substance. Will Bush, the party-backed
candidate with the revered parents stomp McCain, the almost
painfully direct Vietnam POW who has raised a fraction of Bush's
$68.7 million but appeals to New Hampshire's feisty streak?
</P>
<P>
   At a McCain town hall meeting in Exeter, Republican Joan Dacy,
62, said she considered Bush but changed her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just smug and too perfectly put-out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smug,'' nodded Alma Ripel, 58, also a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't seem like a people person,'' Dacy continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love his parents,'' Ripel said, with a broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Boulton, a truck driver and Vietnam veteran and an
independent, said he's a McCain man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a conservative strangely enough, but I like him
because he says what he believes,'' he said at a town hall meeting
in Portsmouth. ``He's more conservative than I am, especially on
abortion. I'm pro-choice. ... What really turns me off is for the
Republican Party operation to shove George Bush down my throat.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Sen. Judd Gregg has been a near-permanent fixture
at Bush's side, scads of Republican governors and legislators have
endorsed Bush and even former New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, the
man Bush helped oust from his father's administration, gave him the
nod last week. That kind of heft has persuaded Republican Kevin
Johnston, 53, to go for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator McCain commands a lot of respect for what he stands
for and what he's been through,'' Johnston said. ``In the long run,
I think Governor. Bush would be a better leader. You just can't
overlook the backing. You've got to vote for somebody who can get
the message to Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Bill Ayer, 72, was torn between McCain and Bush. But
the retired insurance man and substance abuse counselor said he
thinks Bush has improved since his initially uncertain performance
in debates and the slow start campaigning here. That delay got Bush
the cold shoulder in a state where voters expect politicians to
show up early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was initially for McCain, `` Ayer said at a 1,000-person
breakfast thrown for Bush by Republican activist John Dagostino.
``I think voting for ``W'' is more pragmatic. He sounds much more
in charge than he did initially. His reactions weren't that sharp.
He looked sort of like he was feeling his way. My projection into
his mind was that he began to realize, 'Hey, I could take these
guys.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but anything is possible in New Hampshire. Pat Buchanan
won here and is still trying to become president. Clinton lost here
and did become president. In the 11th hour, Bush's New Hampshire
fate remains in the hands of people like Gunnar and Sharon
Trenoweth, independents deciding between Bush and McCain. And with
people like Raymond Ambrogi, an undecided Republican in the same
muddle. He worries about McCain, especially the stories he's heard
about his hot temper, but he hasn't ruled him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line, I'm pretty impressed with this guy,'' Ambrogi
said after hearing McCain at a town hall meeting. ``I think he has
the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
