<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ECONOMY-COX     01-31 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The good times keep rolling
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Congratulations, America, you've spent your way to
another record: the longest economic expansion in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the first day of the 108th month of an expansion that
started in March 1991, as determined by the National Bureau of
Economic Research _ official keeper of business cycle data.
</P>
<P>
   The previous record of growth without a recession was the
expansion in the 1960s, which lasted 106 months and was pumped up
in large part by spending for the Vietnam War and President Lyndon
Johnson's Great Society program.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no mainstream economist thinks the current expansion will
end in a recession any time soon. However, many believe the economy
will grow this year at a pace slower than the 4 percent recorded in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is a better than even chance that real GDP
(gross domestic product) will moderate to 3.5 percent or less, and
the unemployment rate will level out, allaying the Fed's and the
bond market's worst inflation fears,'' said chief economist David
Orr of First Union.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this outlook is because the main engine of
economic growth _ consumer spending _ shows no signs of ebbing.
Consumer spending rose 0.8 percent in December on top of a 0.7
percent November rise, even as income growth cooled from a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1999, personal spending rose 6.9 percent _ the
largest increase in 10 years _ after increasing 5.9 percent during
1998, the government said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are out there spending, and why shouldn't they be?''
asked Richard Yamarone, senior economist at Argus Research in New
York. ``We're at full employment and people have amassed a large
amount of money through stock market gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion, far from running out of steam the way most
lengthy expansions have done, has speeded up in an almost
exponential manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since mid-1995, the economy has grown at an exceptional rate,
above 4 percent per year, far outpacing its normal trend of
growth,'' said Robert E. Hall, director of the National Bureau of
Economic Research's Economic Fluctuations and Growth Program.
``Normal growth is a little over 2.5 percent per year.''
</P>
<P>
   The length of the expansion has become a puzzle for economic
theorists. According to traditional textbooks, when unemployment
drops enough, inflation starts to build, because economic demand is
exceeds supply.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in the 1990s, when the unemployment rate dropped to the
lowest point in 30 years _ 4.1 percent. Inflation, as measured by
the Consumer Price Index, remains below 2 percent, on an annual
basis.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hall, this situation has ``perplexed the Federal
Reserve Board,'' which is responsible for monetary policy and has
by all accounts been the most effective economic regulator during
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's role in controlling the economy is to regulate
interest rates, which it does indirectly by buying or selling
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe the Fed is about to raise interest rates
again, possibly at a two-day meeting that begins today, because Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan has detected early signs of rising prices
on the horizon. Slowing the rate of growth by raising interest
rates would take some of the inflationary pressure off the economy,
in this view.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzle for economists is two-fold: why has the expansion
lasted so long, and how much longer is it likely to last?
</P>
<P>
   Jack Guynn, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta,
attributes the expansion and accompanying low inflation to four
principal causes: consumer spending, which is by far the biggest
source of growth; business investment in computers and other
productivity enhancing equipment; the relative balance of supply
and demand factors within the economy; and, to some extent,
``old-fashioned luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The last item, which appears to have run out, included the Asian
economic crunch that flooded U.S. markets with cheap imports,
helping to keep a lid on consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
   Economists wonder how much longer the productivity factor can
continue at the present rate, and what will happen when and if it
drops back to a more normal growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   There are several recession scenarios, each of which envisions
some shock that would trigger an economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   One, which Greenspan has repeatedly talked about, is the fear
that a stock market crash, or prolonged sell-off, would take the
wind out of consumer spending, causing a recession.
</P>
<P>
   In another scenario, the Fed is so determined to keep a lid on
inflation that it raises interest rates enough to send the economy,
into a recession, or period of declining output and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these is a part of mainstream forecasts for 2000 and
early 2001, even though the Fed is expected to raise short-term
rates by a quarter of a percentage point, to 5.75 percent, at the
end of its meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
   According to Orr, this increase _ the fourth since June _ will
be enough to restrain the economy.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he said, ``We think it's a case of `too hot not to
cool down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
