<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2201 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-2TA     01-31 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV PROGRAMMING FOR BLACK HISTORY MONTH IS MORE BALANCED THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (Resending for all needing) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one television program airing this month that I'd
recommend without reservation, it's ``Freedom Song,'' a startling,
exceptionally well-acted examination of what happens when the civil
rights movement parachutes into a sleepy little Southern town and
engulfs it.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by real-life events and airing Feb. 27 on the cable
network TNT, ``Freedom Song'' is remarkable for what it is and
isn't _ meaning, for a production shoehorned into the Black History
Month celebration, it isn't two hours of white-on-black
victimization or a production devoted explicitly to racist violence
and black rage.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the production is noteworthy for its straightforward,
even gentle, storytelling, a coming-of-age declaration told through
the eyes of a teen-ager who can't comprehend or accept the
nonviolent techniques of his elders, particularly when they seem to
stiffen in the face of white oppressive danger.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't surprised to hear that ``Freedom Song'' was first
conceived as a feature film; nor was it shocking to learn that
executive producer, actor and activist Danny Glover, was turned
away from every major studio leery of this story's odds of
attracting not only a white audience but a sizable black one.
Networks couldn't fathom such a project, either.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, even African-Americans, weary from watching
lynchings and the psychological torture of a race that was once
deemed subhuman, have for the most part stayed away from movies
centering on the civil rights movement and even more so from slave
period pieces. (Which helps explain the box office crash and burn
of Oprah Winfrey's ``Beloved''; well, that, and a convoluted story
line.)
</P>
<P>
   Part of the blame goes to the filmmakers. Let's face it:
Television, from the big networks to the tiny cable channels, is so
hungry for black history product during February it seems that
almost anything passes the black heritage litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings often go up anyway, driven by promotions and provocative
subject matter (the Sally Hemings-Thomas Jefferson
was-it-love-or-rape? project should do just fine), so it's a
win-win situation in attracting a few more viewers than usual and
earning brownie points from that picky NAACP. Unfortunately, in the
past, most of the stuff was bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that some of the best TV movies with
African-American themes have aired during months other than
February and on cable _ ``Miss Evers' Boys,'' ``Dorothy
Dandridge,'' ``A Lesson Before Dying,'' for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's cable's growth or the suggestion that racial
matters are being discussed openly again (the 1998 dragging death
of James Byrd in Jasper certainly got things going here), this is
one of the more balanced months of black history progamming in
years. And it got that way without much help from the major
networks, which are increasingly concentrating on more important
sweeps battles.
</P>
<P>
   Even CBS' ``Sally Hemings: An American Scandal'' (the fact that
``scandal'' is used in the title suggests the kind of viewers CBS
wants to attract) as a four-hour miniseries exploring the origins
of the controversial 38-year relationship between Thomas Jefferson
(Sam Neill) and his slave is more a dramatic serial than historical
examination.
</P>
<P>
   Sally is played by a strikingly beautiful Carmen Ejogo (every
Sally I've seen so far has been enormously gorgeous, which points
to the creators' theories that Jefferson simply couldn't help
himself), who falls for the rich and influential statesman while
working as Jefferson's maid in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Sally Hemings'' shifts back to America, Sally, now a slave,
continues the affair, giving birth to Jefferson's children, which
threatens Jefferson's presidency and wealth. The miniseries airs at
8 p.m. CST Sunday, Feb. 13, and Wednesday, Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   On cable, I recommend ``The Color of Friendship,'' about a white
South African exchange student and her black American family. The
scenes are woefully telegraphed, but it manages to sidestep a
number of cliches to deliver a subtle lecture on prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1977, ``The Color of Friendship'' is based on the true
story of U.S. Rep. Ron V. Dellums and his family, who were shocked
when a white South African showed up on their doorstep. (Director
Kevin Hooks says this actually happened twice to the family; the
first girl adapted well. The second was more entrenched in the
apartheid system, so sparks flew.)
</P>
<P>
   There are other notable programs that are listed below. Does
this signal the television industry's willingness to deal with past
injustices candidly? We'll see. No matter how painful it is to
watch TLC's ``Civil Rights Martyrs: Free at Last,'' which is about
the personal stories of those who gave their lives for the civil
rights movement, it's these cinematic efforts that will ensure that
this American Holocaust is not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs this month (all times CST):
</P>
<P>
   ``Sidney Poitier: One Bright Light, An American Masters
Special'' (8 p.m. Wednesday, PBS) _ How amazing is it that Poitier
remains the only black American to receive a Best Actor or Best
Actress Oscar? His career is defined and documented here through
interviews with Quincy Jones, James Earl Jones and Denzel
Washington, the current best bet to match Poitier in Best Actor
honors. (Washington has a Best Supporting Actor Oscar and just won
a Golden Globe for Best Actor.) Most impressive about ``One Bright
Light'' is how it uses the modern history of blacks in American
film as a nice backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Color of Friendship'' (6:30 p.m. Feb. 5, Disney) _
Inspired by true events in the life of black congressman Dellums,
this is the touching story of a friendship between two teen-age
girls _ a white South African exchange student and the black
American girl whose family has taken her in for the summer. The
South African (Lindsay Haun) is a product of the apartheid system
and views blacks as second-class citizens. The Disney film, which
is set in 1977 and targets young viewers, is moving and effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color Me Dark'' (6:30 p.m. Feb. 7, HBO) _ Fictional story of
Nellie Lee Love, a young Southern girl who moves to Chicago to
learn that even in a place where black Americans can own
businesses, shops and restaurants, racism is just below the
surface. This is part of the terrific ``Dear America'' series of
Scholastic's bestselling book series. (MORE)
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A Storm in Summer'' (7 p.m. Feb. 6, Showtime) _ Sweet and
sentimental story about an embittered Jewish deli owner (Peter Falk
at his crusty best) who finds new hope through an unlikely
friendship with an African-American boy, played by Aaron Meeks.
Meeks plays a character who meets the deli owner through a program
for underprivileged children. Both learn about tolerance and coping
with their current stations in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Civil Rights Martyrs: Free at Last'' (8 p.m. Feb. 10, TLC) _
More than two hours long, this documentary focuses on those who
gave their lives during the civil rights movement. Featured are
Medgar Evers, the Birmingham church bombing victims, Emmett Till,
and Jimmy Lee Jackson, the 26-year-old shot to death by an Alabama
state trooper while trying to protect his mother and grandfather
from state troopers during a peaceful civil rights demonstration.
His death resulted in Martin Luther King Jr.'s famous march to
Montgomery from Selma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delroy Lindo in Conversation With Charles Burnett'' (8:30 p.m.
Feb. 13, Showtime) _ Last year, Lindo interviewed Spike Lee. This
time he takes on a filmmaker just as talented but less known.
Burnett uses the African-American experience as a backdrop for his
films, but they always embrace humankind. His most mainstream
American release was ``To Sleep With Anger,'' and that was because
Danny Glover started as a storyteller/trickster who permeates the
lives of various members of a family. Illuminating, if only to get
a feel for a historical perspective on black filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Black Entertainment'' (7 p.m. Feb. 13, Showtime) _ The
struggles and triumphs of black entertainers. With Vanessa L.
Williams as host, ``It's Black Entertainment'' is segmented into
categories: dancers, divas, rock and soul, male singers, jazz and
swing, and hip-hop. What it does best, though, is show how greats
like Quincy Jones and Smokey Robinson benefited from the
experiences of legends such as Bill ``Bojangles'' Robinson and Paul
Robeson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wishing Tree'' (7 p.m. Feb. 20, Showtime) _ Alfre Woodard
stars in this production about a woman who gets to know the white
family for whom her mother worked. Effective movie with subtle
messages about racial friendship and understanding, ``The Wishing
Tree'' also stars Helen Shaver and Blair Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Brown's Holy War'' (8 p.m. Feb. 28, PBS) _ Madman,
murderer, martyr, hero? The life of one of American history's most
colorful and controversial figures is documented. Taking a ragtag
guerrilla outfit on a crusade against slavery (born out of
religious conviction, it appears), Brown led a bloody battle to end
slavery. Arguably, his execution at Harper's Ferry, Va., at the age
of 57 set off a chain of events that led to the Civil War.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
