<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Feb. 1 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-MEDICARE (Los Angeles) -- Medicare patients in California
who live on tight budgets complain they can't afford the
prescription drugs their doctors say they need.
</P>
<P>
   But starting Tuesday, their prescriptions will be covered by
Medi-Cal thanks to a new state law that should save millions of
seniors across the state hundreds of dollars a year. By Harrison
Sheppard. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-STUDENTS (Los Angeles) -- Big Brother is watching CSUN
students. With classes at Cal State Northridge starting today,
students are discovering something new they'll have to buy in
addition to textbooks and notepads. General Education students are
being told they have to buy $50 hand-held computers from the campus
bookstore; the devices can keep track of their grades, their
attendance and even allow them to take multiple-choice tests. The
new technology will be a boon for instructors, but are students
concerned about being saddled with the additional cost, or the Big
Brother possibilities of the devices? By Steve Carney. (Will move
on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   SALEM-RADIO -- Salem Communications Corp., the nation's leading
multimedia religious company, will buy a Dallas radio station for
$7.5 million, the company said on Monday. The deal with AMFM Inc.
to acquire KSKY-AM also calls for it to include three Colorado
Springs, Colo., stations, KPRZ-FM. Pending regulatory approval, the
Camarillo-based company expects the deal to close during the first
half of this year. By Chris Sieroty. (Will move on the ``f''
financial news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) -- Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in
organizational behavior _ is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News. His column moves Mondays in the ``f'' financial news file.
</P>
