<HEADER>
A2208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-600&AMP;ADD-N     01-31 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS REJECT U.S. ARGUMENT FOR MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright came here Monday
to try to convince Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, whom she has often
called her good friend, of the wisdom of a new missile defense
system for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a lengthy session of talks, she conceded she had
made little headway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can testify to the fact that it is not easy to come to a
common ground on this,'' she said, sitting beside Ivanov at a news
conference. ``We do have a different view.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Albright's senior aides was even blunter: ``We're not at
the stage where we and the Russians agree on the nature of the
threat, or what to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright was once again explaining to the Russians that the
Clinton administration believes that the threat of missiles able to
hit the United States _ and Russia _ from North Korea, Iraq and
Iran, justifies amending the basic arms control treaty of the Cold
War and constructing a limited national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed the system a year ago. For the last six months,
administration officials _ in particular Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott _ have been trying to convince Russia that the
threat from the other countries is real and that the new defense
system is not intended to defend the United States against Russia.
</P>
<P>
   To put such a system into operation, the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile treaty, which prohibits national missile defense systems,
would have to be modified.
</P>
<P>
   But as on past occasions, Ivanov was not buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been telling our American partners that the
modification of the ABM treaty might undermine the agreement,'' he
said. ``We are sure that we together could find other answers to
those threats from third countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The real test for Albright will come Wednesday when she is
scheduled to meet Acting President Vladimir Putin. It will be the
first meeting between a high-level American official and Putin
since he succeeded Boris Yeltsin, who resigned on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been plenty of speculation _ though not much
evidence _ about where Putin stands on economic issues and internal
security matters, little is known about what he thinks about arms
control _ and in particular the proposed national missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is considered likely to win the Russian presidential
election on March 26, but Clinton administration officials have
acknowledged that they do not expect any serious negotiations on
the missile defense system until after that date.
</P>
<P>
   The ``crunch time'' is likely to come between March and the
summer, when Clinton has said he will make a final decision on
whether to deploy the system, a senior administration official said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the missile defense proposal is caught up
in election year politics, as the administration seeks to ensure
that the Democratic presidential nominee is not outflanked by the
Republicans on the issue of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also discussed the war in Chechnya with Ivanov, another
issue on which Americans have made little headway with the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   She repeated her arguments, she said, that the conduct of the
war against the breakaway republic is costing Russia its reputation
and isolating it from the international community. She said that
Russia's military campaign in Chechnya has had a ``tragic cost in
human lives and a high cost to Russia's world standing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the very presence of Albright on the podium with Ivanov,
after six hours of talks on a broad list of subjects, did not
appear to buttress the idea that the United States is keeping its
distance from Russia because of Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the news conference, Albright said she had encouraged Ivanov
to reinvigorate Russia's ties with NATO, which have been basically
frozen since the war in Kosovo. At NATO's headquarters in Brussels,
Belgium, where a Permanent Joint Council was established for NATO
and Russia to discuss issues of mutual interest, the Russians have
refused since the Kosovo war to discuss matters other than Kosovo,
Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov shrugged off the argument that Russia is being hurt in
the eyes of other countries by the war in Chechnya. ``If there is
any isolation, we consider it only temporary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov gave short shrift at the news conference to a question
about whether archival records on the case of the missing Swedish
diplomat, Raoul Wallenberg, would be released.
</P>
<P>
   Wallenberg, who worked in the Hungarian capital, Budapest, for
the U.S. War Refugee Board toward the end of World War II, saved
thousands of Hungarian Jews from the Nazis. He was taken into
custody by the invading Soviet troops in January 1945 and has not
been heard of since.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and historians have pressed successive governments in
Moscow for the records that would show what happened to Wallenberg.
The case has been in the public focus once again because January
was the 55th anniversary of his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   In a curt reply, Ivanov said that Russia had legislation
concerning archives, an apparent reference to a 1993 law making it
difficult to declassify national security materials. ``We follow
the legislation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that Albright raised but found unresolved was the
condition and whereabouts of a Russian reporter, Andrei Babitskiy,
who has been reporting from Chechnya for Radio Liberty, a radio
station sponsored by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   Babitskiy's reports have been critical of the Russian military
and have given much higher numbers of Russian casualties than the
government has acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian authorities announced several days ago that
Babitskiy had been arrested in Chechnya by the Russian military for
participating in ``illegal armed formations.'' This was an apparent
reference to Babitskiy's contacts with Chechen fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov complained at the news conference about what he called
the lack of objectivity by foreign reporters covering the war and
said that Babitskiy's case was in the hands of Putin. He added that
a decision on the reporter would be made soon.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had been informed that
Babitskiy, who was not carrying official Russian government
accreditation when he was arrested, was being held in a Russian
jail somewhere in Chechnya. Monday night, there were indications
that Babitskiy would be brought to Moscow, an administration
official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
