<SLUG> BC-IVORYCOAST-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN PASSENGERS SURVIVE KENYA AIRWAYS CRASH IN THE IVORY COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Ten of the 179 people aboard survived the crash
of a Kenya Airways flight on Sunday night in the Ivory Coast,
airline officials said Monday as friends and relatives waited for
word with a mix of hope and dread.
</P>
<P>
   Ousmane Niangadou, a boutique owner here, went to a hotel that
is the airline's crisis center with a piece of paper that had three
names written in pencil. One, Hadji Kamara, a business partner of
Niangadou from Gambia, survived. But there was no news on
Niangadou's two brothers, Kaddde, 32, and Mamadou, 30, whom he
dropped off at the airport here, where the flight began, on Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their names are not on the list of survivors,'' Niangadou
said, skeptical about whether they might have survived but not
completely giving up hope.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was much the same in Lagos, the destination of the
plane in Nigeria, where many of the passengers lived, news reports
said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members wept after airline executives read a list of
survivors. A U.S. Embassy official here confirmed that at least one
American had been killed, an agronomist based in Nairobi who was
originally from Boston. The official said it was possible that a
second American man might have died.
</P>
<P>
   Monday in the Ivory Coast, rescue workers trawling the swift
currents off the capital, Abidjan, nearly 3,000 miles west of
Kenya, said that they had found 74 bodies. Airline officials said
they had recovered pieces of the Airbus A310 that crashed into the
Atlantic shortly after takeoff from Abidjan, just after 9 p.m. on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The technical director for Kenya Airways, Steve Clarke, said the
black box and cockpit flight recorder had not been found. Those
could provide vital clues about what caused the crash, which Clarke
said remained a mystery. It was the first crash for Kenya Airways
since its founding in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comment on what happened at this stage,'' he said at a
news conference here late Monday afternoon. ``We must let the
investigation take its rightful course.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 survivors, he said, one was reported to be in
intensive care. But Clarke warned that airline executives
themselves were having trouble obtaining information because of
Kenya's limited telephone system. Apart from the names of the 11
crew members, all of whom were killed, the line has not released
the names of the dead, except to say that they were from more than
20 countries, most in Africa and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 431 took off about noon. But it could not land because of
haze and poor visibility, Clarke said. The conditions were caused
by the ``harmattan,'' a seasonal wind from the deserts of North
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The plane landed in Abidjan instead, and took on several
passengers bound for Nairobi, putting the total on board at 168
passengers and 11 crew members. The plane took off at 9:05 to try
again to land in Lagos. Airport officials said the plane was
airborne for not much longer than a minute when it crashed,
breaking into many pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't quite balanced, and the next thing we knew we were
in the water,'' a survivor, Samuel Ogabade Adje, a Nigerian, told
The Associated Press in Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
   It was only on Friday that Kenya Airways announced that it would
invest $750 million over five years to improve its operations and
would replace its four Airbus jets with Boeing 737s. Clarke said
the reason was not that the Airbuses were too old, but that newer
jets have better entertainment systems and are more comfortable. He
said the jet that crashed was in good shape and had undergone a
routine but rigorous service check three days before the crash. The
airline bought it new in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, Kenya Airways set up a crisis center at the
Hotel Intercontinental in Nairobi and staffed it with psychiatrists
and counselors. Those experts have had considerable experience in
dealing with crises in recent years. Some also tended to victims'
families and survivors of the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in August
1998 and to families of people aboard an Ethiopian Airlines jet
that was hijacked and crashed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
