<HEADER>
A2217 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MALES-COLLEGE-HNS &LR;      01-31 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALES-COLLEGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EDUCATORS FEAR MALES BECOMING AN ENDANGERED SPECIES IN
COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CECILIA BALLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   High school males are increasingly less likely than females to
take college entrance exams, creating an unusual gender gap that
puts fewer men in the pipeline to college, according to recent
testing data.
</P>
<P>
   While the trend is true for all income groups, statistics show
fewer low-income males take the tests than any other group and have
fallen behind their female counterparts by a nearly 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one level, that's good news that more women are going to
college, and that's partly because of more opportunities,'' said
Richard Butler, an economics professor at Trinity University in San
Antonio. ``But the real problem here is that increasingly, the
really good jobs are going to require more than a minimal high
school education.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Scholastic Assessment Test, the most widely used college
entrance exam, 52 percent of senior test-takers last year whose
parents earned $80,000 to $100,000 were female, a difference that
reflects the percentage of women in the population. But the gap
widened significantly _ 61 percent female to 39 percent male _
among students from families who earned $10,000 to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The same relationship between gender participation and
socioeconomic status appears on the American College Test, the
nation's second-most popular entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has grown progressively worse for all income groups.
But the testing gap favoring females has widened as much as 10
percentage points for the lowest-income students in just the past
12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in Texas mirrors the national numbers and cuts
across racial and ethnic lines, although African-Americans and
Hispanics are more likely to make up the lower economic groups.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reversal of the well-known gender gap. Society has come
to assume that in cases of inequality, females get shortchanged. In
some respects, that remains true.
</P>
<P>
   SAT scores, for example, continue to be significantly higher for
males than for females _ currently by 43 points _ even though girls
leave high school with higher grade-point averages.
</P>
<P>
   But the smaller percentage of males following the college track
has raised almost no eyebrows among education researchers and
received scant public attention.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the ACT and the College Board, which administers
the SAT, cannot explain the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Bolles, whose sole job is to prepare students in the
inner-city San Antonio School District for college entrance exams,
suggested this: ``It is attributable to that `cool' factor _ that
if you do well in school, it's because you kiss up and play by the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys, she said, don't want to be seen in that light. Yet the
explanation provides just a hint of the larger social and
educational problems that may be afflicting low-income males.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the boys? Bolles doesn't always see more females in
her SAT preparation classes. But, she said, she sees ``more who are
willing to work.''
</P>
<P>
   To Thomas Mortenson, the issue is dead serious.
</P>
<P>
   An independent researcher in Iowa, Mortenson has declared
himself a boys' crusader of sorts, trying to generate national
attention for what he feels is the ultimate casualty of the deep
educational problem highlighted by jagged SAT participation between
genders.
</P>
<P>
   Men, he notes, are now outnumbered by women in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only at the end of the educational pipeline where the
cumulative magnitude of all these differences really shows up in a
dramatic way,'' Mortenson said.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers, taken from government sources, show that in 1970,
men received 56.9 percent of the bachelor's degrees awarded by U.S.
colleges and universities. But by 1996, that figure had dropped to
44.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Education Statistics expects that number
to plummet to 41.7 percent by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Women outnumbered men in college attendance for the first time
in 1976. And by 1982, they received more bachelor's degrees than
men.
</P>
<P>
   Of the one-fourth of U.S. high school students who don't make it
to college today, two of three are males, said Clifford Adelman, a
senior research analyst for the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the shift reflects the gradual opening of educational
doors to women and their personal enfranchisement, an improvement
even teen-age males have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls think they have something to prove,'' said Edmund
Pedraza, 18, a senior at Jefferson High School in San Antonio.
``They didn't go through what their moms went through, but women
were discriminated against a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet women's gains don't explain the fewer men in colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``More women doesn't necessarily mean less men; however, that
started to happen,'' Adelman said. ``So you've got to ask: Where is
the decline coming from? And the analysis by income really tells
you the story. The (lower-income) guys are out doing other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   People should care, Mortenson said, because men without
education have a lower earning potential, are more likely to end up
in prison and sometimes are violent in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Census data shows workers with bachelor's degrees earned
an average of $41,579 in 1997, compared with $27,005 for those who
held only a high school diploma. Dropouts made just half what the
college-educated population earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think of what that adds up to over a lifetime,'' Butler
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
