<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOVEREIGN-CAPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOVERIGN BANCORP PLANS INVESTMENT BANKING GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In its latest effort to refashion itself into a
mainstream bank, Sovereign Bancorp, the Eastern Pennsylvania thrift
moving into New England, plans to launch an investment banking
group focused on capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   The move, unusual for a thrift, reflects Sovereign's desire to
be viewed as a serious competitor to FleetBoston Financial, the
region's dominant bank, and to Citizens Financial Group, the
smaller, Providence, R.I. institution.
</P>
<P>
   Under its plan, Sovereign will focus on asset securitization, or
the conversion of corporate loans and other assets into securities
that are then sold to investors. It will also offer derivatives,
hedging, and foreign exchange services. While Sovereign has no
plans to offer securities underwriting, it is considering launching
financial advisory services and a bond-trading department.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, such sophisticated services were rarely offered
by smaller banks, let alone thrifts. Typically part of larger
commercial banks, including FleetBoston, capital markets units have
become increasingly common at mid-sized banks, including Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign's expansion comes as the Wyomissing, Pa. company works
to shed further its thrift image and prove it can functionally
replace the old BankBoston as a lender to mid-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
   Following Fleet's acquisition of BankBoston last year, Sovereign
raised $1.7 billion in financing to buy nearly 300 branches from
the two banks. Sovereign, now with assets of $25 billion, will
swell to $35 billion in assets once the deal is completed later
this year, but it will still be less than one-fifth the size of
FleetBoston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of being a full-service lender these days involves having
a capital markets business,'' said James Ackor, who covers
Sovereign for Tucker Cleary. ``If you buy into what they're trying
to create, it's something that in theory would allow them to
capture more business from their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hodes, an analyst at Goldman Sachs, called 125-year-old
Sovereign's latest step ``completely consistent with their ambition
to change their profile.'' Sovereign also plans to use its new
capital markets group to help manage its own balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   A Sovereign spokeswoman said she was unable to comment on the
new group, and several Sovereign executives, including Joseph
Campanelli, who heads the bank's New England franchise, did not
return telephone calls requesting details. James J. Calla, who will
head Sovereign's capital markets unit, was not available for
immediate comment. Calla oversaw similar operations at Core States,
a regional bank now part of First Union.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign's plans were outlined in a recent company earnings
statement and detailed Monday by Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign is technically a thrift, with a large home-lending
operation, but it has broadened its portfolio in recent years to
include consumer and commercial loans. The company, which has grown
rapidly through acquisitions, has also worked to shed its thrift
image by announcing plans for an Internet bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Sovereign has also run into troubles.
</P>
<P>
   While the bank is well capitalized, its holding company, under
which the company's stock trades, has far more assets than common
stock. A lower equity-to-assets ratio can leave a company with a
thin buffer against downturns in credit cycles. With the debt
financing Sovereign used to raise money to buy the Fleet and
BankBoston branches, and the premium it paid for the outlets,
Sovereign's holding company ``has no tangible capital,'' Ackor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting some investors' doubts, the company's stock has been
on a steady decline since its high of $15.462 last April. Now at
$6.843, it has lost more than half its value.
</P>
<P>
   John Kline, an analyst at Sandler O'Neill &AMP; Partners, said the
market ``is taking a wait-and-see attitude with Sovereign.'' The
bank's New England acquisition will prove somewhat costlier than
expected. Having originally planned to close its purchase of the
Fleet-BankBoston branches this April, Sovereign has instead opted
to assimilate the outlets in three stages over spring and summer _
a move that will raise its costs by prolonging the payments on the
noninvestment-grade bonds it sold to finance its purchase of the
branches. The new schedule, reported by The Boston Globe last
month, is designed to make things operationally smoother for
Sovereign, which must integrate branches with two different
computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   For its capital markets group, which will eventually include
around 15 people, Sovereign has hired a Morgan Stanley banker,
Charles Clark, to handle its securitization business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
