<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-CHILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGIUM APPEALING RULING RETURNING PINOCHET TO CHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A judge cleared the way Monday for the return to Chile
of former dictator Augusto Pinochet, ruling that the Belgian
government and six human rights organizations had no right to the
medical records that the British government cited in deeming
Pinochet too ill to be extradited to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Although a Chilean jet waited at a British airbase 20 miles
outside London to take the 84-year-old Pinochet home, his legal
odyssey may not be over. Belgium said it would appeal the ruling by
High Court Justice Maurice Kay.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet has been under house arrest in a mansion just outside
London for 15 months while a Spanish judge sought to have him
extradited to face charges of torturing and killing political
opponents during his 17-year military rule in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the British home secretary, Jack Straw, who
last month announced he was leaning toward letting Pinochet return
to Chile on medical grounds, said Straw would not make a final
decision while there was legal action pending. Straw, who is
Britain's top law enforcement official, refused to release the
conclusions of a team of doctors who examined Pinochet, citing
patient confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Belgian government said he expected the appeal
before a three-judge panel to be heard next week, and one of
Pinochet's lawyers, Fernando Barros, said the legal process could
drag on for at least three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Belgian officials' quick announcement of their plan to
appeal, the chief lawyer for one of the six human rights
organizations that joined in seeking the medical records said he
saw little chance of a successful appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Wilder Tayler, general counsel for Human Rights
Watch, said he disagreed with Kay's ruling that neither Belgium nor
the human rights groups had any standing to demand to see the
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a direct interest,'' said Tayler, who nonetheless
concluded that an appeal would likely be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tayler and other human rights activists insisted that
Monday's ruling, and Pinochet's likely return to Chile, does not
change the legal precedent set by the case. British courts ruled
that Pinochet could not claim immunity from charges of murder and
torture because on the grounds that he was head of state at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision will not detract from the huge progress in
human rights law we've made in the last 15 months,'' said Tayler.
``It is a setback, because it allows a highly political decision to
be made in a legal process. But the principle of immunity has been
wiped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed because we'll never know whether he is
really as ill as the home secretary says he is. But no dictator, no
torturer, will ever be able to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Tayler insisted the human rights groups were not being
vindictive. Even if extradited and convicted, Pinochet would not
face prison, because Spain does not incarcerate anyone over 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to put a sick man on trial, we want the right to
know whether he's really that sick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch was joined in the legal challenge by Amnesty
International, Justicia, the Redress Trust, the Medical Foundation
for the Care of Victims of Torture, and the Association of the
Relatives of Disappeared Persons. They argued that the medical
examination was cursory and was not carried out by specialists, and
that there was a public interest in disclosing the results.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium, which like Spain, France, and Switzerland, is seeking
Pinochet's extradition, wants to try the former dictator on behalf
of Chilean exiles who were tortured after he seized power in a
bloody coup in 1973. Spain, however, would have first crack at
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   But Kay ruled that Straw acted ``lawfully, fairly and
rationally'' by refusing to release the medical records on privacy
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said he made his ruling ``conscious that my decision is
unavoidably adverse to, on the one hand, people who have suffered
greatly in Chile's recent history, and, in the case of Belgium, to
a friendly state and its judicial authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bunting, a spokesman for Amnesty International, said his
organization had not yet decided whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's too ill, he's too ill,'' said Bunting. ``We still
believe there is an issue of transparency that needs to be
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in October 1998 as he recuperated from
back surgery at a London clinic. He suffered two minor strokes last
fall and has diabetes.
</P>
</TEXT>
