u e BC-GENIUS-BOOK-REVIEW-AR     01-31 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENIUS-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISES SWEET LITTLE BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Attn: Ill., Calif., Mich.) `STAGGERING GENIUS': CLEVER YOUNG MAN(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Eggers' new book, ``A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering
Genius,'' is part autobiography, part postmodern collage, a
novelistic ``memoir-y kind of thing'' that tells the sad, awful,
tragic story of how the author's mother and father died within
weeks of each other and how he became a surrogate parent to his
8-year-old brother, and tells it with such style and
hyperventilated, self-conscious energy, such coy, Lettermanesque
shtick and such genuine, heartfelt emotion, that the story is at
once funny, tender, annoying and heartbreaking _ an epic, in the
end, not of woe, though there's plenty of that too, but an epic
about family and how families fracture and fragment and somehow,
through all the tumult and upset, manage to endure.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of book David Foster Wallace, Frank McCourt and
Tom Wolfe might have written together if Wallace had never heard of
Thomas Pynchon, if McCourt did not grow up poor in Ireland but
middle-class in the suburbs of Chicago, if Tom Wolfe weren't the
sort of writer who wears white suits and ice-cream colored shirts
but were a 20-something slacker with a taste for shorts and
T-shirts and lots of postmodern pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   There is a self-conscious knowingness to ``Staggering Genius''
that announces itself in the book's opening pages: the story is
prefaced with ``Rules and Suggestions for Enjoyment of this Book,''
an extended discussion of ``the major themes of this book,'' ``an
incomplete guide'' to the book's metaphors and symbols, and a flow
chart detailing the emotional consequences of the deaths of Eggers'
parents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the book's narrative is peppered with asides that
pre-empt, in a Rothian sort of way, any criticisms the reader might
have, asides chastising Eggers for being self-absorbed and
self-pitying, for milking his family tragedy for sympathy and
attention, for cannibalizing others' lives for a book.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eggers' eagerness to continually footnote his narrative
_ like a smart-aleck kid telling you why he knows he's going to get
into trouble, so you can give him points for being clever and cute
_ can be intensely irritating, his use of pomo gimmickry does not
undercut the emotion of his story but somehow heightens it by
throwing the passages of earnest sentiment into high relief.
</P>
<P>
   We become aware that Eggers is not simply wielding high-tech
devices to create a hip, experimental narrative, but that these
self-annotating mechanisms are part of his sensibility, that they
are defensive survival tactics, like his love of hyperbole, invoked
to deal with his chaotic childhood and the horror of losing his
parents. They are part of his constitution as a writer, enabling
him to stand apart from his experiences and turn them into art.
</P>
<P>
   This is why his mother's long, slow, agonizing death elicits not
only fear and grief but also a grisly, stream-of-consciousness riff
on cancer: ``The tumor is a light tumor, empty, a balloon. The
tumor is rotten fruit, graying at the edges. Or an insects' hive,
something festering and black and alive, fuzzy on its sides.'' This
is why sickness in this book is so often made to yield sick jokes;
death, swatted away with irony and black humor.
</P>
<P>
   As Eggers lets us know through a Q-and-A session shoehorned into
the middle of the book, he grew up in Lake Forest, the monied
Chicago suburb depicted in ``Ordinary People.'' His family never
really fit in: ``We were always so oddly white-trashy for our town,
with our gruesome problems, and our ugly used cars, our Pintos and
Malibus and Camaros, and our '70s wallpaper and plaid couches and
acne and state schools.''
</P>
<P>
   His father was an alcoholic given to terrifying rages, his
mother a long-suffering martyr. Both of them were dying of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our house sits on a sinkhole,'' Eggers writes. ``Our house is
the one being swept up in the tornado, the little train-set model
house floating helplessly, pathetically around in the howling black
funnel. We're weak and tiny. We're Grenada. There are men
parachuting from the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   After the death of his parents, the 21-year-old Eggers and his
little brother, Toph, move out to Berkeley, Calif., to be near
their elder sister, Beth. The two orphans set up housekeeping as
father and son. Eggers attends Toph's Little League games with all
the other boys' parents; he fantasizes about picking up women at
the school's open house. On the odd occasion that he leaves the
house for a date, he worries that the baby sitter will murder his
brother, that something terrible _ basically whatever his ``wild,
horror-infested imagination'' can concoct _ will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Of Toph, he writes: ``His brain is my laboratory, my depository.
Into it I can stuff the books I choose, the television shows, the
movies, my opinion about elected officials, historical events,
neighbors, passers-by. He is my 24-hour classroom, my captive
audience, forced to ingest everything I deem worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   He reads his brother ``Hiroshima'' (leaving out the grisly
parts), ``Maus'' and ``Catch 22''; teaches him tricks with the
Frisbee, and instructs him in the fine art of sock-sliding down
their apartment's hallway. ``To not have Toph,'' he writes, ``would
be to not have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the book, Eggers devotes more and more
space to chronicling his and his Bay Area friends' efforts to found
a Gen X magazine called Might. Although his accounts of their
antics (like persuading a former child star to pretend that he is
dead) can grow tiresome _ like watching too many Conan O'Brien
shows in a row _ his writing is so tactile, so hot-wired to his
subconscious, that the reader breezes even through these parts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Eggers demonstrates in this book that he can pretty
much write about anything. He can turn a Frisbee game with his
brother into an existential meditation on life. He can convey the
wild, caffeinated joy he feels after seeing a friend wake up from a
coma. He can turn his efforts to scatter his mother's ashes in Lake
Michigan into a story that's both a lyrical tribute to her passing
and a crude, slapstick account of his ineptitude as a mourner,
lugging about a canister of ashes that reminds him, creepily, of
the Ark of the Covenant in the Spielberg movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius'' may start off
sounding like one of those coy, solipsistic exercises that put
everything in little ironic quote marks, but it quickly becomes a
virtuosic piece of writing, a big, daring, manic-depressive stew of
book that noisily announces the debut of a talented _ yes,
staggeringly talented new writer.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A HEARTBREAKING WORK OF STAGGERING GENIUS'
</P>
<P>
   By Dave Eggers
</P>
<P>
   375 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
