<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUERRILLAS KILL 3 ISRAELI SOLDIERS IN SOUTHERN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Three Israeli soldiers were killed in southern
Lebanon Monday as Iranian-backed guerrillas continued to escalate
their attacks during a lull in peace negotiations between Israel
and Syria, Lebanon's power broker.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli planes responded with artillery attacks and airstrikes
on Hezbollah guerrilla targets in Lebanon. By early evening, all
was relatively quiet in the conflict zone, a 9-mile-wide territory
that Israel has occupied since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The morning attack on an Israeli army post came as the strong
emotions of the Lebanon issue had begun to resurface in Israel,
causing bereaved parents to call in to radio programs and
politicians to debate what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   This latest attack by Hezbollah, or Party of God, also came as
the deputy commander of the Israeli-backed South Lebanese army was
being buried after his assassination by the guerrillas on Sunday.
The commander, Akl Hashem, died in an ambush by Hezbollah a week
after the funeral of the first Israeli soldier to have been killed
in Lebanon in six months.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel Monday, politicians suggested to Prime Minister Ehud
Barak that he consider everything from complete restraint to a
massive retaliatory bombardment similar to the one last June by
Benjamin Netanyahu, then the outgoing prime minister. Several
political figures on the left and right called for an immediate,
unilateral withdrawal of Israeli troops from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was considered reluctant to order a harsh military
response that could further escalate the violence, cause more
Israeli casualties and jeopardize the fragile Israeli-Syrian
negotiations. He was also considered unwilling to demand that the
Syrians enforce a cease-fire because such a demand would probably
be costly for Israel during the negotiations. And he has never
wanted to conduct a unilateral withdrawal, believing that a
withdrawal would be most safely performed as part of an agreement
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting with his security Cabinet and with military
officials, Barak vaguely promised some kind of ``punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever is responsible for the severe attacks on Israeli and
South Lebanese soldiers in Lebanon _ we will make sure that he is
punished,'' Barak said. ``Hezbollah activity is ongoing, and we
will not accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, his office issued a statement in which
Barak warned that Israel would not be able to carry on with the
peace effort if Syria did not rein in the Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak very much wants to return to the negotiating table.
The Israeli-Syrian peace effort resumed in December after a nearly
four-year stalemate only to grind to a halt again earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that Syria tries to manipulate the peace
effort by either restraining or failing to restrain Hezbollah
activity in southern Lebanon. Historically, greater calm prevails
at times of active negotiations, experts say, and the peace talks
with Syria are based partly on the premise that Syria uses its
control over Lebanon as a bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the anguished voices of soldiers' parents revived
the feeling of many that the conflict has become senseless. In
addition to the three who were killed Monday, four soldiers were
wounded, one gravely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that they would pull back from that cursed place,
Lebanon,'' said Avi Azulai, the father of an injured soldier, Roni.
``Enough, enough. If it didn't happen to me, it would happen to the
next guy, or the next.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack came at 11:15 Monday morning when guerrillas hit an
Israeli patrol near its outpost at a Crusades-era castle close to
the northern Israeli border. With rocket-launched grenades and
machine guns, the Hezbollah forces staged what their spokesmen
proudly called ``a daring attack deep in the occupied zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't you who strikes when you strike but it is Allah who
does it,'' Hezbollah's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, many feared an Israeli retaliation to rival that of
last June, when Israel responded to the Hezbollah attacks on
civilians in northern Israel with airstrikes throughout Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope they don't bomb the infrastructure facilities like
last time because it was really bad,'' said Nicole Choueiry, a
Lebanese journalist in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, Hezbollah struck Israeli military targets
within the zone of conflict. Under the internationally monitored
rules of the conflict, Israel is not supposed to strike back
outside the zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In June, the targets were Israeli civilians in Israeli
territory,'' said Timur Goksel, a spokesman for the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon. ``It was a case that could be justified. In this
case, they were Israeli soldiers in the wrong country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
