<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT, RUSSIAN FOREIGN MINISTER, TRADE OPINIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In her first visit to Moscow since Boris N. Yeltsin
resigned on New Year's Eve, Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright played a little game of ``she said, he said'' with the
Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours of talks Monday, the main issues were Russia's
four-month war against separatist rebels in Chechnya and the US
desire to amend the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   She said Russia was inflicting ``an incredible amount of misery
on Chechnya's civilians.'' He said Russia's ``battle with
international terrorists was not a battle against the Chechen
people.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that while ``many in Russia view Chechnya as an
internal affair,'' the conflict is ``casting a long international
shadow'' and Moscow risks becoming ``increasingly isolated'' over
the war. He said that Russia ``understands the concerns of those
abroad and it's therefore open to consultations'' on the situation
in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   On the ABM treaty, the differences were no less serious. The
1972 treaty, considered a cornerstone of the detente-era US-Soviet
arms control pacts, bans defensive missile systems.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Washington sought to amend the treaty to allow
deployment of a limited space-based antimissile system to protect
the United States against missile attacks from ``third states.''
President Clinton is set to decide this spring whether to move
forward with a $6.6 billion missile defense program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seek to maintain the long-term benefits of ABM while
allowing both our countries security against missile attacks,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov retorted that amending ABM would be ``a serious mistake''
that would undermine ``the architecture of security'' between
Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went on the first day of Albright's three-day working
visit to Russia. The open debate at a joint news conference
underscored the deterioration in US-Russian relations following
NATO's expansion to include three of Moscow's former Cold War
allies in Eastern Europe and the alliance's bombing of Yugoslavia
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street at the United States Embassy, more than 100
demonstrators gathered to protest Albright's visit. They carried
signs accusing her of backing the Chechen rebels and of being party
to war crimes in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their obvious differences, both Albright and Ivanov did
their best to maintain an upbeat tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather in Moscow may be frozen but the ability of the
United States and Russia to work together on important issues is
not,'' Albright said, adding that such complex issues ``are
unlikely subjects for one-day miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Ivanov both said they hoped that Russia's
parliament would ratify the 1993 START II missile reduction treaty
that would cut both sides' long-range nuclear arsenals to between
3,000 and 3,500 warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Once START II is ratified, the Clinton administration has said,
it plans to propose a START III treaty reducing each side's nuclear
arsenal to 2,000 to 2,500 warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Albright is scheduled to participate in talks to foster
regional cooperation in the Middle East. The talks, jointly
sponsored by the Washington and Moscow, will focus on the
environment, economic cooperation, arms control, and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Albright is set to hold her first official meeting
with the Kremlin leader, Vladimir V. Putin, who became Russia's
acting president after Yeltsin's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that her meeting with Putin would be substantive,
but she declined to predict the outcome. She also said that
President Clinton was prepared to make a visit to Moscow to meet
with Putin, but did not specify when. The Associated Press, citing
sources in Washington, reported that Clinton is unlikely to go to
Moscow before Russia's March 26 presidential election, which Putin
is heavily favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Ivanov also signed an agreement tightening controls
on technology used in launching US satellites from Russian space
stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1927EST &QL; 
