<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-TRUDEAU-1045(2     01-31 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TRUDEAU-1045(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUDEAUMANIA LIVES, BUT THE POLICIES ARE DYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ To newcomers thronging a busy food court at lunch
time here, there is something familiar about the elderly lawyer
standing patiently in line at the Lebanese food counter.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him dine alone with his usual chicken-in-pita sandwich,
it dawns that this elegantly dressed gentleman is Pierre Elliott
Trudeau, the man ranked recently by Canadians in a poll as ``the
best prime minister of the century.'' The man emptying his plastic
lunch tray is the same one who ranked fourth in another Canadian
poll, for ``the person of the millennium,'' after Gutenberg,
Einstein and Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of mostly English and mostly gray prime
ministers, Trudeau took the stage in Canada some 30 years ago and
captivated the world with his dapper style, his expansive
liberalism and his fast-paced bachelor life, which culminated with
his storied _ and ill-fated _ marriage to a woman nearly 30 years
younger.
</P>
<P>
   Today, three decades after Trudeaumania swept Canada, his
mystique remains strong, fed partly by the celebrations for his
80th birthday last fall, his reclusiveness _ he steadfastly
declines interviews _ and sympathy over the loss of his youngest
son in an avalanche 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   All that has produced a season of Trudeau appreciation here that
is recalling a bright but bygone age. On October 15, three days
before his birthday, a Canadian TV documentary swept Canadian
television ratings, drawing 1.4 million viewers. Earlier, the
surprise Canadian hit at the Toronto International Film Festival
was Catherine Annau's documentary ``Just Watch Me: Trudeau and the
'70s Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   In bookstores, a best-selling anthology of analyses of the
Trudeau era, ``Trudeau's Shadow'' (Vintage Canada), has come out in
paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians' fascination with the Trudeau personal drama is a
measure of how much people connected with him. While his
big-government economic policies are in retreat and his bilingual
policy has failed to blunt Quebec separatism, today's preoccupation
reflects how much Trudeaumania stamped the two generations that
will lead Canada into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this has to do with his style. In 1968, a large part of
Canada's female population developed a crush on this dashing,
self-confident man. His coat lapel sported a fresh rose, his hat
was set at a rakish angle, and his accent was seductively French.
Girls filled scrapbooks with clippings from his 1971 marriage to
Margaret Joan Sinclair, a 22-year-old flower child. Women named
their babies Pierrette and Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   After the Trudeau marriage broke up six years later, he dated
Barbra Streisand and Margot Kidder. Once, when he drove up to his
official residence in a British sports car, a reporter asked him
about his Mercedes. Speaking decades before Austin Powers
popularized such lines, he responded, ``The car _ or the girl?''
</P>
<P>
   The sexual magnetism has proved enduring. At age 71, he fathered
his latest child, Sarah Elisabeth, with Deborah Coyne, who was then
37 and from whom he is now divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Winsor, the political editor of The Globe and Mail in
Toronto, wrote recently that ``with an originality and elan
atypical of Canadian politicians'' Trudeau ``almost single-handedly
dispelled the myth of Canada as dull, wind-swept and boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of this nostalgia also has to do with Canadians who grew up
under Trudeau's spell, attending summer language camps and buying
into his vision of a bilingual nation.
</P>
<P>
   And some of it has to do with the death that shocked Canadians
the way the death of John F. Kennedy Jr. shocked Americans last
summer. Michel Trudeau, 23, an experienced mountaineer, was swept
by an avalanche into an alpine lake on Nov. 13, 1998, in British
Columbia. Burdened with a pack and cross-country skis, he
disappeared into the icy water. His body has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierre hasn't really recovered from it,'' Margaret Trudeau,
51, his former wife and the mother of Michel, told The Ottawa
Citizen recently. In the months before his son's death, the former
prime minister was skiing, canoeing and climbing pyramids in
Guatemala. Now he appears increasingly frail. He was in a hospital
for pneumonia in early January.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging briefly from her own life of guarded privacy, Margaret
Trudeau gave a news conference on a mountainside in British
Columbia recently to raise awareness of avalanche dangers. Speaking
beside her oldest son, Justin, a 28-year-old English teacher and a
snowboard instructor, she said, ``It was like a nuclear bomb went
off in our family, and nothing could put it together again the way
it was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Trudeau lives alone in his austere art-deco house here.
``He's a very distant man,'' Sacha Trudeau, his 25-year-old son,
said in the television documentary. ``He's private, even from our
perspective. I guess he's had kind of a lonely life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Trudeau declines to take part, conferences are
sprouting up to assess his liberal legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Saying in 1967 that ``there's no place for the state in the
bedrooms of the nation,'' Trudeau, then justice minister, helped
ease laws on abortion and homosexual acts. Later, as prime
minister, he appointed the first women to be speakers of the House
of Commons and Senate, and then the first woman to be governor
general.
</P>
<P>
   He introduced a constitutional bill of rights that dramatically
expanded individual freedoms in a nation that was politely
authoritarian.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he persuaded Parliament to enact a bill making Canada
officially bilingual as a way to heal French-English division.
</P>
<P>
   But separatism remains a strong political force, and bitter
memories linger of Trudeau's brief imposition of martial law on his
native Quebec after a wave of separatist kidnappings in 1970. In a
national survey of news media editors last year, English speakers
chose Trudeau as ``the top Canadian newsmaker of the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years after he left political life, it is remarkable
how Pierre Trudeau continues to be a central figure in political
thinking in English Canada, and how his ideas have practically
disappeared from radar screens in Quebec,'' Michel C. Auger, a
newspaper columnist for Journal de Montreal, wrote, skeptical of
the Trudeau-era national unity effort.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   On economic policy, his nationalist, big-government policies
have been toned down. The state oil company that Trudeau formed was
privatized long ago. The foreign investment review agency was
discarded when Canada adopted a free trade pact with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Serge Joyal, a Quebec senator who is a friend of Trudeau, said
the former prime minister lets the critics go unanswered because
``he doesn't want to be dragged into the public debate, into the
public limelight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joyal reminisced briefly on one difference between a Trudeau
Cabinet in the 1970s and a Jean Chretien Cabinet in the 1990s: ``In
Trudeau's time, the Cabinet would meet and we would say, `What do
we create this week?' In Chretien Cabinet meetings, ``we would say,
`What do we cut this week?'''
</P>
<P>
   On Trudeau's 80th birthday, Chretien gave a dinner at his
official residence in Ottawa for 30 friends of the former prime
minister. With attendants at the all-male gathering dressed in dark
suits, Trudeau displayed his old flair, wearing a gray suit, with
his trademark red rose in the lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the gathering around a long banquet table, the
Canadian news magazine Maclean's ventured that it would be
remembered as ``the last supper'' of the Trudeau era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
