<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-AIRLINES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL, American create joint reward program
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ America Online and American Airlines will combine
resources to launch AOL AAdvantage, a combined rewards program for
AOL users and for members of American's frequent flier program.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusive deal matches one of the country's largest
airlines, which has 38 million frequent flier members, with the
nation's largest online service, which has more than 22 million
members.
</P>
<P>
   Users who register with AOL AAdvantage will be able to earn
American frequent flier miles when they purchase products online
from AOL AAdvantage partners.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms were not disclosed, but the three-year deal also
calls for the two companies to launch a multimillion-dollar
cross-marketing campaign. The program is to start May 1.
</P>
<P>
   A joint management team from American Airlines and AOL will
operate AOL AAdvantage. Netcentives, a developer of electronic
marketing software, will create and operate the infrastructure for
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AOL AAdvantage program allows users to get up in the
morning and use the advantage miles they currently have, see them
and spend them,'' says AOL Senior Vice President Dennis Gonier.
</P>
<P>
   Although American has its own Web site (www.AA.com), Gonier says
it will be much easier and convenient to check miles and earn miles
using the AOL AAdvantage program. He also said the AOL AAdvantage
program involves more than just earning travel awards. Members can
earn miles that can be applied to America Online's monthly service
plan. (For example, 5,000 miles will earn three months of AOL
service.)
</P>
<P>
   Gonier said that when the AOL and Time Warner merger is
complete, rewards members will have more options. ``When you look
down the road to a time when we are affiliated with (Time Warner),
you can spend the money on magazine subscriptions, music, movies,
HBO service and more. It's a large landscape,'' he said. ``It's a
very large landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chemel, president of American's advantage marketing
program, says the airline has been talking with AOL for some time.
He said American has made its frequent flier program attractive to
infrequent fliers and to non-fliers by offering credit cards and
long-distance services as an alternative way to earn miles.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks offering online rewards opportunities through AOL is
an idea whose time has come.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
