<HEADER>
A2239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LAFARGE-BLUECIRCLE-NY     01-31 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAFARGE-BLUECIRCLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES OF BLUE CIRCLE INDUSTRIES RISE ON REPORTS OF OFFER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Shares in Blue Circle Industries, a British cement
company, rose more than 20 percent Monday on reports that the
world's No. 1 building materials group, Lafarge SA of France, was
about to bid as much as $5.7 billion for Blue Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Investors began buying Blue Circle shares after the company said
it had rejected an offer from Lafarge and the French company
responded by announcing it might make a formal bid. On the London
Stock Exchange, Blue Circle shares rose 70.50 pence, or about
$11.42, to close at 414 pence, or about $6.71.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in Blue Circle's share price at least temporarily
reversed the trend of last year, when it had declined from a high
of 485 pence in June to about 258 pence in October after
disappointing results in Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   A report in The Daily Telegraph said Lafarge was considering a
hostile $5.7 billion bid for Blue Circle, if Blue Circle refused an
amicable Lafarge offer. If successful, such a hostile bid would
give Lafarge control of roughly half of the British cement market.
</P>
<P>
   Lafarge's expansion would be the latest step in the
consolidation of the European building materials market, especially
in Britain, where rough-and-tumble merger and acquisition activity
is more the rule than on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   RMC Group of Britain, the world's biggest maker of ready-mix
concrete, agreed in November to pay $1.4 billion for a British
cement maker, Rugby Group. At the same time, Hanson PLC, a British
building materials group that does about half its business in North
America, bid $2.5 billion for another cement producer, Pioneer
International Ltd. of Australia, strengthening Hanson's position in
Asia and North America. Cement is the main ingredient in ready-mix
concrete and mortar. Demand is highly dependent on economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   For Lafarge, which had revenue last year of about $11 billion, a
bid would be the next step in a strategy of expanding globally,
and, most notably in Asia, to tap into an economic recovery there.
Lafarge's last major acquisition was in 1997, when it paid $3.5
billion to purchase Redland PLC of Britain, an acquisition that
made Lafarge the biggest building material supplier. Earlier this
month, Blue Circle said it expected net profit of $421 million for
1999, benefiting from cost savings and improved sales in North
America, where it generates about one-third of its $3.7 billion
annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Lafarge has spent about $3.1 billion on
acquisitions, including almost a dozen small and midsize companies
in North America. In recent weeks, Lafarge linked with a Greek
partner to bid for Egypt's biggest cement maker, the Amereyah
Cement Co.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, thechief executive of Lafarge, Bertrand
Collomb, has expressed interest in further expansion, most notably
in Asia. In a statement Monday, Lafarge said it was ``contemplating
making a cash offer'' for Blue Circle and would make a formal
announcement ``as soon as is practicable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ALLIED-COX     01-31 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allied Holdings ready for haul with new deals, management
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mitchell Poole doesn't sound happy about America's
love affair with sport-utilities and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're heavier, they're bigger, they're boxier,'' Poole said.
``They're just harder to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole's frustration isn't rooted in environmentalism or
annoyance at eye-level headlights in his rearview mirror. As a top
executive at Decatur, Ga.-based Allied Holdings Inc., he has more
practical cause for frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Allied is North America's leading car hauler, delivering more
than 12 million new vehicles a year to dealerships under contract
to automakers. It is a vital link in the auto supply chain.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with rising demand for SUVs and trucks is that fewer
of the bulky vehicles fit on a trailer, cutting Allied's average
load about 20 percent over the last few years. That helped push the
company's earnings into the ditch for much of 1999 while Allied
tried to adjust its pricing structure to the new reality, as well
as recover from a mid-1998 strike at its biggest customer, General
Motors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shift in the vehicle mix really put them on their rear,''
said Peter Coleman, transportation analyst at Banc of America
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Now Allied is attempting a U-turn with a reshuffled management
team. Poole, who had been president and chief operating officer,
two months ago became chief executive, succeeding Robert Rutland.
</P>
<P>
   The change was a milestone: Rutland was the grandson of Guy
Rutland Sr., who bought the company in 1934 for $15,000. Robert
Rutland's move out of the CEO spot ended six decades of hands-on
control by the Rutland family, although he remains chairman and the
family is still Allied's biggest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Randall West, former head of Allied's Axis Group logistics
services unit, took the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   Allied hired Hugh Sawyer to run Allied Automotive Group, the
company's core business unit. Sawyer was lured away from
Atlanta-based National Linen Service, where he was credited with
fashioning a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said a turnaround is already under way at Allied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly had some financial issues last year, but we are
over those,'' Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied has renegotiated contracts with its top three customers,
General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler, with new pricing formulas
to offset the changed mix of vehicles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations took time and weren't always easy.
DaimlerChrysler, which provides 15 percent of Allied's revenue, put
its contracts with the company out for bid but wound up keeping 91
percent of that business with Allied, Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied posted a $3.7 million net loss in the first nine months
of 1999, vs. a $3.4 million profit a year earlier. But it recently
told Wall Street that fourth-quarter earnings _ due out Feb. 15 _
will exceed estimates, and Poole said they will give the company a
full-year profit.
</P>
<P>
   Allied stock, which tumbled from a high of $23 in early 1998 to
a low of $5 last October, is showing signs of life. Shares are up
47 percent this month, closing Monday at $9.18 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have huge year-over-year growth this year,'' said
analyst Coleman, who for the time being is keeping a ``market
perform'' rating on Allied stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, after the comparisons wash through you're left
with a good company that already dominates a slow-growth
industry,'' Coleman added. ``So the future question is, where does
the (longer-term) growth occur?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, he said, lies in overseas business, logistics
services and being positioned to capitalize on changes in
distribution wrought by e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Poole, who joined Allied in 1988 as chief financial officer,
said the company is gearing up in all three of those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is an industry that is going to be changing
dramatically in the next few years,'' he said. ``In five years we
will probably be delivering vehicles to your house, not just to
dealers. The consumer may or may not even go through a dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied already is testing smaller, nimbler, quick-loading
trailers for in-city deliveries _ a precursor, perhaps, to home
delivery of made-to-order cars purchased over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, who spent his first week at Allied attending the Detroit
auto show, came back convinced that automakers will use the
distribution power of the Internet to the hilt. But someone will
still have to deliver vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I was attracted to Allied is that I think
it's going to become a low-tech e-commerce player,'' Sawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Home delivery would change the economics of vehicle delivery,
but Sawyer said companies with the infrastructure in place will be
in the best position to capitalize on the potential trend.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, his task is to make the current model _ in which large
numbers of vehicles are gathered at terminals and then grouped for
delivery to dealers _ as efficient as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers want damage-free delivery, reduced transit times
and good problem resolution,'' said Sawyer, ``and we have to keep
focusing on those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole said Allied will continue an international expansion begun
two years ago. It now has a strong presence in Britain and Brazil.
An Asian strategy is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said an overseas presence is necessary not just for growth
but to be a player in global commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old delivery chain was Detroit to Columbus, Ohio,'' he
said. ``Now it's Stuttgart (Germany) to Phoenix. We have to be in a
position to be part of that from end-to-end.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied's competition is fragmented. Allied Automotive Group
claims about 65 percent of the North American car-hauling market
and is five times bigger than its closest rival.
</P>
<P>
   That size is largely the result of a 1997 buyout of Ryder
Automotive Carrier Services, which greatly expanded Allied's
presence in the western United States and made General Motors its
biggest account, followed by Ford and DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said the end of the Rutlands' day-to-day control won't
significantly change the company or its culture. He said he plans
to keep one notable aspect of that culture, a chaplaincy program
that offers non-denominational counseling for workers.
</P>
<P>
   Poole also said the family has given no indication it might sell
its stake to a new owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still involved,'' he said, noting that Robert
Rutland's nephew is a senior vice president in the auto-hauling
unit. ``We had been planning a transition at the top for a couple
of years now and felt this was the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
