<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-NH-PRIMARY-KEYES-BOS &LR;      01-31 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-PRIMARY-KEYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYES ENJOYS NATIONAL STAGE AS N.H. PRIMARY CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRIMACK, N.H. _ From an Iowa mosh pit to a New Hampshire
Lincoln Day brunch, Alan Keyes has spread his message of personal
responsibility, lower taxes, gun-ownership rights and abhorrence of
abortion during this primary season.
</P>
<P>
   And while polls suggest he may wind up the fourth-place finisher
in Tuesday's Republican presidential primary, New Hampshire has
loaned Keyes a national platform from which to make his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message needs to be gotten to the people,'' said Kathleen
Burger of Chesterfield, who had come to Merrimack Monday to hear
Keyes speak. ``And he is a most eloquent means of getting it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, a former UN ambassador and radio talk-show host, spoke
Monday on the Don Imus radio show live from the Lebanon, N.H.,
Opera House, then addressed a luncheon in Merrimack, spoke on
WMUR-TV and attended a party with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must return to the concept that it is the citizens'
responsibility to lead,'' Keyes said Monday. ``The citizens'
responsibility to decide, the citizens' responsibility to defend,
the citizens' responsibility to stand in the breach and do what is
necessary in order to secure the integrity of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   By Keyes's reckoning, beating Steve Forbes, who holds third
place in most polls, would constitute success. A good showing, he
said, would be to come ``within a reasonable distance'' of Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, he fully intends to carry his message to South
Carolina before that state's Feb. 19 primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This depends entirely on people,'' Keyes said of his campaign.
``As long as there are folks willing to work, we'll continue to
present what I think is the right choice to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But while many voters said they like Keyes's message, and are
left invigorated by his oratory, they also may shy from marking an
``X'' next to his name when they go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's between him and John McCain,'' said Greg
D'Arbonne, an independent voter from Brookline, a town near the
Massachusetts border. ``Mr. Keyes probably won't win, but I see
some of the same type of ideals in McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   And Burger, who also praised Keyes's platform and his passion,
said she will vote for Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes offered a tongue-lashing Monday to Republicans who would
vote for Texas Governor George W. Bush simply because they perceive
him as the ``winner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them lemmings,'' Keyes told reporters Monday.
``Remember lemmings? They're that animal that periodically gets
overtaken by a desire to commit suicide, and they all gather
together in big bunches and march off the cliff together. I think
that Bush supporters are lemmings. They're the same lemmings who
handed us Bob Dole last time and marched us off the cliff of
defeat,'' Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Bush has exactly the same characteristics. A decent guy.
Not as effective as others at articulating the issues, but what the
heck? He's got a big name.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, in Keyes's view, doesn't have the skills or strength
of character to press the conservative case and ``promote the
ideals of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The right man for that job, he says, is Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if people look honestly at the debates _ agree with me
or not _ and just ask themselves who is the most effective
spokesman in terms of articulating the sort of moral challenge that
has to be met in this country, I think the answer has been obvious
for quite some time. . . . So why not choose the right tool for the
job?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
