A2251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GAPRIMARY-COX     01-31 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPRIMARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eager Georgians get sneak preview
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.H. _ The local American Legion hall is about the
last place a reporter for this newspaper would expect to run into a
half-dozen Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   But Will Claiborne and his cohorts wanted a taste of
presidential politics in New Hampshire. And there was no better
place for that one recent night than in Rochester, at Republican
John McCain's 112th town hall meeting in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the center of the political world at the moment,''
said Claiborne, 22, president of Emory University's student
government.
</P>
<P>
   He and Phil Smith, the director of the Concord Coalition in
Georgia, were interested in getting all candidates to endorse the
coalition's platform of paying down the national debt before
offering tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain says some things that are very good for deficit
hawks,'' Smith said, stressing that the coalition does not endorse
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the deficit were the business part of the trip.
But this latter-day Peanut Brigade was made up of political
junkies, Democrats and Republicans, who surmised that they would
get better looks at Gov. George W. Bush, Vice President Al Gore and
the others in New Hampshire than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The other travelers included Emory Fiveash of Statesboro, vice
chairman of the Bulloch County Republican Party, and Lawton Jordan,
a University of Georgia law student. Jordan's first taste of
politics came from his uncle, Hamilton Jordan, and adviser to
former President Jimmy Carter and a Senate candidate in his own
right in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamilton took us to Camp David a few times,'' Jordan recalled.
Jordan and Smith also campaigned for President Clinton in New
Hampshire in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne, an Emory senior from Atlanta, said the visit could
not have been better. The group attended a Super Bowl party Sunday
at the home of McCain supporters, where the candidate signed photos
for the Georgians. ``There were 75 people and six of us yahoos from
Georgia,'' Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   On the cold night in Rochester, Fiveash displayed some political
savvy. He wore a tan down jacket, zipped to his chin, presumably to
keep him warm. But as McCain shook hands elsewhere in the room,
Fiveash unzipped the jacket just enough to reveal a Bush for
president logo on his T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
