<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-RAMS01-COX     01-31 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-RAMS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Story still sweet the day after Rams fairy tale
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kurt Warner's NFL odyssey started nearly two years ago
on a practice field at the Falcons' complex in Suwanee, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Warner's long, winding and improbable journey
culminated when the NFL MVP led the Rams to a 23-16 victory over
the Titans in the 34th Super Bowl in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Warner was a 26-year-old rookie with the
Amsterdam Admirals. He had been allotted to NFL Europe by St.
Louis, which signed the former Arena League star to a free-agent
contract during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was miserable,'' Warner said about his first visit to
Atlanta. ``I never wanted to come back here and practice in the
cold and snow again. But I always knew that if I was going to get a
chance to get (to the NFL) that it would be through NFL Europe. It
was ironic when we came out last week and it was cold with the icy
rain. That was exactly how it was when I was here for training camp
(in 1998).''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the stakes were much higher. Warner threw for a Super
Bowl-record 414 yards, breaking Joe Montana's 1989 mark of 357.
Warner, who completed 24 of 45 passes and threw two touchdowns, was
named the game's MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who only five years ago was stocking groceries
in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt Warner reinforces our faith in dreams and fairy tales,''
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said. ``Many people were wondering
whether the dream or the fairy tale would end. Well, it hasn't
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' success doesn't figure to end soon, unless they turn
into a post-Super Bowl toad, as the Falcons and Broncos did.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has only three starters _ cornerback Todd Lyght,
offensive tackle Fred Miller and center Mike Gruttadauria _
eligible for unrestricted free-agency. The Rams, who will be about
$15.7 million under the projected $62.5 million salary cap this
year, probably will keep Lyght by designating him their
``franchise'' player.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the talent and young players that we have on this team,
it looks like things could be in place for a long time,'' Warner
said. ``But again, you never know what tomorrow may bring.
Hopefully, the guys will want to stay together, and we can keep
this thing going for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious offseason issues are the futures of coach Dick
Vermeil and backup quarterback Trent Green, the expected 1999
starter who suffered a season-ending knee injury in an exhibition
game.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil, 63, has two years remaining on his contract, which he
signed in 1997 after a 14-year respite from coaching. Earlier this
month, the Rams signed offensive coordinator Mike Martz to an
extension, which includes a clause declaring him to be Vermeil's
eventual successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I am going to do is give some thought to
getting home and getting myself reorganized,'' Vermeil said Monday.
``I'm going to spend some time with my wife and talk about a lot of
things. It is much better to be talking about (retirement) than
answering the questions about getting fired, which I have done for
two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner said Vermeil didn't tell the team what he might do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I heard,'' Warner said. ``He didn't give any
indications in front of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Rams players say they won't be surprised if Vermeil decides
to retire. Vermeil won only nine games in his first two seasons
with the Rams, who often complained about his long practices and
grueling workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the utmost respect for Dick Vermeil,'' St. Louis free
safety Keith Lyle said. ``You know, a lot of times they say an old
dog can't change his habits. Well, he changed his habits. He
changed his ways. And it got us all the way to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, the former Washington Redskins starter who signed a
four-year, $16 million contract with the Rams in February, might
not have a future in St. Louis. Warner is an ``exclusive-rights''
free agent, and the team can sign him to a one-year contract worth
about $2 million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams could trade Green, but his signing bonus would be
accelerated against the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to work hard and get back to being a starter
again,'' Green said. ``I'd love to be back with St. Louis. It's a
very family-oriented organization, very sound. But I do want to be
a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
