<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2256 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-OXYGEN-COX     01-31 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oxygen takes its first breath on Wednesday
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the new cable network Oxygen, women are going online and
shopping, stretching to yoga instructors and kvetching about bad
dates, delivering the news and having pajama parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a bunch of rowdy girls,'' says Caryn Mandabach, one of
Oxygen's founder-programmers. Actually, they're a bunch of smart,
ambitious women marketing themselves as rowdy girls.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen, a cable network run and programmed by women and aimed at
women, debuts Wednesday. (The launch date _ 02/02/00 _ is a pun on
the chemical symbol for oxygen.)
</P>
<P>
   The channel's unusual name came from Geraldine Laybourne, who
says she woke up one night gasping for breath and decided that what
women need is a little breathing room, a little oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The network provided advance tapes of only a tiny fraction of
programming, but here's how Oxygen's schedule will run at first.
Some shows are repeated several times a day, which is how Oxygen
can fill a 168-hour week with 55 hours of original programming.
</P>
<P>
   Monday-Friday:
</P>
<P>
   _ 7 a.m. ``Inhale.'' _ ``When you wake up in the morning, what
do you want to do?'' asks Mandabach. ``You want to stretch.'' Well,
maybe not everyone does, but those who do can watch an hour of
yoga.
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 a.m., 12 noon and 8 p.m. ``Pure Oxygen.'' _ A two-hour block
of news and features, considered the channel's signature show even
though it lacks the star power of a Bergen or Winfrey. Details are
sketchy. The two-hour block repeats three times a day.
</P>
<P>
   _ 10 a.m., 10 p.m. and 1 a.m. ``Exhale.'' _ Candice Bergen talks
to celebrities (Jodie Foster and Helen Hunt are booked) and a mix
of artists, politicians, sex experts, you name it. The set is very
cozy (there's even a candle burning on the coffee table the guests
gather 'round), and Bergen makes it feel more like a conversation
than a formal interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 p.m. ``As She Sees It'' _ Documentaries about women.
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 p.m. and 11 p.m. ``Trackers'' _ A two-hour block aimed at
teens. Details are sketchy, but it will feature one of the
channel's few male faces, Dr. Mike Riera, a counselor and author of
``Surviving High School.''
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, Oxygen will look significantly different.
</P>
<P>
   The big show will be ``Oprah Goes Online'' at 8 p.m. Sundays.
Winfrey, one of the founding investors in Oxygen, says she was
``completely illiterate'' about computers before she started taping
this series of cyber how-tos. The first one starts with the basics:
This is a screen, a keyboard, a mouse. Oxygen's programmers know
that many women will be way beyond Winfrey's baby steps _ women's
online use exploded after the shows started taping _ but hope that
Oprah will draw them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled for weekends:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``X Chromosome'' (10:30 p.m. Saturday and Sunday), a
laboratory for animation. Lots of quick hits zip in and out,
including ``Bitchy Bits,'' about the agony of trying on bathing
suits, and some material that is pretty risque for TV.
</P>
<P>
   _``SheCommerce'' (8 a.m. Saturday and Sunday), four hours of
shopping tips.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Girl in the Picture'' (8 p.m. Saturday), the only
non-original show on Oxygen: reruns of classic old movies with
stars like Joan Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   _``Pajama Party'' (11 p.m. Saturday) _ An audience and guest
celebs hang out in their PJs and indulge in ``taboo topics,
mind-bending trends and far-out music,'' according to Oxygen's
press release. Hosted by Katie Puckrik, whom Oxygen has dubbed the
``new millennium It Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing certain about Oxygen's cable schedule is that it
will probably be very different in a few months. The learning curve
is steep on any new show, and Oxygen is launching a bunch at once.
Plus the network will be monitoring chat rooms and message boards
on its Website, www.oxygen.com, to gauge what's working and what
isn't with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
