<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-BRADLEY01-C     01-31 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-BRADLEY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Super Bowl team bigger thrill than Super Bowl host
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The difference between having your team in the Super
Bowl and having the Super Bowl in your town is the difference
between heart and head. When it's your team playing, the emotions
are engaged 24/7. When it's your town serving as host, you keep a
clinical distance.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons played in Super Bowl XXXIII. Atlanta staged
Super Bowl XXXIV. The latter was the better spectacle by far, but
to those of us who live here it was almost a game in a bubble _ fun
to watch, riveting in the final quarter, somehow weightless a day
later. It happened downtown, yes, but it had little effect on us.
With the last visitors headed home, what do we locals recall about
the final weekend of the first month of 2000? The ice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was something else. A bad game capped a fortnight of
utter frenzy. Remember the team buses looping through the throngs
at Centennial Olympic Park en route to Hartsfield International
Airport? Remember how every utterance seemed fraught with meaning?
Remember how we parsed Dan Reeves' ``I-have-hurt-feelings''
address, directed at Mike Shanahan and John Elway? Remember the
back and forth over Ray Buchanan's semi-guarantee of victory? Over
his Media Day dog collar? Over Shannon Sharpe's rejoinder?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about Super XXXIV registered in that way and not just
because the weather turned frigid and the NFL Hype Machine got
ratcheted down. To us, it was a football game that just happened to
be played here. Luck of the draw. Super XXXIII, by way of contrast,
could have been a day of deliverance for a franchise that had spent
33 years tripping over itself. For all the Braves' great October
work in the '90s, last year's Super Bowl promised to be the biggest
event in Atlanta sports history. That it wound up a dud only
deepened the hurt.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if Titans fans feel as lousy today as Falcons fans did
a year ago. I doubt it. Tennessee played hard and well. Tennessee
trailed 16-0 and tied the score. The Falcons trailed 17-6 after
three quarters, 31-6 five minutes later. Tennessee lost because
Kevin Dyson's arms aren't telescopic. The Falcons lost without
giving themselves a chance. I've lived and worked here 16 years,
and no morning-after has been so glum as that Monday, when all the
talk was of Eugene Robinson, when the Falcons' welcome-home rally
was as spirited as a Bill Bradley stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   When you're the host city, you want things to go smoothly but
won't agonize over much if they don't. After the fallout over the
Olympics, we Atlantans have become somewhat less sensitive about
what others think of us. But when it's your team, sensitivity gets
heightened to the max. You want your guys to win the game, to lift
the Lombardi Trophy, to give you an excuse to spend $45 on a
sweatshirt that has ``Super Bowl champions'' on the front.
</P>
<P>
   Rams fans have that excuse. Falcons fans didn't get theirs. A
year later, it still hurts. Invest that much feeling in something,
even something as silly as a Super Bowl, and the investment carries
a surcharge. When it's your team playing, you can't stand on the
figurative sidelines. Like it or not, you're involved.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
