<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FLU-VACCINE01-COX     01-31 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-VACCINE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One part of next year's flu vaccine decided; two to go
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal advisers deciding the formula for next winter's flu
vaccine have agreed on one of its three components but deferred a
decision on the remaining two.
</P>
<P>
   In an annual meeting convened Friday outside Washington by the
Food and Drug Administration, representatives of the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, joined by other influenza experts,
took the first stab at defining the best vaccine to offer during
the next flu season nine months from now.
</P>
<P>
   The final choices are to be made by March and will affect the 60
million to 80 million Americans who receive flu shots annually.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine recipe _ decided so far in advance of the next flu
season because the vaccine-manufacturing process is time-consuming
_ is based on the flu strains that have been most troublesome
during the current season, combined with scientific predictions of
ways in which the viruses might change genetically by next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the vaccine is formulated to combat two strains
of influenza subtype A and one of influenza subtype B. On Friday,
those at the meeting agreed on one A strain, a subtype found
recently on the South Pacific island of New Caledonia. But they
agreed to wait for more data on this season's outbreaks before
selecting the remaining portions of the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Type A Sydney, the cause of widespread outbreaks this year,
continues to circulate worldwide, the scientists were told. The
lack of change in the Sydney strain is surprising given that it
first emerged three years ago, said Dr. Nancy Cox, chief of the
CDC's influenza branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really looking for a distinct new variant, and we
haven't seen one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The current vaccine formulation, decided this time last year,
was accurate despite higher rates of sickness and death this year,
said the CDC's Keiji Fukuda.
</P>
<P>
   In numbers released last week, the CDC said that this flu season
began earlier, and caused more deaths, than flu seasons in the past
two years. The season has peaked both nationwide and in Georgia,
according to federal and state health authorities. Flu in Georgia
has been downgraded to ``regional outbreaks'' after peaking between
Jan. 9 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters News Service contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
