<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-PREVENTION01-C     01-31 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-PREVENTION01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC experts put prevention first, in their careers and their
lives
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christine Branche and Michael Pratt work hard at their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   They spend weeks designing programs that affect thousands of
people. They have invested years doing research and developing
their specialties: Pratt is a physician with two master's degrees,
and Branche has a Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   And if they do their jobs very, very well ... nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what they hope for.
</P>
<P>
   Branche, 38, and Pratt, 43, are living exemplars _
professionally and personally _ of one of the knottiest problems
facing the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. That would
be the last word in the Atlanta-based agency's name, the one that
doesn't make it into the well-known abbreviation CDC: prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Prevention is the science of reducing the risks that health
problems will happen, so that adults won't develop avoidable
cancers, members of minority groups won't be at greater risk of
diabetes or high blood pressure, and children won't die from
vaccine-preventable diseases. It takes a tremendous amount of
effort to produce a negative result: no colon cancer, no diphtheria
deaths, no strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a good umpire in a baseball game,'' Pratt
said. ``If you go unnoticed, you've done your job well.''
</P>
<P>
   Prevention is a hard sell. One month ago today, when the world
woke up to find that civilization hadn't ended at midnight, Y2K
suddenly looked like ``Why did we bother?'' Computers weren't
crashing, banks weren't failing, and airplanes weren't falling from
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, of course, that Y2K would have been Yawn2K all
along _ that the billions of dollars invested in millennial
planning were a waste. But it's also possible that nothing happened
precisely because those advance efforts prevented it.
</P>
<P>
   The derision that accompanied the Y2K non-meltdown demonstrates
how difficult that concept can be. For many Americans, it's equally
difficult to believe that taking the stairs today can help fend off
a heart attack 30 years in the future. The task of Branche and
Pratt and hundreds of their CDC colleagues is developing that
trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inactivity itself doesn't kill people,'' explained Pratt, a
researcher in the CDC's division of nutrition and physical
activity. ``It increases the risks for diseases that usually take
place a long time down the line. People don't tend to get excited
about possibilities that far in the future; they're not much of a
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Not trusting that prevention can work is a problem even for
experts. Not long ago, Branche, director of the CDC's injury
prevention division, addressed a group of infectious-disease
specialists. Within 20 years, she told them, research suggests that
the top three causes of death worldwide will be pregnancy-related
problems, mental illness and accidental injuries. Disease deaths
won't make the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if I shot their dog,'' Branche recalled. ``These
were people closely identified with all kinds of infectious agents,
working in all kinds of international settings. What did I mean,
disease wouldn't be a problem? And I said, Well, I think you should
be glad. If you are doing your jobs right, it shouldn't be on the
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of World War II, scientific research has shown
that eating well, using vaccines, sleeping enough, getting
exercise, wearing seat belts and stopping smoking all confer health
benefits. But it's a long leap from scientific research to personal
action. Almost everyone has a story of some friend or relative who
loathed vegetables, disdained vitamins, got their exercise walking
to the corner store for cigarettes and outlived doctors and
doomsayers alike. Faced with the choice between a bacon
cheeseburger and broccoli, we want to believe we have luck _ or
genetics _ on our side.
</P>
<P>
   CDC's prevention warriors make no such assumptions. To spend
time with them is to step into a world where you do not get points
for luck.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt works in a CDC satellite location, a smoked-glass tower
off Chamblee Tucker Road. There are two elevators serving the upper
floors of the building. There's also a colorful sign posted next to
the elevator buttons: ``Next door to the left, no waiting.'' The
next door to the left is the entrance to the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the stairwell project,'' Pratt said. ``They have
been carpeted and painted and there are pictures at each landing.
The idea is that, if you make the stairs much more attractive,
people will choose to take them. There have been several research
projects showing that this does, in fact, work.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt is the principal investigator for a joint project shared
by the CDC and 11 nations in the World Health Organization. Its
goal is measuring how much physical activity different national
groups engage in, and finding ways to encourage each to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a society we have been phenomenally successful at
engineering activity out of people's lives,'' Pratt said. ``Now we
are trying to turn the tables, to see whether there are things we
can do that put activity back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoehorning exercise into a long workday is a challenge for
almost anyone, even scientists whose job is physical-activity
research. In Pratt's office, the answer has been to make lunch do
double duty, sometimes even triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a fair amount of running at lunchtime here,'' he said.
``There are probably at least two dozen people in this center who
run pretty regularly. Sometimes we end up continuing meetings on
the run. It is definitely an office culture that is different from
other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Thought-out behaviors
</P>
<P>
   But taking personal lessons from data on preventive health isn't
unique to Pratt's office. Branche supervises researchers who gather
data on accidental deaths and injuries, from dog bites to backyard
drownings to car crashes. As a division chief, she travels
frequently, and she is famous agencywide for upbraiding taxi
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't get in a vehicle and allow it to move if I don't have
my seat belt fastened,'' Branche said. ``I have gotten into a
couple of tussles with cabdrivers in Washington, because if you are
coming out of an airport they want you to close the passenger-side
door as quickly as possible. But I learned that if you close the
door they'll start to move, and I am like, `No, we are not moving
until the seat belt's on.' So I leave the door open.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds picky. On the other hand, motor vehicle accidents
are the leading cause of death for Americans under age 25 _ and for
every such death, there are 19 hospitalizations, 233 trips to the
emergency room and 450 visits to doctors' offices. Living with
numbers like those might make anyone willing to sacrifice speedy
arrival for fastened seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   Seat belt use hasn't been Branche's only take-home lesson. Her
personal expertise is in accidental drowning, the second leading
cause of death among young adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to structure my life to take into account the things
that I preach,'' she said. ``So, for instance, I have a young niece
and nephew, both under 5, who visit frequently. And I won't buy a
house with a pool _ would never think about buying a house with a
pool _ because of neighbors' children and because of my own family
members.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of thought-out behaviors goes on. She won't wear
stiletto heels. She is African-American but wears SPF 15 sunscreen.
She power-walks, but always facing traffic and never after dark.
</P>
<P>
   She also pokes fun at her own carefulness. ``I exercise four
times a week; I eat my vegetables; they say, `Drink one glass of
orange juice a day,' and guess who drinks two?
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff give me grief, affectionately. They are like,
`Christine, do you really do this stuff?' And I say, `Yes, I do. We
have to be our own best examples.'''
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
