<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREVENTION-BOX01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC's habits for healthy living
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEALTHY HABITS
</P>
<P>
   One of the CDC's goals is to persuade average people _ that
means you _ to weave healthy habits into their daily routines.
Among the most important:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do the basics: Get enough sleep (eight hours nightly) and eat
right (at least five servings of vegetables and fruits a day, and
keep saturated fat low).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for opportunities to get even a little exercise: Walk
from the far end of the parking lot; take the stairs. Aim for 30
minutes of exercise each day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Review your vaccination records, and your children's. Get up
to date on any that have been missed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy sunscreen. Use it. Every day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Next year, get a flu shot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wear your seat belt. Always.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do not allow children in pools, or even bathtubs, unless an
alert adult is present.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy smoke alarms. Buy batteries for them. Change the batteries
twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep children in the back seat of the car until they're at
least 11 _ in an appropriate child seat, or in a seat belt when
they're older. This is not just because of potential risks from air
bags; overall, the CDC says, the back seat is safer.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
