<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2265 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND01-COX     01-31 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Out of office, Gingrich aims to be man of ideas
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich may be out, but he's not down. In an update on the
former U.S. House speaker, U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) says
the new Newt is pulling down $50,000 a speech and has raised $1
million for his Committee for New American Leadership. Shunned by
his Republican political pals, Gingrich says he doubts he will ever
hold public office again. Instead, he wants to be a man of ideas.
His proposals include limiting the combined federal and state tax
load to 25 percent, repealing estate taxes, and using the Internet
as a vehicle for health care reform. ``There's no reason you can't
schedule a doctor's appointment the way you schedule an airline
ticket,'' he says. One thing Gingrich isn't talking about is the
sex scandal that derailed his political career and wrecked his
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In what might be considered a related article, the magazine
examines the reasons we fall in love. Forget the candy and flowers.
It's all about biology and genetics and survival of the species.
Women look for healthy, tall men and men look for women with small
waists and nice legs. Sometimes they are drawn to mates who remind
them of their mothers or fathers. You can compensate for looks,
though, by showing you have a nurturing, caring side, according to
the experts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The laughing game: Sometimes comedy can be tragic. In a
splendid profile of Jerry Lewis in The New Yorker ($3), James
Kaplan recounts the entertainer's roller-coaster career. ``In 1973,
with his career and his nearly thirty-year marriage sputtering,''
Kaplan writes, ``Lewis, in a Percodan haze ... put the muzzle of a
.38 revolver in his mouth.'' The sound of his young sons running
and laughing in the hall kept him from pulling the trigger. Now,
Kaplan says, Lewis is on the rebound, thanks to the popularity of
Jim Carrey and the return of physical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wrestling mania: The matches are as carefully scripted as any
TV sitcom and the characters as outlandish as cartoon figures, but
apparently that doesn't bother the millions of fans who are hooked
on professional wrestling. Newsweek ($3.95) examines the boom that
has spawned best-selling books, merchandise, Web sites and
lucrative TV contracts. In a fun sidebar, Newsweek reporter Cliff
Compton spends four days at a wrestling school and lives (barely)
to tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Following the money: In a new investigative series on campaign
finance, Time ($3.95) reports on who wins and who loses. The
exhaustive investigation tells most of us what we already know: The
folks who contribute the most money to politicians get the most
benefits. One example is Chiquita Brands International, which
contributed $7 million in an effort to get Washington to pressure
Europe into allowing more Chiquita bananas into the food markets.
And Chiquita bananas are not even grown in the United States. So
who gets hurt? According to Time, small business people like Rick
Reinert of Summerville, S.C., whose German bath-product imports
were slapped with a 100 percent tariff.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tut, tut: The rumors about malevolent Egyptian spirits causing
the deaths of more than 25 people involved with the discovery of
King Tut's tomb in 1922 apparently are false. According to Details
($3), researchers have found dangerous levels of radon in several
ancient Egyptian structures, including tourist spots such as the
Sakhm Khat Pyramid at Saggara. Unlike determined archaeologists,
the average tourist isn't exposed long enough to be harmed, the
magazine reports, and officials plan to install improved
ventilation systems. Another article worth reading is U.S. poet
laureate Robert Pinsky's advice to lovers who want to pen a
Valentine's Day poem: Steal from a poem you like, pretend that
adjectives cost more than caviar, and don't rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
