<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, Feb. 1, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-WRAPUP (Concord, N.H.) _ Down to wire in New Hampshire,
where a loss won't be fatal to Texas Gov. George Bush or Vice
President Al Gore, who have resources and party regulars to fight
future battles. A win is nearly essential, however, to the
reformist grassroots GOP campaign of Arizona Sen. John McCain, and
badly needed by the Democrats' challenger, ex-Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MEDIA (NASHUA, N.H._ WMUR-TV of Manchester, N.H., may
be America's most politically influential local television station.
Over the past dozen years, the station has supplanted the state's
largest newspaper, the Union Leader, in terms of the voters it
reaches.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   EXERCISE-STRETCH (Undated) _ Double-knot your running shoes,
drink water and stretch _ that's the long-recommended routine to
start an injury-free workout. But some studies now say stretching
doesn't do much good _ and could be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   By Amy E. Nevala. (Story has moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOVA (Undated) _ ``Nova'' is at it again. Having successfully
attempted to figure out how the ancients built such engineering
marvels as the pyramids and Stonehenge, the PBS series takes on
more ``Secrets of Lost Empires'' this month, beginning with
``Medieval Siege,'' an episode depicting the efforts of two teams
to re-create the ``atom bomb'' of the Middle Ages _ the catapult.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTHORS-NICHOLS (Tacoma, Wash.) _ Mother of three sons, wife of
an attorney, part-time college secretary _ these were the devotions
of Linda Nichols' daily life for many years. And there was her
devotion to writing, as she toiled away at community college
writing workshops, listened to critiques of her work by fellow
students and hoped that someday some of her words might be
published. Then, in just three weeks, life became a fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   By John Marshall. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
