<SLUG> BC-NH-BRADLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY RETURNS TO SOFT-KEY APPROACH ON EVE OF N.H. PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2 and NYT4 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLIS, N.H. _ Sen. Paul Wellstone, a former college wrestler
who knows a thing or two about cheerleading, got a crowd of nearly
1,000 Bill Bradley supporters here fired up Monday morning in his
high-energy style, pumping his arms and screaming at the top of his
lungs, ``We're gonna win in New Hampshire!'' over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd stood and cheered wildly. Then came Bradley. And for
the next 25 minutes, he calmed them back down with a speech that
was part lecture on the global economy and part sermon on human
goodness.
</P>
<P>
   So it went for Bradley on Monday. On the eve of New Hampshire's
first-in-the-nation primary, a time when presidential candidates
typically dash from photo opportunity to photo opportunity,
rallying crowds with thundering stem winders, Bradley returned to
the relaxed, soft-edged, professorial approach he perfected in
front of small audiences months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if he was less than rousing on the day before the primary,
Bradley was clearly connecting with many people in his audiences,
all of which were large and enthusiastic. And it was precisely
Bradley's unwillingness, or inability, to deliver a tub-thumping,
end-of-the-campaign speech that made him seem appealing to many
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just straight, and that's what we like here,'' said
Barbara Schwartz, 60, who came to hear Bradley at the high school
here. ``We're New Hampshirites. We don't like the rah-rah stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Bradley got to sounding like a conventional
candidate on the brink of a critical election was during a
late-afternoon speech before hundreds of charged up campaign
workers in Manchester. Yet even there, the most electrifying
speeches were delivered by his surrogates, particularly Cornell
West, the Harvard professor.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the day, Bradley's style and speech were reminiscent
of his campaign events of the fall. His voice rarely reached
Wellstone-like decibels. His sentences rambled through thickets of
complex clauses, only occasionally landing on punchy applause
lines. He dwelt on spiritual issues as much as bread-and-butter
ones. He seemed almost apologetic about asking people for their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   And after having spent nearly a week bashing his opponent, Vice
President Al Gore, as dishonest, he barely mentioned the vice
president on Monday, and usually it was part of a joke about a
rabidly anti-Knick sports announcer from Boston named Johnny Most.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say Al Gore has done a lot of negative campaigning, but
it doesn't compare to the 10 years of character assassination I
endured at the hands and words of Johnny Most,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had come under criticism in recent days from some voters
for his new, more combative style. But his aides asserted that
polls indicate that the attacks had been working. And they asserted
that Bradley had shifted tone Monday not because of concerns about
alienating undecided voters but because he wanted to finish with an
uplifting message.
</P>
<P>
   And there was inspirational oratory a plenty at every stop. ``I
want to be the president of the United States to use the power of
that office to do good,'' he told the audience at Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   After that speech, the audience gave Bradley a spirited ovation
that lasted nearly a minute. But rather than basking in the
applause, Bradley looked almost sheepish, stepping backward from
the podium and then trying to quiet the crowd like a father with a
noisy child, gently repeating, ``OK, OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was Bradley's low-key approach that Roy Swonger, 35, an
Oracle manager, found most attractive about the candidate. ``There
was no part in the speech when he was looking for applause,'' he
said. ``I'm happy to see that in a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Never comfortable with the scripted gestures of campaigning,
Bradley managed to missed several photo opportunities Monday. In
the morning, he bought a shovel in Concord and went to work
clearing part of a walkway. The display seemed aimed at
demonstrating that Bradley, who occasionally suffers from an
irregular heart beat, is in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   But no television camera crews were around to record the event.
Later, his bus stopped and an aide jumped off with the shovel. But
Bradley never got off the bus. He was concerned, apparently, about
getting to his next speech on time.
</P>
</TEXT>
