<HEADLINE>
WATTS ANNOUNCES FOR FOURTH TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Story has been shorted.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, one of the nation's
most prominent black Republicans, said Monday he would seek
re-election this fall, ending widespread speculation that he would
retire from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that ``there is important work left undone,'' Watts, a
42-year-old rising star in Republican circles, agreed to run for a
fourth term after House Speaker Dennis Hastert and other top
Republicans lobbied him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, the fourth-ranking House Republican, who is in charge of
the party's congressional message, had been dropping hints for
months that he and his family had tired of Washington's political
treadmill. He and his staff had clashed with aides to Rep. Tom
DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, over control of the party's
message.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Watts told supporters at a news conference in his
home state that he would stay in Congress to help shore up Social
Security and Medicare, fight for tax cuts and advocate more money
for the military.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
