<HEADER>
A2274 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HMO-FOR-PROFITS-BOS &LR;      01-31 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-FOR-PROFITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY FOR-PROFIT ROUTE NOT GOOD FOR AILING HMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three for-profit health care companies known to be
interested in buying Harvard Pilgrim Health Care generally score
lower on performance measures ranging from vaccinations to
mammography rates, according to data from a national
quality-monitoring group.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors who did the analysis said Monday the poorer scores
show that CIGNA HealthCare, Anthem Health Plans, and Oxford Health
Plans provide lower-quality care while spending more on overhead
costs such as marketing and executive salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is likely that turning over Harvard Pilgrim's 1.1 million
subscribers to any of these three for-profit companies would result
in a lowering of the quality of care, and an increase in the share
of premium dollars diverted to paperwork and profits,'' concluded
Dr. David U. Himmelstein and Dr. Steffie Woolhandler, who are
well-known for their opposition to stockholder-owned health care
companies.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brian Schilling, a spokesman for the National Committee
on Quality Assurance, which provided the HMO performance data for
the analysis, cautioned against comparing the Massachusetts health
plan with those in other regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woolhandler and Himmelstein have a lot of clout in the
industry. I'm not about to call their results spurious,'' Schilling
said. ``But it's probably premature to say for-profits are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Himmelstein and Woolhandler asserted that deaths from breast
cancer and heart attacks would rise if Harvard Pilgrim switched to
for-profit status. They noted that nationally the three for-profit
plans had lower rates of mammography and appropriate post-heart
attack drug treatment than Harvard Pilgrim reported last year, the
most recent available data.
</P>
<P>
   For every 100,000 women enrolled in CIGNA, Himmelstein said,
there are 12,600 fewer mammograms every two years than among the
same number enrolled in Harvard Pilgrim. Judging by estimates of
mammography effectiveness, he said, that would translate into 66
more breast cancer deaths among every 100,000 middle-aged female
CIGNA subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   A CIGNA spokesman, Howard Drescher, took issue with the new
analysis, asserting that it ``significantly misrepresents CIGNA
HealthCare's performance in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to talk about Harvard Pilgrim, they need to
compare our performance in Massachusetts,'' Drescher said. ``Most
of our scores there approach those of Harvard Pilgrim.''
</P>
<P>
   Among CIGNA's 157,000 Massachusetts subscribers, 78 percent of
women between ages 52 and 69 receive mammograms every two years, as
recommended, compared to 83 percent of comparable Harvard Pilgrim
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing CIGNA's 27 plans nationally to Harvard Pilgrim, the
for-profit company's scores were often much lower on such measures
as immunization of toddlers and adolescents, mammography and Pap
smears, and obstetrical care.
</P>
<P>
   This was also true for Anthem and Oxford, although Athem
appeared to outperform Harvard Pilgrim on obstetrical care and
regular eye exams among diabetics. Attempts to reach officials at
those two companies were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Woolhandler and Himmelstein pointed out that Anthem did not
release data last year for five of its seven health plans, possibly
because scores in those plans were low. In fact, CIGNA did not
release data in 1998 because, its spokesman said, ``we needed to
get our numbers up.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, the National Committee on Quality Assurance
spokesman, acknowledged that plans' decisions not to release data
usually conceal unfavorable scores. ``Common sense would dictate
that,'' Schilling said. ``If I were their marketing person that's
what I would do.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that New England HMOs tend to perform better on
standard measures than others in regions ``that tend to have a lot
of different geographical, cultural, and other challenges you don't
have in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   But Himmelstein challenged that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regional effect is that so far we've managed to keep
for-profits out,'' he said. ``Really what it boils down to is we've
had a strong culture of not-for-profit care. Where those values
have taken a back seat, the quality has been lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolhandler and Himmelstein said the HMO industry's data show
that Harvard Pilgrim spent 8.5 percent of subscriber premium
dollars for administration compared to nearly 12 percent at CIGNA,
15 percent at Anthem, and 18 percent at Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   In other Harvard Pilgrim action Monday, Massachusetts Attorney
General Thomas F. Reilly moved to block hospitals, social workers,
and mental health professionals from intervening legally in the
Harvard Pilgrim case. The Massachusetts Hospital Association, the
Massachusetts Psychiatric Association, the Massachusetts
Psychological Association and the National Association of Social
Workers filed motions to intervene with the court.
</P>
<P>
   If granted, the motions would allow the organizations special
status in the case, including the ability to question Harvard
Pilgrim and request documents. Reilly opposes the motion, partly
because he worries it will slow the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have a say in whatever happens,'' said First
Assistant Attorney General Dean Richlin. ``They need to move
quickly and have maximum flexibility. If you're trying to make stew
in six hours, and you have another six people you're consulting
with about how to make the stew, you can't make it in six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Dreyfus of the Massachusetts Hospital Association said
hospitals asked the organization to intervene. But ``we believe we
are getting the access and information we need from the attorney
general's office and the receiver,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general is not opposing petitions by the consumer
group Health Care for All and the Service Employees International
Union to act as ``friends of the court'' in the Harvard Pilgrim
case, which allows them to express opinions and share information
but not to make legal motions and ask questions in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Liz Kowalczyk of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
