<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KURT WARNER GIVES HOPE TO OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Getting by on ``not a wink'' of sleep, Kurt Warner was
asked to supply a moral to his own story.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the most cooperative of athletes in this Super Bowl
of outsiders, perpetually going back over the fine points of the
$5.50-an-hour wage at the Hy-Vee grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Warner said, fidgeting a bit, suddenly out of
psychic gas. ``You tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Very well. Let's take a look at the saga of Kurt Warner, and
saga it is.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is living proof that dreams need not be put aside at an
early age. There may always be a second option, and a third option,
even when life's brutish linebackers come blitzing.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Warner never gave up. He knew what he loved, and he wanted
to keep doing it, and he might still be pitching footballs in the
Arena Football League if he had not just won a Super Bowl with the
St. Louis Rams, and that would have been all right, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting to the point of thinking how much longer am I
going to have before people say he is too old to give him an
opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of other quarterbacks who will never play in
a Super Bowl. Warner was saying he could have lived being one of
them, with the dream but not the assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been tough for us until last year, really,'' Warner
said. ``Even when I was playing arena football, we did all right,
but a lot of tough decisions, especially when you have kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started dating my wife, she was on food stamps,
and I was in between jobs. That is why I ended up stocking shelves;
I had to do something at nights so I could work out and keep my
chances in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner added: ``A lot of things like that have helped keep
things in perspective, even though we are not making millions of
dollars. We are very fortunate to be where we are at, in this
position, and don't look beyond that, don't take anything for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   In this dot-com world, companies have little loyalty, sacking
people on a whim, because of the erratic zigs and zags of the stock
market. There are no guarantees, but Warner's strength can be an
example.
</P>
<P>
   Monday he recalled the meat market for NFL Europe, with hordes
of hungry players shuttled to Atlanta in the winter to earn the
right to perform in those football hotbeds of Barcelona and
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was miserable,'' Warner said. ``Never want to come back here
and practice in the cold and snow again. But I knew that if I was
going to get a chance to get back here that it would be through NFL
Europe. It was ironic when we came out here last week and it was
cold and the icy rain and all that.'' He stuck it out in foul
weather early in 1998 and earned himself a trip to Amsterdam, where
he played his way back onto the Rams' squad.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he was a ``service quarterback'' as Dick Vermeil calls
it, somebody who pitches against the first-string defense, to save
the arm of the regular quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think from a quarterback's standpoint, it is easier to fall
through the cracks than maybe any other position,'' Vermeil said,
adding, ``Coaches spend a lot of time proving their decisions are
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Warner was allowed to mop up the last game, and was
exposed in the draft to stock the new Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Kurt Warner and told him exactly what we were
doing,'' Vermeil said recently. ``I didn't think anybody would take
a 27-year-old quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact was, Warner was expendable, like many people in this
fluctuating labor market. But the logic was right. The Browns did
not want a 27-year-old quarterback, so Warner was back in St. Louis
when Trent Green tore up his knee in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows what Warner has done since _ the 41 touchdown
passes, the most valuable player of the league and then of the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It is reasonable for the young in age, the young in soul, to
study Kurt Warner at this stage between obscurity and satiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just continue to follow my dreams, believe in the Lord and
live every day for what it is worth,'' Warner said. ``I don't know
if there is a moral in it. If somebody can find one and use it to
their benefit, then more power to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, for somebody operating on ``not a wink,'' living from
the energy of a fantastic and inspirational season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
