<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-PRIMARY-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC ABORTION DEBATE MUSIC TO GOP EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Abortion politics, which almost always agitates the
GOP, rarely causes Democratic primary candidates to squirm. No
wonder Republicans are reacting with glee _ and Democrats with a
little alarm _ to the dust-up between Al Gore and Bill Bradley over
who is more committed to a woman's right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it!'' said Linda DiVall, a Republican pollster who
spends a lot of time worrying about how the GOP can close the
gender gap. ``To have Democrats embroiled on abortion, even for a
couple of days, shows women voters that they, too, have divisions
on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights activists, who are attuned to every nuance on
the issue, say Bradley and Gore have the same position on abortion:
They support legalized abortion and are in the mainstream of the
Democratic Party, which in its 1996 platform endorsed a woman's
right to choose an abortion and to receive public funding to pay
for it, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Bradley and Gore are staunchly, solidly prochoice, and as
president each of them would ensure a woman's right to a legal
abortion,'' said Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion
and Reproductive Rights Action League. She says she's a little
exasperated that the heat of the Democratic primary in New
Hampshire has caused these candidates to shift the light from where
she believes it really belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue, and the threat they should be focusing on, is
that the Republicans _ even those who have toned down their
rhetoric on abortion in their campaigns _ are rabidly antichoice
and as president will deny women their legal rights,'' Michelman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But since polls show Bradley doing less well than Gore among
female voters, the New Jersey senator chose abortion as a way to
get women's attention and use it as a wedge issue to attack the
vice president's truthfulness and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   At a New Hampshire debate last week, Bradley challenged Gore's
credibility and credentials on abortion. The vice president said he
had never waivered in his support of Roe v. Wade, the 1973 Supreme
Court decision legalizing abortion. How then, Bradley questioned,
could Gore have opposed public funding of abortions for poor women
when he was a member of the US House in the late 1970s? As a
senator, Gore supported Medicaid funds for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, Gore also had to explain why, in letters he
wrote to constituents in 1983 and 1987, he called abortion
``arguably, the taking of a human life.'' By Saturday, Bradley was
airing a 30-second commericial accusing Gore of straddling the
abortion issue, and the vice president was admitting that ``my
position has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm puzzled; I don't understand why Gore wasn't more
forthcoming in the debate about his record on abortion,'' said
Eleanor Smeal, president of the Feminist Majority and a longtime
activist for women's rights. ``In the Senate Gore was a more
forceful proponent of abortion rights than Bradley, and the Clinton
administration's record on abortion has been excellent. But that
isn't what Gore said.''
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Ferraro, the Democratic vice presidential candidate in
1984, served in the House with Gore and was troubled then by his
opposition to Medicaid funds for abortions. ``I have a problem with
Gore saying he has always been pro-choice, but I also believe that
he has grown and changed,'' Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party doesn't welcome dissention on the abortion
issue. Since Roe v. Wade, all the party's presidential candidates
have been abortion-rights supporters. In 1992, Pennsylvania
Governor Bob Casey was refused a speaking slot at the party's
convention, reportedly because of his strong antiabortion views.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, according to a new Wall Street Journal/NBC News
poll, 51 percent of all Americans support a woman's right to choose
an abortion. That's down from 60 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore isn't leaving the issue to chance. Saturday, his
campaign had Representative Carolyn Maloney, a New York Democrat
who chairs the congressional women's caucus, fly to New Hampshire
and, along with Governor Jeanne Shaheen, defend the vice
president's record on abortion at a women's forum in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is trying to create a difference where none exists,''
said Maloney, who last week got 33 other Democratic lawmakers to
sign a letter praising the Clinton-Gore administration's tough line
on abortion-clinic violence and vetoes of bills to outlaw certain
late-term abortions. ``When Bradley says he is the only pro-choice
candidate, that is unfair and untrue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TREASURY-MARKETPLACE-     01-31 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURY-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: TREASURY MAKES FED'S JOB HARDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that the U.S. Treasury would do anything
to make Alan Greenspan's job of effecting monetary policy more
difficult than it already is. But that is exactly what is happening
today.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's policy-makers are widely expected to vote
to raise short-term interest rates at the end of their two-day
meeting scheduled to begin in Washington on Tuesday. But some of
the tools that Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, has
to cool the economy down in coming months have been dulled
considerably, thanks to the U.S. Treasury. As a result, the central
banker may have to be even more aggressive in raising rates than
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers at the central bank are in a highly unusual
situation today. The economy is strong by almost every measure and
in recent weeks, some inflation indicators have begun to stir. So
the Fed has tried to slow things down a bit by raising short-term
interest rates three times and signaling that further increases
were likely.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they have done so, yields on long-term bonds have
fallen, the opposite of what normally happens in an escalating-rate
environment. The move has created what is called an inverted yield
curve, where long-term yields fall below those on short-term
issues. Such an occurrence is atypical because investors who take
on additional risk by investing in long-term bonds are typically
paid more to do so than those who have taken on less risk by
investing in shorter-term issues.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond yield has dropped from around 6.75 percent on
Jan. 20 to 6.48 percent Monday. At the same time, the yield on the
2-year note has raced from 6.49 percent to 6.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this oddity is the Treasury's aggressive plan to reduce
the nation's debt. Its two-pronged plan to cut back on issuing
long-term debt and to buy back as much as $45 billion in long-term
bonds has made institutions like insurance companies and pension
funds stampede into the long end of the bond market buying anything
they can. These companies need long-term bonds to offset their
extended obligations; the perception that there is going to be a
shortage of long-term U.S. Treasuries has brought these investors
into the market with a vengeance, causing yields on long-term bonds
to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   What worries some bond market participants is that this plunge
in yields will blunt the impact that the Fed's interest rate
increases will have on the economy. By raising rates, the Fed hopes
to curtail economic activity by making it more expensive to borrow.
But with long-term rates so low, shrewd borrowers who might
typically have tapped the short-term market for capital will simply
issue long-term debt. Easy access to cheap, long-term debt will
help to keep the economy hot, while the Fed wants it to cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising the Fed funds rate has a much more powerful impact
when the yield curve is steepening than when it is inverted,'' said
Timothy Irwin, principal at Irwin Capital Management in New York.
``And if it is the Treasury's actions that are causing the yield
curve to invert, these actions are effectively making Greenspan's
job more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers consider many things, of course, when they
contemplate raising interest rates. They weigh economic data to
analyze the strength of the nation's output and scour the numbers
for evidence of inflation. But they also rely very heavily on the
behavior of the bond market to assay whether credit is too easily
available to companies issuing bonds or too tough to get.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market's moves have become a more critical
consideration for the Fed today than they had been to past central
bankers. That's because while banks once extended most of the
credit to issuers across the economy, now the capital markets are
responsible for the bulk of it. In 1975, banks accounted for 55
percent of total credit extended across the economy while capital
markets accounted for the rest. Now banks account for 30 percent,
while the capital markets dominate.
</P>
<P>
   So the Fed watches the bond market closely. In the late summer
of 1998, as Russia defaulted on its debt, the bond market's
seizures convinced the Fed to cut rates aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the inverted yield curve and the mixed signals that it is
sending to the Fed is troubling. ``It's a difficult situation
because the Fed has relied more upon capital markets to determine
how tight or tough credit terms are becoming,'' said David M. Jones
of Aubrey Lanston &AMP; Co. ``I would say anything north of 6.5 percent
on Treasury yield might have a chance of slowing down the economy.
Now suddenly we're back below 6.5 percent but you don't know what
that means.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as the Treasury's buyback of debt continues to distort
the bond market, the Fed will have to find other signals to monitor
whether credit is too lax or too tight.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making current credit conditions more difficult
for the Fed to measure, the recent behavior of long-term bond
yields carries significant risk to financial institutions and
consumers if it continues. Anyone with an adjustable-rate mortgage
will suffer because short-term rates are high, for example. And
banks, which borrow in short-term credit markets and lend for
longer terms, will be badly hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real risk in the marketplace is a massive inverted curve
for a long time,'' said Stan Jonas of Fimat USA, a brokerage firm
in New York. By raising rates, he added, the Fed may invert the
yield curve even further with short-term rates escalating while
yields on longer-term issues continue to fall. ``This would be good
for pensioners, but bad for people with adjustable mortgages. And
it would kill the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, many of the recent economic figures point to a growth
rate in the United States that is much hotter than Greenspan would
prefer. So short-term rates are expected to get a bump on
Wednesday, possible inverting the curve even more.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody said being a central banker was easy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
