<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT GETS SOME SUPPORT IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft gained some prominent allies in its antitrust fight
Monday, as two former U.S. attorneys general and a pair of former
senior White House lawyers supported the software company's defense
in a court filing.
</P>
<P>
   They crafted a friend-of-the-court brief submitted by the
Association for Competitive Technology, a trade group that has
close ties to Microsoft Corp. and was founded in 1998 when the
government filed its antitrust suit against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's filing was the first of a handful of
friend-of-the-court briefs in the case, with the others scheduled
to be submitted to U.S. District Court in Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Software and Information Industry Association, formerly the
Software Publishers Association, is expected to file a brief on
behalf of the government, according to a Washington lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group, whose members include the United States'
leading software companies _ including Microsoft _ is expected to
argue in its brief that Microsoft has a monopoly in the market for
personal-computer operating systems and that the company should not
be permitted to use its market power to protect its monopoly or to
give it an edge in new markets, according to the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Wasch, president of the Software and Information Industry
Association, declined to comment on whether his group was filing a
brief on the government's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lessig, a Harvard University law professor, is also
scheduled to file a brief Tuesday. His brief is being filed at the
request of Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who asked Lessig to
assess the technological ``tying'' arguments in the case. The
government charged that Microsoft illegally tied its Internet
browser, called Internet Explorer, to its industry-standard Windows
operating system, an allegation that Microsoft denies.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig's brief is expected to be more a careful analysis of how
the law applies to the Internet software market than an endorsement
of either side's courtroom arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has scheduled final oral arguments for Feb. 22. At the
same time, both sides are talking with a mediator, Judge Richard
Posner, chief justice in the federal appeals court in Chicago, who
is trying to see if an out-of-court settlement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's pro-Microsoft document was prepared by the Washington
law firm of Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering. Both Lloyd N. Cutler,
counsel to Presidents Clinton and Carter, and C. Boyden Gray,
counsel to President Bush, worked on the brief and signed it.
</P>
<P>
   Others who joined the brief supporting Microsoft include Griffin
Bell, attorney general in the Carter administration; Nicholas
Katzenbach, attorney general in the Johnson administration and
general counsel for IBM during its antitrust confrontation with the
government; and Howard J. Trienens, former general counsel for AT&AMP;T
during its court-ordered breakup.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-page document echoes Microsoft's courtroom argument that
it was an aggressive competitor but did not harm consumers and that
its conduct should not be declared illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states fought that defense in
court and continue to do so. ``Nothing in that brief can change the
facts or the law in the case,'' said a Justice Department official.
</P>
<P>
   After Jackson issued findings of fact in November that strongly
supported the government's version of the case, many legal scholars
said they expected that Microsoft would be found to have violated
the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The brief supporting Microsoft made no mention of sanctions
against the company. But legal experts suggested that one goal
might be to give Jackson an opportunity to have second thoughts
before approving such sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message they are trying to send is that Washington
insiders and outsiders, Republicans and Democrats, can thoughtfully
conclude that this case is misguided,'' observed William Kovacic, a
professor at George Washington University law school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
