<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PROVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING TRUST IN PROVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shooting death of Providence police officer Cornel Young Jr.
will severely test that city's public institutions in the coming
days and weeks. Incomplete or evasive answers could ignite
smoldering suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the son of the department's highest-ranking black
officer, was shot by fellow officers Friday when he rushed from a
restaurant to assist police in the arrest of a gunman. Young was
off duty and in street clothes; he was mistaken for a suspect and _
according to police _ was shot when he failed to drop his weapon as
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Early reaction suggests that Providence officials lack trust in
the average citizen. The city's mayor and police chief quickly
dismissed questions of whether race or racial profiling might have
contributed to the shooting. As of  &UR; yesterday &LR; , officials were
still refusing to identify the race or races of the police officers
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The citizenry, in turn, suspect the police. One city councilor
said his constituents were ``offended'' and ``in disbelief'' that
officials did not consider the role of race. Another councilor said
her constituents believe that ``Cornel Young Jr. was
assassinated.''
</P>
<P>
   The split-second nature of police work sometimes ends in
gruesome error. Forward-looking departments consider this when they
form ongoing partnerships with church groups and neighborhood
associations. Those community policing partnerships yield crime
tips and public cooperation. But they also yield the most precious
commodity in police work _ forgiveness when things fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Now city officials must act quickly to restore trust. The
investigation by Providence police and the state attorney general
would benefit from outside observers. The presence of a respected
organization, such as the National Organization of Black Law
Enforcement Executives, would help to assure the public that all
investigative options are explored and explained to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Without such resolve, forgiveness will be far away in
Providence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
