<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NH-CAMPAIGN-COX     01-31 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-CAMPAIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates court undecideds in last-minute campaigning
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ The Democratic and Republican candidates
toned down their negative campaigning and romped through the snow
Monday in a final effort to win over voters in the nation's first
primary state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident of victory tomorrow night, although we might be
up a little late,'' said Arizona Sen. John McCain, buoyed by polls
showing him holding to a lead over Texas Gov. George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, seemingly unperturbed by McCain's lead, captured first
place in a pancake flip-off here. GOP rival Gary Bauer flipped
next. He watched his pancake fly overhead, lost his balance,
stumbled backward and then toppled off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   In Concord, Democrat Bill Bradley, who has sparred with the
press during this campaign, scooped up snow and tossed snowballs at
reporters and photographers. Bush strategist Karl Rove and media
advisor Mark McKinnon carried on their own snowball war with
reporters, while their candidate toured the New Hampshire
Department of Safety.
</P>
<P>
   These light-hearted moments eased the tension as the campaigns
waited for the tiny precinct of Dixville Notch to open at midnight,
the traditional beginning of the first primary day.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-charging to the end, Vice President Al Gore began his day
before dawn and made several stops, ending with a town meeting in
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a contest,'' he said as he shook hands outside a
Nashua electronics firm at dawn Monday. ''The real fight is for our
future,'' he added, alluding to the fall campaign against the
Republican Party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush revealed in documents filed with the Federal
Election Commission that he raised another $11 million in the last
quarter of 1999 bringing his total to $68.7 million, the highest
total of all the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor had $38.4 million left in the band at the end
of the year, compared to $7.7 million for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush already has spent almost as much money _ $37.3 million _ as
most of the other candidates will be allowed to spend for their
entire campaigns. Bush is not accepting federal matching funds so
he is not bound by spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic race, Bradley raised some $8 million in the
last quarter, twice that raised by Gore, who reported $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Gore has raised $29 million, plus $2.9 million to pay
legal and accounting costs in the general election. Bradley has
raised $27.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   After days of attacking Gore for distorting his record, Bradley
wound down his campaign on a more positive note. He described his
contest with Gore as a choice between the ``old politics'' of
distortion and the ``new politics'' of telling voters what you are
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that when the returns are announced tomorrow night that
independent voters in New Hampshire will have sent a message to the
country that we can create a new kind of politics,'' Bradley told
400 supporters in Hollis.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned Gore only briefly in his remarks to voters Monday,
telling crowds that he was forced to become more critical of the
vice president because of what he called ``months of distortions.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a choice in this campaign,'' Bradley told a packed crowd
in Derry. ``I'm not prepared to settle. Al Gore is prepared to
settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Two senators supporting Bradley, Bob Kerry and Paul Wellstone,
held a news conference to answer House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt's charge that Bradley had turned the Democratic contest
into a divisive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ``may not end up on Gore's short list, or even his
Christmas card list, but we're all going to be reunited after this
is over,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also sought to strike a positive note after days of sharp
exchanges between the two Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to confine my campaign to the issues, as I have from
the beginning,'' Gore told a diner breakfast crowd, emphasizing the
issue of ''how we keep our prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he mingled with a lunchtime restaurant crowd in
Concord, he asserted that responsibility for the negative tone of
the campaign rests with Bradley. ''Personal attacks, no, I have not
engaged in them and I won't.''
</P>
<P>
   But gone from Gore's standard stump remarks was the often
repeated comment that Bradley is ''a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore kept up a hectic pace throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be campaigning full blast every minute of every
hour between now and (when the polls close Tuesday), leaving off a
few hours for sleep tonight,'' Gore said in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, campaigning with his wife and four of his children, held
five rallies across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The former POW stressed his experience as a Navy captain and a
foreign policy expert in the Senate, saying he would ``not need
on-the-job training'' as president and suggesting the same would
not be true of the other Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, McCain repeated the line that has become his
signature in the closing days of the New Hampshire campaign. ``I
will always tell you the truth, no matter what,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush kept things light after his pancake contest, sledding down
a 150-yard hill in Bedford with 13-year-old twins, Laura and Lizzy
Saggau, of Merrimack, along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   But his aides fired a shot at McCain, raising questions about
the senator's spending in New Hampshire and in South Carolina where
the GOP contenders will compete in that state's Feb. 19 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials said McCain, who has had made campaign
finance reform a central issue, has spent $2.1 million in New
Hampshire, much of it on television ads airing in Boston, Mass. and
far in excess of the $660,000
</P>
<P>
   spending cap. They said he spent $1.5 million in South Carolina,
approaching that state's $1.6 million cap.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has spent $3.3 million in New Hampshire and nearly $1.7
million in South Carolina. However, since he has declined federal
matching funds, Bush is not subject to the spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. Mark Sherman and Ken Foskett, Jena Heath and Scott Shepard
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
