<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NURSE-TRAINING-COX     01-31 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSE-TRAINING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nursing for dummies: Students get hands-on experience
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ She's been having trouble breathing, the patient
tells nurse Mindy Stamm in the emergency room. It's been going on
for a day or so. Her feet are swollen, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been coughing often?'' asks Joanne Crawford, the
respiratory therapist. All night, the patient says. She had to
sleep in her recliner. Another nurse, Stephanie Thompson, puts a
stethoscope to the patient's chest and hears her breathe with the
crackling sound of Rice Krispies in milk.
</P>
<P>
   Stamm asks if she's ever had heart trouble. She had a heart
attack about two years ago. Medication? Oh, what are those little
white pills called? The patient can't remember. And she used to
take another kind of pill, but it made her go to the bathroom too
often so she quit. Now that Stamm brings it up, though, it's been
about a day since the last time she went.
</P>
<P>
   Stamm props up the patient's head, and Crawford puts an oxygen
tube in her nostrils. It's clear by now that she has congestive
heart failure, her heart pumping so ineffectively that her lungs
are filling with fluid, so Stamm administers the diuretic drug
Lasix through her intravenous tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else are you going to give her?'' Louis Conn asks, and
the four discuss alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Conn is able to interrupt the patient's care and start this
discussion because the patient is just a lifeless dummy.
</P>
<P>
   The patient, named Pat for gender ambiguity, is the Human
Patient Simulator at Sinclair Community College, where Stamm and
Thompson are nursing students and Crawford is Conn's respiratory
care student. With plastic and microchips in place of skin and
bones, Pat can replicate the symptoms and vital signs of many
diseases and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   As patient simulators grow as commonplace as, say, flight
simulators, Conn expects them to change the way health-care
professionals are taught, evaluated and retrained on new
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   In the year that Sinclair has used Pat in its health-care
disciplines, students have been able to practice instead of
pretending. Rather than matching written responses to described
circumstances, the students have been interpreting wavy lines on
monitors, drawing conclusions from the sounds of breathing and
heartbeats, making quick decisions, working together with
colleagues and seeing for themselves what happens to a patient when
they do the right or wrong things with real machines and
medications.
</P>
<P>
   The three second-year students, who met Pat last fall, agree
that books and lectures can't begin to engender the confidence
they've developed from knowing they restored Pat's vital signs to
normal when the wrong actions would have stopped its heart and
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer always wants us to be more knowledgeable than
they are,'' Thompson said, ``but they don't want us to practice on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the patient with congestive heart failure, Conn and the
students agree that some morphine is a good idea not only to
relieve the gasping patient's anxiety but also for dilating the
blood vessels and taking pressure off the heart. As Stamm connects
the morphine IV, she hears the patient's bladder already emptying
from the Lasix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make sure the student is actually assessing the
effects of the drug instead of just saying, `I would then check for
urine,''' says Wanda Jelus, the nursing instructor who provided
Pat's voice in the simulated ER while Conn operated the computer.
Thompson, who had the stethoscope, says she could hear Pat's
breathing sounds clear up as the Lasix had time to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Lasix and morphine aren't real, of course. They have bar
codes scanned into Pat's computer, programmed to respond to more
than 50 drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair's patient simulator is one of about 100 worldwide
manufactured by Medical Education Technologies Inc. only since
1997. While METI's simulators are better suited for teaching allied
health fields in community colleges, Sinclair nursing director
Gloria Goldman says another company makes simulators that are used
more for replicating the effects of anesthesia. The only two other
simulators in Ohio are at Columbus State Community College and
Case-Western Reserve University in Cleveland, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair bought the $225,000 mannequin two years ago, and the
school added METI's new pediatric model in December. It took more
than a year to program and prepare Pat for teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Talking with other schools that use simulators, Goldman says she
heard a story about a Florida nursing student in a hospital ER with
some doctors who couldn't figure out what was wrong with the
patient. ``I think this patient has a pulmonary embolism,'' the
student offered.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right, muttered the eye-rolling doctors as they continued
discussing what the patient's symptoms might add up to. Just like
in the movies, the student turned out to be right about the
embolism, an obstruction of a blood vessel in the lungs. She had
seem the same symptoms on the simulator just that week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really real,'' Crawford says. ``They have it fine-tuned
so that when it gets asthma, everything that goes with an asthma
attack actually happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As Pat's asthma attack develops, its pulse, breathing rate and
blood pressure go up and its oxygen level drops. Through a
stethoscope, wheezing is audible in the lungs. Its body temperature
can fluctuate, its eyes can blink or its pupils can become fixed
and dilated.
</P>
<P>
   Pat is a standard, conscious man in this case, but the
instructor's array of choices include a smoker with high blood
pressure, a wounded soldier, a pregnant woman undergoing
complications and an elderly patient. The asthma attack is one of
more than 50 afflictions programmed into Sinclair's simulator,
along with gastro-intestinal bleeding, insulin shock, a diabetic
coma and a variety of heart and lung problems and circumstances
under anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   Asthmatic Pat is getting worse and needs to be intubated, a tube
threaded through its throat to the lungs. As Crawford inserts the
tube, she runs into difficulty where Pat's vocal cords have
constricted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team effort,'' she says, squeezing oxygen through the
tube while Stamm listens to both of Pat's lungs. Intubating a
patient is tricky business. If the tube goes too far down, Stamm
will hear oxygen reaching only one lung. If the tube takes the
wrong path down the esophagus, the oxygen will gurgle into the
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were in a clinical setting, we couldn't let students
make mistakes,'' says Jelus, the nursing teacher. ``But this way
they can go ahead and kill it. We'll just back it up and do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the simulator in her freshman year, Crawford says, ``It
was scary to go out there and hook things up to a patient.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' says Stamm, ``you get that fear of making a mistake
out of the way before you see a patient. When you go into that
patient's room, you have to be confident.''
</P>
<P>
   When they learn something in class, she says, they can apply it
right away. The whole class can. Conn has more than once seen a
dicey scenario at the hospital, programmed it into Pat and had an
entire class experience it.
</P>
<P>
   Before Pat, the students would have pretended to treat each
other for the problem. But students are pretty healthy. Their lungs
all sound the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things you do in the hospital is listen to
breathing sounds,'' Crawford says. That's how diagnoses are made
quickly. ``It would have been nice to hear actual breathing sounds
in class from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretending doesn't generate data on the monitors, either, and
somehow monitors never look like those textbook pictures a student
tries to memorize. ``There's a big difference between book
knowledge and how you apply your knowledge,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   In a word, that difference is speed. ``When we go through mock
situations, whatever works one time doesn't necessarily work
another,'' she says. ``We have to critically think and make quick
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   They also learn to manipulate medical devices in a hurry. A
respiratory therapist might have to guide a tube down a pneumonia
patient's airway to suction out fluids, Crawford says. ``You have
to do it quickly and you have to stay sterile. The only way to
learn it is to practice it time and time again.''
</P>
<P>
   The students will leave Sinclair next spring and start working
full time on patients within the next two years. But they plan to
keep in touch with Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Active nurses, respiratory therapists, paramedics and medical
and dental residents already are coming to Sinclair to use Pat in
continuing education. As Thompson says, ``There's not a patient out
there who's willing to let you experiment on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
