<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-OLD-VET-COX     01-31 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-VET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man happens upon war flag he signed at Japanese surrender
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Old soldiers and their stories are
legion in Bill Muir's Palm Beach store, Grand Armee. Muir sells
military memorabilia, tin soldiers, uniforms from the Raj, swords,
books, all things military and historical. But the stories are
priceless.
</P>
<P>
   Like the old guy who came in wearing a baseball cap with a
military insignia. A lot of guys wear caps like that, says Muir,
maybe with a destroyer's or sub's name, a division or regiment,
Navy SEALS, that sort of thing. But this old guy's cap said French
Foreign Legion, 1st Paratroop Regiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the guy,'' says Muir, ``and I'm thinking, `Sure,
pal. Right, you were in the Legion. Sure.' I thought I could snare
him. So I asked him how long he was in for, because the minimum
Legion enlistment was five years, usually seven.
</P>
<P>
   Three years, says the guy. And Muir thinks, Gotcha.
</P>
<P>
   The old guy detects Muir's skepticism and says, ``My regiment
was disbanded in Algiers in the early '60s, when France gave
Algeria its independence. We were the infamous 1st para regiment,
disloyal to DeGaulle. You know, Day of the Jackal and all that? The
regiment was scrubbed from French military histories. That's why I
served only three years. We were so mad we blew up everything
before we left, blew up the barracks, trucks, weapons. The chaplain
even blew up his chapel.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow, thought Muir.
</P>
<P>
   Another time an old guy comes into the store. He has an East
European accent Muir can't quite place. They start talking about
the war. That's World War II. The old guy quietly says he spent the
last months of the war in Dachau.
</P>
<P>
   Another old guy is at the counter. He's listening to the story.
He turns to the other fellow and says he was with Patton's 4th
Armored Division, the one that liberated Dachau.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later the two old men exit the store, talking, on their
way to share a lunch. And memories.
</P>
<P>
   But Lester Peskin's story is one of the best, says Muir.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Peskin is 83, tall, fit, white hair combed back, sharp
eyes and quick of wit. After 50 years of practicing restaurant law
in New York, he moved to Boca Raton in 1996, two years after
Dorothy, his wife of almost 50 years, died. His two daughters and
four grandchildren live up north. He's alone, but not lonely. He
golfs, takes classes in the history of Judaism and the Old
Testament. He even had a second bar mitzvah last year _ he is,
after all, 13 years beyond the Bible's three score and ten.
</P>
<P>
   And, he browses stores, including Grand Armee.
</P>
<P>
   He was young once and believed he would die young, as a
lieutenant, a company commander in the 108th Regiment, 40th
Division. He thought he'd die in the invasion of Japan scheduled
for the fall of 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I'd come home. We just went from island to
island, battle to battle, and it seemed like it would last forever.
Guadalcanal, mopping up on New Britain, went ashore on Luzon with
MacArthur, Mindanao. Mopping up, now there's an expression. Snipers
and booby traps and sickness _ malaria, dysentery, you name it. I
became company commander because all the captains either got shot
or got sick. Or promoted out to someplace where they'd get shot or
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 1942 and 1943. And 1944. And 1945. A lifetime for a
23-year-old. For many in Peskin's anti-tank company, it was.
</P>
<P>
   But Peskin came home whole, married Dorothy and settled down to
law and family.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, a New Jersey collector sent Muir a large
Japanese flag, on consignment. The flag had been taken at a
Japanese surrender ceremony in late August 1945, in Korea. It was
signed by more than 100 U.S. soldiers from the 108th Regiment, 40th
Division. It went home with a GI, then to his attic, then to his
nephew's attic after the old soldier died. Then to the collector.
And finally, to Grand Armee.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the flag arrived at Grand Armee, Lester Peskin and
one of his daughters wandered in. They browsed. Lester noticed the
flag, gazed at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, I signed a flag like that once,'' says Peskin.
``But a lot of Japanese flags were signed by a lot of U.S.
soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his daughter stopped short. ``Daddy,'' she said. ``There's
your name.''
</P>
<P>
   And there it is, in the lower left corner of the flag: Lt.
Peskin, New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wave of emotion came over me, a big one,'' says Peskin. ``It
was like the time some years ago I visited a GI cemetery on the
French-Belgian border, those crosses and stars stretching far into
the distance. I lived my whole life between the day I signed that
flag and the time I saw it again. Fifty-four years. So much time.
Gone so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Peskin was more than just a signatory to the flag. He was
the commanding officer that day, the guy who took the flag from a
Japanese marine captain in a formal surrender ceremony at a small
air base at Pohang, on the east coast of Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war was over, but you never knew if word had got out to
all the Japanese,'' says Peskin. ``This Japanese captain outranked
me. He said he wouldn't surrender to me. I had my men behind me; he
had his. `You're gonna surrender,' I told him. The translators went
back and forth. I didn't know who was saying what. The captain and
I looked at each other. He surrendered.''
</P>
<P>
   Peskin gave the flag to one of his men.
</P>
<P>
   After the surrender, Peskin was promoted to captain and
appointed military governor of the region. Six months later he went
home. He never thought about the flag again for 54 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my daughters were little, they wanted to hear war
stories,'' he says. ``They loved the tales. But I never told them
how it really was. You had to be there. The horror, the heat, the
disease. The dead. The war.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandson is 24. He doesn't know anything about the war,''
he says. ``They don't teach it in school, you know. Maybe they will
someday. But we'll all be gone. Those guys on the flag? They're
probably all dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good outfit. They were good guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Lester Peskin is gone, heading to his Old Testament
history class.
</P>
<P>
   The flag is worn, fading to yellow, framed under glass. The
names scribbled in pen and pencil are still visible. But they too
are fading away.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
E-mail: paulreid(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
