<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-THERMO-BREAKUP-BOS &LR;      01-31 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THERMO-BREAKUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERMO ELECTRON RESTRUCTURES TO MORE FOCUSED UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes new companies text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thermo Electron Corp., once a luminary of Massachusetts' ``Route
128'' economy, announced Monday a long-awaited restructuring that
closes the door on its unusual strategy of ``spinning out''
businesses based on emerging technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The company had made a name for itself in the 1970s and 1980s
with its policy of selling off minority stakes in its subsidiaries
to public investors. But since the mid-1990s, the Waltham, Mass.
company has disappointed investors as it tried to juggle the
complexities and poor financial performance of as many as two dozen
such spinouts.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in a bid to streamline and get back on track, the
company said it will split into three separate, publicly traded
companies and sell businesses with annual sales of $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of the new companies will retain the Thermo Electron
name and focus on the instruments businesses that had been the core
of the old Thermo Electron; Thermo Fibertek, which will focus on
recycling technologies, mainly for the pulp and paper industry; and
a medical products company.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it plans to sell more than a half dozen
other businesses that do not fit with the three new companies _ a
move that will raise about $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very radical restructuring,'' said Richard
Syron, Thermo Electron's chairman, president and chief executive.
Syron, who previously was president of the American Stock Exchange
in New York, joined Thermo Electron last spring to lead a
turnaround at the company founded in 1956 by George Hatsopoulos, a
Greek immigrant and former MIT professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic structure as a company with many parts just did not
work, given the changes in industrial practices and financial
markets,'' said Syron, who added that no immediate layoffs are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that Thermo Electron's structure _ two dozen
companies, each majority owned by the parent company with the rest
owned by public investors _ had become too unwieldy. The
complicated setup also made it difficult to distribute products, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And he added that the spinout strategy is no longer successful
on Wall Street because it resulted in too many obscure stocks with
little following among analysts and investors.
</P>
<P>
   Syron's announcement of the sweeping changes came after company
founder George Hatsopoulos, who ran the company for 44 years,
stepped down as chairman last month. At the time, he said he agreed
with the sweeping changes Syron and Thermo Electron's board of
directors were implementing. (Hatsopoulos turned the CEO job over
to Syron in June.)
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Thermo Electron's stock price rose a modest 1 1/16 to
close at 17 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The stock did not react much to the news because Wall Street
investors had been first told in May that Thermo Electron planned
to streamline from 23 businesess to 11.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the changes ``are a little more aggressive than I
expected,'' said Jill Lehman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch Global
Securities, ``but they are all very positive because it moves
Thermo Electron in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman cautioned that it is still difficult to determine the
profit levels the company will achieve without its other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Thermo Electron's instruments businesses will be
consolidated into a new company with the same name. Those
operations have annual sales of $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A second company, with yearly sales of $225 million, will focus
on recycling and resource recovery technology and will be formed
around Thermo Fibertek and Thermo Fibergen. The third business,
which will make medical instruments and devices, will have annual
sales of $335 million.
</P>
<P>
   Existing Thermo Electron investors will receive shares of the
latter two companies as a stock dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syron recognizes that Thermo Electron needs a clear and
aggressive strategy which they are showing with this
reorganization, so the question now is can they develop new
products, market them effectively and execute on their business
plan,'' said Paul R. Knight, an analyst at Thomas Weisel Partners,
a New York investment firm. ``That's the next leg in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NEW THERMO ELECTON &QL; 
 &QL; 
