<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-DOCTOR-BOS &LR;      01-31 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DOCTOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH DOCTOR GETS 15 LIFE TERMS IN PATIENT DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ An English doctor was convicted Monday of killing 15 of
his female patients by injecting them with heroin and may face
charges in at least 23 other killings. Authorities said he is
suspected in the deaths of more than 100 others.
</P>
<P>
   Police say that Dr. Harold Shipman, 54, who once seemed to
epitomize the kindly, house-calling English general practitioner,
is probably Britain's most prolific serial killer. He was sentenced
Monday to 15 life sentences for the murders by a judge who
described him as ``a wicked, wicked man'' who had engaged in a
``calculated and cold-blooded perversion'' of his Hippocratic oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have little doubt that each of your victims smiled and
thanked you as she submitted to your fearful administration,''
Preston Crown Court Judge Thayne Forbes told Shipman, who showed no
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   While Shipman's four-month trial for the deaths of his 15 mostly
elderly patients from 1995 to 1998 was widely publicized and
followed one of the biggest police investigations in British
history, it was not until Monday that the public became aware of
the enormity of his alleged crimes. Under British law, the
authorities and the media are not allowed to disseminate
incriminating information about a suspect until a trial is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as Forbes passed sentence on Shipman, Greater
Manchester police and other local authorities said they believe
that he killed more than 100 patients by injecting them with
morphine or heroin, and covered up his crimes by altering medical
records and cremating many of the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Pollard, the South Manchester coroner, said it was
``reasonable to assume'' that Shipman killed 120 to 150 people.
Police say they have investigated 136 suspicious deaths of
Shipman's patients over the past decade. The local prosecutor,
Robert Davies, said his office was considering additional charges
in consultation with victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of Shipman's murderous practice in the small town of
Hyde, just outside Manchester in northwest England, is just sinking
in. The British government is expected to announce Tuesday a formal
inquiry into the circumstances under which Shipman was able to kill
so many of his patients before being found out.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, police made a brief preliminary investigation
into Shipman after a local undertaker took her suspicions to
another doctor, who then went to police. But such was Shipman's
reputation in Hyde, where he was considered a pillar of the
community, that police concluded the probe without questioning him
or any of the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they found nothing in Shipman's records that
pointed to foul play. Police now acknowledge that they were duped
because Shipman had falsified records, attributing to his patients
ailments that they didn't have.
</P>
<P>
   Police also now admit that three more women died since their
initial investigation. Police reactivated their investigation of
Shipman in 1998 after the daughter of his last victim, 81-year-old
Kathleen Grundy, realized that Shipman had forged her mother's will
and had himself named as the beneficiary of her $600,000 estate.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators say Grundy's murder was the only one in which
they were able to establish an obvious motive. As for his other
victims, police said it appeared Shipman enjoyed feeling a sense of
power over his victims. Investigators say Shipman, like other
serial killers, took ``trophies'' of his victims, including
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Postles, the detective who led the investigation, said,
``He just enjoys killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipman replaces Peter Sutcliffe, the so-called ``Yorkshire
Ripper,'' as Britain's most notorious serial killer. Sutcliffe was
imprisoned for life in 1981 for killing 13 women and trying to kill
seven others.
</P>
<P>
   But police say Shipman's final tally will make Sutcliffe's pale
in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Mike Williams, who interrogated Shipman, described him
as arrogant and devious, a sociopath who thought he was smarter
than his inquisitors. He said Shipman complained about some of his
patients, including those he killed, as being nuisances. Pollard,
the coroner, said Shipman ``developed a taste for it. He enjoyed
holding the power over people.''
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's verdict, investigators said that Shipman had been
addicted to pethidine, an opiate, which he had been stealing from
the first practice he joined as a young doctor in 1974. He was
forced to leave that joint practice, but was allowed to return to
practicing medicine 18 months later.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually opened a one-man, storefront practice in Hyde and
became well known and respected among his 3,500 patients and the
rest of the town.
</P>
<P>
   A local undertaker became suspicious of Shipman when she noticed
his dead patients were being found fully clothed, with no sign of
illness or discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   She passed her concerns on to a doctor in a clinic across the
street from Shipman's. Doctors in that clinic had been asked by
Shipman to countersign cremation certificates, as is required by
law. When doctors in that clinic checked their own records, they
found that in 1997, 41 of Shipman's patients died, while their
practice, with almost three times as many patients, had just 14
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Shipman initally killed his patients during house
calls. Then, emboldened, he killed six patients by injecting them
at his small office, just a few feet from his staff, including his
wife, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Shipman administered the fatal doses on the
pretext of giving injections or drawing blood.
</P>
<P>
   Bearded and bespectacled, the father of four, he was widely
admired for his small-town ways.
</P>
<P>
   But the Reverend Denis Maher, a local priest, said a darker side
of Shipman emerged when he saw the doctor at the home of one of his
parishoners, Winifred Mellor, after she died two years ago. Father
Maher said Shipman was cold to the dead woman's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was cold, calculating, evil,'' Father Maher said.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial, Shipman calmly insisted that some of the 15
women had failed to disclose health problems to him. He also told
police that he suspected that Grundy, the town's former mayor, was
a drug addict.
</P>
<P>
   After he sentenced Shipman, Judge Forbes took off his powdered
white wig and in a voice shaking with emotion, consoled the
victims' families who were in court and thanked the jury of seven
men and five women who deliberated for six days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
