<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: RIGHTIST'S UNITY PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Canada's leading conservative politician, Preston Manning,
embarks this week on a nationwide tour to unite the political
right, bolstered by a 75 percent endorsement at the Reform Party
convention for his plan to create a new national party, the
Canadian Alliance. The Liberal Party has governed Canada on the
federal level since 1993, largely because conservatives have been
split along regional lines.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ONTARIO GETS TOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, the police in Ontario, Canada's most populous
province, can arrest people for aggressive begging and offering to
clean windshields at traffic lights. In December, Ontario's
Conservative-controlled legislature banned intimidating panhandling
after complaints from the mayor of Toronto. It is now illegal to
beg anywhere there is a ``captive'' audience _ at bank machines,
bus stops, or in a line of vehicles stopped at a red light.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SCHOOL STRIKE PROTESTED
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred law students opposed to a nine-month strike at
the National Autonomous University of Mexico tried to get into the
law school by tearing down barricades at the entrance, but were
repelled by strikers with rocks and blows. Othon Perez Fernndez, a
law professor who encouraged his students to charge the barricades,
was knocked out by a rock and briefly hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: TEXACO RULING
</P>
<P>
   A New York City federal judge says he is leaning toward ruling
that an environmental lawsuit against Texaco by Ecuadorean Indians
should be tried in Ecuador, as Texaco prefers, rather than in the
United States. But Judge Jed S. Rakoff, citing Ecuador's recent
coup, asked the parties and the Ecuador government for more comment
about whether Ecuador's courts ``might reasonably be expected to
exercise a modicum of independence and impartiality'' if the suit
was sent back there.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: VATICAN TELLS OF INTIMIDATION
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has stepped up its intimidation campaign against
Catholic clergy loyal to the pope, the news agency of the Vatican's
missionary wing reported. The agency, Fides, said church buildings
had been destroyed and priests and bishops abducted in the past
three years, including an 80-year-old bishop, James David Lin Xili,
who has been missing from Shanghai since September. Beijing
recognizes only the official, state-backed church.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: CHALLENGE ADJOURNED
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional challenge to October's army coup was adjourned
until March 1 by the nation's new chief justice of the Supreme
Court, Irshad Hassan Khan. The court's new leader was given the job
after his predecessor, like several other judges, refused to take
an oath of allegiance to the new military government.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SWISS AID SOUGHT ON SUHARTO
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia is preparing to ask Switzerland for new help in
tracking down huge sums of money said to have been deposited in
Swiss banks by former President Suharto, the current president,
Abdurrahim Wahid, said. Jakarta said it is seeking the return of $9
billion thought to have been diverted to the personal accounts of
Suharto, who has denied any wrongdoing. Suharto's successor, B.J.
Habibie, made an initial request for legal help last June.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: TRUCKERS START PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after their bosses set up blockades to protest the
government-imposed shorter workweek, truck drivers retaliated with
blockages of their own. The drivers said the concessions the
government made had robbed the drivers of some of the main benefits
that employees in other sectors would enjoy in the transition from
a 39-hour to a 35-hour workweek. The protests, focused on blocking
truckers from entering France, are expected to go on for two days.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: DOCTOR KILLED 15 WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   A general practitioner from near Manchester, Dr. Harold Shipman,
was given 15 life sentences after he was found guilty of murdering
15 female patients, most of them elderly, with heroin injections.
Prosecutors are considering bringing murder charges involving as
many as 23 other patients who died in his care.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PRISON REFORM SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Home Office set up a working group to identify failing
prisons and suggest ways to promote education and to combat drug
addiction. Recent reports by the chief prison inspector have
painted a dismal picture of conditions in two of the country's
prisons. ``We need better warning systems to identify much earlier
those prisons which are not operating to an acceptable standard,''
Home Secretary Jack Straw said.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: UNIONS BEGIN PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions began a three-month
campaign of lunch and teatime demonstrations and worker forums to
highlight the government's failure to create jobs. The campaign,
which will not disrupt business for the time being, was kicked off
by the South African Textile and Clothing Workers' Union and the
National Union of Metalworkers of South Africa. Some estimates put
unemployment as high as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ZAMBIA: DOCTORS END STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Striking public hospital doctors returned to work after a court
refused to grant an injunction ordering the government not to fire
them. Calling their work stoppage a leave of absence, the senior
doctors walked off the job in support of hundreds of striking
junior doctors who were fired for protesting hospitals' poor
working conditions and lack of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   CYPRUS: TALKS WITH ANNAN BEGIN
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the divided island began negotiating separately with
Secretary-General Kofi Annan of the United Nations in an attempt to
break a long-running impasse between Greece and Turkey. The two
sides never met. First, the Greek Cypriot delegation trooped into
the U.N. European headquarters in Geneva to meet with Annan. Then
the Turkish Cypriot delegates arrived, led by Rauf Denktash. Annan
said he thought a deal could be reached within the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
