<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-TITANS01-CO     01-31 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-TITANS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee to try for two Super Bowls in a row
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Titans might have seemed to the public to be a
surprise entrant in the Super Bowl. But they sounded Monday as if
they plan on making a return trip, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been expected from a team that rallied from a
16-0 third-quarter deficit to tie the game _ and then missed by the
longest yard of forcing Super Bowl XXXIV into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that came from nowhere and did things no one
expected us to do this year,'' coach Jeff Fisher said about the
Titans, which lost to the Rams 23-16 Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we'll be respected and perceived around the league as a
team to be contended with the next few years,'' Fisher said. ``I
told the team they didn't fail. It's just success put on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   That new-found respect is not necessarily such a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Losers of Super Bowl XXXIII a year earlier, the Atlanta Falcons
entered the offseason very much as will the Titans, who face
relatively little roster re-shuffling.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's 16-3 record from last season landed the Falcons both
new respect around the league and a tougher schedule. The Titans
(16-4) can plan on the same.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta went 5-11 and missed the playoffs. What will become of
Tennessee?
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business in Nashville will be for owner Bud
Adams to sign a contract extension with Fisher, who has one year
left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has just four players who will become unrestricted
free agents Feb. 11, chief among them right tackle Jon Runyan.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Yancey Thigpen, who has a broken foot, was missed
in the Super Bowl; the addition of depth at the position will be a
goal of the offseason. Linebacker Joe Bowden, free safety Marcus
Robertson, tight end Jackie Harris and backup quarterback Neil
O'Donnell also will be eligible to hit the market.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's loss, Tennessee executed its offensive game plan in
the second half only, after the Rams had taken a 9-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, however, got strafed by the Rams, who flew to 443
yards of offense, 294 in the first half. Only a heavy dose of
Tennessee blitzing held St. Louis to three field goals in five
first-half possessions inside the Titans' 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, running back Eddie George, tight ends Harris
and Frank Wycheck and quarterback Steve McNair helped tie the game
through vintage smashmouth football.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who has been criticized for his shortcomings as a
passer, made some poor throws Sunday. However, his final passing
numbers of 22 of 36 passing numbers for 214 yards looked decent.
</P>
<P>
   He also proved that he makes good decisions, and he rushed for
65 years, as his athletic ability was essential in Tennessee's
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, neither team turned over the ball, and the Titans,
who set a franchise record in the regular season with 54 sacks, got
just one.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, when the Titans beat the Rams 24-21 in Nashville
on Oct. 31, Tennessee sacked St. Louis quarterback Kurt Warner six
times, and scooped up three of his fumbles without turning the ball
over.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in the Georgia Dome, McNair's pass to wide receiver
Kevin Dyson on the final play nearly sent the Super Bowl to
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   With Wycheck double-covered in the end zone, Dyson caught it on
the 5. ``I thought I was going to score,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rams linebacker Mike Jones, who had the responsibility of
covering the first receiver to break toward the middle of the
field, was behind Dyson. Jones got his right hand on Dyson's right
hip and his left hand on Dyson's left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended with Dyson going down at the 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran out of time,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got all we could ask for _ our wide receiver on a
linebacker,'' McNair said. ``But their linebackers are very quick
and athletic, and the guy just made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
