<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Super Bowl scores high in TV ratings
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rams and Titans didn't bring tradition or
familiarity to the Super Bowl, but that didn't matter to America.
</P>
<P>
   ABC enjoyed a typical Super Bowl audience for the Rams' 23-16
win on Sunday, drawing an estimated 130,745,000 viewers. The game's
national Nielsen rating of 43.2 was up 7 percent over the
Falcons-Broncos game in last year's Super Bowl on Fox. (One
national rating point equals 980,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's rating was the 19th highest of the 34 Super Bowls. The
game has drawn a rating of 40.2 or higher for 29 of the past 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dispels any notion that small-market teams can't pull in
big ratings,'' said ABC vice president Mark Mandel. ``It's all
about the Super Bowl and not so much about what teams are
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is the nation's 21st biggest market; Nashville is
30th.
</P>
<P>
   Mandel said the rating grew every half-hour and reached 46.9
during the last 30 minutes of the telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's rating was 52.0, falling between Saint Louis' 55.0 and
Nashville's 50.0. (For Atlanta, one local ratings point equals
16,750 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Enhanced TV, ABC's interactive component, set a record with
650,000 users, who averaged 42 minutes per connection. The previous
high for Enhanced TV was 125,000 during the Florida State-Virginia
Tech showdown for the collegiate national championship in the Sugar
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Prentis Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
