<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ON-THE-BUS-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S `STRAIGHT TALK EXPRESS' TAKES ITS LAST RIDE ACROSS N.H. 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also NH-MCCAIN) 
(nk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Seats on Sen. John McCain's Straight Talk
Express were hard to come by Monday, as the now famous rolling
press conference took its last ride across the state.
</P>
<P>
   For days, media bigwigs like David Westin, who runs ABC News,
and Peter Kahn, publisher of The Wall Street Journal, had been
showing up to take their turn on the bus, where reporters for The
New Yorker and Seventeen magazines, MTV and NPR have all jockeyed
for seats.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Lindsey Graham and Mark Sanford, South Carolina
Republicans who are campaigning for McCain there, were along for
the final trip, too. To help work that all-important South
Carolina-New Hampshire connection? No, said McCain. ``They just
wanted to come up and be part of this the last couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wanted to miss the experience of a fairly radical
experiment in the whole dance between candidates and the media. And
for those who had been with McCain for months, ``it's like the last
day of camp,'' said Jake Tapper, a reporter for Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tapper asked a newcomer if in her first hour with McCain on this
trip she had fallen in love: ``Have you had the Kool-Aid yet?''
</P>
<P>
   The bus driver, hard at work in a drizzling snow, was anything
but weepy: ``He gets on every morning, says, ``Hello, friend,' and
is absorbed'' by the media, said the driver, Walt Pim, of Columbus,
Ohio. ``I'd never done a political deal before, but this is like a
county fair all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate himself, though, en route from one outdoor rally
to another on his last full day of campaigning here, was already
nostalgic: ``It's been a great ride. I know it sounds like I've
gone insane, but I'll miss New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   But that, of course, is not the insane part.
</P>
<P>
   Unlimited media access _ which any political consultant will
tell you is way too risky to work in any candidate's favor _ has
become part of McCain's message that greater openness begets
greater trust _ and makes life on the trail more fun.
</P>
<P>
   But will other candidates, seeing how well it's worked for him,
follow his lead? The Arizona Republican doubts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had an occasional flash of stupidity, it was certainly
well reported,'' he said, perhaps thinking of his comments about
how in the Navy he just knew who was gay.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, then, was this experiment a good idea? He sipped his
coffee, and said, ``It almost doesn't matter if it was a good idea;
It was the only way I could do it, because it's just the way I
am.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Monday morning, his wife, Cindy, was sitting in one of several
chaise lounges reading a magazine while McCain was perched on a
bench, surrounded by reporters who wanted to know what his eclectic
foreign policy advisers have in common, whether he has a health
care plan, and if he is ``waffling on Al Pacino.''
</P>
<P>
   (Earlier, he had revealed that he did not think Pacino would be
too convincing as a football coach in ``Any Given Sunday,'' but
then backtracked to say that he generally appreciated Pacino's
oeuvre.)
</P>
<P>
   He explained why the Straight Talk Express will work a little
differently in South Carolina, where the day's events are more
likely to be held all in one town rather than all across the state.
And while he talked, Rice Krispie Treats sailed over his head,
lobbed by a reporter distributing goodies to his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The whole McCain team was much amused by one reporter's
assertion that the Bush campaign had been putting out the word that
McCain is only polling well because his supporters tend to be older
and thus are home on weekends, resting up, rather than out leading
vigorous lives like the Bush crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're down to that,'' said Mike Murphy, a senior adviser,
``then all I can say is, poor, poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCain answered her cell phone then, and handed it to her
husband: ``It's Gary Bauer. He fell off a stage today.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was solicitous of his fellow candidate, who fell while
flipping pancakes at a campaign event. But not long-winded: ``Are
you alright? Be careful, my friend, and good luck tomorrow, my
friend. I've grown to appreciate you very much.''
</P>
<P>
   When he hung up, he said a word about this new friendship:
``He's a decent person. I just got attracted to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then another call came through, and several aides, along with
Mrs. McCain, put their heads together, laughing, whispering, and
trying to get the candidate's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he stopped talking about trade and bit. ``What? I am
like the cuckholded husband! I am the last to know anything in this
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   With the proper build up, Murphy announced new poll numbers that
had their guy up by 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh?'' said one reporter, John Dickerson, of Time Magazine.
``Is the sample this bus?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
