<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL TELLS SYRIA TO REIN IN HEZBOLLAH GUERRILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak says Israel will not
resume peace talks with Syria until it reins in the Hezbollah
guerrillas who killed three Israeli soldiers during intensified
fighting in Lebanon Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel will not be able to negotiate peace as long as the
Syrians do not restrain the Hezbollah from acting against the
Israeli army in the security zone,'' Barak said Monday. The United
States has been pushing the two countries to resume the difficult
negotiations that picked up in December after a four-year
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli fighter jets pounded Hezbollah targets in south Lebanon
heavily Monday as Barak promised to respond aggressively, using
language that has in the past presaged massive retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have known in the past and we still know to strike at the
place and time of our choosing,'' Barak said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The escalation of tension in Lebanon came one day after
Hezbollah forces killed the top field commander of the
Israeli-financed militia, the South Lebanon Army, in a carefully
planned and executed attack.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military strategists said the killing of Colonel Akel
Hashem, who was buried in his south Lebanon village Monday, was a
deeply damaging blow to the already faltering morale of Israeli and
SLA forces in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   US officials in Washington sought to minimize the likely impact
on the stalled peace talks. ``We condemn the violence and urge
restraint on all parties that have influence in the regions,'' said
Security Council spokesman David Leavy.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's response to the bomb attack on Hashem and the ambush of
the three Israeli soldiers proved again just how closely tied the
newly rekindled Israeli-Syrian negotiating track is to the
protracted conflict in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers are stationed inside a 9-mile wide ``security
zone'' in south Lebanon, where they face a daily guerrilla war of
ambushes and roadside bombs waged by Hezbollah fighters trying to
force Israel to leave what they see as illegally occupied land.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which has about 35,000 troops stationed in Lebanon, has
long backed Hezbollah and used the conflict as a proxy war against
Israel. The two countries have been bitter enemies for more than
half century.
</P>
<P>
   The three Israeli soldiers were killed when their patrol was
attacked on a road between the villages of Taibe and Deir Mimas
near the Crusader-era Beaufort Castle, only 2 miles from the
Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the attack, Israeli warplanes staged air raids
against suspected guerrilla positions in areas facing the Israeli
occupied zone. There was no immediate word on casualties from the
raids.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, the Associated Press quoted a Hezbollah statement
saying its fighters staged a ``daring attack deep in the occupied
zone,'' targeting Israeli soldiers as they gathered. Other
guerrillas opened fire on nearby positions at Beaufort and Dabshe
to prevent reinforcements and rescuers from reaching the area, the
Hezbollah statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah statement gloated that its ambush was carried out
``despite all the threats of Israeli leaders,'' a reference to
Barak's statement Sunday that Hashem's death would be avenged.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's tough tone in promising reprisals underscored the
domestic political pressures he is facing. The prime minister is
under fire in a campaign finance scandal, and the spiral of
violence in Lebanon has called into question whether he will live
up to the pledge he made during his election campaign last year to
have Israeli troops out of Lebanon by the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deaths brought to four the number of Israeli soldiers
killed in Lebanon since the resumption of Syrian-Israeli peace
talks in December. One of the three soldiers killed was an officer,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating violence in Lebanon comes at a time when Israel
and Syria seemed to be grudgingly softening the the positions that
had kept them frozen out of peace talks for four years.
</P>
<P>
   US diplomats and President Clinton himself have been making
strenuous efforts to help the sides bridge their differences and
resume the historic talks that began in December in Washington and
continued in January in Shepherdstown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Syria postponed the next scheduled round of
negotiations at the last minute. Analysts said the decision was
triggered by Israel's refusal to accept Syria's precondition that
it commit to total withdrawal from the disputed Golan Heights, and
over the degree of demilitarization that would be enforced along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Barak said Syria was allowing the new Hezbollah attacks
in order to pressure Israel into making concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is . . . the Syrians, not just Hezbollah, that are behind
supply lines and freedom of movement (for the) guerrillas,'' the
Associated Press quoted Barak telling his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts saw significance in the fact that Barak,
Israel's most highly decorated soldier, issued his statement on
Defense Ministry letterhead and used language that in the past has
been a precursor to major Israeli counterattacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
