<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-CAMPAIGN-WRAPUP-SPI &LR;      01-31 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-WRAPUP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN TO THE WIRE IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, New Hampshire _ An estimated 350,000 voters will cast
the first primary ballots of America's 2000 presidential election
here Tuesday, in a serenly beautiful but fiercely independent New
England state famous for making frontrunners stumble.
</P>
<P>
   A New Hampshire loss won't be fatal to Texas Gov. George Bush or
Vice President Al Gore, who have resources and party regulars to
fight future battles. A win is nearly essential, however, to the
reformist grassroots GOP campaign of Arizona Sen. John McCain, and
badly needed by the Democrats' challenger, ex-Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a small lead in pre-election polls over Bradley in a
battle between two candidates and two campaigns that have come to
intensely dislike each other. After watching Gore take apart his
health care plan, Bradley has taken a sharply negative turn,
pummeling Gore's credibility and urging the Democratic Party to
``clean our house'' of the Clinton administration's campaign
finance scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is a new politics of belief and conviction and
giving America a new candor,'' Bradley tells rallies, echoing a
slogan of the late 1960s and early 1970s. But the former New Jersey
senator is under fire for refusing to release his health records
and being less than candid about his bouts of irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, with 64 days of campaigning and 114 town
meetings, McCain has caught fire and threatens to put at least a
temporary halt to Bush's seemingly unstoppable march to the GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls Monday put McCain in the lead. Typically, he put
down the good news. On his bus, McCain spied reporters and aides
whispering about the latest figures. ``I am like the cuckolded
husband,'' he joked. ``I am the last to know anything about the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican candidate is operating largely beneath the radar
screen. Millionaire publisher Steve Forbes is mobilizing phone
banks, calling radio talk shows and courting religious
conservatives as well as the 30,000 members of Gun Owners of New
Hampshire. Forbes is waging a political ground game aimed at
repeating his strong second place showing behind Bush in the Jan.
24 Iowa GOP caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire may mark the end of the line _ or end of serious
consideration _ for two other GOP candidates. Former Reagan
administration official Gary Bauer fell off the stage at a
pancake-flipping contest yesterday. He has nearly disappeared from
the race, too, registering barely 1 percent in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Former diplomat Alan Keyes has aroused the Republican right with
his anti-abortion oratory. ``Creation does not take place in the
womb. It's just announced there,'' Keyes declared at one stop.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has offended others, including several parents of children
in a class he spoke to last week. He asked the fifth graders a
series of questions about whether it is okay to kill other people.
They replied in the negative. Whereupon, Keyes told his youthful
listeners: ``We live in a country where, according to the law and
courts and some of our politicians, it is okay to kill children.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the 2000 campaign has been positive in tone,
with debates revolving around serious choices facing the country.
In part, candidates have responded to polls suggesting an American
public sickened by the politics of personal destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most polite, the most civil, the most
issue-oriented campaign the state has seen in 30 years,'' said
Steve Duprey, state GOP chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, however, gloves have come off between the
Democrats with Bradley accusing Gore of deliberate misstatements. A
pair of Bradley surrogates, Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey and Washington
Rep. Jim McDermott, showed up at Gore's Sunday rally at
Somersworth. Two 1992 presidential candidates, Kerrey and Sen. Tom
Harkin of Iowa, a Gore surrogate, got into a shouting match.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, however, the real drama may come if the
Republican front-runner goes down to defeat. The Bush campaign has
progressed toward the nomination with the majesty of a royal coach.
At times, it seemed like New Hampshire was being called upon to pay
tribute to the procession as it passed this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame, since Gov. Bush is going to be elected
president, for him to be elected without the support of New
Hampshire,'' former Gov. John Sununu said. Sununu was part of a
daily parade of endorsers, culminating in a Saturday appearance at
which former President George Bush praised ``this boy, this son of
ours,'' and predicted of George W: ``He's going to go all the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   But a large number of New Hampshire voters seem of a mind that
the presidency is not a royal inheritance. ``If you listen to Bush,
it's pretty much what we've already got in politics,'' said Roy
Parker, a retired Digital Equipment Engineer, who heard McCain
speak in Nashua.
</P>
<P>
   McCain cannot match Bush's money or nationwide organization. But
the former Vietnam POW has found themes that resonate _ campaign
finance reform, an end to corporate welfare and cutting pork barrel
spending. ``(Voters) want someone independent of special
interests,'' he declared to cheers at a noontime rally here
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Belatedly and awkwardly, Bush has tried to sound like an
outsider. ``I am not of Washington, D.C.,'' the Texas governor has
declared in prefacing his tax cut program. But he has trouble
sounding humble. ``I have the right organization, I am the right
person to lead the party to victory,'' he declared at a weekend
stop.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has one strategy: Come out of New Hampshire with
momentum, grace the covers of national magazines, and use
grassroots enthusiasm to rout the Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 35 percent of today's voters will have enjoyed
personal contact with at least one presidential candidate. Melissa
Jahn and Wayne Goertel, young New Hampshire professionals, are
among thousands who have gone to watch several candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was for Bush a couple days ago, but McCain seems more
competent on the issues with a better sense of integrity,'' said
Jahn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of ideology, we see at least four strong
candidates,'' added Goertel. He identified Gore, Bradley, Bush and
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In Newmarket, high school senior Larry Gladhill considers
himself a Republican but will vote for Gore. ``I like how he stands
on violence in schools,'' Gladhill said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Republicans once exploited bad times under Jimmy Carter,
the campaign of Democrat Gore never fails to mention that Bush's
father presided over the worst recession since the Great
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of this country don't want a president who will
bring us back to the way things were back in 1992 with layoffs and
factory closings, when there was another George Bush in office,''
New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, Gore's chief local booster, told
a weekend dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Democratic voters are uneasy at the excesses of
America's political system and are receptive to Bradley's
reformism. ``I buy into his idealism,'' said Susan Stafford, a
businesswoman who attended Bradley's rally Sunday in Exeter.
</P>
<P>
   At a town meeting in Lebanon, school administrator Frank Fahey
asked Gore about his attendance at a 1996 Democratic fund-raiser at
a Buddhist temple in California, and overnight stays by
Clinton-Gore campaign donors in the Lincoln Bedroom of the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you get into that situation?'' asked Fahey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made a mistake in the episode you asked me about. I
learned from that mistake,'' Gore replied. He ignored the Lincoln
Bedroom question, but said of the Buddhist temple event: ``I should
have learned what its intended purpose was.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president argued that when he was in Congress, he
sponsored or co-sponsored more than a dozen campaign reform bills.
Gore called for federal financing of campaigns for the presidency
and Congress, and for broadcasters to offer free times to political
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey was unimpressed. ``No, I don't think he has learned,''
said Fahey, a political independent. ``I guess I feel more
genuineness, honesty and believability in Mr. Bradley's answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
