<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SAVOR THE MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Memo to the half-naked teen-ager waving the
Bradley poster on the corner in Concord: It's winter in New
England. Bill wants you to put your shirt back on.
</P>
<P>
   This New Hampshire primary has been wonderful. For one brief
moment, in one smallish state, the American people are really hyped
about the presidential election. Even the little kids seem excited.
(Well, maybe not the ones who got cornered by the anti-abortion
candidate Alan Keyes and asked how they'd feel if he bashed their
brains out.)
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, fire marshals were actually turning people away
from political rallies. At a high school near Nashua, you could see
folks forlornly/ peeking in the windows, yearning to be let inside
to hear George W. Bush call for ``a law that provides liability to
teachers who enforce discipline in the schools.'' All the
candidates are tired, but Bush's speeches are getting particularly
unintelligible _ at the same high school, he announced, ``I think
we need not only to eliminate the tollbooth to the middle class, I
think we should knock down the tollbooth.'' At a Lincoln Day dinner
in Manchester last week, his handlers approached Gary Bauer, the
candidate who had drawn the first-speaker slot, and told him ``the
governor is really exhausted'' and would appreciate being allowed
to switch places.
</P>
<P>
   If you have seen the diminutive Bauer in any of the Republican
debates, glaring at Bush like the Chucky doll in those horror
movies, you can imagine the response.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowds are so great and the races so competitive, the
candidates are practically bouncing off the walls with adrenaline.
If Bush's audiences can't make much sense of what he says, they can
hear the underlying music _ something between ``Onward Christian
Soldiers'' and ``Boola Boola.'' Al Gore, who always gets louder
when he gets revved up, has been sounding like a bull on branding
day.
</P>
<P>
   Today is really about John McCain and Bill Bradley _ unless they
do well, we may be down to nine months of incoherent babbling
versus unimaginative bellowing. All the candidates are claiming to
be ``genuine'' this year, eschewing polls and speaking from the
heart. (The polls say genuine is in.) But McCain seems to be trying
to strip away everything, including his own superego, going for
direct id-to-id communication. He has had 114 town meetings with
the folks in New Hampshire. He talks and talks and talks _ to the
voters, to the reporters, to the lamppost _ creating a sort of
stream-of-conscious communication with the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, on the other hand, is all about repression, the
rejection of the cheap shot and easy headline. ``No pretense, no
manipulation,'' he told a crowd at a law school in Concord
solemnly, warning that he only wants the votes of people who
``agree with the direction I want to take the country.'' Al Gore,
of course, would be perfectly happy to get the votes of people who
were under the impression he was a new brand of breakfast sausage.
He is the archfiend of the Bradley world view, but the vice
president should really be more worried about his own admirers, who
have developed a disconcerting habit of using words like
``shameless'' and ``junkyard dog'' to describe his debating skills.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's anti-Gore attacks are so obscure, the only charitable
interpretation is that he wants to avoid saying anything that could
be turned into a sound bite for a Republican ad in the fall. One of
his strongest statements about the Clinton-Gore record on campaign
finance was: ``there's more explanation that is needed ... And I
believe that unless that explanation is forthcoming, that the
public will reject a candidacy in the fall that fails to come to
terms with this circumstance in our Democratic Party in 1996.'' But
during his ``no manipulation'' speech you could hear faint but
fervent cheers from a classroom down the hall where an overflow
crowd of eager Bradley supporters had been stashed. They had picked
him not as the lesser of two evils, but as the best of a lineup of
very interesting candidates, several of whom appeared, at least for
that moment, to be perfectly feasible presidents. Outside, children
and dogs romped on a frozen pond. The sun shone. Nobody looked as
if he would have rather been watching ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   It must be tough being the candidate for a new politics on the
one day of the year when the old politics seems just fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2050EST &QL; 
