<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-TVADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From cats to munchkins, Super Ads entertained _ but did they
sell?
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Next to the heart-stopping finale of Super Bowl XXXIV,
one of the game's most memorable images was a computer-aided
commercial of paralyzed actor Christopher Reeves getting up and
walking again.
</P>
<P>
   And for comic relief, there was a hilarious commercial showing a
group of trail-hardened cowboys rounding up a herd of cats.
</P>
<P>
   But quick: Who were those advertisers and what exactly were they
trying to sell you?
</P>
<P>
   While millions of Super Bowl viewers were riveted by the
commercials, some top marketing experts argue that the megabucks
ads leave many viewers dazed and confused, and may wind up being a
bust at the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too soon to tell if the ads will justify their
$2.5 million pricetags for a 30-second spot, the age of instant
information produced several Monday morning quarterbacks trying to
determine which ads were the most popular.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today ran a ``Super Bowl Ad Meter'' on its Website, allowing
visitors to vote for their favorite commercials. With results
updated every five seconds, the three most popular commercials
Monday were the World Wrestling Foundation, ETrade, and
Epidemic.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous search engine Yahoo! also had an online ``Super
Bowl Poll'' that allowed viewers to pick the top ads. Their big
winners included Autotrader.com, the cat herders for EDS
information systems, and the singing sock puppet for pets.com. The
Christoper Reeve ad for Nuveen Investments, a financial services
company, didn't fare as well, only getting 3 percent of online
votes.
</P>
<P>
   However John Antil, a professor of Business and Economics at the
University of Delaware, said while such ads are increasingly
expensive and inventive, some of them are too entertaining for
their own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an ad entertained you but you can't remember what it's
about, it becomes a popularity contest, not a measure of
effectiveness,'' Antil said. ``Those kinds of ads make great
conversation around the office photocopier the next day, but most
people still couldn't tell you what the message was.'' As a group,
one of the most prolific Super Bowl advertisers this year were
online companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Allvine, a professor of marketing and electronic commerce
at Georgia Tech said online companies apparently hoped to repeat
the success of Victoria's Secret, the lingerie company that
launched its Website during eye-opening commercials at last year's
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big conclusion we can draw is that the dot.coms
were duds,'' Allvine said. ``I just think they were naive to think
they could drive traffic to their Website with a 30-second ad. Next
year, I think you will see far fewer dot.coms wasting their money
on the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The real trick is to make sure the ads will work with viewers
before they ever get on the air, said Wade Holmes, a marketing
group manager for Advance Research System in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found a lot of things that work, but there is no magic
formula,'' he said. ''We can tell people what we think before they
get to the Super Bowl, but it's very hard to tell if a commercial
is going to move the needle with viewers or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
