<HEADLINE>
THE CREATION OF THE HOPIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 
Editor's note: The Navajos are not alone in their reverence for the
windswept rangelands of northeastern Arizona. These excerpts from
the Hopi creation story show how they too feel a sacred bond with
the land. 
 
In the beginning, there was only Tokpella, Endless Space. . . .
Tawa, the Sun Spirit, gathered the elements of Endless Space and
put some of his own substance into them, and in this way, he
created the First World. . . .
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Tawa commanded Gogyeng Sowuhti, Spider Grandmother, to lead the
insectlike creatures up to a Second, then a Third World, each more
habitable than the First. The people then climbed through the
sipapuni _ hole in the sky _ to the Fourth World.)
</P>
<P>
   As the first climbers emerged through the sipapuni and stepped
into the Upper World, Yawpa the mockingbird . . . sorted them out.
``You shall be a Hopi and speak the Hopi language,'' he said to
one. ``You shall be a Navajo and speak the Navajo language,'' he
said to another. . . . He assigned every person to a tribe and a
language. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The people gathered around while Yawpa the mockingbird placed
many ears of corn on the ground. One ear was yellow, one was white,
one was red, one was gray, some were speckled, one was a stubby ear
with blue kernels. . . . The mockingbird described the life that
went with each ear, and then he told the people to choose. . . .
The leader of the Navajos reached out quickly and took the yellow
ear that would bring a short life but much enjoyment and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   . . . . (The other people choose until) only the Hopis had not
chosen. The ear that was left was the stubby ear of blue corn.
</P>
<P>
   So the leader of the Hopis picked it up, saying, ``We were slow
in choosing. Therefore, we must take the smallest ear of all. We
shall have a life of hardship, but it will be a long-lasting life.
Other tribes may perish, but we, the Hopis, will survive all
adversities.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Hopis became the people of the short blue corn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
