<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, FEB. 1
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NH-CAMPAIGN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Jan. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Jan. 25,
about the presidential candidates' positions on abortion misstated
the history of planks on the subject in the Republican Party
platform. The first such plank was included in 1976, not 1984;
every platform since then has opposed abortion and the use of
federal funds to pay for it. The plank has never allowed exceptions
for rape, incest or to save the life of the pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SARALEE-NYT (moved on Thursday, Jan. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Jan. 27,
about John H. Bryan, who is stepping down as chief executive of the
Sara Lee Corp., misstated the location of Rhodes College, from
which he graduated. It is in Memphis, not Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-PARRANDOS-PARADOX-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 24,
about a paradox in game theory, a discipline that seeks to extract
rules of nature from the gains and losses observed in games,
misspelled the name of its discoverer. He is Dr. Juan Parrondo, not
Parrando.
</P>
</TEXT>
