A2331 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-N.MYTH31-AZR &LR;      01-31 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.MYTH31-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYTH OF THE NAVAJO-HOPI DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(KYKOTSMOVI, Ariz) - _ Beyond the battles over which tribe has the
stronger spiritual connection to the land or the more powerful
claim for historic justice, the Navajo-Hopi dispute has also been a
battle of public relations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, that worked to the advantage of the Hopis, long
celebrated among non-Indians for their highly spiritual,
peace-loving ways.Most outsiders heard ``Hopi'' and thought:
kachina dolls.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Hopi tribal leaders bolstered their position with
a PR campaign portraying the Navajos as marauding bullies.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, it's the Hopis' turn to be cast as the villains.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Honyumptewa, director of the tribe's lands office, hears
it in telephone calls about the forced relocation of thousands of
Navajos from land granted by federal law to the Hopis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know about this so-called genocide we're putting
on the Navajos,'' Honyumptewa said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Nutumya, a Hopi art dealer, encounters it at shows in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get questions all the time,'' he said, ``because the Navajos
have made people feel sorry for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the relocation issue has spawned pro-Navajo ``support
groups'' across the United States and as far away as Europe and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   They blast relocation as a human-rights violation and demand
that Congress cancel the program it created in 1974 to settle the
Navajo-Hopi dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The activists have spread their message on the Internet,
sometimes with an exaggerated sense of drama.
</P>
<P>
   In December, for example, an ``International Urgent Action''
bulletin was posted in English, French, German and Spanish, warning
about trouble on Feb. 1, when the Hopis will assume jurisdiction
over the 911,000 acres that were partitioned to them.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, the bulletin warns, ``the over 2,000 remaining
Dine people will be forcibly relocated.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal and Hopi authorities call the date a non-event, and
pledge that there will be no forced evictions Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, federal officials concede that they _ and the
Hopis _ face a public-relations nightmare in the specter of elderly
Navajos being dragged off before news cameras. That could still
happen, they say, after eviction proceedings expected to last a
year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Such anti-Hopi feelings mark a curious historical counterpoint
to the 1960s, when admiring non-Indians streamed to the Hopi
mesas. &QL; 
THE HOPI WAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were drawn by the 1963 publication of Frank Waters' Book of
the Hopi, which celebrated the Hopis as a mystical people whose
very name means ``peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The book became part of the American counterculture, an anthem
of rejection of consumer culture and the nuclear age. It remains in
print, in a paperback edition that calls Waters' account ``a
reassertion of a rhythm of life we have disastrously tried to
ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Hopi Chairman Ferrell Secakuku said many of the eager
visitors camped near Old Oraibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in vans filled with flower children in white
robes,'' he said. ``I guess they were looking to realign their
lives in a Hopi way.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Hopis petitioned federal officials to remove the
``hippies.''
</P>
<P>
   But such romantic views of the Hopis _ never endorsed by the
Hopis themselves _ were only partially based on reality.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, not everyone agrees that the name Hopi means
``peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekkehart Malotki, a linguist at Northern Arizona University,
said the name actually means ``well mannered or civilized.'' The
Hopis adopted the name, he said, to distinguish themselves from
nomadic tribes that lacked agricultural and architectural skills. &QL; 
THE HOPI REALITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the tribe may never have fought the U.S. Cavalry, but
they do have a long tradition of fighting among themselves:
</P>
<P>
   In 1700, Hopi warriors wiped out one of their own villages,
Awatobi, after villagers embraced Christianity and welcomed back
Spanish priests who'd been driven out years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Hopi legends tell of a feud at the village of Shungopovi that
led to the establishment of Oraibi village. History documents that
a 1906 schism at Oraibi spawned the village of Hotevilla.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, four of the 13 Hopi villages guard their
independence so fiercely that they refuse to send representatives
to the Tribal Council, which they consider an alien institution
imposed by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Hopis are far from united on many issues _ notably including
Navajo relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Hopi public opinion ranges from nationalistic pride over
achieving massive Navajo relocation to outright support for the
Navajos who are refusing to move.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse from a PR standpoint, some traditional Hopi religious
leaders are among the Navajo supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mina Lansa, traditional leader of Old Oraibi, criticized tribal
officials for warning of war unless Congress intervened in the land
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are not true, and it makes us very ashamed to
hear and see that some of our young people who claim to represent
us created much publicity in this way,'' Lansa said in a visit to
Washington. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE HOPI AMBIVALENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other traditionalists agreed, calling the Navajos good neighbors
and buffers against non-Indian encroachment.
</P>
<P>
   But even Hopi traditionalists aren't united. After Lansa's
death, her brother replaced her as kikmongwi. He has thrown his
support solidly behind the Tribal Council in the land dispute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So has Frazier Nasaftie. His family holds bitter memories of
problems with Navajos that began 50 years ago at their ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Navajo will steal from you even if he's your good friend,''
said Nasaftie, 64, who said Navajos helped themselves to Hopi corn
and peaches. ``The Hopis always say, `You can't trust a Navajo.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Quotskuyva, 88, also remembers conflict with Navajos, who
``burned Hopi houses and even killed some of our animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he said, ``I'm in between'' about the relocation question.
``I had a lot of Navajo friends.''
</P>
<P>
   And former Hopi Tribal Chairman Lee Thomas concisely expressed
the ambivalence felt by many Hopis that belies their stereotype as
the villains of relocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good friends,'' Thomas said of the Navajo neighbors he
pushed to have evicted from nearby land.
</P>
<P>
   Wiry and energetic at 83, Thomas leaned on his tractor and noted
that Navajos are not only friends but family: He has two Navajo
daughters-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with Navajos,'' he said calmly, ``except
they tried to take over the whole land.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Navajo-Hopi land dispute is also a battle of public relations,
and for years, that worked to the advantage of the Hopis. The tribe
has long been celebrated among non-Indians for its highly
spiritual, peace-loving ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
