<HEADER>
A2338 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-N.HOPI:PR31-AZR &LR;      01-31 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.HOPI: </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC RELATIONS OF THE HOPI 
</HEADLINE>
 PR31-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(KYKOTSMOVI, Ariz) - _ Beyond the battles over which tribe has the
stronger spiritual connection to the land or the more powerful
claim for historic justice, the Navajo-Hopi dispute has also been a
battle of public relations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, that worked to the advantage of the Hopis, long
celebrated among non-Indians for their highly spiritual,
peace-loving ways.Most outsiders heard ``Hopi'' and thought:
kachina dolls.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Hopi tribal leaders bolstered their position with
a PR campaign portraying the Navajos as marauding bullies.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, it's the Hopis' turn to be cast as the villains.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Honyumptewa, director of the tribe's lands office, hears
it in telephone calls about the forced relocation of thousands of
Navajos from land granted by federal law to the Hopis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know about this so-called genocide we're putting
on the Navajos,'' Honyumptewa said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Nutumya, a Hopi art dealer, encounters it at shows in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get questions all the time,'' he said, ``because the Navajos
have made people feel sorry for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the relocation issue has spawned pro-Navajo ``support
groups'' across the United States and as far away as Europe and
