<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-NAVY-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO LETS NAVY RESUME SOME USE OF BASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Puerto Rico agreed Monday to let the Navy resume
limited training on the island of Vieques as part of a deal that
includes up to $90 million in aid if residents of Vieques vote to
allow live-fire exercises.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement closely resembles the pact rejected by Puerto Rico
in December, with one important exception: an offer to more than
double the initial $40 million aid package. During six weeks of
often bitter negotiations, a compromise became possible when
``everyone agreed that the centerpiece should be that the people of
Vieques should decide the issue through a referendum,'' said a
senior official who took part in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Monday, President Clinton said the plan ``will
help resolve the impasse over Vieques in the fairest possible way,
because it will meet our training needs while giving the people
most affected by this decision _ the people who actually live on
the island _ the ability to choose for themselves the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Gov. Pedro Rossello of Puerto Rico said the Navy
could resume training with inert, or nonexploding, bombs, a
concession that was immediately criticized by Vieques activists who
vowed to block the return of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is treason,'' Roberto Rabin, head of the Coordinating
Committee for Peace and Justice in Vieques, said in a telephone
interview. ``This is a very serious reversal of the position of the
Puerto Rican government that there will be no more bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabin said that his group, which includes some of the protesters
now occupying the Navy range in Vieques, would ``resist and
mobilize massive numbers of people the moment the Navy resumes
bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Monday to Clinton affirming the agreement, Rossello
said he would help evict the protesters occupying parts of the
900-acre range.
</P>
<P>
   The governor wrote that Puerto Rico would ``support federal
efforts to assure that trespassing or other intrusions on the range
cease entirely by providing complementary support required of state
and local jurisdictions.''
</P>
<P>
   That will relieve some of the concerns voiced by Attorney
General Janet Reno, who strongly argued that local law-enforcement
officials should be involved in any forcible removal of the
protesters from the range, which is scattered with unexploded
ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   All training was suspended last April when a civilian Puerto
Rican security guard was killed in a bombing accident, touching off
widespread protests there. The issue has even shaped the
presidential campaign and the Senate race in New York, which is
home to a large population of Puerto Ricans. Vice President Al Gore
and Hillary Rodham Clinton both sided with Puerto Rico in the
dispute with the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before Congress last fall, Rossello said the Navy
would not drop another bomb on Vieques after what he described as
six decades of poor stewardship of the island.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Navy has described the Vieques range as the
``crown jewel'' of its training ranges, the only site along the
East Coast where battle groups could use live ammunition during
joint training exercises that included amphibious landings of
marines, shelling from ships, and aerial bombardment from fighter
jets. Those exercises, the Navy says, are essential to prepare
sailors and marines for overseas deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum, tentatively scheduled for May 2001, will give
the people on Vieques a choice of letting the Navy resume full use
of the range with live bombs and ammunition or ordering the
military to end all training by May 1, 2003. If the voters favor
the Navy, Clinton has agreed to give an additional $50 million in
aid to encourage employment and development of the small island.
</P>
<P>
   With the resumption of training with dummy bombs, the island
will immediately receive $40 million to improve infrastructure,
like roads, ferry piers and the airport; to help the fishing
industry and offer job training for young adults; and to protect
the threatened waterways and wildlife of Vieques.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The negotiations became urgent when several members of Congress
threatened to close down the large Roosevelt Roads Naval Base in
Puerto Rico if Vieques training was ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Armed Services committee was even scheduled to begin
hearings Tuesday on the issue, but the session was canceled Monday
night after the agreement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general sense that it would be good to get this
done,'' said the official who took part in the negotiations. ``It
wasn't helpful to anyone to have the intensity of the opposition
between the military and Puerto Rico build up any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   In his annual speech on the state of Puerto Rico on Monday
evening, Rossello portrayed the agreement as a victory for the
island, which is a commonwealth of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I have the pleasure to announce to you with immense joy
that after six decades of military exercises on Vieques we have
arrived at a solution to ensure peace for Vieques,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign to win approval of the referendum in Vieques,
the Navy will highlight the fact that its officials now understand
the mistakes made in the past and are willing to spend $90 million
in programs to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this represents a definite step ahead,'' Richard
Danzig, secretary of the Navy, said in an interview. ``Now the
people of Puerto Rico and the people of Vieques in particular
should embrace a process of reconciliation that is peaceful,
law-abiding, and doesn't allow for trespassing on the range.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
