<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-FINAL-PLEAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS N.H. CAMPAIGN WINDS DOWN, CANDIDATES PUT THE GLOVES BACK ON
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRIMACK, N.H. _ With the last hours before this state's
presidential primary ticking away and plenty of undecided voters
out there, it was time Monday for the candidates to make their
final pleas, show their best sides and conclude their campaigns on
memorable grace notes.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Gov. George W. Bush and Gary L. Bauer found
themselves on a stage at an armory in Manchester around 9 a.m.,
spatulas in hands and pancakes at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   At this and other photogenic endeavors, the candidates turned
their attention away from detailed policy discussions and, by and
large, from biting verbal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect case in point was the presidential pancake flip-off.
Bush sent his pancake high into the air, where it did more than a
dozen revolutions before he caught it, for a score of 59 out of a
possible 60.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican opponent, Bauer, then lofted his own, stepped
backward and plummeted from the stage, but not before getting in a
dig at a conservative rival, the wealthy publisher Steve Forbes,
who was not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's over on the other side of town,'' Bauer said, ``at a
Faberge egg scrambling contest.'' Bauer's score was 29.
</P>
<P>
   At times Monday, the campaigns took on an aura of willful
levity, but the goal was utterly serious. By carefully contriving
scenes irresistible to television cameras, the candidates sought to
guarantee themselves a hefty share of the coveted time on local
news programs.
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted to project images of unflappable confidence or
unwavering determination, and they were not about to let too much
speechifying or too many unpredictable questions from voters get in
the way. Dropping by diners and family-run stores, they chattered
playfully, and any apprehension they felt was buried deep.
</P>
<P>
   When Forbes slid on a patch of ice outside his headquarters,
where he and several family members made telephone calls to voters
as television crews and photographers surrounded them, he was
nonplused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the ground is slipping,'' he said, ``we are
standing firm.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking potshots at each other for days, the Democratic
candidates, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley,
had a fairly sedate day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent the day trying to win voters over one by one. He
campaigned in diners, on the telephone, on radio, on television and
at a town meeting Monday night in Amherst. He was still answering
questions about his relationship with President Clinton. ``I want
to take my own values into the presidency,'' he said. ``I think
people understand that any two human beings are very different.
That's where it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside the inevitable questions about whether he would
respond to allegations by Bradley that Gore had trouble telling the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm focusing on the issues and I'm focusing on a positive
message for the future,'' he said. ``There's a big difference
between differences on the issues and having manipulative old
politics-as-usual attacks. I'm not going to do that, haven't done
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley stepped back Monday from the more confrontational
approach he has taken over the past week and returned to the
quieter, more cerebral, even inspirational style of his appearances
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the president of the United States to use the
power of that office to do good,'' he told workers a software
company, Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was a bit more rousing. With his four
youngest children he traveled from Keene, to Hanover, Concord,
Portsmouth and Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we win tomorrow night,'' he said in Keene, ``the message
is going to be sent from New Hampshire to America and the world
that we are going to give the government back to the people of the
United States, take it out of the hands of the special interests
and the big money and give it back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the candidates struck their most fetching poses in
public, their campaigns were also operating on another, less
visible track. Each operation was marshaling its resources and
lavishing its energy in the service of last-ditch efforts to get
out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A senior adviser for Bush said that his campaign had an army of
4,000 volunteers _ nearly half of them from outside New Hampshire _
who were placing phone calls and canvassing neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Bush campaign placed about 110,000 phone calls
Monday and would place nearly as many on Tuesday. Voters who had
already indicated steadfast support for Bush got a recorded message
Monday from his wife, Laura Bush, who thanked them and encouraged
them to go to the polls; undecided voters heard the taped voice of
Bush, asking them for their help.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made calls himself.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., the chairman of Bush's campaign in the
state, said that more than 180,000 pieces of literature touting
Bush's candidacy had been distributed door-to-door over the last
week. Additionally, the amount of money Bush had devoted to
advertising for the New Hampshire race climbed to $3.3 million,
much more than the $2.1 million that his advisers estimated that
McCain was able to spend. A spokesman for McCain said that the
senator had spent much less than that, but said he could not
provide a specific figure.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides, the intensive efforts reflected polls that showed
races still too tight to call.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates themselves talked less about actual numbers
and more about the general success they insisted they were
anticipating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something going on out there,'' Bush told reporters as
he visited a state government office in Concord. ``It's called
energy and enthusiasm and excitement, and I like my chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
