<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ILL-DEATH-PENALTY-ART     01-31 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-DEATH-PENALTY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPRINGFIELD, Ill.: the wastebasket.''   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Illinois seems to have become a center of debate over the
death penalty, the issue is gaining resonance around the nation,
after many years in which it was seen as essentially a dead letter
in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the halt on executions here, and the vetoed moratorium
in Nebraska, the death penalty has been the focus of intense
scrutiny in Florida and other states. Last year, in a visit to the
United States, Pope John Paul II called on Catholics to oppose the
death penalty. And a new movie, ``Hurricane,'' examines the life of
a man, Reuben Carter, who was sent to death row for a crime he did
not commit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to raise more concerns about the death
penalty,'' said Steven Hawkins, the executive director of the
National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty. ``It's becoming
obvious that mistakes can be made, and innocent people'' can be
sent to death row.
</P>
<P>
   While the wrongful convictions in Illinois have generated
intense scrutiny and debate, Florida has seen 18 death row cases
reversed, the most of any state.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who said he would appoint a panel to study death penalty
sentences, heads the Illinois campaign for Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the state that executes more people than any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that a public dialogue must begin on the question of
fairness of the application of the death penalty in Illinois,''
Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   In about a year as governor, Ryan has taken some actions that
have put him at odds with conservatives in his party. He has called
for strict gun control, expressed support for the civil rights of
gay people and traveled to Cuba and met with Fidel Castro, the
communist leader. Some suburban and downstate lawmakers have
complained that Ryan has maintained too cozy a political
relationship with Mayor Daley, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has lately been beleaguered by an investigation into a
bribery scandal at driver's license bureaus that occurred during
his watch as the Illinois secretary of state. While Ryan has not
been charged with wrongdoing, one of his top aides is expected to
be indicted. Seventeen people have pleaded guilty to taking bribes
to fix driver's license exams, and some of the bribe money went to
Ryan's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, Illinois has executed 12 inmates, the most recent in
March 1999, the lethal injection of Andrew Kokoraleis, a suburban
Chicago man who had been convicted of an especially grisly murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Cook County state's attorney's office has instituted special
internal reviews for all cases that would be eligible for the death
penalty. The prosecutor's office, which is headed by Richard
Devine, a Democrat, has not called for an execution date since
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   David Erickson, the first assistant state's attorney, said the
governor's call for a moratorium was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy thing would have been to finger-point, and the
governor did not do that,'' Erickson said. ``If something has
fallen apart here, it is a systemic problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0457 </DOCNO>
