<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBO-ATLANTA-HOMICIDES     01-31 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ATLANTA-HOMICIDES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL linebacker questioned after double murder in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta police are trying to determine if Baltimore
Ravens middle linebacker Ray Lewis had any connection to a double
slaying that occurred in the tony Buckhead club district just hours
after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   National Football League officials said they were taking a
wait-and-see attitude after learning Lewis' name had surfaced in
the murder investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Monday night he had been cleared by Atlanta homicide
investigators in the stabbing deaths of Jacinta Baker and Richard
Lollar. But Atlanta homicide investigators declined comment on the
NFL star Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens coach Brian Billick and Ravens owner Art Modell said they
are waiting to see how the situation unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was allowed to fly to Hawaii where he will play in the Pro
Bowl, NFL officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Angry Buckhead activists, meanwhile, vowed to ask the Atlanta
City Council for a temporary curfew that would shut down the area's
nightclubs and bars at 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   No arrest warrants had been issued as of late Monday and police
said they were desperately seeking any witnesses who may have seen
the fatal altercation near the Cobalt Lounge on East Paces Ferry
Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone can come forward we would really appreciate it,''
said Lt. Mike Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Officers and detectives involved in the double murder
investigation said Lewis was inside the black stretch limousine
that roared away from the spot where Baker and Lollar were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and his agents denied any wrongdoing on his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not involved in any aspect of the investigation as far as
I know,'' said Roosevelt Barnes, Jr., one of Lewis' agents.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lewis confirmed to the Baltimore Sun he was
questioned by Atlanta police, but says he was told he could go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cooperated fully (with police). As far as the situation, I
have no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, 21 and Lollar, 24, were stabbed several times as the pair
fought with a handful of men who were passengers in a stretch
Lincoln Navigator limousine with Maryland plates, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens owner Art Modell said, ``I don't believe he had anything
to do with it. I'm going to give Ray the benefit of the doubt and
defend him until something is proven otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis became the NFL's highest-paid linebacker in November 1998
when he signed a four-year, $26 million contract, which included a
$7 million signing bonus. A first-round draft choice of the Ravens
in 1996 out of the University of Miami, Lewis has played in three
straight Pro Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is scheduled to stand trial in Maryland's Baltimore County
next month for assaulting a woman in a bar on Dec. 6, 1999. The
24-year-old woman claims Lewis struck her on the left side of the
face, knocking her into the bar at Baltimore's Windsor Mill Inn.
Lewis left the scene before police arrived. Atlanta homicide Lt.
Mike Smith said detectives are seeking any witnesses who may have
seen the 4 a.m. altercation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want anyone who saw this to please come forward,'' Smith
said Monday afternoon. ``We just want to question anyone who may
have seen anything or heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The one big break in the case came just a couple of hours after
the killings when detectives found the stretch limousine behind a
Holiday Inn on Peachtree Road. Homicide detectives spent most of
the day talking to the driver of the luxury sedan, but they would
not provide details concerning those conversations. Police were
called to the hotel after someone told them a man with bloodstains
on his clothing had gotten out of the Lincoln Navigator limousine
and entered a bathroom in the hotel lobby to wash off, officers
said.
</P>
<P>
   No arrest warrants had been issued as of Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa and Mark Schlabach write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
