<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS CRAFTING BILL TO EASE `MARRIAGE PENALTY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to keep President Clinton from stealing one
of their tax-cut proposals, House Republicans on Monday put the
final touches on legislation to ease the so-called ``marriage
penalty'' in the federal tax code.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, drafted by Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, with no input
from Democrats, would provide tax relief for more married taxpayers
in higher-income brackets and would cost four times more than the
proposal outlined last week in Clinton's State of the Union
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people support this, representatives and senators
of both parties support this, so there's no excuse why this
shouldn't be done this year,'' said Archer, who chairs the House
Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 million two-paycheck couples pay more income tax,
largely because their combined income boosts them into a higher tax
bracket than if they were filing separately.
</P>
<P>
   Archer plans for his tax-writing committee to consider the bill
Wednesday and send it to the full House for debate by Feb. 14,
Valentine's Day. Archer's bill is similar to a provision included
in last year's $792 billion tax package Republicans pushed through
Congress last year only to have it vetoed by Clinton complaining it
was too large.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by Clinton's veto, which prompted little public
backlash, Republican leaders in the House last month announced
plans to repackage their tax-cut proposals in a series of separate
bills that will make them harder for Democrats and the White House
to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it is approved by the House, the marriage-penalty relief
bill faces an uncertain future in the Senate, where many
Republicans prefer combining smaller tax cuts into one large tax
package.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual address to Congress, Clinton on Thursday called
for easing the so-called marriage penalty for about 9 million
couples. The president's plan, which would be phased-in over the
next 10 years, would increase the standard income deduction for
two-income couples to an amount twice what is allowed for single
filers.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's measure, which is backed by the House leadership, would
increase the standard deduction for married couples to twice that
for single tax filers beginning in 2001. This would translate into
a standard deduction of $8,800, compared to the current $7,351.
</P>
<P>
   It would allow married couples to pay the lowest tax rate on
their first $52,500 of income, compared to the $43,850 under
current law.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer proposal would provide no tax break for middle- and
lower-income couples who already are in the 15-percent tax bracket
until at least 2006. Archer estimated it would extend a tax break
to a total of 44 million two-income households by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer bill also would enlarge the bottom 15 percent income
tax rate to ensure a tax cut for couples with higher incomes and
those who itemize deductions. Clinton proposes relief only for
couples who take the standard tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the GOP and the president propose increasing by
$2,000 the income cutoff for lower-income married couples who claim
the earned income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP bill would reduce government revenue by $182.3 billion
over 10 years, or almost 10 percent of the projected $1.9 trillion
non-Social Security surplus. Clinton's proposal to ease the
marriage penalty would cost $45 billion.
</P>
<P>
   New York Rep. Charles Rangel, the ranking Democrat on the Ways
and Means Committee, said Archer and other Republicans are
signaling that they prefer to put Democrats into a position of
having to accept the GOP proposal or appear to vote against relief
from the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also signals that they (the Republicans) do not want to get
something done for the American people,'' Rangel said. ``The bulk
of the cost of the bill is accounted for by the tax break to those
with incomes that exceed the top of the 15 percent tax bracket,
(and) that's the most affluent one-quarter of tax filers.''
</P>
<P>
   Before agreeing to support the Republicans' proposal, White
House officials said the president wants to see how they balance
projected budget surpluses among the overall priorities of Social
Security, Medicare, government spending, debt repayment and tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
