<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-KEYES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND N.H., KEYES SEES A PATH TO THE NOMINATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT31 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ From the stage at a hotel ballroom here the other
night, Alan Keyes was scorching another Republican audience with a
speech about, among other things, the depravity of President
Clinton, the moral crisis endangering the Republic, and most of
all, Keyes' conviction that he alone could save the Republicans
from losing the White House for a third time in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience, Susan Davis leapt to her feet again and again.
When Keyes finished, Ms. Davis, a Republican from Nashua, pulled
him over for a handshake and a compliment. ``Ambassador Keyes, it
is an honor _ an honor _ to meet you!'' she proclaimed. ``I look
forward to coming to Washington and serving in your
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Keyes moved away, Ms. Davis offered a quiet confession.
Yes, she said, she would vote for him in the primary here Tuesday,
but would he win? ``Sadly, I don't think he will,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, Keyes _ or Ambassador Keyes, as he prefers to be
addressed _ should be on a roll. Since finishing third in the Iowa
caucuses, he has been cheered by Republican audiences here and has
appeared on television talk shows. The candidate who had complained
that he had been ignored by the news media because he was black
says that these days, he is finally getting the attention he
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   But even Keyes is already talking about what is next after New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I know there is a path that leads to the
nomination,'' Keyes said in an interview at his hotel in Concord
the other morning. ``That path, while not likely, is possible.
There is a very possible series of events that leads to Alan Keyes
being nominated.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes is, without question, a distinctive presence in this
Republican contest: an unusually evocative speaker, a black
Republican and a conservative who stands to the right in a
conservative field, an ideological stance that served him well in
the Iowa caucuses. But New Hampshire is not Iowa, with its strong
and influential bloc of Christian conservatives and Keyes' speeches
about moral decline and abortion _ the defining platform of his
candidacy _ may not carry quite the weight here that they did in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   That his sensibilities on abortion may be slightly askew from
those of some potential supporters was particularly clear the other
day when he took his case to an audience of elementary school
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now tell me something. If I were to lose my mind right now and
pick one of you up and dash your head against the floor and kill
you, would that be right?'' Keyes asked his young audience. ``It's
wrong to kill children, isn't it? At what age is it all right to
kill children?'' Keyes worked backward until he posed the question
about a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   The point, Keyes explained later, was to provide the children a
lesson they would never forget. Some of the parents found it
unsettling, though Keyes said he had no apologies. ``I think the
message and the result was entirely appropriate,'' he said. ``And
in fact, it was the way they should be taught, if you don't mind me
saying so.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes remains an intense and at times angry man, wary of what he
sees as discrimination against him, which he said is frequent. He
recounted, by way of an example, an episode in which he showed up
at MSNBC studios here to offer his reaction to Clinton's State of
the Union address, only to learn that he had been inserted as part
of a panel, rather than being given his own platform. He left.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Keyes perseveres, proclaiming his faith in God _ ``Our
rights come from the hand of the creator God almighty: that is the
first premise of American life'' _ and denouncing abortion, big
government, homosexual marriage, and the income tax system to
anyone who will give him an ear or a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   And there is arguably no one in the field who is quite as
unambivalent _some Republicans suggest the word is extreme _ in his
views as Keyes. Steve Forbes supports a flat tax, and George W.
Bush and John McCain favor a cut in the tax rates. Keyes supports
eliminating the payroll and income tax entirely, replacing it with
a sales tax of about 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All the candidates decry Clinton: Keyes describes him as ``a
traitor'' and his presidency as ``the most humiliating and
degrading and shameful'' in the history of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he shows signs of fading away, Keyes continues to argue
that he alone can win the White House for his party next year,
dispatching Bush and McCain as candidates headed for certain
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open your eyes,'' he said. ``Money will not win this election.
Name will not win this election. The only thing that will win this
election for the Republican Party is a champion that can stand
before the American people and challenge them to return to their
allegiance to our great moral principles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
