<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-N     01-31 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-MANNESMANN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN MAY RECONSIDER A MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., skedded earlier as VODAPHONE-MANNESMANN)  
(lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Mannesmann AG reversed its opposition to
talks with Vodafone AirTouch PLC on Monday and began to consider a
face-saving friendly merger, executives close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said there was a growing feeling within
Mannesmann that the company could not defeat the $156 billion
hostile takeover bid from Vodafone, especially after Vivendi SA,
historically an ally of Mannesmann, joined an alliance with
Vodafone on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While advisers to Mannesmann and Vodafone have already been in
contact, the talks are now expected to intensify, the executives
said. ``There is greater likelihood of a friendly deal now,'' one
executive said. Mannesmann is also ready to accept a lower stake in
the combined company, the executives said, though it is still not
ready to accept Vodafone's current proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Vodafone, increasingly confident that it will capture a
majority of Mannesmann shares by the time its offer expires on Feb.
7, has yet to raise its offer, and people on both sides were
skeptical that it would do so.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann's chief executive, Klaus Esser, has insisted that he
would reject any offer in which Mannesmann shareholders ended up
with less than 58.5 percent of the shares in the combined company.
Vodafone's current offer would give them 47.2 percent, though
Vodafone has offered to raise that share to about 49 percent if
Esser agrees to a friendly deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mannesmann's spokesman said the company was receptive
to a higher offer. ``If there is an improvement in the offer, then
this would be a totally different situation,'' said Georg Denoke,
Mannesmann's spokesman, in a telephone interview. But he added,
``We would only negotiate a deal that is really good for our
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Other people close to Mannesmann said Esser might accept an
offer that gave Mannesmann control of just 51 percent of the
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann executives were still stunned Monday by Vodafone's
agreement on Sunday to form a big new Internet venture with
Vivendi. The news was a big blow to Mannesmann, which has been
Vivendi's partner in France's second-largest wireless telephone
company, SFR, and which had been trying to negotiate its own merger
with Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Mannesmann said Esser endured a stormy meeting
with members of the company's supervisory board. Several board
members are now forcefully prodding Esser to reach an agreement if
possible. Among those who favor an agreement are Henning
Schulte-Noelle, chief executive of Germany's largest insurance
company, Allianz AG, and Juergen E. Schrempp, chief executive of
DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   But one person close to Mannesmann said Vodafone's hand seemed
so strong now that it might be able to acquire a majority of shares
without sweetening its deal at all.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts in London questioned who was in the driver's
seat. ``Why would Vodafone do this deal with Vivendi if they had
the whole deal locked up?'' one analyst asked. Another analyst
acknowledged the counter point, ``Mannesmann no longer has a card
to play,'' referring to Vodafone's alliance with Vivendi, spoiling
a white knight scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholders have already begun offering their shares to
Vodafone, but Vodafone has refused to say how many shares it has
received. Typically in a takeover battle, most stockholders wait
until the last day or two before selling.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and institutional investors said the Feb. 7 deadline is
self-imposed by Vodafone and that some investors said they might
hang onto their shares and make their decision before Feb. 21, when
the deadline lapses under German takeover regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the actual percentage of Vodafone shares that end
up in the hands of Mannesmann's current shareholders, control of
the combined company would rest with Vodafone's chief executive,
Chris Gent. Mannesmann's shares are widely distributed among
shareholders and Esser would not be able to invoke them in a bid to
retain management control of the ``new'' Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Gent remains eager to reach a peaceful agreement. Even if a
majority of Mannesmann's shareholders trade in their shares for
stock in Vodafone, Mannesmann's dissenting shareholders could still
block or at least delay Vodafone from taking full legal control of
the company. Those problems are greatly reduced if Mannesmann
management endorses Gent's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Investors interpreted the Vodafone-Vivendi alliance as a sign
that Vodafone would prevail. Mannesmann shares closed up 4.5
percent, or 12.05 euros ($11.69), at 280.25 euros ($271.81) in
Frankfurt trading, while Vodafone closed 1.5 percent lower in
London, down 5.25 pence (8.48 cents) at 338.50 pence ($5.47),
though most London stocks dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
