<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRADITIONAL SPONSORS SCORE BIGGEST SUPER BOWL WINS
</P>
<P>
   The Ad Bowl, interrupted at various times by Super Bowl XXXIV on
Sunday, was emblematic of a new era for Madison Avenue. For
instance, there were more commercials aimed at women, the first
paid public service announcements and a larger presence for media
outlets. The most significant change was the proliferation of
dot-com spots, as 17 of the 36 marketers buying national commercial
time during the game came from the Internet world, including an ad
from Monster.com.
</P>
<P>
   Most preliminary opinion, buttressed by the results of polls,
agreed that commercials for Web sites and e-commerce marketers
fared less well than spots for traditional Super Bowl sponsors like
beers, soft drinks and credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END JANUARY WITH A RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended their first losing month since September with a
rally, as investors bought beaten-down telecommunications and
financial shares. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index advanced
34.30 points, or about 2.5 percent, to 1,394.46. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained 201.66, or nearly 1.9 percent, to
10,940.53. The Nasdaq composite index closed at 3,940.35, up 53.28
points.
</P>
<P>
   EX-OFFICIALS BACK MICROSOFT POSITION
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft gained some prominent allies in its antitrust fight,
as two former attorneys general and a pair of former senior White
House lawyers supported the software company's defense in a court
filing. They joined a friend-of-the-court brief submitted by the
Association for Competitive Technology, a trade group with close
ties to Microsoft that was founded in 1998 when the government
filed its antitrust suit against the company.
</P>
<P>
   RIVALS INCREASE OFFERS FOR NATWEST
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland and the Royal Bank of Scotland raised their
bids for National Westminster Bank. The Edinburgh rivals are in a
heated bidding war for NatWest, a bank that is twice the size of
either Scottish suitor and that wants to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER SPENDING GROWS AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending rose 0.8 percent in December. That helped lift
the increase for 1999 to a 10-year high of 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   UPS EARNINGS UP 37 PERCENT IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service said fourth-quarter earnings rose 37
percent, disappointing investors who had expected the provider of
package delivery service to get a bigger lift from holiday-season
shipments by online retailers. Shares of United Parcel fell $5, or
about 8 percent, to $59.9375. It was the lowest price since shares
were issued at $50 in an initial public offering on Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Union Carbide rose 40 percent in the fourth quarter
because of strong sales and improved prices in chemicals and
polymers. The results beat the 46 cents that analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett said fourth-quarter earnings increased 14 percent,
spurred by continued growth in advertising sales at its flagship
newspaper, USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   LAFARGE BID EXPECTED FOR BLUE CIRCLE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Blue Circle Industries, a British cement company, rose
more than 20 percent on reports that building materials group
Lafarge of France was about to bid as much as $5.7 billion for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   SONY MUSIC IS SUED BY RETAILERS
</P>
<P>
   Sony Music Entertainment was sued by retailers who said the
company illegally steered customers to its online stores by
including hyperlinks on music compact discs. The National
Association of Recording Merchandisers filed suit in federal court
in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
