<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER-COX     01-31 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MLB's Selig suspends, fines Rocker
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Major League Baseball ended its six-week silence on
the John Rocker matter in a big way Monday, suspending the Braves
reliever for the first month of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, whose racially inflammatory remarks in the December
issue of Sports Illustrated magazine sparked outrage throughout the
country, is suspended from opening day on April 3 until May 1, a
span of 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pitcher also is forbidden from working out with the
major league club in any capacity until then, including this week's
``Camp Leo'' and the entire seven weeks of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker also was fined $20,000, with the understanding that the
money would go toward an organization that promotes diversity. And
he will be required to undergo diversity training, the nature of
which is yet to be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is the longest not related to drugs since Lenny
Randle of Texas was suspended 30 days in March of 1977 for punching
manager Frank Lucchesi.
</P>
<P>
   ''Major League Baseball takes seriously its role as an American
institution and the important social responsibility that goes with
it,'' Commissioner Bud Selig said in a statement. ''Mr. Rocker
should understand that his remarks offended practically every
element of society and brought dishonor to himself, the Atlanta
Braves and Major League Baseball. The terrible example set by Mr.
Rocker is not what our great game is about and, in fact, is a
profound breach of the social compact we hold in such high
regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker indicated Monday he plans to file a grievance through the
Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not believe it is appropriate that I should be harshly
disciplined for my misguided speech unaccompanied by any conduct on
my part,'' Rocker said in a statement issued through his agents.
''I have previously apologized for my unfortunate remarks and stand
by my apology.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been in consultation with Mr. Rocker and it is our
present intention to appeal,'' said Gene Orza, the players union's
No. 2 official. ''It is literally unprecedented to impose a penalty
on a player for pure speech, offensive though the speech may be.
That, coupled with the magnitude of the penalty, just as
unprecedented, makes us optimistic about the outcome of the
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Braves president Stan Kasten nor general manager John
Schuerholz was willing to venture an opinion on the severity of the
punishment. But Schuerholz indicated the penalty was about what the
Braves expected.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Braves players, at least one fellow relief pitcher
was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a whole month? Holy cow,'' said Rudy Seanez. ``I figured
they might do one or the other _ suspend him or fine him. I don't
know what to say but I'm pretty shocked. That's real big.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten and Schuerholz indicated they were against a grievance, a
feeling they said was reiterated two weeks ago in a private meeting
they had with assistant general manager Frank Wren and seven
veteran Braves players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believed that if John was suspended or disciplined in
some fashion, they'd be willing to give him a second chance as a
teammate to rectify the wrong he had done,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object should be to get John to a place where he's
accepted by his teammates and by his community,'' Kasten said.
``That's the war to win. And to win the battle by getting back a
few days early or what-not and have that viewed unfortunately as
something that would diminish the sincerity of his apology _ I
think that might be winning the battle but losing the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, what's most important is getting through successfully,
having people recognize the sincerity of his apology and put this
behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning April 3, Rocker will be allowed to work out either
with a Braves minor league team or in the Braves extended spring
training workouts. The Braves will renew Rocker's contract in March
and he will be paid during his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very difficult,'' Schuerholz said. ``The perception
has been we've been dragging our feet when we didn't have the power
to do anything about it. We're glad to have a decision. Now we can
go forward and plan for our needs in spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
