<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BOSTON-RAIL-NYT &LR;      01-31 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOSTON-RAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH FANFARE AND A TECHNICAL PROBLEM, AMTRAK BEGINS HIGH-SPEED
SERVICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Maine, Wis., N.H., Conn., R.I., Colo., Va., Ill.,
Ga., France)   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amtrak unveiled new fully electrified train service
between Boston and New York Monday, but the day was marred by
technical problems that seemed symbolic of the difficulties the
company has faced in a $2.6 billion high-speed rail venture.
</P>
<P>
   The improved service was the first step in a project to
introduce 150-mile-an-hour trains that would reduce travel time to
Boston to three hours from five and cut about 15 minutes off travel
time to Washington. But Monday, as Amtrak officials boasted about
the superiority of the service, called Acela, mechanical problems
delayed the start of the first train.
</P>
<P>
   As a news conference concluded in Boston about 9:30 a.m.,
engineers rushed to fix the mechanical problems that caused a
20-minute delay. The minor setback, which company officials blamed
on an engine problem, did not seem to faze Amtrak officials.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, the chairman of Amtrak's board
of directors, said that the ``first step'' in building a national
high-speed railroad system ``has got to be the Northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this really means,'' Thompson added, ``is that we will be
able to become really competitive with airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   The train, which left Boston at 9:51 a.m. and arrived at
Pennsylvania Station in New York at 3:30 p.m., was also delayed as
officials stopped for news conferences in Connecticut and Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The service introduced Monday, Acela Regional, shortens the trip
to and from Boston to about four hours. It was made possible by
extending electricity along the entire corridor between the two
cities; previously, electrified service ended at New Haven, where
train crews switched to slower diesel locomotives.
</P>
<P>
   A faster service, Acela Express, which would reduce the trip to
just over three hours, has been delayed by problems with the
manufacture of high-speed trains. Both Monday's train and the
express train had been scheduled to begin service in September, but
Amtrak officials now say it is unclear when the contractor on the
project will be able to deliver the express train.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor, Alstom SA, a French manufacturing company, is
redesigning the express train's suspension after problems with wear
on the wheels.
</P>
<P>
   That train, which is being tested in Pueblo, Colo., was delayed
after the wheel problems made it difficult for the trains to make
curves.
</P>
<P>
   The delay has caused problems for Amtrak, which hopes to
generate $180 million a year in profits from the new train service.
Those profits are needed to help the railroad meet a cutoff in
operating subsidies at the end of the 2002 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials said that the delays would not cause budget
shortfalls because of a contingency plan and fines that could be
assessed against the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials hope the express service will help cut into the
airline business between Washington, Boston and New York. Amtrak
now carries only about 15 percent of the combined air-rail traffic
between Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, Amtrak replaced nearly a dozen bridges and
installed 115 miles of electrified rail between South Station in
Boston and New Haven. Much of this work was paid for by
Congressional appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's president, George D. Warrington, said he hoped to see
rail improvements and speedier trains, similar to the Acela,
traveling soon to transportation hubs like Richmond, Va., Chicago
and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Electrification of rail lines between New Haven and Boston was
originally proposed in 1912, but was never attempted by the private
railroads that ran passenger services at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s the idea was revived again, but stalled during
the Reagan administration, which opposed additional public
subsidies for Amtrak, officials explained.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1990s, a bipartisan coalition of business
leaders, academics and environmental advocates won reluctant
approval from the Bush administration, which helped secure funds
for the electrification that was completed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Electric trains cannot run all the way from Maine to Washington
yet, officials said, because of a small section of track missing
between two Boston stations.
</P>
<P>
   James P. RePass, the president and chief executive of the
National Corridors Initiative, a Providence-based organization that
has advocated for the improvements, said his group is lobbying for
a quick completion of that set of tracks to allow direct service
from New York City to New Hampshire, Maine and Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
