<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKW-BONSIG-COLUMN-LAD     01-31 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BONSIG-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURRY ISN'T GOOD SPICE FOR CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Remember when you were a kid and you held your
breath when you didn't get what you wanted?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Cal State Northridge women's basketball standout
Edniesha Curry is doing. Curry remains AWOL from the Matadors after
walking out on the team last Monday over a dispute with coach
Frozena Jerro.
</P>
<P>
   When Curry left, she took teammate Jamilah Jones along,
extracting from CSUN (12-6, 6-2) two starters including its top
scorer and playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are not only letting down their teammates, who have
worked hard to make this a special season, but themselves as well.
Someday, Curry and Jones maybe will realize this. It is hoped they
will do so in time to restore their tarnished images and salvage
the Matadors' season.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, a 5-foot-6 junior guard from Palmdale High, is averaging
15.3 points and 6.7 assists. She is also the school's leader in
scoring average and 3-point field goals attempted and made. Jones,
a 5-6 guard, is one of the Matadors' top defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   The longer Curry is absent, the more she resembles the kid with
the puffed-out cheeks who threatens to hold her breath until she
gets her way.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates indicate Curry's quarrel with Jerro stems from an
ongoing problem Curry has with certain members of the coaching
staff. The situation came to a head Jan. 23, when Curry argued with
assistant Karen Howell during practice. Jerro sided with Howell,
and Curry sulked out of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Curry quit a day later. Jones, her roommate, soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   They, along with Jerro, have left the door open to return. In
fact, they're probably waiting for Jerro to show up at their front
door with a bouquet of roses, get on her knees and beg them to come
back.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Curry: You can let your breath out now because it's not
going to happen. The best you can hope for is Jerro to call you
this week, which on Monday she indicated she might do to bring
closure.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that Jerro, the Matadors 29-year-old second-year
coach, won't budge any further. And she shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Curry to understand this and before it's too late
for her or the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Many predicted CSUN would win the Big Sky Conference, and the
Matadors seemed on their way until Curry and Jones left. They're
1-1 without them, beating Sacramento St. 76-52, then losing 61-59
Wednesday to Weber St, a setback that dropped them into second
place.
</P>
<P>
   Curry's abrupt exit threatens to tear the team apart. Players
might choose sides, some aligning with Curry, others standing with
Jerro. Curry might not have considered this when she turned her
back on the Matadors, but it was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each side thinks the other side is wrong,'' CSUN's Neda Milic
said. ``I don't like the way it is. I want (Curry and Jones) back.
I am hoping they come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerro does, too, but on her terms.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that Curry overplayed her hand, which often happens
when star players think the program will crumble in their absence.
Certainly, the Matadors are worse off without Curry, but they'll
move on.
</P>
<P>
   As for Curry, the hope here is that she realizes her mistake and
apologizes to Jerro, the coaching staff and her teammates and
returns to the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
