<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BROKER-BANK-NYT &LR;      01-31 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKER-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH TO COMPETE WITH BANKS FOR CUSTOMER DEPOSITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For more than a year now, Wall Street analysts have
been wondering whether Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the nation's biggest
brokerage firm, would buy a commercial bank or be bought by one.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the response from Merrill: Why not just be a bank?
</P>
<P>
   The firm is preparing to make its biggest push to compete with
banks for customers' deposits. Merrill is taking advantage of
recent changes in national banking laws to roll out new banking
services, including a federally insured, interest-bearing account
tied to its customers' investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill brokerage executives also are developing the first new
version of the firm's Cash Management Account, which broke new
ground 25 years ago by combining interest-bearing checking with a
standard brokerage account that held stocks and bonds. The new
version, known internally at Merrill as CMA 2.0, would allow
customers who are queasy about mixing investments and savings to
choose how to segregate various assets within the account.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the vast majority of our clients have a fairly
significant amount of money at banking institutions,'' said John L.
Steffens, a vice chairman who runs Merrill's brokerage operation.
``I think we're offering a better deal than banks.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Merrill cash management account, all the cash that is not
invested in securities is regularly swept into a money-market fund
that pays dividends; for taxable funds, the current yield is 5.43
percent. But that cash, which amounts to about $118 billion, is not
guaranteed by Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., as most bank
deposits are.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in June, Merrill plans to automatically switch the
cash that is being swept into taxable money market funds over to
insured accounts at two banks Merrill owns. Because Merrill owns
two banks, it will offer federal insurance on up to $200,000 per
account, twice the per-account limit for deposit insurance. The
firm's banks, in turn, will use the cash deposits to finance their
lending and investing activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the brokerage firms couldn't have previously was insured
deposits,'' said Joan Solotar, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``Now, with the financial services reform legislation,
there is no banking product that the brokerage firms can't offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill would not be the first financial services firm to offer
insured deposits. American Express Co. has such an account through
its online bank.
</P>
<P>
   After Congress repealed the Depression-era regulations known as
the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933 last fall, some analysts predicted a
wave of mergers among banks, brokerage firms and insurance
companies. Ms. Solotar said at the time that she thought the
changes were ``less of a mergers-and-acquisitions event than an
opportunity for the brokers to get into other businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Solotar said the new products provided Merrill with ``a huge
opportunity'' to draw customers away from commercial banks, which
pay significantly lower rates on deposits than Merrill is
considering. She said she expected similar offerings from other
brokerage firms, like Charles Schwab, which has said it will buy
the private-banking company U.S. Trust Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will show that it is not a zero-sum game in retail
brokerage,'' Ms. Solotar said. ``It's not just Merrill Lynch versus
Schwab. It's Merrill and Schwab versus the consumer banks, which
currently don't seem well prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, an analyst with the Salomon Smith Barney unit of
Citigroup, estimates that no more than 30 percent of all investment
assets in the United States are held in accounts at brokerage
firms. Still, he said, that is double the market share the
brokerage firms had a decade ago and most of the gain has come at
the expense of banks and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of last year, after Merrill introduced an
all-in-one brokerage account that provided unlimited stock trades
for a preset annual fee, Merrill and Schwab showed that they could
simultaneously rake in new assets at a fast pace. Investors had
worried that Merrill's profit margins would shrink because it was
charging too little, less than 1 percent of assets in many cases,
for the new account, known as Unlimited Advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The potential gains to Merrill from introducing the new banking
products could go ``a long way toward offsetting a lot of the
erosion that some people have been concerned about in the
profitability of their retail commission business,'' Moszkowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill is not making any projections about the impact the
banking products could have on its earnings but analysts think it
could be significant. Moszkowski said a conservative,
back-of-the-envelope estimate was an increase of 50 cents a share
in Merrill's annual earnings after the transition to the insured
accounts is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be able to offer a product that is more
profitable for them, and more attractive to the customer, than the
money market is,'' Moszkowski said. ``If Merrill wants to do this
bank lending and they can't fund it this way, they have to go out
into the market and buy that money and they'll buy that money at
higher prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill can afford to offer higher rates than banks offer
because it does not have to factor in the costs of operating its
network of branches, as banks do, Moszkowski said. Merrill's
730-branch system already is profitable, from selling stocks, bonds
and mutual funds, so the firm can treat the bank products as
virtually costless and consider them profitable even though there
will be a relatively slim gap between what it charges for loans and
what it pays for deposits.
</P>
<P>
   At commercial banks, that gap, or spread, runs as high as 5
percentage points. In recent years, a new breed of electronic
banks, unburdened by the costs of branches and tellers, has risen
to challenge established banks by offering cheaper loans and higher
yields on certificates of deposit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PINOCHET-BRITAIN-1STL     01-31 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-BRITAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COURT UPHOLDS DECISION TO RELEASE PINOCHET
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: ADDS new 9th graf, Belgium and ..., with background on why
Belgium is involved in the case; corrects first name of judge in
14th graf) 
 (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A High Court judge issued a tough-worded judgment
Monday supporting the British government's decision to release Gen.
Augusto Pinochet and let him return home to Chile, but Belgium held
up any final action by lodging an appeal against the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Home Secretary Jack Straw had said on Jan. 11 that he was
inclined to set the 84-year-old former Chilean dictator free
immediately because of his deteriorating health but would await the
outcome of any legal objections before issuing a definitive order.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's ruling, Judge Maurice Kay turned down appeals from
six human rights groups and the Belgian government contesting the
British government's finding that Pinochet is medically unfit to be
extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture charges.
</P>
<P>
   But the hopes of Pinochet supporters that Kay's verdict
constituted the end of legal moves in the 15-month-old case were
dashed by Belgium, which filed its appeal Monday afternoon. It will
be heard by a panel of three High Court judges on Monday and
Tuesday of next week. Amnesty International and the five other
rights groups have until noon Tuesday to file any appeals of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Office withheld all comment on Monday's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Kay was emphatic in rejecting the arguments presented in two
days of hearings last week, saying they were ``inappropriate'' and
``utterly without merit.'' The groups had jointly protested Straw's
refusal to make public records of a medical examination of Pinochet
conducted by four British doctors that was the basis for the
findings on the general's infirm physical state.
</P>
<P>
   Kay found that Straw acted ``lawfully, fairly and rationally''
in not disclosing the medical documents. Straw had argued that to
do so would violate a pledge of doctor-patient confidentiality made
to the general before the Jan. 5 examination. ``In legal, if
somewhat peremptory terms,'' the judge said of the complainants'
request, ``it is none of their business.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge added that he was ``conscious that my decision is
unavoidably adverse to, on the one hand, people who have suffered
greatly in Chile's recent history, and, in the case of Belgium, to
a friendly state and its judicial authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgium, France and Switzerland had joined Spain in seeking
Pinochet's extradition on behalf of residents who said they
suffered under the general's military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's pursuers denounced Monday's ruling but did so in a
way that suggested they realized chances of judicial relief might
now be slim. Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human Rights Watch,
said: ``We are dismayed by Monday's decision, which is a setback
for Pinochet's thousands of victims in their quest for justice. It
is a shame that the attempt to prosecute General Pinochet for the
worst international crimes may be halted on the basis of secret
medical evidence examined behind closed doors.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its conclusion, the case has already resulted in a
fundamental change in concepts of international law to allow the
prosecution of dictators and leaders of repressive regimes by
courts in countries where the alleged abuses did not occur.
</P>
<P>
   This came about when Britain's highest court, the Law Lords of
the House of Lords, turned aside the general's claim that, under
the principle of sovereign immunity, he could not be tried for acts
committed while he was Chile's head of state, from 1973 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet has been under house arrest in England for more than 15
months while complicated legal moves unfolded around a Spanish
judge's request that he be extradited to Madrid to stand trial on
charges of genocide, torture, kidnapping and murder in connection
with the disappearance of more than 3,000 people in the years after
he seized power in the 1973 coup that ousted President Salvador
Allende.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Baltasar Garzon, considered something of a maverick
in the Spanish judiciary, had gathered his evidence during an
investigation into the so-called dirty wars in Latin America in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 16, 1998, the general was arrested as he lay in a London
clinic recuperating from back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days later, Pinochet won his first legal battle in a
ruling by the High Court that upheld his claim to sovereign
immunity. But in the judgment that was to create the case's legacy,
on Nov. 25, 1998, the Law Lords overturned that decision, saying
that being head of state did not excuse crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The case returned to the House of Lords after one of the
original judges was found to have had an association with Amnesty
International, a party to the case. But the second Lords' decision,
on March 24, 1999, was even more assertive on the principle than
the first one, though it drastically reduced the number of charges
and narrowed their scope to torture and conspiracy to torture.
</P>
<P>
   The case then moved on to the validity of the actual extradition
order itself, which was upheld by a London magistrate last October
and is under an appeal from Pinochet's lawyers that is likely to
become moot because of Straw's expected intervention.
</P>
<P>
   In Pinochet's one court appearance, on Dec. 11, 1998, he
maintained the defiant attitude he has adopted from the beginning,
saying that he did not recognize the jurisdiction of any court
outside Chile to try him and that he was innocent of ``all the lies
of Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since Pinochet's arrest, there have been boisterous gatherings
outside the House of Lords and the downtown magistrate's court,
with supporters and opponents behind barricades angrily facing one
another down, hurling taunts and jeers and holding aloft flags and
placards with accusatory slogans and pictures of missing friends
and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For the past 14 months, the general has been living under house
arrest with his wife, Lucia, in a rented mansion in one of London's
exclusive southern suburbs. He has had periodic visits from Chilean
supporters and from backers in Britain, the most outspoken of whom
has been former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. She has argued
that, far from holding him in custody, Britain instead owes him its
gratitude for the support he provided during the 1982 Falkland
Islands war with Argentina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2401 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      01-31 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWN FROM A NINE-STORY HIGH HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - It was perfectly clear to me as long as I was looking
at it through the ninth floor win dows of The Arizona Republic's
newsroom.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of Phoenix cops stopped a guy for not having a headlamp
on his bicycle and wound up shooting him three times in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Are you kiddin' me?
</P>
<P>
   From a vantage point high above the towers of St. Mary's
Basilica and only slightly below the roof of Bank One Ballpark, it
was a slam-dunk case of po lice brutality, of officers glee fully
using the traffic code to abuse unsuspecting citizens.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious, unequivocal, easy to write.
</P>
<P>
   If only I hadn't gotten the idi otic notion to take the elevator
to the ground floor, get in my car and drive to 22nd Avenue and
Monroe, where the incident happened.
</P>
<P>
   From the high-rise buildings of downtown, it's a short drive
west on Van Buren to 19th Ave nue, then south, then west on Monroe
over the railroad tracks and into the city's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called the St. Matthew's neighborhood,'' said Phoenix po
lice Sgt. Jeff Halstead. ``If you stand on the corner of 22nd Av
enue and Monroe, you'll find the problem. The houses are forti fied
like Alcatraz.''
</P>
<P>
   Stately old porches are cov ered in iron bars, like jail cells,
as are windows and doors. In recent years, a considerable part of
the local crack cocaine and prostitution businesses have moved into
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Residents asked the police for help, and they responded by
declaring the neighborhood a ``high-intensity'' patrol area.
</P>
<P>
   `'The officer's (who fought with the bicyclist) were on
high-intensity,'' Halstead said. ``Their job is to make contacts
and hopefully impact and improve the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Within these few square blocks, even a ridiculously mi nor
violation of the traffic code will get you stopped.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, police say the suspect, Mark William Meador, had
an outstanding warrant for failing to appear in a drug case. They
say he knocked down one officer and was trying to pull the
officer's weapon from him when the other officer fired.
</P>
<P>
   They say the second officer tried other options first, warn ing
Meador and fighting with him, but nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a man in ``serious'' condition in the hospital, the
rest of us get to ask why the po lice were there in the first
place, hassling people.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old neighborhood. Some longtime residents re member
friends displaced when I-17 was built. The incident with the
bicyclist happened not far from a house where, late last week, an
elderly woman spread laundry over the leafless shrubs on the side
of her house, each blouse like a blooming flower.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby two toddlers played with a tricycle on the dry grass of
their front yard. Just a block away is St. Matthew's church and
school, the voices of chil dren carrying over the traffic on Van
Buren.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, a man with a gun ran through St. Matthew's
schoolyard while students in green shirts and khaki pants roamed
about. Luckily, none was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when it's dark and difficult to see who's driv ing,
prostitutes using the school parking lot approach the car of Sister
Ginger Downey, who's been at the church for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough neighborhood,'' Downey said, ``but filled with
really wonderful people, many of whom have lived here for
generations. They deserve a safe place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure they do. Cleaning up a neighborhood is a down and dirty
business, though. Messy. Complicated. And tough to see with your
head in the clouds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
