<HEADLINE>
RIVAL SCOTTISH BANKS INCREASE BIDS FOR NATWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Bank of Scotland and the Royal Bank of Scotland
Group raised their bids for National Westminster Bank PLC on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The rival Scottish banks, both based in Edinburgh, are in a
heated bidding war for NatWest, a bank twice the size of either and
one that very much wants to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Bank raised its bid first, increasing it by 6 percent, to
22.8 billion pounds, or $36.8 billion at current rates of exchange.
The offer includes 1.6 billion pounds in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Bank said it would pay 0.968 share of its stock plus 4
pounds in cash _ a total of 14.26 pounds, or $23.03, for each share
of NatWest. It also offered an alternative deal that would give
NatWest shareholders 0.92 share of its stock plus 4.50 pounds in
cash and a dividend of 1 pound a share through 2003. The Royal Bank
said that arrangement was worth 14.96 pounds a share, or $24.16.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland showed its hand later, offering 24.1
billion pounds, or $38.9 billion. Its offer is for 14.41 pounds a
share, or $23.27, of which 3.56 pounds is in cash.
</P>
<P>
   While Royal Bank's offer is the lower of the two, the cash
component of its basic bid is 12 percent higher than that of the
Bank of Scotland bid. The cash component of the alternative bid is
nearly 27 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   Increased offers had been expected, and each Scottish bank
played down the other's move while trying to rally shareholder
support for its own bid. ``Our record of performance is
significantly better than RBOS','' said Peter Burt, chief executive
of the Bank of Scotland, adding that his company's ``management
strength and depth should now be conclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Goodwin, deputy group chief executive of Royal Bank, took
up the sparring. ``The cash element on offer from Royal Bank of
Scotland is significantly ahead of that of the Bank of Scotland,''
he said. ``This is significant, given the importance investors have
placed upon this component of the transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   With a midnight deadline Monday night for making final offers,
it is unclear which bank might win control of NatWest, or if the
London-based bank would be able to escape from the clutches of both
and remain independent. NatWest shareholders have until Feb. 14 to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both banks are running close to the wire,'' said John Tyce, an
analyst at SG Securities in London. Tyce said he thought that Royal
Bank would be the victor in the bidding war. ``Cash is what people
want,'' he said, alluding to Royal Bank's larger cash component.
``Equity is grossly out of fashion, especially in the banking
business.''
</P>
<P>
   For either Scottish bank to prevail, it would need votes
representing a majority of NatWest shares. Analysts noted that
Britain's Takeover Panel would be able to decide which bank would
control NatWest if neither suitor received enough support. Neither
Scottish bank can make another bid for NatWest for one year if it
does not receive a majority, unless NatWest pursues a friendly
merger with one of them, according to Takeover Panel regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of all three banks dropped Monday, as investors grew
bearish on the banking industry and on the value of a NatWest deal.
NatWest stock slumped 88 pence, or 6.9 percent, to 11.88 pounds,
the biggest one-day drop since Jan. 13, 1999. Bank of Scotland
shares dropped 40 pence, to 6.20 pounds, and the Royal Bank fell 58
pence, to 10.02 pounds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's funny how we've been praying for consolidation in the
banking sector for three years,'' Tyce said, ``and then the banks
get pummeled in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland is being advised by Credit Suisse First
Boston Europe and Morgan Stanley. Royal Bank is advised by Merrill
Lynch International, Goldman Sachs International and Noble
Grossart. NatWest's advisers are J.P. Morgan and Dresdner Kleinwort
Benson.
</P>
</TEXT>
