<HEADLINE>
THROWN FROM A NINE-STORY HIGH HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - It was perfectly clear to me as long as I was looking
at it through the ninth floor win dows of The Arizona Republic's
newsroom.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of Phoenix cops stopped a guy for not having a headlamp
on his bicycle and wound up shooting him three times in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Are you kiddin' me?
</P>
<P>
   From a vantage point high above the towers of St. Mary's
Basilica and only slightly below the roof of Bank One Ballpark, it
was a slam-dunk case of po lice brutality, of officers glee fully
using the traffic code to abuse unsuspecting citizens.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious, unequivocal, easy to write.
</P>
<P>
   If only I hadn't gotten the idi otic notion to take the elevator
to the ground floor, get in my car and drive to 22nd Avenue and
Monroe, where the incident happened.
</P>
<P>
   From the high-rise buildings of downtown, it's a short drive
west on Van Buren to 19th Ave nue, then south, then west on Monroe
over the railroad tracks and into the city's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called the St. Matthew's neighborhood,'' said Phoenix po
lice Sgt. Jeff Halstead. ``If you stand on the corner of 22nd Av
enue and Monroe, you'll find the problem. The houses are forti fied
like Alcatraz.''
</P>
<P>
   Stately old porches are cov ered in iron bars, like jail cells,
as are windows and doors. In recent years, a considerable part of
the local crack cocaine and prostitution businesses have moved into
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Residents asked the police for help, and they responded by
declaring the neighborhood a ``high-intensity'' patrol area.
</P>
<P>
   `'The officer's (who fought with the bicyclist) were on
high-intensity,'' Halstead said. ``Their job is to make contacts
and hopefully impact and improve the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Within these few square blocks, even a ridiculously mi nor
violation of the traffic code will get you stopped.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, police say the suspect, Mark William Meador, had
an outstanding warrant for failing to appear in a drug case. They
say he knocked down one officer and was trying to pull the
officer's weapon from him when the other officer fired.
</P>
<P>
   They say the second officer tried other options first, warn ing
Meador and fighting with him, but nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a man in ``serious'' condition in the hospital, the
rest of us get to ask why the po lice were there in the first
place, hassling people.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old neighborhood. Some longtime residents re member
friends displaced when I-17 was built. The incident with the
bicyclist happened not far from a house where, late last week, an
elderly woman spread laundry over the leafless shrubs on the side
of her house, each blouse like a blooming flower.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby two toddlers played with a tricycle on the dry grass of
their front yard. Just a block away is St. Matthew's church and
school, the voices of chil dren carrying over the traffic on Van
Buren.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, a man with a gun ran through St. Matthew's
schoolyard while students in green shirts and khaki pants roamed
about. Luckily, none was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when it's dark and difficult to see who's driv ing,
prostitutes using the school parking lot approach the car of Sister
Ginger Downey, who's been at the church for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough neighborhood,'' Downey said, ``but filled with
really wonderful people, many of whom have lived here for
generations. They deserve a safe place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure they do. Cleaning up a neighborhood is a down and dirty
business, though. Messy. Complicated. And tough to see with your
head in the clouds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
