<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     01-31 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WOODS' MISLEADING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tiger Woods tees off Thursday in the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am, he will be seeking his sixth consecutive victory
in a PGA Tour event. But it's misleading to think that, if he were
to win, he would be halfway to breaking Byron Nelson's record of 11
consecutive PGA Tour triumphs in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   What made Nelson's streak historic was not that he won 11
straight PGA Tour events, it was that he won 11 straight
tournaments that happened to be PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, in contrast, won four straight tournaments at the end of
the 1999 PGA. Tour season, then finished 6th and 10th,
respectively, in two non-PGA Tour events (the Johnnie Walker
Classic in Taiwan and the Williams World Challenge in Scottsdale,
Ariz.), before opening this year's PGA Tour with a playoff victory
over Ernie Els in the Mercedes Championship in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Woods' current winning streak is one, not five.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, the 24-year-old Woods has not boasted of the
streak or speculated on his chances of breaking Nelson's record.
When asked about it, he has talked about how a winning streak
should be considered only within the context of a calendar year,
not carried over from the previous year. He knows he didn't win in
Taiwan and Arizona even if the PGA Tour statisticians ignore those
events.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Nelson, who will be 88 on Friday, sounded almost in awe
of Woods' domination as the world's No. 1 golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger can win any tournament he's in, and if he breaks
my record I'll be the first to send him a letter of
congratulations; I'm very fond of him,'' Nelson said from his
Roanoke, Texas, ranch. ``As good as he is, he may get even better.
He's long and straight off the tee. He's a good 3-, 4- and 5-iron
player and he's a wonderful putter. He consistently reads the green
better than anyone I've ever seen, and he makes more long putts in
the clutch than anybody I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   But a winning streak in golf should be considered only within
the context of consecutive 72-hole tournaments, not merely
consecutive PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' streak in PGA Tour events began last August at the World
Golf Championships NEC Invitational in Akron, Ohio, followed by his
victories in the National Car Rental Classic in Orlando, Fla., the
Tour Championship in Houston and the American Express Championship
at Valderrama in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Woods' recent victory in Hawaii extended his streak
to five in PGA Tour events is technically accurate, but it's
deceptive in regard to Nelson's streak.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 consecutive tournament appearances from early March until
early August in 1945 (when there was no Masters and no U.S. Open
because of World War II), Nelson won every time. Now that's a
streak. The next best streak is Ben Hogan's six in a row in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Nelson won a record 18 PGA Tour events in 1945,
including three before the streak and four after it.
</P>
<P>
   In that era long before corporate sponsors of tournaments,
Nelson began his streak by teaming with Jug McSpaden in the Miami
Four-Ball, then won the Charlotte Open, Greensboro Open, Durham
Open, Atlanta Open, Montreal Open, Philadelphia Inquirer
Invitational, Chicago Victory Open, the PGA Championship over five
rounds of match play, the All-American Open at Tam O'Shanter and
the Canadian Open.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, that year's PGA Tour had almost a two-month
break between the Atlanta Open in early April and the Montreal Open
in early June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play in any tournaments during that break,'' Nelson
said. ``I was the club pro at Inverness in Toledo, Ohio, in those
years, and I went back there for those two months. I might've
played two or three 18-hole exhibitions in the Toledo area, but I
didn't play in any tournaments there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson did duel Sam Snead in late May in a medal play-match play
event at Fresh Meadow, then in Queens, N.Y., and at Essex County
Country Club in West Orange, N.J. But on overall score, 272 to 276,
he was considered to have won that event, too.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Woods' schedule, if he is to break Nelson's record,
he must continue to win at the AT&AMP;T, the Buick Invitational at
Torrey Pines near San Diego, the Nissan Los Angeles Open at
Riviera, the Andersen Consulting Match Play at La Costa, the Bay
Hill Invitational in Orlando, the Players Championship in Ponte
Vedra Beach, Fla., and the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   That seems too much to ask of any golfer, but it would surely be
something special: breaking the record at the Masters, where Byron
Nelson hits the ceremonial first tee shot. Then again, Tiger Woods
is really riding a streak of one, not five.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
