<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER-REAX-COX     01-31 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans, civic leaders respond to Rocker's suspension and fine
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For weeks, the Atlanta Braves community has stood
nearly mute while John Rocker's fate rested in Bud Selig's office.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's one month suspension finally loosened some opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Brian Jordan, who a month ago suggested the Braves
closer be traded, sounds as if he has turned the other cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time has passed, you see there is a chance for
forgiveness,'' Jordan said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   From his home in El Centro, Calif., reliever pitcher Rudy Seanez
said, ``I guess you could say I do feel for (Rocker). But heck, I
don't know. Everything he's gone through, that's a lot of stuff. To
have this (suspension) on top of it is quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher John Smoltz had reserved comment until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people that reacted right away, it was like,
'there's a problem...get rid of it. Don't want to deal with it,' ``
Smoltz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not perfect and I'm not the person that should determine
anyone's fate,'' Smoltz said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the organization, opinion was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Lowery, former president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, said the action is good, but not enough,
while the Rev. Hosea Williams denounced what he described as the
crucifixion of the Braves relief pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Lowery, who has taken part in demonstrations urging Braves team
officials to punish Rocker _ up to and including his dismissal from
the team _ applauded the action by Major League Baseball's
Commissioner Selig.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the commissioner's office is concerned, this is a
good step. They mean to be fair,'' Lowery said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said enough is more than enough in the case of Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jesus could forgive ... his hanging on Calvary, if Martin
Luther King Jr. could forgive the Ku Klux Klan and other racist
advocates in this country for their exploitation of our people, why
in the hell can't we forgive this young man?'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he said was wrong, but he is willing to apologize
and ask for forgiveness. I think crucifying him will just make him
more bitter. I can't believe, in particular, that religious and
civil rights leaders are saying crucify him, crucify him.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Doug Payne and Carroll Rogers contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
