<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-OXYGEN-SIDE-COX     01-31 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGEN-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oxygen aims to be breath of fresh air on cable, Net
 &HT;    (EDS: MOVING TO (f) Financial and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Geraldine Laybourne thinks she knows what women really
want from their televisions and computers _ and she's gambling
hundreds of millions of dollars that her instincts are right.
</P>
<P>
   Laybourne's bet begins Wednesday, when the 52-year-old veteran
programmer launches her new Oxygen channel. It will feature _ on
air and online _ women chatting in ``Pajamas,'' learning how to
surf the Internet with Oprah Winfrey and cartoon superheroes saving
women from failing relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to lure women as a group is not new to television. Many
have tried, few have succeeded. What distinguishes Oxygen is the
level to which it harnesses television to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen will simultaneously broadcast shows online and on air,
and the Web site offers a heightened interactivity, with women
sharing with one another on such intimate subjects as divorce and
child-rearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are neither a cable TV channel nor a group of Web sites,''
said Tom Werner, who, with his wife, Marcey Carsey, heads Oxygen's
programming efforts. ``Hopefully the two add up to something better
than each of them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a big if, even to some fans of Laybourne, who built the
Nickelodeon children's channel into a television powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerry has a very good ear for what people want and she has a
track record of success,'' said Marianne Paskowski, editor in chief
of industry trade journal Multichannel News. ``However, Oxygen is a
very, very risky thing.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be a long shot, Oxygen has already earned one notch
on its belt: a whole lot of press.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about Oxygen is that it must be the most hyped new
channel of all time,'' said Bruce Leichtman, a media analyst at
Boston-based industry consultant The Yankee Group. ``Come on,
Oxygen's only launching with 10 million subscribers. Does it really
deserve all this attention?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten million subscribers is not nearly enough to make Oxygen a
success. The industry's rule of thumb is that channels need at
least 30 million subscribers to break even.
</P>
<P>
   The top cable TV channels, such as Turner Broadcasting's TNT,
have 70 million-plus subscribers. Oxygen's chief competition and
the undisputed queen of the women's channels, Lifetime, goes into
75 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Laybourne has said she expects to have 50 million subscribers
within five years, but is currently having a difficult time
breaking into the crowded cable landscape. There are some huge
markets, like New York City and parts of Los Angeles, that won't be
seeing any Oxygen for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping a prized market
</P>
<P>
   What television executives like about women is that they watch
the most television. On average, women watch 4.5 hours a day, or 40
minutes more than men. That's according to surveys by ratings giant
Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, Nielsen's research shows that women control
the shopping in most households. They buy up to 85 percent of all
goods, including 66 percent of all cars.
</P>
<P>
   Women as a group are also growing increasingly interested in the
Internet. Nielsen's research shows about 30 percent of them are now
using the Internet, but that figure will reach 50 percent in the
next three years. Women will surpass Internet usage by men in that
time frame, according to the projections.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder television and Internet executives are trying to win
the loyalty of women. Yet most of their efforts have failed, says
Laybourne, because their shows spoke at women rather than with
them. That's a mistake she doesn't intend to repeat. And she
intends to use the Internet, with its built-in interactivity, to
get and keep women viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Laybourne says her shows will be driven by ``girl power.'' That
is, they'll listen to what women want (for example, through chat
rooms on the Web site) and then tell them how to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want feedback,'' Laybourne told the New York Times. ''We
want audiences to be as involved in the creation of Oxygen as we
can get them.''
</P>
<P>
   For women who want to get online, for example, there'll be
Winfrey's Internet lessons. The show will coddle and empathize with
struggling Web novices.
</P>
<P>
   And those who just want to kvetch, there's ``Pajama Talk,'' a
late-night talk show featuring guests and hosts in PJs. The Web
sites are open in the same way for women to talk to each other and
to Oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of what Laybourne sees as what's special about the
Internet. She believes that the Web's interactivity _ talking in
real time to other women anywhere, anytime _ offers the kind of
intimacy that women crave.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy hitters back network
</P>
<P>
   It may be short on initial subscribers, but the channel, based
in an old cookie factory in New York, is long on talent,
influential partners and money.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen's financial partners include such heavyweights as
investment bank Morgan Stanley and America Online, which traded
three Web sites for a stake in the channel.
</P>
<P>
   With the likes of AOL, Laybourne has raised $200 million in
capital. She expects to raise $450 million to spend on programming,
an amazing amount for a TV start-up.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Laybourne has used her capital to do something new for
the cable TV industry: She's airing all new shows.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a new channel airs reruns and then slowly adds
original programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxygen is more of a service brand than a competitive
programming service,'' Caryn Mandabach, president of the
Carsey-Werner Co. and a partner in Oxygen, told the Los Angeles
Times. ``What we play at 8 p.m. should be very different to get
women's attention in a very important, immediate way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing something very fresh and modern,'' said Werner.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh, yes, but on the cheap. Its lineup will feature talk
shows, news shows, self-help shows and cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been good our whole lives in casting talent,'' said
Werner, who has been involved in the creation of such shows as
``Roseanne,'' ``Cosby'' and ``Third Rock From the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of new talent on Oxygen who are terrific
performers,'' Werner said.
</P>
<P>
   Werner plans to sprinkle in some big names. Winfrey is one;
another is Candice Bergen, who will host a talk show called
``Exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   The programming strategy is also new. Rather than building its
schedule around a handful of hits, Oxygen will break the day into
lifestyle segments catering to specific groups of women viewers
likely to watch at a particular time.
</P>
<P>
   For example, weekday afternoons will feature shows designed to
attract teenage girls home from school.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that has the industry shaking its collective
head, Laybourne has said Oxygen will not be hit-driven. In other
words, the channel will not look to establish itself with one show,
the way Comedy Central did with ``South Park,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   Old strategy, new game
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Laybourne's strategy at Oxygen is an old move on a
new chess board. It mirrors the tactics she used to turn
Nickelodeon into one of cable's largest channels, with some 70
million-plus subscribers and $8 billion in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Laybourne came to Nickelodeon in the early 1980s with a master's
degree in elementary education from the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   What drew her to television was a strong belief that the medium
was failing children. She wanted to create shows that celebrated
children, in all their quirks and anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   In her 16-year tenure at Nickelodeon, Laybourne aired shows such
as ``Rugrats,'' a cartoon in which kids have real fears, do bad
things and learn hard lessons _ all with a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   When the Internet began to become popular, she skillfully
integrated it with Nickelodeon's programming. Nickelodeon garnered
viewer feedback from kids and used that to design new shows and
promote current ones.
</P>
<P>
   Can Laybourne repeat Nickelodeon's success with young people
with a channel for women? Schwartz, for one, thinks so. One reason:
If Laybourne can successfully plumb a niche audience of women
through both the Internet and television, Oxygen may need fewer
subscribers to become successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small niches with good demographics can be profitable,'' said
Jeremy Schwartz, senior analyst at media consultant Forrester
Research.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some experts see the Internet as the key to Oxygen's
success. Hook a woman on a Web site branded Oxygen, and she might
check the programming on the channel of the same name _ or vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving that goal is easier said than done. While most TV
channels have Web sites and are posting content online, few are
doing it well. The person or company that figures out how to do it
right will probably win big.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Holy Grail of media,'' said Schwartz. ``The trick is
to create a rich, immersive experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning a commanding position in even a small market won't be
easy. There are already several entrenched players vying for the
loyalty of women.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there's Lifetime. It has been calling itself a
women's channel for the past 15 years. After struggling through
most of its history, Lifetime has finally hit pay dirt. With 75
million-plus subscribers, the channel ranked number one among
advertisers in delivering women viewers.
</P>
<P>
   There's also strong competition on the Net. Sites such as
iVillage, CyberGrrl, Women.com and HomeArts all cater to women and
have attracted a following. Pioneer iVillage alone has some 3
million unique visitors a month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stiff competition, no one is counting Laybourne out.
Her track record, connections and ear for popular programming are
just too strong.
</P>
<P>
   Said media analyst Leichtman: ``Laybourne has done a great job
of generating attention. Now the question is, can she generate the
eyeballs?''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
