<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PG&AMP;E Hit For Words On Judge  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
With the California Public Utilities Commission slated to vote this
week on a multimillion-dollar rate increase for Pacific Gas and
Electric Co., the debate took an unexpected turn yesterday as the
head of the PUC reprimanded the utility for making ``unfounded''
and ``inflammatory'' charges against the judge overseeing the
matter.
<P>
   Commission President Richard Bilas cited a November statement
from PG&AMP;E that Judge Mark Wetzell's proposed $243 million rate
increase is ``short on evidentiary analysis and long on fundamental
bias.''
</P>
<P>
   The utility is seeking an increase of $822 million. It has
warned that as many as 3,500 workers could get the ax and that tree
trimming around electrical lines could be reduced if it fails to
get close to this amount.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement yesterday, Bilas called PG&AMP;E's charges against
Wetzell ``serious and untimely,'' and said they ``typify a
breakdown in the civility of the adjudicatory process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E's comments demonstrate a lack of respect for our
regulatory process, diminish the process and distract the parties
and decision-makers from the overall merits of the proceeding,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the rate increase is scheduled for Thursday. It will
come after months of frequently acrimonious debate between PG&AMP;E and
consumer and industry groups over the size of the increase.
</P>
<P>
   While Bilas' reprimand imposes no penalty on the utility, it may
influence commissioners ahead of their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly hope the other commissioners will look at the
sanction order before the vote,'' said Mindy Spatt, a spokeswoman
for The Utility Reform Network, a San Francisco consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   She said PG&AMP;E ``had no legal argument'' in addressing the
judge's proposed increase. ``They were reduced to making
accusations instead.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, PG&AMP;E said its words have been misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fundamental misunderstanding of what the company
said,'' insisted Ronald Low, a PG&AMP;E spokesman. ``We never intended
the comments to be a personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said PG&AMP;E intended its remarks to be a ``critique''
of the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC has two proposals on the table. On the one hand, the
five commissioners will pass judgment on Wetzell's proposed
$243-million rate increase. On the other, they will consider an
alternative increase of about $400 million offered last month by
Commissioner Carl Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Wood presented his own rate plan because he said Wetzell's
proposal ``has cut too deeply into muscle and bone.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Bilas said PG&AMP;E's November statements ``exceed
the bounds of professional courtesy to be accorded to the
commission, commission staff and fellow advocates.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear why Bilas waited until the week of the PUC's vote
on the matter to issue his reprimand. He could not be reached for
comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
