<HEADER>
A2422 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SUPERBOWL-SUPERBOWL_S     01-31 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-SUPERBOWL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Dot-Com Companies Score During Super Bowl With TV Ads  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Despite some technical glitches, dot-com companies were declaring
victory yesterday following their first widespread appearance
during the holy grail of advertising.
<P>
   A total of 17 online firms _ almost half of the 38 Super Bowl
advertisers _ shelled out an average of $2.2 million for a
30-second ad during ABC's telecast of the four-hour contest between
the St. Louis Rams and Tennessee Titans. Only two dot-com ads
(three if you count Victoria's Secret promotion for its Web fashion
show) aired during last year's game.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been hard for consumers to differentiate among the
various Internet companies such as Monster.com, Kforce.com,
Lifeminders.com and Agillion.com, let alone figure out what herding
cats or cheerleaders had to do with cyberspace. Still, the firms
behind the ads were practically gleeful Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   OurBeginnings.com, an online stationery supplier in Orlando,
Fla., said traffic to its site increased 550 percent, and sales
were up about 400 percent following the airing of its ``Angry
Brides'' spot, which showed a group of violent brides-to-be
fighting over a limited number of invitation styles in a
traditional brick-and-mortar store.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, and additional servers to handle the extra
traffic, cost the 20-person company a cool $4 million. But
OurBeginnings.com's chief executive said it was money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't be happier,'' said Michael Budowski. ``We had a
lot of experts criticize spending that kind of money on one event;
they thought it should be more spread out over prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   OurBeginnings wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   According to PC Data Online, a Reston, Va., Internet researcher,
most dot-coms saw a spike in the number of visitors just after
their ads ran. The increases ranged from 15 to 541 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that advertising during the Super Bowl
helped drive traffic to these dot-coms _ especially those trying to
establish a name or a brand,'' PC Data analyst Jeff Moulton said in
a statement. ``The real question is whether these sites can sustain
these traffic volumes throughout the remainder of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   PC Data tracked the number of unique home Internet users that
came to each site preceding and after the game on Sunday. A
proprietary software tool allows the firm to measure visitors and
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com built on the success it had with last year's Super
Bowl ad, which featured children making world-weary comments about
their future careers, such as, ``I want to be forced into early
retirement'' and ``I want to file all day.'' Its ad this year was a
black and white spot featuring city dwellers reciting a Robert
Frost poem.
</P>
<P>
   Although it didn't grab many accolades in post-game polls, the
spot garnered Monster.com an 80 percent gain in traffic, according
to PC Data Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the amazing thing about the Super Bowl; it's really the
Ad Bowl,'' said Monster.com's chief executive Jeff Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   After its ad featuring boxer Muhammad Ali ran, WebMD enjoyed the
highest number of visitors it's ever had in one 24-hour period,
according to Reggie Bradford, WebMD's chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, it was a home run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some Super Bowl advertisers actually saw
decreases in post-game Web activity. Pets.com, which sells
aquariums, leashes and other pet paraphernalia, saw its visitors
fall 5 percent; and Lifeminders.com, which sends people customized
information via e-mail, dropped 13 percent, according to PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites also experienced technical glitches, perhaps from a
spike in usage.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites for nine of the 38 Super Bowl advertisers had some
kind of performance problem in terms of page download times,
according to Keynote Systems, a San Mateo firm that measures
Internet performance. Keynote said five of the nine offenders were
dot-coms: AutoTrader.com, Computer.com, Epidemic.com, Kforce.com
and Lastminutetravel.com. The other companies experiencing problems
were Pizza Hut, Universal Pictures, Motorola and Oxygen Media.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Shklar, a researcher at Keynote, said both Autotrader and
Lastminutetravel suffered a major increase in the amount of time it
took to download their home pages. Autotrader went from 6 seconds
to 28; Lastminutetravel, from 5.5 seconds to 62 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   And Shklar said one site, Denver's Epidemic.com, was completely
inaccessible around 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Although Keynote doesn't measure the number of visitors to each
site, Shklar says the glitches were almost certainly related to a
spike in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web sites that have done well either didn't have
significant traffic or they've had lots of experience with traffic
surges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
