 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Writing Off Deadbeat's Bad Debt 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I am a self-employed consultant using the cash accounting
method. One of my clients hasn't paid for the services I provided.
The client has ignored all my efforts to collect the debt. Am I
permitted to deduct the amount of the debt from my taxable income?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: You should be able to claim a bad-debt deduction, says
Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller. But you must be
able to demonstrate that you took ``reasonable steps'' to collect
the money.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it would help your case if you hired a lawyer or
collection agency to go after the debtor. But the IRS doesn't
necessarily expect you to go to that extra expense if the amount
you are owed is small, or if your business isn't prosperous enough
to afford such measures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: I bought 80 shares of Compaq stock in January 1999 at $41
each, and 40 shares in April 1999 _ after the stock plummeted _ at
$24 each. Later in the year, I sold 40 shares at $25 each and 40
more at $22, leaving me with 40 shares at present. How do I figure
my capital gain or loss?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: It depends on whether you told your broker exactly which
shares you were selling at the time you placed your sell orders. If
you did, then you would subtract the purchase price of those
particular shares from the selling price.
</P>
<P>
   However, the mere fact that you posed your question suggests
that you did not tell your broker which shares you were selling.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the Internal Revenue Service insists that you
account for the sales on a first-in, first-out basis. That means
the 80 shares you sold would be the first 80 you bought _ the ones
you got in January at $41 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   So, you would have a capital loss of $1,400 _ the $1,880
proceeds minus the $3,280 you paid _ before commissions and fees.
In addition, you can increase the loss total by any commissions and
fees you paid on both the purchase and sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a Schlumberger shareholder. I received shares of a
spin-off company called Transocean Sedco Forex at the end of 1999.
Do I need to declare these shares as a dividend or capital gain for
1999 and pay taxes on them? If not, how do I figure my cost basis
on them for tax purposes, both the date and the amount, in case I
ever decide to sell them?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: According to Schlumberger's investor relations
department, the company's shareholders received 0.1936 Transocean
shares for every share of Schlumberger they owned. Because that
multiplier is irregular, probably most shareholders were entitled
to a fractional share of Transocean in addition to full shares.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger's lawyers say that the full shares are not subject
to any tax for 1999. However, to qualify for tax-free treatment you
must enclose a notice of the transaction with your 1999 tax return.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger sent shareholders a form to be signed, dated and
filed with their tax returns. If you didn't receive one, telephone
the company's investor relations department at (212) 350-9432, or
send a letter to 277 Park Avenue; New York, NY 10172.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the fractional shares, there are immediate tax
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The fractional shares were not delivered to the shareholders.
Instead, the company pooled them, sold them on the open market, and
sent the cash proceeds to the shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The gain or loss on the fractional shares must be reported on
your tax return.
</P>
<P>
   I'll come back to that in a moment, because first I have to
explain how to figure the cost basis on your Transocean shares, and
how to revise the cost basis of your Schlumberger shares.
</P>
<P>
   To determine the cost basis for the Transocean shares _
including the fraction _ take the cost basis of your Schlumberger
shares and multiply by 0.10508.
</P>
<P>
   The Transocean purchase date, for tax purposes, is the same date
on which you bought your Schlumberger shares.
</P>
<P>
   The new cost basis for your Schlumberger shares will be the old
cost basis multiplied by 0.89492.
</P>
<P>
   Your cost basis for a fractional Transocean share can be
calculated by multiplying the cost basis for all your Transocean
shares by 0.0186. If you got more than that in cash, then you have
a capital gain; if you got less, then you have a capital loss.
</P>
<P>
   After you figure the cost basis for the fractional share, you
should subtract the result from your total Transocean cost basis.
The result will be the cost basis of your remaining, full shares of
Transocean.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly held companies are required to relay this sort of
information to their shareholders. The moral of the story: It is up
to the shareholders to give company mailings their full and careful
attention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
