<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2424 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ORDERFLOW-ORDERFLOW_S     01-31 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORDERFLOW-ORDERFLOW </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 SEC Fears Activities of Market Makers  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Placing a trade with your broker may seem quick and simple. You
make a phone call, or click a computer mouse, and seconds later you
receive confirmation that the transaction has been completed.
<P>
   Quick it is, thanks to the miracle of electronics _ but simple
it's not. There is a lot of hidden activity going on behind the
scenes _ and the Securities and Exchange Commission worries that it
could be costing you extra money.
</P>
<P>
   In filling your order, your broker will route it to an
independent trading firm that holds the stock in its inventory and
provides liquidity to investors while trading for its own profit.
</P>
<P>
   These market makers compete vigorously to process trades placed
by brokerage customers, because most of the trades they handle
produce a quick, sure profit.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they are so eager to get these orders that they
typically pay the brokers a fee of about $2 per 1,000 shares traded
_ a procedure known in the industry as ``payment for order flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Order-flow payments also add up to big money for brokers.
E-Trade Group received $39 million in order-flow payments during
its 1999 fiscal year, or 11 percent of total revenues. Ameritrade
got $22.1 million in payments, or 8 percent of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC dislikes payment for order flow. It contends that the
practice can breed conflicts of interest, causing brokers to send
orders to market makers that don't necessarily execute them
efficiently and impartially, at the best possible price for the
customers.
</P>
<P>
   If a customer loses one-sixteenth one-16th  &LR; of a point per share
_ 6.25 cents _ because of a faulty execution, that adds up to
$62.50 on a 1,000-share trade. The customer may be paying, say, a
$15 brokerage commission, but the hidden cost from getting a bad
stock price is several times greater than that.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has stopped short of banning payment for order flow,
evidently because it is nearly impossible to prove that market
makers are negligent.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Luparello, senior vice president for market regulation
with the National Association of Securities Dealers, the parent of
the Nasdaq market, says he and his colleagues check on member firms
from time to time to determine whether they ``ensure the quality of
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the NASD hasn't found enough evidence to bring
disciplinary actions against any firms for poor executions.
However, it has cited a couple of small firms for not adequately
documenting their trading procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Market makers prefer to get market orders from the brokers _
orders to buy or sell a stock at the current market price _ rather
than limit orders, in which the investor specifies a minimum
selling price or a maximum buying price.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, market makers generally don't pay brokers for limit
orders.
</P>
<P>
   That's because with market orders, it is easier for the market
makers to play the spread _ the difference between the best current
bid (buying) and ask (selling) prices. The bid-asked prices
sometimes can vary slightly from one market maker to another, but
in general they are quite close.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, that the bid price for Microsoft stock is
$98 per share and the ask price is $98.0625. If you place a market
order to sell 1,000 shares, the market maker will take them off
your hands for $98 apiece and can immediately sell them to someone
else for $98.0625, for a quick $62.50 profit.
</P>
<P>
   With a limit order, the seller might specify a minimum selling
price of $98.25. This would cramp the market maker's style, because
the trade can't be completed unless Microsoft moves up from current
levels. If there is no trade, there is no profit.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal of market makers to pay for limit orders is
reflected in the commission schedules of some brokerage firms. The
broker, not receiving any payment from market makers for limit
orders, compensates by charging its customers more to place such
orders.
</P>
<P>
   For example, E-Trade Group, the Palo Alto -based  &LR; online
discount broker, charges its customers as little as $14.95 to place
a market order _ which it can sell to a market maker _ but $19.95
to place a limit order, which probably cannot be sold.
</P>
<P>
   SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt has repeatedly expressed his distaste
for order-flow payments, most recently in a stern speech last
November to the Securities Industry Association, whose members
include all the leading brokers.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, Levitt asked: ``Are conflicts in the order
routing and execution process diluting the natural forces of
competition in our markets?''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Levitt posed this as a question, rather than a
conclusion, underscores the fact that it is hard to prove his
point.
</P>
<P>
   Market makers and brokers insist that there are no abuses _ or
hardly any.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Pasternack, chief executive of Knight Securities in New
Jersey, one of the leading market - &LR; makers for Nasdaq stocks, says
that most of the trades his firm handles are matched
``algorithmically _ with a black box,'' without human intervention.
That, he says, ensures fairness and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Pasternack adds that the brokers he deals with are deeply
concerned about getting good prices for their customers. In fact,
they make good execution a condition for doing business with the
market makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come in here and negotiate an industry-best execution
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Griffin, a spokesman for Fidelity Investments, one of the
leading discount brokers, says his firm receives payment for order
flow, but he won't say how much.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that the payments don't influence Fidelity's
decisions about where to route orders _ that the orders are sent to
the firms that appear to provide the best execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never will sacrifice quality of execution,'' he says.
remarks.  &LR; ``We're always searching for the best execution for our
clients' trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Marta von Loewenfeldt, a spokeswoman for Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.,
says that her firm accepts payments for order flow, but that
``execution quality is what drives the routing of orders.''
</P>
<P>
   James Spellman, a spokesman for the Securities Industry
Association, says that customers who suspect that they got an
inferior execution on a stock trade should complain to their
broker, the NASD and the New York Stock Exchange. ``Brokers have an
obligation to do right by their customers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Do your best to document your complaint, he says. For example,
you should ask your broker to provide a list of the prices at which
the stock traded just before and just after your order was
transacted.
</P>
<P>
   However, Spellman notes that the best order execution doesn't
necessarily equate to the best price.
</P>
<P>
   Also involved are ``speed, accuracy, and a reasonable certainty
that the trade will happen within the time frame you would like it
to happen,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt conceded as much in his speech to the SIA, S.I.A., &LR;   &LR; but
he warned: ``In any case, the quality of execution must always be
viewed from the customer's perspective, not the firm's.''
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that Levitt's jawboning is having some
effect on industry practice.
</P>
<P>
   Datek Online, one of the leading online brokers, announced this
month that it will begin rebating all payments for order flow to
its customers. If a market maker sends Datek $2 for your trade, the
full $2 will wind up in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree with Chairman Levitt,'' says Mike Dunn, a Datek
spokesman. ``We didn't want to give the impression that we had any
conflicts. The potential is there _ there's an inherent conflict of
interest in the payment-for-order-flow system.''
</P>
<P>
   Payment for order flow could diminish considerably once the U.S.
markets make their planned conversion from fractional prices to the
decimal system. (Decimal pricing has been the rule for many years
in most foreign markets.)
</P>
<P>
   The decimal system could shrink the spreads on many stocks,
making order-flow payments less generous.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the minimum spread on the most actively traded
issues is 6.25 cents, or one-sixteenth 1/16  &LR; of a point. In many
cases, once it is allowed, the spreads could shrink to just 1 cent
under the decimal system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the SEC released details of its previously announced
decimalization plan, decreeing that the markets must begin quoting
stock prices in decimals no later than July 3.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, the minimum price increments for most stocks will
be reduced to 5 cents _ slightly less than today's basic increment
of 6.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   However, the SEC also demanded that the markets launch a pilot
program in which some heavily traded stocks will be priced in
1-cent increments.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers say that if market makers eventually are
unable to make more than a penny a share playing the spread,
order-flow payments are bound to decrease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
