u a BC-HOMELESS-CHILDREN-NYT     01-31 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-CHILDREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DOCUMENTS HOMELESSNESS IN AMERICAN CHILDREN EACH YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About 1.35 million children in the United States,
nearly 2 percent of the total number of children and nearly 10
percent of poor children, are likely to experience at least one
episode of homelessness over a year, a new analysis of national
census and survey data being presented Tuesday has found.
</P>
<P>
   The children are among an estimated 3.5 million people
nationally who become homeless at least once in the course of a
year, according to the analysis by the Urban institute, a
Washington research group. The work was done by the team that
prepared a recent federal report on homelessness released last
month by the secretary of housing and urban development, Andrew M.
Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 percent more Americans had an episode of homelessness
annually in 1996, during a sustained economic boom, than in 1987,
the institute found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been homeless as a child is a predictor of being
homeless as an adult, so you're building the next generation here
to an alarming extent,'' Martha Burt, director of social service
research at the institute, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, at the time of the previous national survey, Ms. Burt
estimates that about 1.8 million people became homeless at some
point in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are doing well are pushing the price of housing
up and taking over more space, and they're doing that all over the
country,'' she said to explain the rise.
</P>
<P>
   The national report found deep poverty and illness among the
homeless served in shelters and soup kitchens, though almost half
were in their first episode of homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   The new projections are consistent with studies based on several
years of complete, computerized shelter data in New York and
Philadelphia, and with more recent data in eight other metropolitan
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis P. Culhane, a professor of social welfare policy at the
University of Pennsylvania, said shelter data show that 1 percent
of the population in New York and Philadelphia uses a homeless
shelter for some period each year, with the rate about 10 times
higher among young poor children and highest among poor African
American children under 5.
</P>
<P>
   Most poor families, Culhane added, are paying 60 percent and 70
percent of their income on rent, twice what it was 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Burt said the impact of homelessness may be longlasting.
About 21 percent of homeless adults experienced homelessness as
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
