u a BC-ALASKA-AIRCRASH-NYT &LR;      01-31 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRCRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JET WITH 70 ON BOARD CRASHES OFF CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An Alaska Airlines jetliner bound from Mexico to
San Francisco crashed into the Pacific Ocean northwest of Malibu on
Monday afternoon with 70 people aboard, after reporting mechanical
difficulties. Coast Guard boats, rescue helicopters and a Navy
search plane scoured the choppy waters for several hours into the
winter twilight, and found several bodies, but no survivors so far,
the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The jet, an MD-83 headed from the Mexican beach resort of Puerto
Vallarta, had reported mechanical difficulties and requested
permission to land at Los Angeles International Airport, Ron
Wilson, a spokesman for San Francisco International Airport said,
according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   But at about 3:45 p.m., the plane, Flight 261, was reported down
in the ocean off the Naval Air Station at Point Mugu, according to
Mitch Barker, a regional spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all we know at the moment,'' Barker said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson reported that radar indicated that the plane fell from
17,000 feet and then was lost from radar screens. FAA officials
said there were 65 passengers and five crew members aboard. Skies
were clear at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The plane came down about 20 miles northwest of Los Angeles
International Airport, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell, local television stations offered live coverage
of search helicopters hovering over scattered pieces of debris and
a spreading fuel slick on the deep blue water about 12 miles
offshore, where water temperatures are typically in the low 50s at
this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   As temperatures cooled, and searchlights played across the 10-
to 12-foot swells, fog began to roll into the area between the
California coast and the Channel Islands, complicating search
efforts, which drew Coast Guard craft from as far away as San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In the early evening the Coast Guard ordered private craft that
had sailed into the area to stay away from the debris field, to
prevent confusion in search and rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 261 is a seven-day-a-week flight from Puerto Vallarta to
San Francisco. It is scheduled to leave at 3:30 p.m. and arrive at
5:05. The plane that usually flies the route is an MD-80 or an
updated model like the MD-82, which has two engines attached to the
fuselage near the tail. The models first entered service in 1980,
and depending on configuration, usually carry 144 to 152
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-83, a two-engine craft with engines on the tail, is the
successor to the McDonnell-Douglas DC-9, and like the Boeing 737 is
frequently used on midrange flights. The jet was built less than
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines has built a successful business and a strong
safety record operating north-south routes that serve more than 40
cities in Canada, Alaska, Mexico and states up and down the Pacific
Coast. The downed flight was to have stopped in San Francisco and
continued to Seattle, the carrier's corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The airline had two fatal accidents in the 1970s, both in
Alaska, according to Airsafe.com, a Web site that tracks plane
crashes. In 1971 an Alaska Airlines Boeing 727 approaching Juneau
crashed into a mountain slope after the crew had received
misleading navigational information. All 104 passengers and seven
crew members were killed. In 1976 one passenger was killed when a
727 overran a runway in Ketchikan.
</P>
<P>
   The crash is the first for a commercial airline involving
fatalities since an American Airlines MD-82 crashed in Little Rock,
Ark., last June 1, killing 11 people including the pilot, as the
pilot attempted to land in a heavy storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2229EST &QL; 
