<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-HNS &LR;      01-31 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ It's probably going to be awhile before Rams quarterback
Kurt Warner can fully digest the incredible changes in his life.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a guy who only last summer was simply hoping to make the
St. Louis roster. Now, less than six months later, he's heading to
the Pro Bowl with a league Most Valuable Player trophy, a Super
Bowl MVP trophy and a Super Bowl ring on the way.
</P>
<P>
   And while team achievements always mean more than the personal
ones, Warner reached some on his own that were much loftier than he
could have dreamed of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has dawned on me that we won the Super Bowl and
that I am going to have a ring,'' Warner said Monday morning.
``Obviously, that is what we all play for. That is the goal, and it
is great to have achieved it at this point in time. There have been
some great ones that have gone to it, but took them awhile to do
it. I am fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   John Elway didn't earn a champion's ring until his final two
seasons in the league. Dan Marino still doesn't have one. Warner
got one during his first season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Former Raiders defensive end) Howie Long came in and talked
and said he got a ring (early in his career) and thought that he
would be there every year, and he never got back there,'' Warner
said. ``So I think we realize how fortunate we were, and it is
great to get that one under our belt. But hopefully, we have got a
lot more in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was an exciting night for the quarterback who set a Super
Bowl record with 414 yards passing in the Rams' 23-16 victory over
the Tennessee Titans. He didn't get much sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a wink,'' Warner said. ``It was all right. I've got plenty
of time to catch up before minicamp starts.''
</P>
<P>
   There won't be much else for the Rams to do in the offseason.
They've gone through so many personnel changes since coach Dick
Vermeil took over three years ago that most of the players are
signed for a while. Among the starters, only cornerback Todd Lyght,
center Mike Gruttaduaria, offensive tackle Fred Miller and tight
end Ernie Conwell will become unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   But with a team that only looks to get better, Warner said the
Rams have the best bargaining tool when it comes time to sign free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the same thing: Get another ring,'' Warner said of his
team's new goal. ``I don't know if there is any other way to do it
better than we did it this year than to be able to repeat next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question is whether Vermeil will return. He has
already said he will turn the reins over to offensive coordinator
Mike Martz when his contract expires in two years. There has been
speculation, however, that Vermeil could step down now, having won
a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil has said he will give it some thought, but he has not
indicated which way he is leaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is much better to be talking about that than to be
answering the questions about getting fired, which I have done for
two years,'' said Vermeil, who retired once before and was out of
coaching for 14 years before returning to guide the Rams. ``And I
didn't give those questions much thought, and I haven't given
(retirement) much thought. I mean that sincerely. Right now, the
only thing on my mind is to get home and enjoy this experience with
my organization and football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil accomplished something close to a miracle, taking a team
that finished 4-12 one year ago and turning it into a Super Bowl
champion. His Rams went 13-3 in the regular season, then swept
Minnesota, Tampa Bay and Tennessee to win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I wrote a legacy, guys,'' Vermeil said.
``Coaching football is not like putting a man on Mars. The only
time I shed tears was when my brother said, `Our mother (was
right). She said you would go back and coach a Super Bowl-winning
team before you quit, and God was she right.' I didn't think she
was, but she was.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
