<HEADLINE>
RAMS MANAGEMENT REMAINS CHEAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  ATLANTA _ Since the St. Louis Rams are the second-youngest
team in the NFL, it wasn't surprising Monday that the main topic of
the new Super Bowl champions was their future.
</P>
<P>
   No one was talking dynasty, but two men who played vital roles
in the Rams becoming world champions, Dick Vermeil and Kurt Warner,
said the team should be a formidable presence for several more
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be able to keep this team together,'' said
Vermeil, who could lose three starters, Pro Bowl cornerback Todd
Lyght and offensive linemen Fred Miller and Mike Gruttadauria,
through free agency. ``I'm confident that, if the dollars and cents
are close in contract negotiations, our players will decide to
remain with the Rams. I'm confident that the leadership we've given
these players will make it hard for them to want to go play for
another team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can keep this together a long time,'' Warner said at the
early-morning press conference at the Hyatt Regency. ``The guys on
this team have developed a tremendous camaraderie and like playing
with one another. I just don't see this team breaking apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite Vermeil reciting the party line about the
contract-negotiating virtues and salary-cap prowess of Rams
executives John Shaw and Jay Zygmunt, there are no guarantees St.
Louis will remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the Dallas Cowboys and Green Bay Packers
were shredded after stirring Super Bowl triumphs by the loss of
talented free agents.
</P>
<P>
   It's known that Lyght, who earned $3.4 million this season, is
looking for $5 million, which the Rams might be unwilling to give
to a player who will turn 31 in nine days.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams actually have to watch their salary cap P's and Q's
now. That never was the case when they were ensconced in Anaheim
and the Shaw-Zygmunt Tag Team routinely bludgeoned players with
below-market contracts and the club's payroll annually ranked among
the league's lowest.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams have dramatically altered their fiscal policies since
moving to St. Louis and are reaping the enormous profits from the
taxpayer-subsidized $300 million Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   They are committed to giving Marshall Faulk $49 million through
2005 _ ``We kind of mortgaged our future slightly on that one,''
said Vermeil _ and there is three years left on Trent Green's $18
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams now will attempt to trade Green, but will they be able
to find a team with a flexible enough salary cap?
</P>
<P>
   The Rams also realize they're going to have to tear up Kurt
Warner's puny contract _ Warner stands to make only $280,000 next
season and is bound to the Rams through 2002 _ and give him a lot
more money. Warner kept saying Monday morning he wasn't thinking
about such matters and that he wasn't worried about it. But that
could change quickly if the Rams decide to play hardball with
Warner and his agent.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw and Zygmunt have well-documented histories of squeezing
players when holding the negotiating leverage, and Shaw has
confided to friends that salary-cap considerations might prevent
Warner from winding up with what he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   What Kurt Warner deserves is about, oh, at least a $2 million
raise from the $250,000 he made this season _ the Rams charitably
added a $500,000 bonus _ after climaxing a 4,353-yard, 41-TD
regular season with storybook playoff heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Kurt Warner did was revive our faith and dreams in fairy
tales,'' NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said Monday in his
introduction of Warner.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when so many jocks are self-important boors whose
cultural enlightenment doesn't extend beyond regular visits to
strip joints, Warner is a refreshing anomaly. He's genuinely modest
and constantly speaks about family and religious values. He seems
to be a well-grounded person who won't be adversely affected by his
newly found celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked Warner what could be learned from his
implausible odyssey, he shook he head modestly, shrugged his
shoulders and finally said, ``Continue to follow your dreams.
Follow the Lord. And live every day for what it's worth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
