<HEADLINE>
RAMS' NFL TITLE IS NO GATEWAY TO PERENNIAL GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kurt Warner had stayed up Sunday night reliving the
pass. Yes, that pass. The one that gave his St. Louis Rams a 23-16
victory over the Tennessee Titans only hours before. The one that
probably has Hollywood agents calling screenwriters for a script on
Warner's hard-to-believe life.
</P>
<P>
   But in Warner's hotel room, sometime before sunrise, amid the
chaos and smiles and jubilation among a small group of friends and
teammates, Warner's wife asked her husband a simple question. It
was a relevant one, a smart one and one that will trail the Rams as
they go through their parades and sign their new contracts and are
declared kings of the free world.
</P>
<P>
   How long, Brenda Warner asked, can the team keep this going?
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when a professional football team could be a
dynasty. Then came free agency, which was followed by two words
that cause allergic reactions in the systems of general managers _
salary cap. Because free agency is such an integral part of modern
football and the salary cap is as formidable as any on-field
opponent, there will probably never be another decade dominated by
one team, the way Green Bay captured the 1960s and San Francisco
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And because the sport is more year round than it ever was, 21st
century champions have little time to soak in their Champagne. The
Rams beat Tennessee in one of the more thrilling title games in the
sport. Passing records were broken. Careers were made. History was
set.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, however, will soon have to fight off predators. Other
teams, through free agency, will try to sign some of its top
players and reserves. The salary cap will force management to make
hard decisions, like cutting popular starters. And money will
become a constant topic in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in position to keep this thing together,''
Warner said. ``But there are going to be pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   The future for Warner and the Rams seems as if it's a long,
unending path paved with gold. The team has only four starters
older than 30. Warner has demonstrated he can be a franchise
quarterback. Marshall Faulk is one of the best running backs in the
National Football League and the defense is full of talented, young
and hungry players.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities seem endless. But that was what Denver Coach
Mike Shanahan thought after winning his first Super Bowl, and then
his second, until quarterback John Elway retired and running back
Terrell Davis blew out his knee. The same could be said for
Atlanta, primed to make a return to the Super Bowl this season,
until Jamal Anderson tore ligaments in his knee during the first
game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre once declared the Packers were
on their way to becoming a dynasty, then they lost to Denver in the
championship game the following year, thus the dynasty crumbled
before it ever got started.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees in anything,'' St. Louis Coach Dick
Vermeil said. Then he sounded this note of caution when discussing
the threat of how money can erode team chemistry like acid through
a piece of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things today is the influence of the
agent,'' Vermeil said, ``and that influence is not always the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Vermeil is already anticipating problems. That
makes him a smart man, because those who have tried to keep a
championship team together say the faster a general manager and
head coach map out a plan of attack to keep the continuity going,
the better off they will be.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis faces several key challenges. Meet them all, or even
most of them, and the Rams can at least make a good run at doing
something no team has ever done, which is win three consecutive
Super Bowls. But fail at meeting most of them, and the Rams will be
doing what other teams with great long-term potential have done,
and that is ask themselves where things went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One challenge is free agency. St. Louis has three unrestricted
and three restricted free agents, with the most notable being
safety Todd Lyght. This is where a team can quickly become less
effective. Losing a key starter is bad enough, but the departure of
several primary backups can also be damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be able to sign everybody,'' Vermeil said. ``That
would be impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the jealousy factor. After the game, Warner shot
his Disney commercial. It is only the beginning of the riches that
await him and other Rams. There will be shoe contracts,
endorsements, their faces on the sides of billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame a player for simply taking advantage of these
things, after all, when they worked hard to reach this point. But
something that the former Giants general manager George Young once
called ``the greed of me'' can creep in. Players can easily cross
the line from trying to do what is best for both their families and
the team, to cutting out the team part.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge will be the schedule. St. Louis will have it
much tougher on the road next year. Like every defending Super Bowl
champion discovers, each week for the Rams will be like a
mini-Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are concerns to address,'' Vermeil said, ``I don't mean
this egotistically, but with our talent and skill people. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil didn't finish his sentence. He didn't have to. With the
Rams' abilities, they should be able to withstand any challenge
next year. But then again, that is what every defending champion
thinks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
