<HEADLINE>
WALKER PICKED TO COACH WIZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael Jordan brought in a new coach Monday in his
role as head of the chronically underperforming Washington Wizards,
but he made clear that he was not about to trade away point guard
Rod Strickland, who has been the subject of trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference called to introduce Darrell Walker
as the new coach, Jordan was asked whether Strickland, who has been
described as a disruptive influence on the Wizards, might be
traded, perhaps to the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Jordan said. ``The Knicks would like him very much, but
I'm very impressed with him. I don't think that trading Rod
Strickland to New York is going to make this team better.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Walker, who played for the Wizards from 1987-91
when they were called the Bullets, came after a weekend of
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Wizards, in last place in the Eastern
Conference with a 14-30 record, fired Coach Gar Heard, and the
players were told that Rod Higgins, an assistant for the Golden
State Warriors, would be their new coach.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, word came that the job would go instead to Walker,
who was coach of the Rockford Lightning of the Continental
Basketball Association. Jordan said Monday that Golden State had
denied him permission to talk to Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has continued to make Chicago his home, and the actual
firing of Heard was done by Wes Unseld, the Wizards' general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered to do that,'' Jordan said of the dismissal, ``but
Wes said that it was his responsibility to fire him.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Heard, an old-school disciplinarian, was fired,
Jordan said, ``He lost the respect of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Jordan went on, hindered their performance.
``Unfortunately, the coach is the first person to get the blame,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heard said he expected to be fired when Jordan was brought in as
part-owner and president of basketball operations on Jan. 19.
Jordan met with several veteran players and with Unseld, but not
with Heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, that's the nature of the business,'' Heard told
The Associated Press. ``I think they had their mind made up when he
got here. I never had the opportunity to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the team's owner, Abe Pollin, who has spent millions on
players and built the new MCI Arena only to see the team founder
again and again, confirmed that the team had decided earlier to
drop Heard. Heard was 2-3 after Jordan's hiring, including a
victory over Cleveland the night he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wes and I considered a change before Michael came aboard,''
Pollin said in an interview after the news conference. He added,
``We would have changed coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether his teams had underperformed because he is,
by reputation, a nice guy, Pollin disputed it. ``I'm not a nice
guy,'' he said. When asked why the Wizards had underperformed, he
said: ``I wish I knew the answer. If I knew, I would do something
about it. I was very optimistic going into this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Walker, Pollin said, ``I'm sure you're going to see 110
percent performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what level the Wizards had been playing at under Heard,
Pollin said: ``Maybe 80 percent. That's unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, 38, played for the Knicks, the Denver Nuggets, the
Bullets, the Detroit Pistons and the Chicago Bulls, with whom he
joined Jordan in the 1992-93 season. As a coach, he was 41-90 with
the Toronto Raptors from 1996 to 1998, and his Rockford team in the
CBA was 11-13.
</P>
<P>
   When it was noted at the news conference that Walker had a
losing record as a coach, Jordan said, ``When you look at someone's
record, it can be because of the talent or lack of talent on the
team.'' The Wizards, he said, have the talent to win.
</P>
<P>
   If the Wizards do not improve despite that talent, Jordan said
that Walker would be evaluated at the end of the season and that
there might be more changes in the Wizards' management. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
