<HEADLINE>
TOP THREE REPUBLICANS ON SOME ABSENTEE BALLOTS IN N.Y.
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York election officials agreed Monday to put the three
leading contenders in the Republican presidential primary on
absentee ballots for members of the military while a court fight
continues over who will appear on the regular ballots.
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates, Sen &UR; . &LR;  John McCain of Arizona, is asking
a federal judge to overturn the primary rules, which make it
difficult to qualify without the backing of the Republican State
Committee, and place him on the ballot across New York on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   After legal challenges to his nominating petitions by the state
party, which is supporting Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, McCain is
on the ballot in only 18 of the state's 31 congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Edward R. Korman of Federal District Court in
Brooklyn, last Friday criticized the primary rules as needlessly
complicated, and is expected to issue a decision this week.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials are scheduled to mail military absentee
ballots on Friday, and lawyers for McCain and another candidate in
the lawsuit, Steve Forbes, expressed concern that because the two
men have, for now, been thrown off the regular ballot in some
districts, their names would not appear on the military absentee
ballots for those districts.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has been disqualified in three Long Island districts, but
is on the ballot in the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   After a conference call among the judge and participants in the
case Monday, state election officials agreed that the names of the
three candidates would be on all the military absentee ballots. If
after the legal wrangling a candidate is disqualified in a
district, any votes for him on a military ballot for that district
would be disregarded, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Other absentee ballots are set to go out later in the month.
</P>
</TEXT>
