<HEADER>
A2438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-IBF-INDICT-NYT &LR;      01-31 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING INSIDERS OFFER DETAILS OF CORRUPT RANKINGS BY OFFICIALS OF
IBF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr. and RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the pattern had struck many people in the boxing
business as fishy. One after another, Colombian fighters with
almost no experience outside Colombia would appear out of nowhere,
rise rapidly up the International Boxing Federation's rankings and
get a shot at a title. Most of them then lost the title fight and
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Mercado, a junior bantamweight of little renown, rose to
the No. 1 contender's spot, then was soundly beaten by the
champion, Robert Quiroga, in 1992. Felix Naranjo, a miniflyweight,
also ascended rapidly to contender's status and got a 1993 title
fight against the champion, Ratanapol Vorapin of Thailand, who
knocked him out in two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Julio became the top lightweight contender in 1995 with
dubious credentials and persuaded the IBF to order the champion at
the time, Oscar De La Hoya, to fight him. But De La Hoya gave up
the IBF belt instead, saying the match would be an embarrassment.
Julio was later whipped by Philip Holliday, a lower-ranked South
African.
</P>
<P>
   The boxing insiders' suspicions turned out to have merit. The
Colombian fighters' manager, Ivan Feris Chadid, said in a sworn
affidavit that he had paid dozens of bribes from 1989 to 1997 to
IBF officials to advance his fighters in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Feris' affidavit was part of thousands of pages of testimony,
documents, tape transcripts and videotapes that a federal judge in
Newark, N.J., unsealed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The documents underpin a civil racketeering lawsuit filed by the
federal government against the IBF, in which prosecutors
successfully sought the appointment a monitor to oversee the
sanctioning organization's operations. The civil case grew out of a
grand jury indictment last November of the IBF's founder, Robert W.
Lee Sr., and three other officials on charges of mail fraud and
soliciting bribes.
</P>
<P>
   The documents and transcripts paint a picture of pervasive
corruption involving some of the biggest boxing promoters in the
United States, including Bob Arum, Don King and Cedric Kushner.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the government's case appears to be the testimony
of C. Douglas Beavers, who headed the IBF's rating committee from
its founding in 1983 until 1998. Facing prosecution himself,
Beavers agreed to cooperate with federal agents in May 1997,
secretly recording more than a hundred conversations with Lee and
other officials in which soliciting bribes and manipulating
rankings were discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers also helped the FBI surreptitiously videotape several
transactions. On a videotape of a meeting in October 1998 with Lee,
Beavers hiked his pants leg and untaped a cellophane package
containing $5,000 in what prosecutors contend was a bribe collected
by an IBF official in Colombia, Francisco Fernandez. In turn, Lee
then placed an envelope with $8,000 in cash on the table,
describing it in code as a payoff from King.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers, in a long deposition, described how he and Lee referred
to payoffs as ``turkey'' or ``stuffing'' in their conversations,
many of which were recorded. They had code names, too, for many
promoters; King was known as ``fuzzy'' or ``cuz,'' and Kushner, who
is portly, was called ``the fat man.''
</P>
<P>
   Beavers said he and Lee had regularly solicited bribes from
managers and promoters, starting in 1985, in essence selling
rankings to the highest bidder. They also accepted payments to
order rematches.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers said Lee had often given preferential treatment to
King's fighters, known to them as ``fuzzy's guys,'' even though
they often lacked the skills to deserve their rankings. Some
fighters were also abruptly dropped from the rankings once they
split with King, Beavers said.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers apparently never received money directly from King, but
he said Lee had given him payments on at least two occasions,
saying the money was from King. In December 1997, for instance, Lee
told Beavers a $4,000 cash payment was ``turkey from Don King.''
</P>
<P>
   In his sworn statement, Beavers said, ``Because we were
receiving payoffs from Don King, we gave special consideration to
his fighters and frequently rated them higher than they would have
been rated on merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the fighters promoted by King whose rankings were
artificially inflated were the heavyweights Gary Ballard and Henry
Akinwande, Beavers said.
</P>
<P>
   King was not charged in the case, and neither the affidavits nor
the transcripts indicate that the government's witnesses can
directly link King to specific payments.
</P>
<P>
   But Beavers and another IBF official, Donald William Brennan,
considered King to be the promoter with the most influence over the
IBF's rankings. In one taped conversation, Beavers said Lee was
``essentially working for King.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeated calls to Don King Productions and to lawyers for King
for comment on the allegations were not returned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   King was not the only promoter paying bribes, the documents
show. Kushner sent payments of $5,000 to $10,000 three to four
times a year, Beavers said. In one instance, Kushner paid Beavers
$100,000 in return for the IBF's forcing a rematch between the
heavyweight George Foreman, then in his 40s, and Axel Schulz, a
German fighter whom Kushner promoted in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1995, Beavers collected the $100,000 from Kushner at his
home on Long Island, N.Y., Beavers said, and then delivered $50,000
to Lee's son, known as Robby, at a service area on the New Jersey
Turnpike. Beavers then drove to Virginia and gave $25,000 to
Brennan. He kept $25,000 for himself. Both Robby Lee and Brennan
are also under indictment.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of that payment, Beavers said, ``Kushner's
payoffs were not to benefit a specific boxer in a specific manner,
but instead were to benefit Kushner's boxers generally.''
</P>
<P>
   Kushner, through a lawyer, has declined to comment on the
federal case. He has not been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   The payment from Kushner came after Foreman narrowly defeated
Schulz in 1995, but the first match was also tainted, according to
the affidavits. Foreman became the IBF's heavyweight champion in
1994, and rather than face again the boxer he defeated for the
title, Michael Moorer, he wanted a bout with Schulz, an unranked
heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit, Arum said he agreed at a meeting in the Mayfair
Hotel in Manhattan in December 1994 to pay Lee $200,000 to give
Foreman an exemption from the IBF's rules requiring a rematch with
Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   Arum used Stanley Hoffman, a New York manager, to funnel
$100,000 to Lee, both Arum and Hoffman said in separate affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he had refused to pay the second $100,000 installment
after he learned that another IBF official had demanded and
received a $250,000 bribe from Foreman to fight Schulz. Arum said
in his affidavit that he had then ordered Hoffman ``to tell Lee
that I refused to pay any more money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
