<HEADER>
A2440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-GORE-NYT     01-31 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL IS A BIT PERSONAL FOR THE TWO DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Even after Bill Bradley compared Al Gore to
Richard Nixon on national television, his campaign continued to
insist last week that he had nothing against the vice president,
and that any harsh words were merely a response to Gore's
aggressive campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But several longtime associates say Bradley has disliked Gore
and made negative references to him since their days in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley's campaign chairman, Douglas Berman, acknowledges
that their differences do appear to predate the campaign. ``There
should be no suggestion that this is why Senator Bradley is
running,'' he said. ``In no way did that affect his decision. But
that their relationship is testy and getting testier and didn't
start warmly is probably true.''
</P>
<P>
   Several friends said that Bradley viewed his Senate colleague
then in much the same way he has portrayed him in recent days: as
untrustworthy and insincere.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the last year, Bradley has repeatedly said he barely
knew Gore when they served together from 1985 until the end of
1992. On Wednesday, he said on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' that
``I've spent more time in a debate room in this campaign than I had
with him in any previous time.''
</P>
<P>
   But while that is no doubt true, it is also true that there are
reasons, particularly on Bradley's part, why the two did not spend
more time together.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Sunday, through his spokesman, Eric Hauser, about his
friends' recollections of specific things he had said about Gore in
the past, Bradley refused to comment, saying he would not
characterize private conversations.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Bradley has said that Gore's attacks on him have been
unfair and inappropriate. Mostly, Gore's criticisms have centered
on Bradley's record and his proposals, particularly his health care
plan, which Gore suggested would hurt minorities. But in
complaining about these criticisms, Bradley has suggested that Gore
has no conscience and has repeatedly branded his opponent as a
liar.
</P>
<P>
   And the bad feeling seems to go back at least to Gore's first
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Bradley said he told them in 1988, when Gore was
running at age 39, that his colleague was nowhere near ready, that
he saw Gore's decision as self-indulgent and that he felt Gore was
unqualified.
</P>
<P>
   A Bradley campaign aide said, ``Given how Bill has always
thought about what it takes to run for president, and what you owe
the country in terms of being ready, he thought Gore was incredibly
ahead of that curve, that Gore viewed it as pure ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman acknowledged the tensions between the two candidates in a
general way after hearing the detailed recollections of several of
Bradley's friends who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Three friends of Bradley _ two of them former campaign aides,
both loyal to him and irate about Gore and the campaign he has run,
and a third who knows them both professionally and socially but is
not in either camp _ said they remembered hearing Bradley speak
disparagingly of Gore. And each of the three said Bradley had
referred to Gore as a phony.
</P>
<P>
   During the time the two men were in the Senate together, Gore,
for his part, does not appear to have shared his feelings about
Bradley one way or the other. And the same holds true more
recently.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president did, however, tell friends he thought Bradley
was a defeatist because he announced soon after Republicans took
over Congress that he planned to retire from the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has often repeated the criticism during the
campaign, playing off Bradley's departure with a slogan reminding
voters that he, on the other hand, had decided to ``stay and
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bradley's friends who said he had long had a negative
impression of Gore emphasized that that did not mean that Bradley
had spent a lot of energy on his feelings about Gore. One said that
any residual ill will from that era ``pales in comparison to what's
occurred since Bill got into the race.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in an interview in 1997, Bradley spoke in flattering
terms of every other possible presidential candidate, Republicans
included.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether Gore would make a good president, Bradley
said, ``I assume there are a lot of people that could be good
presidents, and he'd be among them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
