<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS IN BRIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE FUND-RAISER: The McCain campaign has scheduled its first
live online fund-raiser on Feb. 10, an event that political
professionals said was probably a first for any candidate. Sen.
John McCain will be at a fund-raiser in Washington, and for $100,
anyone will be able to participate over the Internet, watching and
hearing him on a computer. He will take questions from people
online. Campaign aides said that more than 60,000 people had
volunteered through the McCain Web site and that the campaign had
raised more than $1.5 million through the site.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Richard Perez-Pena
</P>
<P>
   PAPER WAR: The Manchester Union Leader, New Hampshire's largest
newspaper, was a battleground for Steve Forbes on Monday. On the
front page was yet another editorial supporting him. Inside was a
half-page advertisement from the Bush campaign, criticizing Forbes
for his attacks on Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and a full-page
advertisement from the Catholic Alliance, an anti-abortion group,
thanking Forbes for having ``spoken out on Catholic issues.''
William Dal Col, campaign manager for Forbes, said that the Bush
advertisement mimicked ones by the Republican Leadership Council,
which was proof, he contended, that the independent political group
was improperly coordinating with the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By Leslie Wayne
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   EARLY MORNING EVENT: After the vote is counted Tuesday night,
Vice President Al Gore will fly to New York for a 3 a.m.
appearance. Why an event at that hour? ``I don't want the traveling
press corps to get any rest,'' Gore said with a straight face. ``I
think that disorientation and jet lag work in my favor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Katharine Q. Seelye
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE CONTESTS: The results of 11 polls available on the eve of
the New Hampshire primary showed Vice President Al Gore with a lead
of 3 percent to 12 percent over former Sen. Bill Bradley. All but
three of the results fell within the margin of sampling error. Ten
of the polls found Sen. John McCain leading Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, with eight of the leads within the margin of sampling error.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE RESOURCE: One of the newest media outlets in this
campaign is Voter.com, a political Internet site. Run by a
bipartisan cast of politicos, Voter.com seeks to be a clearinghouse
for the political process. On the evening of the Iowa caucuses, the
site (www.voter.com) provided running vote totals, linked to the
results being fed to the state Democratic and Republican Parties.
Jeff Hunter, Voter.com's director of political outreach, said in
New Hampshire the site would report real-time results using The
Associated Press and Reuters news services.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Peter Marks
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   WATTS SEEKS RE-ELECTION: Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, one of
the nation's most prominent black Republicans, said Monday that he
would seek re-election this fall, ending speculation that he would
retire. Watts, 42, agreed to run for a fourth term after Speaker
Dennis Hastert and other Republicans furiously lobbied him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Eric Schmitt
</P>
</TEXT>
