<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-CRUI     01-31 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-CRUISE-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILING THE CARIBBEAN WITH A FEW PALS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name tags scared me. They were the first thing I saw _ lined
up neatly in alphabetical order on a table _ when I entered the
observation lounge of the Nantucket Clipper on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. I was here to cruise the Virgin Islands for the beaches,
for the swimming and snorkeling in jewel-blue waters, for the
Caribbean's gentle wind in my hair, not to make new friends. So I
silently vowed to be polite but retiring, to commune only with a
good book, to smile and nod and keep to myself.
</P>
<P>
   Famous last words. By Wednesday, I didn't know how I'd ever
gotten along without Anne and Dave from Buffalo. I'd bonded with
Jane the naturalist from Seattle (even if I did skip her lecture on
hummingbirds). I'd watched myself on a land tour, one of a dozen
rowdy cruise-ship passengers in an open-air minibus, smiling and
waving at strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises as a vacation form inspire mixed feelings in me.
Traveling by water, I have always thought, should mean either
making the trans-Atlantic crossing in evening clothes or hugging
the coast of Ischia, stretched out on the sun deck of a friend's
yacht, getting up only when a cold chicken salad and white wine
lunch is served at a table 20 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   But this time I was seduced by the experience and came away with
the conviction that the cruise is an art form _ and the fastest,
purest wind-down possible for the chronically stressed. Maybe it
was because this cruise was called the Yachtsman's Caribbean. The
brochure promised I'd be able to swim and snorkel directly from the
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Things went well from the beginning. American Airlines got me
from New York to the St. Thomas airport nonstop in four uneventful
hours flat. The Clipper's dock was five minutes from the airport,
but it was too early to board, so the ship's representative whisked
my luggage away (it appeared magically later that afternoon in my
cabin) and sent me in a taxi to the Island Beachcomber Hotel, about
three minutes from the airport. In fact, on the way back, some
people actually walked from there to the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The Beachcomber is a simple place and the sound of airplanes
landing isn't particularly tranquilizing, but there is a gorgeous
little beach and the requisite open-air restaurant and bar. (A
pleasantly chatty American bartender pointed out that some other
people at the bar were going on the same cruise; I ignored them.)
</P>
<P>
   We boarded the ship around 4 p.m. And after the initial shock of
the name tags, I noticed something wonderful: there were only 64 of
them. The 207-foot Nantucket Clipper has a 102-passenger capacity
and is usually fully booked, but this particular cruise began on
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Y2K anxiety had discouraged a lot of people from
scheduling travel right after New Year's Day. Fine with me; it had
helped my travel agent negotiate a sizable discount on the package
price.
</P>
<P>
   But to whom did those name tags belong? The stereotypical cruise
passengers are, of course, an elderly couple in polyester with lots
of time on their hands. I admit I didn't look forward to being
surrounded by retirees, not because I'm ageist (I'm getting old
pretty fast myself) but because I hate feeling out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my horror when I turned on the ship's on-board sound
system and heard the first number: ``Kiss me once and kiss me twice
and kiss me once again; it's been a long, long time'' (one of my
mother's sentimental World War II favorites). And the first
on-board conversation I overheard was about blood pressure
medication. As it turned out, two of the four people talking were
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, several passengers appeared to be in their 30s. There
were always young faces around, because the members of the crew
were bright-eyed all-American 20-somethings who looked as if they
might have been on semester break. And a number of people who
claimed to be retirees looked awfully young and fit, ready for the
hikes and snorkeling excursions ahead. Remember, while you're
sitting at your desk all week, these people are out power-walking
and taking tennis lessons.
</P>
<P>
   But even the laziest couch potato could have managed our
leisurely itinerary. We left St. Thomas on Monday morning, making
stops at Jost Van Dyke (a tiny island with a population of about
150), Tortola, Virgin Gorda, Peter Island (a last-minute
substitution for Salt Island, where we couldn't dock that day
because of the breakers), Norman Island (population 0) and St. John
before returning to St. Thomas on Saturday for a Sunday morning
departure.
</P>
<P>
   These are fairly unchallenging distances (from one end of all
the Virgin Islands to the other is only about 60 miles), so there
wasn't a lot of actual cruising involved. I never heard of a single
case of seasickness during the week, and I had forgotten to bring
Dramamine.
</P>
<P>
   So during most of our meals, the ship was sitting still. But
there were still gorgeous water views from the dining room, which
was spacious with lots of big windows. This is where I was forced
to talk to people. On the first night I asked Craig, the cruise's
hotel manager, if there was a small table I could sit at alone. He
promptly ushered me to an empty seat at a table for six, where I
met a family-and-friends group of five from upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, OK, I enjoyed talking to them. The next day at lunch, I
insisted on a table alone but was soon joined by two single women
from St. Louis traveling together.
</P>
<P>
   The food was very good if a little underseasoned at times. At
both lunch and dinner, there was normally a soup, a salad or two
and a choice of three or four main courses (one of them
vegetarian). The wine list was extremely reasonably priced (most
bottles were below $20).
</P>
<P>
   I loved the ship's portion-size policy. Maybe all the best
places are doing this now, but I hadn't run into it before:
Passengers are allowed _ even encouraged _ to order half portions
of a dish if they want or double portions if they're in the
opposite mood.
</P>
<P>
   One day I couldn't decide between the chicken Monterey and the
avocado and seafood main-course salad, so I had a half portion of
each. The half-portion idea took a lot of the guilt out of ordering
dessert, but after a week of unusual but tasty confections like
chocolate-chip banana cake and peanut butter satin pie, I still had
gained a little weight.
</P>
<P>
   There was also always the option of eating more informally in
the observation lounge: a breakfast buffet with cereals, fruit,
muffins and the like; a lunch buffet of soup, sandwich fixings and
dessert. The buffet also reduced my antisocial tendencies _ I could
take one of the little round cocktail tables alone but be close
enough to exchange a few words with people nearby. This was where I
met Ned and Terry from Maine, and Frank and Sandy from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After dinner I was happy to go to bed early with my book, but on
most nights entertainment was available. Both naturalists gave
lectures, as did a visiting professor whose subjects were pirates
and voodoo. There were on-shore parties on at least two nights _
one of them complete with, yes, a limbo contest. There were a
couple of movie nights, in the dining room. I was glad to see ``The
Sixth Sense'' again but decided to skip a repeat of ``Runaway
Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   No one I met spent much time in the cabins. Mine, a category 3
(right in the middle of the ship's price range), was neat and
tasteful enough, but as tiny as I expected. There were twin beds
with batik spreads on either side of the door, and just enough room
to walk between them to get to the blond-wood desk (with a big
mirror above it) and chair, the wall of three narrow closets and
the shower-equipped bathroom, which was a decent size by maritime
standards.
</P>
<P>
   There were a couple of tasteful tropical-pastel framed prints on
the wall and two large windows with shades and short aqua
draperies. The shades stayed closed most of the time, because
people were always walking by. On the other hand, when I opened my
cabin door I was right on the deck, just a couple of steps from the
rail, enjoying blue water, green hills and the sea breeze.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, passengers could stay busy, with almost constant
excursions, or do nothing but relax on the sun deck or in the
observation lounge, a pleasant room with a bar, banquettes, sofas
and three walls of huge windows. The lounge was the only public
space on the ship besides the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   When you choose a small ship, you don't get a spa, casino or
pool; there wasn't even a gift shop, although a small selection of
merchandise was put on sale at the front desk twice during the
week.
</P>
<P>
   In total, there were 20 possible outings. They ranged from the
Sage Mountain National Park hike in Tortola to the snorkel
excursion (the cruise didn't offer scuba) at the wreck of the
R.M.S. Rhone, which sank in 1867. Prices ranged from $10 for a bus
to the beach to $75 for the Atlantis submarine trip.
</P>
<P>
   I chose three of the least labor-intensive: the Tortola island
tour, the bus to the Baths (a beach with great rock formations) in
Virgin Gorda and the bus to the beach at Trunk Bay in St. John.
</P>
<P>
   The island tour was only moderately interesting. At one point,
our guide, Elroy, got out of the bus to show us what a papaya
looked like. (Gee, and back home I would have had to walk two
blocks to the Korean market to see one.) The tour also involved one
of those winding-mountain-road-on-a-cliff-edge drives that I swear
I will never go on again but always do.
</P>
<P>
   It was, however, a pro-social experience: I always feel closer
to people after I've exhibited abject fear in front of them. At the
top of the mountain was something called Skyworld, where the
restaurant was closed and the bathrooms were locked and unavailable
but the gift shop was open.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard that the trip to the Baths the next day involved a
similar death-defying mountain drive, I canceled. But the afternoon
snorkeling trip I wanted to go on instead was canceled, so I was at
loose ends. Luckily, I remembered seeing a price list on the ship
for the Spa at Leverick Bay, and I passed that very spa on the walk
back to the ship. I went in and had an excellent $80 one-hour
massage that was worth every penny. Strangely, though, there was a
$15 charge for using the whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite excursion was the bus to Trunk Bay on St. John.
Trunk Bay is a beach that lots of cruise ships shuttle their
passengers to, I'm told, but it wasn't really crowded. And it's
widely known as one of the most gorgeous beaches anywhere: white
sand against a backdrop of palms and sea grape trees, calm blue
water clear enough to examine your toenails under, and rockside
snorkeling so organized that there are signs underwater identifying
the sea life at hand.
</P>
<P>
   (Don't ask me how the parrotfish know to go to their sign every
day.) Even I, the clumsy snorkeler whose mask is always filling up
with water, could glide along peacefully and confidently here,
watching the fan coral fan.
</P>
<P>
   There were other swimming and snorkeling opportunities. At Jost
Van Dyke, for instance, we took Zodiacs from the ship to White Bay,
which was small, peaceful and beautiful. But the experience I had
come for was the opportunity to swim right off the ship.
</P>
<P>
   We did this twice: on Thursday at Norman Island and on Saturday
morning at Christmas Cove in St. Thomas. This meant you could leave
your cabin in just your swimsuit, pad down the stairs to the little
swim platform set up at the main deck exit and just dive or step
into the Caribbean. It was heaven.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, I had paddled out to a good snorkeling spot when I
looked back to the ship and saw what looked like a man holding a
tray aloft in the water. Yes, the hotel manager had put on a swim
belt and gotten into the water with a tray of rum punches.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of swimmers happily accepted them, even though it was
around 10 a.m. (I honestly don't think there was much rum in them,
but the idea of hedonism like this was extremely satisfying.) For a
minute there, I could have been on a rich friend's yacht. With Anne
and Dave, Valerie, Marilyn, Frank and Sandy, the Romines from New
Mexico. All my good friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
