<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2450 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-CRUISE-     01-31 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-CRUISE-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECOROUS HULAS AND NO SEQUINS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SARAH FERRELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A one-week American Hawaii Cruise among the Hawaiian Islands,
calling at five ports on four islands, sounds like exactly the
ticket for alleviating the winter drearies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It does not, however, begin well. In fact, it begins with one of
the worst _ and longest _ days of my life, a day on which, because
of an escalating series of mishaps too boring to detail, it has
taken me 22 hours to get from New York to Honolulu. To miss the
ship. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So there I am, after a night in an airport motel and a brief
interisland flight, standing on the pier at Nawiliwili, Kauai,
watching the Independence maneuver slowly into its first port of
call. Ah, but my spirits lift at the sight, and I enjoy a moment of
mild Schadenfreude when I realize that the docking is something my
soon-to-be-fellow voyagers, already aboard, will not get to see. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My cabin is welcoming, especially the single bed that makes up
into a tropical-flowered sofa. It is small, and without a porthole
(I had requested the cheapest inside single), but so what. The
Independence has acres of deck space where I can relax and read and
watch flying fish.
</P>
<P>
   There is a closet more than ample for a week's casual wardrobe,
a desk-cum-dresser with good lighting, and a tiny bath with a round
tiled shower that might double as a goldfish pond. I add a touch of
romance to the decor by hanging my orchid lei, a gift upon
boarding, on the back of the door. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a nap, I set out to poke around the ship. The Independence
is an aging beauty _ built in 1951, 20,221 tons, 1,066 passengers _
with great bone structure. Two pink-and-purple leis are painted
around each stack. Interior spaces are modest, with comfortable
rattan furniture and bits of Hawaiiana _ graphics, artifacts and
historic photographs _ throughout. (But why, I wonder, does the
picture in my room illustrate and translate the word ``hapai'' _
``pregnant?'') There are pots of orchids here and there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My cabin is on the Ohana deck, the fifth of 10, counting down
from the top, which turns out to be very convenient indeed. It is
one deck below the Kamaaina deck, with its little theater space,
library, bar and lounges, and just above the Aloha deck, where the
gangplank is set. The Ohana buffet stands midship; the Ohana Club
bar (which has a generous happy hour) serves large drinks in
plastic cups, which can be taken out onto the spacious afterdeck,
with its small pool, one of two.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good place to meet other passengers, who seem to be
almost 100 per cent mainland Americans and mostly middle-aged.
(Many are couples, a few newly wed and a lot celebrating
anniversaries.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The captain's formal dinner, my first night aboard, is
surprisingly informal and lacking in glitz, with nary a sequin in
sight. To be sure, the captain is elegant in black tie, with a lei
of fragrant maile vine, while the kumu, the teacher or storyteller,
is regal in a purple silk shirt, a flower tucked behind his ear.
</P>
<P>
   I take my place at my assigned table for six, which I share with
two older women from Florida and a woman from Maine with her two
daughters. The menu this evening is typical, no foie gras or
caviar, but surprisingly good Pacific Rim food. The ingredients,
especially the seafood, are splendidly fresh and carefully
prepared, their exotic elements more rational than bizarre. (Yes,
lemongrass does add a perky note to tiger prawns, and a Kona coffee
glaze gives a little kick to meltingly tender rare roast lamb.)
</P>
<P>
   The servers, all of whom are Americans and most of whom seem to
be from the islands, manage to be both attentive and laid back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast, lunch and dinner are all served in the two (Orchid
and Hibiscus) dining rooms; the two earlier meals may also be put
together from a buffet on the Ohana deck, just a few steps from my
cabin. The breakfast selection is ample and varied, verging on
awe-inspiring, so I never make it downstairs (or whatever you call
it on a ship).
</P>
<P>
   I am happy filling my plate with, perhaps, fresh pineapple and
Portuguese sausage and biscuits with gravy and settling down on an
outdoor deck to eat it. The buffet lunch is themed, Italian one
day, Mexican the next _ but the dining room serves a daily and
delicious ``traditional Hawaiian plate lunch,'' something like
chicken shoyu or lau lau (meat wrapped up in taro and steamed in ti
leaves), with two scoops of rice and one of macaroni-potato salad _
the apotheosis of greasy-spoon food, and irresistible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to choose from among the more than 50 shore
excursions and activities, so I take the easy way out and book the
Deluxe Captain's Choice, six bus tours and a big commercial luau.
Since the buses _ which bear the delightful logo of a galloping
rabbit wearing a lei _ tend to leave in the morning, I forgo most
of the evening entertainment for an early bedtime. In fact, I do
not set foot in the Hoi Hoi Showplace until I perform there, of
which more later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I see some spectacular scenery in the course of the next few
days, from the red-striped Waimea Canyon on Kauai to the spiky,
mist-enclosed pinnacles of Maui's Iao Valley and the lava beds of
Volcano National Park on Hawaii, but there is also a lot of good
man-made stuff.
</P>
<P>
   On Maui, for example, there is the shiny new Ocean Center, with
its collection of endemic wrasses that come in colors that are
gaudy even for tropical fish, and the ruined fort in Lahaina that
proves that James Michener did not make up the
whalers-versus-missionaries wars. On the big island of Hawaii, just
outside Hilo, the Hawaii Tropical Botanical Garden is my idea of
Eden.
</P>
<P>
   And a single trip out of Kona, on the big island, comprises a
visit to an ancient place of refuge and royal enclosure and a tiny
church, perhaps my favorite thing in the islands, where Father
Damien preached before he went to Molokai to minister to its leper
colony in 1873. This charming miniature, where a weekly
Hawaiian-language Mass is celebrated, is carpenter-Gothic outside
and inside entirely painted, by another Belgian priest, with faux
architecture and biblical and allegorical scenes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the course of my sightseeing, I acquire a large supply of
souvenirs without actually buying any, although there are plenty of
opportunities to shop. It is perhaps a requisite of the much
advertised ``aloha spirit'' of kindness and generosity, but
someone, a guide or shopkeeper or passer-by, is always giving you a
little gift or treat _ a soft drink or a chocolate-macadamia nut
bar here, a postcard or a refrigerator magnet there.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, I am slightly ashamed of myself for signing up for the
luau, held in the Hyatt Regency Hotel in Kaanapali, Maui _ how
touristy can you get? Well, plenty touristy, with a hokey
torch-lighting ceremony and a parade of the pit-cooked pig, and a
sleek show of pan-Polynesian dances.
</P>
<P>
   I love every minute of it (although the unlimited mai tais may
have helped). The pig is richly smoky, reminiscent of North
Carolina pulled-pork barbecue, the poi, although dull to the taste,
is a very pretty lilac color, and the dancers are adept and
beautifully costumed.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting dance is a stomping, grunting Maori challenge
dance, with much thrusting out of the tongue. It is performed by
the remarkably wasp-waisted young man who, earlier on, put a shell
lei (tonight's little present) around my neck as I got off the bus.
He looks even handsomer with his face half-painted in tattoos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show the next morning could not be more different. As we
sail into the harbor at Hilo, on the rainy side of the big island,
a troupe from a nearby senior-citizen center is waiting, as they
are every week. Those of us going on early excursions meet in the
Kamaaina Lounge, where two men with ukuleles play and sing Don Ho
songs (it is the only time on the trip that I hear ``Tiny
Bubbles''), and six women, two of them gray-haired, three of them
bespectacled and all with flowers in their hair, perform a decorous
hula.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, I return from a visit to the botanical garden,
in time for another amateur performance, this time by a group of
charming children from a well-regarded Hilo hula school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passengers _ or at least about a dozen of them, women, children
and one brave (and graceful) young man _ hula as part of the
graduation exercises that take place in the Hoi Hoi Showplace as
the voyage winds down. We have had a choice of classes in hula,
ukulele and something called ``Hawaiian implements,'' which turn
out to be an assortment of gourds, sticks and other rhythm
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   I choose the last, because it's clearly the easiest, and reminds
me of the fun I had in kindergarten band. My group goes on first _
the single man in our group leads us in, making amazing sounds on a
conch shell. We line up to play _ I have mastered the puili, two
joints of slivered bamboo that are struck together to produce a
jangling beat _ while the kumu chants. Then the hula class hulas,
accompanied by the ukulele graduates playing ``Little Grass
Shack.'' The audience is generous in its applause. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the voyage, the kumu, a man of imposing size and
voice, has given talks on history and mythology and made himself
available to answer questions. He comes into his own the night we
sail from Hilo to Kona, passing close to shore to view the fiery
pit and glowing lava flow of Kilauea Volcano. There, on the
afterdeck, he intones the story of Madame Pele, the fire goddess,
and the journey that brought her here. The flashbulbs that explode
from all sides seem a manifestation of the gods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost every night aboard has a theme _ paniolo (cowboy)
evening, with line dancing, or the '50s and '60s evening with a
sock hop _ which one may honor or ignore. It is Polynesian night
when we pass the volcano, and almost everyone has dressed in newly
acquired tropical prints, with flower leis or headbands. We look
really pretty. The evening ends with a gala buffet in which ice
sculpture is elevated to a fine art. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The leis come into play again the next evening, our last on
board, when we gather to weave them together into a chain that
crosses and recrosses the deck. We carry them to the rail, where
they are gathered up and thrown overboard. Tradition has it that if
your lei floats back to shore, you will return to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Night is falling fast, as it does in the tropics, and no matter
how hard I peer into the gathering dark, I am unable to see what
direction our flowery little island is taking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Debarking at Honolulu, I have time for one last tour, a visit to
the Arizona Memorial in Pearl Harbor. It is heartbreaking. After a
terrifying movie of the attack of Dec. 7, 1941, assembled from both
Japanese and American sources, the visitors board a Navy launch to
be ferried to the memorial itself.
</P>
<P>
   Eerily, for a boat full of normally chatty tourists, you can
hear a pin drop. The austere white structure that intersects the
sunken ship beneath it gleams in the light; inside, an orientation
table identifies the wreckage visible at water level.
</P>
<P>
   The back wall is inscribed with the names of the more than 1,000
crewmen whose bodies rest below; an oil slick spreads out across
the sea from the sunken battleship, and will probably continue to
do so for centuries. Among the floral offerings at the wall of
honor is a rainbow of origami flowers, left by students of a
Japanese high school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
