<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES MAKE FINAL PLEAS IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note dateline change) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE, N.H. _ Presidential candidates blitzed across New
Hampshire in a final flurry before the nation's first primary
Tuesday. Republican John McCain predicted victory while George W.
Bush, the front-runner turned possible runner-up, spent Monday
sledding and bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley also kept campaigning to a
minimum Monday. Gore, who has evaporated Bradley's early lead in
polls, handed out coffee at a diner and greeted Lockheed workers.
Bradley worked hard to establish optimism among his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the senator from Arizona who has staked the survival of
his presidential campaign on a win in New Hampshire, clutched the
latest tracking polls that give him as much as a 10-point lead over
the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident of victory tomorrow night, although we may be
up a little late,'' the Arizona senator told about 150 people on
the Keene town square, freshly covered from an overnight snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   Various polls of Republican voters in New Hampshire all give
McCain a lead, from as little as 1 percentage point to as many as
11 percentage points over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, apparently concerned his confidence would sway his
supporters to stay home, urged voters at his four other campaign
stops scattered across the Granite State that their presence was
sorely needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win tomorrow night, and the message is going to be sent
from New Hampshire to America and the world that we're going to
give the government back to the people of the United States, take
it out of the hands of the special interests, the big money
people,'' he said at his Keene rally.
</P>
<P>
   Bush addressed employees of the New Hampshire Department of
Safety and Blue Cross Blue Shield before noon Monday, then
conducted TV interviews and enjoyed the sunny, snowy day.
</P>
<P>
   At breakfast, Bush flipped pancakes with some of his rivals.
Later, he hopped on an innertube sled in Amherst with a pair of
13-year-old twins and hurtled downhill backward, legs akimbo, pants
legs flapping up to expose his out-of-place cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the man play. He's been working hard,'' one teen-age boy
yelled at the throng of reporters surrounding Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush portrayed tube sledding as a metaphor for his overall
campaign for the GOP nomination rather than any possible result of
the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel everything is downhill from here. I feel optimistic. I
feel exhilarated,'' Bush said. ``As we went downhill, one of these
girls said the faster we go the more likely we are to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush canceled a street-walking tour of Exeter after his staff
learned that about 20 people advocating legalization of marijuana
were awaiting him there.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates were struggling for attention and Gary Bauer
got some he might have wished he hadn't. At the presidential
pancake-flipping event, Bauer flipped a pancake into the air, and
backing up to catch it, fell off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer recovered, holding up the pan and pancake and declared,
``I'm a survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, flipped his pancake high in the air and
caught it on a spatula while hecklers shouted and waved.
</P>
<P>
   But ``people don't just want a nice smile, and a nod and wink.
They want something real,'' declared magazine mogul Steve Forbes
who has used his relentless attacks on Bush's conservative
credentials to secure a second-place finish in Iowa, and establish
hopes for a third-place showing in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done for most of the campaign, Forbes directed his
criticism primarily at Bush. He said the Texas governor has
proposed inadequate tax and education proposals and has not
addressed health care and Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats shored up their support across the state as well
as the various polls showed Gore leading Bradley by anywhere from 3
percentage points to 12 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent Monday stopping at diners and workplaces to shake
hands with voters, hand out cups of coffee and sign autographs. He
greeted factory workers at Nashua's Lockheed Sanders, visited with
patrons at a diner in Tilton and an Italian restaurant in Concord,
and then stopped in at his campaign headquarters in Manchester to
help telephone undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
