<HEADER>
A2453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-TRUCKERS-SUIT-NYT &LR;      01-31 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TRUCKERS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SUES OVER LAW LIMITING TRUCK TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group representing about 3,000 of the United States' largest
trucking companies sued New Jersey in federal court Monday, saying
that a state regulation banning interstate trucks from local roads
violates the Constitution's protection of interstate commerce and
will lead to arbitrary traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   In July the state Department of Transportation issued a rule
prohibiting large trucks that are not making a pickup or delivery
inside New Jersey from traveling on roads that are not part of the
National Highway System. In New Jersey the system consists of all
the interstate highways, the New Jersey Turnpike and several state
roads that link them.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks based in New Jersey are exempt from the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman directed her transportation commissioner,
James Weinstein, to issue the ban after years of complaints from
residents and local officials that big trucks are dangerous, noisy
and dirty and take a heavy toll on roads.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ban was imposed six months ago, tickets have not
been issued. Officials said Mrs. Whitman signed a bill on Jan. 13
providing penalties of up to $400 for a first offense, after it was
approved unanimously by both houses of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties must be added to police summons books before
ticketing begins. In the meantime, the police are redirecting
trucks onto authorized roads, said Jayne O'Connor, a spokeswoman
for Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Trucking Association, which filed the suit
Monday in U.S. District Court in Newark, says the ban violates the
clause of the Constitution that bars states from interfering with
interstate commerce, as well as the equal protection clause,
because it treats trucks based in New Jersey differently from those
based outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also claims the ban cannot be enforced legally, because
a police officer has to pull a truck over to learn whether it has
business in New Jersey. ``To enforce the regulations, local police
must inevitably make decisions to stop and detain individual
restricted vehicles on local New Jersey roads without probable
cause,'' the suit asserts.
</P>
<P>
   The association's state affiliate, the New Jersey Motor Truck
Association, has remained neutral on the ban. ``It doesn't affect
the people we represent,'' said Sam Cunninghame, its executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, because states can decide which of their roads are
part of the national highway system, Cunninghame said he was
lobbying the state to expand the system to include state Routes 1,
17 and 130, all north-south arteries. He is waiting for a meeting
to be scheduled with Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   John Dourgarian, a spokesman for the Transportation Department,
said, ``Certainly we could meet with the group, but at this point I
don't think we're inclined to add to the national network in New
Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Dourgarian said the state was well within its rights to impose
the ban, which has reduced truck traffic by as much as 30 percent
on some roads. ``The U.S. Department of Transportation advised us
last summer that the DOT had the authority to regulate truck
traffic on non-national highways,'' he said, referring to the state
agency. ``We feel quite strongly that the law does not impact
interstate commerce, because we're providing a good system of roads
for truckers to use.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0529 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2454 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-NHLCOL-COLUMN-LAD     01-31 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS RUN GOOD, BAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike the Los Angeles Kings, who are playing hard but losing to
just about everyone, the Anaheim Mighty Ducks seem to beat good
teams but get embarrassed by the lousy ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have victories over St. Louis, Detroit and Phoenix,
each at a point in the season when those teams were leading the NHL
in points. They have road wins over Toronto and Colorado, both
division leaders. And, they have three victories over the defending
Stanley Cup-champion Dallas Stars, a team that has beaten the Kings
22 straight times.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Ducks lost to the lowly New York Islanders, who had
dropped their previous seven.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray has been disappointed with his team's
results but pleased with the effort. Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg
can't say the same. If both aren't careful, they could find
themselves out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(A coach) can scream and yell, but sooner or later, it has to
come from the players,'' Hartsburg said. ``This league is about
players being hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have lost twice to last-place Montreal and once to
Tampa Bay, which is just three points ahead of expansion Atlanta in
the Southeast Division. They also have tied Chicago (last in the
Central) and Vancouver (last in the Northwest).
</P>
<P>
   And, they lost at home to Boston and Buffalo during stretches
when the those teams were slumping badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating when your team is playing great against
the great teams but playing so bad against the not-so-good teams,''
Teemu Selanne said. ``Those points against Dallas and Detroit and
St. Louis don't mean anything if you don't win games like (the
Islanders).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fit to be tied: If the Kings season comes down to a point or
two, they can look at their inability to win in overtime as one of
the problems.
</P>
<P>
   They entered Monday night's game with the Islanders with 52
points, tied with Calgary for seventh. The Kings, however, are
0-7-3 in overtime compared to the Flames, who have a record 10 OT
victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames have done it despite being the lowest-scoring team in
the Western Conference. But they have taken a different philosophy
than other teams, which have become conservative after new rules
gave clubs one point for a tie in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary, led by the exciting Valeri Bure, has the speed to take
chances. Bure and All-Star defenseman Phil Housley have five points
apiece in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams know our record in overtime and they start
thinking, `Jeez, we can't give them anything in OT,' so they start
sitting back, and it allows us carry the puck,'' Jason Wiemer said.
``Bure and Housley are not going to give the puck up unless you
force them. They bring one or two guys to them and that creates an
opening for everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   One team that is watching is Edmonton, which began Monday two
points ahead of the Kings and Flames. The Oilers were 0-7-13 in OT
before finally beating Vancouver last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we know how Calgary is doing in overtime,'' Edmonton's
Mike Grier said. ``But we're trying not to get caught up in just
looking at them.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Stranded: There are plenty of worse places to be than the
Embassy Suites in Cary, N.C., but it's hard to convince the Phoenix
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived there last Monday, just hours before the beginning
of a snowstorm that dumped a record 20.3 inches on the area. The
next morning, everything was closed, including the airport. The
Coyotes' game with the Carolina Hurricanes was cancelled, as was
Wednesday's game in Atlanta because they couldn't get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   They were able to practice a little, however, shuttling five or
six players at a time to the arena in four-wheel-drive vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Embassy Suites, with more than 400 guests _
including a convention of pharmaceutical people who had already
been there for two weeks _ ran short of supplies and had a skeleton
crew working 40 straight hours and sleeping on the premises. The
hotel chef told the Coyotes they couldn't cook the team's requested
menu of chicken, pasta, brown and white rice, salad and salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard they ran out of beer, too,'' goaltender Sean Burke
said. ``Heck, we were ready to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix finally played Thursday afternoon and beat the
Hurricanes 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Montreal Canadiens might have had it worse. After
their game Monday night against the Hurricanes, they were stuck in
nearby Chapel Hill for the next three days. They never practiced
and were forced to cancel Thursday night's game in Boston when
their plane froze and wouldn't start. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BLUELINES
</P>
<P>
   HOT, HOT, HOT
</P>
<P>
   When Washington defeated the Philadelphia Flyers 2-0 on Sunday,
it gave the Capitals the longest unbeaten streak (10-0-1) in the
NHL this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ollie Kolzig made his 17th consecutive start and earned his
third shutout of the season for the Caps. It was the fifth by
Washington in the last 31 games after having none the first 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps, a playoff long shot at the beginning of the season,
are just five points behind the Flyers for the fourth playoff spot.
They are 15-4-5 at home after winning just 16 all last season. They
have allowed 50 goals in 25 home games _ the fewest in the
conference _ and have not allowed more than two goals in a home
game since Nov. 19 (14 games).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TONY THE TIGER
</P>
<P>
   Former King Tony Granato, now with San Jose, must have forgotten
about the blood clot in his head four years ago that threatened his
career and nearly his life.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe when you're 5-10, 185 in a land of 6-5 speedskaters,
you know you can never let up. Just a week after giving the Kings
Mattias Norstrom 30 stitches with a cross check to the mouth,
Granato elbowed Colorado's Alexei Gusarov in the face, resulting in
a concussion and two lost teeth. Both plays were reviewed by NHL VP
Colin Campbell, who ruled they did not warrant a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN RIDDLE
</P>
<P>
   When Detroit comes to the Staples Center on Thursday, make sure
to watch Sergei Fedorov. Despite injuries and a recent 11-game
scoring drought, he is critical to the Red Wings playoff chances.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov had 20-plus points for four consecutive postseasons from
1995-98 when the Red Wings played three Cup finals and the Western
Conference final. In last year's playoffs, he was dominated by
Peter Forsberg in a second-round loss to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   With just 11 goals and 31 points, Fedorov seems to make more
news about his cooling romance with tennis star Anna Kournikova,
who also has been seen with Florida's Pavel Bure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DECISIONS DECISIONS
</P>
<P>
   Before the March 14 trade deadline, the Panthers have to decide
what to do with veteran Rob Niedermayer, who was the Panthers'
first-ever draft pick taken as the fifth overall selection in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Florida obviously wants to go far in the playoffs, but
Niedermayer is in the final year of a $6.1 million contract, a deal
that pays him $2.3 million this season. Niedermayer also can become
a restricted free agent this summer. For the Panthers to retain his
rights, they must offer him at least a 10 percent raise by July 1.
He is seventh on the team in scoring and eighth in goals with
eight, although four are game winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
