<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBO-LEWIS-ARRESTED-CO     01-31 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-LEWIS-ARRESTED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL linebacker arrested for murder in post-Super Bowl slayings
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Ray Lewis, a middle linebacker for the Baltimore Ravens
football team, was arrested Monday and charged with murder in
connection with a double homicide in the Buckhead section of
Atlanta hours after the Super Bowl, said Atlanta police spokesman
Officer John Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in our custody,'' Quigley said Monday night. He could not
say where Lewis is being held, whether the charges were for more
than one count of murder, or whether any other person had been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   A Lincoln Navigator stretch limousine and its driver are also
keys to the Atlanta police's investigation of the fatal stabbings
of two Decatur, Ga., men.
</P>
<P>
   Officers and detectives involved in the double murder
investigation said Lewis was inside the black stretch limousine
that roared away from the spot where Jacinth Demarus ''Shorty''
Baker, 21 and Richard Dameco Lollar, 24, both originally from
Akron, Ohio, were killed early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrest, Lewis and his agents denied any wrongdoing on
his part.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis confirmed to the Baltimore Sun on Monday night that he was
questioned by Atlanta police, but said he was told he could go. He
had been scheduled to fly to Hawaii this morning for Sunday's Pro
Bowl. ``I cooperated fully (with police),'' he said. ``As far as
the situation, I have no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, 21, and Lollar, 24, were stabbed several times as they
fought with a handful of men who were passengers in a stretch
Lincoln Navigator limousine with Maryland plates, police in the
Buckhead precinct said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker was a sketch artist looking to get into art school, Lollar
was a barber who moved to Atlanta two years
</P>
<P>
   ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police were searching for six men who fled the lounge in a
limousine. Witnesses said the men in the limousine were involved in
an argument with the victims and fired at least five gunshots as
they drove away. Although shots were fired, Baker and Lollar died
of multiple stab wounds, accourding to the Fulton County Medical
Examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta homicide Lt. Mike Smith said detectives are seeking any
witnesses who may have seen the 4 a.m. altercation that ended at
the corner of East Paces Ferry Road and Grandview Avenue in
Buckhead Village. Smith said it started at the Cobalt Lounge, also
located on East Paces Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want anyone who saw this to please come forward,'' Smith
said Monday afternoon. ``We just want to question anyone who may
have seen anything or heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The intersection where the blood of both men stained the street,
is flanked by outdoor cafes, galleries and upscale apartment
complexes. On an early morning drive along East Paces Ferry Road,
one is treated to joggers in colorful outfits, business people with
cups of coffee in their hands and merchants starting their workday
at small shops and boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt Barnes Jr., an agent for Lewis, said Monday evening he
did not believe his client was directly involved in the fatal
altercation. Ravens owner Art Modell agreed: ``I don't believe he
had anything to do with it. I'm going to give Ray the benefit of
the doubt and defend him until something is proven otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis became the NFL's highest-paid linebacker in November 1998
when he signed a four-year, $26 million contract, which included a
$7 million signing bonus. Lewis is scheduled to stand trial in
Baltimore County next month for assaulting a woman in a Baltimore
bar on Dec. 6, 1999. A Ravens official said the team is concerned
about the crowd Lewis associates with. He said management had
expected to meet with Lewis when he returned from the Pro Bowl next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the team officials's statement, Lewis replied: ``The
devil is always busy, always after God's children. He wants to get
you, one way or another. It's something I will discuss with (the
Ravens) at the proper time. I can't speak about it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A big break in the case came just a couple of hours after the
killings when detectives found the stretch limousine behind a
Holiday Inn on Peachtree Road near Lenox Mall. Homicide detectives
spent most of the day talking to the driver of the luxury sedan,
but they would not provide details concerning those conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Police were called to the hotel after someone told them a man
with bloodstains on his clothing had gotten out of the Lincoln
Navigator limousine and entered a bathroom in the hotel lobby to
wash off, officers at the scene said.
</P>
<P>
   The slayings are the second in two weeks along East Paces Ferry
Road in the heart of the city's entertainment district. The
killings, as well as street fights and the hit-and-run death of a
34-year-old woman in 1998, have prompted Buckhead activists to
repeatedly ask the City Council to pass legislation that would
close the bars before 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa and Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Ben Smith and Doug Payne
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
