<P>
   A handful of relatives were whisked away to a VIP lounge at San
Francisco International Airport by airline officials. Clergy were
reported to be on the way to the airport to offer counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In the early evening the Coast Guard ordered private craft that
had sailed into the area to stay away from the debris field, to
prevent confusion in search and rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board, said in a telephone interview on ``Larry King Live'' on CNN
that a ``Go-Team'' from the agency was scheduled to leave the East
Coast about 2 a.m. Tuesday to begin its investigation of the crash,
and was already considering whether to call for additional Coast
Guard ships from Hawaii for possible salvage efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're just trying to gather information,'' Hall
said.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 261 is a seven-day-a-week flight from Puerto Vallarta to
San Francisco. It is scheduled to leave at 3:30 p.m. and arrive at
5:05 p.m. It was then to continue to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The plane that usually flies the route is an MD-80 or an updated
model like the MD-82, which has two engines attached to the
fuselage near the tail. The models first entered service in 1980,
and depending on configuration, usually carry 144 to 152
passengers. About 1,170 of them have been built.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-83, a two-engine craft with engines on the tail, is the
successor to the McDonnell-Douglas DC-9, and like the Boeing 737 is
frequently used on midrange flights. The jet was built less than
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Evans, an Alaska Airlines spokesman in Seattle, said the
plane in question had completed 14,350 cycles of takeoffs and
landings. The craft had more than 26,000 hours of flying time.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines has built a successful business and a strong
safety record operating north-south routes that serve more than 40
cities in Canada, Alaska, Mexico and states up and down the Pacific
Coast. The downed flight was to have stopped in San Francisco and
continued to Seattle, the carrier's corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The airline had two fatal accidents in the 1970s, both in
Alaska, according to Airsafe.com, a Web site that tracks plane
crashes. In 1971 an Alaska Airlines Boeing 727 approaching Juneau
crashed into a mountain slope after the crew had received
misleading navigational information. All 104 passengers and seven
crew members were killed. In 1976 one passenger was killed when a
727 overran a runway in Ketchikan.
</P>
<P>
   The crash is the first for a U.S. commercial airline involving
fatalities since an American Airlines MD-82 crashed in Little Rock,
Ark., last June 1, killing 11 people including the pilot, as the
pilot attempted to land in a heavy storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
