<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      01-31 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Maybe something was in the air when Matt Bullard got up _ yes, he
confirmed, he did elevate _ and violently smacked back a Glen Rice
shot. Or perhaps it was evident moments later when Kobe Bryant went
through his typical gyrations only to be denied by Kelvin Cato
inside.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But if any of the first seven blocked shots of the afternoon did
not drive the point home, Cato did with No. 8, slapping back a
Shaquille O'Neal drive and giving the Rockets their final push
through the homestretch of Sunday's upset of the Los Angeles
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   There were the usual moments of O'Neal dominance inside. And
Bryant and Steve Francis traded NBC-friendly slams, with Francis
adding a spectacular reverse around Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   But if conversation at Super Bowl parties Sunday drifted to the
Rockets' win that afternoon, the talk undoubtedly was of the block
party Cato and the Rockets enjoyed before the dip was served that
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was not idle chatter, either. A day later, the Rockets said
the blocked shots were indicative of their renewed emphasis on
defense and the rehabilitation of their best shot-blockers, Cato
and Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blocked shots, people have to talk about more,'' said
Olajuwon, the NBA's all-time leader in the category. ``When you
have a shot-blocker in the lane, it creates a whole different
scenario for your opponent. They feel his presence. They know
you're there. They don't see you. But they know that you're around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's no shot-blocker around, the door is open. They
can go in any time. When you have a shot-blocker in the lane, the
door is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his struggles to regain his conditioning since his
return from the injured list, Olajuwon has been blocking shots from
the day he stepped back on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Since rejoining the team, he has averaged 2.25 blocked shots per
game, which would rank eighth in the league. But it is a more
impressive figure considering he has played an average of just 18.6
minutes in his eight games back.
</P>
<P>
   Cato has come back slowly from a sprained right wrist. But in 35
minutes over the past two games, he has blocked seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the value of denying an opponent a basket, the Rockets
say the blocked shots have offered the same sort of emotional lift
that comes with a spectacular offensive move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve does some fantastic things on the offensive end,''
Bullard said. ``On the defensive end, the most fantastic thing you
can do is block a shot. The crowd gets fired up. It's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does a lot for us emotionally. It solidifies our defense. I
can't think of anybody else in the league that can block Shaq's
shot like that, so it was really a big emotional lift for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It also serves to boost the confidence of teammates forced to
defend highlight-makers on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, I told Dream (Olajuwon) he was helping me out a lot
when I was forcing Kobe to go to the middle and pushing Ron Harper
to the middle,'' Francis said. ``I just want him to be there to put
that fear in their heart if they bring it in there. They're either
going to get it blocked or get fouled.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich: ``It's a big psychological
boost. You have confidence you can get up and pressure somebody. If
you make a mistake and the guy gets by you, there's an eraser back
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychological effect on the opposition is often even
greater. But the Lakers did not get shy. And Cato was careful not
to sound as if he was gloating, knowing a rematch is coming at the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have to see Shaq one more time,'' he said. ``There
might not be any more blocks after that. He might get that shoulder
and put me in the basket a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   But on one Sunday drive, Harper shied away from Olajuwon and
left his shot off the backboard short. And there is no telling how
many drives never come because of the threat of a shot-blocker
waiting inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``A blocked shot is a demoralizing deal,'' Tomjanovich said.
``When you've got somebody in there that slaps something back, it
doesn't matter if it's on a big guy or a small guy. It's not only a
physical barrier that's there; it becomes invisible. There's an
image that, `Well, I can't take this in there.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' eight blocks Sunday aside, Olajuwon and Cato
sounded more proud of shots they altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blocking shots is intimidating,'' Cato said. ``If you block
two or three shots, they stop coming. And if they don't stop
coming, you keep trying to block them. If you don't get in foul
trouble and everything is going right, it's pretty fun out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon said changing shots, rather than blocking them, is
really the more important part of his ``closed door'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a key to defense,'' he said. ``When you have a
shot-blocker in the lane, it's a whole different game.''
</P>
<P>
   If the idea is to remind that a shot-blocker could be waiting in
the lane, the thought is never far away in Compaq Center. A plaque
there honoring Olajuwon as the NBA's all-time block leader speaks
louder than any scouting report.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a reminder,'' Olajuwon said. ```He's still here.'''
</P>
<P>
   And though such things don't come quickly, Cato adds: ``I need
to get one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
