<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON WON'T BLAME TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Coach Phil Jackson said neither the Lakers'
offense nor the players were to blame for Glen Rice's lack of
scoring opportunities Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rice clearly was irritated about a lack of touches after taking
just one shot in the second half as the Lakers lost at Houston.
Jackson's offense doesn't rely on many designed plays, so the
players themselves dictate ball distribution most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe his teammates weren't looking for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``In recalling the situation, I don't remember anything that was
specific about that,'' Jackson said Monday, then quickly added,
``Maybe he didn't deserve any more shots, he was having trouble
putting it in anyway. But I didn't find anything that was sitting
there for him, now that I think about watching that second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice missed the only shot he took in the second half and
finished 1 for 7. His irritation isn't new. Rice frequently
grumbled about his role in the offense last season as well.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to Rice's streaky shooting, Jackson has at times
directed the offense to get him early opportunities and establish
his rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the game off in that direction to see if Glen was
hot,'' Jackson said. ``He had what we consider an easy defensive
man (Walt Williams) playing him and it was a point of weakness on
the Houston team, but we couldn't take advantage of it. So that
hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Rice's scant opportunities late in the game, Jackson said,
``I don'tknow it it's a problem or not. I mean, it depends upon
what happens. If he's being played well enough, other people are
going to be open for shots. And those are the things that come with
the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Veiled threat: Jackson is concerned about a lack of intensity
among his players during their current 3-5 stretch, and he has an
idea why the energy is lacking _ ``but I'm not sharing it with
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a situation where we've got to have more
enthusiam about playing selfless basketball, which is a problem for
us. And being able to play through situational things that are
difficult on the floor. Sometimes we get mired into a game and it
looks like mental fatigue is the biggest problem we've got. We've
got too many worries by the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how to snap the Lakers out of it, ``Maybe it's time for
us to start thinking about moving personnel out, who knows?''
Jackson said with a smile. ``Maybe we can't get anybody to play
together, we're just going to have to do it, but we're going to fix
it some way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
