<HEADER>
A2586 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-ROCKER-BAN-1STLD-WRIT     01-31 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-BAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVE'S PITCHER ROCKER BANNED FROM PLAYING UNTIL MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Double parens in 7th graf substitute for brackets.) 
(Eds: Subs to move up reference to his psychological evaluation in
new 11th graf and to clarify material in 15th graf)  (DW) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Commissioner Bud Selig, saying John Rocker had
dishonored Major League Baseball by disparaging many groups of
society with his harsh comments in a magazine interview, suspended
the Atlanta Braves' No. 1 relief pitcher Monday for 73 days,
marking the first time a baseball player has been disciplined for
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The players' union said that it would file a grievance
challenging the suspension and suggested that the disciplinary
action was a public relations move.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said that Rocker could not participate in spring training
with the Braves, a 45-day period, and could not play during the
first 28 days of the season. The commissioner also fined Rocker, a
25-year-old Georgian, $20,000 and ordered him to undergo
sensitivity training.
</P>
<P>
   Under baseball practice, Rocker will not lose any of his salary
while he is suspended. He has yet to sign his contract for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball takes seriously its role as an American
institution and the important social responsibility that goes with
it,'' Selig said in a statement. ``We will not dodge our
responsibility. Rocker should understand that his remarks offended
practically every element of society and brought dishonor to
himself, the Atlanta Braves and Major League Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who initially gained notoriety by lashing out at Mets
fans during the National League Championship Series last October,
expanded his target group in a Sports Illustrated article last
month. He disparaged an assortment of foreign people _ ``I'm not a
very big fan of foreigners,'' he said, adding, ``How the hell did
they get in this country?''_ as well as gays and others. He also
called a black teammate ``a fat monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about playing for a New York team, he said: ``Imagine
having to take the 7 train to the ball park, looking like you're
((riding through)) Beirut next to some kid with purple hair next to
some queer with AIDS right next to some dude who just got out of
jail for the fourth time right next to some 20-year-old mom with
four kids. It's depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marge Schott was the owner of the Cincinnati Reds in the
1990s, she was suspended more than once for her public statements
on blacks and Jews, but no player whom anyone could remember was
ever disciplined for words that he spoke. Players have been
suspended for drug abuse, and Dennis McLain, a well-known pitcher
for the Detroit Tigers, was suspended for the first half of the
1970 season for his relationship with gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker will not be permitted to begin formal preparation for the
season until April 3, when, he was informed, he could participate
in extended spring training and/or minor league activities. He
cannot play for the Braves until May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe it is appropriate that I should be harshly
disciplined for my misguided speech unaccompanied by any conduct on
my part,'' Rocker said in a statement released by his agents. ``I
have previously apologized for my unfortunate remarks and stand by
my apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had previously been ordered to undergo psychological
evaluation under baseball's Employee Assistance Plan. The
announcement Monday said he had completed that evaluation but did
not provide additional information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's remarks triggered an outcry from the Atlanta community
as well as Braves officials and players.
</P>
<P>
   As unpopular as Rocker's comments were, even with his own
teammates, the magnitude of the penalty is prompting the Players
Association to challenge it, Gene Orza, the union's associate
general counsel, said. A grievance would be heard by Shaym Das,
baseball's arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems fairly obvious to me,'' Orza said, ``that they
imposed this penalty in almost defiance of but certainly with an
eye toward the arbitration process. You wash your hands of it and
let others worry about the propriety of what you've done. I just
don't think they're going to fool anyone with what they're trying
to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the Constitution's freedom of speech
provisions do not apply to private industry as they do to
government action, Orza said: ``Speech which harms the business is
subject to discipline. The question is whether the harm is real or
just a function of the belief. You have to actually demonstrate the
harm. Even assuming that, the magnitude of the penalty has to be
taken into account.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were quick to link Rocker's remarks to potential
economic harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a very difficult time for the Braves' front
office,'' Stan Kasten, the club's president, said at a news
conference in Atlanta. Saying the Rocker issue generated the most
calls and mail he could recall on a single issue, he added: ``It
has been difficult for us businesswise because all of these people
had strong feelings. It's been difficult for the sales department,
the promotions department, the community relations department.''
</P>
<P>
   John Schuerholz, the team's general manager, said Braves players
had expressed the view that if Rocker were ``suspended, punished in
some way, probably fined for his comments, they would be willing to
give him a second chance as a teammate. They would be willing to
see him get a chance to redeem himself.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first players who criticized Rocker publicly was Tom
Glavine, an Atlanta pitcher, who is the union's National League
player representative. He might have been one of the people Orza
had in mind when he said, ``Even the people who are offended by
what Rocker said should see the stakes in this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All players,'' Orza added, ``who work in an industry that
encourages them and sometimes insists that they talk to the press
have a stake at not being penalized for pure speech unaccompanied
by bad conduct, particularly when the penalty for that pure speech
is as enormous as this one has been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
