<HEADLINE>
GORE ON THE LINE, NO JOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ It isn't easy being the vice president of the
United States, particularly when people don't believe you.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore had that experience Monday as he placed nearly two dozen
calls to voters to urge them to go to the polls on Tuesday for the
nation's first primary. Some people just accepted that the vice
president was phoning them. Others had a harder time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, it's Al Gore calling,'' the vice president told one woman
as he sat at a phone bank in his headquarters here. ``This is Al
Gore. No, it really is. I'm not joking. I'm calling from our
headquarters over here in Manchester. No, I'm not joking you. It
really is Al Gore. No, it's not a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman told him she thought he was her grandson Michael.
Laughing at her resistance, Gore finally asked her, ``How can I
prove it to you?''
</P>
<P>
   She asked him what her address was. He looked at the phone list
and told her. She asked him how many children she had. ``That I
don't know,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Gore asked to speak to her daughter, Mary. ``Mary,
hi, it's Vice President Al Gore. Your mom doesn't believe it's
really me. It's not Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking he had made some headway, he smiled, then looked
crestfallen as he said into the phone, ``No. This is Al Gore.''
Even Mary thought the voice on the other end of the line was that
of her prankster son.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, Gore was greeted with words of
encouragement by the woman who answered the phone. Then he asked to
speak to her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm so sorry,'' he found himself saying. It turned out
that the woman's husband had died just the night before. But her
daughter was planning to take her to the polls anyway, to vote for
Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
