<HEADER>
A2593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPER-JONES-NYT     01-31 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALONG CAME JONES TO MAKE THE TITLE-SAVING TACKLE 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By TOM JOLLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Dick Vermeil of the Rams was already thinking overtime. So
was Titans quarterback Steve McNair.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of them thought linebacker Mike Jones was about to make
the play of his career, tackling Titans wide receiver Kevin Dyson 1
yard short of the end zone on the final play of Super Bowl XXXIV on
Sunday night, securing the Rams' 23-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' route to that moment was nearly as unusual as Rams
quarterback Kurt Warner's path to stardom. Jones was a running back
at the University of Missouri, and holds the school record for
receptions by a running back. But he was not drafted and he did not
become a National Football League-caliber player until he played
linebacker in the World League for a season. He signed with the
Raiders in 1992, and then came to the Rams as a free agent three
seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the Titans at the Rams' 10-yard-line, Jones said the
discussion was simple: ``There's six seconds left, they have to get
in the end zone. Keep them out and we win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As he lined up at his spot on the left side, Jones said he
thought back to the touchdown the Titans' Eddie George had scored a
few moments earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, no matter who it is, I can't let him in the end
zone,'' he recalled thinking. ``We got a chance to win this game.
Get him on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had called for three-on-two coverage on the left side,
with Jones, cornerback Todd Lyght and safety Billy Jenkins assigned
to cover tight end Frank Wycheck and wide receiver Kevin Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson lined up on the outside, a step behind Wycheck, then went
in motion inside before turning and jogging back to the outside as
the ball was snapped. Wycheck ran downfield a step ahead of Dyson
as the play unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, though, the Titans presented Jones with an unexpected
wrinkle. Jones expected the bigger Wycheck to cut to the middle of
the field; instead the speedy Dyson suddenly darted inside.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson thought it was great strategy. ``I didn't think anybody
would be in the middle of the field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, for one, did not expect Dyson's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking they're going to run the tight end on the inside
route,'' he said. ``But I guess they must have been studying our
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's pass hit Dyson in stride at the 5, and for an instant,
he seemed to have a clear path to the end zone. McNair was sure
Dyson would get into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement you have and the positive attitude you have
when you get the ball into your guy's hands, he catches it and is
running, you expect him to score,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones reacted instantly. ``I saw him plant in the cut and I
broke in on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones reached out with his left hand, grabbing Dyson around the
waist and then fully grabbed him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dyson thought he could score. ``I didn't think he had a
good grip on me and I stretched out,'' he said. ``But I was just
short.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were champions, even if it was not quite the way Jones
had dreamed about.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream of making the interception or the fumble or the sack
and taking it for a touchdown,'' he said. ``But not necessarily
tackling a guy to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had to agree it was the biggest play of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won the Super Bowl,'' he said. ``So it had to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
