<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS' FISHER REFLECTS ON THE LONGEST YARD; BISHOP ON THE MEND
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four stadiums and seven years ago, the Tennessee
Titans last posted a winning season, that is, before this campaign
came to a spectacular, if losing, conclusion to the St. Louis Rams
in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   Curling his lip defiantly Monday morning, Coach Jeff Fisher of
the Titans said: ``I believe this is a team that came from nowhere
and did things no one expected us to. Now it's a team that is
respected and will be perceived around the league as a contender
for some time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during the opening game this season, Fisher pointed out,
Titans quarterback Steve McNair was booed by his own fans for an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   McNair and his teammates went on to a 13-3 regular season and a
Super Bowl run that included a miraculous finish in one playoff
game and the heartbreaking 23-16 loss here to the Rams, with the
Titans 1 yard from the end zone and no time left.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on what impact this season will have, Fisher said,
``We kind of stamped the blueprint yesterday for what this team is
all about: we'll have to run the football.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Fisher talked of getting better production out of his
cornerbacks, he suggested that he did not believe in any major
changes and wanted his coaching staff back next season.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said the loss did not make him despondent, only more
resolute in finding ways to improve the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure this game was an exciting game,'' he said, ``if you
didn't care about the score.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop on the Mend
</P>
<P>
   Blaine Bishop of the Titans, who suffered a neck sprain in the
third quarter and was on the ground for 10 minutes before being
lifted onto a stretcher for X-rays and a CAT scan, said he felt
fine Monday as he left with the team. Bishop wore a neck collar and
said his only lingering effect was ``a nerve that was messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The 203-pound strong safety attempted to tackle the 265-pound
tight end Ernie Conwell and instead crashed into him head first.
Bishop, who was knocked out on the play, said he asked to go back
into the game. But of course, he did not. Instead, he was sent to
the hospital for tests and returned before the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would make him `questionable' for next week,'' Coach Jeff
Fisher said Monday, cracking his only smile of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
