<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEDIUM MARKETS PRODUCE ONE BIG RATING FOR SUPER BOWL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the St. Louis-Tennessee Super Bowl match was set on Jan.
23, the assumption was that two medium-market upstarts with low
profiles would produce low television ratings. The notion held that
only large markets can turn Mr. Nielsen feverish.
</P>
<P>
   That supposition was turned on its head Sunday when the game
between St. Louis, the No. 21 market, and Nashville, the No. 30
market, produced a 43.2 Nielsen rating, up 7.5 percent from the
1998 and 1999 games and ahead of both Giants Super Bowls, in 1987
and 1991. Nielsen estimated that 130.7 million people watched at
least part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Great stories and great games produce great ratings, even when
the markets are not in the top 10 or 20. The appearance of Buffalo,
the No. 42 TV market, in four straight Super Bowls did not cause a
ratings mudslide; the 1993 game against Dallas produced a 45.5.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-game St. Louis-Milwaukee World Series in 1982, for
example, produced a 27.9 rating, the fourth best of the 1980s and
16 percent better than any Series in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl ratings have not tumbled like those of the rest of
prime-time _ or baseball _ as cable and other choices have
segmented viewing habits. They redefine sturdiness, which is why
National Football League TV rights cost so much and why networks
gross at least $150 million in ad sales on Super Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The heyday of Super Bowl ratings lasted from 1978 to 1986, when
the Nielsens peaked at a 49.1 (in 1982) and never fell below a 44.4
(in 1981).
</P>
<P>
   The highest since then was a 46.0, for San Francisco-San Diego
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   So it's clear that as fans grew more familiar with the Rams'
explosive offense and the improbable rise of their quarterback,
Kurt Warner, and came to appreciate the skills of Tennessee's Steve
McNair, Eddie George and Jevon Kearse, they found no reason to
watch the ``Matlock'' marathon on TBS instead of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And they were rewarded for sticking through three middling
quarters, because the fourth quarter made it one of the best of 34
Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been around the good teams of the '90s so often that you
really had to search to find something people didn't know about the
games,'' said ABC's Al Michaels, who called the game. ``It was
great to have fresh blood. This was like you were introducing these
teams to the country, like a debutante ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings rose in each successive half-hour, starting with a
39.0 upon kickoff at 6:26 p.m. and culminating with a 46.9 from
9:30 to 10 p.m. (The only dip occurred for the halftime show, which
rated a 40.8.)
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis led all markets with a 55.6 rating, followed by
Nashville at a 50.3. The cities left behind by the Titans and Rams
did not boycott. Houston generated a 47.0 and Los Angeles a 37.8.
Memphis, where the Titans decamped in 1997 before moving to
Nashville, posted a 35.8.
</P>
<P>
   Millrose Next on Schedule
</P>
<P>
   Track and field is in a perpetual muddle: How can a sport so
popular at the Olympics _ and crucial to the broadcasts _ be such a
television afterthought the rest of the time?
</P>
<P>
   For Craig Masback, chief executive of USA Track and Field, there
is encouraging news, just not enough of it. Broadcast ratings for
its Golden Spike Tour of indoor and outdoor meets averaged a 1.7
last year; not great, but comparable to hockey, soccer and women's
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong coverage of the Adidas D.C. International on NBC
Saturday produced a 2.4 overnight rating, which means somebody's
watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That beat the Senior Skins, auto racing and college
basketball,'' Masback said. Well, it tied the Senior PGA Skins Game
in its rating, but narrowly beat it in the share of TV households
watching at that time.
</P>
<P>
   But in its hour, the track meet never went head-to-head for long
with the Skins Game on ABC, the Kentucky-Miami college basketball
game on CBS, or the Indy Delphi Electronics 200 auto race on ABC.
Also, the meet led into NBC's National Basketball Association
doubleheader, while the Skins Game competed directly against it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the point is made. Track and field isn't dead. It is
dramatically underexposed and undersponsored. The impact of years
of lost opportunities can't be made up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who watch are upscale, educated and diverse,''
Masback said. ``But we don't have big investors willing to lose
$100 million over three years, like Major League Soccer. Now we're
in a situation where some sports that are better-heeled than us do
ratings lower than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Masback is hoping for a better fate for Saturday's Millrose
Games telecast (on NBC, from 2:30 to 3:30 p.m.) than for last
year's. The showing of Monica Lewinsky's deposition video at
President Clinton's impeachment trial pre-empted or delayed the
Millrose telecast last year, pushing the rating down to a slim 1.3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been and remains the world's best indoor track
meet,'' Masback said. ``To have it associated with USA Track and
Field is crucial to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the athletes entered in the meet, which takes place Friday
night at Madison Square Garden, are Maurice Greene, Ato Boldon, Jon
Drummond, Inger Miller and Carlette Guidry-White in the sprints;
Stacy Dragila and Lawrence Johnson in the pole vault; Joetta
Clark-Diggs in the 800-meter race; and William Tanui in the
Wanamaker Mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is what the other sports have done: develop
stars and try to tie the fortunes of the sponsors and advertisers
to the stars,'' Masback said.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila stars in a new Visa ad, and Marion Jones, the sprinter
who is likely to run in at least one Golden Spike outdoor meet, is
the star of new Nike and GMC Envoy TV spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
