<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-ART-N     01-31 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE AT ISSUE AS 5 DIALLO JURORS ARE SELECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JANE FRITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Five jurors, including two black women, were
chosen Monday as jury selection began in the trial of four white
police officers accused of murdering Amadou Diallo, a West African
immigrant who was shot 19 times as he stood unarmed in the lobby of
his Bronx apartment building one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of the jurors came after a lengthy and contentious
discussion between the prosecution and the defense in which each
side accused the other of using race as a basis to remove potential
jurors from the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had said it wanted to strike 10 jurors, 7 of
whom were white men, from a panel of 19 left at the day's end; the
defense said it wanted to strike 6 people, including 3 black women.
Each side is allotted a total of 20 peremptory challenges.
</P>
<P>
   In two decisions in 1986 and 1992, the Supreme Court ruled first
that prosecutors and then criminal defendants could not use race as
a basis to exclude jurors from serving.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Warner, the lead prosecutor for the case, said it was
inevitable that the prosecution would strike large numbers of white
jurors because Albany has a largely white jury pool. ``This is not
the Bronx,'' Warner told the judge as the issue went back and
forth. He labeled the defense's attempt to disqualify the black
women as ``blatantly discriminatory on race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett M. Epstein, one of the lawyers for Officer Sean Carroll,
said they were seeking to remove one black woman because she had
lived in the Bronx in a neighborhood relatively near where Diallo
was killed, and the other two because they had had relatives
arrested on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   The sidebar concluded with Justice Joseph C. Teresi saying,
without elaborating on his reasoning, that he was going to seat two
of the three black women and that he was upholding all of the
challenges by the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   One of those reinstated by Teresi was a soft-spoken middle-aged
black woman who lived in the Parkchester section of the Bronx from
1973 to 1983. ``I've had absolutely no interaction with the police
whatsoever,'' the woman said. She was selected as jury forewoman
because she happened to be seated in the first chair in the jury
box.
</P>
<P>
   The others selected were a black woman in a wheelchair who said
a family member had once been convicted of a drug charge; an
elderly white woman whose husband is a lawyer and had once been an
FBI agent; a young white woman who said she had once been held up
at gunpoint in North Carolina; and a middle-aged white man who said
he was against the private ownership of handguns by anyone except
the police.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in the case said they were surprised by the
rapid pace of jury selection. Defense lawyers used 4 of their 20
peremptory challenges, used to remove jurors without explanation,
one lawyer said, and prosecutors used 10 of their 20. It was not
possible to determine which side objected to which jurors because
they were removed in a private conference with Teresi. The judge
also excused 16 potential jurors because they said they did not
think they could be fair.
</P>
<P>
   The day began about 9 a.m. as the four grim-faced police
officers walked past demonstrators and reporters to make their way
into the Albany County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Carroll, one of the four, paused to wait for his wife
outside the courthouse and offered his condolences to the Diallo
family. ``I hope one day I'll be able to sit with the Diallos and
tell them I'm sorry about the loss of their son,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-31-00 2329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
