<DOCNO> NYT20000131.0547 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-31 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-SENATE-FUNDRAISING     01-31 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-FUNDRAISING-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY ATTRACTS MONEY FOR RICH NEW JERSEY SENATE CONTENDER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ When he set out to run for the U.S. Senate from
New Jersey, Jon Corzine, a political novice with a reported net
worth of $300 million, vowed to spend as much on his campaign as he
needed to get elected. Apparently, he was not bluffing.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., paid
his top campaign workers salaries more typical of big business than
of grass-roots politics, en route to spending more than $3.6
million on his Senate campaign last year, according to records
filed with the Federal Election Commission on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1999, no nonincumbent had spent as much for a Senate race
in the year before an election, according to the Campaign Study
Group, a Virginia organization that monitors candidate spending.
But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, who spent $4.4 million last
year, and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is believed to have spent
more than $3 million, appear with Corzine to be setting a new
benchmark in campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine hired two co-campaign managers, each at $20,000 a month,
a far more generous salary than the $150,000 a year that many
veteran campaign officials would consider themselves lucky to get.
He also hired a political director at $18,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   He paid $1.05 million for a roster of political consultants and
pollsters so long that it could be mistaken for an advertisement
listing all the underwriters of a Wall Street deal.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine lent his campaign $3.2 million himself last year, $2.65
million of that in the last six months. But even more noteworthy is
that he also managed to raise more than $1.4 million in donations
from other people. That sum exceeded the total, loans and all,
amassed by his only rival for the Democratic nomination, Jim
Florio, the former governor. What is more, most of Corzine's
contributions from others came in November and December, said Orin
Kramer, the Democratic fund-raiser who first talked Corzine into
running.
</P>
<P>
   Money has been a dominant theme in the New Jersey Senate race
since Corzine announced his interest a year ago. His willingness to
pay any price was cited by nearly every candidate who eventually
withdrew, among them Gov. Christie Whitman, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's supporters also promised that he would be able to
raise enough from individuals to show he could appeal to a broad
range of voters.
</P>
<P>
   They clearly hoped to force Florio from the race, too, by
starving him of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, whose political base is in the southern third of the
state, lost a great deal of fund-raising potential as Democratic
organizations in nearly all the wealthier North Jersey counties
endorsed Corzine. Florio's challenges mounted when Sen. Robert
Torricelli, the chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, though officially neutral, made it clear that he was
tacitly supporting Corzine. The effect was to dry up contributions
to Florio from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   During the last few months, Florio, who is determined to fight
on until the June primary, has often likened Corzine's easy-money
ways to a hostile takeover of the electoral system. ``I have some
trouble with someone buying an office,'' he said Wednesday night.
``We'll see what the voters say.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Corzine's aides insist they have to spend heavily
to compensate for a disadvantage in name recognition, given
Florio's more than 20 years on the New Jersey political scene.
Despite Corzine's spending, Florio enjoys a better than 2-to-1 edge
in the most recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Corzine's two campaign managers, Steven Goldstein,
went much further today, belittling Florio's war chest of $796,340
at year's end. In the last six months of 1999, records show, Florio
raised $511,500 in donations, lent his campaign $200,000 of his own
money and spent $444,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is utterly incomprehensible how any candidate in the modern
media age can run a campaign of even the slightest significance
with the embarrassing amount of money Jim Florio is reporting
today,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio brushed off such criticisms. ``We're not competing on the
basis of who raises more money,'' he said. ``He wins that
competition. Our game plan right from the beginning is a budget of
$2.5 to $3 million for the primary. We're on track to do that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But as one indication of the importance attached to money,
Florio's campaign said Monday that it had actually raised $1.61
million, about $250,000 more than was reported in its federal
filing. But that included contributions made as recently as Monday.
And a campaign official later confirmed that $200,000 of the extra
money was actually lent to the campaign by Florio.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Corzine's fund-raising ability, however, his own
filing with the Federal Election Commission raises questions about
his appeal among New Jersey residents.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $1.4 million Corzine raised in the last six months of
1999, more than one-third ($514,750) came from employees at
Goldman, Sachs and from Wall Street executives and investors. And
more money came from residents of New York ($561,525) than from New
Jerseyans ($475,085), records show.
</P>
<P>
   Among the five Republican contenders, state Sen. William L.
Gormley showed surprising financial strength by raising $1,530,990,
a figure far higher than any of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Franks was second, reporting $883,715 in
contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
