<HEADER>
A2608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-MENS-FASHION-AR     01-31 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-MENS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ELECTRIC MOMENT FOR A MEN'S DESIGNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The notion that a first-rate designer can emerge from
the marginal world of menswear and become one of the true fashion
rebels worth watching anywhere is almost too remote to contemplate.
The audience for the sort of clothes shown on the men's runways is
too small, and the designers who get the most attention _ like Tom
Ford, Miuccia Prada and Calvin Klein _ do so largely because they
already rule in the women's field.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Hedi Slimane of Yves Saint Laurent men's the most
exciting figure in fashion at the moment?
</P>
<P>
   Because his show on Jan. 25 at the French fall 2000 menswear
shows cut through all the hype and headline build-up (``The return
of elegance'') by concentrating on the things that have always
counted: cut and proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was a palpable sense of sexual energy in the
clothes; it was directed at men, skinny men, but all right, a woman
could appreciate it, too. Because when the last of the models had
left the runway and there was only the lone, reed-thin figure of
Slimane standing against the white wall of lights that formed the
show's backdrop, the audience became unglued and rose in a cheering
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, he is the only one who comes close to the genius of
Yves Saint Laurent,'' Pierre Berge, the former chief executive of
Saint Laurent, said afterward, with a Gallic flourish of hands.
``Let's not talk about these ridiculous things that people call
fashion _ no! It is about wonderful technique, cut and proportion.
Hedi understands this.''
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the body-conscious cut, Slimane banished every hue
except black. ``I wanted to show just the silhouette, like a
sketch,'' he explained afterward. That meant slim trousers, coats
with razor-sharp shoulders and a long, tapering torso.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes evoked some of the allure and sense of erotic danger
one associates with 1970s fashion, specifically Saint Laurent's, as
models in black leather trench coats and crocodile-embossed
trousers came out to fast-paced music commissioned for the show.
(Catherine Deneuve, a Saint Laurent muse, added her voice to the
soundtrack.)
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to say that an abundance of black leather (as a
tail coat, no less), shimmering T-shirts and slinky halter-style
tops of the dominatrix genre all verge on the homoerotic. Yet
rarely do tailored clothes hover so temptingly between what you
like and what you know you shouldn't have. And there's no doubt
that Slimane influenced the new sleek couture look that swept the
men's runways in Milan earlier last month.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether he is willing to be less a rebel,
and incorporate into his cut and technique some of those modern
marketing strategies that Ford, who was front and center at the
show, will surely expect as Saint Laurent's new creative director.
Slimane is one designer who deserves a wider commercial audience.
</P>
<P>
   The rich, gray-flannel look of English schoolboys was the
subject of Raf Simons' show, but don't bother thinking of oxford
bags or Sebastian Flyte. Just as the show was about to begin in a
sound stage on the edge of Paris, with the crowd sitting on either
side like students waiting for a pep rally, up rolled a Lincoln
Continental stretch limousine and out stepped two young men in dark
suits with crests on their jackets.
</P>
<P>
   It was hilarious. Simons has a knack for making the ordinary
seem subversive. Here were guys in those familiar gray flannels,
navy blazers, crew-neck sweaters over blue oxford shirts, and
slightly oversize Chesterfields (the coat, not the smoke) that
would have warmed a mother's heart if she had seen one of them
coming across a prep-school lawn, fresh from morning prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But these were no choirboys. For one thing, they all had
boot-black hair, which suggested something kinky, and for another,
the clothes _ the ultra-high turtleneck sweaters, the waistless
trousers, the tongue-in-cheek clerical collars _ expressed a
knowingness about fashion's ability to toy with convention and
illusion. Lest anyone think Simons was soft on bourgeois statements
of decorum, he also sent out the quintessential playboy-mobile, a
DeLorean.
</P>
<P>
   If the Milan shows are about product (clothes to wear!), the
French shows are about inventiveness and avant-garde fun (clothes
to write about!). It's hard to imagine there are too many followers
for the clownish plaids that Rei Kawakubo showed at Comme des
Garcons, although the models came out whirling and jiving to the
rock music with such youthful exuberance that the many plaid
trousers and shrunken-looking jackets seemed an antidote to the
strait-laced elegance attempting to return to men's fashion. They
are certainly the kind of clothes that die-hard individualists
wear.
</P>
<P>
   There were plaids, along with fabrics that looked lovingly worn
in, at Paul Smith's show, too, but these were of the English
variety for which Smith is known.
</P>
<P>
   Yohji Yamamoto's show was neither here nor there. The designer
seemed to be trying to move away from all-black statements, with
such things as jewel-embroidered cuffs and silky pajama pants in
pastel colors with striped or waffle-knitted sweaters. But his loud
patchwork effects and oversize jackets seemed to be a case of a
designer trying to work out a problem whose solution only he would
be interested in.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the runways, Marc Jacobs put on a good show at
Louis Vuitton. The collection focused on classic looks, like tweedy
jackets, turtleneck sweaters (often under shirts or matching V-neck
sweaters) and this season's apparently smart shoe, the tasseled
loafer. There was a flourish of logos, including on silk pajama
pants, but Jacobs wisely played things straight.
</P>
<P>
   The cool factor at Hermes was to be found in single-breasted
suits in olive and Hermes-orange velvet, buttoned over black
shirts. There were also leather trousers with knits, and a vivid
orange zip-front cardigan, worn by a model with fuzzy hair and
glasses, which made one think the clothes would look great in an
off-beat young Hollywood movie.
</P>
<P>
   In the program notes to his show, which was held in a loftlike
space with carpets placed in concentric circles on the concrete,
Walter van Beirendonck said he wanted his fall collection to
``bring back a feeling of pride and dressing up to fashion.'' He
mentioned that the clothes would be layered.
</P>
<P>
   And how! Van Beirendonck took stripes and cotton checks, even a
pattern that looked suspiciously as though it were copied from a
baby's crib bunting, and layered them, piling shirt upon
identically cut shirt until, indeed, the finished garment (its
layers connected only by tiny metal rods that stood up at the
shoulders) seemed to praise the process of dressing itself.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the design team of Viktor &AMP; Rolf tried a similar feat
at the autumn haute couture shows here last July, but van
Beirendonck was not imitating them. His layered coats and tops were
more naive, mixing common and high-tech fabrics, and presumably
they are also meant to be worn. And what was striking about seeing
clothes in six layers of the same shape is that they had texture
and depth and suddenly movement, too. They looked multidimensional.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the show, the models, standing front to back in
two circles, each stepped forward and removed the shirt or coat
from the person in front of him, holding van Beirendonck's artful
layers by the tiny rods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
