<HEADER>
A2610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPER-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-31 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: THE BEST SUPER BOWL EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What is your lasting memory of Super Bowl XXXIV?
</P>
<P>
   How about Blaine Bishop's headfirst, third-quarter tackle that
left him unconscious for a few moments and scared both teams and
the Georgia Dome crowd of 72,652 into eerie silence? What about
Kurt Warner's fancy 73-yard touchdown pass to Isaac Bruce in the
final minutes that proved to be the winning points? How about Steve
McNair jousting two tacklers for a last-minute scramble and a
16-yard fling to Kevin Dyson in a shot at glory?
</P>
<P>
   All memorable moments, but the play of the game was the last
one: the 9-yard pass from McNair to Dyson that St. Louis Rams
linebacker Mike Jones made sure was good for only 9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A thrilling, definitive finale of a play that saved the Rams'
chilling 23-16 victory. You just saw the best Super Bowl ever
played.
</P>
<P>
   No turnovers. No goats. No decisive controversy. Few penalties.
High drama.
</P>
<P>
   There have been Super Bowls with more points scored and with
more precise execution and with bigger crowds and with bigger
stars. There has never been another Super Bowl, however, that took
all 60 minutes, each and every second, and created a more dramatic
finish.
</P>
<P>
   The game's signature play will always be the last one: McNair to
Dyson, with Jones in the mix as the clock struck zero.
</P>
<P>
   For every Super Bowl to come, the play will be replayed, fixed
permanently in our minds and in Super Bowl lore. And on every
rerun, on every recount, Dyson will always finish 1 yard shy of the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what Tennessee faces,'' said Solomon Wilcots, the
former Cincinnati Bengals defensive back who now works for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   He was part of Super Bowl XXII when Joe Montana's 10-yard
scoring pass to John Taylor with 34 seconds left won it for San
Francisco, 20-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year at Super Bowl time, they show that play,'' Wilcots
said. ``I keep looking at it hoping this time will be the one where
Taylor drops the ball. You know, he never does. And that is what
will happen for the Tennessee Titans. They will never escape that
play. Every time they see it, they will bleed a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never run and hide from it and in some ways you never
recover from it. You learn to live with it, but it's always harder
when the Super Bowl rolls around again.''
</P>
<P>
   We saw the Rams slip on their Super Bowl victory T-shirts and
caps. No doubt, the Titans had a box of them ready, too, just in
case. They can burn them now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a whole lot,'' Titans cornerback Samari Rolle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a lot of talking between us,'' Titans tight
end Jackie Harris said Monday. ``It is amazing, though, and we
realize that for all of the hype and hard work, for everything it
took to get here, that the game at the end boiled down to one play
and the basic fundamental of tackling.''
</P>
<P>
   For a true champion, the bigger the game, the bigger the
tackling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a combination coverage and with only 10 yards to
defend before the end zone, we were looking for them to try and
throw it before the goal line and to try and lunge in,'' Jones
said. ``I saw Dyson's move and sensed the ball coming. He planted.
I planted and anticipated his move. I got underneath him. I was
going downhill on him. I had the angle and made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Warner passed for a Super Bowl record 414 yards. The Rams
won despite possessing the ball for only 5 minutes 49 seconds of
the second half. The team that runs best wins? Not this time,
because Tennessee easily won the rushing battle, 159 yards to 29
yards. McNair rushed for 64 yards, the most by a quarterback. St.
Louis scored the game's first 16 points. Tennessee scored the next
16.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Warner to Bruce for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Then McNair to Dyson for the desperate finale.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams move forward, with coach Dick Vermeil considering
retirement and with his offensive coordinator, Mike Martz, set to
replace him. Warner will receive a long-term contract. The Rams
will play a Super Bowl champion schedule next season, one much
tougher than this season, but they are suited for the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans look to develop a deep passing game in the
off-season. They played this Super Bowl without two pivotal injured
starters, receiver Yancey Thigpen and safety Marcus Robertson. For
much of the second half, Bishop was injured and gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   Would Robertson or Bishop deny the game-swinging play on Bruce?
Would Thigpen get into the end zone when Dyson could not?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team made great strides in our passing game, and there is
no question it will continue to mature and evolve and we will look
to develop more deep threats,'' Titans coach Jeff Fisher said.
``Yancey Thigpen watched this game from the sideline, and I'm
telling you that is a big difference for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built this offense to run the ball and move the chains
with a short passing game, and that style is predicated on getting
turnovers and creating more chances. We got no turnovers. That was
big. With all of that said, I'm sure the game was exciting to watch
if you didn't care about the score.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was exciting to watch if you did care.
</P>
<P>
   It was the best Super Bowl ever.
</P>
<P>
   And once it was over, one of the most glorious postgame sights
Monday morning was Bishop. He walked on his own from the hotel to
board the team bus to catch the team plane back to Nashville. He
wore a cumbersome white neck brace.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was knocked out,'' Bishop said. ``I didn't remember
anything. Once I was aroused, I told them I could get up and go
back in. Once they got me on the cart, I knew I couldn't even stand
up. My head was spinning. I messed up a nerve in my left arm. But I
feel OK now. The doctors tell me it is only a sprained neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the way from the hospital back to the stadium, they told me
the score was 16-16. I had hope. Once I got there, I found out we
had lost. I didn't even see how until I saw the highlights this
morning. Could I have made a difference at the end? It's hard to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 132 plays in Super Bowl XXXIV. It was the best Super
Bowl ever because every single one coalesced, from start to finish,
for a memorable football tapestry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
