<SLUG> BC-TERROR-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER QUESTIONS TIMING OF ARREST IN BOMB PLOT INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lawyer for a Brooklyn man charged with assisting in
an aborted bomb plot accused the government Monday of timing his
client's arrest to coincide with a court holiday so that he could
then be interrogated at length before being given a lawyer or taken
before a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Abdel Ghani Meskini, was arrested on Dec. 30, and
charged with assisting in a terrorist plot that involved an attempt
by a group of Algerians in Canada to smuggle powerful explosives
into the United States near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation that the government had improperly delayed
Meskini's arrest was sharply disputed by prosecutors and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Meskini's lawyer, Roland Thau, suggested that ``the
government timed the arrest very specifically in order to deny this
defendant his opportunity to appear before a judicial officer and
have counsel appointed promptly.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the hearing, Thau said that Meskini had
been under surveillance for several days but that the government
waited to arrest him until the morning of Thursday, Dec. 30, after
the federal District Courthouse in Manhattan had closed for New
Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Meskini, 31, was then interrogated for about eight hours, Thau
said. He did not make a court appearance until the next day, also a
court holiday, when Thau was appointed defense counsel. Meskini has
since pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI and prosecutors were very, very eager to get
statements from this defendant,'' Thau told Judge John F. Keenan on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A federal prosecutor, David N. Kelley, sharply disputed Thau's
contention. He said the allegation was ``an ill-founded premise _
and the fact it's an ill-founded premise will be borne out,''
Kelley added, if a hearing is held on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the FBI in New York, Joseph A. Valiquette,
denied that the timing of the arrest ``was intended to deny him due
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Thau has said that any statements by his client relating to a
bomb plot could not be construed as a confession, but rather as an
explanation of his own innocence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
