A2616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      01-31 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE USES OF NEGATIVE CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 1:
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after a speech in which he had, by implication,
questioned George W. Bush's readiness to be commander in chief and
linked him to Clintonesque fund-raising techniques, Sen. John
McCain was asked if he was violating his promise not to indulge in
negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm close,'' McCain said with a laugh. As usual, he
was being more candid _ and wittier _ than the other leading
candidates about a game that all of them are playing to some
degree.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, for example, Bush responds to the hint
that he will need ``on the job training'' by depicting McCain as a
crypto-Democrat who is ``mimicking'' Al Gore's timid tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic campaign, the exchanges between Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley are blunter and more personal. But the
plain fact is that all four are ready to go negative when it serves
their interests, and each man is capable of histrionic displays of
virtue when he thinks he can accuse an opponent of taking the low
road.
</P>
<P>
   The entire show provides an opportunity to reflect on exactly
what constitutes negative campaigning, what conditions bring it to
the surface and what value it can bring to a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a boil-lancing benefit to attack politics. It can
bring into the open key questions about temperament, character and
leadership ability.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's accusation that Bradley would not ``stay and fight'' in
Washington does touch on the important question of whether Bradley
has the inner toughness and practicality for the job he seeks.
Bradley's assertion that Gore cannot be counted on to tell the
truth does point up the vice president's habit of exaggerating and
revising his record. Attacks on Bush as green and untested and
McCain as outside the Republican mainstream clearly have relevance
to the choice before GOP primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for voters is that attack politics can lead to
distortion of the issues debate. For example, no one seriously
believes Bradley's suggestion that Gore's early waffling on
abortion means that he is not currently a reliable defender of
women's right to choose. Similarly, Gore's charge that Bradley's
proposal for universal health care would mean abandoning the people
on Medicaid is a willful misrepresentation. Bradley's plan to
replace Medicaid with other insurance programs is similar to the
approach used in the Clinton-Gore health plan of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the Gore-Bradley contest has brought out a
whiny quality in both men. Bradley seems to think that a rule of
his ``new politics'' is ``Thou shalt not attack Bill Bradley.''
Gore seems to think that negative campaigning is defined as others
doing to Al Gore what Al Gore does to them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the GOP contest has shown that Bush and McCain have
to struggle to keep their inner bullies in check. But the nature of
the campaign and the earnestness with which it is being contested
inclines us to cut all four a little slack.
</P>
<P>
   At least three of the four have faced problems of political
self-preservation. Insurgency candidates like Bradley and McCain
usually have to slash and burn in order to have a chance. Gore, in
becoming the first of the four to go negative in a big way,
energized a candidacy that was in danger of sleepwalking to defeat.
Bush has not really had to get tough yet, but it is worth
remembering that he is the lineal heir to a trend-setting
enterprise in the techniques of opponent destruction, that being
the campaign that his father, President George Bush, waged against
Michael Dukakis, the Democratic nominee, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   That campaign and the Clinton-Gore campaigns of 1992 and 1996
convinced the current generation of candidates and consultants in
both parties that the politics of destruction are a necessary part
of any campaign arsenal. Voters invariably tell pollsters they do
not like tough campaign tactics, but as Bradley learned in Iowa,
fighting back is a necessary skill for anyone who aspires to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The voters have a good sense about what is rough but acceptable
and what is over the top. That is why candidates like Steve Forbes,
who do not balance their attacks on opponents with an uplifting
appeal of their own, seldom get to the big show.
</P>
<P>
   For the main contenders, the New Hampshire battle has been harsh
and sometimes unfair, but it has also been consistently
illuminating about what the candidates stand for and how they might
react under the much greater pressures that bear in upon the Oval
Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
