<SLUG> BC-CRASH-ALASKA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JET CRASHES OFF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES --Moments after reporting mechanical problems, an
Alaska Airlines jet with 88 people aboard plunged nose-first into
the Pacific Ocean off Point Mugu northwest of Los Angeles Monday.
There were no signs of survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 261, en route nonstop from the Mexican resort of Puerto
Vallarta to San Francisco, disappeared from radar around 3:45 p.m.
after its crew reported problems with the McDonnell Douglas DC83
stabilizer trim and asked permission to make an emergency landing
at Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   On Anacapa Island, witnesses saw the plane plummet into the
Pacific Ocean about 10 miles off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   A broad oil slick littered with debris marked the crash scene.
One body was recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard and Navy ships and helicopters, aided by boats from
Channel Island fishermen and oil rigs, searched the cold and choppy
water through the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every resource we can muster either on-scene or en
route,'' said Coast Guard Capt. George Wright. ``We are going to
search for survivors until there is about zero chance of finding
anyone alive.''
</P>
<P>
   As darkness fell, the Coast Guard's four helicopters, one
airplane and three boats on the scene were joined by more than a
dozen civilian boats combing the water for survivors. Coast guard
personnel were armed with infra-red vision devices to spot the body
heat of survivors floating on the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always hope there will be a survivor out there,''
Wright said. ``We've seen miracles before.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the 58-degree water temperature, however, officials said
it was unlikely people could survive for long.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration officials and an National
Transportation Safety Board an investigative team was immediately
mobilized and was expected to arrive in Los Angeles early today.
</P>
<P>
   They will lead recovery efforts and the search for what
Washington D.C. at 2 a.m. today and seek the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   An Alaska Airline spokesman said the plane had no previous
problems with the stabilizer trim, which controls the jet's
up-and-down maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   The flight left Puerto Vallarta at 2:30 Pacific Standard Time
and was scheduled to land in San Francisco just after 5 p.m. before
heading on to Seattle later in the evening. Eighty-three passengers
and five crew members were on board, according to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers lost contact with the crew over Los
Angeles air space around as the plane cruised along the coast at
17,000 feet, said a spokesman for San Francisco International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Airline officials said the crew members radioed that they were
having trouble with the stabilizer trim and were diverted back to
LAX.
</P>
<P>
   The jet was still 20 miles northwest of the airport when it
crashed, plunging into water at least 300 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   On Anacapa Island, roughly two miles away, a National Park
Service employee watched the plane slam into the ocean, said Suzan
Smith, a spokeswoman for Channel Islands National Park in Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went in nose first,'' she said. She declined to identify
the employee.
</P>
<P>
   The plane hit just outside the park's boundaries, she said. The
employee called in the crash to the park's dispatch center, which
called the Coast Guard with the information. The park's dispatchers
also reached a fishing boat crew that had witnessed the crash and
was speeding to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman Mitch Barker said the first reports of the crash
indicated the plane was upside down in the water. Further details
were not available Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The twin-engine plane was built in 1992 and is a version of the
MD-80 first flown in 1979. Since then McDonnell-Douglas, and now
Boeing, has sold nearly 1,200 of of the MD-80 in its various
versions.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB records indicate Alaska Airlines has never had a fatal
crash before, outside of a 1990 incident in Phoenix in which a
mental patient ran onto the runway in front of a Alaska Airlines
727 and was killed.
</P>
<P>
   A passenger list of the downed plane was not available Monday
evening. However, those who think family members may have been on
the plane can call (800) 553-5117 to reach the airline.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
