u a BC-ALLEN-RADIO-OPERA-NYT     01-31 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-RADIO-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING THE PLAY BY PLAY FOR MET'S LISTENERS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ And all these years you thought that Peter Allen was
alone in the broadcast booth at the Metropolitan Opera on Saturday
afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. There are two people in there, facing the plate-glass
window. In the chair on the right sits Allen's wife, Sylvia.
</P>
<P>
   He says, in the deep-but-not-too-deep voice that has introduced
507 opera broadcasts: ``She performs a function. She kicks me when
I make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   She says, in a voice not heard on the 360 radio stations that
carry his: ``I never kicked him in my life. I poke him. And I'm
always right.''
</P>
<P>
   They laugh. They have been carrying on like this for 25 years
now, sounding happier than the characters he talks about, week
after week. Talk about contrasts: down on the stage, all those
messy entanglements, all that cavorting with other people's wives,
husbands, princes, princesses. Up in the broadcast booth on the
Grand Tier, a couple as proper and polite as Papageno and Papagena
in ``The Magic Flute.''
</P>
<P>
   They have his-and-hers binoculars to watch the action,
his-and-hers headphones to hear it. And when the ``on the air''
light is off, he is accommodating, even self-effacing. ``With all
those voices out there on the stage, to call me `the voice of the
Met' is very odd,'' he says. But he also manages to sound
authoritative.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, about the same as when the ``on the air'' light
is on. There is, perhaps, only one difference between on and off
the air. When he arrives at the Met on Saturdays, he transfers the
change in his right pocket to his left. In case of a kick (or a
poke), he does not want the microphone to pick up jangling coins.
</P>
<P>
   His 25 years as the Met's announcer have gone as fast as the
Queen of the Night's high F in ``The Magic Flute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to emphasize my age,'' he says, ``not out of
vanity, but I don't like to reinforce the cliche that opera is for
old people. I am 79, but I don't like to advertise that.''
</P>
<P>
   He no longer opens with the same five words every week _
``Texaco presents the Metropolitan Opera.'' Texaco has been the
sponsor since 1940, but to avoid monotony, the scripts now vary; on
Saturday, his first word was ``Welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long the audience was applauding and he was doing the
opera world's equivalent of play by play: ``The bravos rise as he
mounts the stand, smiling to the house, bowing to the house, now
turning to conduct,'' he said as the Met's artistic director, James
Levine, arrived for ``Der Rosenkavalier.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen also does the color, telling radio listeners what they
cannot see: after Act III, the soprano Heidi Grant Murphy was
``wearing a modest but very pretty dark red dress.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for the woman on his right, he might not be doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sylvia cast me in my first radio production, `Of Mice and
Men.' I was Slim. She was the director.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been the principal violist in the Ohio State Symphony.
Ohio State's radio station hired him to play in a string quartet,
but the three other musicians never appeared, so it was his voice,
not his viola, that went on.
</P>
<P>
   He was hired by a commercial station in Columbus, Ohio _ ``I did
the `RCA Victor Record Showcase,''' he says _ and eventually
married his former director (who became a painter). They moved to
New York and shared a subscription to the Met with another couple,
and in 1947, he became an announcer on WQXR.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to the 1973-74 season: He was hired as a standby
for Milton Cross, who had been presiding over the microphone since
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   For a year Allen sat through the Saturday matinees. Cross died
on Jan. 3, 1975, a Friday. The next day, the Allens were in the
booth. They have not missed a Saturday since.
</P>
<P>
   On his fourth broadcast, he was introducing the second act of
``Tosca'' when he was handed a note that said, ``Keep talking.'' He
did. Later he learned why Act II had been delayed: The tenor Carlo
Bergonzi, had had a coughing fit backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Allen also talked his way through what he calls ``the `Macbeth'
episode,'' when an 82-year-old singing coach committed suicide by
jumping from a balcony during the intermission of ``Macbeth'' in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, he talked for 23 minutes when the Met's
stage-moving machinery stalled during a scene change in
``Parsifal'' and stagehands had to do the work by hand. Joseph
Volpe, who is now the Met's general manager, heard Allen's
ad-libbing on his car radio, driving in from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``How he came up with those things, from one subject to another,
from `Parsifal' to Wagner to you name it, I don't know,'' Volpe
said. ``It's not something you can prepare for.''
</P>
<P>
   But Allen tries. He writes about an hour's worth of his own
filler, material that can be pulled out if he needs it. ``There's a
lot to say about almost any opera or composer,'' he says, ``except
maybe Cilea.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise that if you ask what his three favorite
operas are, Cilea's ``Adriana Lecouvreur'' is not on the list.
``Otello,'' ``Tristan und Isolde'' and ``Boris Godunov'' are.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty happy diet,'' he says, though he adds, ``It
would be easier to name 25.''
</P>
<P>
   Having wrapped up ``Rosenkavalier'' and signed off, the Allens
hang up the headphones. He puts away the binoculars. And, as they
start out of the booth, he takes the coins out of his left pocket
and puts them back in his right pocket. No more kicks (or pokes)
until next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
